 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON (Moved in ``w'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLL (Undated) _ President Clinton's standing with
Americans has rebounded widely in the days since the release of his
video-taped testimony before a grand jury, and, in fact, people are
so exasperated with the Lewinsky scandal that there are stirrings
of a backlash against the Republican-controlled Congress as it
presses forward with an impeachment inquiry, the latest New York
Times/CBS News Poll shows. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ Ask in Foggy Bottom, ask in
Whitehall, ask on the Quai d'Orsay, ask at the Kremlin, and you get
the same deeply discreet answer: No, of course, Bill Clinton's
personal and political troubles have not impaired the capacity of
the United States to conduct foreign policy. But scratch a little
deeper, push a little harder, and you discover that diplomats and
politicians in most of the world's major nations are worried sick
by the spectacle of a distracted president in Washington at a
moment when, in their view at least, bold American leadership is
all but indispensable. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT15) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-COUNTERATTACK (Washington) _ When the report of Kenneth
Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, landed like a bombshell
on Capitol Hill, the devastating questions all concerned President
Clinton's behavior. But in the weeks since then, Democrats have
done everything they can to refocus the spotlight onto
congressional Republicans. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRESS (Undated) _ A look at what stories news
organizations are not covering because all of the attention on the
Lewinsky matter. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-AFTERMATH (Peggy's Cove, Nova Scotia) _ The pattern of
life traditionally followed by the 60 residents of Peggy's Cove was
shattered on a clear night at the beginning of the month when a
huge jet tumbled out of the sky and slammed into the Atlantic with
enough force to make earthquake detector instruments quiver. And
while Peggy's Cove is returning to some kind of normalcy, what
everyone wants to know is if it can ever be the same again. By
Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Dobrosevac, Yugoslavia) _ Western aid workers
estimate that as many as 10,000 civilians were dislodged from their
villages on Tuesday. Many are stranded in the Cicavica hills, too
scared to move but living in precarious conditions with little food
and only flimsy shelters fashioned from trees, blankets and plastic
for the cold nights. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-LEGISLATION _ Nearly two decades into the AIDS epidemic,
legislators around the country are passing an increasing number of
laws intended to protect the public. This latest wave of
legislation shifts the focus from earlier laws that protected the
civil liberties of HIV-infected people to laws that seek to
identify, notify and in some cases punish people who have the
virus. By Lynda Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HAND-TRANSPLANT _ Surgeons in France said Thursday that they
had attached the right hand and forearm of an anonymous donor to
the arm of a 48-year-old Australian man whose own hand was
amputated after a logging accident in 1989. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT (New York) _ If the $3.5 billion cash infusion
by a consortium of banks and brokerages to save a large investment
fund from collapse was designed to bring stability to world
markets, it is not yet working. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-TEAM (New York) _ When Salomon Brothers was raking in
the money, investors would grin at one another and say, ``J.M.'s
done it again.'' ``J.M.'' is John Meriwether, who turned huge
profits by using complex trading strategies and huge amounts of
capital to exploit price discrepancies in the world's bond markets.
Now, in perhaps the clearest sign to date of the current fragile
state of global financial markets, Meriwether's latest bubble has
burst. No longer at Salomon, he is at the center of a $95 billion
storm that led to this week's $3.7 billion bailout of his hedge
fund orchestrated by the Federal Reserve Bank of New York. By Peter
Truell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   HEDGEFUND-RISK (Undated) _ A look at those funds that have not
taken these risks and may be tarred unjustifiably. By Geraldine
Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-AIRLINES (Hong Kong) _ What happens when a sprawling
island nation suddenly loses its national airline? That question
reverberated through the Philippines on the morning after
Philippine Airlines ceased flying. The airline, Asia's oldest, shut
down at midnight Wednesday after the president of the Philippines
failed to resolve a bitter labor dispute. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-IPO-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Now we know what it takes to
shake Wall Street's initial public offering blues: Beanie Babies
and lots of them. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   RUBICAM-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ A cadre of top executives at
Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. is being redeployed as the huge agency company
seeks to build on the momentum gained from recent high-profile
account assignments. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROSENTHAL-COLUMN (Undated) _ A.M. Rosenthal examines the latest
peace proposals of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times on the Mets
and Cubs in the final weekend of the season. By Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-BASEBALL-SEASON (Undated) _ Setting up the last week of the
regular season: A NYT/CBS News poll shows that 63 percent of
respondents consider themselves baseball fans, up from 42 percent
last year. And it's no wonder. This has been a season energized by
an unprecented home run race that promises to go down to the very
last game, and wild-card races that promise the same. Meanwhile,
the Yankees have set an attendance record and are pursuing victory
records. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
