<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURIER ON BENCH AS FAST-RISING GAMBILL MOVES IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ When the time came to unveil the identity of the
U.S. Davis Cup squadron that will battle Italy in the semifinal
here this weekend, the hot hand won out over the old hand during a
chilly outdoor draw ceremony a few blocks from the designated
battlefield, a semi-sluggish indoor hardcourt at the Milwaukee
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Tradition practically mandated that Tom Gullikson, the U.S.
Davis Cup captain, turn to Jim Courier, a veteran so reliable that
he has never been on a losing team, to back up Todd Martin in
singles. But Gullikson gave the second singles slot to 21-year-old
Jan-Michael Gambill, a Jaguar-driving, cellular phone-toting ``Star
Trek'' groupie from Spokane, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of two singles matches scheduled for Friday,
Gambill, who jumped from 227th to 50th in the ranking this season,
makes his Davis Cup debut against Italy's top player, 47th-ranked
Andrea Gaudenzi. The Italian defeated him in their only encounter,
a rain-plagued meeting on Austrian clay, earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the second match, the 28th-ranked, 28-year-old Martin faces a
backup singles player for Italy by way of UCLA, Davide Sanguinetti.
For Saturday's doubles, Martin and another Davis Cup neophyte,
Justin Gimelstob, tackle Gaudenzi and Diego Nargiso, a veteran
whose specialty is doubles. The singles pairings are reversed on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come here thinking I wouldn't play,'' Courier said,
``but once I was here I kind of got the feeling that that was the
way Gully was leaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Now ranked 72d, Courier developed a chronic and puzzling case of
``dead arm'' around 18 months ago. ``It's an ongoing battle,''
Courier said of the arm trouble, which he has traced to his biceps
and likens to the plight of a pitcher who has thrown one fastball
too many. ``I don't think the human arm was designed to do what I
asked mine to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been five years since the former No. 1 captured the last
of his four Grand Slam titles. Consecutive opening-round losses in
summer hardcourt events prompted him to withdraw from the U.S. Open
and take six weeks off until he reconsidered his position on the
sideline and, aware that Pete Sampras, Andre Agassi and Michael
Chang had said no to this semifinal, volunteered for duty.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson said current form, rather than current sentiment, took
precedence in Gambill's selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just basically an issue of match toughness,'' Gullikson
said. Gambill, who notched victories over Agassi and Courier this
year and took the French Open champion, Carlos Moya, to a fifth set
at the Open two weeks ago, has it; Courier does not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
