</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TOP DEVIL RAYS, 5-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An American League scout lounged in the stands at
Yankee Stadium on Thursday night, in his second week of trailing
the Yankees for a potential playoff opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The scout feels he knows how to pitch Chuck Knoblauch
effectively, how to beat Orlando Hernandez. But he acknowledged he
knows almost nothing about Shane Spencer, the late-season call-up
who continued his rampage by bashing a grand slam in the Yankees'
5-2 victory over Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Yankees' 111th in 159 games, surpassing the
club record of 110 set by the 1927 Yankees, who played 154 games.
The Yankees have matched the American League record set in 1954 by
the Cleveland Indians, who also played a 154-game season.
</P>
<P>
   The achievment prompted a congratulatory statement from the
Yankee owner, George Steinbrenner: ``From the time I was a kid
growing up, all I ever heard was how great the '27 Yankees were.
That's why this means so much. Joe Torre, his coaches and players
deserve all the credit. You all know winning is important to me.
But it is second _ first is breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre, in his third year as Yankee manager, said of the team's
milestone: ``It feels enormous. We've made our place in history.''
</P>
<P>
   David Cone agreed, saying of the accomplishment of tying the
record of the '27 Yankees: ``Around here, it almost feels like
you're trying to compare yourself against ghosts, with all the
legends and all the stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer is creating his own legend. The Yankees trailed Wilson
Alvarez of the Devil Rays by 2-0 after five and a half innings on
Thursday night, but scored a run in the sixth and loaded the bases
with nobody out for Spencer. The burly right-handed-hitting slugger
reached out and smashed a change-up over the wall in right-center
field, setting off an explosion of cheers from the crowd of 24,555
at Yankee Stadium. For the second time in two nights, Spencer was
shouted out of the dugout for a curtain call.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer has 5 homers and 6 other hits in his last 17 at-bats,
with 14 runs batted in, and he has 8 homers in only 57 at-bats for
the Yankees this season. Spencer, according to a member of the
Yankee organization, has not only made a case for winning a spot on
the post-season roster, but also may well persuade Torre to start
him in left field in the playoffs, particularly with both Tim
Raines and Darryl Strawberry recovering from minor leg injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to have a hot streak,'' Torre said, ``now's
the time to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Spencer does play in the post-season, at least one scout says
he does not yet know how to counter Spencer. ``He's hit everything
they've thrown him _ up and down, inside and outside, fastballs and
soft stuff,'' the scout said. ``I saw him swing at one changeup in
the dirt, and besides that, he hasn't taken a bad swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer will get three more games to prove himself to Torre, and
other Yankees will have three more games to achieve personal goals.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams shares the American League lead in hitting with
Mo Vaughn of Boston, at .334. Derek Jeter ranks third at .324 and
Paul O'Neill, who did not play on Thursday night, is ninth at .318.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be great preparation for the playoffs,''
Williams said. ``It's going to be very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams needs one more run scored and six more driven home to
achieve 100 in each of those categories. Jeter needs one more hit
to reach 200.
</P>
<P>
   Needing one victory to reach 20, Cone has one more start
remaining, against Tampa Bay on Saturday. But Torre is not sure
Cone will have a chance to pitch the five innings to qualify for
the victory. Rather, Cone will be working with a limited pitch
count of 70 to 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could take him to a chance to get his 20th,'' Torre said,
``but that's not our focus. If we take him out with the lead,
you'll see our best guys out there following him.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone has had two shots at 20 and lost both games, and he
acknowledged part of him feels as if he has already missed his
chance. ``I may get another shot,'' Cone said, ``but that's not my
No. 1 priority.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
