<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLINS: TEAM HAD WRONG IDEA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ The Anaheim Angels arrived in Oakland early Thursday
morning with a Texas-sized hangover, a result of the Rangers'
three-game sweep that all but ended the Angels' hopes for their
first division title since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared the pressure got to the Angels, who were outscored
by a combined score of 25-3 in the three games. The Angels, though,
said throughout the series that they felt no pressure because no
one expected them to be there.
</P>
<P>
   But manager Terry Collins now says that was the wrong approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan on being in the same situation next September _ in a
pennant race,'' Collins said. ``One thing I learned from this is
don't hide from the pressure. Embrace it. You don't think there's
pressure? You're kidding yourself. You're playing in the big
leagues. There's a lot at stake. When there's pressure, you have to
raise your concentration level.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter how badly the Angels played in the series, they also
must give credit to the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They totally dominated us in every phase of the game,''
shortstop Gary DiSarcina said. ``They shook the total foundation of
everything we had built the entire year. That's the most
frustrating thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though some players talked about the season in the past tense
even before Thursday's game, Collins said he would implore the team
not to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that's certainly going to be discussed between
myself and the players (Thursday) is that we're not dead yet,''
Collins said. ``Certainly the lights are pretty dim. But one thing
I don't want to do is have anyone think for one second we're not
still in it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Nothing's easy: The trip to Oakland didn't get off to such a
good start. The team flew from Burbank to San Francisco, got off
the plane and waited for the bus to the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The players watched as the bus drove onto the tarmac, then into
a stationary plane, the wing crashing through the windshield of the
bus. After the airport police came to investigate, then a quick-fix
using duct tape to cover the hole in the window, the Angels were on
their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never a dull moment,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Lineup switch: Collins said he would make some changes in the
lineup Thursday and he was true to his word. The most notable
change was moving DiSarcina up from No. 9 in the batting order to
No. 2. It was the first time DiSarcina has hit second since June 1,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty similar to hitting ninth,'' DiSarcina said.
``Hitting ninth you try to get guys over for the top of the order.
I hit second for three weeks in '95. I don't think it's a big deal.
I'm happy to hit anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Velarde absent: Second baseman Randy Velarde left the team to
be with a relative who is ill. Velarde was expected back late
Thursday night or today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
