<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 00:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3666 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-LADN     09-25 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN TROJANS COPE WITH FSU DEFENSE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ It took three games, but John Fox finally
might have found a reason to be happy he's no longer playing
quarterback for USC. He only has to think back to last season's
game against Florida State. After just a couple series, Fox figured
out his options against the Seminoles' swift defense were severely
limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like, I wanted to take seven steps to drop back and
pass, but I'd get five and get killed,'' said Fox, who is now a
tight end. ``You either get the ball off and get killed or wait to
throw a bad ball and still get the heck beat out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   USC never solved Florida State's defense, as the Trojans netted
a paltry 184 yards offense against the Seminoles and 25 yards
rushing in their 14-7 loss last season.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the 18th-ranked Trojans can muster any more points
Saturday remains the key issue is this year's matchup with the
10th-ranked Seminoles.
</P>
<P>
   USC is 3-0, but the offense's inconsistency produces doubts
about how the Trojans will crack a defense that is probably faster
than any they will face this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the fastest defense I've ever seen. Their defensive
tackles run like linebackers,'' offensive lineman Travis Claridge
said. ``They whipped our butts.''
</P>
<P>
   Free safety Rashard Cook remembers being on the sideline,
marveling at the Seminoles' ability to shut down plays that
initially seemed successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like on a play, somebody was open and then they
would only get two yards,'' Cook said. ``They were all over the
place. When they tackled you, you were down.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the dilemma facing the Trojans' offense, which other
than tailback Chad Morton (95 yards per game), has not really found
its identity. And it has not had to flourish on the road or against
a top-notch opponent.
</P>
<P>
   That all changes Saturday at Doak Campbell Stadium. Will this be
a repeat performance of last year? Although the players vividly
remember being outclassed by Florida State's defense, some changes
give them reason to expect better success.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first reasons is Morton, who is faster than anyone
Florida State saw in last season's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we open up a hole, Chad will see it,'' Claridge said.
``That didn't happen last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Delon Washington gained 16 yards in 18 carries in last
year's contest, and Fox passed for just 159 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember everything about them. They were so fast,'' wide
receiver Mike Bastianelli said. ``If there's an opening, they close
it in a split-second.''
</P>
<P>
   Another major change is quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst, who has
shown better poise than Fox. Perhaps more important, Van Raaphorst
won't be making his first career start as Fox did a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stuff's open, you just have to capitalize on it,'' Fox
said.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's new coach Paul Hackett, who is supposed to be
an offensive wizard. Right? Hackett has been trying to get passes
off quicker in practice, to avoid succumbing to Florida State's
stifling pass rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed. Speed. Speed. They run by everybody,'' Hackett said.
``You need to slide around and make some plays. Pass protection in
combination with getting rid of it quickly. Or they're going to get
at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Easier said than done, especially when USC's offensive line has
been its weak link this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to really wire in,'' Claridge said.
``Their defensive tackles are something. I don't think I've ever
faced a guy better than (defensive tackle) Jerry Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Johnson dominated the line of scrimmage with seven
tackles. Also back is linebacker Lamont Green, who racked up 10
tackles. But their importance underscores another reason the
Trojans might be more optimistic this time. The Seminoles return
just five starters on defense. Gone are defensive end Andre
Wadsworth and linebackers Sam Cowart and Daryl Bush.
</P>
<P>
   That's the good news, although USC players were hardly
encouraged after watching game films this week. And yes, they are
aware the Seminoles were upset by North Carolina State 24-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're faster than any team we'll face this season by far,''
Bastianelli said. ``They might not be quite as fast as last year,
but they're still Florida State, so they will be fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Another crucial factor is whether the Trojans are able to hold
on to the ball. Hackett was upset after the Oregon State game by
the number of dropped passes, and he wasn't just referring to usual
suspect R. Jay Soward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disturbed by the number of drops in a game. You
can't have four, five, six drops in a game,'' Hackett said. ``One
of our biggest disappointments last week was when the the turnovers
and field position came to our offense, our offense was not able to
score touchdowns. We had to kick field goals, and if you kick field
goals against this team, you probably will come out on the short
end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
