u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-2ND     09-25 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ALMOST 200 DEAD IN CARIBBEAN, STORM HEADS TOWARD FLORIDA
KEYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs for new 5th graf updating storm's strength; subs 16th
graf to update number of Florida counties receiving hurricane
warnings.) (lh) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ As the death toll from Hurricane Georges's rampage
through the Caribbean rose to nearly 200, the storm crossed Cuba
Thursday, turned northward and took aim at southern Florida, where
750,000 people were advised to evacuate mobile homes and low-lying
coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
   At least 125 of the deaths were reported in the Dominican
Republic, where workers recovered 76 bodies Thursday from a river
in San Juan de la Maguana, 120 miles west of the capital, Santo
Domingo. Earlier, at least 45 people in the town of San Cristobal
were killed when the walls of a school being used as a shelter
collapsed in flood waters.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dominican Republic and Haiti, which share the island of
Hispaniola, hundreds of people were missing and feared dead. Leonel
Fernandez, president of the Dominican Republic, said the storm had
left more than 100,000 people homeless and severely damaged sugar,
banana, rice and coffee crops that were nearly ready for harvest.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a national tragedy,'' Fernandez said in a
televised address to the country's 7.5 million people. ``We face a
titanic task.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hurricane Georges moved back over open water, its winds
reached 90 mph late Thursday night and they were expected to reach
105 mph on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The airport in Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic, was closed
because of damage to the control tower and terminals. It was
uncertain when it would reopen, but the earliest estimate for
restoration of jet traffic was Sunday, American Airlines said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 3.8 million residents of Puerto Rico were reported
still to be without electricity and water. The local telephone
company said 339,000 of its customers had no long-distance service,
making communication with relatives in the continental United
States difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Some shops and restaurants have reopened, using generators as
their power source, and the government said it hoped to restore
power to half the island by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, officials reported two dead from the hurricane, both
electrocutions because of downed power lines. Civil Defense
officials warned residents to expect mudslides and coastal flooding
in the eastern part of the island up to Cayo Coco, a small island
popular with tourists north of Ciego de Avila in central Cuba, and
urged them to avoid the streets.
</P>
<P>
   About 370,000 people had been evacuated to safer areas in the
eastern provinces, but some had begun returning home Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Government television showed some rivers overrunning their banks
after seven hours of rain, cutting off some municipalities and
flooding nearby housing. Power was out in many areas.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, the energy expended by Hurricane Georges in its
four-day rampage across Puerto Rico, Hispaniola and Cuba appeared
to have exhausted the storm. But as the hurricane moved back out
over the warm waters of the Caribbean, it gained force, and
meteorologists warned that it could strengthen to a Category 3
storm, with winds over 125 miles per hour, by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   With the storm gaining speed and strength as it moved toward the
Florida Straits, forecasters predicted that the eye would strike
the Florida Keys early Friday. From Miami to Tampa, millions of
residents rushed to complete their storm preparations in
anticipation of that landfall and the flooding and destruction that
are expected to accompany it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992, we weren't as ready for Hurricane Andrew as we should
have been, and I vowed not to let that happen again,'' said Lisa de
Grandy as she loaded plywood into a van outside a home-supply store
here this morning. ``It's tense in there, like a scavenger hunt,
and this is not something I really want to be doing again, but we
want to suffer as little damage as possible this time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The course Hurricane Georges is thought most likely to follow in
the coming days would take it directly over the lower Keys early
Friday and on into the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of both Miami and Fort Lauderdale awoke Thursday to
find that a hurricane warning had been issued for their
communities. By late Thursday, warnings were posted for 5 million
people in eight counties _ Monroe, Miami-Dade, Broward, Collier,
Lee, Charlotte, Sarasota and Manatee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may become a major hurricane, and we need to be ready for
that,'' Jerry Jarrell, director of the National Hurricane Center
here, cautioned Thursday, after radar images indicated the eye of
the storm was reorganizing. ``People really need to count on it
being bad.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hurricane Georges was regrouping, Alex Penelas, the mayor of
Miami-Dade County, which has 2 million residents, issued a decree
for the evacuation of Miami Beach, Key Biscayne and other
communities on barrier islands facing the Atlantic. But the
directive was strictly voluntary, and many residents, especially
young people and those who did not experience Hurricane Andrew,
said they had no intention of complying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in a hurricane before, but I'm not
panicking,'' said Carolina Aguirre, a 32-year-old teacher and Miami
Beach resident. ``It's more dangerous to leave than to stay, so I
will stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of mobile homes and trailer parks, many of whom
experienced the full force of Hurricane Andrew and its 150 mph
winds, seemed to be treating a mandatory evacuation order for them
more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   At Fowler's trailer park in southern Miami-Dade County, Xiomara
Lopez, 44, and her family of five were loading an air-conditioner
and clothes into a truck and preparing to leave for a relative's
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trailer survived Andrew, but we're not taking any
chances,'' said her daughter, Ayza Corujo, 23. ``We're lucky,
because a lot of the people here are poor and don't have anyplace
to go. We're just praying that our home is still here when we come
back, because we don't have any insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation directive also applied to Homestead and Florida
City, both of which were leveled by Hurricane Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are extremely concerned because of the extensive flooding
we believe will be associated with this hurricane,'' Penelas said
Thursday afternoon in explaining the measure and announcing the
opening of public shelters across the county.
</P>
<P>
   James Witt, director of the federal Emergency Management Agency,
said: ``It is the storm surge coming behind the Keys that will have
a lot of the force. We're worried about flooding and crop damage.''
</P>
<P>
   Key West, through which the eye of the storm is expected to
pass, was reported Thursday to be virtually a ghost town, with
tourists having fled and hotels, bars and boutiques along normally
bustling Duval Street closed. The airport was closed this morning,
and a 9 p.m. curfew was ordered for the city and all the rest of
Monroe County.
</P>
<P>
   At Cape Canaveral, the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration initially ordered the space shuttle Discovery rolled
back to its hangar, three and a half miles from the Atlantic, but
decided Thursday evening to keep it on its seaside launching pad.
The shuttle had been moved to the pad on Monday for next month's
flight with Sen. John Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels in nearby Orlando were filling rapidly with residents
fleeing threatened areas further south, and MacDill Air Force Base
in Tampa was ordered evacuated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
