<HEADLINE>
SMITH, WILDCATS RACE PAST AZTECS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Summer turned to autumn in the time it took Arizona
to stay unbeaten.
</P>
<P>
   And unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a season changes into a challenge that is sure to change
the Wildcats, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats said so long to a sweet September and awaited an
uncertain October with a 35-16 victory Thursday night over San
Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   The win, itself, was predictable. But unpredictable was what it
said about the rest, the real, part of Arizona's season.
</P>
<P>
   It's either an Octoberfest, or the unmasking of a team
masquerading as a rising contender in the national polls. The party
starts on Oct. 3 at Washington. By then, Hawaii, Stanford, Iowa and
San Diego State will look a lot like stops on a rendition of what
the Wildcats did on their summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to start playing some of the best teams in the
country,''said Arizona coach Dick Tomey, whose Wildcats follow the
Washington date against Pacific-10 Conference favorite UCLA.
``We'll see if we belong.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, most of the numbers seem to say yes. The Wildcats are
4-0. They are No. 16 in both the Associated Press and USA
Today/ESPN polls.
</P>
<P>
   Their 19-point victory over San Diego State on ESPN's national
telecast could land them enough votes for a boost up the ratings
ladder to somewhere between tenth and 15th.
</P>
<P>
   But there are reasons for caution. So far, Arizona has compiled
its unbeaten record against teams with a cumulative mark of 2-9.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, San Diego State might rank as the worst. The Aztecs
are 0-3 without many apparent prospects at a winning season, much
less a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona is a very talented team,'' said San Diego State coach
Ted Tollner, who saw a few during his days as the head coach at
Southern California.``They just jumped all over us.''
</P>
<P>
   After giving up a field goal to San Diego State in the opening
minutes,the Wildcats struck hard and fast with their wide array of
talent.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, the Wildcat blitz accounted for two
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Strike one: Dennis Northcutt jumped out from behind a jarring
block by Chris McAlister and raced 51 yards on a punt return. On
the next play, quarterback Keith Smith hooked up with Jeremy
McDaniel for a 19-yard TD pass.
</P>
<P>
   Strike two: Linebacker Scotter Sprotte got the first of his two
interceptions, this one at the Aztec 39. Five plays later, Smith
rolls right and races 20 yards into the end zone with Aztec
defenders chasing after him as though he were a runaway
rollerblader.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats, playing their second game within a week, _ got it
all done within a handful of plays. Total elapsed time for both
scoring drives: 62 seconds, 14 for the first and 48 for the second.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody got a stop watch?
</P>
<P>
   By then, it was abundantly clear that the Aztecs were just
interactive spectators among the gathering of 23,811 at the
strangely named Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats put another seven points on the stadium's computer
board when senior running back Jim Wendler scored for the first
time in his career on a five-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   Wendler's debut in the end zone was set up by a 40-yard pass to
Kelvin Eafon from Ortege Jenkins, who came on in relief of Smith in
the second quarter of Arizona's eighth straight victory of a streak
that dates back to last season.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins ran right and threw left, across his body and the field,
to a wide-open Eafon. The play was a thing of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   It defined Arizona's dynamic potential. Tomey has an aerial
circus at his disposal. But this circus is like a lot of them.
Arizona's high-wire act does not include a net. The Wildcats are
often plagued by inconsistency and mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   The offense lost its sharp edge in the second half, despite a
10-yard TD strike from Jenkins to McDaniel in the third quarter.
That, in part, was rooted in an abridged playbook that was scaled
down at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``By then, we didn't want to show everything we had,'' said
Smith, who didn't mention Washington and didn't have to.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcat defense also let the Aztecs score two TDs after
halftime: one on a five yard pass from Brian Russell to Jim Ange
and the second on a 3-yard run by Larry Ned, who rushed for 144
yards.
</P>
<P>
   The first Aztec TD hurt. Frustration was evident in the face of
secondary coach Duane Akina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was angry,'' said Akina, a former Washington quarterback who
will undoubtedly use some of that anger in preparations next week
for Arizona's first test. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
