<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-GREEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN'S ARDUOUS TREK LANDS HIM WITH DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - That's one small step for a football player,
another giant leap for Gerald Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come a long way,'' Green said, not referring solely to
his climb up the Arizona State depth chart to No. 2 tailback.
</P>
<P>
   Making second team normally is little cause to stop and take
note, but Green is not a normal person, nor athlete. Which is why
backing up J.R. Redmond this week looms as large as, say, someone
bigger and stronger with a more conventional background making
All-American.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Green's story has been well-chronicled _ how he
surmounted a horrific childhood and a learning disability; how,
with his mother in prison, he lived five years in a Mesa home for
neglected and abused kids; how he attended two high schools and two
junior colleges and went mostly unrecruited beyond that; how his
old junior high coach and special education teacher got married and
became his guardians even though he is Black and they are White;
how he walked on at ASU this summer and forced a scholarship when
everyone realized this 5-foot-8, 190-pound bundle of sunshine and
energy could play.
</P>
<P>
   A junior, Green began fall camp as essentially fourth-string
behind Redmond, redshirt freshman Davaren Hightower and Marlon
Farlow, who was battling academic problems but whose status was
still up for grabs. Farlow never made it back, and Hightower, who
missed all of last season because of a broken leg, suffered a knee
sprain last week against North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond missed Tuesday's practice to attend a funeral, meaning
Green was the ``No''.``'' ``1'' tailback for a day. But Redmond,
who has a sprained toe, will carry most of the load Saturday at Sun
Devil Stadium against Oregon State. Green, who is not listed in the
team media guide, stands ready if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done everything we've asked him to do,'' running backs
Coach Cornell Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he knew nothing about Green's history or
attention-deficit disorder until he read about it. To Jackson,
Green was simply a friendly, upbeat kid who worked ceaselessly in
the weight room, watched a lot of tape, quickly picked up the
complicated blocking schemes (playing at pass-oriented Mesa
Community College last season helped) and ran hard despite his
purported lack of size.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I knew,'' said Jackson, ``was that here was a guy
determined to be a football player at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't put him out there if he didn't have the ability.
He's got the ability to carry the football, to block if the
linebacker comes. He's got good vision and quick feet. Good hands.
We're glad to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson sometimes teases Green, reminding him that he worked his
way up ``by default.'' But Jackson knows that really isn't true,
that even though the problems of others have created the
opportunity, Green still had to seize it.
</P>
<P>
   Green knows that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I could make it,'' he said. ``And here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Green made his ASU debut last week, playing mostly in a mop-up
role against North Texas and rushing nine times for 35 yards. After
getting up from the pile left by his first carry, he looked around
at the gold-shirted home crowd and thought, ``I'm a Sun Devil. This
isn't a dream. It's real.''
</P>
<P>
   If Green knows anything, it's what's real. And the reality is,
Redmond is the man. But Green wouldn't mind getting a little
quality time in relief. He figures his size is an asset, given that
teammates on defense have complained about locating him among the
mass of large bodies.
</P>
<P>
   But Green doesn't need to hide behind anyone. He has good speed
and loves contact. He enjoys blocking, especially when he gets to
``truck'' someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say the smallest guys pack the biggest punches,'' he
said. ``If you're willing to stick your head in there, you can do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything that happens on the football field is a joy compared
with what Green had to endure most of his life, to ``all that
commotion,'' as he calls it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you want,'' he said, ``you have to go through a lot
to get it.'' &QL; 
Note &QL; 
Starting tight end  &UR; Kendrick Bates remains questionable for the
Oregon State game with a shoulder injury suffered in practice. Look
for  &UR; Matt &UR; Cercone and first-year freshman  &UR; Todd Heap to get play
more. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
