<HEADER>
A3683 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-PEP-LADN     09-25 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-PEP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART OF THE PEP TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the middle of a dreary, winless football
season, a desperate coach tried to inspire his players before a
game a few years ago. Nothing seemed to work with this group.
Screaming fell on deaf ears. Encouragement was useless. This time
he used an example.
</P>
<P>
   The coach told the team about Larry Csonka, a hard-running
fullback who played for the Miami Dolphins in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry Csonka was just a tough SOB,'' the coach started off.
``He didn't care about stats. He didn't care about getting hurt. He
didn't care about himself. All Larry Csonka cared about was
winning. And that's how he played, to win.''
</P>
<P>
   For 10 minutes the coach talked about his hero, Larry Csonka:
Larry Csonka did this. Larry Csonka did that. Maybe if
!ital!we!off! played more like Larry Csonka, we'd win a ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all I have to say,'' the coach said, wrapping things
up. ``We have to play more like Larry Csonka.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, the coach left the locker room. The room fell quiet.
Nobody spoke as the players pondered what the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after a few silent minutes passed, a big lineman
sitting in the corner said: ``Man, f--- Larry Csonka.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly inspired, the team went out and got crushed.
</P>
<P>
   The art of inspiration
</P>
<P>
   Pep talks are as much a part of football as tackling. At the
right moment, when delivered by the right coach, a well-crafted
speech can motivate a team to play beyond its ability. Others, like
the one about Larry Csonka, couldn't rouse a dog from its sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Some pep talks challenge players, others calm them. The
objective is to provoke teams to a proper level of intensity,
although the tricky part is not pushing players past that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they're liable to go out there and do stupid stuff,''
Newbury Park coach George Hurley said. ``You need to know how to
get them fired up but also when to rein them in.''
</P>
<P>
   Some coaches find that the fire-and-brimstone, ``It's us against
them'' speeches work best, but a case can also be made for control
and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to remind them about who they are, what their
responsibilities are and what's at stake,'' Sylmar coach Jeff
Engilman said. ``They have pride, they know that they're playing
for themselves and the guys that have been here in the past and
built this program up.''
</P>
<P>
   Choosing your words carefully
</P>
<P>
   There are two talks a coach gives his team. One before the game,
the other at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, just a few prudent words can do the trick before
a game. A wise coach understands that his players have built up
enough emotion through the course of the week. By game time, a
simple reminder of what lies ahead is more effective then a
contrived, chest-thumping sermon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you aren't pumped up by the time of the game, then
definitely some yelling and screaming is needed,'' Agoura wide
receiver Garrett Lepisto said. ``But most of the time, we're ready
to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a coach can make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   That happened in the early 1960s when Glendale hosted Crescenta
Valley in the Falcons' first varsity game. Crescenta Valley was the
new school in town, and a number of Falcons players attended
Glendale before moving on to Crescenta Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Glendale was coached by the legendary Roy
Vujovich, an imposing figure who spoke with a booming voice.
Vujovich made his players sit in a dark room before games to
visualize making big plays and key tackles. After a half-hour,
Vujovich would speak.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Crescenta Valley game, Vujovich stood in the doorway
as he spoke to the Dynamiters. The Glendale players barely made out
his silhouette as he talked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men,'' Vujovich said, his voice deep and steady. ``Two years
ago we gave those guys over there some helmets and shoulder pads
and wished them good luck with their program. Tonight, they're
back.''
</P>
<P>
   That was all Vujovich needed to say. The Dynamiters ran out of
the room ready to beat the Green Bay Packers. Crescenta Valley
never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Not that a well-planned speech doesn't work also.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago Newbury Park was playing a team many considered
superior to the Panthers. George Hurley finished his own pregame
talk and then turned things over to assistant Jack Willard.
Willard, now the coach at Channel Islands, was wearing a
button-downed dress shirt and tie as he spoke. He started his
speech under control, but that didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next thing you know he climbs on top of a table,'' Hurley
remembered. ``Then he rips open his shirt, buttons are flying
everywhere, and he's wearing a blue shirt underneath with a big red
S on it. He starts screaming `If we play like f------ Superman we
can win this f------ game. Now let's go out there and get after
it!!!'''
</P>
<P>
   Hurley doesn't remember who won the game, but he knows this
much: The Panthers were ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, I was ready to run out of that room and play,'' Hurley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more colorful stuff takes place at halftime when
games are hanging in the balance and emotions are high. That's when
coaches challenge players, appealing to their pride and toughness.
But it can also get dicey. Coaches have been known to turn over
tables, punch lockers and attack chalk boards, all in the pursuit
of motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year one of our coaches, and it wasn't me, hit a table
full of water cups and the water went all over a poor kid sitting
nearby,'' said Canyon coach Larry Mohr. ``You've got to be careful.
You may end up punching something and coming to practice Monday
wearing as cast.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is also the zany, when a coach simply losses
it. Such was the case a few years ago when the coach of a winless
team went off on his players at halftime of the last game of the
year. He was tired and disgusted and let his players know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what's sad?'' the coach asked. ``It's sad that the
only thing that motivates you guys is fear. The fear of me kicking
your f------ a-- at practice on f------ Monday after you've played
like s--- on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But guess what? There are no more f------ Mondays, so I can't
kick your f------ a-- anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who were there remember that players chuckled to
themselves during the rampage, which was delivered in a calm,
almost scary voice. When the coach left the room, the players burst
out laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Be yourself
</P>
<P>
   For coaches, the key to pep talks is, as coaches are fond of
saying, staying within themselves. Some have the ability to weave
an inspiring speech, then deliver it smoothly and effectively.
Others trip over themselves when they say anything more then ``Go
get them, boys.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing worse then listening to a tongue-tied coach
spin a shaky speech. And the minute players sense a phony, they'll
tune him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some coaches will sit there and b.s. you and say all kinds of
stuff,'' said Westlake wide receiver Travis Campbell. ``When all
they need to do is tell the truth. Our coaches just say, `It's
gametime, guys. Either put up or shut up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
