<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3684 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-MANNING-AZR &LR;      09-25 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-MANNING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANNING'S PROGRESS SURPRISING  
 SUNS FORWARD AIMS TO PLAY BY DECEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When the NBA owners and players finally settle their
differences and decide to play basketball again, the Suns may have
a pleasant surprise awaiting them.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Danny Manning, who underwent the third reconstructive
knee surgery of his career in April and was thought to be out for
most of next season, may be ready to play as early as December.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a huge boost for the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Manning won the NBA's Sixth Man of the Year award last season,
despite missing the last six regular season games because of the
knee injury. He averaged 13.5 points and 5.6 rebounds a game while
shooting 51.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Manning is one of only three players currently under contract
with the club, along with Jason Kidd and Mark Bryant. Knowing that
Manning will be available for most of the season will make it a lot
easier for the Suns to determine which free agents they want to go
after when the lockout ends.
</P>
<P>
   Manning needed almost a year to come back from each of his two
previous surgeries, but he's cautiously optimistic about a much
quicker return this time.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is the type of surgery. Instead of having a third
of his patella tendon removed and used to replace his anterior
cruciate ligament, the ligament of a cadaver was implanted.
</P>
<P>
   Because Manning's patella tendons had been used in the two
previous procedures _ the first on his right knee during his rookie
season of 1988-89 and the second on his left knee in February 1995
_ the patella transplant wasn't an option this time.
</P>
<P>
   The risk of using a cadaver's tissue is that a person might
reject the ligament, and thorough testing has to be done to make
sure there is a match and that there is no chance of contracting a
disease from the donor.
</P>
<P>
   Manning said if his body was going to reject the ligament, it
already would have happened.
</P>
<P>
   The big advantage of the procedure is that it allows ``a more
aggressive'' rehabilitation process, according to Manning, his
personal trainer, Karl Horne, and Dr. Richard Emerson, the club's
orthopedic surgeon who teamed with Dr. Stephen Lomardo of the
Kerlan-Jobe Clinic in Los Angeles on the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had known then what I know now, and if they had the same
thorough testing available, I would have done it this way the first
two times,'' Manning said. ``It is a quicker process, but a lot of
it still depends on the person and what they're going to do, how
hard they're going to work at the rehab. I've been through this
three times now. I pretty much know what has to be done. I just
have to get my work done every day.''
</P>
<P>
   While it seems that Manning is far ahead of schedule, this is
apparently what the Suns and Manning hoped for when the cadaver
option was considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's doing very well,'' said Emerson, who is allowed to work
with Manning despite the lockout. ``I'd say his rehabilitation is
progressing very well. If everything keeps going as well as it has
been, we would anticipate that he would be activated, possibly by
the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Horne said that's the target Manning has been shooting for, and
Manning has responded to the more aggressive approach. But Manning
has enough experience in the process to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could go out tomorrow and aggravate it,'' Manning said.
``Right now, it's going very well. But there's a fine line there
between doing too much and not doing enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, it has to get strong enough to take the pounding from
running. Then you have to start doing the basketball things, like
cutting and jumping. But as much as you work out, there is no way
to simulate NBA-level competition and the demands of practicing and
playing every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Manning could have retired and avoided all the
rehabilitation work. He never seriously considered it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know why I'm doing this,'' he said. ``I'm doing it because I
want to, because I still believe I can play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' Manning added with a smile, ``even if I'm not quite as
quick as I was before, I'm still 6-10.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
