<SLUG> BC-BBM-DBACKS-EL-PASO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIABLOS JOIN D-BACKS FARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SHANA NEWELL  
 c.1998 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO _ The Diamondbacks continued their quest to become
``Mexico's favorite major league operation'' by announcing Thursday
that the Texas border town of El Paso will become the franchise's
first Double-A affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks signed a four-year working agreement with the
Texas League team, and held dual news conferences in El Paso and
across the border in neighboring Juarez, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so close to Mexico in Phoenix, in our Triple-A team in
Tucson and now in El Paso, we would like to become Mexico's
favorite major league operation,'' Senior Executive Vice President
Roland Hemond said. ``We have a working agreement with Monterrey,
and we work closely with Hermosillo in the Mexican Pacific League
in winter ball.''
</P>
<P>
   When its 18-year relationship with the Milwaukee Brewers ended,
six major league teams, including the Diamondbacks, expressed
interest in El Paso, which is about six hours southeast of Phoenix
along I-10.
</P>
<P>
   El Paso is the westernmost Double-A franchise, and Arizona
competed with Anaheim, Colorado, Seattle and Oakland for the right
to call the city home. But El Paso, looking to expand its own
horizons, saw Arizona as an opportunity to cash in on the market
across the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is it geographically desirable for us,'' Diablos
President Rick Parr said, ``but we want to build a friendly
relationship with our fans across the border. Once you're a friend,
you're family for life. The Diamondbacks have already started that
relationship, and we're going to ride those coattails.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have moved to spark interest among Mexican fans
with a Triple-A team in Monterrey of the Mexican League and by
arranging travel packages from Mexican cities such as Nogales.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of El Paso in its minor league ranks gives Arizona
yet another bridge to the Mexican market. Without professional
baseball for nine years, since the Mexican League's Juarez Indios
folded, Juarez is starving for the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks hope to draw the attention of the Hispanic
market by staging player appearances, exhibition games and more in
El Paso and Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   El Paso, known as the Diablos for 25 years, will not change its
team name, but a new logo was revealed Thursday incorporating the
Diamondbacks' recognizable ``A'' in the word ``Diablos.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks also announced Thursday that Manager Don
Wakamatsu, pitching coach Dennis Lewallyn and hitting coach Ty Van
Burkleo will move from High Desert to El Paso for the 1999 season.
Wakamatsu was the California League's Manager of the Year after
leading High Desert to an 82-58 mark and a second-half title. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
