<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING FOR SENSE OF HUMOR MIGHT BE DIFFICULT IN NEBRASKA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Having seen the movie ``Fargo,'' I have some anxiety
about the Midwest passion for woodchipper justice.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I will sojourn to the heartland this morning,
laptop holstered, eyes squinted for trouble, ready to meet the Big
Dread . . . er, Red.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly, my purpose in going to Lincoln, Neb., is to write
about Saturday's Washington-Nebraska college football game. My real
goal was larger _ to find the continental drain.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, before the Husker-Husky game in Seattle, I wrote
that there was not much to recommend Nebraska and its team, other
than as an ideal site to draw down any oversupply of national
liquids. Which was just one of several sensitive and helpful
thoughts I offered that day.
</P>
<P>
   The local paper, the Lincoln Journal Star (Motto: ``Nebraska
Football, and the Rest of the World on Page B-20''), ran the
column, which provoked a wounded wail among the citizenry the likes
of which I have never heard in my time as a paid keyboard slapper.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hundreds of letters, faxes, e-mails and packages from
grumpy Nebraskans (state motto: ``Boy, do we have a lot of free
time'') was a notable scold from Gov. Ben Nelson, who took a moment
from a press conference to upbraid the scoundrel from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   When I responded that it was surprising the gubernatorial
bloomers were bunched as tightly as the rest of Nebraska's
citizens, the governor, with a politician's sixth sense about bad
PR, reversed course.
</P>
<P>
   He invited me to be his guest for the Washington-Nebraska
rematch. Get to know us, he said in a letter. He even promised to
supply the overalls.
</P>
<P>
   Having never been to Nebraska _ really, who has? _ the
temptation was strong. I wanted to find out if these people have so
much chaw in their cheeks they don't know there is room for tongues
in there too.
</P>
<P>
   So I accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a scoop for you,'' Diane Gonzolas, the governor's
public affairs director, said by phone earlier this week. ``We sold
the continental drain rights to Oklahoma.''
</P>
<P>
   Argh. What a loss, for my column and Nebraska. I'll find
something else to write about, but now the state really must be
down to one thing, and one thing only _ Husker football.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Washington coach Jim Lambright put it succinctly in his
Monday press conference, ``The program runs the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, Lambo _ I needed a buddy in the dungeon with me (not
that dungeons and Nebraska can be easily distinguished . . . ah,
jeez, there I go again).
</P>
<P>
   Really, I'm going to make my best effort to be open-minded. The
governor's office sent me piles of wonderful visitor information
about Nebraska, and I've read all of it. Did you know that tourism
is Nebraska's third-largest industry? (No. 1, of course, is
offensive linemen with size-22 necks, and No. 2 is red textiles.)
</P>
<P>
   Details about the tourism industry were scant, so I don't know
if they were counting the cross-country drivers who stop for gas.
It's a long state, so a dried-out burrito under a mini-mart heat
lamp is almost a mandatory tourist purchase.
</P>
<P>
   But is there tourism other than for Big Red football? Not if you
judge by the other great piece of literature from Nebraska _ the
university's football media guide (price, $13; weight, 3.1 pounds;
words, 6.2 million, give or take a hosannah in front of the name
Tom Osborne).
</P>
<P>
   The creation of this work must occupy the rest of the state not
engaged in the top three industries. The detail is breathtaking.
Did you know that this year's team lost 435 pounds of fat, gained
145 pounds of muscle and improved 161 inches in the vertical jump?
</P>
<P>
   As an investigator of the obscure and pointless, Ken Starr, you
are a dilettante compared to these people.
</P>
<P>
   At least in regard to the notion that too much is never enough,
perhaps Nebraskans are little different from other Americans, who
are scrupulously loyal to the cultural mandate that I believe is
somewhere in the Constitution: nothing succeeds like excess.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing unusual about Nebraskans is that when the fact is
pointed out to them, they forget to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   So in the absence of a continental drain, I will search instead
for a sense of humor. I've been promised a tour of the Capitol, a
visit to the annual meeting of the state's political, business and
community leaders, and a tailgate lunch Saturday at the governor's
residence.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in these red-festooned throngs must be someone who
isn't dead-serious about Nebraska and its football team, someone
who doesn't have a welcome mat at the foot of the woodchipper.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 0134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
