<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-PLAYOFFS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES' FUTURE UNCERTAIN  
 WEST CHAMPS ARE DEPENDENT ON FREE AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres will part ways with the Diamondbacks on
Sunday, headed to a far better place _ the exciting and
nerve-racking world of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring how difficult it is to advance, San Diego has
qualified for the playoffs for only the third time in its 30-year
history. Even though this is the second time in three years that
the Padres have reached this level, their future appears tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Four key members of the team are potential free agents. All-Star
pitcher Kevin Brown, who could have been a Cy Young Award candidate
with any kind of run support, heads the list.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman and former Most Valuable Player Ken Caminiti,
center fielder Steve Finley and first baseman Wally Joyner also
will be free agents after this season.
</P>
<P>
   What was perceived as a dogfight for the division title quickly
turned into a runaway this summer, with San Diego grabbing an early
lead and pulling away, which had to come as a surprise to General
Manager Kevin Towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's got a feeling that we've got our work cut out for
us,'' Towers said during spring training. ``Three or four clubs (in
the NL West) could be close to 90 wins. I really think this is a
division that's going to be played out in September. Nobody's going
to run away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Padres did run away. Now the attention turns to the
postseason and what San Diego will do in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   The team's core could be missing next year, and the Padres can't
expect some of the other potential monsters in the National League
West to keep making blunders.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the big-money franchises in Los Angeles and
Colorado are sleeping giants that could awaken at any moment,
especially the Dodgers, who just hired the highly respected Kevin
Malone as their general manager.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has a new ballpark on the way, a fact that could
easily translate into streams of revenue flowing into the Giants'
budget. And if the Diamondbacks' inaugural season is a fair
barometer, then they will shoot into the elite when it comes to the
ability to spend.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves San Diego, which is anxiously awaiting the results
of a November referendum for a new downtown park. The Padres' front
office has made not-so-subtle remarks concerning the club's future
in San Diego if voters fail to support the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of the Padres is, I guess the fairest way to put it
is, uncertain,'' club President Larry Lucchino said earlier this
season. ``We are proud of what we are doing and trying to do. And
this is an important time for the franchise, as it is for the city
and the whole county.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to make baseball solid, stable, competitive
and anchored in San Diego for a long time to come, if humanly
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Which all points to what an important postseason this will be
for the Padres, who enter this weekend having won just nine of
their past 24 games. Another sweep in the first round of the
playoffs, like the one St. Louis handed San Diego two years ago,
could be devastating.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres will do everything they can to keep Brown in the
coming years, but the reality is that they may not be able to
compete with some of the offers Brown is expected to receive,
specifically anything in the $50 million to $70 million range.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has been everything San Diego expected, posting an 18-7
record with a 2.36 ERA, the tiniest in the NL. Padres pitching
coach Dave Stewart has said Brown has pitched well enough to have
won at least 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   Over a recent 10-game stretch, the Padres averaged 1.4 runs when
Brown pitched. He pitched nine scoreless innings in his last start
but got no decision when San Diego lost, 1-0, in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will take Kevin Brown head to head with Randy Johnson in any
game,'' Towers told the ``San Diego Union-Tribune.'' ``On
AstroTurf, cement, asphalt, grass, you name it. I'll take my
chances with Kevin Brown anywhere, I don't care where it's at.''
</P>
<P>
   Towers may very well get his wish. Houston and San Diego are
potential first-round playoff partners. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
