<SLUG> BC-FBN-FANTASY-MULLER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL IS DOUBLING AS SENIOR QB TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though I somehow missed the press release, the NFL apparently
decided to honor the past Sunday with its first unofficial
old-timers day.
</P>
<P>
   Playing for the Jets,  &UR; Vinny Testaverde used his long years of
experience to toss four touchdown passes against the Colts.
 &UR; Randall
 &UR; Cunningham (still scrambling, slowly) helped the Vikings beat the
Lions with five (yawn) field goals, and Denver dusted off  &UR; Bubby
 &UR; Brister's old bones to euthanize the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere,  &UR; Joe Theismann is warming up.
</P>
<P>
   I think more than one fan thought  &UR; Boomer Esiason could have
sprinted straight from the ``Monday Night Football'' booth and done
a better job than  &UR; Danny Kanell against the Cowboys. I'm sure
Boomer did.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, is Kanell from the Planet Earth? He has at least heard
of
 &UR; Deion Sanders, right?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, all these old fogies are fighting their way into
the lineup because NFL quarterbacks have the life expectancy of a
Mediterranean fruit fly these days.
</P>
<P>
   For fantasy owners, it's time to take stock of the quarterback
position. If you drafted  &UR; Brett Favre,  &UR; Steve Young,  &UR; Mark Brunell
or
 &UR; Drew Bledsoe, you're grinning a big grin about now.
</P>
<P>
   We are not amused.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I guess things could be worse.  &UR; Dave Brown could be
starting somewhere. Still, as disasters go, it's right up there
with ``Black'' ``Sunday''.
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore,  &UR; Jim Harbaugh is essentially a large welt, meaning
always-the-bridesmaid  &UR; Eric Zeier is the answer. The question: How
will the Ravens lose 10 games this year?
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde's solid performance against the Colts makes the Jets
quarterback situation a mess for fantasy owners. Amazingly, Coach
 &UR; Bill
 &UR; Parcells is more worried about winning games that having one
quarterback with good statistics. Parcells reportedly has invested
in a giant cane that he'll use to yank  &UR; Glenn Foley at the first
sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile,  &UR; Charlie Batch (Charlie Batch?) is starting for the
Lions, but for how long is anyone's guess. He did an incredible
 &UR; Scott
 &UR; Mitchell impression Sunday (40 attempts, 20 completions, two picks
and no touchdowns), much to the chagrin of  &UR; Bobby Ross.
</P>
<P>
   The young guys haven't done much better. Chargers quarterback
 &UR; Ryan
 &UR; Leaf is scanning the schedule for Oregon State, and Indianapolis
quarterback  &UR; Peyton Manning has finally realized the significance
of wearing a horseshoe on your head.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, you're going to get stepped on.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a glimmer of hope. A few quarterbacks who probably
went undrafted in your league are putting up decent numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington,  &UR; Trent Green looks like he'll hold on to the
starter's job for a while. Cunningham should produce solid numbers
while  &UR; Brad
 &UR; Johnson is on the mend. And  &UR; Tony Banks always has the potential
for a big day in St. Louis, though  &UR; Isaac Bruce has been plagued by
a bad hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, in Dallas, there's  &UR; Jason Garrett, whose SAT
scores were waaaay higher than yours. &QL; 
Tip of the week &QL; 
Denver is riding high and headed for a letdown Sunday in
Washington. Green,  &UR; Terry Allen and  &UR; Michael Westbrook might just
be worth starting. Cincinnati quarterback  &UR; Neil O'Donnell should
have a bounce-back game against Baltimore. &QL; 
Waiver wire &QL; 
The running back situation is a mess. In Baltimore,  &UR; Jay Graham
and &UR; Errict Rhett have been benched in favor of obscure backup
 &UR; Priest
 &UR; Holmes. In Dallas,  &UR; Sherman Williams or  &UR; Chris Warren will start if
 &UR; Emmitt Smith can't go. In St. Louis,  &UR; Greg Hill's broken leg means
more time for  &UR; Robert Holcombe. In Jacksonville,  &UR; James Stewart is
done for the year, meaning  &UR; Fred Taylor will start. &QL; 
One-hit wonder &QL; 
This week, it's Jets running back  &UR; Leon Johnson, who scored three
touchdowns against the Colts. He shall be Leon, and he shall be a
flash in the pan. &QL; 
Bill Muller's Fantasy Football notebook appears every Friday. He
can be reached at 602-444-8178 or at bill.muller(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
