<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANDERS, BRUCE REUNITE SUNDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. -  &UR; Frank Sanders used to be the best blocking tight
end at Fort Lauderdale Dillard High School.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 Florida Class 5A state champions didn't need to throw
him the ball. They had two 1,000-yard rushers and a wide receiver
who would end up being one of the best in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the high school secondary trying to cover Sanders and
 &UR; Isaac
 &UR; Bruce, the St. Louis Rams wide receiver who leads the NFL in
receiving yards with 323 and is second in catches with 21.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders and Bruce will be together again Sunday when the
Cardinals play the Rams at the Trans World Dome in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was smooth,'' Sanders said of Bruce. ``Now, he has become
more explosive. When I watch him (on film), I say, `This is Isaac?'
''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Lauderdale Dillard lost only one game in 1989 when Sanders
was a junior and Bruce was a senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody stopped us,'' said Sanders, who began his high-school
career as a left-handed quarterback. ``We had 90 players, and the
starters were out by halftime.''
</P>
<P>
   After Bruce graduated, Sanders was moved to wide receiver. He
caught 33 passes for 704 yards and 10 touchdowns for another team
that lost only one game. &QL; 
Nervous times
</P>
<P>
   Sanders and offensive tackle  &UR; Lomas Brown, a native of Miami,
Fla., have been concerned about Hurricane Georges, which is headed
for the Florida Keys.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and father have been here and were going to go back
to Miami Friday,'' Brown said. ``Now, they will wait through the
weekend to see what happens. But they forgot to (put) boards up or
storm shutters, and there's no one there who can help them. I
understand what they're going through. I lost a home there to
(Hurricane) Andrew six years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie defensive linemen  &UR; Andre Wadsworth, a native of St.
Croix, Virgin Islands, and  &UR; Jomo Cousins, who grew up in Jamaica,
said they also have talked to their families to make sure they're
OK. &QL; 
Stealing signs
</P>
<P>
   Rams middle linebacker  &UR; Eric Hill, who spent nine years with the
Cardinals, acknowledges that he knows most of his former team's
defensive signals. But Cardinals Coach  &UR; Vince  &UR; Tobin said he
doesn't expect to change them for Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We holler in a lot of our signals, anyway,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals expect Hill to be psyched and play well despite
having a broken hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the last of a dying breed,'' center  &UR; Mike Devlin said.
``He'll hit you in the mouth. Eric would rather run through you to
make a play than run around you. When you're going against him, you
know it's going to be physical. You have to hit force with force.
If he smells any back-off on you, it's going to be a long, long
day.'' &QL; 
Happy returns &QL; 
Second-year cornerback  &UR; Ty Howard, who has been inactive the first
three games, will replace injured  &UR; J.J. McCleskey.
</P>
<P>
   McCleskey underwent arthroscopic knee surgery Thursday and will
be out about four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ty's finally back healthy,'' Tobin said. ``He was a good
training camp until his knee started bothering him. Now, he's back
to where he was before he got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard said he didn't lose confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been down,'' he said. ``My goal still is to be a
starting corner. But I have to take small steps before the giant
one.'' &QL; 
New look &QL; 
A new short-arm cast was placed on the injured left wrist of
linebacker  &UR; Jamir Miller, who practiced Thursday but still doesn't
know if he'll play Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends how I feel,'' Miller said. ``I felt pretty good,
but a cast is a very restrictive thing. Still, it's not that bad. I
can still use my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver  &UR; Rob Moore (hamstring), running back  &UR; Larry
Centers (hamstring) and offensive guard  &UR; Lester Holmes (ankle)
didn't practice. Only Moore should miss the game.
</P>
<P>
   Punter  &UR; Scott Player, slowed by a calf injury, is expected to
test the leg today. He hasn't punted this week because of the
injury. &QL; 
Staff writer Tim Tyers contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
