<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-SAPP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAPP'S SHIFT: BACK TO 'BACKER  
 EX-QUARTERBACK FINDS SUCCESS ON DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Your son, the prep All-American, has been a
starting quarterback at Clemson for 2{ years. He comes to you at
semester break and says he plans to tell his coaches that he wants
to be a linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are _ shriek! _ you react the same way Patrick Sapp's
parents did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was like, `No, you shouldn't do it,' '' Sapp said.
``Even my coaches were sort of against it when I told them. But it
was my decision. I told them I had given them three years at
quarterback and now it was time that I gave myself my best
opportunity to make it into the league (NFL).''
</P>
<P>
   For most people, one spring training and a summer wouldn't be
enough time to gain the needed ``good'' bulk to play the position,
but in Sapp's case, he had been a 240-pound wishbone quarterback
and had to put on only 10 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good about the decision,'' he said. ``I was benched
halfway through my junior season at quarterback. We had a new
coaching staff and the new system better fit the guy who replaced
me. Most of our linebackers were graduating, so I thought I had a
good chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, after the first play I lined up at linebacker,
I knew I'd made the right decision. It helped going from
quarterback because I had read defenses and it helped me understand
them. Also, it helped me recognize what the offense was trying to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a credit to his rare athletic ability that his gamble paid
off. He not only made the transition, but is playing his third
season in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   His rookie season in San Diego was spent mostly on special
teams, and he started nine games during his second year before
coming to the Cardinals in the big trade in which the Cardinals
swapped No. 1 draft positions with the Chargers and came away with
Eric Metcalf and the Chargers' No. 1 pick in the 1999 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he was basically considered a throw in, Sapp's
acquisition paid dividends last week when he filled in for injured
Jamie Miller and acquitted himself well.
</P>
<P>
   This Sunday in St. Louis, unless Miller can play with his
dislocated left wrist in a cast, he will be starting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played OK,'' defensive coordinator Dave McGinnis said of
Sapp's play against the Eagles. ``I wasn't displeased. He made a
big play on the one fumble. He's not a finished product by any
means, and he can't afford to become complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ongoing process. He has great intelligence and
athletic ability. His biggest thing is intensity and playing at a
high intensity level for a complete game.''
</P>
<P>
   But is he ready to start if Miller can't go?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we're hitting the beach; it's not about whether he's
ready or not,'' McGinnis said. ``We want results. He's getting paid
and he's wearing the uniform. We're not interested in progress. We
want results. We can worry about progress in camp, but we're not in
camp any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Sapp knows what the situation is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm ready,'' he said. ``You practice every week like
you're going to be thrown in there, but it's kind of hard because
it doesn't always happen. On that day, I was ready and made some
plays that helped us win, and I feel good about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different this week and so is my approach. I'm feeling
confident coming off last week and I've been working some with the
first group and playing at their tempo. I haven't played a whole
game yet, and maintaining the intensity and concentration level you
need for that many snaps is my biggest challenge.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
