<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MARINERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CLOSE IN ON TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The American League West cannot be won until tonight.
</P>
<P>
   July 31, though, likely will be viewed as the afternoon the
Rangers captured the division title.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Todd Zeile and shortstop Royce Clayton, whom
general manager Doug Melvin acquired in trades along with
right-hander Todd Stottlemyre on July 31 before the trade deadline,
served as the catalysts during the Rangers' 9-3 victory against the
Mariners last night at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   The victory kept the Rangers three games in front of the
second-place Anaheim Angels, who defeated Oakland, 10-6, and
reduced their magic number to one with three games remaining. The
Rangers will lay claim to their second AL West title in three
seasons with one more victory in Seattle or one loss by the Angels
during the season's final three days.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Aaron Sele got his 19th victory, giving up three
runs, eight hits and five walks in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile and Clayton played significant roles during the Rangers'
decisive three-run second and third innings last night. The two
infielders went 3-for-3 with two runs batted in and scored three
times as the Rangers erased a 1-0, first-inning deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile and Clayton also helped propel the Rangers to five
consecutive victories against the Angels since Sept. 16, and
Stottlemyre defeated the Angels twice in his two starts Monday and
Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made moves,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said, ``that
really didn't benefit us until the last few days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels noticed the difference those three players made
during their recent five games with the Rangers. The Angels,
recall, failed to make a significant addition before or after the
trade deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not supposed to be here,'' Angels shortstop Gary
DiSarcina told reporters after the Rangers' 9-1 victory Tuesday in
Anaheim. ``Everyone is hurt, and we didn't make a damn move at the
trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strange how those three guys helped beat us in the last two
games. Clayton had a great game \RMonday\S. Todd hit a homer
against us, and Stottlemyre pitched two great games.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile served as the second-inning catalyst with his two-out
double against Mariners right-hander Mac Suzuki (1-2) and scored
the tying run on Clayton's single.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton advanced to second on the throw to the plate and later
scored on Tom Goodwin's triple that eluded the glove of Mariners
right fielder Ryan Radmanovich, who was bidding for a sliding catch
on the Kingdome's artificial surface. Left fielder Rusty Greer
later collected the Rangers' fourth two-out hit of the inning with
a run-scoring single to center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers built a 6-1 lead in the third inning. First baseman
Will Clark led off the inning with a double and eventually scored
on a triple by designated hitter Lee Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile drew a one-out walk, and Clayton followed with a
run-scoring single that chased Suzuki from the game. Zeile later
scored his second run in two innings on an error charged to
Mariners catcher Dan Wilson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
