<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS MUST CATCH THE BUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Jon Kitna has been Kordell Stewart for all of
two days. But the Seahawks' scout-team quarterback has taken enough
snaps as the Pittsburgh Steelers' starter to figure out the best
way to stop Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   With Stewart making only his 24th NFL start in Sunday's marquee
matchup at Three Rivers Stadium, the Seahawks need to treat him the
same way they have three other young quarterbacks this season.
</P>
<P>
   Which is, rudely and aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still young,'' said Kitna, who is running the Steelers'
offense against the Seahawks' defense in practice this week. ``I'd
come after Kordell and make him prove that he's going to beat you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a defensive coordinator,'' Kitna added, ``but I'd come
after him.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad read by Kitna. Pressuring Stewart into another poor
performance is exactly what the Seahawks would like to do.
</P>
<P>
   One small problem. Actually, make that one very large problem:
Jerome Bettis, the Steelers' battering-ram of a running back.
Stopping the Steelers starts with slowing down the player they call
The Bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to know at no point will they abandon the running
game. That's why they have the big backs. They want to wear you
down,'' said linebacker Chad Brown, who played with the Steelers
for four seasons before signing with the Seahawks last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what if you stop them in the first quarter, second quarter,
third quarter? You can't last,'' he said. ``They're going to run
the ball and keep pounding on you and hope that you break. They
start every quarter running the football. In the fourth quarter, if
you start to bend, they'll break you.''
</P>
<P>
   Detouring this Bus will take the same kind of swarming defense
that has helped the Seahawks dominate three lightweights from the
NFC East in their first 3-0 start since 1986. The 250-pound Bettis
is not the kind of back who can be tackled by one player.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerome is a load. That's why they call him The Bus,''
defensive tackle Cortez Kennedy said. ``He's tough to bring down.
We've got to gang-tackle him. That Bus gets rolling, then he turns
into a big ol' semi-truck when he gets into that secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: 180-pound cornerback Willie Williams one-on-one
with Bettis in the open field is not a matchup the Seahawks want to
see.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the secret, but also the trick, to stopping Stewart
and the Steelers. If a defense becomes too preoccupied with the
smash, the flash can burn them. If all the efforts are centered on
containing the dash, there's not enough left to counter the bash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing these guys is like facing three different offenses,''
defensive tackle Sam Adams said. ``They're capable of running trick
plays very well. They've capable of throwing the ball if they
really want to. And, of course, they've very capable of running the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   As Kitna said, the Seahawks need to back Stewart into a
we-dare-you-to-beat-us corner. Dangerous? Yes. Stewart ran and
passed for 32 TDs and nearly 3,500 yards of offense last year. But
that's the A side. The B side to the egnamatic Stewart was being
intercepted twice while throwing into double- and triple-coverage
in the Steelers' loss to the Denver Broncos in the AFC Championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Stewart has thrown six interceptions in three games,
completed 45.7 percent of his passes and his quarterback rating is
the lowest in the league (38.0). In last week's 21-0 loss to the
Dolphins, Stewart was 11 of 35 for 82 yards, with three
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks, meanwhile, lead the NFL with 19 sacks, are second
in the league with six interceptions and tied for third with four
fumble recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   These contrasting numbers add up to a mismatch. But the looks on
the faces of the Seahawks' defenders say, ``Yeah, right.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Darrin Smith played Stewart and the Steelers in Super
Bowl XXX while with the Dallas Cowboys. He has seen how the player
who was once called Slash for his versatility can turn a broken
play into a big play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to keep him in the pocket. You let Kordell get
outside the pocket, he's got too much speed,'' Smith said. ``They
can use him like a running back because of his speed and his
vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to play quarterbacks like that who are so mobile.''
</P>
<P>
   HAWK TALK: LB Dean Wells returned to practice Thursday and moved
well enough that he should be able to play this week, coach Dennis
Erickson said. Wells has missed the first three games with a pulled
right calf. . . . Also returning to practice were WR Joey Galloway
(sprained ankle) and DE Phillip Daniels (concussion). Galloway
still was limited, but Daniels worked with the No. 1 defense . . .
CB Shawn Springs passed out chocolate bars to celebrate the birth
of his twins. The wrapper reads ``Here They Are.'' On the back, it
says, ``Manufactured by Shawn and Ellie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 0139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
