<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COUGARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMPSON RETURNS HOME FOR WSU PAC-10 OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For Washington State, Saturday's game against Cal in
Berkeley is the Pac-10 opener. For Cougar safety Lamont Thompson,
it's homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   The East Bay sophomore, who is on pace to shatter every WSU
record for interceptions, grew up just 15 minutes from Memorial
Stadium and starred as a defensive back and wide receiver for
nearby El Cerrito High, a small city north of Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson, with the nonchalant manner in which he takes his
football accomplishments, shrugs off the importance of playing a
major-college football game in his old neighborhood for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game probably won't be any different than any other
game,'' said Thompson, reflecting on how far he has come in his two
Cougar seasons. ``I'm adapting pretty good to Pullman. This is my
home now.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go on vacation to my other home, it's like I'm going
there to visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is more worried about keeping Cal quarterback Justin
Vedder out of the Cougar end zone than how many friends and family
members will be there to watch him. The scrambling Vedder, third in
the Pac-10 last year in total offense with 249.4 yards a game,
presents the Cougar secondary with its biggest challenge so far
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a quarterback of his caliber, you have to stay in
coverage a little longer because he can run,'' Thompson said.
Although Vedder's favorite target last season, Bobby Shaw, is gone
after catching 75 passes in 1997, Thompson believes the Cal
receivers ``have more speed than they had last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson also has other things on his mind. He is rumored to be
a secret weapon on offense that WSU coach Mike Price might unveil
at wide receiver. The 6-foot-1, 204-pound free safety has
scrimmaged at receiver and Price this week wouldn't say whether he
would be deployed both ways against Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is willing to do anything to help the Cougars win, and
pass-catching makes him better at defending against the pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just catching the ball in general helps me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why Price is considering him as a receiver as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like he just makes casual plays but they are spectacular
catches,'' he said of Thompson's interceptions. ``He is something.
He's our Charles Woodson. Lamont Thompson can play both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of last year's Pac-10 championship team, Thompson
knows how important the Cal game is if WSU (3-0) is to be
considered a serious contender for to play in back-to-back bowl
games for the first time in the history of the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole team is anxious to win our first Pac-10 game,''
Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson started the final three games and the Rose Bowl last
year as a true freshman after senior Duane Stewart was injured and
the secondary was picked apart against Arizona State in WSU's only
Pac-10 loss. He had three interceptions (tying a school record)
against Washington and ended the year with six, which tied him for
the Pac-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With two interceptions, including a touchdown-saving pick, in
WSU's 24-16 win over Idaho, Thompson now has nine for his career,
just five short of WSU's all-time leader, Rick Reed, who had 14
from 1966-68.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson doesn't pay too much attention to records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Satisfaction-wise, me, I'm never satisfied,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He's too busy fielding punts, chasing down passes on offense and
concentrating on his college career to keep count of his
interception total. He wants to earn a degree in communication and
has a serious side that admires poetry and the works of Maya
Angelou. But he doesn't write much poetry anymore, unless it's on
the football field.
</P>
<P>
   ``In high school, I took a couple of poetry classes, but I kind
of got away from that now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson is now a veteran with two full years of eligibility
ahead of him. He can relate to the experience that defensive tackle
Joey Hollenbeck is going through as a freshman called on to step in
for an injured senior captain, and offers this advice:
</P>
<P>
   ``Just keep doing what you're doing and never be satisfied with
what you did the previous week. Just come out and practice harder
and be the player that you want to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
