<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS' NEW ERA OFF TO FALSE START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The head coach is new. The problems are old ones. And the
freshly installed offensive scheme appears to be swirling in their
heads like some bad '60s trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland Raiders, who come calling on the Cowboys Sunday, are
1-2, which goes to show that a ``commitment to excellence'' doesn't
go as far as it used to.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders are having trouble drawing 42,000 to 63,263-seat,
once-loyal Oakland Coliseum. The great unwashed that does go to see
Al Davis' team have been treated to familiar old Raider
idiosyncrasies, such as scattershoot quarterbacking and a weekly
maelstrom of penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way our team is fighting,'' said first-year coach
Jon Gruden.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, we knew what that meant.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, Gruden's team has just been fighting to hang on. The
Raiders have been roundly outplayed by two fill-in quarterbacks,
Kansas City's Rich Gannon and Denver's Bubby Brister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to build on the positive,'' Gruden, 35, repeated at
his weekly news conference this week. ``For three straight weeks,
our team has been fighting in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's the trouble. The old Raiders would have been biting
and eye-gouging.
</P>
<P>
   For the Cowboys, therefore, Week 2 of the Jason Garrett ``Home
Alone'' show might not be the test of mettle that we originally
thought. The NFC East smells like a bad cheese. A guy in a do-rag
who skipped most of training camp just hypnotized the New York
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Was I reading this right? The division's five quarterbacks of
record last week were Garrett, Danny Kanell, Trent Green, Bobby
Hoying and Jake Plummer?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, we find ourselves singing the Cowboys' praises.
They're 2-1. But by mere glimpse at the apparent NFC food chain, we
see they could win eight, nine games, if Deion Sanders and Richie
Cunningham merely show up.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who desperately needed a jackrabbit start, appear
capable of concocting one at the expense of the Giants, Redskins,
Bears, Eagles and, yes, even the AFC Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Some new head coaches never recover from poor starts (See
Wannstedt, Dave). But others, like the Cowboys' Chan Gailey, can
turn a few quick victories into a locker room full of converts.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys needed somebody to believe in. Somebody who cared
about how hard they worked and how deeply they were committed.
Coaching does matter, contrary to what the mantra was around here
for four years.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys aren't any better than they were 12 months ago. But
they're playing better. And Gailey has given them a fresh start and
a new offense to believe in.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that to the Raiders, who remain as fresh as an old
Grateful Dead album. They are on their third alleged ``new''
offensive system in three years, but their three-week output this
season: only three field goals and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders committed 15 penalties in a season-opening loss to
the Chiefs and 16 in their lone victory the next week over the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, they can't seem to keep quarterback Jeff George on his
feet. In three games, George has been sacked 19 times, second-worst
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Defenses have been preying on the Raiders' unfamiliarity with
Gruden's system, which is supposed to be his own but, on second
glance, has the oily fingerprints of owner Al Davis all over it.
Can bomber George even run Gruden's ball-control passing game
offense?
</P>
<P>
   So teams blitz. And George's feet freeze. The Chiefs reportedly
blitzed George on 51 of 62 plays in the season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we prove that we can handle the blitz,'' Gruden said,
``we're going to continue to see the blitz.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, rest assured, will not hesitate to blitz.
</P>
<P>
   In Oakland, they're talking about bringing in fullback Craig
``Ironhead'' Heyward, who was last spotted being ousted from the
Rams camp and weighing in at 5-foot-11 and 300 pounds. They're
wondering how long will it be before Davis impatiently starts
tweaking with what Gruden is trying to get started.
</P>
<P>
   It's all a tale of two franchises. Two owners. Two new head
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   All this, Cowboys fans, and you also get the NFC East.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 0141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
