<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK: ONLY NEW DEAL WILL END HOLDOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Holdout left wing  &UR; Keith Tkachuk said for the first
time publicly that he won't report to the Coyotes unless he
receives a contract extension that makes him one of the NHL's
highest-paid players.
</P>
<P>
   But its doubtful the team's captain and leading scorer will have
his wish granted anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith has continued maintain that all
negotiations are off indefinitely and that he expects Tkachuk to
honor the final two years of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not going to do that,'' Tkachuk said from his home
near Boston when asked whether he will consider returning to the
team without a new deal this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even thought about doing that, and I'm ``not'' going
to think about that. What I expect is a new contract, something
they promised to give me this summer. Hopefully, they'll be able to
hammer something out, it'll get done, and I'll be able to start
practicing with the team again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk already has forfeited $132,353 of his $2.8 million
salary this season after being suspended by the club Sept. 12 for
refusing to report to training camp. He is scheduled to earn $3
million in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   He and his agent, Bob Murray, have been seeking a new deal that
calls for a three-year extension worth about $41 million over the
next five seasons _ an average of more than $8 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   But after Smith flatly rejected two proposals the day before
camp opened, he said he had nothing else to talk about and
suspended negotiations. The two sides have not talked since, and it
apparently has affected some of their memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still waiting to hear from them,'' Tkachuk said. ``The
ball's in Bobby Smith's court with that last offer we sent to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk, 26, said he was referring to the two offers Murray made
to Smith on Sept. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that Smith rejected both offers, calling them
``outlandish and offensive,'' Tkachuk said, ``Well, you've got to
get both sides talking. This is a tough thing to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk said he will not instruct Murray to make another pitch
to Smith. Teams sources have said that management is prepared to
let him sit all season if he doesn't honor his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the next week to 10 days are pretty pivotal,'' Tkachuk
said. ``There's only so much time left, and I need a certain amount
of time to get ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough not being there, working hard with the other guys
on the team, but we've felt all along that a promise was made to us
that a deal would get done. Time's running out, but I'm still
hopeful that eventually, we'll get something worked out and I'll be
there.'' &QL; 
Loose pucks &QL; 
Smith and Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld are expected to pare the training
camp roster significantly after Saturday night's home preseason
game against the Los Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Players on the bubble include defensemen Gagnon,  &UR; Richard
Lintner,
 &UR; Brad Tiley and former No. 1 draft pick  &UR; Dan Focht, veteran forwards
 &UR; Joe
 &UR; Dziedzic,  &UR; Louie DeBrusk,  &UR; Barry Niekar and  &UR; Ron Murray, and goalie
 &UR; Scott
 &UR; Langkow, who probably will start the season in Las Vegas of the
International Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Coyotes sent rookie left wing  &UR; Adam Dewan back to
his junior team in Peterborough, Ontario, this week, they are
trying to sign the non-drafted training camp free agent to a
contract. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
