<HEADLINE>
DISNEY FALLS ON MODEST 4TH QUARTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shares of The Walt Disney Co. fell 3.5 percent
Thursday as Chairman Michael Eisner threw cold water on Wall
Street's expectations for the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner, on tour in New York to promote the release of his
autobiography, ``Work in Progress,'' said the results for Disney's
fourth quarter ending Sept. 30 represent a ``speed bump'' rather
than a ``sinkhole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A year of modest growth is not the end of the world,'' he
said, referring to the certainty that the entertainment giant won't
match its goal of 20 percent annual earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Disney were down 93.75 cents to $25.875 and are off 39
percent from their all-time high set May 4.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank-based Disney announced Sept. 14 that it expected
fourth-quarter earnings to come in at 15 or 16 cents a share, well
below Wall Street's consensus of 21 cents, due to Asia's economic
turmoil, slack demand for consumer products, rising film costs and
a downbeat performance by ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner said Thursday that earnings performance also has been
held back by major investments in new ventures such as the Animal
Kingdom theme park, DisneyQuest interactive play parks and ESPN
restaurants, along with soaring prices for professional football
and hockey broadcast rights.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
