<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOSE WHO KNOW OATES BEST SAY MANAGER SHOULD RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It is not, by any stretch of the imagination, a
scientific poll. Margin of error could be estimated at plus or
minus 50 percentage points, give or take 10 or 20.
</P>
<P>
   But the three guys I questioned before the Rangers and Mariners
opened a four-game series that, at some point, should include a
champagne celebration for the Texans, all give manager Johnny Oates
a thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   Two thumbs up each, in fact. That's six in all, if you're
counting, Mr. Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever that's worth.
</P>
<P>
   You already know how I feel, but something tells me that's not
worth all that much or this wouldn't even be a subject for
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Oates, in fact, prefers not to discuss it at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more important issues to take care of before we
worry about that,'' Oates said yesterday at the Kingdome. ``We've
still got a job to do, and hopefully that'll take another month or
so.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rangers are still playing in late October _ or even
clinch their second division title in three seasons sometime this
weekend, as expected _ then the issue of Oates' future should
immediately become a moot point.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it should be in question at all. Meanwhile, he remains
quietly unperturbed by rumors and speculation that the Rangers must
at least win the A.L. West to guarantee his _ and his coaches' _
job security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely proud of the job my coaches have done,'' Oates
said, ``but all of us are only as good as the players.''
</P>
<P>
   That's been plenty good when it counted most. The Rangers, who
beat the Angels five in a row, arrived at the Kingdome with a
three-game lead over Anaheim and a magic number of ``2'' after
gaining 6 1/2 games in the standings since Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' emotional state for the five games against the
Angels, particularly the three-game series just concluded, was
perfect, and Oates, who knows when to push, when to prod and when
to plead, deserves credit for his team's ``relaxed intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what I call it. Oates' brief pregame meeting before Game
1 in Anaheim produced the perfect blend of confidence and
concentration. His players say he's even better in one-on-one
situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's excellent,'' said former Rangers catcher Dave Valle, now
a radio analyst with the Mariners. ``He has such a respect for the
players and the privacy of that communication, that it's never
spoken about.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a player leaves his office, he feels like there's a true
concern there for you as an individual. It goes beyond \ROates'\S
concern for you as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates' greatest overall strength as a manager, said Valle, who
played a critical role as a team leader in the Rangers' drive to
the '96 division flag, is his consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what to expect every day,'' Valle said. ``There are
no surprises. That's really a great asset because consistency is
what this game demands from a player, too. When you're on his team,
it's good to know that he's at the helm of the ship.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so maybe you'd prefer current players. Let's try pitcher
John Burkett, who says Oates' even-handed approach is perfect for a
veteran team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he's not overemotional, he's a good match for the team
we have here,'' Burkett said. ``Plus, he has a lot of patience with
people. He showed it with me, and he stuck with Fernando Tatis
early in the season when a lot of managers would have buried him on
the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's John Wetteland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny's not only a good manager, he's a good person,''
Wetteland said. ``He and his coaches do a great job. Sometimes I
feel sorry for them when we're playing bad. I feel like I ought to
go out there and tell the fans, `This is not how they're teaching
us to do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   So that's three players, one former and two current, who will
happily stand up for Oates. They understand that whatever problems
this team _ which is about to take on the Yankees in the playoffs _
may have, they don't include the man in the manager's office.
</P>
<P>
   We can round up more, if needed, but it'll just get boring.
We're all prejudiced. It's a natural byproduct of hanging around
the guy for a good part of the last four years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
