<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGLES' GOOD NIGHT IS TOO LATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Anaheim Angels manager Terry Collins sat in the dugout
Thursday afternoon at the Oakland Coliseum and still had no answers
for why the Angels offense could do nothing in losing three to the
Texas Rangers, scoring only three runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't hit, we absolutely just didn't hit,'' he said.
``For whatever reason.''
</P>
<P>
   And for whatever reason, the Angels bats suddenly came to life
against the Oakland A's in a 10-6 win before 9,268. The Angels got
13 hits, including five by shortstop Gary DiSarcina, batting in the
No. 2 spot for the first time in more than a year. It was
DiSarcina's second career five-hit game, the other coming June 13
at Texas earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Angels win, the Rangers clinched at least a tie for
the division title with a victory over the Mariners in Seattle. The
Angels' only hope for postseason play is to beat the A's the next
three days and hope Texas loses the next three to Seattle. That
would force a one-game playoff Monday in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   In all probability, the game featured Jack McDowell's final
appearance of his career. Though he was staked to a 5-0 lead,
McDowell wasn't able to last long enough to qualify for the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell went four innings, allowing six runs and eight hits. He
has pitched with pain in his elbow all season and has said he is
leaning toward retirement so he can spend more time with his family
and his band, Stickfigure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm approaching it as though it's not his last game, he hasn't
said anything to me,'' Collins said before the game. ``If it is, I
consider myself fortunate to have watched him this year. I hope it
isn't. He tells me his arm doesn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a pitcher, these are the guys you sit and talk with.
If there's an open seat next to him on the bus, you sit next to
Jack McDowell.''
</P>
<P>
   It took the Angels only five batters in the first inning
Thursday to score more than they did in the entire series vs.
Texas. Against the Rangers, the Angels sent 103 batters to the
plate and scored three runs in the three games.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first inning against the A's, the Angels got started
quickly. Jim Edmonds led off and reached on second baseman Scott
Spiezio's error. DiSarcina followed with a single off the third
baseman Eric Chavez's glove, Edmonds taking third.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Salmon doubled home Edmonds, then Darin Erstad drove in
DiSarcina with a groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Next up, Todd Greene hit a two-run homer, his first since Aug.
19, 1997. That gave the Angels four runs in five batters, and they
weren't through. Matt Walbeck doubled and went to third on center
fielder Ryan Christenson's error. Troy Glaus then singled home
Walbeck for a 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, though, couldn't get comfortable. The A's got three
hits in their first three at-bats off McDowell in the first inning
and eventually all three scored in the inning to cut the Angels'
lead to 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels continued their assault on A's starter Jimmy Haynes
(11-9) in the second inning. Edmonds led off with a double, his
42nd of the season to tie a club record. Doug DeCinces (1982) and
Johnny Ray (1988) also had 42 in a season.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina drove home Edmonds with a double and then scored
himself later in the inning on Erstad's groundout. DiSarcina
doubled home another run in the fourth, and Haynes didn't make it
out of the inning, trailing 8-3.
</P>
<P>
   The A's rallied for three more runs in the bottom of the fourth,
two coming home on Chavez's double and a third run on a single by
Mike Macfarlane.
</P>
<P>
   But again the Angels responded, getting two runs in the sixth
off A's reliever Blake Stein to go up 10-6. Salmon drove in the
first run of the inning with a single and Erstad drove in the
second when he hit into a fielder's choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
