<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS AVOID NO-HITTER, WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Out of it in the standings and on the field, the
Los Angeles Dodgers seemed like the perfect team for Steve
Woodard's attempt at a perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   In the first game of the season's final series Thursday night,
Woodard, the 23-year old Milwaukee Brewers right-hander, retired
the first 18 Dodgers he faced. But for the second time in two
weeks, the Dodgers not only broke up a perfect game, they actually
won, too.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno opened the seventh with a home run and the Dodgers
went on to beat the Brewers 4-1 in front of 30,024 at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 10, San Diego's Kevin Brown also retired the first 18
Dodgers he faced. He then got the last six. In between, the Dodgers
scored four runs to win 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did that against Brown and we had to execute that way
again,'' Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard is no Kevin Brown, a Cy Young Award candidate. He
entered the game 1-7 in his last eight decisions. But he was rarely
challenged until Cedeno drove a 2-0 fastball into the empty
right-field pavilion to tie the game at one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for the fastball on the 2-0 count,'' Cedeno
said. ``When we are down and not getting hits, we do what we need
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the eighth inning, with Woodard out of the game,
that the Dodgers took over.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Chad Fox (1-4) allowed three runs in the eighth and
again Cedeno was at the center of the action. He walked, raced from
first to third on a wild pitch and scored on a single by Trenidad
Hubbard to make it 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's wild pitch scored Juan Castro, who reached base on the
weirdest play of the night. After rookie Paul LoDuca opened the
eighth with a double off the wall in right-center, Castro tried to
sacrifice him to third. But Brewers first baseman Mark Loretta
booted the bunt, then threw wildly to first for two errors on one
play. LoDuca scored and Castro went all the way to third.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers rookie Eric Weaver (2-0) replaced right-hander Dave
Mlicki after six innings and picked up his second major-league
victory. He also beat the Padres on Sept. 13 after coming on in
relief of Ismael Valdes. This time he pitched two scoreless innings
before turning the game over to closer Jeff Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw retired all three batters he faced to record his 46th save
and 23rd with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard was coming off a dismal performance against St. Louis,
when he allowed nine hits and seven runs in 52/3 innings of a 12-10
loss. But lost in that start were nine strikeouts and just one
walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had his good stuff tonight,'' Brewers manager Phil Garner
said. `` He only gave up two hits in seven innings. If we had any
kind of offense we would have been able to keep him out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't overpowering Thursday, but after some early fly balls
Woodard starting getting outs on the ground. Hubbard took
left-fielder Geoff Jenkins to the wall in the first, but Woodard
didn't get challenged again until Cedeno in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt good all night,'' Woodard said. ``I was making some
good pitches. You know I wasn't thinking about it at all. I've had
a couple like that before that got away. They ended up hitting the
same pitches I was throwing all night.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his performance, Woodard had just a 1-0 lead over
Dodgers starter Dave Mlicki.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee scored its only run in the second inning on a home run
by shortstop Jose Valentin. Mlicki, who left his last start with
lower back pain, allowed just four hits before being lifted for
pinch hitter Angel Pena in the sixth..
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I felt good, I thought I could keep going,'' said
Mlicki, who said he had no soreness in his back. ``When you have a
good pitcher like Woodard and he is throwing a perfect game. I'd
rather have a batter hit than me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
