<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ORIOLES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS FALL INTO PLACE; RED SOX GAIN PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On the night the Red Sox captured the American League
wild card with a 9-6 win over the Baltimore Orioles at Fenway Park,
the bubbly of choice was Le Domaine Extra Dry California Champagne,
and it wore as well as it tasted.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Sox CEO John Harrington, who lost the dry look as soon
as Bret Saberhagen clutched his arm and Tim Wakefield took aim with
his bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody have a little champagne for Mr. Harrington?'' said
Saberhagen, the 15-game winner who didn't play Thursday night but
issued a call to arms before the game, when he walked purposefully
to the TV set and switched off the Jerry Springer video that was
drawing howls in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got work to do,'' Saberhagen said. ``Batting practice is
in 10 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Batting practice never ended for the Red Sox, not on a clinching
night when they won their 90th game and collected 18 hits,
including two home runs by Nomar Garciaparra, who scored four
times; three hits by Mo Vaughn, who regained a razor-thin lead in
the AL batting race; and four hits by catcher Scott Hatteberg, all
of which took the sting out of the three home runs allowed by
winning pitcher Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider my game to be a bad game for myself and for the
team,'' said Martinez (19-7), who was long gone to the clubhouse
when closer Tom Gordon struck out the side in the ninth for his
major league-record 42d consecutive save, the last out coming when
umpire Jim Evans called out Robbie Alomar on a checked-swing third
strike at 10:14.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm glad,'' Martinez said, ``that my teammates were there
to back me up like they've done all year long.''
</P>
<P>
   The cigars were Partagas, a Jamaican brand, and Montecristo,
from the Dominican Republic. Everyone seemed to have one in the
winners' clubhouse, except for Lauren Hatteberg, the 10-month-old
daughter of the catcher. She still preferred her pacifier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the absolute best,'' Scott Hatteberg said. ``I hope
she remembers it. I know she won't, but I'll tell her she was in
here.''
</P>
<P>
   True story: Lauren Hatteberg raised her tiny index finger.
``That's right,'' Hatteberg said. ``No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   The hugs, the handshakes, the smiles, and even the tears shed by
Leroy Vaughn, father of the first baseman, had no labels. But the
new caps modeled by everyone in the clubhouse, from Midre Cummings,
the man who was released twice by other clubs in spring training;
to Mike Stanley, the recycled Red Sox DH; to Dennis Eckersley,
baseball's 2,000-year-old man, who tied Hoyt Wilhelm's major league
record with his 1,070th career pitching appearance, told the story.
</P>
<P>
   The caps didn't just have a red ``B.'' There was a wild card
tucked on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how with Chinese food, you can mix everything up and
it tastes great?'' Leroy Vaughn said. ``That's what this team was
like. This team had a little bit of everything. That's what
happened. And next year, you can't explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Duquette, the man who put this team together, walked into
the office of manager Jimy Williams after first passing under a
champagne sprinkler. The two men embraced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice going, Dan, goldang it,'' Williams said to Duquette. ``I
mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We got 90 wins and we're going to the dance,'' Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ain't going to the dance,'' Williams said as Duquette
pulled away from him. ``We're going to the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel real good. I feel really proud for all of 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then, Harrington came in. ``Congratulations to you,''
Harrington said in mid-hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to you,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started with that long talk we had in October,''
Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   What October was that? Williams was asked. ``I don't remember
which October,'' Williams said. ``A red October.''
</P>
<P>
   There hasn't been a red October in these parts since 1995, when
the Sox won the AL East and were eliminated by the Cleveland
Indians in three straight games. The best-of-five first round of
the playoffs opens Tuesday, probably in Cleveland, though if the
Indians and Rangers should finish the season tied, the Sox will be
headed to Texas instead.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, the Sox cared little about whom they will be
playing. This was a night to celebrate that they'll be playing at
all in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling,'' said Darren Lewis, the
bargain-basement center fielder who in 1993 played for a team, the
Giants, that won 103 games and went home on the last day of the
season. ``We're not finished yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a start. This is a mini-celebration for all the
hard work we did during the season. But soon we're going to have to
stop and refocus on what our real goals are. Celebrate tonight and
start again tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   When the last out was recorded, Vaughn and Valentin converged
from opposite corners of the diamond, met on the mound, and wrapped
each other in joyful embrace, even as Gordon pointed skyward.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had two outs, I tried to get Mo's attention,''
Valentin said. ``Mo and I, we're the only ones who were here in
'95.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone here knows what it feels like. Obviously, there
are other veterans who have been there, but the playoffs are a
different animal. We're going to have to bear down and make as few
mistakes as possible, because the team that makes the fewest
mistakes wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't supposed to be here,'' Valentin added. ``But now
that we're here, maybe we'll sneak up on somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the whole idea, Vaughn said. ``I know pretty much what
we're going to experience. I look forward to it. I'm glad to be
here. Respect everybody, fear no team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
