<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DUQUETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUQUETTE DOES CLUBHOUSE VICTORY LAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Champagne streams and champagne droplets were still
floating down through the thickest of cigar smoke when general
manager Dan Duquette entered a Red Sox clubhouse that best could
best be described as controlled happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette shook the hands of players, stopped to congratulate
players, and, carrying a ``Red Sox Wild Card'' T-shirt in his
hands, hugged a few in the melee of restrained joy that followed
Thursday night's 9-6 victory over the Orioles at Fenway Park. But
when the GM entered the office of manager Jimy Williams, he showed
emotions that seldom are on public display.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got it!,'' Duquette said as he wrapped Williams in a
prolonged bear hug. ``We got it ... we're going to the dance ...
and we got 90 wins!''
</P>
<P>
   When Duquette left Williams's office, he went along the row of
lockers just outside the door, the lockers of the coaches, and he
shook all their hands and said to all the men virtually the same
words: ``We got 90 wins. Did you know that?'' and ``We won 90
games. Isn't that something.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as he enjoyed his team surprising one and all in the
baseball world by earning the American League wild card, Duquette
seemed almost as pleased that Boston had won 90 games. In his mind,
this was a benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety wins,'' he said again and again. ``Did you know the Red
Sox haven't won 90 games since '86?'' Needless to mention, that was
the last year Boston was in the World Series, the last time the Red
Sox won a postseason game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all great,'' Duquette said when asked to compare this
surprise to the surprise of 1995, when the Red Sox last made the
playoffs, as AL East champions. ``We had a bunch of guys who had
great individual years. This was a complete team effort ... and we
won 90 games. First time we won 90 games since '86. It's a great
achievement for everybody involved; that's what's great about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Not far behind Duquette in the locker room was CEO John
Harrington, who noted the controlled celebration and said, ``In
'95, we were a lot happier, we were out on the field, and we may
have been riding horses.''
</P>
<P>
   The point, said Harrington, ``is that those of us who've been
through it and have been there before are saying, `We're happy.
We're just as happy but we're not showing it. We're going to show
it when we can reach the next level.'''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said he was not surprised by this team: ``We expected
this and wanted this.'' But getting to the AL Championship Series
and perhaps the World Series? ``Now,'' conceded Harrington, ``that
would be a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not, said Harrington in his next breath. ``We've got
it all. Nomar (Garciaparra) is the MVP (of the league), we've got
the top stopper (Tom Gordon), we got a Cy Young guy (Pedro
Martinez), don't we? We've got it all.''
</P>
<P>
   And more champagne dripped through the cigar smoke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
