<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3719 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-HNS &LR;      09-25 1149
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Get enough mail, and you begin to recognize signs of trouble.
Before long, you can see anger in an address.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Return addresses identifying militant-sounding groups from
post-office boxes are a good clue to what is inside the envelope.
Crayons are not a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska senior center Josh Heskew, a veteran of all sorts of
mail, should have recognized the clue on the envelope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have known,'' he said, ``when it comes addressed to
Mrs. Josh Heskew.''
</P>
<P>
   Heskew is not married, but the letter, if it could be called
that, was meant for him. And like most well-thought-out,
constructive criticism of its kind, it contained no return address,
no signature.
</P>
<P>
   Scribbled on a scrap of paper, the letter read: ``How does it
feel to be the captain of the worst offensive line in America?''
</P>
<P>
   It included a prediction that Washington would stomp Nebraska on
Saturday. Heskew laughed and tacked it to the wall outside the
Nebraska locker room.
</P>
<P>
   But as ready as college football players are to accept
motivation wherever it can be found, his teammates needed no such
reminder of the strange attitude that has developed about the
Nebraska Cornhuskers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a remarkable run of injuries, Nebraska is 3-0, is ranked
No. 2 in both polls and has outscored opponents by an average of
26.6 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   But most conversation about the defending national co-champion
centers on what is wrong. The running game has been without its
usual swagger and taste for the jugular. The defensive line rarely
has punished quarterbacks. And discussions about pass coverage are
not appropriate in mixed company.
</P>
<P>
   The more understanding observers allow only that the game
against respected Washington will provide Nebraska with a chance to
show if it has solved its many problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers, while aware of the opinions, contend they are
on schedule. And Nebraska's schedule usually leads to a bowl with
the national championship at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel tremendous about where we're at, and I hope our players
feel good about it. I think they do,'' Nebraska coach Frank Solich
said. ``Sometimes when you don't win in terms of big numbers like
maybe the public wants or expects or the media want or expect, or
you yourself want or expect, it could be looked at as discouraging.
But it should not be for our ballclub. I think we've come through a
lot in these first three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of teams out there, as you saw from the past
weekend or the weekend before, that are outstanding football teams
that couldn't get it done. It can happen to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen to Nebraska as the Cornhuskers posted wins of
56-27 over Louisiana Tech, 38-7 over Alabama-Birmingham and 24-3
over California, despite injuries that forced the Cornhuskers to
start a different quarterback in each, to play without their best
rusher and with their top pass rusher limping at half-speed.
</P>
<P>
   Starting quarterback Bobby Newcombe is scheduled to return
Saturday. Tailback DeAngelo Evans is considered at 100 percent and
will play for the first time since 1996. Defensive end Mike
Rucker's groin injury is almost healed. Starting defensive tackle
Jason Wiltz and cornerback Erwin Swiney also returned to practice
this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does strike me; it seems like you'd think about more
positive things than the negative,'' Heskew said. ``It sounds like
we haven't been playing well. I don't know whether people take it
for granted, but maybe we have spoiled our fans. They expect us to
score 50 to 60 points every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they expect more, and the demands are specific.
Nebraska must win to form, with a dominating, merciless running
game and a punishing pass rush. The rest, as long as Nebraska wins
by embarrassingly large margins, are details.
</P>
<P>
   But through three games, Nebraska averages 259.7 yards rushing
per game, good for third in the nation but far off last season's
daily pace of 392.6 yards. The Cornhuskers averaged 513.7 yards of
total offense, the most in the nation. This season they rank 18th,
averaging 446.7.
</P>
<P>
   And after ranking fifth last season in total defense, allowing
257.3 yards per game, the Cornhuskers now rank 62nd, allowing 338.3
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were disappointed after the (1996) season and came out the
next year with a lot of confidence,'' senior fullback Joel
Makovicka said. ``We knew we could play well and play with anybody.
This year, we need to get that confidence. You build confidence as
you play and play well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have potential to be a really good football team. As a
senior class, it's been a great ride, and now it's our time to keep
it going. We don't want to go out as a senior class and not play up
to our abilities. We've been spoiled and played well, so well our
fans are spoiled too.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the Cornhuskers are considered off recent form, solutions
seem at hand. Wingback Lance Brown is the only injured starter not
expected back in the lineup Saturday. Solich said Newcombe, who was
sensational in his one outing as Scott Frost's successor, was a
natural at the option from his first day on campus. And Solich, who
is usually as cautious in his comments as was Tom Osborne, his
mentor as Cornhuskers coach for the previous 25 seasons, raves
about Evans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got great quickness,'' Solich said. ``He's got great
acceleration off of his cuts. He gives us a back that can make a
big play, that can make a 60-, 70-, 80-yard run. He's done that in
games. He's done that in scrimmages. He's a tremendously confident
back. He can make you miss. When something is not there, he can
make something out of it. You don't see a lot of those backs
around. We have one.''
</P>
<P>
   And against California two weeks ago, Nebraska's defense seemed
to improve as much as the return of Evans and Newcombe could
bolster the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some questions by some people about where we were
defensively, but we played a total defensive game, playing the pass
well, getting a rush on the quarterback and stopping their running
game,'' Solich said. ``It was a great game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last season, the Cornhuskers do not need to make up
ground in the polls. And Solich will point to the other champions
of the past two seasons _ Florida, Michigan _ that have lost while
the Cornhuskers roll on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased. We're 3-0; we've done some very good things,''
Solich said. `` I'm not concerned about this football team. If you
would have told me when I first got named as the head coach at the
University of Nebraska we would now be 3-0, I'd have felt great,
and I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can continue to improve _ and we have ability, we have
talent _ we can be an excellent football team. I think we're on
track.''
</P>
<P>
   But keep those cards and letters coming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
