<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3722 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-STRETCH-HNS &LR;      09-25 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-STRETCH-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ By winning three of four games in the Astrodome last
week _ all in dramatic, late-comeback fashion _ the New York Mets
captured the hearts of America's largest city.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But these are not necessarily kind hearts. New Yorkers can be
almost schizophrenic in the way their mood swings from euphoric to
homicidal.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were booed Wednesday by a crowd of 29,728 as they
trudged off the Shea Stadium field after losing their second
consecutive game to the Montreal Expos, the third-worst team in the
National League.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction was hardly surprising. When John Franco, a native
New Yorker, blew a two-run lead in the ninth inning in a loss to
Florida a week ago, he was assailed with obscene chanting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what some people are thinking when they come to
the ballpark _ or if they're thinking at all,'' Mets manager Bobby
Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, a 14-year veteran who, like Valentine, has never made a
postseason appearance, called the Houston expedition ``the best
single series I've ever been involved in.''
</P>
<P>
   It was especially meaningful to the Mets, because if they win
the wild-card race to get into the playoffs, they will play the
Astros in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Mets, tied with the equally self-destructive Chicago
Cubs in the wild-card shuffle, depart their not-so-comforting home
and hope for the sort of results they got on their last excursion.
</P>
<P>
   This time the destination is Atlanta, where the Mets play their
final three scheduled games against a team that has won its seventh
consecutive division title. The Cubs, McRaemeanwhile, head to
Houston, where they open a three-game series tonight in the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Expos manager Felipe Alou predicted the Cubs ``won't win another
game'' after defensive substitute Brant Brown swatted a fly he
should have caught and caused a victory to slip away Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lose a 7-0 lead, and you have to take a four-hour plane
ride to Houston,'' Alou mused. ``Everybody's celebrating two home
runs by (Sammy) Sosa, and suddenly you get beat. It takes two weeks
to recuperate. And they don't have two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets have some recuperating of their own to do, thanks
to Alou's youthful spoilers.
</P>
<P>
   Mets center fielder Brian McRae said the Expos were extra
motivated because of ill feelings toward Valentine, who is often
called ``the most disliked manager in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Their coaches don't like Bobby,'' McRae said. ``It gives them
added incentive for them to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou emphatically disputed that, but Valentine suggested
animosities might be connected to the Mets' little-used and
disgruntled reliever, Mel Rojas, a former Expo and a nephew of
Alou.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of Dominicans on that team (the Expos) that
talk to Mel,'' Valentine noted.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their motivation, the Expos beat the Mets eight of 12
games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's up to the Mets to regain the opportunism that was so
apparent in Houston. They lead the league with 35 one-run
victories. But their lineup lacks punch aside from Mike Piazza and
John Olerud, and the pitching is suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Although Al Leiter, Rick Reed and Armando Reynoso are a combined
39-17, only Leiter has pitched well recently.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, who starts tonight against rookie Bruce Chen, has allowed
15 home runs in his last eight starts. But he claims he has found
the problem: His follow-through off the mound was occurring too
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My arm wasn't catching up, so I was elevating my pitches,'' he
explained. ``My side work (Tuesday) was unbelievable. I think I've
got it figured out.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter is scheduled to pitch Saturday (against Tom Glavine),
with Reynoso probable for Sunday (vs. Greg Maddux).
</P>
<P>
   If the starters falter, Valentine can always call on Turk
Wendell. A quirky righthander known for throwing the resin bag
almost as hard as he throws his pitches, Wendell has pitched in a
club-record nine consecutive games, aided by two days off and a
cortisone shot to relieve arm soreness.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he was concerned about damaging his arm, Wendell
shrugged and said, ``They can rebuild it in the offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an offseason the Mets are having trouble postponing, while
the buzz here continues over a possible intracity World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are dominating the American League while the Mets
try to replicate Florida's wild-card ride of last October that
ended in a World Series championship.
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets and Cubs finish the regular season in a two-way tie,
the teams will meet at Shea for a Monday winner-take-wild card.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised,'' Piazza said, ``if this comes down
to a one-game playoff after all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
