<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARA,VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN, GARCIAPARRA: DIFFERENT STROKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mo Vaughn and Nomar Garciaparra were the first Red Sox
to take the field in the top of the ninth inning, joining ace
reliever Tom Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   That was at 10:06 p.m. Eight minutes later, after Gordon blew a
pitch by Baltimore's Roberto Alomar for the final out, Vaughn went
to the mound, embraced third baseman John Valentin, and joined in
the celebration. Garciaparra stood at second base alone, and
eventually, his teammates formed a line behind him and exchanged
congratulatory handshakes.
</P>
<P>
   The two are a contrast in styles. Vaughn is a vocal leader whose
bat speaks as loudly as his words. Garciaparra is a player whose
power and presence far outweigh his oratory. Thursday night both
asserted themselves in their own way, guiding the Red Sox to their
third postseason berth this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Both players went 3 for 5 in the 9-6 victory over the Orioles
that clinched the American League wild-card playoff berth.
Garciaparra belted two home runs, his 34th and 35th, and drove in
three runs. Vaughn collected his 200th hit of the season, scored a
run, nudged ahead of the Yankees' Bernie Williams for the AL
batting lead, and registered eight putouts at first base. He also
went to the mound to offer advice to Pedro Martinez in the fourth
inning after the starter gave up a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, in their own way, they savored the accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Both Vaughn and Garciaparra were late arrivals in the Red Sox
clubhouse. Their teammates, already pouring bottles of champagne,
awaited them. Garciaparra was doused as soon as he entered.
</P>
<P>
   After growing weary of waiting for Vaughn, several players went
out to the field to retrieve him. The slugger entered the locker
room trying unsuccessfully to outrun pitcher Jim Corsi, who was
pouring champagne over his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out of here, everyone had us picked for fourth place.
But April is when it started, with all those comeback wins,'' said
Vaughn, who added that this postseason clincher is better than
1995's, when the Sox won the AL East. ``I think the concept of this
team is what it's all about. We have guys interchanging in the
outfield, guys who got hurt and came back.''
</P>
<P>
   The slugger spoke nonstop for about 20 minutes to reporters,
making certain he mentioned the efforts of various teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``First and foremost, we've had some of the best pitchers in the
league, guys who have had double-figure wins,'' said Vaughn.
``We've had guys who have swung the bat well. We played some sharp
defense. But the main thing is we never got down. This team is
built on character. This team stuck together as a ball club, and
you need to do that. We have no individuals on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Garciapparra, initially, he was nowhere to be found.
Finally, he emerged for comment but seemed impatient throughout,
like someone who had just been told he inadvertently double-parked
in front of a police station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a small step, and we understand that,'' he said. ``I
think we were the only guys who believed in ourselves. So we'll
take it, enjoy it, as well as we should. It's a long season, and
when you go through what we've been through, the bump and grind, we
enjoy it. But we know it's a long season and there's still the
postseason to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
