<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3725 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-25 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE story was told so often, sometimes it seems as if I was sitting
alongside my father and his friends on that remarkable day, leaning
against crates, watching the radio, cherishing a moment.
</P>
<P>
   It was Oct. 8, 1956. In a dank warehouse on the south side of
San Antonio, deep among the blue-collars and thousands of miles
from New York, a handful of men were putting in an extra shift at
the plant. They were busting calluses as they moved crates of
machinery onto a truck, trying to meet a deadline. A co-worker
rushed into the warehouse carrying a radio, shouting, ``You're not
going to believe what's happening in the Series.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' Don Larsen had pitched seven innings of perfect
baseball in a World Series game against the Brooklyn Dodgers. Like
everywhere else across the country, everything stopped. Crates
slammed to the ground. The men pulled off their work gloves,
gathered around the radio, sat on boxes and agonized over every
pitch they heard called on the scratchy portable. Finally, Larsen
sent 27 men down in a row, pitching perfection and carving his
place in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   We all have such stories. We all remember where we were, what we
were doing, what it was like to witness _ even via the airwaves _
something special in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Until October 1969, I always believed Sister Mary Ambrose at St.
Ann's School knew nothing and cared nothing about baseball. The
only lumber she ever swung was a yardstick across the backs of my
knees. I wasn't even sure she had a heart, that she could feel such
things as the anxiety and anticipation of a dramatic baseball
moment.
</P>
<P>
   But there she was on that October day, announcing to the
third-grade class the lesson for the day was about courage. She
then wheeled in a TV, and we watched the black-and-white images of
the Miracle Mets defeating the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Pick a moment, any moment, and you probably remember the
lingering taste the moment left: Larsen's perfect game, Roger Maris
slamming his 61st, Bob Gibson pitching his third World Series
complete game, the Miracle Mets, the colorful A's, Carlton Fisk's
legendary homer, the Big Red Machine, Bucky Dent's drama, Reggie
slamming three in a single World Series game. There's just
something special about something special in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why this weekend and the upcoming playoffs have all the
markings of days we will rehash years from now. We'll spin stories
to our children about where we were, what we were doing, when Sammy
Sosa and Mark McGwire engaged in the greatest home-run drama the
game has known.
</P>
<P>
   We'll talk about the Renaissance Season of 1998, when,
remarkably, going into the final weekend of the year there were 11
of the 30 big-league teams in the playoffs or with a chance to get
there.
</P>
<P>
   We'll talk about how the Giants scratched back into the
three-team NL wild-card race, as the Cubs took on the powerful
Astros and the Mets challenged the great Braves for the final berth
on the season's final weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the fondest memories this game and this city will have
figure to be happening right now. No longer will the best Astros
days only have to do with aging video of Mike Scott wrapping up the
division title with a no-hitter in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   We'll shake our heads in amazement at how this final Astros home
series of 1998 was as much a playoff scene as the playoffs
themselves, with Sosa swinging mightily not just to edge McGwire
but to lift his team into the playoffs and lift the spirits of his
hurricane-ravaged Dominican Republic homeland.
</P>
<P>
   We'll remember the Astros' 100-win season and perhaps the day
Shane Reynolds won his 20th for a staff on which he is overshadowed
by Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   We'll wonder how long it will be before someone else posts a
50-50 season of doubles and stolen bases the way Craig Biggio did
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   We might remember how Brant Brown's game-losing play in
Milwaukee two days before this season-ending series foreshadowed
the Cubs' demise.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe we'll recall how Cubs pitcher Kerry Wood ended his
rookie season with a playoff berth on the line. Maybe somewhere in
town, someone will walk into a warehouse Saturday and announce,
``You're not going to believe what Kerry Wood is doing to the
Astros.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a riveting season, so why not expect a fitting
conclusion? This has been a season we haven't been able to keep our
eyes off of, from the Yankees' flirtation with the all-time wins
record, to Sosa and McGwire, to Wood, Johnson, Roger Clemens, Cal
Ripken, the wild races, the fading Anaheim Angels and the surging
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   You get the feeling the baseball stories we will tell years from
now are happening now. Where will you be this weekend? Where will
you be this October?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
