<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CLINCH TIE FOR WEST TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Things sometimes seem pretty serene in Ken Griffey
Jr.'s corner of the Mariners clubhouse. The leather recliner, the
video game cartridges and the general affability of its most
prominent resident all give evidence of that.
</P>
<P>
   But Griffey turned defiant for a moment before Thursday's game
against the Texas Rangers. The subject: the possibility that with a
Rangers win and an Anaheim Angels loss Thursday, Texas could
celebrate an American League West pennant on the Kingdome floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, yeah, it matters,'' Griffey said. ``Would you want me to
come over to your house and throw a party?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, if you're a kid and your bedroom is decorated with
Griffey posters, that might sound like a pretty cool idea. But the
point was clear enough: nobody likes to watch someone else's
celebration, especially when it's on your turf.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers made a clinching possible by storming through
Anaheim with three straight wins over the Angels, who had led the
division for much of the season. Their momentum continued Thursday
night, as they pounded Mac Suzuki and beat the M's, 9-3, before
22,891 fans.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels also won, beating the Oakland Athletics, 10-6 in
Oakland, meaning the most the Rangers clinched Thursday night was a
tie for the division title. Texas can secure its second division
title in the past three seasons with a win or an Angels loss
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go into Anaheim and play the way we did the whole series
and to continue that here just shows what type of team we are,''
said shortstop Royce Clayton, who had three of the Rangers' 15
hits. ``We didn't get down at any point, and we kept our focus and
played solid baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored three times in both the second and third off
Suzuki, who lasted only 21/3 innings in his last _ and shortest _
start of the year. The 23-year-old right-hander allowed six runs
(five earned) on seven hits and four walks.
</P>
<P>
   Suzuki (1-2) worked into the seventh inning in starts against
Boston and Minnesota this month, but was coming off a four-inning
outing at Anaheim Saturday. In all, he worked 222/3 innings in his
five starts, allowing 17 earned runs for a 6.20 earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suzuki didn't throw the ball well (tonight),'' said manager
Lou Piniella. ``He couldn't hit his spots with his fastball, and
his split-finger was up, plus he was behind in the count. He didn't
really have a good outing at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is a learning experience. I'm not disappointed in
him. We'd like to see these kids pitch well, but we have to be
realistic and patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Suzuki escaped a shaky first by getting Will
Clark to fly to center to strand two runners, both of whom had
walked. After two quick outs in the second inning, Todd Zeile lined
a double just inside the foul line in left field. Clayton's single
tied the score at 1-1, and a triple, walk and RBI single increased
the Rangers' lead to 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Clark led off the third with a double, and Lee Stevens' one-out
triple scored him. Then Zeile walked and a Clayton single scored
Stevens, driving Suzuki from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling different; not the same as Boston and the
Twins,'' Suzuki said. ``I don't know why, but I will find out
tomorrow. That's not me. I didn't throw strikes. I was behind in
the count, everything was up.''
</P>
<P>
   The first batter reliever Paul Spoljaric faced, Tom Goodwin,
bounced to second baseman David Bell. Bell fielded it near the bag
and reached behind himself to tag Clayton, then fired a one-hopper
to first, where David Segui scooped it for what looked like an
inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, umpires ruled Bell had missed Clayton and that his
throw arrived too late to catch the speedy Goodwin. Runners were
safe all around, and Zeile scored the Rangers' sixth run one batter
later. After Mark McLemore popped to first base for the second out,
catcher Dan Wilson mishandled Segui's three-hop throw to the plate,
scoring Zeile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
