A3794 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VISAS-HOUSE-SFCHRON &LR;      09-25 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISAS-HOUSE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OKS MORE VISAS FOR SKILLED WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LOUIS FREEDBERG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ After months of delays, the House easily passed a
bill Thursday expanding the number of temporary visas issued to
foreign workers, a measure designed to help Silicon Valley firms
who say they can't find Americans to fill many skilled positions.
<TEXT>
<P>
   California lawmakers as well as industry representatives hailed
the 283-to-133 vote for the bill, which benefited from overwhelming
Republican support. The legislation was worked out as part of a
compromise with the White House, and is expected to pass easily in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it is a temporary solution to what is hopefully a
short-term problem,'' said Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif. ``In the
long run, America must make a long-term investment in our nation's
children so that our high-tech industries are not dependent on
foreign workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the federal government has issued 65,000 temporary
``H1-B'' visas each year, which allow workers to stay in the
country for up to six years. But this year, the supply of visas was
exhausted by May, four months before the end of the fiscal year on
September 30.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new bill, the cap would be raised to 115,000 for each
of the next two years, and to 107,500 in 2001. After that, the cap
would revert to 65,000.
</P>
<P>
   The White House threatened to veto earlier versions of the bill.
Administration officials argued that the temporary visa program was
rife with abuse and insisted on stronger protections for American
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation had been stalled mainly because of disagreements
about whether high-tech companies should be required to ``attest''
to the fact that they had tried to find American workers before
hiring a foreign one, and to pledge that they would not lay off
American workers in order to hire lower paid foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   The bill approved Thursday was the result of a compromise
reached over the past few weeks between the White House and
Republicans and Democrats on Capitol Hill. At the same time, the
White House had to satisfy two competing constituencies to which it
has built close ties: labor unions and the high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   Under the compromise, only companies whose labor force is made
up of 15 percent or more temporary foreign workers will have to
declare to the Labor Department that they had sought Americans
before hiring a foreign worker. The compromise bill would also
require employers to pay $500 for each temporary foreign worker
they hire into a fund that would provide 10,000 scholarships and
job training. The fees are expected to generate between $75 million
and $100 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement will dramatically help California's high-tech
industry, which has been hurt by the lack of qualified skilled
workers available for employment,'' said Rep. Ellen Tauscher,
D-Calif., a strong supporter of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the compromise bill would grant the U.S. Labor
Department additional powers to to make spot checks of companies
suspected of abusing the law. Until now, the federal government
could only investigate a firm if a formal complaint had been filed
against it.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lopsided vote, there was spirited opposition to the
bill from an unusual alliance of liberal Democrats and conservative
Republicans, who questioned why high-tech firms needed foreign
workers when many have laid off thousands of Americans over the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about a powerful business lobby that is trying to
ensure a supply of cheap labor,'' said Rep. Dana Rohrabacher,
R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Even Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, the chair of the House
subcommittee on immigration who helped broker the compromise, said
he is not altogether convinced there is a shortage of qualified
American workers. ``The evidence is inconclusive, but I believe we
should give industry the benefit of the doubt and grant these
additional visas,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 0331EDT &QL; 
