</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-CANCER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE SEEMS TO CUT CANCER RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Wine drinkers seem to run a lower risk of
developing certain types of cancer than people who drink beer and
hard liquor.
</P>
<P>
   Research published in this week's British Medical Journal, based
on detailed health studies of 28,180 adults in Denmark, suggests
that the type of alcoholic beverage you drink makes a big
difference in your odds of developing cancer of the upper digestive
tract.
</P>
<P>
   The study authors, led by Morton Gronbaek of the Copenhagen
Center for Prospective Studies, concluded that wine may contain
protective compounds that cancel out the well-known cancer-causing
effects of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies have identified a plant substance called
resveratrol, found in grapes and fresh grape skins. Red wine has
been found to contain more resveratrol than white or rose
varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Another explanation may be that wine may not contain
cancer-causing substances that are present in the other beverages.
The British journal included an editorial note discussing one
possible example _ DNA-damaging substances called nitrosamines,
which are found in beer and distilled spirits but not in any
significant amounts in wine.
</P>
<P>
   Until more is known, researchers stopped short of recommending
alcohol, in any form, for cancer prevention, suggesting that whole
grapes or juice might be your best bet. Besides the well-known
hazards of heavy drinking, there is also a danger that some types
of malignancies, such as breast cancer, may increase in frequency
with exposure to alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   The Denmark study released Thursday confirmed previous research
showing the carcinogenic effects of alcohol generally. Heavy
drinkers, in fact, ran a 12-fold increase in the risk of cancer of
the upper digestive tract compared with abstainers _ making alcohol
a worse carcinogen than smoking.
</P>
<P>
   But the amount of wine consumed made a major difference, the
research showed. Among the moderate drinkers, those who took at
least 30 percent of their alcohol in the form of wine were even a
bit less at risk than nondrinkers for the type of cancer included
in the study.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers took into account such factors as age, sex,
educational level and tobacco use. Although alcohol is no health
tonic, they found that a little wine may not be all bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``A moderate intake of wine probably does not increase the risk
of upper digestive tract cancer, whereas a moderate intake of beer
or spirits increases the risk considerably,'' they concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
