<HEADER>
A3961 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMAN-ELECTIONS-HNS &LR;      09-25 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMAN-ELECTIONS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 KOHL'S BIG MISTAKE MAY COST HIM POWER   c Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Helmut Kohl's 16 years as Germany's head of government
may be ended Sunday by a major error he committed nearly a decade
ago at the time of his country's re-unification following the
collapse of communism.
</P>
<P>
   His decision to exchange the virtually worthless communist
currency known as the east mark on equal terms with West Germany's
strong deutsche mark was a bid to cement the previously divided
country and make himself a popular hero to the economically
strapped residents of what used to be East Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The move, which was taken against the advice of nearly all
financial experts, turned out to be an economic disaster that still
haunts him and his party, the Christian Democratic Union.
</P>
<P>
   With prices of its goods and services suddenly pegged to the
D-mark, former communist East Germany's outmoded industry found it
impossible to compete even in its old markets in the ex-Soviet
Union and its satellites. Unemployment soared to as much as 30
percent and hundreds of factories shut down almost overnight.
</P>
<P>
   East Germans' enmity toward their western brethren and
especially the Kohl government deepened into something close to
outright hatred. In some ways, as one Bonn commentator noted,
differences between the two halves of the newly unified country
seemed greater or at least more bitter than in communist times. The
``essies'' as they came to be called felt themselves ill-used and
treated with contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions have since somewhat improved. Joblessness in former
East Germany is down to 18 percent _ still more than twice the
figure in the west of the nation _ and foreign investment is at
long last trickling in. But there is still a long way to go.
Disillusionment with Kohl appears almost certain to deprive his CDU
party of enough votes in the east to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
   The best that the long-time chancellor may be able to hope for
is a so-called grand coalition with his main rivals, the Social
Democrats. who currently hold a small edge in the polls. If that
happens, a humiliated Kohl would almost certainly have to step
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the east's former communists. now known as the Party
of Democratic Socialism, smell the scent of revenge. The latest
polls suggest the ex-communists could win enough parliamentary
seats to prevent the main parties from forming a government except
on their terms.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean political paralysis in Bonn. But for easterners,
it would above all be a demonstration that they also possess power
that has been dismissed for too long as insignificant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
