<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KY-COUCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKY'S QUARTERBACK: BORN FOR THE BIG TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ky. _ There is a gold chain hanging from his neck and
the lore of a mountain hero weighing him down. Folks from the
hollows of Thousand Sticks and Hell For Certain watched him grow up
and throw touchdowns in neighboring Hyden _ at 357 people, a big
place by eastern Kentucky's standards.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Couch is 6 feet 5inches and 225pounds of square-jawed
quarterback with a high and tight haircut and manners honed in
Sunday school. Only the No. 2 _ his now-famous jersey number _ that
hangs and sparkles from that chain shouts Big Time. And why
shouldn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Couch, a junior, is a Heisman Trophy candidate. He is the golden
arm behind the nation's most productive offense. He is also the
most visible ambassador of the Commonwealth of Kentucky's other
sport. Even at Leslie County High School, where he became the most
prolific passer in national prep history, Couch signed autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always visualized that I'd be a big-time quarterback leading
a team,'' he said. ``It is what I was born to do.''
</P>
<P>
   How big time both the leader and his team have become will be
measured Saturday when the Wildcats go to Florida Field and take on
the No. 8-ranked Gators. Couch has thrown 133 times this season, 99
of them complete, for 1,171 yards and 13 touchdowns to 9 different
receivers. His Wildcats are 3-0 and ranked in the polls _ No. 25 by
the coaches _ for the first time since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to put a ball in there so they catch them,'' said
Florida Coach Steve Spurrier, the 1966 Heisman winner and an astute
judge of quarterbacks. ``His receivers have few drops.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a further history between Couch, Spurrier and
Florida that resonates beyond the nationally televised matchup and
the Wildcats' bid for respect. In 1995, the quarterback was named
National High School Player of the Year and was the center of
intense recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Most thought Couch and Spurrier were a natural fit. Spurrier
grew up in Johnson City, Tenn., was a celebrated high school
quarterback and, as a coach, turned the Gators into one of the most
pass-happy teams in the nation. But the two never warmed to each
other. ``They had a lot of passers they were talking to and I
thought he'd be a lot different,'' Couch said diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Elbert, tells it more pointedly. Spurrier never
visited the Couches. Instead he sent the defensive coordinator, Bob
Pruett. ``You got the best quarterback in the nation and you send
your defensive coordinator,'' Elbert Couch said. ``I'm sure it
offended Tim. It offended me.''
</P>
<P>
   But not Tim's mother, Janice Couch. She had painted his room
Kentucky blue in an overt hint about where she wanted him to go.
The then-Kentucky coach, Bill Curry, had won the recruiting battle,
but two years ago at Florida Field he lost the tight-knit Couch
family's good will.
</P>
<P>
   Couch did not have a good day in The Swamp. In his first
collegiate start, he was 6 of 18 for 13 yards with 1 interception.
Worse, No. 2 took a beating about as severe as the 65-0 thrashing.
``I was running the option and I'm not an option quarterback,''
Couch said tersely, which explained why Curry is no longer the
coach.
</P>
<P>
   If Spurrier spurned him and Curry alienated him, Couch found a
soulmate in Hal Mumme, now in his second year as the coach. The
Texas native is an iconoclast. He came to Kentucky from Valdosta
State in Division II, by way of Iowa Wesleyan, and brought some
funny ideas from the coaching sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Every Wildcat practice is open to anyone _ family, alumni,
students and representatives of the news media _ creating a loose
atmosphere reminiscent of an ice-cream social. And Mumme gambles.
Last year, Kentucky was 21 of 38 on fourth downs and the Wildcats
have converted 6 of 8 so far this year _ including a fake punt last
week against Indiana on fourth and 21 when Kentucky was down by 17.
That gamble resulted in a 79-yard touchdown thrown by Mumme's son,
Matt, who is Couch's backup, and keyed a 31-27 comeback victory.
</P>
<P>
   But the reason Couch is breaking records at Kentucky and not at
Tennessee _ where he threatened to transfer after his freshman year
_ is because Mumme brought the Brigham Young University offense to
Bluegrass country, after devloping a friendship with BYU Coach
LaVell Edwards. Its tenets are simple: pass short, pass long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The run is not our first choice, not even the second choice;
it's usually third,'' Mumme said of an offense averaging 572.7
yards a game.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Couch became the trigger man of an air-missile
offense that launched him into the national stratosphere. He threw
for 3,884 yards and 37 touchdowns and led the nation in pass
attempts, completions, yardage and completion percentage. He had a
better day against Florida, completing 33 of 59 for 348 yards and 2
touchdowns, but the first of his 3 interceptions helped spot the
Gators to a 28-0 first-quarter lead, and the Wildcats lost, 55-28.
</P>
<P>
   So, in the Couch home, Tim's return to Florida matters a great
deal. It may be his last time _ although only a junior, he is
expected to enter the National Football League draft next spring
and is projected as a first-round selection. Couch said he has not
decided whether he will return for his senior year, but he did take
out a $3 million insurance policy for the season.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Couch will forget about his season-long goals. How
he wants to lead the Wildcats to a bowl game. How he wants to win
the Heisman. He will focus on beating Spurrier, on erasing the
single lowest moment of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to remember me for more than what happened the
first time,'' Couch said. ``We've got a lot of confidence. We can
win down there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 0946EDT &QL; 
