<HEADER>
A4015 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-ART-REVIEW-N     09-25 1536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAJECTORY OF A BRIEF CAREER HINTS AT WHAT MIGHT HAVE BEEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The American painter Bob Thompson lived hard and died
young, in 1966, just short of his 29th birthday, after years of
substance abuse. He painted at a fairly brisk pace, too.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of his career at the Whitney Museum of American Art
is densely occupied by bright paintings large and small. They, in
turn, are densely populated by tumbling, frolicking, coupling and
sometimes fighting figures _ men and women, birds, horses, the
occasional satyr or imaginary monster. These paintings often have a
seen-before familiarity; their themes include Depositions,
bacchanals, Nativity scenes, Last Judgments and numerous Greek
myths, portrayed in compositions drawn from Poussin, Piero, Goya
and Titian.
</P>
<P>
   But these figures and the landscapes they occupy are silhouetted
in flat, feverish monochrome colors that provide an indisputably
modern air, as does their frequent tone of ribaldry, satire and
conflicting emotion. Altogether they convey a sense of headlong
momentum, of a smart young man in a hurry, in love with painting
and its history, with the possibilities of contemporary art and
with life itself. (And, judging from the number of female nudes and
their predicaments, he was visited by not altogether pleasant
feelings about women.) The intensity of these works is heightened
by galleries painted bright yellow or red, an iffy tactic that, for
once, makes the art sing.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson was born in 1937 in Louisville, Ky., the only son of a
successful, educated middle-class black family that expected its
children to go to college and into one profession or another. He
arrived in New York from art school in Louisville some time in 1959
by way of a summer in Provincetown, Mass., where he met such
figurative Expressionists as Lester Johnson, Red Grooms, Mimi Gross
and Gandy Brodie and abandoned the precocious Abstract
Expressionist style of his student days.
</P>
<P>
   He also became familiar with the painterly figuration of Jan
Muller, who had died the previous winter. He was so drawn to
Muller's art that he made an imaginary painting of his funeral. And
a piece of Muller's advice, quoted by his widow, Dody, became a
central tenet of Thompson's work: ``Don't ever look for your
solutions among the work of your contemporaries _ look at Old
Masters.'' The seven-year whirlwind career that followed included
critical and financial success and a couple of longish stints in
Europe studying art in the museums of Paris, Rome and Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever he went, Thompson seems to have made friends and
influenced people. He was magnetic, confident and determined to
succeed. His friend, the painter Emilio Cruz, called him ``a man of
unique, contagious character'' and ``perhaps the only black man I
ever met who was totally intolerant of the notion of inferiority.''
</P>
<P>
   Including more than 100 works dating from 1959 to 1966, this
show brims with a raw talent and unquenchable ambition that are
engaging and irresistible, even if Thompson never quite gained
control of them. The show does not confirm the assertion made by
Thelma Golden, the curator, in her introduction to the exhibition's
disappointing catalog, that his prolific career included many works
that are ``truly great.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, however, a number of remarkable works. Front and
center in the first gallery, one of the show's best, hangs the
monumental ``Garden of Music'' of 1960, a magnetic mural-size group
portrait of some of post-bop jazz's leading lights that may be
Thompson's masterpiece. Painted in relatively subdued tones, it
shows Ornette Coleman, John Coltrane and others with their
instruments in an abbreviated landscape of colored dots and stark
trees. It has the mysterious power of a Gauguin or a Munch expanded
to the scale of Pollock.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the middle of the show is Thompson's ``St. George and the
Dragon,'' a big reprise of Tintoretto's treatment in the National
Gallery, London, which turns the image into an abbreviated, still
scary cartoon, a Color Field painting gone wildly Classical. And
among the later works are a relatively realistic portrait, ``Le Roi
Jones and His Family,'' which shows Thompson mustering a probing
figurative style reminiscent of Alice Neel's, and paintings like
``Death of the Infants of Bethel,'' a composition reminiscent of
Poussin. Here the blazing figures form a tight, bright jigsaw,
while landscape and sky benefit from more variegated brushwork, as
if Thompson at the end of his life was toying with the idea of
breaking up his big flat shapes and painting in a more spontaneous
manner. (The fragmenting skies in the paintings in the last two
galleries portend change.) And everywhere there are instances of
ecstatic color, like the blue and white sky of ``Foetus'' of 1961.
</P>
<P>
   But too many of these paintings are unresolved and indifferently
painted. Their figures and colors jangle rather than jell,
side-stepping the sense of rightness or inevitability basic to
``great.'' They often feel like they could be adjusted, improved in
color or composition, and it often seems that Thompson agreed.
Especially in the middle of the exhibition, he seems to be
reworking similar motifs from painting to painting, so they end up
feeling both formulaic and hesitant. And almost invariably the
smaller works and studies are stronger; their colors sharper, their
surfaces less brusque than their blown-up counterparts. In fact,
the heart of the show is the red-walled gallery at its center,
where more than 40 small works dot the two walls, more or less
summing up Thompson's development and major themes in images that
have the taut radiance of cloisonne enamel.
</P>
<P>
   As few artists are able to do, Thompson's art at its best held
form, content and subject matter in equal balance, an important
example in the present moment, when content is so frequently
reduced to subject matter _ to art's detriment. He did this in an
unusual, circular way that was astutely formal and yet deeply
personal.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Thompson's work consisted of images from art history
rejuvenated by modern color and given weight by oblique or not so
oblique references to relations between the races. Thompson's red,
blue and yellow madonnas, gods and goddesses may relate to the
palette of Fauvism and Pop Art. But they create a rich
psychological resonance, as if demonstrating again and again the
relationship of color and form to feeling. And they also imply a
multiracial world, a kind of rainbow universe which, while not
without its tensions, especially where women are involved, suggests
an acceptance of difference that Thompson's real world could not
muster.
</P>
<P>
   His marriage to a white woman, Carol Plenda, cannot have been
without tensions, if only socially instilled ones; but to make such
a marriage is to dream of a world in which skin color does not
matter. Such a world, however fraught with drama, is one that he
often painted. A vivid exception is ``L'Execution,'' one of the
show's smallest, most powerful works, which features a small, black
human form, blindfolded and hanging from a tree, a lynching
descended from Piero's ``Flagellation of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's trajectory reflects the hard work and passion
required of a mature painting style, even if he did not achieve
one. Would he have continued his tango with art history? Might he
have marshaled his inspirations into a more synthesized style as
Philip Guston did? We will never know.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime his work should animate a rich discussion that
might examine his debt to various post- and post-Post-Impressionist
tendencies _ Symbolism, Fauvism and German Expressionism, his
relationship to the nonfigurative painters of his time _ to the
flat, undiluted colors of early Al Held or Jack Youngerman or late
Stuart Davis, who also drew inestimable inspiration from jazz. His
figuration needs to be closely related to other black artists from
Robert Colescott to Jean-Michel Basquiat, who also made black
achievement one of their subjects. But it also could be examined
within in a wider context of nonblack contemporaries who quoted the
Renaissance (Leland Bell, for example) or who used color to
intensely psychological ends (Lucas Samaras, for example).
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, almost none of this occurs in the exhibition's
catalog, whose main essay, by the art historian Judith Wilson,
provides a fascinating account of the artist's life. The essay is
especially enlivened by the recollections of Thompson's
contemporaries, like those of Cruz and Mrs. Muller, but it devotes
too much space to detailing paintings that appear in neither show
nor catalog and draws few useful insights from the carefully
assembled information. Still, exhibition and catalog make Thompson
an indisputable fact of recent art history, which is a cause for
celebration and, undoubtedly, an impetus for further study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Thompson'' is at the Whitney Museum of American Art, 945
Madison Avenue, at 75th Street, through Jan. 3. The show is partly
sponsored by AT&AMP;T, with additional support from Fletcher Asset
Management and TLC Beatrice International.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
