u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROADWAY-YOUTH-NYT &LR;      09-25 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY-YOUTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY FINDS AN UPSURGE IN THEATERGOERS UNDER 20 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The proportion of Broadway theatergoers younger than
20 has nearly tripled in the last 30 years, and most of these young
people attend musicals rather than plays, according to a study
released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The study, commissioned by the Theater Development Fund and the
League of American Theaters, found that theatergoers under 20 made
up 13.9 percent of the total Broadway audience last year, up from
4.9 percent in 1966. In addition, the report found Broadway's
audience was younger than Off Broadway's, with an average age of 40
compared with the Off Broadway average of 45. The research was
conducted by Audience Research and Analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The study's results may in part reflect the youthful appeal of
``Rent,'' the rock musical about life in the East Village. But
George Wachtel, president of Audience Research, said that the study
surveyed a variety of productions _ 104 audiences over 52 weeks _
and that the increases in younger audience members more likely
reflect the success of the Disney musicals ``The Lion King'' and
``Beauty and the Beast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing the children of the baby boomers attending the
theater,'' Wachtel said. ``That's healthy for the theater.'' But he
added that the report was ``also a warning.''
</P>
<P>
   Children and young teen-agers ``are going to the theater because
their parents loved it so much,'' he said. ``But we have lost the
audience in between, ages 18 to 24. That has showed a long-term
decline.'' While the report did not track that age group
specifically over the long term, Wachtel said other research showed
this trend.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that audiences remained predominantly
white: 87.1 percent for Broadway and 89.1 percent for Off Broadway.
But it showed that younger theatergoers were more ethnically
diverse. In the age range of 18 to 24, Asian, Hispanic and
African-American theatergoers represented 20 percent of the
Broadway audience and 25.4 percent Off Broadway. Those groups
accounted for 12.9 percent of the total Broadway audience last year
and 10.9 percent of the Off Broadway audience.
</P>
<P>
   The report also suggested that early exposure to theater through
arts education programs and field trips was most likely to create
adult theatergoers.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Goldstein, executive director of the Theater Development
Fund, the nonprofit organization that operates the TKTS booths,
said that he was heartened by the findings, but that there was
still a long way to go in developing young audiences for straight
plays. While people under 18 account for 12.8 percent of the total
audience at all musicals, the study found they were only 1.1
percent of the total at other plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a job to do in terms of the awareness and
accessibility of the straight play,'' Goldstein said. ``I think the
well-rounded theatergoer needs to be interested in both the
straight play and the musical.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire study can be read on the Web at www.tdf.org. It also
surveyed the attitude of theatergoers under 25. It found that 4 out
of 5 agreed that ``going to the theater is cool''; the majority
agreed ``I would spend my own money on the theater''; two-thirds
agreed that ``theater is for someone my age,'' and only 1 in 10
agreed with the statement ``I attend the theater because my parents
or teachers want me to.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the survey's other notable statistics: the percentage of
international visitors attending Broadway shows increased to 12.9
percent of the total audience in 1997, from 7.4 percent in 1991,
and Broadway theatergoers were more likely to be from out of town,
while Off Broadway audiences come predominantly from the New York
metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Women accounted for the majority of the total audience both on
and off Broadway; 26.1 percent of the Broadway audience had
children under 18, compared with 16.4 percent of the Off Broadway
audience, and theatergoers surveyed at Off Broadway performances
reported attending on average more than twice as many shows in the
last year as the Broadway audience.
</P>
</TEXT>
