<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGHWAY-FIRST-AID-NYT     09-25 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHWAY-FIRST-AID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST AID IS ESSENTIAL IN HIGHWAY FIRST AID 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ MAny highway accident victims who are pronounced
dead on arrival at emergency rooms have injuries doctors find to be
surprisingly small.
</P>
<P>
   A bump on the head, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you render someone unconscious by giving them a blow to the
head,'' said Dr. Henry Bock, an emergency room physician at
Methodist Hospital in Indianapolis, ``one of the things that gets
scrambled is the urge to breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   In the time it takes for an ambulance to arrive _ 10 minutes on
average in urban areas and 19 minutes for rural crashes _ that bump
could become fatal. Many people who are transported to emergency
rooms with head injuries, Bock said, ``never have any diagnosed
brain injuries; they have hypoxic injuries,'' meaning those caused
by lack of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Carl P. Valenziano, who is the president-elect of the
American Trauma Society, a professional association of
emergency-room doctors, said that when doctors see such a person in
the emergency room, ``We all have thoughts of, `This guy doesn't
have injuries he should have died from.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bock, who is also the medical director of the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway, said drivers hurt in crashes at the track don't have this
problem, simply because help arrives so fast.
</P>
<P>
   But help could arrive more quickly for ordinary drivers on
ordinary highways, experts say, if only bystanders were willing to
pull over and begin artificial respiration.
</P>
<P>
   In August, the Shell Oil Co. began distributing 35 million free
booklets, called ``Crash Course,'' at its service stations around
the country, to give simple instructions on what to do if you
arrive at the scene of an accident. (The information is also
available at www.countonshell.com; it was developed with the
National Safety Council, www.nsc.org, and the American Trauma
Society, www.amtrauma.org, both of which have more information.)
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, part of the
U.S. Transportation Department, is hoping to begin widespread
bystander training, like cardiopulmonary resuscitation training, in
the next few months, working through the trauma society and similar
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials and private experts say most drivers will
not stop to offer assistance unless they are confident they will do
more good than harm, and part of the training is to convince them
they can help. The training materials also point out that most
states have good Samaritan laws that protect the person who tries
to help.
</P>
<P>
   The advice from experts breaks down into five steps:
</P>
<P>
   _ Watch for accidents, especially broken guardrails or skid
marks. (About half of all fatal motor vehicle crashes are
single-vehicle accidents; in many cases a car or truck is in a
ditch or far off the road.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Park your car beyond the wreck, off the road, so you are not
hit by traffic.
</P>
<P>
   _ Call for help, or assign someone else to do so.
</P>
<P>
   _ Check for injuries. ``You tend to go to the people who yell
and scream,'' Bock said, but this is a mistake. ``Go to the quiet
people first,'' he said. ``If somebody is talking, they they are
breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Try to stop severe bleeding. The Shell booklet recommends
placing a thick pad of clean cloth over the site of the bleeding,
but other experts say a finger with a thin wrapping of clean cloth
is better, because it produces more pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, when dealing with someone who is unresponsive and
does not appear to be breathing, the latest advice contradicts a
longstanding belief about accident victims: that it is important
never to move their heads or necks. It is now recommended that a
victim's head be pointed head straight and that his jaw be lowered.
Listen for gurgling, and if necessary, the victim's mouth should be
cleared of liquid or debris. If there is still no sign of
breathing, pinch the victim's nose shut and blow into the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Bock, who helped inspire the highway safety agency to begin
working on its training course, said worries about moving a victim
are secondary. ``If they've got a neck injury, probably most of the
damage has already been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts said a significant number of the 40,000 people who die
annually because of traffic accidents could have survived if more
people stopped to help, and they hoped that training would
encourage more people to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of infection may be a problem, but experts say the risk is
very low. For AIDS, Bock said, ``you have to get the blood into
your blood, and unless you do that somehow, it's not a problem.''
Even swallowing blood would not result in infection, he said,
because that does not put contaminants in the bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   Valenziano, who is also the director of surgical critical care
and trauma at Morristown Memorial Hospital in New Jersey, said, ``I
think most people are much more scared to address injury because it
is not something they've been taught about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people feel that their actions may be futile because they
don't know what they have to do,'' he said. ``So many people say
they know CPR, but as soon as you ask them, are they confident to
stop and help at scene of crash, they say no.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
