A4090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIMES-SQUARE-DRUGS-NY     09-25 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMES-SQUARE-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIX ARRESTED IN DRUG RAID NEAR TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police officers Thursday night raided a Times Square
building that had been transformed into a haven offering services
and shelter for the poor, arresting six residents on charges that
they had sold or possessed crack cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   The raid, which came after complaints from residents and
management, was the second such operation in the last three weeks
at the Times Square Hotel on West 43d Street near Eighth Avenue.
The first one resulted in seven arrests, said Capt. Kenneth
Kelleher of the Manhattan South Narcotics District.
</P>
<P>
   The raids are part of a larger effort to rid the Times Square
Hotel of drug dealers under a plan drawn up this year by the police
and the hotel's management, the nonprofit Common Ground Community.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, which provides lodging for the poor, has made
remarkable strides in recent years to transform itself from a
rodent- and drug-infested building into a spruced-up center
offering an array of social and medical services. And both sides
hope to maintain the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to send a message that we have a zero-tolerance policy
as far as illegal activities,'' said Rosanne Haggerty, executive
director of Common Ground Community.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's raid occurred without incident as the suspects
were escorted into an unmarked police van outside the building. The
police had battering rams in tow in case they needed to break down
doors but found that most doors were open.
</P>
<P>
   Common Ground Community renovated the Times Square Hotel in 1993
and 1994. Half the building's 652 studio apartments are set aside
for the working poor; the other half are reserved for homeless
people, including those with AIDS or a history of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   As with any kind of housing for people who have had substance
abuse or other problems, there is always a struggle to maintain
order, Ms. Haggerty said.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents say that they have complained for months about
crack dealers next door; others say that some residents have loud
parties with lots of alcohol. So they said it was about time that
the police acted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the goal is to evict the people if they're not
going to be receptive to the treatment programs here,'' Captain
Kelleher said of the crackdown. ``They're just squandering a great
opportunity that others could use as a stepping stone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
