<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-PROTECTED26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida art bundled up for storm
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Multimillion-dollar art collections went
under wraps throughout South Florida recently because of Hurricane
Georges.
</P>
<P>
   Literally, in the case of the Norton Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar statues of Acteon and Diana on the museum's facade
were shrouded with tarpaulin for protection. The museum will be
closed through the end of the storm, along with many area art
museums.
</P>
<P>
   The Norton is in a flood plain. But the art-storage facility in
its expanded building is no longer on the ground floor, said
spokesperson Sarah Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   The Flagler Museum in Palm Beach is ready to restore damaged art
year-round. It has two strategically placed carts loaded with
restoration materials such as oil absorbent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say, you have a painting soaked in a storm,'' said director
John Blades. ``If you can apply some treatment to it right away,
you can sometimes minimize long-term damage.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the massive building, the former home of railroad pioneer
Henry Flagler, Blades said ``it has withstood two major hurricanes
in its time. I think it can get through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Water, not wind, worries Morikami Museum officials in Delray
Beach. ``Our concern is flooding because the water level of our
lake is already very high,'' said director Larry Rosensweig.
Unprotected art has been moved off the ground floor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Boca Raton Museum of Art, officials were preparing to
move more than a half-dozen large metal sculptures indoors if the
storm neared the city. Some huge sculptures are bolted to concrete
and would remain outside. ``These are two- and three-ton metal
sculptures,'' said museum registrar Marc Ransdell. ``If a hurricane
can move them, we're all in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
