<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurricane chat storms internet
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is my first cyber-hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't online in previous years, which means I didn't have
access to a vast array of knowledge and information on the screen
of my home computer.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't have the ability to engage in something called
``hurricane chat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Georges may not be the end of the world for us. But
you could make the argument that ``hurricane chat'' is.
</P>
<P>
   There are places on the Internet where real information from
reputable sources is available. But certainly not at an electronic
watering hole where legions of bored and nervous people gather to
yammer about a looming natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of computer technology, as a storm approaches we
now can touch the lives of thousands of other mildly uninformed
people by swapping bad information and unwarranted panic while at
the same time trolling for members of the opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, you're in a gay hurricane chat room.
</P>
<P>
   (Editor's note: Frank, it sounds like you're saying that the
hurricane is gay. Is that what you mean?
</P>
<P>
   Note to editor: No, the ``gay'' refers to the people in the chat
group. Although, now that you mention it, hurricanes rarely go
straight.)
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't think hurricane chat would be an excuse to pick up
women. It's hard to imagine trying to put the make on somebody with
a patio-furniture-in-the-swimming-pool question.
</P>
<P>
   But after spending lots of time in hurricane chat over the past
couple of days, I've discovered that even an approaching maelstrom
is no reason to suspend cyber-trolling operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have a daughter my age?'' one of my cyber-companions
just blurted out during a plywood discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, another communicant just started greeting
other chatters with, ``Hi, sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, a hurricane chatter will abandon all talk of
storm tracking and flat-out ask others to reveal their age and sex
_ making it easier to pick one off from the herd.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that if there's an Ebola virus chat group, guys will
be on it, looking to hit on women.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some people are actually in hurricane chat to chat
about hurricanes. Here's just a sample of the information and
opinions I was offered: 1. The hurricane is heading to Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   2. Canned peaches are hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   3. Being stoned during a hurricane makes drowning less painful.
</P>
<P>
   4. Looters should be shot.
</P>
<P>
   5. If a hurricane wipes out your possessions, you'll get to
upgrade your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the funniest bit of hurricane paranoia was exhibited by
one participant who asked everybody else: ``Who thinks it will go
to the East Coast? Press 1.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, that person counted the number of ``1's'' to determine
whether he or she should be concerned about the storm. Tracking by
popular vote.
</P>
<P>
   I confess, my plan to remain passive in these hurricane chat
groups evaporated sometime after midnight on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some guy in Miami was asking about the best way to secure his
doggie door.
</P>
<P>
   Another person suggested he buy ``tiny sand bags from Home
Depot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Depot's out of the tiny sand bags,'' I typed. ``I've got
little rollaway shutters on my dog door.''
</P>
<P>
   This began a 15-minute discussion on possible doggie door storm
protection.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of it, I was suggesting: ``Of course, when all else
fails, you can plug up the hole with the animal, itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how low have I fallen!
</P>
<P>
   I can't wait for this hurricane to go away so I can go back to
using my computer for more edifying purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Such as reading the footnotes in the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
