   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-READING _ Do teenagers read? The answer is, well, kind of.
And because there is growing alarm in national educational circles
about the general state of literacy in America today, some of that
concern is distilled onto teenagers, the group on the cusp of
becoming reading or non-reading adults. (Sauer, Grand Junction
Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WHALEY_ Emily Whaley, whose 1997 book, ``Mrs. Whaley and Her
Charleston Garden,'' won the hearts of gardeners and non-gardeners
alike because of her candid outlook on life after 80, is still
making headlines. Whaley, who died this summer, has a new book
coming out in October, ``Mrs. Whaley Entertains,'' in which she
demonstrates how to enjoy yourself _ and make the best of your home
and garden _ while planning and throwing a party. As more folks tap
into her insight and her memory endures (the Charleston Garden
Festival is dedicated to next month), we talk to acquaintances
about her many contributions during a rich life. (Flanders ,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). ETA: 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WHALEY-REVIEW _ A review of ``Mrs. Whaley Entertains.'' (Brock,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). ETA: 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   GARDENFEST _ The Charleston Garden Festival, the Southeast's
largest fall gardening event, will feature talks by several Atlanta
area experts, including University of Georgia professor Alan
Armitage and garden designer Ryan Gainey. (Flanders , Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). ETA: 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   YOM-KIPPUR _ Even the beginning of the 10 Days of Awe, Rosh
Hashana, the New Year, can boast the first, dramatic blasts of the
shofar, a ram's horn. It's a joy for children to watch and hear.
But it is a stirring wake-up call for adults, the beginning of a
10-day period of introspection and review, which ends on Yom
Kippur. (Benarde, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOM-KIPPUR-REPENT_ Yom Kippur. It's the most sacred day on the
Jewish Calendar, and literally means, Day of Atonement. Bill
Clinton recently said he has ``repented,'' even quoting from the
liturgy used by Jews during Yom Kippur services. But does saying
you're sorry really mean you've repented. We explore the concept of
forgiveness, atonement and repentence, focusing on the president
and the news of the day, but including a theological and historical
perspective. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 5 p.m.
</P>
