<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Funeral home dispute goes to mediation
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A $445,000 dispute between the world's largest
funeral home company and the State of Texas is headed for
mediation.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Funeral Service Commission voted recently to send the
controversial case about alleged illegal embalming to a state
mediation program.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has rocked the funeral home industry in Texas as
1,200 funeral homes watch to see which side will prevail: the tiny
state regulatory agency or the $2.5 billion industry powerhouse,
Service Corporation International, known as SCI.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy arose last spring after state regulators
conducted surprise inspections of two Dallas-area funeral homes
owned by SCI and found what they described as evidence of
unlicensed embalming companies operating there. Regulators also
reported finding that embalming had been performed by apprentices
without proper supervision.
</P>
<P>
   The inspections _ and additional subpoenas issued to almost two
dozen SCI homes _ angered the Houston-based funeral home company.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Robert Waltrip hand-delivered a complaint to the
funeral commission and to Gov. George W. Bush's office.
</P>
<P>
   He accused state regulators of ``storm-trooper tactics'' and
urged that staff members be disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission staff proceeded with its investigation of
SCI, and last month a commission panel recommended fines of
$445,000 against 23 SCI funeral homes and funeral directors. The
fines would be the largest penalty ever imposed by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the recommended fines, SCI informed the
commission it would ask for individual informal appeal conferences
to challenge the case against each funeral home and director.
</P>
<P>
   But SCI officials also said they would be willing to try to
resolve the dispute in mediation. The commission voted to sign a
$70-an-hour contract for mediation with the State Office of
Administrative Hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, it will be settled at mediation,'' said funeral
commission member Kenneth Hughes of Nacogdoches, who chaired the
committee that recommended the fines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to be going to mediation,'' said Bill Miller, an
Austin consultant hired by SCI last month to handle media
inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great way to resolve differences amicably and
completely,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mediation may not resolve one lingering disagreement among
board members.
</P>
<P>
   The commission voted in May to reprimand its two members who
work for large, national funeral home chains _ Tommy Metcalf, an
SCI employee, and Robert Duncan of Equity Corporation
International, which is merging with SCI.
</P>
<P>
   They were accused of harassing the commission's regulators and
trying to interfere in investigations.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's meeting, Metcalf and Duncan addressed the
commission to deny any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I in no way threatened or intimidated (staff) of this funeral
service commission, and I most certainly did not obstruct
justice,'' Duncan said.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf said the commission owes him an apology for maligning
his reputation and integrity. He said he had done nothing more than
challenge staff members during routine commission meetings to
verify that they had proper evidence for their cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they take this as a personal attack on them, that's their
problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
