<HEADER>
A4114 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENS-READING26-COX     09-25 1932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-READING26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Do teens read? Kind of
 &HT;    By Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So there was this enormous white whale that was driving the
obsessive-compulsive Captain Ahab insane, and this guy Ishmael
wrote all about out.
</P>
<P>
   You know, Ishmael, as in ``Call me Ishmael.'' As in the first
line of ``Moby Dick.'' By Herman Melville. Come on, surely you've
heard of it.
</P>
<P>
   OK, how about this: In a moment of spiritual blindness, King
Lear booted out his good daughter, Cordelia, trusted his sneaky
daughters, Regan and Goneril, and eventually paid for it in a big,
big way.
</P>
<P>
   A big way. It was terrible. He went crazy and died. Is any of
this ringing a bell?
</P>
<P>
   Sigh. Never mind. Go back to your Gameboy or soccer practice or
Must-See TV or whatever and let the pundits wring their hands and
gnash their teeth and despair about how teenagers today just don't
read.
</P>
<P>
   Don't they?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's not that simple. Do teenagers read? The answer
is, well, kind of. Maybe. Some do, some don't. And because there is
growing alarm in national educational circles about the general
state of literacy in America today, some of that concern is
distilled onto teenagers, the group too old to be forced to read
and on the cusp of becoming reading or non-reading adults.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Assessment of Educational Progress, in
1994 approximately 24 percent of high school seniors surveyed said
they read for fun almost every day, while 27 percent reported never
or hardly ever reading for fun. In the same survey, 45 percent of
fourth-graders said they read for fun almost every day.
</P>
<P>
   So somewhere between ages 9 and 17, 21 percent of America's
youth stop reading for fun almost every day, and by the later teen
years a person's reading habits are basically set, said Dr.
Elizabeth Moje, an assistant professor of literacy, language and
learning disabilities at the University of Michigan at Ann Arbor.
She has conducted extensive national research on the reading
practices of at-risk youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think teenagers today do read, actually, sometimes quite
avidly, but they don't read all of the things that their teachers
might value or the things we might deem to be classics,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But still, approximately 76 percent of high school seniors don't
read for fun almost every day. That's a lot. And with Mesa County's
estimated functional illiteracy rate at about 28 percent of all
adults, that's worrisome. And that leads to a lot of finger
pointing by older generations that these kids today just don't read
as much as they did when they were young.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder about that, though,'' said Lorena Thompson, who
teaches English and literature at Grand Junction High School. ``Did
older generations really read that much more when they were
teenagers?''
</P>
<P>
   Josh Gumpert, 15, said that might be possible, but only because
there were fewer distractions 50 years ago than there are today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time things have changed,'' he said. ``There's so much
more entertainment now, computers, TV, the Internet, video games.
And more of us have jobs and play sports. A lot of times we don't
have time to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Clara Brown, 17, agreed: ``Time is a constant issue. We don't
have time to read for fun because we're already reading so much for
school. Most of us like to read,'' she said, indicating the rest of
the students in her advanced placement English class, ``but we're
doing so many other things in addition to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, today's teenagers are part of a generation that grew up
using a day planner. Because of modern conveniences people have
more leisure time than in previous eras, said Al Kreinberg, a
language arts and social studies teacher at R-5 High School, but
those increased leisure hours are increasingly packed with things
to do.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why, unlike previous generations, teenagers now are
victims of stress and must find ways of coping with it. Perhaps
that is why they frequently turn to the television to relax and
unwind, said Shaina Kaufman, 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you've been in school all day, you want to come
home and veg out,'' Kaufman said. ``You watch TV and it's easy, you
don't have to think or worry about whether you're understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   But TV is commonly seen as contributing to the abysmal reading
scores on national standardized proficiency tests. According to the
National Center for Educational Statistics, 25 percent of high
school seniors tested scored below the basic reading level in 1994.
That same report said there is a direct correlation between TV
viewing and reading proficiency. The more TV a teen watches, the
less likely he or she is to be a proficient reader.
</P>
<P>
   Still, though, some teenagers are reading. About 24 percent of
high school seniors surveyed in a 1994 National Assessment of
Educational Progress study said they read for fun once or twice a
week, if not every day. So coupled with the 24 percent who read for
fun almost every day, almost 50 percent of America's high school
seniors read for fun at least once a week.
</P>
<P>
   That's still not nearly enough, most would agree, but it's a
start, Moje said. The dilemma is how to satisfy a generation of
teenagers who grew up with instant gratification, who know if one
thing doesn't appeal to them they can push a button and have dozens
of other choices. It's that sound-bite mentality that confounds
people who don't relate to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be able to relate to the things I read, to be
interested in them. There's nothing worse than a boring book,''
said Mandy Bottger, 17.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most realistic and worldly generation in a while,
teenagers need to see how what they read is going to be useful to
them or at least entertain them without being boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key to getting teenagers to read is if it grabs
their interest right off,'' said Sue Ann Thompson, teen librarian
at the Mesa County Public Library's main branch. ``If it speaks to
them they'll read it, and it doesn't matter how long it is if it's
something they can identify with.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why a humanities teacher at a District 51 high school
took ``The Agony and the Ecstasy'' by Irving Stone off the required
reading list for a humanities class, causing some literary purists
to weep. The students wouldn't read it, maybe out of laziness,
``but more because students couldn't relate to it,'' said Marcia
Beuscher, 17.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is yet another shameful hallmark of dumbed-down
school curricula and a non-existent student work ethic, but Moje
emphasized that ``teenagers are reading a lot, but they don't
necessarily read or write the kinds of things valued in schools.''
</P>
<P>
   In her research, Moje said she has found that teenagers like
popular magazines and comic books and popular paperbacks by V.C.
Andrews, Tom Clancy and Stephen King. If the point is to get teens
to read words strung together into sentences, then they're doing
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reading is like a sport,'' said Brian Hurd, 15. ``You do it if
you're interested. There are always going to be people who just
don't like to read.''
</P>
<P>
   And most teenagers agree that they don't like having books
forced on them. So an adult shoving a copy of ``War and Peace'' in
a teenager's face and saying read it, for the love of all things
holy, because it's a classic and we should love the classics isn't
exactly a good motivator. Which isn't to underestimate the
classics, but if the mystique was removed and they were presented
as having real life applications, maybe more teenagers would want
to read them, Kaufman said.
</P>
<P>
   And if teens could talk about the dangers of modern
relationships instead of having to memorize the exact chronology of
Miss Havisham's descent into lunacy in ``Great Expectations,'' that
might be more successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're forced to memorize facts and then have to do a book
report or something, it stops being fun,'' said Audra Price, 15.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Ann Thompson agreed: ``You can lead a teenager to the
library but you can't make him read,'' she laughed, citing teens
who come in on their own because someone has said something about a
book that piqued their curiosity or because they developed an
interest in something and want to read more about it.
</P>
<P>
   Again, not to make things easier for students or take away their
educational responsibility, but they want to talk about a book and
understand it, said Kathryn Winkleblack, 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to discuss a book with somebody who's read it
really helps me,'' said Desiree Harris, 15.
</P>
<P>
   Having parents or friends who encourage reading also helps, said
Robert Gilmar, 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents always read, always had books for us when I was
little, and that really helped me love reading,'' said Sarah
Whitehurst, 15.
</P>
<P>
   Educational and literacy experts agree that a love of reading
begins at birth, with parents reading to their children daily,
telling stories, having books around the home, visiting the library
and setting an example by reading themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers can help, too, by having story time, which Michelle
Hays, 14, said was her particular favorite, and doing things to get
kids thinking about books, to get them interested and engaged in
their reading, Moje said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you discuss a book, get kids to see how it can apply to
their lives, see how it's exciting and interesting, that will help
kids learn to love reading,'' Moje said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teachers should not assign reading that will not benefit
students in some way,'' Lorena Thompson said. ``Teachers should
give them a reason to read it. Some will choose not to and they
will fail, but it will be an informed choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Shanks, 15, said adults need to be more informed about the
reading teenagers are doing. That means not underestimating the
value of what they read on the Internet, which Kreinberg said is
becoming a huge source of reading material for his students, or
even in comic books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things teens read for pleasure outside of school are
really devalued,'' Moje said. ``Things like comic books. I've tried
to read them and I don't understand them, I can't make sense of
them. It's a really sophisticated literary practice to be able to
understand these, their multiple layers of text and being able to
follow all of it. Some of them are really challenging pieces of
text.''
</P>
<P>
   And if all else fails, bribery never hurts: Ellen Hardy said her
parents offered her $5 for each book she reads during the summer.
Julia Berry, 17, said her mother buys her a new book as soon as she
finishes the previous one.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that goes for adults, too,'' laughed Kristin Smith, 15.
``There's that contest with Oprah's Book Club that if you read the
book you could win lunch with Oprah. My mom reads those books every
month.''
</P>
<P>
   But back to the main question: Do teenagers read? The answer is
not as much as they should for the their own futures and the good
of society, but there's hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's true that maybe our teenagers aren't reading in the
same way that the generation before us read, they're still reading
and they need to be encouraged to read a wide variety of things,''
Moje said. ``That doesn't mean throw the classics out, but it means
we need to expand our repertoire of reading.''
</P>
<P>
   So maybe teenagers could relate better to the pride of man
trying to dominate nature and himself in Jon Krakauer's ``Into Thin
Air'' more than Melville's ``Moby Dick.''
</P>
<P>
   And the mighty fall of King Lear? Check out popular magazine
articles about President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
