<SLUG> BC-NY-ROBBERY-GANG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN POSING AS UTILITY WORKERS PREY ON ELDERLY AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It begins with frantic knocking and doorbell-ringing,
and the elderly Brooklynites who answer are met by men in hard hats
and fluorescent-orange vests, carrying crackling walkie-talkies.
The men claim to be from ``the water company'' and warn of a nearby
water main break and the possibility of flooding, broken gas lines
and contaminated tap water. They ask, in urgent tones, to come
inside to check the pipes.
</P>
<P>
   But these men do not work for any utility, the police said.
Rather, they are a sophisticated team of thieves who have used
their disguises and tales of impeding emergency to enter, ransack
and rob at least 20 homes in Brooklyn in the last month.
</P>
<P>
   Like many con artists, the police said, they prey on the elderly
_ so far, the victims of the scam have all been between the ages of
70 and 92.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Salvatore Magaddino of the Brooklyn Robbery Squad said that
four men posing as utility workers have carried out the robberies,
mostly in Bensonhurst and Bay Ridge but some in Coney Island,
Flatbush and Park Slope, since Aug. 20. Some people have been
robbed of as much as $4,000, he said, and many lost favorite
heirlooms.
</P>
<P>
   Among the victims was Iole Cascio, a piano teacher who said she
was in her 70s and whose Bensonhurst home was hit on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One rang the bell and I said, `Who is it?''' she recalled
Thursday. ``They said, `We're here to check your water _ there's
been a break on 63d Street. Have you drunk any water today? Has
anyone gotten sick?'''
</P>
<P>
   As the two men continued to speak, Mrs. Cascio recalled, they
walked into her house.
</P>
<P>
   ``One went upstairs with my daughter and said that he needed to
check for any discoloration in the bathtub,'' she said. ``The other
took me out to test a hose. He said I had to hold the hose while he
looked at the water. I was holding that hose for 15 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   While she held the hose, she said, the man kept talking, telling
her that he had been a plumber, that he likes the sun, that he
sleeps with two blankets. He told her that the utility company
would pay her $23 for her troubles, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point he began speaking into his walkie-talkie in a
language Mrs. Cascio did not recognize. When she asked, he told her
it was Hungarian. A few minutes later he went back inside, met his
partner at the bottom of the stairs, and walked out.
</P>
<P>
   Then Mrs. Cascio saw what had happened. Her closet was open, her
dresser had been emptied, and her rooms had been ransacked. Some
money and keepsakes were missing, she said, but she has yet to
tally the extent of her loss.
</P>
<P>
   She figures that while the former plumber kept her busy at the
hose and his partner kept her daughter in the upstairs bathroom,
their accomplices went through her house.
</P>
<P>
   The police are looking for four men between the ages of 25 and
50 who are all tall and heavyset. After several homes were hit on
Aug. 27, he said, the police distributed thousands of warning
fliers at centers for the elderly in southern Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the police said another robbery with the same
modus operandi occurred at 3:20 p.m. Four men wearing yellow hard
hats entered a home in Bensonhurst on the pretense of repairing a
water main, and, as one of the men took the home's elderly
occupants to the basement, the others ransacked the home, making
off with $1,600 and jewelry, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The next time the robbers strike, Magaddino said, the aviation
unit plans to send a police helicopter to track their getaway. The
robbers hit five homes on Wednesday, the police said, and one 911
caller said the men fled in a red van.
</P>
</TEXT>
