<HEADER>
A4119 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATCHER-COLUMN26-COX     09-25 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATCHER-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Childish response to juvenile crime
 &HT;    By Candy Hatcher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, while the nation was distracted by slime, Congress
performed a sleight-of-hand on juvenile justice.
</P>
<P>
   The House took a simple bill that would have provided money to
help reunite families with their missing children, turned it into a
$1.5 billion, tough-on-crime sound bite and called it a lesson in
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   It's brilliant. Guaranteed to teach us all a lesson. Here's how
it works:
</P>
<P>
   When a child commits a crime, punish him. If he commits another,
lock him up in a state-of-the-art detention center or, better yet,
an adult prison, where he can hone his crime skills. Make his
juvenile records public so he can't get a job or a college
education. Don't provide money for counseling, mental health
treatment or job training.
</P>
<P>
   Even Florida's conservative, tough-talking corrections officials
shook their heads in disgust this week when they heard the proposal
had passed the House. They know such draconian measures don't
reduce crime. Such laws turn petty thieves and troubled adolescents
into self-absorbed, manipulative, sometimes-violent adults whose
only skill is breaking the law.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, 280 members of Congress thought it sounded good.
They didn't tack it onto a proposal to help more mentally ill
children get treatment. They didn't tack it onto a bill that would
have provided therapy for children from abusive homes. Those
proposals are still stalled.
</P>
<P>
   But this one is a winner. To hear Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Orlando,
tell it, this bill will ``show juveniles that there are
consequences for their actions.'' It will encourage states to
prosecute more children in adult court, make juvenile records
public and increase the penalties for second and subsequent
arrests. The reward for any of the 40-odd states that rewrite their
juvenile laws to conform to this legislation: part of a three-year,
$1.5 billion pot of money that will pay for more detention centers,
more prosecutors, more probation officers.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds good, right? Take a seat in the courtroom of Palm Beach
County's chief juvenile judge, Ron Alvarez. Listen as social
workers, prosecutors, defense lawyers and the judge try to help
12-year-old Dorothy. Mentally retarded and mentally ill, she is
accused of having attacked her mother while in a rage. Judge
Alvarez has seen her before.
</P>
<P>
   The social worker: ``Dorothy's primary problem is mental
health-related as opposed to being a delinquent child. The
consensus is she needs . . . something that is secure. But there's
no funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Alvarez: `It's July (the beginning of the budget year).
How did you run out of money already?'
</P>
<P>
   Social services administrator: ``The treatment, annualized, is
$300,000, which is our total budget for the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Alvarez: ``Do you have any idea . . . when the Legislature
is going to wake up and realize how many kids need help with mental
health services as opposed to the jail cells they keep building? .
. . This lady needs help. She doesn't need to be placed in a
facility where there's a high probability of her conduct becoming
worse. Dorothy's not a delinquent child. She needs a mental health
placement. Today.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is nowhere to put her. Congress and the Legislature
have ignored Dorothy and others like her, choosing to concentrate
instead on the 20 percent of juvenile delinquents who truly need to
be locked up and kept away from society.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the other 80 percent, who enter the criminal
justice system in need of help, not incarceration? They are
mentally ill, or addicted to drugs or alcohol. Some are grappling
with learning disabilities; others are simply struggling with
adolescence. Many have no parents at home to give guidance and
discipline and set a good example.
</P>
<P>
   Do we just lock them up and expect them to behave better when
they get out?
</P>
<P>
   Candy Hatcher is an editorial writer for The Palm Beach Post.
E-mail her at candy_hatcher(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
