<HEADER>
A4120 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELSO-COLUMN26-COX     09-25 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In search of a Starr-proof president
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The next president of the United States?
</P>
<P>
   My pick would be John K. McMillan, 41, the only person I know of
who might be able to stand up to the intense personal scrutiny
elected officials have to put up with today.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan, of Austin, is not exactly what you could call a party
animal. In fact, he is the founder, and only member, of the
Progressive Prohibitionist religion.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those churches with no building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a real advocate of fruit juice,'' the unflamboyant
McMillan said. He would like to start up an alcohol-free zone in
Austin consisting of fruit juice parlors, health food stores and
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   So far the groundswell for this movement has been nonexistent.
In fact, McMillan says he has created virtually no interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put an announcement on community access television and have
had, let's see, basically no calls on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan just isn't the kind of guy who would make this nation
look foolish by creating a scene. This guy is so dull that
sometimes he uses his compensatory and vacation time from his
clerical job with the Texas Department of Public Safety to speak
before the Austin City Council.
</P>
<P>
   A regular at council meetings, he speaks once a month on such
topics as sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I even give my phone number each time, but I haven't gotten
any calls on my speeches,'' McMillan said.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine McMillan involved in a scandal, because to
create one usually takes at least two people. And I suspect when
McMillan is around, he is often the only one there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been invited to more than one party in the last year
and a half,'' McMillan said. He amended that to say that since
March 1997 he has been invited to just four parties in the Austin
area.
</P>
<P>
   He declined going to an Academy Awards-watching affair because
``I would have been up too late.'' One party he went to occurred at
The Spaghetti Warehouse downtown.
</P>
<P>
   What was that like? ``OK. We basically just sat there at this
table, about 10 of us, and we ordered an Italian meal,'' the stolid
McMillan said.
</P>
<P>
   Even Monica Lewinsky and a side order of breadsticks couldn't
liven up that gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's McMillan's sex life. Shoot, he says he didn't even
achieve what the Romans called Hankius pankerooni during the two
years he was a student at the University of Texas in the late '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had zero sex of any sort, not even French kissing,'' the
single McMillan said. ``The most I did was shake hands with
people.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McMillan added, he didn't even get many phone calls to
his apartment while he was attending UT.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the calls I got were almost always wrong numbers for the
Police Department,'' McMillan said.
</P>
<P>
   So let's elect John K. McMillan as our next U.S. president.
Under the new rules, he may be the only man left qualified for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes a humor column on Mondays, Wednesdays and
Fridays. He can be reached at 445-3606 or at jkelsostatesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
