<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celebrity crushes are (mostly) harmless . . .
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just in case Bruce Springsteen needs any character references to
cinch his induction into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame, I'll go on
record: He has never taken advantage of the clause in my marriage
contract stipulating my unrestricted right to run off with His
Scruffiness.
</P>
<P>
   My husband worries about this quite a bit, as well he should.
Why, if Bruce spent an hour or two with me, he'd realize we're
soulmates, and leave that red-headed woman in the dust.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, I'm terribly anxious about the clause in Jim's
contract granting him the same privileges with Lena Olin (the
actress who wore that bowler hat in The Unbearable Lightness of
Being, remember?).
</P>
<P>
   I thought every couple played this
``What-celebrity-would-tempt-you-to-abandon-your-marriage-vows?''
game. It's innocent, it's entertaining, it's a bellwether of
tastes. (No second dates with a guy whose feminine ideal is Pamela
Lee Anderson or Heather-Be-Thy-Name Locklear.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet when I mentioned this custom to a friend, she gasped: ``You
tell him that?''
</P>
<P>
   Are we the only ones who talk about this stuff? After conducting
a scientific survey of my girlfriends, I have good news for all
those who fantasize about celebrities: You're not alone.
</P>
<P>
   There's even good news for those who fret about America's moral
turpitude: Half the fun is that it poses absolutely no threat to
our true loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``My almost always number one is Kenneth Branagh,'' writes
Hildegarde. ``That face, that accent, that everything else. He's
got it all and could quote me Shakespeare all day to boot. Also on
my list is Ralph Fiennes: Striking, brooding, magnetic _ you get
the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I have talked about the healthiness of admiring
beauty everywhere, but only expressing that admiration with your
one and only. He says it's OK to work up an appetite as long as you
eat at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculates my friend Bathsheba: ``I have a greater chance of
being struck by a meteor than having celebrity sex.'' Still, she
wouldn't mind taking a gander at Paul Newman, ``although he's
getting a little long in the tooth to induce intense wantonness.''
</P>
<P>
   Fantasies are tailored to the emotional needs of the moment.
After her divorce, Penelope ``had a huge crush on Bob Vila. He
seemed like a nice, patient guy who would teach me how to hang
drywall without getting angry if I used the wrong drill bit. In my
daydreams I imagined that he would let me borrow his flannel
shirts. Maybe he'd even think I looked cute in his flannel
shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ophelia dares not tell her husband of her secret passion for
Peter Jennings: ``Yes, he's balding, smokes and doesn't have a good
track record with women _ but so erudite! And the way he says 'We
begin tonight. . . .' is just thrilling. He understands me, I just
know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Esmerelda goes for the dangerous type: ``I would like to spend a
weekend with Tom Petty, but my sense is that, aside from being a
brilliant musician, he is also a skinny little stoner from
Gainesville who reeks of cigarettes. . . . So I gotta say, when I
think about it, I wouldn't run away with anyone. And I've noticed
that my husband just gets better-looking all the time. I'm serious.
He looks like someone in a Nautica ad.''
</P>
<P>
   What's this? She starts out fantasizing about Tom Petty, and
ends up rhapsodizing about her husband. Hey! That's not the way the
game should be played.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it is. What if we lived out our celebrity fantasies?
Poor Bruce. Poor Lena. How cruel it would be, were Jim and I to toy
with their affections, only to come running back to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
