<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-FIGURE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High court: Reporter was public figure
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In an unusual case of a Waco television reporter
suing another television station for libel over his coverage of the
1993 Branch Davidian siege, the Texas Supreme Court decided that
the Waco reporter had no case.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision _ that the Waco reporter was a ``public
figure'' _ was its first to define when someone involved in a
high-profile controversy falls into a category that makes winning a
libel case harder than someone considered a private person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Supreme Court once again showed its commitment to
free speech and free press,'' said Dallas media lawyer Chip
Babcock, a former newspaper reporter who defended television
personality Oprah Winfrey in her suit earlier this year for
violating Texas' so-called veggie libel law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the court hit the nail on the head,'' Babcock said.
</P>
<P>
   John McLemore, who covered the raid at the Branch Davidian
compound, alleged that Dallas television station WFAA and one of
its reporters defamed him in a story on speculation that the
Davidian sect members were tipped off to federal agents' raid of
the sect's Mount Carmel headquarters. McLemore sought $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Four agents of the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms
and three sect members died in the raid that began a protracted
standoff that ended in fiery destruction of the compound that
killed 76 sect members.
</P>
<P>
   The court, in a unanimous opinion, held that a television
reporter was a public figure when _ as in McLemore's case _ the
reporter interjected himself into the controversy surrounding the
news event.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore, one of the few journalists who reported live from the
raid, was at the Davidian compound when federal agents stormed it
early in the morning on Feb. 28, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In the decision, Justice Deborah Hankinson wrote that McLemore
was a public figure because he ``clearly voluntarily interjected
himself into the controversy'' over why the raid failed. Hankinson
determined that McLemore entered the compound when other reporters
did not and said McLemore portrayed himself to other reporters as a
hero by risking being shot to assist wounded federal agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``By reporting live from the heart of the controversial raid,
McLemore assumed a risk that his involvement in the event would be
subject to public debate,'' Hankinson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore, who now works for a Waco life insurance company, said
he was merely covering the story and responding to federal agents
who asked him to help with the wounded. ``If that's interjecting
myself into the story, I don't get it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore said he probably would appeal to the U.S. Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Being deemed a public figure, McLemore would have to prove that
WFAA's reporter knew what she reported was false or that she was
reckless about whether it was true.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Supreme Court said McLemore could not prove that.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore alleged that reporter Valeri Williams _ now a reporter
with ABC News _ libeled him by reporting that federal agents
claimed Waco reporters were hiding in trees at the compound before
the attack began.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' story repeated an allegation told to ABC's
``Nightline'' program by Houston Chronicle reporter Kathy Walt that
authorities believed Waco reporters tipped the Branch Davidians to
an impending raid.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore also sued Walt and the Chronicle, but he dismissed them
from the suit before trial.
</P>
<P>
   The trial judge refused to dismiss the suit against Williams and
WFAA. The Texas Court of Appeals in Waco upheld the judge's
refusal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
