<SLUG> BC-STORM-WATERBOYS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Water boys deliver through storm
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ A moment of applause, please, for the water
boys.
</P>
<P>
   They've been restocking grocery shelves and making extra
deliveries this week, and they're in the running with the Weather
Channel folks for Most Popular.
</P>
<P>
   They're a little modest. ``I didn't even shave today,'' says
Jeff Forschbach, rubbing his chin.
</P>
<P>
   He's a Culligan man, and he's on the road every day at 7:15 a.m.
He doesn't plan any breaks, and he might get home to Lake Worth by
nightfall to close the hurricane shutters.
</P>
<P>
   His route is the area bounded by Okeechobee, Military Trail,
Southern and Jog. He's serving regular customers, but his
900-gallon truck is ready for the unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Like the polite request from Betty Shrewsbury, who meets him at
the door of her shuttered home. ``Can I get an extra bottle in case
of a hurricane?'' No problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's gonna happen, it's gonna happen,'' Shrewsbury says as
Forschbach heads for the truck for another five gallons. ``I'm not
gonna run from it.''
</P>
<P>
   At another stop, Forschbach shows off the note stuck in the
door:
</P>
<P>
   ``Culligan _
</P>
<P>
   Please leave three free jugs.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Smith.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have been doing this,'' Forschbach says. ``I
can give them one or two. If we did this all day, we'd run out.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaves two. Aaron Smith, Carolyn's son and a student at Palm
Beach Community College, doesn't seem to care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here all my life,'' he says. ``Another hurricane,
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Another hurricane, another 72 extra calls for water, Forschbach
says. The Culligan men split the load.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you want me to say we've brought in temps or
something,'' says Bill Bauer, general manager at Culligan's Palm
Beach County office on Military Trail. ``But we're efficient
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even he had to leave the office on Sept. 23 for the
first time in months to make deliveries. Fourteen of them.
</P>
<P>
   In Riviera Beach, the Mountain Water Co. got 167 calls, compared
to the average 60. Bishop's Water Co. in Lake Worth has two extra
trucks making deliveries, and calls have increased about 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Culligan usually gets two tractor trailers of water a week from
its plant in Ocala. Now it gets one a day. The plant is working
around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   They can't ship it fast enough, Bauer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the drivers were in by 8:30 last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
