<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Did tapes backfire?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It couldn't be. Or could it? Could the nearly mythical survival
power of Bill Clinton be triggered at death's door by what,
possibly, is the lowest moment in any presidency ever?
</P>
<P>
   Hard to imagine, but, here goes: The tapes backfired. As alarmed
as Americans are over the personal revelations, so too do people
resent someone shoving this in their faces, a wall-to-wall X-rated
TV show. And, no, this wasn't ``The People's Court.'' This was an
evidentiary fishing expedition, no presumption that a word of it
would ever make it to trial. Grand juries are secret for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was like one of those coup moments in countries whose
names change every other Friday: The deposed ruler stares into the
kliegs of seized state TV. Glowing cigarettes wait off-camera to
burn star-shaped scars into his flesh until he makes a statement to
signal the takeover complete. Next, we find his body wrapped in a
blanket on a street corner, and the people dance.
</P>
<P>
   Did GOP leaders (GOP now standing for Gratuitous On-screen Porn)
expect a street dance? They didn't get it. Maybe it's the corpse
that's missing.
</P>
<P>
   The amazing thing about this is that the Republicans didn't need
to offend the country in such a way. They could have left that up
to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   You can't defend the man in this case. My steps would be lighter
if he left office tomorrow. I'd vote for resignation rather than to
hear one more apology, and, goodness gracious, not one that makes
the State of the Union five minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   But meanwhile, since it doesn't appear the president is ready to
resign or die from his self-inflicted wounds, there is the matter
of impeachment and a moment's pause for the gung-ho crowd. It seems
a key point used to bring the Monica matter into Ken Starr's
dragnet is missing.
</P>
<P>
   Starr sold Janet Reno on the expansion of his investigation _
from Whitewater and more to a sexual relationship _ in major part
based on the presumption of evidence that Clinton asked Lewinsky to
lie and that he got her a job to shut her up.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far that evidence is not there _ not from anything Lewinsky
has testified and not from anything Clinton friend Vernon Jordan
has testified. This may simply be well-covered tracks. But Lewinsky
is steadfast on that point.
</P>
<P>
   So there was no cover-up? Of course there was. Every affair is a
cover-up. It's like burger and bun. They come together. Right,
Congressman Hyde? Congresswoman Chenoweth? Congressman Burton?
</P>
<P>
   The issue of impeachment must come down to abuse of power _ to
the extent Clinton abused his office to conceal the truth. As one
who has generally supported Clinton's policies, I must say the
notion of trotting out staffers for months to say there was nothing
to the story is as troubling as anything aside from his insanely
reckless affair itself.
</P>
<P>
   Did someone say that trotting out staffers to tell untruths is,
well, the Washington way? Sen. Phil Gramm got extra-huffy about
this. Well he should, since we know that every word his staffers
say is stack-of-Bibles stuff. Ahem.
</P>
<P>
   Many among the great unwashed watch all of this and see
hypocrisy and overkill. To many, what's been done to expose
Clinton's affair is like fighter jets clearing the barn of field
mice.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal actions are indefensible. So how does he
survive in public opinion?
</P>
<P>
   One had to ask the same question in 1996. How did he survive
enemies' relentless 1,460-day personal barrage in his first term?
Is it possible that with Monday's release of the grand jury tape,
as bad as he looks, those people in their zeal once again have done
the impossible _ to make a known philanderer, liar and draft dodger
from Arkansas into a sympathetic figure? Could be.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald. He can
be reached by e-mail at jyoungmail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
