<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-WOODSON26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woodson over hill? Nope.
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI, Ohio _ The skeptics say he has lost it. That the
knee injury he suffered in 1995 made him damaged goods. That his
place among the NFL's elite cornerbacks is no more.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Ravens' Rod Woodson hears none of it. He listens
only to the voice within . . . you're the best.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year veteran, seven-time Pro Bowler and future Pro
Football Hall of Famer earned a berth on the NFL's 75th Anniversary
Team as a member of the Pittsburgh Steelers from 1987-96.
</P>
<P>
   And just in case you think he's over the hill after spending '97
in San Francisco, try this: A week ago, he blocked a Mike Hollis
field goal in Jacksonville. Two weeks ago against the New York
Jets, he pushed his career interception total to 43, picking off
Glenn Foley twice and racing 60 yards for his sixth career
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   For the Bengals to be successful at Baltimore on Sunday night,
they have to avoid Woodson's wrath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rod Woodson is great,'' said Bengals defensive coordinator
Dick LeBeau, who was Woodson's defensive coach in Pittsburgh from
1992-96. ``There were games he graded out with 12 tackles, two
sacks and an interception. He's a great playmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Ravens head coach Ted Marchibroda agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woodson is our big-play guy on defense,'' he said. ``He's been
the guy the others look up to. They can raise their game a little
bit more because they've seen how he has played the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has speed. He may have lost a little bit, but you
certainly can't see it when you watch him practice or play.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his speed, intensity and playmaking ability,
Woodson has the ingredient common in great cornerbacks _ amnesia.
</P>
<P>
   You get burned. You immediately erase it from your memory and
keep attacking.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be aggressive and very, very confident,'' Woodson
said. ``It borders on the edge of cockiness. You have to be that
way. You have to think that way. You have to believe you're better
than the guy in front of you; that there's no way in the world that
guy can catch the ball on you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to sometimes be a calculated gambler. Show me a guy
that's not a gambler, and I'll show you a corner that's not very
good. Show me a corner that's gambling, that's taking chances at
times, wise chances, playing with good fundamentals and
understanding of the game, and I'll show you a corner that has a
good opportunity to be a very good player in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodson will cover Carl Pickens, who leads the AFC with 20
receptions. Pickens needs seven catches to overtake Cris
Collinsworth (417) as the Bengals' career receptions leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fun to play against Carl again,'' Woodson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Is the feeling mutual?
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment,'' Pickens said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
