<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVREVIEW-BROTHERS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Filled with wit, charm this ``Brothers''' a keeper
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are three things you can count on in life. Death, taxes
and at least one odd couple TV show every year.
</P>
<P>
   This season there are quite a few, but the best of the bunch is
Brother's Keeper (ABC, 9:30 p.m. Friday). Two brothers, Porter
(Herman's Head's William Ragsdale), a stuffed-shirt history
professor and Bobby (Sean O'Bryan), a bad boy San Francisco 49ers
place-kicker live together. Oh, yeah, there's also Oscar (Liar
Liar's Justin Cooper), Porter's 8-year-old kid. Named after some
guy named Oscar Madison, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Porter and Oscar were doing just fine until Bobby showed
up. Seems as if the New York Jets traded their partying kicker to
the 49ers. Part of the $1 million-a-year deal is Bobby must live
with Porter and be babysat by his not-too-pleased sports agent
(Bess Meyer).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Porter's world is turned upside down. Now, instead of
preparing his son for tests by asking him questions like, ``What's
the speed of sound?'' or ``Who was the 19th president?'' Porter now
watches his son blow game pieces from his nose.
</P>
<P>
   As Porter, Ragsdale has the thankless role of playing straight
man to O'Bryan's high school hijinks. And it's O'Bryan who makes
Brother's Keeper fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he's nailing a net to a living room floor or blowing up
surgical gloves, the guy is hilarious. He has the same kind of
presence and manic energy as a young Robin Williams in Mork &AMP;
Mindy.
</P>
<P>
   Ragsdale's no slouch, either and knows he's not there to upstage
O'Bryan. And Cooper looks like a real kid, not one of those
assembly line sitcom tykes who sound smarter than their parents.
</P>
<P>
   The only smart thing, is this keeper comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
