r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVREVIEW-TWO26-COX     09-25 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVREVIEW-TWO26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Twins make 'Two' the kind of comedy family can enjoy
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's see . . . how can you double your pleasure on a ho-hum
Friday night?
</P>
<P>
   If you're 13 or under, watching the perpetually cute Olsen twins
should do the trick. The perky duo star in Two of a Kind (8 p.m.
Friday), a comedy tailor made for ABC's slate of family-friendly
kid-coms.
</P>
<P>
   It's basically Full House 2. But, instead of playing the same
person, the girls play two very distinct characters. They really
play themselves, which shouldn't be too hard, considering they've
had 12 years of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Mary-Kate is the tomboy who likes jeans, baseball and wearing
her hat backward. Ashley is the straight-A student who likes
makeup, dresses and boys.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle is Kevin (Christopher Sieber), the single science
professor dad. At least Kevin's not some thick-headed dope of a dad
who thinks the Spice Girls are something you'll find on the Playboy
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   But harried Kev still needs help. Enter Carrie (Sally Wheeler),
a free-spirit student in Kevin's class.
</P>
<P>
   What happens next is sitcom typical. The girls like Carrie.
Kevin doesn't. Kevin gives in and let's Carrie babysit. Carrie
messes up after teaching the kids poker and taking them to a Cubs
game. Kevin fires Carrie. Everyone kisses and makes up. Two of a
Kind lives.
</P>
<P>
   And it should. This is one of those comedies that is impossible
to hate. The Olsen twins, though older (and future head-turners),
are still appealing. They're cute without being make-me-want-to-gag
cute. Even Kevin and Carrie make you want to go, ``Awwwww.''
</P>
<P>
   And Two of a Kind should make you _ and your kids _ laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
