<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4131 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOM-KIPPUR26-COX     09-25 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOM-KIPPUR26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An annual second chance: Yom Kippur's solemn day of atonement
not child's play
 &HT;    By Scott Benarde
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the most memorable Yom Kippur holiday of my childhood, I was
playing with friends outside a synagogue in Edgeware, England, a
suburb of London. (It's tough for kids in any country to sit in the
sanctuary and pay attention during the longest, most solemn day of
prayer in Judaism.)
</P>
<P>
   It was my turn to use the slingshot one of the kids brought to
services. We had been trying to hit a telephone pole across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   I placed a pebble in the sling, pulled it back, took careful aim
at the pole, let fly _ and shattered the front windshield of a
shiny red van on the lot of an automobile dealership.
</P>
<P>
   On the Day of Atonement, on the final day of the 10 Days of Awe
when mortals seek forgiveness and are asked to be forgiving, when
God decides ``who shall live and who shall die,'' I scored a direct
hit on a clean, curved sheet of glass with a small,
harmless-looking stone.
</P>
<P>
   I ran back into the synagogue thinking my life was over at the
ripe age of 10. Not because God was going to strike me dead, but
because I'd be doing time in an English jail. I don't think I yet
understood the full meaning of the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Yom Kippur is not for kids. At least not like Hanukkah, with its
exciting candle-lighting ritual and gift giving; Purim with its
costume parties and games; Passover with its seder and hunt for the
Afikomen, the middle matzo, and the prize for finding it; Sukkot
with its sleeping under the stars.
</P>
<P>
   Even the beginning of the 10 Days of Awe, Rosh Hashana, the New
Year, can boast the first, dramatic blasts of the shofar, a ram's
horn. It's a joy for children to watch and hear. But it is a
stirring wake-up call for adults, the beginning of a 10-day period
of introspection and review, which ends on Yom Kippur.
</P>
<P>
   Atonement is not child's play.
</P>
<P>
   On Yom Kippur, you fast and pray. All day. The other major
holidays are festive and celebrated with friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   On Yom Kippur, while you pray and chant with a congregation,
you're really out there on your own. The cantor with his soulful
chanting, the rabbi with his Torah explanations and sermons, are
but guides setting mood and tone to help you on your way.
</P>
<P>
   Yom Kippur is just you and God.
</P>
<P>
   You take a good, honest look in the mirror. You reflect on the
year and pray you've been worthy enough to be inscribed in the Book
of Life for another year. (Sometimes I think it's akin to Ebeneezer
Scrooge being visited by the Ghost of Christmas Past, except Yom
Kippur forces the issue; Jews don't wait for such visits.)
</P>
<P>
   Yom Kippur is an annual second chance.
</P>
<P>
   We seek forgiveness for a multitude of sins great and small: We
have trespassed, dealt treacherously, robbed, spoken slander, acted
perversely, done wrong, done violence, practiced deceit, counseled
evil, spoken falsehood, scoffed, and more. We have gone astray and
led others astray. And that's just the short list.
</P>
<P>
   As a congregation, as a people across the globe, we're not just
asking forgiveness, but admitting _ repeatedly _ a litany of flaws
and wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The long list also includes sinning against God willingly and
unwillingly, by hardening our hearts, by disrespecting parents and
teachers, by foul speech and foolish talk, by bribery, idle gossip
and false pride. And more.
</P>
<P>
   We pray for compassion and forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   I also pray for self-improvement _ and fear regression and
hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the most important prayer is one my father sent me seven
years ago. It's not even a prayer, really. It's a ``supplemental
reading'' at the back of the Mahzor, the prayer book used on Rosh
Hashana and Yom Kippur. It's called We Wait Too Long.
</P>
<P>
   It's about the biggest sin of all: Squandering the time we have
on earth.
</P>
<P>
   It's also about finding the courage to do the right thing when
it needs to be done: being charitable, or loving or kind,
apologizing, setting aside hatreds, being thankful, offering
comfort to others, being parents to our children.
</P>
<P>
   It begins, ``We often wait too long to do what must be done
today, in a world that gives us only one day at a time, without any
assurance of tomorrow.'' It ends with, ``God, too, is waiting _
waiting for us to stop waiting, and to begin to do now, all the
things for which this day was made.''
</P>
<P>
   I carry this passage in my wallet, reading it from time to time.
I still have a lot of work to do. I still need an annual second
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Now more than ever.
</P>
<P>
   This year, our son is almost 15 months old, not the 3-month-old
lump he was last year at this time. He's curious. He expresses a
sense of awe and delight each Friday when we light the Shabbat
candles in our home. This is really year 1 in his Jewish life.
</P>
<P>
   This is the time I have to start thinking about keeping
slingshots out of his hands and putting a love of Judaism in them.
</P>
<P>
   A READING FROM THE NEW MAHZOR
</P>
<P>
   We often wait too long to do what must be done today, in a world
which gives us only one day at a time, without any assurance of
tomorrow. While lamenting that our days are few, we procrastinate
as though we had an endless supply of time.
</P>
<P>
   We wait too long to discipline ourselves and to take charge of
our lives. We feed ourselves the vain delusion that it will be
easier to uproot tomorrow the debasing habits which we permit to
tyrannize over us today, and which grow more deeply entrenched each
day they remain in power.
</P>
<P>
   We wait too long to work at the self-renewal of which these holy
days remind us. While we wait, our lives become progressively
depleted of spiritual content. The estrangement between us and our
heritage grows larger and more painful.
</P>
<P>
   We wait too long to become more deeply involved in Jewish life _
in Jewish observance and in Jewish study. While we wait, the time
for the harvest comes and we haven't even planted.
</P>
<P>
   We wait too long to show kindness. We wait too long to speak
words of forgiveness which should be spoken, to set aside hatreds
which should be banished; to express thanks, to give encouragement,
to offer comfort.
</P>
<P>
   We wait too long to be charitable. Too much of our giving is
delayed until much of the need has passed and the joy of giving has
been largely diminished.
</P>
<P>
   We wait too long to be parents to our children _ forgetting how
brief is the time during which they are children, how swiftly life
urges them on and away. We wait too long to express our concern for
parents, siblings, and dear ones.
</P>
<P>
   We wait too long to read the books, to listen to the music, and
to see the art which are waiting to enlarge our minds, to inspire
our spirits, and to ennoble our souls.
</P>
<P>
   We wait too long to utter the prayers which are waiting to cross
our lips, to perform the duties waiting to be discharged, to show
the love that may no longer be needed tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   God, too, is waiting _ waiting for us to stop waiting, and to
begin to do now, all the things for which this day was made.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
