   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Howard Kleinberg's regular Sunday column
moved Thursday for immediate release. The topic was Hurricane
Georges. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The next president of the United
States? My pick would be John K. McMillan, 41, the only person I
know of who might be able to stand up to the intense personal
scrutiny elected officials have to put up with today. (Kelso,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HATCHER-COLUMN _ Last week, while the nation was distracted by
slime, Congress performed a sleight-of-hand on juvenile justice.
The House took a simple bill that would have provided money to help
reunite families with their missing children, turned it into a $1.5
billion, tough-on-crime sound bite and called it a lesson in
accountability. (Hatcher, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ It couldn't be. Or could it? Could the nearly
mythical survival power of Bill Clinton be triggered at death's
door by what, possibly, is the lowest moment in any presidency
ever? Hard to imagine, but, here goes: The tapes backfired. (Young,
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ Just in case Bruce Springsteen needs any
character references to cinch his induction into the Rock and Roll
Hall of Fame, I'll go on record: He has never taken advantage of
the clause in my marriage contract stipulating my unrestricted
right to run off with His Scruffiness. (McCarty, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CERABINO-COLUMN _ This is my first cyber-hurricane. I wasn't
online in previous years, which means I didn't have access to a
vast array of knowledge and information on the screen of my home
computer. I didn't have the ability to engage in something called
``hurricane chat.'' Hurricane Georges may not be the end of the
world for us. But you could make the argument that ``hurricane
chat'' is. (Cerabino, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
