<SLUG> BC-NY-METHADONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI STEPS UP CRITICISM OF DRUG CZAR OVER METHADONE CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Several months ago, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani wrote
to Gen. Barry R. McCaffrey, the White House drug policy director,
in part to express pride that New York City's drug policy was
consistent with the national strategy. The mayor closed with, ``I
look forward to an opportunity to discuss these issues in person.''
</P>
<P>
   But the two men never had that discussion, and since then have
quarreled _ through the news media _ over the merits of methadone
treatment, a debate prompted two months ago by the mayor's
declaration that he wanted to curtail and eventually end the city's
role in providing methadone to heroin addicts.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the mayor personalized his criticism of the
general, calling him a ``disaster'' of a drug czar who prefers
providing subsidies to the methadone industry to weaning people
from dependence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if those doctors or General McCaffrey were dealing
with their own children or the people they loved, they wouldn't
have them on methadone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, McCaffrey said his staff was being told by city
officials that the administration was actually modifying its
position on methadone treatment, after several internal discussions
and a flurry of complaints that its stand defied medical research
on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Giuliani one of the most effective mayors in the
country, McCaffrey said: ``I can't imagine a responsible individual
would actually go through with it, now that he's got an
overwhelming pulse from an informed community that's said, `Don't
go this way.' This is a smart guy who will be held responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials deny that they have retreated or modified their
plan, which is intended to move the 2,100 addicts who come to city
hospitals for methadone toward abstinence as quickly as possible.
But many details of the approach have yet to be worked out. And
while the mayor has continued to talk tough on the subject, other
officials have emphasized that the program will be flexible enough
to meet the needs of individual addicts.
</P>
<P>
   The city has programs at Bellevue, Elmhurst, Harlem, Kings
County and Metropolitan Hospital Centers that offer methadone, a
synthetic drug that has been used for more than a generation to
curb the cravings of heroin addicts.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. Luis R. Marcos, president of the city's Health
and Hospitals Corp., it now considers only those applicants who
express a desire for abstinence, and has stopped admitting those
``who do not see the option of abstinence, because we believe that
it would be unfair to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcos also said that the patients have been evaluated for their
ability to be weaned off methadone voluntarily through a support
program being developed by the city. ``At least half of these
patients will be entering the program,'' he predicted, although he
said the process might take about three months for many and longer
for others.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neal L. Cohen, the city's health commissioner, emphasized
that the program's model, which is still being developed, will be
designed to address individual needs. ``There's no cookie cutter
here,'' he said. ``There's no one-size-fits-all.''
</P>
<P>
   But administration officials are vague in discussing what will
happen to patients who cannot or will not quit methadone. Marcos
said, ``We will not deny to anyone who needs the methadone or who
doesn't feel ready to enter an abstinence program.'' But other
officials suggested that patients would not be allowed to continue
in the program indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Parrino, the president of the American Methadone Treatment
Association, said that he and other drug-policy analysts had met
with the city's health officials last month, and were told that
``there was going to be some attempt to provide education to the
Mayor for a more informed policy decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But after the mayor's incendiary remarks yesterday, he said, ``I
don't have a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has been applauded at Republican fund-raisers
around the country for his scathing comments about McCaffrey and
methadone use, said that the federal official favored subsidizing
the replacement of one drug with another at the expense of Phoenix
House, Daytop Village and other abstinence-model programs.
</P>
<P>
   But McCaffrey said that his office had substantially helped
those programs, and that while he agreed ``that the best objective,
when it can be achieved, is abstinence,'' he thought that Giuliani
had adopted a ``ready-fire-aim policy analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Methadone, he said, is a scientifically proven approach to
stemming heroin addiction, transforming addicts who commit crimes
into people who work and otherwise benefit society. ``The mayor's
public stance on this issue is irrational and would create such
damage to life,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
