<SLUG> BC-NJ-SCHOOL-DRUG-TESTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING SUIT, SCHOOL ENDS DRUG TESTING OF ATHLETES 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ The school board in Ridgefield Park, N.J.,
has decided to end its policy of random drug testing of student
athletes rather than engage in a long and costly court fight over
whether the policy is legal under the New Jersey Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a settlement with the parents of a high school
football player who contended the policy violated the State
Constitution's protections against illegal searches and seizures,
Ridgefield Park will adopt voluntary drug testing for all students
in grades 7 through 12 and retain the right to test any student if
school officials have a ``reasonable suspicion'' the student has
used drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The school superintendent, David Rightmyer, said today that the
decision, made on Wednesday night, would allow the board to spend
hundreds of thousands of dollars it would have spent on legal fees
for the educational needs of the district's 1,744 students. ``If
it's going to take years for us to get there,'' Dr. Rightmyer said
of a lengthy court fight, ``why not let the battle be fought with
someone else's funds?''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Sybil R. Moses of New Jersey Superior Court approved the
settlement here Thursday and dismissed a lawsuit filed in August
1997 by the American Civil Liberties Union on behalf of Bryan
Wilson, a senior who plays offensive end on Ridgefield Park's
football team, and his parents, Robert and KamaRae Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us, it seemed like Big Brother was telling us how to raise
our children,'' Wilson said of the district's mandatory urinalysis
policy. He said that if student athletes could be required to
undergo drug testing, the board might then begin testing students
in particular religious or ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   He said he endorsed the voluntary testing program the settlement
allows. ``There has to be something to stop a kid who's doing
drugs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Rocah, a lawyer with the ACLU, said the settlement would
have no bearing on other New Jersey districts with similar testing
policies because the challenge dealt only with the policy at
Ridgefield Park.
</P>
<P>
   At least eight other districts in the state require the tests,
including Clearview Regional, Washington Township and West Deptford
in Gloucester County; North Bergen in Hudson County; Clifton in
Passaic County; Pennsauken in Camden County, Hunterdon Central in
Hunterdon County and Brick Township in Ocean County, according to
the New Jersey School Boards Association.
</P>
<P>
   Rightmyer said the settlement did not disturb other elements of
an aggressive antidrug policy instituted at Ridgefield Park High
four years ago when, he said, the use and sale of drugs was
widespread at the school.
</P>
<P>
   The policy includes using drug-sniffing dogs to search students'
lockers, stationing undercover police officers in classes and on
school grounds and lengthy suspensions of any students caught using
or selling drugs. Six were suspended in the first two years of the
crackdown, Rightmyer said. No students have been caught in the last
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Moses had ordered the random testing program suspended
shortly after the challenge was filed.
</P>
</TEXT>
