<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Sept. 25, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MURDER-WITNESS (Berkeley, Calif.) _ A sophomore at the
University of California at Berkeley says in a television interview
that he failed to tell police that his best friend abducted and
killed a 7-year-old girl because ``I didn't want to be the one who
turned him in.'' By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   GE-CLEANUP (Albany, N.Y.) _ The General Electric Co. agreed to
pay at least $150 million to clean up PCBs in the Housatonic River
and the city of Pittsfield, Mass., avoiding a potential legal
battle with the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency over who
should pay for a cleanup. By PAUL ZIELBAUER.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-GOV (San Francisco) _ Police unions say Republican
gubernatorial candidate Dan Lungren owes them an apology for
comparing their demand for binding arbitration to the case of
Latrell Sprewell, the Golden State Warrior who was fired after
choking his coach and then had his league suspension reduced and
contract restored by an arbitrator. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-SEX (San Francisco) _ Politics as sex scandal has been
with us from the very beginning, says Erna Smith, chairman of the
Journalism Department at San Francisco State University. ``The
desire for this kind of titillation is part of human nature. The
country is fascinated and repelled at the same time,'' says Smith.
By DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ A review of the latest and greatest
computer chips and what to consider and what to avoid. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader wants to know about using
the ``Close Program'' in Windows 95 and the repercussions of
eliminating the Network Neighborhood icon from the desktop. A Q&AMP;A.
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEBARTOLO (San Francisco) _ Aiming to avoid a possible prison
sentence and regain control of his beloved San Francisco 49ers,
Edward J. DeBartolo Jr. has testified before a Louisiana grand jury
after apparently agreeing to become a government witness for his
role in a casino licensing scandal. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE (San Francisco) _ Diagnosed 10 months ago
with non-Hodgkins lymphoma, Terry Reinhard had already undergone 12
weeks of chemotherapy and another month of radiation when he
learned in July that his single tumor had turned into three.
Reinhard, 56, of San Francisco, hasn't given up on conventional
treatment but he is also planning to explore alternative medicine.
By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   HUDSON-MANSIONS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Many mansions built between the
late 1700s to the early 1900s dot the landscape along the Hudson
River from Albany to as far south as Yonkers. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
(For release Sunday, Sept. 27.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Government boundaries in New York
and throughout most of the Northeast are 350 years old. Everything
important is set up on town and county levels, as though we were
still living in 1650. In the case of getting emergency help, this
outdated system puts lives at risk. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   ENDANGERED-FORESTS (San Francisco) _ With some of California's
last remaining stands of redwoods targeted for cutting, lawmakers
had no choice but to pay an exorbitant price to protect these
irreplaceable treasures. Some critics labeled the recent $480
million deal for Headwaters forest area ``extortion.'' Regardless
of what you call it, we could be confronted with the same no-option
scenario with regard to forests worldwide unless we take action
soon. By PETER SELIGMANN.
</P>
<P>
   BEANIE-BABIES (San Francisco) _ Suddenly, the beanie baby market
is collapsing. Toy stores, stationery stores and drugstores are all
beaned up. Where before children would descend on a sales clerk,
pleading for beanies _ any beanies _ now stores have them _ and
it's just not the same. By RUTH SHERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   HIV-REPORTING (San Francisco) _ Because new HIV therapies have
lengthened the time between initial HIV infection and an AIDS
diagnosis for many individuals, thousands of Californians who are
HIV-positive, but not diagnosed with AIDS, are missed by our
current reporting system since it does not track HIV. That will
change as a result of a new law. By MITCH KATZ.
</P>
</TEXT>
