<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: To mark Breast Cancer Awareness Month in October, The New
York Times Syndicate offers a personal essay by a woman undergoing
her first mammogram.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY FIRST MAMMOGRAM: THE BONDING OF STRANGERS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (800 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JACKIE RUBENSTEIN
</P>
<P>
   Breast irregularities send the author, not yet 40, for her first
mammogram. In the waiting room she finds the peculiar intimacy and
comraderie of women facing the same fears. ``In a week, or a month,
we won't recognize each other on the street. But today, in this
place, there is a truth we both know: We are all in this
together,'' Rubenstein writes. (slugged:
BC-FIRST-MAMMOGRAM-(BREAST-CANCER-AWARENESS-MONTH)-NYTSF, priority
code r, category code l)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase one or more of these articles, contact your New
York Times Syndicate sales representatives:
</P>
