<HEADLINE>
MY LIFE AS A BLONDE: PART 2 
</HEADLINE>
  North American rights. 
 &HT;    (To publish this ``separate buy'' article it must be purchased
-- the rate is not prohibitive -- from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax, 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
 &HT;    (--Mexico, Central America, South America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los
Angeles, 310-996-0075; fax, 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    (----- Please call or fax for a price quote.)
 By CRISTINA SARALEGUI  
 From ``My Life as a Blonde'' 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    One day a representative of CBS Records called to ask me a favor
with these fateful words:
 &HT;    ``We just signed a local group called Miami Sound Machine. We're
going to book them into Regine's in New York and launch them as the
company's new artists and we need you to back us up in print.''
 &HT;    At the same time _ life's little coincidences _ another friend,
a newspaperman in Puerto Rico, had called to say that he was
organizing a festival of Caribbean music in Cancun, Mexico, and he
wanted me to recommend the hottest U.S. group playing Latin music.
 &HT;    I recommended Miami Sound Machine.
 &HT;    On the plane carrying us to the festival in Cancun I met Emilio
and Gloria Estefan and (by chance!) Marcos Avila, the band's bass
player.
 &HT;    Emilio and Gloria were very pleasant companions during that
trip, and we quickly became friends, so spontaneously and sincerely
that soon Tony and I began hanging out with them. Since we lived
only five minutes away, we went everywhere together.
 &HT;    Seeing them, watching how happily they were married, I realized
how unhappy I was. I began to realize that following their example
of working together and getting ahead together, I had to change the
circumstances I found myself in.
 &HT;    One day Emilio said, ``I'm going to Peru with Gloria and the
band. You've filed for divorce. Your problems are out of your
hands. Why don't you let me invite you to come with us?''
 &HT;    It was my destiny to meet my destiny.
 &HT;    Emilio who's always joking, began selling me on Marcos, I don't
know why. He said over and over, ``Marcos Avila is my right hand
and a very serious fellow. Why don't you two get together?''
 &HT;    Now I believe that maybe Emilio sensed the chemistry between
Marcos and me before the things happened I'm going to tell you
about.
 &HT;    But I listened and thought, ``Marcos is short, fat,
short-tempered and close-mouthed. And he's married! I like tall,
handsome, elegant men. And I'm short-tempered too. We'd make a
terrible couple!''
 &HT;    One night we all went to a discotheque. I was at Gloria and
Emilio's table but had gone to the ladies' room. There I saw a
black girl and a white girl get in a fight _ with razor blade _
over a musician.
 &HT;    The musician was Marcos! I froze. I did what you do on automatic
pilot and, eyes straight ahead, walked out the door.
 &HT;    As I stepped outside, Marcos came up and said, ``Want to
dance?''
 &HT;    ``Not on your life!'' I answered, and went back to the table to
see how everything turned out.
 &HT;    That night Marcos explained that he was going through the stage
of total upheaval that precedes a divorce. Sometimes he left home
and took refuge in his grandmother's house, where he hid out before
going back to his own house to see his baby girl.
 &HT;    As for me, my husband and I were legally separated.
 &HT;    We were two miserable souls that met like homeless people under
a bridge. Marcos says today that by then he had determined to
captivate me. It's true, we began to see each other differently.
 &HT;    One night after a concert, we all got together in a suite and
had a tremendous party. Afterward Marcos offered to walk me back to
my room. He came in with me, sat on my bed, began to massage my
back, and said, ``If you and I make love ... ''
 &HT;    He corrected himself. ``No. When you and I make love, you're
going to see what a real man is like.''
 &HT;    I pretended I hadn't heard him. I quickly told him good night,
gave him a stupid kiss on the cheek, and he left. But I was left
with that promise in my heart. The next day I got up at 6 a.m. and
carefully painted my toenails red.
 &HT;    That night he came back, and he was better than his promise. It
was like making love with someone for whom you had been created
with that one purpose in mind. The earth moved, bells rang and I
was left stupefied because that had never happened to me and I was
35 years old!
 &HT;    It was well worth painting my toenails.
 &HT;    From that moment Marcos began his campaign to move into my house
so I wouldn't go out with anyone else. He intended that after eight
years of marriage to one man I should pass directly to him, with no
romantic interlude in between.
 &HT;    Marcos is 11 years younger than I am. At that time he had a
ponytail halfway down his back, but a buzz cut in front. And he had
an earring. After all, he was a musician.
 &HT;    My parents were totally opposed to our relationship. My first
marriage had been plagued by economic problems. At one point my
father asked if I was proposing to support men all my life.
 &HT;    To add to the complications, Titi, my daughter, was a holy
terror! I remember the first day Marcos came to the house. Titi had
some plastic handcuffs, and under the pretense of playing cops and
robbers, she cuffed him to the metal stairway and threw away the
key--so he couldn't be with me. We had to break the handcuffs to
get them off.
 &HT;    Faced with that situation, I told Marcos, ``You'll have to win
Titi over, because I'm not going to marry you if she doesn't want
me to.''
 &HT;    By the end of our first year together, Titi was so fond of
Marcos that she told me one day, ``Mami, he loves us. He's nice.
Why don't we marry him?''
 &HT;    All I could do was laugh!
 &HT;    For the wedding I wore a white cotton dress I'd bought in
Mexico, and Titi wore one just like it. I bought white flowers for
my hair and white flowers for hers. She stood by my side in her
identical white dress, and the two of us wed Marcos Avila.
 &HT;    Later, despite his success and the money he was earning, and
after 12 unbroken years with Miami Sound Machine, he decided to
leave the group. ``I've had the fans, the limousines, the Johnny
Carson show,'' he said. ``Now I want a family.''
 &HT;    Marcos opened a public relations agency to offer to
Spanish-language performers the things he had learned while
traveling with Miami Sound Machine.
 &HT;    Once Marcos felt he was on solid ground, he began brainwashing
me to leave Cosmopolitan. My reaction was: Are you crazy?
 &HT;    Marcos, though, convinced me that what I was doing in that
corporation was selling my time instead of my talent.
 &HT;    Take note, all you reading this book, of that important
difference, whatever your situation at the moment.
 &HT;     c.1998 Cristina Saralegui Enterprises  
