<HEADER>
A4306 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTLAND-SECEDE-$ADV2     09-25 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTLAND-SECEDE-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A DIS-UNITED KINGDOM? SCOTLAND LEADING MOVEMENT TOWARD REGIONAL
INDEPENDENCE
 &HT;    With SCOTLAND-PRIMER-$ADV26.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Sept. 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Forged 70 years before American independence, the
United Kingdom is showing distinct signs of disunity.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, three of the kingdom's four principal regions --
Scotland, Northern Ireland and Wales -- will elect legislatures
with varying degrees of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   Each region has a legitimate political movement pushing for at
least some measure of freedom from England, ranging from a sort of
American-style statehood to full-fledged independence.
</P>
<P>
   So much has changed that even Wales, which was conquered by
England a century before Chaucer wrote ``The Canterbury Tales,''
voted a year ago to form its own assembly only two decades after
rejecting the idea by a 4-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   As the 20th Century comes to an end, there is real possibility
that Great Britain, the world's most vast and powerful political
force at the turn of the last century, soon may be whittled down to
little more than England and a few possessions.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in popular support for regional autonomy -- called
``devolution'' here -- was capitalized upon by the savvy British
Prime Minister Tony Blair, who swept to power 16 months ago on a
landslide. For Blair, it was a calculated political venture
intended in part to build support by addressing complaints that the
government in London was inattentive to local matters.
</P>
<P>
   While providing an avenue for people in the other regions to
gain more local control, some leaders fear -- or hope -- that Blair
may have unwittingly unleashed a new and potentially fatal burst of
nationalistic ambition.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Sked, a senior lecturer in international history at the
London School of Economics, worries that devolution is dismantling
the framework of British government without a well-defined
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're getting is strange ad hoc bodies rather than a part
of a general constitution,'' Sked said. ``You're going to end up
with a constitutional stew that could bubble over and burn
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there seems to be no turning back. The momentum seems
particularly potent in Scotland. Earlier this week, Alex
Salmond(CQ), the head of the Scottish National Party (SNP), told
spirited delegates attending a party convention that they -- not
the English -- control the country's future. ``Scotland's party,''
Salmond said to thunderous cheers, ``is ready to be Scotland's
government.''
</P>
<P>
   If Salmond's party captures a majority in the Scottish
Parliament in May elections, then his party says it intends to open
negotiations with the British Parliament on the terms of
separation. Recent polling suggests his surging party may fall
short of a majority, which still is expected to be held by Blair's
Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the issue of independence will persist because of popular
support. A new poll for The Scotsman newspaper shows that 51
percent of Scots would vote for independence if given the chance in
a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   John MacInnes, a researcher for the SNP, said the rise of the
independence movement has paralleled a 50-year rise in the Scottish
national identity. It also parallels the decline of the British
Empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scots used to be able to move out into the empire to Canada
and Australia and make successes of themselves, and that's been
closed off to them,'' he said. ``At the same time, there has been
the rise of Europe in economic terms.''
</P>
<P>
   The SNP intends to make Scotland an independent nation within
the European Union and look after its national interests without
the influence or interference of the government in London, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Sked, also a Scot, questions whether Scotland would really
be better off on its own. He believes the EU if anything would be
less responsive to Scottish interests than the London parliament.
</P>
<P>
   And he worries about the talent base of a fledgling legislature.
``The likely prospect is one of second-rate Scottish politicians
finding themselves with a lot of problems which they used to talk
about but which they cannot solve; and bringing in constitutional
and economic measures which will only exacerbate them,'' Sked said.
</P>
<P>
   Scots may cool to independence when they take a harder look at
it, he added, saying, ``If it ends up leading to higher taxes, and
the Scottish financial services industry leaving the country, the
consequences could be dire.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ireland, the push for independence from Britain fueled a
30-year guerrilla war that claimed more than 3,000 lives. The New
Northern Ireland Assembly, which convened for the first time
earlier this month, has been charged with plotting a course that is
consistent with the what the majority wants.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the population of Northern Ireland is divided over
remaining part of Britain, with a majority still indicating support
for the union, polls show. However, most political observers doubt
the separatists such as Sinn Fein, the political party affiliated
with the Irish Republican Army, would participate in the assembly
without for hope of eventually obtaining independence and,
ultimately, union with the Republic of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Much depends on economics, said Barry Jones, a professor of the
University of Wales in Cardiff who studies devolution. ``If there
is a sudden severe downturn in the global market or if the British
economy weakens significantly, then it could be destabilizing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A weakened British economy could make breaking away and seeking
an independent affiliation with the EU appear attractive to
supporters of independence, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Wales, there seems to be much ambivalence about devolution.
``The paradox is that we've been united with the English longer
than either the Scots or the Irish, yet we've preserved our
language and culture better than either,'' he said. ``But that
hasn't translated into a political movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Welsh are interested in controlling their own affairs but
not becoming an independent state, said Jones, who believes the
Welsh model could represent a shift to a kind of federal republic
on the order of the U.S. system.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the United Kingdom is entering unchartered water. One
potentially troubling and divisive issue could come if the English
begin to feel they are the political losers in the new order.
Ironically, the English will be the only people without a directly
elected assembly to represent their interests. Members of
Parliament from Scotland, Northern Ireland and Wales will be poised
to set policy in England, while the English will have no voice in
affairs in these regions.
</P>
<P>
   This could lead to a call for an English assembly, said Bill
Shaw, an official with the Edinburgh office of the Conservative
Party. ``There are signs of an English backlash already,'' Shaw
said. ``People will wonder why some Scottish (member of parliament)
can vote on an issue important to Surrey while their (member of
parliament) has no say over how their money is spent in Scotland.
And once your average person starts realizing the consequences of
this, they'll take great offense at it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is even some concern about how well the fabric of British
nationhood is holding together. The sense of feeling British is
stronger in older generations who experienced or at least remember
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were the 15 days when Britain stood alone against
Hitler,'' Jones said. ``That's not so important for younger people
but it is for people over 40.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones believes that British nationalism remains a powerful
binding force. ``Look at something as recent as the Falklands
war,'' he said. ``That produced a tremendous flood of British
nationalism that surprised even the British.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is some concern the ship may founder before anyone
takes full account of the rocks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to dawn on the English in the next year or so that
there are going to be some changes,'' Sked said. ``By then, it may
be too late to do anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
