<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4310 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-BARTER-$ADV26-     09-25 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BARTER-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRADING ON THIN ICE: RUSSIA BARTERS AMID THE ECONOMIC BREAKDOWN
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-REGIONS-$ADV27.
 &HT;    EDs: Engels is on the Volga River about 450 miles south of
Moscow.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Sept. 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENGELS, Russia _ The good news for Trolza, a mammoth assembly
plant and major employer in this depressed town on the Volga River,
was a recent deal worth $25 million to produce buses for several
Russian cities.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: No cash will be exchanged and no profits will
result.
</P>
<P>
   Barter made the deal possible. In a country with a sick economy,
a flimsy currency and a sea of debt, barter accounts for more than
two-thirds of all transactions in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The electric trolley buses will be built on an intricate web of
trades and swaps involving Trolza, dozens of companies who provide
component parts for the buses and the cities who need the vehicles
for their public transit systems.
</P>
<P>
   The factory, deep in the red since the Soviet Union collapsed in
1991 and with barely a ruble to its name, conducts an astounding 92
percent of its business in barter.
</P>
<P>
   It swaps buses to the city of Engels in lieu of paying its local
taxes. Farms give food in exchange for stocks of sheet metal, paint
and other items from Trolza's warehouses. Since Trolza cannot fully
afford to pay its employees, they get their salaries in onions,
cucumbers and macaroni.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't like barter. The best option is the classic one:
money for goods and services. But we don't have a choice. We've
returned to ancient times: a piece of meat for a piece of fur,''
said Arthur Mikhel, Trolza's chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, ``cashless society'' conjures 21st century images
of ``smart'' credit cards and high-tech cash registers and instant
electronic debits from a bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's cashless society is from a century in the other
direction. It emerged from a Soviet-era economy that never quite
made the transition to capitalism. The Russian marketplace is
hamstrung by failing banks, the falling ruble, government
corruption and an oppressive tax system.
</P>
<P>
   The result is survival-by-barter from the corner fruit stand to
the highest levels of industry.
</P>
<P>
   Every Russian province, even in the relatively prosperous
capital, Moscow, has examples of barter. Workers get paid in toilet
paper and t-shirts. Companies stay in business by wrangling
supplies and swapping their products to pay their utility bills and
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   About 8,000 teachers in the impoverished Altai district of
Siberia have not been paid since February, owed $3.5 million in
wage arrears. They agreed this week to accept their pay in 15
bottles of vodka per teacher per month, which then can be re-sold
on the streets and to local markets.
</P>
<P>
   Barter now accounts for about 70 percent of trade in Russia and
the figure is growing amid the current economic crisis, according
to Yaroslav Lisavolik, a Moscow economist who has studied the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, barter reflects the fortitude of Russians who
are determined to survive in tough times, keeping the factories
running and commerce humming.
</P>
<P>
   But economists warn that more barter will only produce more
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Barter perpetuates trading between companies and individuals,
but perverts the system by making it impossible for the economy to
grow and for government to collect badly needed taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a law in economics that says bad money drives out
good money and this is exactly what has been going on. Barter,
which is bad money in a way, has been replacing cash,'' said
Lisavolik.
</P>
<P>
   Since the demise of the Soviet Union, about 70 percent of
Russia's economy is now in private ownership. Barter transactions
make it possible for businesses to remain in business. Bankruptcies
are rare.
</P>
<P>
   But barter leaves businesses with little capital for their
payroll and no clear picture of their prices and earnings. It chews
up time and productivity among the financial officers and corporate
planners who must arrange the often elaborate deals.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of cash also prevents Russian businesses from doing
things that fundamentally would improve the Russian economy, such
as modernizing aging Soviet-era plants and retraining the work
force.
</P>
<P>
   Without barter, debt-ridden companies would be forced to compete
in the hard world of a genuine market economy. Many factories would
fail and unemployment would rise.
</P>
<P>
   One of the world's largest enterprises, Russia's natural gas
monopoly, Gazprom, conducts 80 percent of its business in barter,
according to the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no cash and the chain begins from there. Everybody
uses electricity and everybody uses gas ... Enterprises couldn't
make their payments, so they started bargaining,'' said Andrei
Laptev, financial director for Sapkon/Neftemash, a company in the
southern city of Saratov which manufactures equipment for the oil
and gas industry.
</P>
<P>
   Since Russia's troubled economy means its customers cannot pay,
Sapkon/Neftemash has been forced to do about 60 percent of its
business this year in barter, up from 40 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the dilapidated river town of Engels (named for the 19th
century philosopher Friedrich Engels who helped found the Communist
movement) the trolley bus factory struggles simply to exist. Dreams
of profit are sheer fantasy at Trolza, founded 130 years ago and
operating from a plant built just after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The electric buses, which are tethered to overhead wires running
along city streets, are a common form of mass transit in Moscow and
dozens of other Russian cities. The company with 2,200 employees
had during its Soviet heyday the ability to produce 2,500 buses a
year. In 1996 and 1997, it manufactured only 120 each year.
</P>
<P>
   Trolza currently owes about $4.2 million in back taxes and
penalties -- a sum it cannot pay. Barter complicates the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Under Russia's tax laws, the company must record the sale of its
buses even if no cash changes hands. Thus, Trolza will owe taxes on
$25 million in sales after the recent barter deal is completed. And
without cash, it cannot pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You work and work and there is no result,'' complained Nikolai
Polulyakh, the company's general director and a member of the
regional parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two real questions in Russia, 'What is to be done?'
and 'Who is to blame?' I think we are all to blame to take part in
such a system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
