<HEADER>
A4311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOTLAND-PRIMER-$ADV2     09-25 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTLAND-PRIMER-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE DIS-UNITED KINGDOM
 &HT;    With SCOTLAND-SECEDE-$ADV26.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Sept. 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The countries that comprise the United Kingdom of Great Britain
and Northern Ireland are on a course that could further fragment
what's left of the once great empire.
</P>
<P>
   ENGLAND
</P>
<P>
   Population: 48.9 million
</P>
<P>
   Area: 50,362 square miles
</P>
<P>
   Capital: London
</P>
<P>
   Government: Unlike Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland, England
has no government minister or department exclusively responsible
for its central administration.
</P>
<P>
   Prospect: As Scotland, Northern Ireland and Wales move toward
more autonomy, politicians in England may well begin pushing for a
government more focused on England alone.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND
</P>
<P>
   Population: 5.2 million
</P>
<P>
   Area: 30,418 square miles
</P>
<P>
   Capital: Edinburgh
</P>
<P>
   Government: Formed the United Kingdom with England in 1707.
Elections for the newly instated Scottish Parliament will be held
in May with the body convening in June. The parliament will have
authority over spending in Scotland and will have the power to levy
a local tax -- called the Tartan tax -- and will assume
responsibility for many areas of governance, including health,
education, transportation and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects: Scottish nationalists, who want Scotland to dissolve
the United Kingdom and join the European Union, have shown
themselves to have far greater political strength than anyone
expected and have a fair shot at gaining a majority in the new
parliament. Polls show considerable public support for independence
and dissatisfaction with being governed from London. Unionists fear
that Scotland is unprepared to go its own way, but for now are
losing their following.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND
</P>
<P>
   Population: 1.7 million
</P>
<P>
   Area: 5,452 square miles
</P>
<P>
   Capital: Belfast
</P>
<P>
   Government: Came under British rule in 1690. A new assembly
convened earlier this month with measured authority over the nine
counties known as Ulster. As part of the Good Friday peace accord,
the assembly is to determine the political future of Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects: The assembly includes representatives of the Unionist
and Republican movements. Unionists seek to remain a part of the
United Kingdom, while Republicans want Ulster to become part of the
Republic of Ireland, which encompasses the rest of the island. At
the very least it seems that the assembly -- if it holds together
-- is a major step toward some form of autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   WALES
</P>
<P>
   Population: 2.9 million
</P>
<P>
   Area: 8,019 square miles
</P>
<P>
   Capital: Cardiff
</P>
<P>
   Government: Brought under English rule in 1282. A year ago, a
razor-thin margin of voters endorsed a plan to create an elected
assembly to assume control of many governmental functions.
Elections are set for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects: The nationalistic ardor is much cooler than in
Scotland or Northern Ireland, even though there is growing interest
in the distinct Welsh culture; the existence of which is
underscored by the fact that 20 percent of the inhabitants speak
Welsh as well as English and there are pockets of populations that
speak Welsh only. But the political support for full independence
seems thin.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
