<HEADER>
A4313 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-25 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHEAST'S POCKETS OF POWER PUT LIVES AT RISK 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Here's another example of how and why nothing
really seems to work any more:
</P>
<P>
   Paula Taggart is a nurse practitioner. She works for a
gynecologist. Not long ago, she was at an area shopping mall when
her beeper went off. The caller was a menopausal patient in the
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called her right back,'' Paula Taggart told me. ``She's
going on and on, telling me about her whole week. And I finally say
to her, `Are you suicidal?' And she says, `Yes, I'm suicidal.' So,
I said, `OK, I'm going to get you some help.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the key thing when you're going through this is that you
have to keep them on the phone ... So thank God I had another pay
phone next to me ... I picked it up and dialed 911 ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them what my emergency was. I said, `I need some help.
I need you to get someone to her house.' They said, `What's the
address?' ... I tell the address, and the dispatcher says, `Well,
that's not our jurisdiction. We can't help you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `You've got to be kidding me ... They said, `We'll
give you a phone number, and we can't do anything more than that.'
I said, `But this patient is suicidal ... I'm telling you, I'm a
medical professional, and I need your help.' They wouldn't help me
...
</P>
<P>
   ``I dialed the next phone number and got somebody in Saratoga
County. They told me, `I'm sorry, you've called the wrong number.
Let me give you the right number.' I mean, like, this is a
nightmare, and my key goal all through this is to keep her on the
other phone ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally got somebody at the third number, and they sent
help. But it was, like, a 25-minute ordeal. The whole thing is that
nobody knows that if you dial 911, you're not going to get help if
it's out of their jurisdiction ... Everybody I've told this story
to, including my boss, has asked, `Why couldn't they just patch you
through?' And I have to say, `I don't know.'''
</P>
<P>
   I do. I've harped on this before. Sure, the Albany metro area is
a contiguous region of nearly a million people. But government
boundaries in upstate New York _ and throughout most of the
Northeast, for that matter _ are 350 years old. Everything
important is set up on town and county levels, as though upstate
New Yorkers were still living in 1650.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The politicians like it that way, even though it gives New
Yorkers in particular and residents of the Northeast in general the
highest local taxes in America. It means more political jobs _ more
little, local dukes and earls suckling greedily at the public teat.
</P>
<P>
   That's why New York has roughly 850 school districts while
Florida, for example, administers education more efficiently at the
county level. That's why many communities in New York don't even
have 911 service available. They have to finance it locally, and
those communities are too small to afford it. The whole system is
loony, and every time anybody talks about regionalization, the
local pols start howling about the evils of big government.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Steve Heider of the Colonie Police Department knows quite a
bit about the 911 system. It's partially administered by his
department. He told me that each county 911 system in the Albany
metro area does have a limited capacity to communicate with the
systems of neighboring counties. But that happens only if the
person receiving the call figures that the emergency is severe
enough to get up, leave his or her station and go to another
station to push the patch-through button.
</P>
<P>
   I know from spending a night in a 911 operation just how hassled
these people are. Step away from your station, and you can miss
emergency calls.
</P>
<P>
   Heider said, ``If the person who took her call on the 911 level
evaluated her situation and didn't feel it was an emergency at that
very moment, that's why she was probably given a regular number to
call at the Saratoga County Sheriff's Department.''
</P>
<P>
   What it boils down to is that the Albany metro area has roughly
750 taxing units serving a population less than half of Manhattan's
_ where 911 works pretty well, by the way _ and that local
politicians cling desperately to all these ancient, outmoded and
utterly useless local governments.
</P>
<P>
   And if somebody dies needlessly?
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's a small price to pay to stave off big government.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
