r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLU     09-25 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE LINE DOESN'T CUT IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I have a 56K modem, but I can only get it to
sign on at 28.8 or less. I confirmed that my modem and Windows 95
settings are correct. U.S. Robotics support determined there is
noise on my telephone line preventing a 56K connection. The phone
company will only guarantee a 14.4 connection. They sent out a
technician who determined my phone line met their specifications
for noise. Is there anything else to check? If there isn't, why
aren't consumers warned about this ``conflict'' with telephone
companies? I can't believe I'm the only one.
</P>
<P>
   _ Baudly Frustrated
</P>
<P>
   DEAR FRUS: Yes, you ARE the only one. The phone company has
singled out you _ and you alone _ for harassment. The rest of us
aren't having any problems.
</P>
<P>
   Your alternatives aren't very attractive: You could move closer
to the phone company's switching station. You could switch phone
companies. You could rewire your house with better telephone cable.
All that still may not fix the problem. I'm sure that the phone
company would be happy to let you pay more for a data-grade or ISDN
line, though. Why else would it be acting like the south end of a
northbound horse?
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I just finished reading the letter from the
person who heard creepy sounds while on the Internet. I, too, have
heard creepy sounds. Mine is a door slamming, and/or a squeaky
door. It doesn't happen regularly, just often enough to keep me
wondering when it will happen again.
</P>
<P>
   _ Haunted II
</P>
<P>
   DEAR II: Not to worry. That's just the escaped mental patient
who's been living in your crawl space waiting for just the right
moment to murder you in your sleep. Your computer is perfectly OK.
You must be really relieved!
</P>
<P>
   C'mon, you guys have all seen one too many ``X-Files.'' Look for
some rational explanation, like the couple next door having a
Hillary-size door-slammer of a fight. Or sound clips that are
programmed to play at certain points. As my computer tells me all
the time, you carbon-based units are way too suggestible.
</P>
<P>
   STUPID SOFTWARE TRICK: Seems like the only way Microsoft
engineers and developers get credit for something is when they
sneak their names into the product in places only they would know
to look. A reader who prefers to be known only as Cigar Boy _ for
legal reasons, he says _ earns a tip o' the homburg for this
Internet Explorer 4.0 trifle:
</P>
<P>
   Open the Help menu and click on About. Hold down Control and use
the mouse to drag the Explorer ``E'' over the picture of the globe,
then ram it against the ``Microsoft Internet Explorer 4.0'' text,
which should retreat from the screen, exposing an Unlock button.
Click the button, which starts the globe shaking.
</P>
<P>
   Drag the ``E'' on top of the globe, which should start expanding
to fill the window. Close that window and another opens with a
scrolling list of hundreds of Microserfs, many of whom are still
chained to their cubicles. To break up the monotony, the
programmers also slipped in a couple of jokes. At least I think
they're jokes. It's so hard to tell when a geek is trying to be
intentionally funny.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4363 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEANIE-BABIES-HNS &LR;      09-25 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEANIE-BABIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH, BABY, THE BEANIE REVOLUTION IS OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH SHERMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While the rest of the world has been occupied
with matters of great moment, the little people, aka children, have
been experiencing what could only be called Beanie Baby Meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   In case there are no children in your house (and you've been
sojourning on Mars for the last several years), Beanie Babies are
cuddly little beanbag animals, complete with birth date tags, that
have quietly taken over lives and established empires.
</P>
<P>
   Originally designed as playthings, these toys, through clever
marketing techniques, have morphed into something else; they now
belong in the rarified atmosphere of ``collectibles.'' Translated,
that means: Adults have gotten into the action, driving up prices
and unleashing Beanie Mania on an unsuspecting populace.
</P>
<P>
   Through a process known as early retirement from the line,
seemingly innocent stuffed piggies, puppies and platypi have soared
in price from a modest $4.99 to stratospheric levels _ at one
point, hundreds of dollars for a bear dedicated to Princess Di, and
thousands for Peanut, the Royal Blue Elephant (not to be confused
with the more pedestrian Peanut, the Light Blue Elephant, worth
about $15 and distributed en masse at an Oakland A's game in
August). Of course, as some learned to their sorrow, the
collector's prices could only be realized if the specialized tags
stayed firmly and perfectly attached.
</P>
<P>
   It became routine to enter a store to find hordes of anxious
grown-ups waiting in uneasy clumps for the next delivery of
beanies. No one was ever sure when or what would be available.
</P>
<P>
   People waiting in line developed a hunched posture _ with a
glazed, hopeless look in their eyes. Some were on missions,
dedicated quests aimed at placating anxious children whose
collections were lacking a special bear or bird. Others were
seasoned beanophiles, waiting to make a killing on the secondary
market, hoping to retire one day to Tahiti where the only beans
allowed would be fresh roasted and ground.
</P>
<P>
   Now, suddenly, the beanie market is collapsing. Where are the
headlines? Toy stores, stationery stores and drugstores are all
beaned up. Where before children would descend on a sales clerk,
pleading for beanies _ any beanies _ now stores have them _ and
it's just not the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I have all of those,'' my 9-year-old daughter Micki
observed coolly the other day, quickly surveying a pile of beanies
filling a counter at Nordstrom. ``Let's go get some ice cream,''
she said, walking off without a backward glance.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same daughter who, just a month before, grabbed a
small beanie cat, a duplicate of one she already had at home,
begging for it just because it was the only beanie baby in the
store.
</P>
<P>
   So, let the word go forth _ give the people what they want and
they won't want it any more. The Beanie Revolution is winding down.
</P>
<P>
   But, fear not _ a new and better place awaits the beanies of
this world. I like to think of it, with affection, as The Pet
Rock-Cabbage Patch Doll-Tickle Me Elmo Retirement Villa. In our
house, it's also known as the closet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Ruth Sherman is a San Francisco writer and filmmaker.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
