<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     09-25 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VISIT TO MCGWIRETOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   McGWIRETOWN, U.S.A. _ My actual location is Fairview Heights,
Ill., which is just 15 miles from downtown St. Louis, which is
where Mark McGwire reigns as king of the world.
</P>
<P>
   If you are anywhere in the St. Louis area, you are in
McGwiretown. McGwire owns the region, from Busch Stadium to
wherever it is in upstate Illinois that baseball fans stop rooting
for the St. Louis Cardinals and start rooting for the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, home-run rival Sammy Sosa is king of the world. But
here in southwestern Illinois, where we can look across the
Mississippi River and see the famous Gateway Arch, life revolves
around Big Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Go into any supermarket, quick stop or department store and you
are knee-deep in vast arrays of Mac memorabilia: shirts, caps,
books, posters ...
</P>
<P>
   McGwiretown went nuts when Mac broke Roger Maris' single-season
home-run record Sept. 8, and sanity seems disinclined to return.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the day that the videotape of President Clinton's
grand jury testimony was released to America and the world, the
White House sex scandal had to share the top of Page 1 in the ``St.
Louis Post-Dispatch'': ``McGwire hits 65th homer but loses 66th in
controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   The locals are still snarling about that stupid umpire in
Milwaukee who voided No. 66 by ruling that a fan interfered with
the baseball before it cleared the outfield wall.
</P>
<P>
   The ump should thank his lucky stars he didn't make that call in
St. Louis. He might still be hanging by his heels from the top of
the Arch.
</P>
<P>
   Just a joke _ I think. Folks around these parts are fired up
about the home-run race. They live and die with every swing of
Mac's mighty bat.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, this is not a good place to be for someone who
is attempting to conduct a boycott of baseball. There is no way to
avoid baseball in McGwiretown, U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect that a person might get locked up faster for
bad-mouthing baseball in McGwiretown than for hijacking a truckload
of those weird new $20 bills that will soon be confusing consumers
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Bad-mouthing Mark McGwire would surely be treated as a capital
offense.
</P>
<P>
   So I haven't said much about my baseball boycott. When I'm in a
public place and the ball game is on TV _ it's on everywhere, of
course _ I shut up and watch right along with everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   And when McGwire is finished batting, I go on about my business
_ right along with everybody else. Interesting thing about
Macmania: Nobody is particularly involved with the ball game; the
fans only care about McGwire's at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   In restaurants and sports bars, people will be ready to leave
and then someone will say: ``Wait, we have to stay until McGwire
comes up.''
</P>
<P>
   After McGwire bats, they rush for the door, determined to arrive
at their next destination in time for McGwire's next at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   If boycotting baseball means boycotting McGwire _ and it does _
there can be no boycott in McGwiretown. And if I don't get out of
here soon, there will be no boycott for me.
</P>
<P>
   It almost ended Wednesday. Sosa had hit two homers earlier to
pull even with McGwire at 65, and the Cardinals were playing at
home against the Houston Astros. The game was scheduled to start
shortly after 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:45, I was sitting in my hotel room, listening to the
pre-game show on the radio and calculating how long it would take
me to get to the ballpark. If I couldn't get there by game time, I
figured, I could certainly get there in time for McGwire's first
trip to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The boycott was hanging by a thread. I was hoping that the
announcer would declare the game sold out and advise me to stay
away from Busch Stadium. He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, I procrastinated long enough that I lost the urge
to attend the game. I went on about my business, although I didn't
go anyplace that didn't figure to have a TV set tuned to the game.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire didn't hit a home run, and the boycott survived for one
more day _ but there were still four games to play.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for me to get out of town.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
