<HEADLINE>
DERSHOWITZ AS CHARACTER WITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A group of public-spirited virtue-mongers has designated one
week next month as Character Counts! week ... and not a moment too
soon! To commemorate said event (Oct. 18-24), the Joseph and Edna
Josephson Institute of Ethics is publishing ``The Power of
Character: Prominent Americans Talk About Life, Family, Work,
Values and More.''
</P>
<P>
   They've certainly assembled quite a list of characters. They've
got Dan Rather, Arianna Huffington, Dr. Laura Schlessinger,
Marianne Williamson, Charles Colson, Vartan Gregorian, the Rev.
Robert Schuller, Stephen Covey, Stephen Carter, and many, many
others. Diet book diva Susan Estrich, who once lied to me in an
interview (I know; it's like lying to Congress _ who cares?) is
here, with a nicely turned essay on the late Judge J. Skelly
Wright. Among local notables, we find Clark University's Christina
Hoff Sommers and O.J. Simpson's favorite appeals lawyer, Alan
Dershowitz.
</P>
<P>
   The Dersh, last spotted at Martha's Vineyard airport awaiting
the First Character's vacation arrival, leaves us with these
musings on character: ``Good character consists of recognizing the
selfishness that inheres in each of us and trying to balance it
against the altruism to which we should all aspire. It is a
difficult balance to strike, but no definition of goodness can be
complete without it.''
</P>
<P>
   Watch out, William Bennett. He's gaining on you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Heard on the street
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I hear a sea change has occurred at the three national magazines
unloaded by mutual fund giant Fidelity Investments earlier this
year. The new owners, a bunch of rich guys out of Travelers Corp.,
actually expect the publications to make money!
</P>
<P>
   The three rags in question are Peter Lynch fanzine Worth, the
world's worst financial publication; Civilization, an elegant,
little-read paean to haute kultur; and American Benefactor, which
covers philanthropy. For several years, the magazines were the
plaything of deep-pocketed Fidelity boss Ned Johnson, and money
flowed freely. Current publishers Greenwich Street Capital Partners
are keeping a closer eye on the bottom line. My spy reports: ``The
place is a slave shop. Come back, Fidelity!'' ... Elsewhere,
Kathryn Harris reports in her Bloomberg column that Mitt Romney's
Bain Capital may be plunging deeper into Hollywood, as Bain,
through a tiny film company called Artisan, seems to be the only
bidder for PolyGram Filmed Entertainment. Bain has been mucking
around Tinseltown since last year's purchase of Artisan, formerly
known as Live Entertainment. Live's chief executive was Jose
Menendez, gunned down in his home by his own sons.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Romney, a Mormon, ``avoids alcohol, tobacco, and
even caffeine,'' Harris asks: ``Why would a guy like Romney be
putting money in Hollywood?'' Maybe for the same reason the
Episcopalians at Boston Ventures put money in Motown Records _ to
make a bundle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hi-ho the glamorous life!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   H.L. Mencken once remarked to his pal Charles Angoff that
writers are people who work for a couple of hours a day and talk
about themselves the rest of the time. So how do writers really
pass the time? My friend Paul Brown, coauthor of the business
classic ``Customers for Life'' has tapped into a group of scribes
who check the sales volume of their books at the amazon.com Web
site _ three or four times a day! (Amazon's entire inventory is
updated in real time, so a sale of a dozen books can propel a book
from number 4,678 in sales way up to number 235, in minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   Paul says his book generally hovers in the 10,000s to 20,000s,
but on one day it was the 641st best-selling volume in Amazon's
inventory. His friend Barbara Rudolph likewise cops to being ``a
compulsive Amazon checker'' who used to check the Web site 12-15
times a day. (``I'm down to five or six.'') Her book,
``Disconnected,'' about six &UR;  &LR; laid-off AT&AMP;T employees, has yoyoed
from number 6,000 to 1,500 within hours. A National Public Radio
feature sent ``Disconnected'' into the low 600s. Given that Amazon
represents only 3 percent of the US book market, ``I know I'm silly
to be doing this,'' Rudolph admits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
