<HEADLINE>
RACIAL GAP WIDENS IN HUB SCHOOLS' TEST SCORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Despite more than a decade of effort by the Boston
public schools to close the test score gap between whites and
minorities, the gap has widened, scores show.
</P>
<P>
   While the schools have succeeded in the past two years in
boosting a significant number of black and Hispanic students out of
the lowest-scoring category, many minorities have not moved into
the higher scoring ranges at the rate of white students,
particularly in math.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the 1996 citywide math test of 11th graders,
only 1 percent of blacks and 2 percent of Hispanics were ranked
``proficient'' or ``advanced.'' This compared to 18 percent of
whites.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the percentage of blacks and Hispanics scoring in those
top categories had increased _ to 2 percent of blacks and 4 percent
of Hispanics. Whites, in contrast, made an 11 percent gain, with 29
percent scoring at those levels.
</P>
<P>
   The city's test scores since 1985, reviewed by the Globe, are a
disheartening result for a school system that has made narrowing
the achievement gap between racial groups a priority for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's puzzling to us,'' said Maryellen Donahue, head of
research, assessment, and evaluation for the city's public schools.
``It's one of the most important issues we have.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is by no means unique to Boston. Nationally, the
test score gap between whites and minorities in city school systems
has generally either reached a plateau or increased, according to
the educational literature, after years of improvement during the
1970s and early 1980s following desegregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about this is that we saw the gap narrow before; it
is fully in our power to do it again,'' said Amy Wilkins, senior
associate of the Education Trust, a nonprofit Washington
educational think tank that has published reports on the
achievement gap nationally.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston School Superintendent Thomas Payzant said narrowing
that gap today is more difficult than it was 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between the late '90s and the '70s is that
then, it was a task of simple literacy and basic skills,'' he said.
``Now, it's more complex. ... We've got some schools doing a better
job at it than others.''
</P>
<P>
   Payzant said that by mid-October, schools that have made the
most gains in closing the racial achievement gap will have been
identified so their methods can be replicated.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1985 and 1995, whites made much greater gains in math
and reading scores than blacks and Hispanics. The scores of Asian
students tended to either increase slightly or stay the same; their
greatest gains were in math.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, 50 percent of white 7th graders scored in the 66th
percentile or above for reading; 50 percent of blacks scored in the
44th percentile or above.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, 50 percent of whites were scoring in the 79th
percentile or higher, while 50 percent of blacks were scoring in
the 46th percentile or higher, according to Metropolitan
Achievement Test results supplied by the School Department.
</P>
<P>
   The citywide achievement test was changed in 1996 to the
Stanford 9. The scores on that test also show an increasing gap in
performance at the highest ranges.
</P>
<P>
   The most encouraging sign, however, is in reading, a focus of
the Boston schools for two years. Whites and minorities made about
equal gains in the last two years into the ``proficient'' and
``advanced'' levels.
</P>
<P>
   Payzant says he intends to work on closing the gap by raising
expectations for all students, through stricter promotion standards
and better professional development for teachers. Critics of the
school system have charged for years that many teachers have lower
standards for minority students than for whites.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Alkins of the Boston branch of the NAACP said Thursday
that many minority children are also demoralized by the racism that
remains in America, which can affect achievement level.
</P>
<P>
   Others in education say there is a disparity in the education
level of white and minority parents that can affect children's
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Andrews, headmaster of the Neighborhood Charter School in
Dorchester, and Barney Brawer, who is working with him on the
achievement gap issue, say they see a high number of white students
doing well who are from well-educated families who live in the city
by choice.
</P>
<P>
   They also see an equally high number of black students not doing
well who come from poor and uneducated families. They say they are
struggling with how to make up in school for the educational
disadvantages students may have at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``School success is like a path you travel on,'' Brawer said.
``If you come from a family who has already traveled on it, they
know what to expect and what to do. But if you are someone who has
never done it, you can get very lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews said: ``Here ... we teach the parents the rules of the
game: `Here are the rules for success. Here is what your child
needs to know.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
