<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SUPPORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP EYES TEXAS AS BUSH BUILDS A DOMINANT BASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Squealing schoolgirls crowded a rally for Governor
George W. Bush here the other day while Emilio Navaira, a
heartthrob from the world of Tejano music, serenaded the governor
in Spanish with a campaign song, ``Juntos Con Bush'' (Together With
Bush). Bush responded with a few words in Spanish himself, then
winked impishly at his feat.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was strange, even in exotic Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But in this traditionally Democratic city, a bastion of
Mexican-American voters, Bush seemed to be flexing muscles for his
race for re-election this fall as well as rehearsing for a run at
the next Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The governor says he will not make a decision about the
presidential race before winning re-election and dealing with the
legislature early next year, but this fall's contest does not
appear to be an obstacle to higher ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   According to polls this month by Texas newspapers, Bush holds a
staggering, 49-point lead over his Democratic challenger, Land
Commissioner Garry Mauro. The prospect of impressive victory
already has catapulted Bush into the thick of 2000 presidential
politics, where Hispanic votes are critical in three of the most
vital states, California, Florida, and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While noting the ``sullied process'' in Washington and worrying
about how a presidential run would invade his family's privacy,
Bush expresses confidence about a national campaign and says he did
not fear reports about his high-living past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been investigated,'' he said in an interview. ``There was
opposition research and profile pieces when I ran last time. I
think America is going to have to get used to the baby-boomer
generation of politicians. The relevant question of George Bush is
not: Have you made mistakes? But: Have you learned, grown up, and
become prepared to lead?''
</P>
<P>
   While chaos swirls in Washington, these are stable times for the
52-year-old Bush. The son of former President Bush is completing
his first term as governor with high popularity marks, presiding
over a period where prosperity has handed the state an extra $7
billion in revenue _ more than the annual budget of many Third
World countries. In Florida, Bush's brother Jeb is poised to be
elected governor.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor says his proudest accomplishment after four
years in office is ``the tone in Texas, a lack of divisiveness.''
With the Tejano singer at his side, Bush fielded several questions
from a Spanish-speaking television reporter after the San Antonio
event. He resorted to English words for Spanish expressions he did
not know, explaining afterwards, ``I refuse to let my sentences
dangle. My vocabulary's getting better, but I need more practice. I
want to show the people I care about their language.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning nearly a quarter of the Hispanic vote in 1994,
Bush hopes to become the first Anglo Republican candidate to make
substantial gains among Mexican-Americans in a Texas governor's
race.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats have already conceded the election. ``It's a
non-race,'' said a well-known Texas Democrat, speaking on the
condition he would not be identified. ``No one thought Mauro could
win, so he got no money. What's left of the Democratic Party is
willing to let Bush go.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview between fund-raising calls at a friend's office
here, Mauro sounded philosophical. ``Maybe it was not the smartest
political decision to run against the son of Barbara Bush,'' he
said. ``But I decided to run because I saw it as a unique
opportunity for this generation.''
</P>
<P>
   At 50, Mauro is a still-youthful veteran of Texas politics, the
last incumbent left from a colorful slate of Texas Democrats,
including Lloyd Bentsen, Ann Richards, and Jim Hightower, that
swept statewide races in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro is popular among Hispanics; some even think he is
Hispanic. ``I'll hang on to that vote big-time,'' he said. ``Bush
has a lot of money and support from the Austin insiders, but
there's not a depth of feeling for him around the state.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the governor has ignored Mauro's appeal for a debate.
``He's going to run for president, but he can't debate a land
commissioner,'' Mauro said in frustration. ``George Bush doesn't
understand textbook civics. He's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   With little excitement in the governor's race, politicians in
Texas appear preoccupied with President Clinton's quandary and are
curious about Bush's long-range plans.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's chief political strategist, said no national
campaign staff was being assembled. Asked about frequent visits to
Austin by Ralph Reed, former executive director of the Christian
Coalition and now a private consultant, Rove said Reed was ``a
longtime friend'' of the governor's and not part of any campaign
apparatus.
</P>
<P>
   In an expansive interview at his office in the state capitol
last week, Bush called the situation in Washington ``embarrassing
and depressing. The nation is focused on matters that are not of
state. ... But I have a more patient view, and I think the system
will be purged by the time the presidential race begins to jell.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has acknowledged being ``young and irresponsible,'' but he
said he does not intend to confess to a ``laundry list'' of
indiscretions. Before he was married, Bush had a reputation as a
carousing ladies' man. But he quit drinking abruptly on his 40th
birthday, and friends now describe Bush as a family man devoted to
his wife, Laura, and their twin 16-year-old daughters.
</P>
<P>
   With politics intruding into private lives, Bush said he is most
concerned that his family will be upset if he runs for president.
``It's a lifetime commitment,'' he said, that will make impossible
such ordinary outings as to go ``down to Wal-Mart and buy a power
mower.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Clinton bore much of the blame for the poisonous
political atmosphere. ``He didn't tell the truth and he misused the
Oval Office.'' But the governor also criticized ``zero sum politics
_ I win; you lose _ that's been festering for a decade'' as well as
the practice of ``gotcha journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The written word has been denigrated,'' Bush said. ``Scribes
have become pundits on TV. Political journalism has been changed by
TV and the Internet. There's a plethora of programming, of
information, a competition of opinion. It's almost anarchistic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
