<SLUG> BC-HIV-REPORTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA NEEDS A NEW HIV REPORTING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MITCH KATZ  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Powerful HIV therapies have lengthened the time
between initial HIV infection and an AIDS diagnosis for many
individuals. The result is that thousands of Californians who are
HIV-positive, but not diagnosed with AIDS, are missed by our
current reporting system since it does not track the human
immunodeficiency virus.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Pete Wilson's signature on a bill (AB 1663), sponsored by
Assemblywoman Carole Migden, would enable California to modernize
its AIDS case reporting system to incorporate HIV cases, providing
a more complete picture of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   With AB 1663, cases of HIV infection would be reported to local
health officials through the use of a unique code _ rather than a
person's name _ in an effort to protect both public health and
confidentiality. In recent months, there has been a great deal of
national debate about the importance of medical privacy. When
asked, the majority of people prefer that their medical records not
be made available to the government or other private entities for
fear that this information could be used inappropriately.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of HIV reporting, protecting confidentiality is more
than just an issue of privacy _ it also represents sound public
health policy. Studies have shown that when people know that their
names will be reported to their local health department, they are
less likely to get tested for HIV and obtain medical care because
of the very real fear of AIDS discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of names reporting, who say that collecting HIV case
information by name is more accurate, often fail to recognize this
serious deterrent effect. If names reporting ultimately undermines
the community's trust in the public health system, driving
individuals away from testing and treatment, we have caused great
harm.
</P>
<P>
   Because of these concerns, the City and County of San Francisco
_ distinguished by its longstanding leadership in the fight against
HIV _ firmly opposes name-based HIV reporting and strongly supports
the public health approach outlined in Migden's bill.
</P>
<P>
   I believe that this legislation represents a tremendous
opportunity for California. Not only has it gained the approval of
mainstream medical groups like the California Medical Association
and the California Conference of Local Health Officers, but support
also comes from advocacy groups for people living with HIV that
have traditionally opposed any type of HIV reporting system.
</P>
<P>
   Migden's bill is a unique compromise that provides a reasonable
response to a critical public health need. If the legislation is
not signed into law, California will continue to have no system of
HIV reporting, reducing our state's ability to accurately monitor
and track the epidemic. We must begin implementation of an HIV
reporting system immediately to ensure that we are not at a
disadvantage in federal resource allocations that may be based on
counting HIV infections rather than just AIDS cases.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, such a system allows us to continue to notify the
partners of those who are infected, when appropriate, just as we
currently do. Reporting the name of the infected person to the
health department is not necessary for such partner notification
services.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, by implementing the bill, California would join a
growing number of states that have rejected names reporting for a
more sound public health approach to HIV reporting. In addition to
Maryland _ which has used a unique identifier system successfully
for nearly five years _ Massachusetts and Hawaii are implementing
similar systems, and other states (including Connecticut and
Washington) are seriously considering this option. California's
current approach to AIDS reporting is outdated and should be
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Migden's bill will provide much-needed information to public
health officials without driving individuals away from HIV testing
and medical care. California should swiftly take advantage of the
critical and exciting opportunity afforded by this bill.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mitch Katz, M.D., is head of San Francisco's Department of
Public Health.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
