<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESOLVE TO KEEP MAKING CONTRIBUTIONS TO (401)K 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 27, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am totally lost and don't know how to think and plan for
the future. The new market changes have created a kind of
confusion. I am 46 and have a 401(k) plan evenly divided between
balanced funds and a stock index fund. Last quarter the returns
were low _ the balanced funds advanced 2.95 percent, and the stock
index was up 3.30 percent. God knows what the results are going to
be for the second quarter. Is my money in the right place? Should I
make changes before the end of this quarter?. One idea I had is to
close the 401(k) account, pay the penalties, pay off all my debts,
and start over.
</P>
<P>
   C.M., Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I think the problem is one of expectations. We don't really
have a ``new market,'' but simply a market which is, for the first
time in several years, showing that the direction isn't always
going to be up. The quarterly returns you achieved in the second
quarter, far from being low, are actually stronger than the
long-term average historical returns from stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at what was going on before the bull market of the
late '90s began. From 1950 to 1994, the Dow Jones industrial
average achieved gains in 310 months. For the other 230 months, the
average was in the red. This amounts to a 57.4 percent record of
gains. When you are dealing with a long-term program such as a
401(k) plan, your expectations should be more in line with those
1950-1994 results than with what has been happening in the
extraordinary markets from 1995 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to retire at age 65, this means you will be building
this account for another 228 months, and I think it's reasonable to
expect sour results in something very much like 97 of them _ this
is simply what happens with the market. (You should be guessing by
now that I'm entirely against cashing out the 401(k) plan.)
</P>
<P>
   Let's consider the effect of cashing out. If you were to take
that move, beginning over with the $200.33 combined monthly
contributions to the fund that you and your employer have been
making, it would take you a little more than 54 months to get back
to your current $13,655 balance. Then during the remaining 174
months the account would grow to $129,480. (These examples presume
10 percent average annual returns and continued total contributions
of $200.33 a month.) But if you left the current balance in the
account and continued making contributions at current levels, the
account would be worth $212,146 after 19 years. It seems to me that
having an additional $82,666 in your retirement pool should far
outweigh having $9,832 to spend now.
</P>
<P>
   Like other savings programs, a 401(k) is a discipline _ you have
to resolve to keep making your contributions no matter what else is
going on with your finances. When you have your 401(k) invested
primarily in stocks, the discipline becomes even tougher _ you have
to keep shoveling it in during those many months when the market
will lose ground.
</P>
<P>
   I have no problem with your choice of investments; you outline
that the alternative investments are a short-term interest account,
an equity fund, and your company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly with your long-term time frame, you don't want the
short-term interest account, and since you don't specify the equity
fund or your company, I can't make a judgment on those options.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 47-year-old union iron worker, and I have $110,000
invested through my union's annuity plan, which is being switched
to Vanguard investments. I contribute $7,000 annually. I plan to
work 10 more years, and like to make the most of the years I have
left to invest. How do you suggest I diversify my investments?
</P>
<P>
   D.G., Canyon Country, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Ten years is a tough time frame to work with. It is the
precise stage at which intermediate-term investing ends and
long-term investing begins. Since I'm pretty distrustful of the
current market, and since you'll soon enough be in the intermediate
term anyway, I suggest you take a cautious approach to investing
the $110,000 you've already saved, and then take a more aggressive
approach with investing your ongoing contributions.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest that half of your nest egg go into Vanguard Balanced
Index, which invests 60 percent of its assets in a broad array of
stocks, basically designed to emulate the performance of the stock
market at large, but dominated by the large-cap stocks that drive
most indexes. I would put the remaining 50 percent of the money in
Vanguard GNMA, a fund invested in government-guaranteed mortgage
securities.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest you divide the current contributions among three
funds, selected to counterbalance the conservative approach
suggested above. First, I'd put 25 percent of this money in the
Vanguard Specialized Health Care portfolio. This takes you into
expensive stocks, but it's a fast-growing sector of the market, and
profits in the kind of health care companies favored by this fund _
pharmaceuticals and health care equipment companies _ tend to move
even faster than sales. Such a holding can give you a bumpy road,
and might especially do so in the near term. But remember, you will
be engaged on a dollar-cost averaging program, and if the fund
stumbles, that means that next month's contribution will be buying
shares at a lower price, bringing your average overall cost per
share down.
</P>
<P>
   I would then put a similar percentage into Vanguard Small Cap
Stock Index. This is a sector of the market which has over the very
long haul tended to outpace the established large-cap issues that
have driven the recent markets. My feeling is that, more than any
other market sector, the small caps are ``due.''
</P>
<P>
   For the final 50 percent, I'll stick with stocks but be more
conservative, recommending Vanguard Index Value. This is a fund
which holds about two-thirds of the issues in the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500, selecting those with the lowest price-to-book value ratios.
These tend to be the solid, established, perhaps sleepy, but also
dividend paying stocks _ a lot of utilities, auto makers, and so
forth. The dividends and established franchises of these companies
would, I think, give it a little protection in a market downturn.
You might keep an eye on this one, and if the market appears to
have returned to more normal values _ which I would define as
dividends in the area of 2.5 percent, and price-to-earnings ratios
in the neighborhood of 15 to 20 _ then you might consider switching
to Vanguard Index 500. But for the current market, I'd venture no
further than Index Value.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
