<HEADER>
A4465 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV27-BO     09-25 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCEDES-BENZ SHOWS ITS NEW V-8S IN VERMONT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, September 27, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASIN HARBOR, Vt. _ If you want a driving challenge, you don't
need to go the the expense of a trip to Monaco, Baja California, or
Pikes Peak _ Vermont will do quite nicely. The Green Mounmtain
State is chock-full of scenic routes, nasty mountain switchbacks
and an automotive mountain climb that's steeper than the famed
Pikes Peak run.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont, where the natives are a practical bunch, is a state
where an ``improved'' road means the dirt has been scraped by a
grader recently, and the paved roads are no wider than they
absolutely have to be. It is a place to test the mettle of a new
model, demonstrate the virtue of a car _ or show very quickly the
lack of it.
</P>
<P>
   It was here that Merceedes-Benz decided to introduce its newest
machines, the 1999 ML430 and CLK430, the first a sport/utility that
elegantly blends performance, luxury, and safety, the second a
sports car disguised as an elegantly civilized luxury coupe. The
routes included some few short stretches of interstate, quite a lot
of narrow mountain pavement, plenty of ``improved'' dirt, and, in
the case of the ML430, a couple of miles of muddy, rocky track
through the woods pretending to be a trail.
</P>
<P>
   The ML430 is the Benz answer to the luxury sport utility that
first appeared as the ML320 _ meaning it has a 3.2-liter V-6 under
the hood. The ML430 gets its numerical handle from the fact of a
4.3-liter, 268-horsepower, multivalve V-8 under the hood. For the
$43,750 list price, you get lots of room, seating for a small mob,
comfort, elegance, and a safety package that includes traction
control, the Electronic Stability Program that senses imminent skid
and corrects, Brake Assist that senses panic stops and increases
braking force, four-wheel antilock brakes, front and side air bags,
and a ``thinking'' five-speed automatic transmission that adapts to
the driver's mode of operation. And _ a challenge to the rest of
the SUV world _ a bumper the same height as that of a passenger
car; the Benz SUV is less of a threat to the wee ones on the road.
There is also the Baby Smart technology that turns off the air bags
to protect children in the Benz baby seat, and, if you like
sunroofs, the ML430 is to have the mother of them all available, a
4-foot-by-3-foot skyview.
</P>
<P>
   The proof, as they say, is in the pudding, so early Tuesday
under lowering skies, a herd of motor journalists set forth in 20
of the new SUVs, headed across Vermont Route 17, thence onto a
variety of roads. There are signs that tell you the roads will be a
... challenge? ``Winter travel not advised,'' it may say, or
``tractor trailers and busses (sic) not permitted.''
</P>
<P>
   The first tricky bit was a dirt trail in the process of being
graded with a mound of soft dirt running about where the left wheel
should be tracking. The ML traction control doesn't lock axles to
get you out of the muck; it senses slip and adds brake to improve
traction _ one wheel on the ground is enough to keep you moving.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to get into trouble with an ML, but you have to
be prize-winning stupid to do it, and somebody on the route did,
but not trouble enough to need help _ merely an errant drift
slightly over the edge onto a shoulder that wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   We tracked up mountains and down, on dirt, semi-dirt,
semi-pavement, and at last found ourselves dashing up Route 108 out
of Stowe across Smugglers' Notch, a paved, tortuous trail that at
one point barely becomes one lane as it bends around the rocks.
More dirt, more turns, then lunch and real craziness.
</P>
<P>
   We dined, as it were, at Zack's On the Rocks. Zack greets us in
a frilled purple garment somewhere between house dress and toga.
The decor can only be described as bizarre, the sugar is purple as
is the salad dressing, but the food is quite good _ if you enjoy
eating in what looks like the flower-festooned set of a horror
flick starring Bette Davis and Freddie _ in a cave.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was into the CLK430 with its 275-horsepower V-8, a
$47,900 luxury package that will leap from 0 to 60 miles per hour
in 6.1 seconds and offers the ESP as standard equipment _ it's an
option on the CLK320 sister coupe.
</P>
<P>
   Back down 108 through Smugglers' Notch from the north, now, then
a sprint on Interstate 89, and back onto the secondary tracks, and
the misadventure begins. The ML is no slouch in the corners, but
the CLK bends around the turns like an articulated rat _ CLK is
pronounced smooth, soaks up the bumps and ruts. My driving partner,
John Bugsy Lawlor of NPR and WBZ, is navigating this leg. We are to
``bear right at the round church and turn right onto Hinesburg
Road'' but Bugsy merely advises ``you go right'' and flashes past
Hinesburg for an eventual 14-mile detour. Another team follows us.
Later, I hear: ``I think we were supposed to go straight back there
on Moncton ....'' Oh, what the heck; we got 20 miles' more driving
than anybody else _ except for those other guys behind us.
</P>
<P>
   The ML430 is an SUV that looks more like a van than a truck,
behaves like a good sedan, handles and accelerates like a sporty
coupe, yet it is a rigid box on a frame just like the truck-based
SUVs. The CLK430 has the manners of a road racer, the ride of a
luxury sedan, and induces joy in a driver like a basket of kittens
evokes fun in a kindergarten. The V-8 engines in both cars offer
peak torque over a wide, flat band, 3,000 to 4,500 r.p.m.; the
result is surprising responsiveness in virtually any gear. The ML
is good at passing, the CLK is a lightning bolt.
</P>
<P>
   These are pricey cars for the well-to-do, but Benz cars wear
well. Sooner or later, they will be affordable used cars with all
that good stuff still working ... and then maybe I can afford one
to enjoy my approaching geezerhood.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, thumbs up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
