<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 12:35 p.m., the industrial average was
down 12 points, and the Nasdaq index was up 3 points. Overseas,
prices decreased 3.4 percent in Tokyo and 1.7 percent in Hong Kong.
They fell 0.6 percent in Frankfurt, 2 percent in London, 3.2
percent in Brazil and 2 percent in Mexico. On the American debt
market, the long bond was up 5/32 point at midday, with the yield
at 5.15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Coca-Cola says it expects earnings for
the rest of the year to be below expectations because of slower
sales caused by the currency and economic difficulties in Asia,
Latin America and eastern Europe. The company expects earnings in
the current quarter of 35 cents a share, roughly equal to its
earnings a year ago before gains from bottling transactions. Its
fourth quarter earnings will be less than a year earlier. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-AUTOS (Taubate, Brazil) _ The Brazilian car industry is
slamming on the brakes. Next week, 20,000 Volkswagen workers in the
country will start 10 days of forced vacation, while those at Ford
will have to stay home for 12 days. Mercedes will send workers home
for two days, and workers at General Motors will stay home for 11
days in October. Just two years ago, Brazil was viewed as the most
promising new market for car makers, the natural gateway to more
than 300 million consumers in Latin America. But now that the
international financial crisis is buffeting Brazil and the rest of
Latin America, all bets are off. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
