<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4478 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-DAVIS-BOS &LR;      09-25 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-DAVIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER CAN'T STOP THE ORIOLES' DAVIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN ROMANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was early in the baseball season, an off day for the
Baltimore Orioles, but far from an off day for Eric Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran outfielder was on the phone to Boston, giving advice
and encouragement to a woman who had just been diagnosed with colon
cancer and was about to undergo the rigors of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   At the all too young age of 36, Davis knows of what he speaks.
On June 15, 1997, just weeks after doubling over in the dugout with
severe abdominal pain, Davis underwent surgery at Johns Hopkins
Hospital in Baltimore. Doctors removed a baseball-sized growth and
a third of his colon. He then began a once-a-week chemotherapy
regimen that lasted nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Truly, no one expected Davis to return last season to the
Orioles, who at the time were trying to win the American League
East title. But four months after major abdominal surgery, he was
playing at Camden Yards as Baltimore clinched. A few weeks later,
just days after a chemotherapy treatment, he belted the winning
home run in Game 5 of the AL Championship Series against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   His courage and determination won him many awards, including
those named in honor of Roberto Clemente, Tony Conigliaro, and Fred
Hutchinson.
</P>
<P>
   But what of 1998? Still subjected to chemotherapy treatments as
late as January, Davis had his fitness, his ability to play a full
season of baseball, called into question. Saying he didn't want to
``hurt Eric,'' his manager, Ray Miller, projected Davis for 100
games at the most.
</P>
<P>
   Even Davis's oncologist, Dr. Ross Donehower of Johns Hopkins,
wasn't sure what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if there is a huge precedent for this,'' said
Donehower. ``Most people who get colon cancer are older and most
aren't world-class athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   What Davis has done in 1998 is simply this: play in 128 games,
bat a team-high .328, hit 27 home runs, and drive in 87 runs _ all
while battling painful bone chips in his right elbow. After the
Orioles stumbled out of the gate and were a dreadful 38-50 at the
All-Star break, Davis brought them alive and back into the
wild-card race. He hit in a club-record 30 straight games during a
27-7 run, batting .400 with 12 homers and 41 RBIs during that
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   How impressive is all that? To comprehend, you must understand
the long-term effects chemotherapy can have on the human body.
</P>
<P>
   For colon cancer, the drug commonly used is 5-FU. In Davis's
case, it was administered once a week in six-week cycles, with two
weeks off between cycles. Davis was hooked up to an IV, and a form
of folic acid called leucovorin, which helps bind the 5-FU to its
target, was dripped into a vein in his arm for two hours. Midway
through the process, a nurse would inject the 5-FU into the IV.
</P>
<P>
   The drug targets fast-growing cells in the body, which cancer
cells are, but in the process, it also can damage cells in the bone
marrow and lining of the intestines.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Eric's case, he did very well on the drug,'' said
Donehower. ``He would experience a little nausea, and certain foods
would bother him. But mostly, he had profound fatigue that evening
and the day after.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After the chemo, you can see Eric is just wiped out,'' Orioles
assistant general manager Kevin Malone was quoted as saying last
year. ``He looks lifeless. Your heart goes out to the guy. But he
bounces back so fast. The spark returns to his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, Davis weathered more chemotherapy treatments
and served as a spokesman for the Mid-Atlantic chapter of the
American Cancer Society, all the while working hard to keep his
6-foot-3-inch, 195-pound body in playing shape.
</P>
<P>
   Just before spring training, he received his last treatment at
the UCLA Medical Center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone has been on chemotherapy for a number of months,
whether he's a world-class athlete or not, there's a cumulative
effect on the body,'' said Donehower. ``A person's energy level and
stamina are affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case with Davis, who sat out about 30 games this
season. ``My manager would tell me that whenever I felt tired to
let him know,'' said Davis. ``There were a couple of times I told
him I was tired, and I was expecting that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that was a side effect from the chemo. I think
the tiredness was coming from not being able to work out like I
normally do in the offseason. I would miss almost three days a week
because I would take chemo on Wednesdays and I wouldn't be able to
do anything until Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the circumstances, I feel about as well as I can expect
to feel, because I came into the season without any expectations at
all, so I feel great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the hardest part was getting people around me to
relax. Even my own manager had predicted that he would bring me
along slowly, try to minimize the games that I played. That was my
biggest obstacle, getting the respect from him and letting him know
that, hey, I can go out there and be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the season he's had, Davis is not a lock for the AL's
Comeback Player of the Year Award. Pitcher Bret Saberhagen has had
a terrific season, bouncing back from major elbow surgery to win 15
games for the Red Sox. In any given year, he would be a worthy
choice.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to compare his case with that of Davis, whose
accomplishments on the field are as great as his courage off it.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, his 13th year in the majors comes to an end. A free
agent, he expects to re-sign with the Orioles for 1999. But unlike
many of his teammates and fellow ballplayers, who will relax and
take another season of baseball as a given, Davis will have to take
one day at a time. His blood work last month proved normal, with
his six-month colon checkup due next. Tests will always be a part
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll ever be normal,'' said Davis, who lives in
Los Angeles with his wife, Sherri, and children, Erica and Sacha.
``Because I was diagnosed with cancer, it will always be a part of
my life, my body, my vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did often during this past season, once hurrying from the
park late on a Friday evening to take part in a rally against
cancer, Davis will devote much of his free time to helping others
with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Orioles fan, stricken at age 29 with cancer of the
lymph nodes, who wakes up every morning and goes to work, helped in
large part by the inspiration he gets from watching Davis play
baseball. And the young woman with breast cancer who became a fan
when Davis bought her and other patients lunch as they received
their chemotherapy treaments side by side at Johns Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget the woman from Boston with colon cancer
whom Davis called earlier this year. That was me.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's obviously an inspiration to others with the disease, and
it's wonderfully exciting that he didn't allow the disease to
distract him from his goals,'' said Donehower. ``As Eric has said
himself, it's just something he had to do. He's very matter-of-fact
about it. He's doesn't look at what he's doing as anything special.
But, of course, it is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe correspondent Shira Springer contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
