u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-25 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUGHT UP IN THE `GOTCHA' MILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sun Myung Moon and his friends have done for me what Jenny Craig
and hers could not.
</P>
<P>
   If my experience is any guide, bogus allegations of plagiarism
could become the hottest weight-loss fad among the writing set. I
lost 6 pounds this week; I am wearing a dress that has not fit me
in a year.
</P>
<P>
   This slimming silver lining came cloaked in allegations of
plagiarism by a sympathizer of the Rev. Moon, the self-proclaimed
messiah who runs the multimillion-dollar Unification Church
business and religious empire.
</P>
<P>
   It was an attorney for the Moons who circulated a series of
passages from ``The Advent of Sun Myung Moon,'' a flattering
portrayal of the cult by George Chryssides, that he alleged were
stolen by Nansook Hong, a former daughter-in-law of the Rev. Moon
who has far less kind things to say in her just-published memoirs
about life in ``the True Family.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hong's book, ``In the Shadow of the Moons,'' is a memoir of
a young woman forced into marriage with the crown prince of the
Moon family when she was only 15. It is her story of the abuse she
suffered for 14 years until she escaped with her five children in
1995. Her publisher, Little, Brown &AMP; Co., hired me to help Ms. Hong
craft her narrative.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the Moonies say we ``stole'' from Mr. Chryssides:
</P>
<P>
   _A quotation from The Pledge, a prayer akin to the Lord's Prayer
in Christian denominations. (Ms. Hong memorized it when she was 7
years old.)
</P>
<P>
   _A passage from ``Divine Principle,'' a collection of the Rev.
Moon's ``revelations.'' (``Divine Principle'' is the cult's sacred
text, not unlike the Christian Bible.)
</P>
<P>
   _A description of the prayer service conducted eight days after
the birth of a baby. (Ms. Hong is the daughter of two of the Rev.
Moon's original disciples and the mother of five of his
grandchildren. What are the chances she needed to consult a
secondary source to describe church ritual?)
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, this newspaper ran a chart comparing a passage
from Ms. Hong's book with a passage from ``The Advent of Sun Myung
Moon.'' Both recount a widely circulated rumor about the early
Unification Church called The House of Three Doors. &UR;  &LR; That chart did
not include a passage from the primary source, a church document
that was referenced by both authors. It reads: ``.... there were
three different kinds of doors in the Unification Church: When you
went through the first door you had to take off your jacket; upon
entering the second door you had to take off more; and after
passing through the third door you took off all your clothes and
then committed adultery or fornication.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the wording similar in all three passages? Sure it is. This
is church lore, passed orally among members. Like any oft-repeated
story, it settles into a familiar form. In telling the story of
``Little Red Riding Hood,'' wouldn't we all note her mother's
warning not to ``leave the path?'' Wouldn't we all have her
exclaim, ``What big teeth you have'' to the disguised wolf?
</P>
<P>
   This is an ugly time in America. Accusation alone destroys
reputations. The respect we once had for evidence, the attention we
once paid to an accuser's motives, has been usurped by a national
game of ``gotcha.'' The media play it. Political candidates play
it. Special prosecutors play it. False messiahs play it, too. The
price we all pay is an erosion of human decency.
</P>
<P>
   I spent much of my summer explaining to my children _ ages 12,
10, and 7 _ why those of us who write for the public prints have a
responsibility to tell the truth. For any of us to lie, to fudge,
to trim in these pages is to debase the very real privilege
entrusted to a free press in a democracy.
</P>
<P>
   I have been at this work long enough to have grown a coat of
armor to deflect the often nasty criticism that comes with
committing one's opinions to newstype twice a week. But my voice
cracked when I told my children that this newspaper would carry a
story about someone &UR;  &LR; accusing me of plagiarism that I knew to be
baseless.
</P>
<P>
   I have my share of conspicuous faults. I am reliably told I am
too often profane in my private speech and too sanctimonious in my
public pronouncements; the Improper Bostonian calls me ``Eileen of
Arc.'' I might even be, as the Boston Herald once said, a
gender-and-class-obsessed ``shrieker.'' Whatever else you think of
the opinions that appear under that dreadful sketch of me, know
this: I am as poor an excuse for a plagiarist as I am an
advertisement for Jenny Craig.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
