<HEADER>
A4485 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-25 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOVER OF MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a guru is a wise man with mysterious powers who can move his
followers in ways impossible to explain by either science or art,
then surely Alan Greenspan is Mr. Guru with a capital ``G.''
</P>
<P>
   His Svengali-like influence over not just the American financial
system, but the world's, was demonstrated yet again this week.
After some abstruse ruminations before two congressional
committees, many of the planet's largest wealth-holders shoved
billions around. It is uncanny.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Al runs the Federal Reserve system in the way the pope
runs the College of Cardinals. His steady hand gets the last twist
on the spigot of money supply and interest rates. If any man can be
said to wield the throttle of the world economy, it's Big Al. Watch
his feet: If Al steps on the gas, the economy lunges ahead. If Al
tromps the brakes, things slow down so swiftly that stockbrokers
everywhere find their noses flattened on the dashboard.
</P>
<P>
   Because no man on earth has the raw power that America's
president always has (and still has), you can't nominate Greenspan
as the skipper of this giant ocean liner that is the US economy.
But if he's not the captain, he's at least the pilot-navigator. And
in rough weather, the people with dough in Wall Street and
everywhere else keep close tabs on Chairman Al.
</P>
<P>
   If your money is riding on the Titanic, slicing through
hazardous waters at high speed, you want a guy on the bridge who
sees the icebergs clearly. And the undisclosed debts of the world's
banks, the Japanese ones that are already underwater, and the US
and European ones that get killed by defaults and devaluations are
the iceberg that can slice open the US economy below the waterline.
Those bank debts are the hole in the boat. We need waterproof
bulkheads the Titanic didn't have. The closest thing we have to a
patch is the International Monetary Fund, which Congress refuses to
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Refusing money for the IMF in this world crisis is like
announcing you won't pay the Fire Department in the middle of a
five-alarmer. Sure, the IMF has problems, Al sighed before our
solons. But ``it's better to fund the IMF, than to have nothing at
all.'' Giving up, he brought the rationale down to their level.
Look, he said, ``It is far better to have a bicycle than to walk,
even though to have a limousine would be much better.'' Get it,
senators?
</P>
<P>
   Big Al moved markets mightily, twice in the last week, by doing
little more than taking his seat before two committees of Congress,
whose posturing politicians turn lapdog whenever Al's balding pate
shows up across the witness table. A week ago Wednesday, he
lectured the House Banking Committee and seemed to be witholding
any promise of a cut in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Since all the House seats are up for grabs Nov. 3, congressmen
look at a preelection interest rate cut like a crack addict eyeing
his smoking pipe: gimmee that! ``Greenspan talk trips up Dow;
216-point decline triggered by dashed hopes for rate cuts,'' was
the Globe headline next morning.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Chairman Al taketh away, so also he giveth _ in
spades. Appearing one week later before the Senate Budget
Committee, Al was at his winkin', blinkin', elfish best. His
routine calls for him to read, in deadpan fashion, a carefully
hedged assessment of world economic conditions, toss in a few
bromides (we should all spend less, save more, stay cool, be calm,
and diet regularly), and then answer questions with droll
allegories and the sorrowful head-shaking of an old grandfather who
has seen it all and is never surprised by the greed or stupidity
which is never far from the world of finance.
</P>
<P>
   He has a sense of humor, a lively wit, really. He told departing
Joe Kennedy ``Joe, I'll really miss you,'' and everyone broke up.
He did not take the bait when Barney Frank cracked shrewdly that
``The death of communism cost the IMF about 50 votes in the House
of Representatives.'' He remained above the fray when US
Representative Bernie Sanders, the independent from Vermont, railed
that ``your strategy has failed.'' Congressman, drolled Mr. G: if I
agreed with your diagnosis, I might agree with your solution _ but
I don't, so there.
</P>
<P>
   Big Al's style is like Jack Benny's _ it's all timing, and he
needs a straight man to furnish the setup. Fortunately for him,
Congress is loaded with straight men. When Al conjures up a riposte
he particularly likes, his eyebrows start to flutter. Imagine
Groucho Marx with a PhD in macroeconomics and no cigar; that's our
Al.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Senate panel got to the Q&AMP;A, members fell all over
themselves to get to ask the big R-question: so what about interest
rates, Mr. G, begged Senator Judd Gregg, Republican of New
Hampshire. Smiling Al, the Wizard of Oz, beamed. ``I think I know
where we have to go,'' he murmured. ``I do not think we
underestimate the severity of the problems ...''
</P>
<P>
   With a wink here, a blink there, a shrug, a sigh, having called
the world's economic distress ``more virulent'' than anticipated,
and ``likely to intensify,'' with ``erosion around the edges'' of
the US economy, and action definitely called for, Al then clammed
up. But the effect on the world's economy was like the Titanic's
lookout spying ice ahead. The Dow went up 257.
</P>
<P>
   In financial houses all over the planet, bells rang in the
engine room: ``Rate cut, rate cut! Buy, buy, buy!'' On bourses
everywhere, the word went forth. Now, if Al and his Fed governors
don't deliver what he all but promised when they meet in secret
Tuesday, you'll be reading about another meltdown Wednesday. Such
is Big Al's power. The Guru is in the house. No world figure, save
Nelson Mandela, for obvious reasons, gets this kind of respect.
</P>
<P>
   But you get the feeling Mr. G. knows how good he is. In a rare
moment of back-patting, with his irony meter clicking to the max,
Chairman Al opined: ``I have been able to string more words with
fewer ideas than anybody I know.'' Al, you're (itals) too(unitals)
modest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
