<HEADLINE>
HOW CAN CLINTON PUSH DOMESTIC ISSUES? HE CAN'T 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no need to ask if President Clinton's trysts will
cripple his domestic agenda. He is already on crumbling crutches.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Senate defeated Clinton's proposal to raise the
minimum wage by $1 an hour, to $6.15 by Jan. 1, 2000. Despite the
fact that $6.15 an hour would still not equal, in real dollars, the
value of the minimum wage 30 years ago ($7.21), the measure was
defeated, primarily by Republicans, 55-44.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times news story said that ``little groundwork had
been laid to build public or congressional support for a
minimum-wage increase this year. President Clinton mentioned it in
his State of the Union address in January, but as the Monica
Lewinsky scancal began to engulf him, he did little to follow up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was in stark contrast to his actions in 1996, when he
twisted arms and triumphantly pushed through the
Republican-controlled Congress the first wage increase in six
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse was Clinton's race initiative. With braggadocio 15 months
ago, Clinton christened an advisory board to travel around the
nation and help him challenge America toward a more equal,
multi-ethnic future.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming to be ``obsessed'' with the task, Clinton said, ``If we
do nothing more than talk, it will be interesting but it won't be
enough.'' He said, ``Anybody who looks at my entire life can see
that it's been dominated by three things: economics, education, and
race. If there is any issue I ought to have credibility on, it is
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the advisory panel turned in a final report so tepid,
it was panned in news reports.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times said, ``Almost from its inception,'' the
panel ``was plagued by a lack of organization, a youthful staff
with few policy experts, and continued interference by White House
officials who feared the political consequences of its work ...
Another problem the board faced was that with public attention
diverted by the Lewinsky episode, it was hamstrung in efforts to
stimulate a nationwide dialogue on race.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Morning News said the panel had ``a string of miscues
that drew bad reviews of the board, its staff, and even its mission
... The intiative, too, had to compete for media space and air time
with Monica Lewinsky and the ensuing scandal that has engulfed the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times wrote: ``By mid-December 1997, even
Clinton was distracted from his aggressive advocacy of the race
initiative. Bunkered in the White House with his legal advisers,
Clinton curtailed his public appearances to deal with allegations
of a sexual relationship with former intern Monica S. Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Tribune, under the Web page headline ``Race Panel's
Report Thick But Lightweight,'' wrote: ``Clinton had hoped to carve
out his place in history as the president who bridged America's
great racial divide. But a slow start by his advisory panel and
controversy over the panel's political makeup, not to mention the
distraction of the growing sex scandal in Washington, reduced bold
ambition to the cautious rhetoric of a report titled ``One America
in the 21st Century.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bergen Record had a particularly damaging interview with
panel member Thomas Kean, a former governor of New Jersey. It was
embarrassing because even Kean, a Republican, said that Clinton's
interest in the panel, as the newspaper put it, was ``deflated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Record wrote that Kean is concerned ``that the White House
sex scandal will prevent Clinton from carrying out his promise to
continue the work of the commission.'' Kean told the Record:
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's involvement was not what it was supposed to be
... You could see it at our meetings. It started out with the
president there, and the first couple of meetings there were three
or four Cabinet members there and a lot of interest. The last six
months, we haven't had a single Cabinet member show up for a single
meeting, even hearings that involved the Cabinet member's own
department.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Edley, the Harvard law professor and Clinton
adviser, said Clinton needs to ``lay claim to the bully pulpit'' on
race. But this week, Clinton was a man lying down for
safer-than-safe Republican politics, proposing an increase in
military spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post wrote that the White House had been
reluctant to commit to new defense dollars, because it wanted to
use the new federal budget surplus to fund ``various high priority
domestic programs. But the forceful and increasingly public case
being made by the Pentagon appears to have compelled Clinton to
signal his backing for more defense resources.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon will get billions to drop more bombs. Meanwhile,
Kean has declared that if the Clinton race initiative is ``dropped
here, then I think we've wasted our time.'' Deflated, distracted,
and disinterested from fighting Republicans on major domestic
issues, few dare suggest that Clinton will now do anything on
economics, education, and race except waste our time with rhetoric
and drop the ball when it counts. It is hard for Clinton to hold
America in his hands and get to his bully pulpit while hobbling on
his crutches.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
