<SLUG> BC-BBA-SABERHAGEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABERHAGEN SHOLDERS A FULL LOAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bret Saberhagen isn't merely the obvious pick as this
year's Comeback Player of the Year in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He's the poster child for comeback players of any year, in any
sport.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the evidence, starting with the injury the Red Sox
pitcher came back from. Or, more precisely, the injuries. He'd torn
the sheath of ligament that helped hold the ball in his shoulder
socket. He'd also torn his rotator cuff, the collection of tendons
that maintained the necessary separation between the ball and the
socket.
</P>
<P>
   Either injury alone would have posed a huge challenge; coming
together, they spelled an almost certain end to his career, as well
as his use of the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   To understand what the ligaments in Saberhagen's shoulder looked
like back then, imagine ripping a tablecloth in half. Then imagine
the two halves clinging to a sticky table to the point where they
have to be peeled free, further fraying the edges. Now envision
trying to stitch together the shredded halves so precisely that no
one can tell they've been torn.
</P>
<P>
   That's the challenge Saberhagen's surgeons faced two years ago.
It was partly that the initial injuries were ``incredibly
serious,'' recalls David Altchek, the New York Mets team doctor who
performed the operation. Even worse, he adds, Saberhagen ``was
playing for a team (the Colorado Rockies) who didn't want him to
have open surgery. He waited a considerable period and it made his
injury considerably worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Altchek peeled the ligaments away from surrounding muscles, cut
away the scar tissue, and sewed the ligaments back together. He
also installed in the bone a harpoon-like anchor with sutures
attached to it to repair the torn rotator cuff. And he did it all
without damaging any nearby muscles or tendons, and with the
shredded pieces fitting together precisely enough that Saberhagen
at least had a chance to resume the rotational motion necessary for
pitching.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark for difficult shoulder operations used to be San
Francisco Giants righthander Orel Hershiser, the first pitcher to
come back from major reconstructive surgery. But doctors familiar
with Hershiser's injuries and Saberhagen's say the Sox pitcher's
woes were substantially worse.
</P>
<P>
   What goes on on the operating table, however, merely laid the
foundation for Saberhagen's comeback. As anyone who has undergone
an orthopedic procedure knows, it's the rehabilitation that matters
even more, and that tests a patient's will.
</P>
<P>
   To an extent, I have an idea what Saberhagen has gone through.
Because of the wear and tear of running six marathons and dozens of
short races, I've undergone three arthroscopic procedures plus a
full cartilage transplant operation on my knee. It has meant an
arduous recovery just to regain adequate mobility. And I do not
make my living as an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   In Saberhagen's case, that rehab lasted 18 months and assumed
Sysyphian proportions. He started every day with hot packs and
massages to get his blood flowing. Then there was an hour of
shoulder exercises, followed by running, lifting leg weights, and
doing other workouts to keep the rest of his body toned. Afternoons
brought more shoulder and other exercises designed to restore the
flexibility he'd lost, along with the strength. He generally was
the first player at the ballpark in the morning and one of the last
to leave at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few other players have come back and made a considerable
effort and done well. But none who have been away from the game as
long as he'd been away,'' says longtime Sox physician Arthur
Pappas. ``He barely pitched last year; the year before, he
basically didn't pitch; and the year before that was a spotty year.
He had between two and three years of not pitching or not pitching
effectively, which is a a tremendous amount of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of anyone who's been away that long and come back
and done as well as he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Altchek was equally impressed: ``Most people would be too
discouraged to go through this. He just did it because he loves the
game. That's the greatest statement about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen's injuries were imposing. His surgery was inspired.
And his rehab was awesome. But there's one last critical element to
comebacks as defined by the Major League Baseball Players
Association, whose members last season began picking a Comeback
Player of the Year for each league: The winner not only must
rebound from injury or adversity, he also has to ``achieve
excellence on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   That should cinch the award for the 34-year-old Saberhagen. He
has won 15 games and lost just seven this season, the second-best
winning percentage (.682) among Sox starters. He struck out three
batters for every one he walked, allowed fewer home runs and hits
than ace Pedro Martinez, is second in the American League with 1.5
walks per nine innings pitched, and was effective enough that the
Sox recently extended his contract for three years, with an option
for a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   He's still a long way from the form he showed in 1985, when he
was the youngest player to win the World Series MVP Award, or four
years later, when he went 23-6, compiled a 2.16 ERA, and won his
second Cy Young Award. But nearly every trip to the mound this
season has inspired his team and delighted his doctors _ more so
when, between innings, he would remove his shirt so the trainer
could apply a salve and give him a quick rubdown.
</P>
<P>
   And while lots of Sox fans have held their breath every time
Saberhagen took the mound, wondering whether that was the night his
arm would fall apart, he improved over time, requiring less time to
loosen up and get his velocity up over 90 miles per hour. The
dreaded fade never happened, and he remains a criticial part of the
starting trio upon whom the Sox are pinning their postseason hopes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
