u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV2     09-25 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSING FLASHING MAY FIX A LEAK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 27, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have a leak in the roof by the chimney. I think the
flashing is leaking. I checked the attic and I can see a line of
daylight, near the chimney. How can I close that gap?
</P>
<P>
   ANONYMOUS CALLER
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Sometimes you can see daylight through flashing because it
sits on top of the roof shingles, unsecured, and may bend up a
little. Naturally, it is better if the flashing were touching the
shingles, glued with roofing cement. And that is what you could do:
Buy roofing cement _ it comes in cans and in caulking cartridges _
and slather some between flashing and roof, and hold the flashing
down or put weights on it so it will stay down. Or nail the
flashing with roofing nails, and dab a bit of cement over each nail
head. Roofers might be shocked at face-nailing flashing (with the
nail heads showing), but it is often done, with a dab of cement on
the nail heads, and nearly as often works.
</P>
<P>
   It may work for you. It worked for one flashing dabber, who
thanked the handyman for his sage advice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I like the idea of mulching my leaves. How long will it take
for leaves to break down into compost?
</P>
<P>
   SUSAN REED, Wellesley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If you shred the leaves (and other organic matter such as
grass), the breakdown will take six months to a year. Unshredded,
two years and longer, because unshredded leaves tend to lie flat
and compact on each other. Being flat, they might also smother
anything under them that might try to poke through in spring.
</P>
<P>
   If you shredded your leaves and put them two or three inches
thick on garden beds this fall, they will be virtually invisible by
spring, but still provide considerable nourishment, allowing all
those perennials to come up swinging.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am stripping my front door, which is exposed to the
weather. I used Citristrip, and sanded to the bare wood, but it is
discolored. I would like to stain it, but is there a way to reduce
those discolorations?
</P>
<P>
   MARK PELOSKI, Arlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Treat the bare wood, the entire door, with liquid chlorine
bleach, straight from the jug. After it dries, do it again. Rinse
thoroughly and let dry. This will reduce the discolorations as much
as anything will. Wear skin and eye protection when working with
bleach.
</P>
<P>
   Then apply a stain and two to three coats of an exterior,
oil-based, high-gloss polyurethane varnish. Or use spar varnish or
marine varnish. Because the door is exposed to the weather, don't
expect long service from the varnish; three to five years is a
guesstimate.
</P>
<P>
   Or instead of the stain and varnish, apply an oil-based
semitransparent house stain. Choose your color and apply one coat;
two if the first coat is sucked well into the wood. This will last
up to five years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R.W. of Needham, Mass. called to tell us where he found some
concrete stain. ``I originally used Benjamin Moore concrete stain,
and it worked pretty well, but it has been discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I found a new concrete stain made by a company called H&AMP;C,
at Babel's in Needham. It comes in lots of colors, too. It is a
silicone acrylic with Shield Plus.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, thanks, R.W., for the information, which we will dutifully
file for further reference. And incidentally, Muralo makes a
concrete stain that comes in several, not lots of, colors. We
discovered it on a visit to Factory Paint Store in Weymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Why all the fuss over a concrete stain? Because, unlike paint,
it will not peel, which is one of the big bugaboos about painting
concrete, especially flat, walked-on surfaces. The stain will not
peel, at least is not supposed to. The handyman has received no
complaints of any concrete stain peeling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have some quarry tile on my kitchen and entry floor, and
it's the worst thing I have had in my life. The tile is stained,
and the grout is many different colors. I sanded the grout to
reveal fresh material, then sealed it. Can I paint it? There is
something on the tiles themselves, but I don't know what. Is there
a way to make the tile a little more resistant to stains?
</P>
<P>
   EILEEN RUDY, Holliston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I would not suggest painting grout, but there are two things
you can try tht might be just as good or better. A tile colorer and
sealer called Grout Colorant, sold in tile stores. The other is to
use a semitransparent stain, like the stain used on house
exteriors. This stain is not designed for concrete, masonry or
grout, but is worth trying. Colors are limited.
</P>
<P>
   As for the tiles themselves, no one knows what's on there now,
so it would be risky to apply anything else, which could make it
worse.
</P>
<P>
   If you can get everything off the tiles by rubbing with steel
wool and paint thinner, then you can try Future, an acrylic finish
designed for linoleum, but it can work also on quarry tiles. No
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
