<HEADLINE>
NET MARKETER IXL BUYS INTO BOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: iXL is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing on a buying spree in a rapidly consolidating
industry, a leading Internet marketing company has established a
presence in Boston by acquiring Larry Miller Productions of
Charlestown and Spinners Inc. of Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   The two small firms said Thursday they were bought by iXL
Holdings Inc., an Atlanta firm that has merged the two companies
into an operation that will now be known as iXL's Boston office.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the acquisitions were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   To a lay person, iXL might qualify as an on-line ad agency,
``but they'll get all sour at you if you call them that,'' says
Marc Johnson, an on-line advertising analyst at Jupiter
Communications, a New York market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``A provider of Internet marketing solutions'' is sometimes how
such companies like to be described, Johnson says.
</P>
<P>
   In Larry Miller and Spinners, iXL gets two companies that
together can build both the creative ``front end'' of a Web site as
well as a Web site's technical ``back end.''
</P>
<P>
   On the front end, Larry Miller has provided such high-tech
clients as Hewlett-Packard Co. with the creative expertise they
need to graphically design Web sites for electronic commerce and
other on-line marketing projects.
</P>
<P>
   On the back end, Spinners has been devoted to building intranets
_ internal networks based on Internet protocols _ and highly
sophisticated, interactive Web sites for such financial services
companies as Merrill Lynch and Brown &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spinners has the technology, and Larry Miller has the
creative,'' says Larry Miller president Jeff Janer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is blend the right combination of
creative and technical skills so we can provide strategic Internet
services for major corporations in such industries as health care,
financial services, media and entertainment, travel,
telecommunications, and retail,'' says iXL founder Bert Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Growing mostly by acquisitions, iXL has bought similar companies
in such cities as New York, Denver, San Francisco, and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   IXL is hardly alone on its acquisition spree.
</P>
<P>
   ```Bigger is better' is the recurring theme in this industry,''
says analyst Johnson, who adds, ``If you're a 25-person firm and
you tell Fidelity Investments, `We want to design your Web site,'
they'll just laugh at you.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent survey by Adweek magazine, privately held
iXL had estimated annual revenues of $60 million, tying it with a
New York company known as Agency.com for first place among the
nation's top 50 agencies in the field.
</P>
<P>
   As the frontiers of this business expand rapidly, small firms
such as Spinners are in danger of being rolled over by rivals that
are part of huge communications conglomerates such as Omnicom Inc.
or the Interpublic Group of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The needs of clients are growing so rapidly that they can
quickly outgrow us,'' says president Niraj Shah of Spinners, a
company with 1997 revenues of about $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   By agreeing to be absorbed by iXL's national network, Spinners
now has access to the resources to work on $5 million assignments
from big clients, ``instead of getting $200,000 projects from
midsize companies,'' Shah says.
</P>
<P>
   With 1997 revenues of about $5 million, Larry Miller faced
similar challenges, says Janer, adding, ``We're too big to be small
and too small to be big.''
</P>
<P>
   If the acquisition gives Spinners and Larry Miller much needed
size and access to more resources, it gives iXL a list of local
clients as it seeks to gain a Boston presence.
</P>
<P>
   iXL was founded two years by Ellis after he sold off a regional
media empire he had put together by buying up a string of local TV
stations.
</P>
<P>
   Now Ellis seems to be applying a similar strategy to buying up
small Internet marketing companies, Johnson says. Until the stock
market's &UR;  &LR; recent mood swings, there had been talk of iXL exploring
an initial public offering of its stock.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Shah and Janer's two companies will consolidate
office space at Spinners' headquarters in Cambridge. Shah holds the
title of president of iXL's Boston office, and Janer is executive
vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Spinners and Larry Miller employ 70 staffers; no
layoffs will result from the merger, Shah and Janer say.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed at Internet marketing, three things are needed:
technical know-how, expertise in Web-site graphics, and an
understanding of how to develop an on-line maketing strategy, Janer
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``What iXL is trying to do is put together a three-legged stool
of technology, creative design, and strategy in a way that we can
offer one-stop shopping to large clients,'' he says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
