<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RONIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RONIN' PLAYS LIKE DEATH WARMED OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
RONIN 
Directed by: John Frankenheimer 
Screenplay by: J.D. Zeik &AMP; Richard Weisz 
Starring: Robert De Niro, Jean Reno, Natascha McElhone, Stellan
Skarsgard, Sean Bean, Skipp Sudduth, Michael Lonsdale, Jan Triska 
Running time: 121 minutes 
Rated: R (strong violence and some language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was Alfred Hitchcock who coined the term ``McGuffin'' for the
object that set a chase movie in motion. It didn't matter what the
object was. ``Ronin'' is a classic McGuffin movie. Its gang of
good-guy mercenaries chases all over France to snatch a briefcase
that contains the key to the Irish peace process. What's in the
briefcase nobody is told _ not us, not the ad hoc bunch of heavy
hitters consisting of Robert De Niro, Jean Reno, Stellan Skarsgard,
Sean Bean and Skip Sudduth. That, however, doesn't stop them from
being willing to die to get it. They are the ronin of the title _
Japanese for samurai disgraced because they allowed their master to
die while they live.
</P>
<P>
   We're not told what these ronin did to be demoted from samurai
status. We're asked to accept that they're willing to face death _
and dish it out _ from a sense of professionalism. The post-Cold
War landscape being what it is, there's no morality or ideology
attached to their eforts, only money. You sign the contract, you do
the job, no matter what. It doesn't make for the most compelling
plot motor and all the skill in the direction of the chase scenes,
shoot-outs and set pieces can't conceal a fundamental hollowness
here. Action, after all, can't impart meaning to action, and the
veneer of rueful world-weariness _ and world-wariness _ stretched
across the faces of the actors can't supply the urgency we're
hoping for, either.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, this means that we ironically fall back on studying
the professionalism that has gone into this movie about
professionalism. There's even a certain comfort in John
Frankenheimer's slightly retro take on the hugger-mugger, and in
Robert De Niro's containment as the taciturn star of the team. Even
when he isn't fully immersed in a film (the potential for immersion
is decidedly limited here), De Niro can be depended upon to make
interesting choices. Here he makes carefulness the salient
characteristic of his veteran of the killing fields, a logical
choice when you think of it, that pays dividends.
</P>
<P>
   There's no real bang-up climax. There wouldn't be, given the
burn-out factor in the genre and in these particular characters,
ashen and disillusioned, staring old age in the face. The film
might have meant more if they hadn't been so opaque, if there had
been a bit more back story to go with them. As it is, they're
ciphers, generic technicians of death who are allotted only the
most perfunctory human faceting (Reno is the warm, comradely one,
Skarsgard is the cold, isolated one, etc.). ``Ronin'' goes through
the motions proficiently, but is unable to avoid seeming warmed
over and, for all its skill in execution, awfully ordinary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4516 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-KIDS-BOS &LR;      09-25 1654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS TV MOVES UP A GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the jungles of the Amazon to the battlefields of the Civil
War, from Greek mythology to the secret world of a toy shop,
there's no shortage of adventure in the fall children's television
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there. What is striking, though, is that there is
also no shortage of quality in the new shows for kids _ which is
not to say there's a surplus, either. As always, it's an eclectic
menu, featuring both nourishing fare and junk food.
</P>
<P>
   But there are encouraging signs aplenty as a new season dawns:
more prominent roles for girl characters, a flood of programs based
on children's books (as the search for the next ``Arthur''
continues), subject matter that ranges from intergenerational
relationships to the teaching of history.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many of the new and returning programs for children
have nothing more on their minds than whizbang cartoon antics. A
surprising number, though, demonstrate originality and ingenuity in
the way their characters resolve dilemmas, learn life lessons, or
just have fun.
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon, the top-rated cable channel among children, is
likely to make further inroads with an irresistible new show, ``The
Wild Thornberrys,'' along with the less impressive but potentially
audience-pleasing ``Animorphs'' and ``Cousin Skeeter.'' PBS adds to
its already strong children's lineup with a quiet charmer called
``Noddy,'' while there is nothing quiet about ``Warner Bros.
Histeria!,'' the WB network's rock 'em, sock 'em cartoon version of
history.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Channel weighs in next week with two new shows aimed
at preschoolers: ``Rolie Polie Olie,'' an inventive romp through
the life of a boy robot in an all-robot world, and ``Out of the
Box,'' which uses songs and crafts to teach young children about
growing up. CBS, which caused a stir when it dumped its entire
Saturday morning children's lineup in January because of low
ratings, is rolling out six new animated shows as replacements,
including the endearing ``Franklin,'' based on the books by
Paulette Bourgeois. ABC's only new offering for kids is
``Hercules,'' a spinoff from the 1997 movie, but the ABC children's
show to watch is the witty and winning ``Squigglevision,'' formerly
known as ``Science Court.'' NBC is adding ``One World'' to its
Saturday lineup aimed at teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the new shows on other networks, however, go in the
other direction and target the 3-to-7 age group. Among the best is
the eye-catching, sweet-natured ``Noddy,'' created by Rick
Siggelkow, vice president of BBC Worldwide and one of the forces
behind ``Shining Time Station.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Noddy,'' the set is the star. Adapted from an animated BBC
series and based on the children's books by British author Enid
Blyton, ``Noddy'' takes place in an old-fashioned curiosity shop
that is lavishly and lovingly detailed. It is a place you want to
linger in, conveying the sense of an inanimate world that needs
only a child's imagination to bring it to life.
</P>
<P>
   The shop is owned by a retired sea captain named Noah whose
grandchildren, Kate and Truman, along with their friend, DJ, play
in the shop each day while their parents are at work. Their
creativity kindled by the shop's antique toys and dolls, the
children tell each other stories, which are then enacted in
animated tales featuring Noddy, a wooden toy who drives a
red-and-yellow taxicab.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful process of kids creating their own reality,''
Siggelkow said in an interview. ``Creative play, using your
imagination: These are tools that people need throughout their
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories the children devise often contain lessons about such
issues as acting responsibly. Another goal of ``Noddy,'' Siggelkow
said, is to explore the ``rich area of intergenerational
relationships'' by focusing on the rapport between Noah and the
children. The leader among the children is Kate, which is no
accident, Siggelkow says. ``I felt it was important to have a girl
in the leadership position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noddy'' was slated to be just weekend filler until PBS
stations got a look at how good it is; now, it is scheduled to run
Monday through Friday on more than half the nation's PBS stations.
It premieres MondayM Sept. 28, and will air at 9:30 a.m. each day
and be repeated at at 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the spectrum from ``Noddy,'' but equally
engaging in its own frenetic way, is the WB's ``Histeria!''. The
show's theme song promises to ``make fun of history,'' and it does,
but ``Histeria!'' also manages to pack a surprising amount of
historic dates and details into its hijinks.
</P>
<P>
   We see Abraham Lincoln delivering the Gettysburg Address,
intoning ``Four score and seven years ago...'', only to be
interrupted by a noisy brat who screeches: ``What is it, some kind
of new math? ... Why not just say 87 years ago?'' But the essence
of Lincoln's address is eventually communicated, along with other
information about the Civil War. In another episode, 10th-century
Vikings burst into jovial-but-instructive song: ``We were always on
surprise attacks, which people found alarming. But when we weren't
sacking things we were really good at farming.''
</P>
<P>
   The pace of ``Histeria!'' is relentless, but as Tom Ruegger,
executive producer of Warner Bros. Television Animation, said in an
interview: ``We're covering 35,000 years of human history in 65
half-hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruegger said the show was inspired by episodes of
``Animaniacs,'' another WB cartoon show, in which such historical
eminences as Einstein and Michelangelo made appearances. Leonardo
Da Vinci will ``host'' an upcoming ``Histeria!'' on the
Renaissance; cartoon versions of Napoleon, Joan of Arc and Genghis
Khan will also be featured.
</P>
<P>
   The WB network is also launching two other new programs this
fall: ``Steven Spielberg presents Pinky, Elmyra and the Brain'' and
``Brats of the Lost Nebula.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Loesch, head of Jim Henson Productions, which created
``Brats of the Lost Nebula,'' says the show's three-dimensional
puppets are a ``technical breakthrough.'' In dramatizing the
exploits of five teenagers who wander the universe after they are
separated from their parents, ``Brats'' imparts an upbeat message
of ``resourcefulness and teamwork,'' according to Loesch,
</P>
<P>
   My personal favorite among the new children's shows is
Nickelodeon's ``The Wild Thornberrys'' (Tuesdays and Thursdays at 8
p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   Produced by the creators of ``Rugrats,'' ``The Wild
Thornberrys'' is loaded with visual and verbal wit. This animated
show features a 12-year-old girl named Eliza (voiced by Lacey
Chabert of ``Party of Five'') who is a red-haired, freckle-faced,
braces-wearing ball of fire.
</P>
<P>
   Eliza is endowed with the gift of communicating with wild
animals, and she's always eager to explore the natural world by
striking up conversations with, say, lions. There's wildlife
aplenty since Eliza's parents (including a delightfully dim dad
voiced by Tim Curry) are on perpetual safari in order to make
nature documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   Her beleaguered sidekick is a thoroughly domesticated chimpanzee
named Darwin (reminiscent of the finicky talking chimp voiced by
John Cleese in ``George of the Jungle'') who wishes his human chum
was less intrepid, less eager to mingle with ... animals.
</P>
<P>
   ```Oooh, Darwin, there's a cliff; let's go climb it,' '' he
mimics her. `` `There's a lion; let's go see if it's hungry.' Can't
we just sit around for once?''
</P>
<P>
   Nickelodeon's other two new prime-time offerings for kids are
``Animorphs'' and ``Cousin Skeeter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cousin Skeeter'' (Tuesdays and Thursdays at 8:30 p.m.)
features a fast-talking, hip-hop puppet (voiced by Bill Bellamy)
who moves in with his shy cousin and begins wreaking havoc. With
its African-American cast, ``Cousin Skeeter'' has the chance to
break some ground, but only if it moves away from predictable
moves. Right now, the only original element is the sight of the
puppet interacting with humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animorphs'' (Fridays at 8:30 p.m., Saturdays at 9:30 p.m.) is
based on the popular books by K.A. Appelgate. It revolves around
five teenagers whose mission is to save the world from an invasion
by alien ``Controllers.'' Luckily, they have the power to transform
themselves into any animal they want by touching them and
``acquiring their DNA.''
</P>
<P>
   With its paranoid outlook and lines like ``Trust no one,''
``Animorphs'' may become an ``X-Files'' for kids, and there's no
denying the arresting power of the special effects when the teens
morph into animals. But the plotting and characterizations are
strictly paint-by-numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for NBC's ``One World'' (Saturdays at 1 p.m.). This series
about a multiethnic group of orphans adopted by a pro baseball
player and his sculptor wife seldom rises above standard sitcom
level.
</P>
<P>
   The only new CBS series available for review was ``Franklin,''
and it's a winner. You can spot the moral a mile away in these
gentle animated parables involving a young tortoise and his
friends, but who cares? The pace and themes _ loyalty,
individuality, growing up too fast, learning to play with kids
whose interests are different from yours _ are just right for very
young children. ``Franklin'' will air at 7 a.m. Sundays once it
premieres on Oct. 3, along with ``Anatole,'' ``Flying Rhino Junior
High,'' and ``Birdz.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a mixed bag at Fox this fall. The network's live-action
``Young Hercules'' (Monday through Thursday at 4:30 p.m.) displays
a wry sense of humor and well-choreographed action scenes that make
it highly watchable. But Fox's ``Mystic Knights of the Tir Na Nog''
(Monday to Thursday at 4 p.m.), an adventure series set in Ireland
and involving quests and journeys and a lot of medieval
blah-blah-blah, features five of the most charmless heroes since
``Power Rangers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
