</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MONUMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARY SHINES ON `MONUMENT' MEAN STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
MONUMENT AVE. 
Directed by: Ted Demme 
Screenplay by: Mike Armstrong 
Starring: Denis Leary, Ian Hart, Lenny Clarke, Jason Barry, Colm
Meaney, John Diehl, Billy Crudup, Greg Dulli, Noah Emmerich, Martin
Sheen, Famke Janssen, Jeanne Tripplehorn 
Running time: 90 minutes 
Unrated 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Monument Ave.'' is the Irish ``Mean Streets.'' Set in
Charlestown among a bunch of boyos buying into an old system of
street-enforced rot posing as manliness, it's dark, edgy,
provisional-looking and immediate. The look and texture of the film
_ claustrophobic and ripe with corruption _ bespeak a world where
predatory viciousness leaves no room for loyalties, even of the
family kind, as evil is linked to false notions of honor and
manhood.
</P>
<P>
   This translates to Denis Leary's professional car thief, Bobby
O'Grady, simmering helplessly as Colm Meaney's boss thug, Jackie
O'Hara, has Leary's cousin shot to death in a neighborhood bar he
knows will yield no witnesses. Martin Sheen's sputtering cop from
West Roxbury, helpless on a patch of turf where talking to cops is
taboo, can't dent the stonewalling, as Jackie swaggers around in
his camel's-hair coat, buying the drinks, paying the rent for
impoverished grannies in the projects and letting everyone know
about it, while terrorizing everyone into submission with his
hair-trigger temper and galloping paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   Meaney's sadistic bully is juicily and scarily performed,
reinvigorating a type extinct since Cagney. But it's Leary who
gives the film its moral center in the most complex role of his
deservedly snowballing career. The conflict between Bobby's pain
and shame eat at him and push him. They're written on a face that
knows better than to reveal softer impulses that would be perceived
as weakness, with lethal consequences. When in the space of a
single year you can triangulate performances like the ones Leary
has delivered in ``Suicide Kings,'' ``Love Walked In,'' and now
``Monument Ave.,'' you are looking at the emergence of a figure who
has to be taken seriously as an actor.
</P>
<P>
   The film's brutal, episodic flavor also accommodates Bobby's
struggle to confront a code he had been proud to be thought part of
all his life. At one point, his rage is expressed in an incident of
vicious racism. But he's just as convincing in a woozily
atmospheric scene where he and his buddies have come to rest in his
living room after a night of drinking, egging each other on with
what even in their drunkenness they realize are hopelessly
unattainable sex fantasies involving movie stars. When sober, they
work off some aggressions playing playground hockey, the ones left
over from their pedal-to-the-metal nights.
</P>
<P>
   Director Ted Demme meshes Bobby's restless character into the
film's jagged rhythms and heads-up ensemble performance. Ian Hart
and Billy Crudup shine as his lifelong cronies. So do Jason Barry
as his Irish cousin whose sanity and decency are offended; Famke
Janssen as a full-blooded neighborhood woman smart enough to worry
about the future; and especially Marilyn Murphy Meardon as Bobby's
agonized mother banking on her moral authority when the killing
becomes too much. There's no melodrama, no sentimentalizing, just a
long, hard look at a life-sdestroying situation, inscribed in
gritty, jolting verite style. ``Monument Ave.'' is a long night's
journey into what its protagonist can only hope is day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
