<HEADLINE>
WATER'S DISARMING `PECKER' EMBRACES SWEETNESS, CAMPY EXCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
PECKER 
Written and directed by: John Waters 
Starring: Edward Furlong, Christina Ricci, Mary Kay Place, Brendan
Sexton III, Lili Taylor, Jean Schertler, Martha Plimpton 
Running time: 87 minutes 
Rated: R (sexuality, graphic nudity, language , and brief drug
use) 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Pecker,'' the latest John Waters comedy, the amiability
that has always been a part of his work moves to the forefront and
becomes the main event, reminding us that the once-trademark
impulse to outrage has receded in the older, mellower Waters.
Nominally, ``Pecker'' is the story of a Baltimore boy from a
blue-collar neighborhood who becomes an overnight celebrity
photographer. Jaded New York gallery sycophants gravitate to his
photos of friends and neighbors because they crave a fix of the
authenticity that no longer comes naturally to them. The joke, of
course, is that once the boy wonder (Edward Furlong, in a
disarmingly spacy performance) goes to New York, his celebrity
status threatens to cut him off from the world from which he draws
his naive vitality.
</P>
<P>
   Let's get that red-herring nickname out of the way. He's called
Pecker because ever since he was a boy he pecked at his food.
Blown-up photos of genitalia and rats having sex are about as
taboo-pushing as ``Pecker'' gets. The film doesn't even mean to set
up any stinging collision between blue-collar Baltimore and arty
Manhattan. Rather, it suggests a party to which Waters has invited
both camps, perhaps motivated by the fact that he has taken up
photography in recent years and now lives part time in New York.
Perhaps ``Pecker'' represents Waters trying to integrate the two
halves of the bifurcated life he now leads. But the film's
celebration of eccentric openness and campy excess leaves no doubt
that Waters's heart remains in his native Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The impression left by ``Pecker'' has little to do with its
perfunctory gestures at story or huffings at irony. It adds little
to our disregard for celebrity culture, and its surprises are few,
especially to Waters aficionados. It's not satire, it's a series of
postcards from a thrift shop, the Bargai Hut, run by Pecker's mom
(Mary Kay Place, at her most grimacingly hospitable, especially
when she's pushing her full line of plastic garments), and from
such comfortably run-down dives as the Claw Machine and the Pelt
Room, to say nothing of the laundromat run by Christina Ricci's
softhearted drill sergeant in love with Pecker. Waters obviously
had such fun conceiving and dressing these settings that it seems
curmudgeonly to demand that anything much be going on in them.
Besides, the film is an embrace of littleness. It's certainly no
chore to sit through. But who ever thought to find oneself reaching
for words like ``sweet'' and ``mild'' to describe a John Waters
film?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4530 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SOLDIER-BOS &LR;      09-25 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SOLDIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCHANT-IVORY KEEP UP WITH THE JONESES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
A SOLDIER'S DAUGHTER NEVER CRIES 
Directed by: James Ivory 
Screenplay by: Ruth Prawer Jhabvala (novel: Kaylie Jones) 
Starring: Kris Kristofferson, Barbara Hershey, Leelee Sobieski,
Jane Birkin, Dominique Blanc, Jessae Bradford, Anthony Roth
Costanzo, Harley Cross, Isaac de Bankole, Virginie Ledoyen 
Running time: 127 minutes 
Rated: R (language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries'' gives Kris Kristofferson
the role of his career as a world-class novelist and world-class
father. It's also a rich, moving and altogether satisfying return
to form for the Merchant-Ivory team _ and a new direction, too. In
filming Kaylie Jones' autobiographical novel about growing up as
the daughter of expatriate novelist James Jones in the 1960s and
'70s, Merchant-Ivory forego their usual sheen and control and take
their stylistic cue from the unruliness that goes with the process
of keeping up with the Joneses.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tempestuous household, but a loving one, first as
transplanted Americans in Paris, then after moving abruptly back to
the US as Jones (called Billy Willis in the film) comes to grips
with heart trouble. The heart trouble, in refreshing contrast to
the family dysfunction that has become a screen fixture, is
mechanical, not emotional. Plenty of eventfulness swirls around the
family, but the core of the film is the loving father-daughter
relationship between Kristofferson's Willis and his daughter,
Channe, played by Luisa Conlon as a child and Leelee Sobieski as an
adolescent.
</P>
<P>
   Although he spent many of his waking hours immersed in reliving
his experiences as a GI fighting in the Pacific in World War II
(Terence Malick's film of Jones' novel, ``The Thin Red Line,'' is
due at Christmas), his sympathy for what his kids are going
through, and his wisdom in helping them get past it, cap
Kristofferon's re-emergence as an actor able to project vast depths
of experience, emotional solidity, generosity, crinkly-eyed humor
and a genius for never leaning too hard on his kids, who touchingly
grow closer together during the family's time of trial.
</P>
<P>
   Without ever lapsiong into banal sentimentality, Ruth Prawer
Jhabvala's script embraces all the characters in the film's loose
three-part structure. The first is named Benoit, for the French boy
they adopt. He blossoms under the emotional security he finds for
the first time, although it takes him quite a while before he feels
safe enough to unpack the suitcase he kept ready for a possible
return to the orphanage. Later, as played with winning
vulnerability by Jesse Bradford, he adopts his adoptive father's
name, Billy, feeling a full-fledged member of the family, although
his equilibrium is shaken when he receives a sympathetic
communication from his natural mother.
</P>
<P>
   The film's second part is called Francis, after a precocious
misfit Channe befriends at school in Paris, and with whom she
develops an outsider's complicity. The final act, Daddy, is
touchingly played out in the '70s, back in the states when Channe
finds adapting to new circumstances tougher than ever in the Long
Island suburb they move to, but is bolstered emotionally by her
father until she rights herself. Almost as a throwaway,
Kristofferson conveys a nobility of the heart in concealing from
his daughter the difficulties he's facing in marshalling his
remaining strength to try and beat the clock and complete his last
problematic novel.
</P>
<P>
   Sobieski makes a really strong impression in what has to be
regarded as her breakthrough role, conveying Channe's purity,
fragility and distress. Barbara Hershey shines as the family's
poker-playing earth mother, reminding us what she can do with
richly-textured material, although the scene most people will
probably remember most strongly comes when she confronts in lioness
style her son's power-tripping teacher in Paris. And you're not
likely to soon forget Kristofferson's low-key but high-profile
patriarch. This family glories in its eccentricity, but it's their
turning to one another in crisis that will get to you most. The
chronicle of this family is more than a little messy around the
edges, and the film is right to follow suit stylistically because
it's there with the goods when it counts. It's one of the most
affectingly acted, unabashedly loving films you'll see this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1347EDT &QL; 
