<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFFALO TOM GROWS BEYOND ITS WILD SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Eleven years is not an eternity for most careers, but it is
for a rock 'n' roll band. For the Boston-based Buffalo Tom, the
shock is just setting in, but so is the pride that the group has
gotten this far without ending up on the alt-rock scrap heap like
many of its peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day you're the next big thing, the next day you're
veterans and all your friends are having children,'' says Buffalo
Tom singer-guitarist Bill Janovitz. ``But the idea is that you can
grow older in rock 'n' roll and deal with different issues, though
the essential elements for us are still there. We still deal with
the quieter moments of relationships, the darker side of normality,
and the `Blue Velvet' side of growing up in suburbia.''
</P>
<P>
   They deal with them all in the alluring ``Smitten,'' the sixth
album by Buffalo Tom, which comes out Tuesday. The new disc shows a
deeper, more thoughtful, but still rocking, Buffalo Tom. Janovitz
and bandmates Chris Colbourn (bass-vocals) and drummer Tom Maginnis
(drums) were joined by keyboardist Phil Aiken, whose influence is
apparent in the heightened melodic sense that shows how far the
group has come from its early days as a thrashy, Husker Du-styled
guitar trio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always a pop band at heart,'' says Janovitz, ``but we
obscured that with big noisy guitars and sometimes bad production.
... We used to layer on five guitars, then layer them out to three
and maybe add keyboards as an afterthought. But this time we made a
pre-assumpton that keyboards would be there from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   The songs, which began to get hatched during a long weekend on
Chappaquiddick island two years ago, range from the pretty,
acoustic-flavored ``Under Milkwood,'' to the electric riff-rock of
``Walking Wounded.'' But the surprise is the increased role of
Colbourn, who eases the pressure on Janovitz by singing lead on
several tracks, including the first single, the XTC-meets-Squeeze
number, ``Rachael.''
</P>
<P>
   The increased democracy of the band was inevitable, says
Janovitz. ``You've got to put aside your ego for the band. For the
first time, I won't be singing the single, but hopefully it will be
our biggest to date.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Tom has a great attitude about coming this far. ``We've
always done okay, even though we haven't hit the lottery,'' he
says. ``But we've had our taste of mainstream success. There's
something great about going to Sydney, Australia and playing for
1,000 people singing along to every lyric. Or to Stockholm and
having people do the same. Sometimes you can't ask for much more
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in limbo: A song associated with reggae pioneer Jimmy
Cliff is ``Sitting in Limbo,'' which, unfortunately, is the state
he's in these days in his dual careers in music and film. His new
album, ``Journey of a Lifetime,'' is only being released overseas,
not here. His stateside record label, Island/PolyGram, wants to put
out a ``Best of Jimmy Cliff'' instead, he says. ``I'm stuck in
limbo right now, but I'll step out,'' he adds during a recent chat
from his Jamaican home.
</P>
<P>
   The import-only ``Journey of a Lifetime'' disc is ``a
philosophical album, but rooted in reality,'' says Cliff. ``All the
songs are a journey.'' One of them, ``Super Bad,'' comes from his
upbringing in a Jamaican ghetto. ``I saw many of my friends die
(there). '' Another one, ``Daddy,'' is ``about our lives as
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   As you might expect, Cliff isn't thrilled that the album lacks
an American release date. ``If it's advertised to the people,
they'll go get it,'' he says confidently. ``Fortunately, I can go
to the rest of the planet, but America is 32 percent of the world's
music market, so it's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff, also known as Dr. Cliff after receiving an honorary
doctorate from the University of the West Indies last year, is
still trying to mount a sequel to the award-winning reggae film,
``The Harder They Come,'' in which he acted and sang such classics
as ``You Can Get It If You Really Want,'' ``Many Rivers to Cross,''
and ``Wonderful World, Beautiful People.'' Cliff has worked up a
synopsis for a sequel, but says the people he shows it to just want
to take it for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that hasn't changed is Cliff's role as reggae
ambassador. He was the first reggae act, even before Bob Marley, to
tour Africa. He plans to play in Nigeria for six weeks this fall,
and hopes to go to China soon. ``I think they would like my music
over there,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Cliff is a long way from retirement. ``I don't enjoy
doing anything else as much as this,'' he says. ``When I evaluate
my life, I'm here to be an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bits and pieces: Tommy McGann, 43, who died in a car accident
Wednesday in Ireland, was the owner of the Irish Embassy Pub and
McGann's in the North Station area of Boston, plus another McGann's
in Falmouth, Mass. It's a devastating loss because a classier pub
owner simply did not exist. He also was in the forefront of the
Irish pub renaissance and even just brought in Sinead O'Connor to
sing at the McGann's in Boston. He was a sweet man who ran a sweet
operation ... Paul McCartney will tour next year to benefit
vegeterian and animal rights causes. Chrissie Hynde will open the
shows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1348EDT &QL; 
