<HEADLINE>
`BUDDY' ADDS HUMOR, STYLE TO THE PI GENRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
BUDDY FARO 
Starring: Dennis Farina, Frank Whalley, Allison Smith 
On: CBS 
Time: Friday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes fast friends turn to enemies just as quickly. And so
the kooky, kicky premiere of Dennis Farina's ``Buddy Faro'' should
be approached warily, and with a healthy sense that few TV series
could ever live up to such a giddy and stylish introduction. We can
only pray to the gods of prime time that ``Buddy Faro'' doesn't
pull a Mr. Hyde next week and turn into ``Dellaventura,'' last
season's smarmy Danny Aiello crime vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The premiere is a wonderfully snazzy and light-hearted hour,
with enough cinematic flair to make it feel like a little
theatrical movie. It's the story of the return of Buddy Faro, a
legendary P.I. who dropped out of society 20 years ago and landed
face down in the gutter _ the gutter being along the lanes of a
bowling alley South of the Border. He's a crude Rip Van Winkle with
his long white beard, but beneath the caked dirt is a reservoir of
snappy Rat Pack cool. After Buddy revisits a bathtub and razor,
once he's been retrieved by a younger detective played by Frank
Whalley, he's a natural with a martini in one hand, a cigar in the
other, and Tom Jones blaring ``Delilah'' over the show's lively
soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   While the plot of tonight's premiere isn't complicated, there's
no point in spoiling it with too much information here. And anyway,
the real strengths of ``Buddy Faro'' are in its smart casting and
its rich visual atmospherics. Farina, who fit perfectly in two
Elmore Leonard movies, ``Out of Sight'' and ``Get Shorty,'' is just
right as Buddy. He's easily believable as both the down-and-out
caveman and the slick charmer with a glittery-gowned date on his
arm. He's pure unflappability, and it's a thrill when he looks
directly into the camera and says he feels ``like a hundred
bucks.'' And Frank Whalley is effectively eager as Bob Jones, the
gumshoe who idolizes Buddy, having trained himself according to
Buddy's classic detectiving book, ``I, Private Eye.'' Whalley, who
has been in movies like ``Pulp Fiction'' and ``A Midnight Clear,''
makes his second banana character simultaneously clueless and
intelligent.
</P>
<P>
   The look of ``Buddy Faro'' is an embarrassment of riches. The
shadows swimming over Bob's hands at his computer, the neon glow of
a barroom, mobsters with garish faces, the chandelier sparkle of a
dinner club, an alleyway lit in blue haze _ the show is dense with
these sorts of crafted images. The action may be set in 1998, but
the aura is pure vintage Hollywood. And there's a beautifully
designed sequence that's set in Bob's girlfriend's oppressively
modern, sterile home, where even the silverware may be art. ``She
has a very strong aesthetic,'' Bob tells Buddy, warning him not to
touch anything.
</P>
<P>
   Bob's girlfriend is a hysterical parody, an art-world ghoul
whose pale face and red lipstick put her on a visual scale not far
from the Master of Ceremonies in ``Cabaret.'' Her oddness is a
reminder that Mark Frost from the stranger-than-strange ``Twin
Peaks'' is the driving force behind ``Buddy Faro,'' as writer and
executive producer. Let's hope Frost stays interested in this
project, which will need to keep up its fresh sense of humor in the
manner of ``Maximum Bob,'' the quirky and consistently amusing
summer series. At a time when most of TV's crime shows are steeped
in realism, ``Buddy Faro'' has the opportunity to have a dazzlingly
good old time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
