<HEADLINE>
FAMILY TRAGEDIES HAUNTING COATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ He was arrested during training camp,
charged with assaulting the mother of one of his children, an
allegation that will be addressed at a hearing Tuesday. Not long
after that incident, his aunt died in South Carolina. Then came a
knee problem and double ankle sprains which forced him to sit out
for the first time in his NFL career after 113 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   And last Friday, Ben Coates got word that his older sister, 38,
had died suddenly. He wasn't with the Patriots Monday, missed
Thursday's practice, and not expected for Friday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a tough haul,'' said his agent, Michael George.
``He's really devastated by his sister's death. He's had to be
there for his family. It's been a very tough time for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Long a key part of the Patriots' offense, the All-Pro tight end
has caught only three passes for 24 yards. A year ago at this time,
he'd caught 10 passes. There have been years when he was basically
Drew Bledsoe's only target, but in this spread-the-wealth offense,
that's no longer the case.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe has tried to make Terry Glenn the main man. With Troy
Brown also considered a big-play receiver, Coates has been
relegated to the background.
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, the Patriots even drafted a tight end in the
second round, Alabama's Rod Rutledge, to go along with Lovett
Purnell, who is considered a fine receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Sidelined against Indianapolis in the second game, Coates
returned to action last week against the Tennessee Oilers and was
once again a secondary receiver. The Patriots are off this week and
play at New Orleans Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben can always use the bye week,'' said coach Pete Carroll.
``The way he responded to this ankle, I think he's fine now. We
missed Ben on two chances last week _ once we had him on a corner
route when we couldn't get the ball to him and then we missed him
in the end zone. Ben would have had a big game if we had got the
ball to him. It'll go in cycles where you'll see Ben more active
than he is in other weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   At 29, Coates is still one of the most feared tight ends in the
business. The pounding he's taken over the years hasn't diminished
his desire to play and contribute. When he was hobbling after
twisting his ankle in the opener against Denver, he argued with
Carroll on the sideline in a futile effort to stay in the game.
</P>
<P>
   On any given pass route, Coates is drawing a linebacker and a
strong safety in coverage. His limited speed, caused by the leg
problems, has made it more difficult for him to get open.
</P>
<P>
   But Bledsoe hardly has abandoned him. When in trouble, he will
still fire the ball in the general direction of Coates.
</P>
<P>
   For eight seasons, Coates has been the greatest player New
England never knew. His shunning of the media over the years is
reminiscent of Jim Rice's behavior with the Red Sox. Coates has
trusted less than a handful of reporters, and there have been fewer
stories written about him than about any great athlete in this area
in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Coates doesn't like to be in the spotlight, at least not this
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben's a strong person,'' said George. ``He'll come out of this
fine. Right now it's just a rough period in his life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
