<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COULD PARITY SPOIL THE PARTY AT FIESTA? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forida and Florida State have already lost. Nebraska has won
each week but has not been dazzling. UCLA has also had some shaky
moments. Kansas State remains an unknown because of the lack of
quality opposition.
</P>
<P>
   What we have in college football as October and conference play
approach is parity. There are lots of good teams that can beat each
other on any given Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no great teams.
</P>
<P>
   Well, let's hold up a little bit on that. Ohio State may be
classified as great by the end of the season, but the Buckeyes
still have to face their biggest obstacle, archrival Michigan, and
they trailed against Missouri at halftime last Saturday in
Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   It is plausible that when the matchup for the national
championship game in the Fiesta Bowl Jan. 4 is selected, neither
team will be unbeaten.
</P>
<P>
   Is this good or a nightmare for the people who put together the
Bowl Championship Series?
</P>
<P>
   We say it's good. We say it's great. The more controversy, the
better, and the thought of having to choose from a group of four or
five once-beaten teams for two slots is exactly the kind of turmoil
college football needs to convince the powers that be that the only
sane way to do things is to have a playoff system with eight or 16
teams.
</P>
<P>
   We could have a marquee matchup of unbeatens such as Ohio State
vs. the Kansas State-Nebraska winner or Ohio State vs. UCLA, but if
this season has shown anything, it's that everyone is capable of
losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I could see a situation where you have no unbeaten teams
at the end of the year,'' said Big East commissioner Mike
Tranghese, who hopes Syracuse can run the table and find a way to
sneak into the Fiesta Bowl. ``There's not a whole lot of candidates
out there to go unbeaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent history suggests that the chances of having at least two
unbeaten, untied teams at the end of the regular season are fairly
good. In every year since 1991, we've had at least two unbeaten,
untied teams. In 1992 and '93, there were three.
</P>
<P>
   Form might again take over, but thus far, we think getting just
one unbeaten team will be a major accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Taking a WAC-ing
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are bad road teams and then there is Hawaii. The Rainbows
have lost their last 21 Western Athletic Conference games on the
road, and the last time they won any road game was in 1995 ... Some
people feel Nebraska will have its most severe test of the season
Saturday when it hosts unbeaten Washington, the last team to beat
the Cornhuskers in Lincoln. ``There's still talk that we're not a
proven team and that our win over California wasn't impressive
enough,'' said Nebraska center Josh Heskew. ``I guess we didn't get
enough style points. But Washington is a Top 10 team. They're going
to come to our place fired up.'' ... Here's some encouraging news
for Michigan fans. Although the Wolverines are 1-2 going into
Saturday's game against Michigan State, the last time Michigan
started 0-2 was in 1988, when the Wolverines finished 9-2-1 and
beat Southern Cal in the Rose Bowl ... A virus that hit the Duke
team last week before its game against Florida State has spread to
the Seminoles. At least 10 FSU players, including quarterback Chris
Weinke, came down with the bug and missed practice this week. That
could be good news for Southern Cal, which visits Tallahassee
Saturday ... Tennessee's 20-17 overtime victory over Florida last
week was costly _ literally. Fans did $25,000 worth of damage to
Neyland Stadium when they stormed the field and tore down the
goalposts ... Florida ranks 112th (out of 112) in turnover ratio
after turning the ball over four times against Tennessee. After
three games, the Gators are minus-10. ``I don't know what to do
about it,'' said coach Steve Spurrier. ``We haven't had this
problem until this year.'' ... After beating Houston last week,
UCLA quarterback Cade McNown criticized the Cougars. ``I felt like
they played us dirty with a lot of cheap shots, a lot of going for
the knees on late hits,'' said McNown. The response from Houston
coach Kim Helton: ``I don't think he's accustomed to throwing
laying on his back.'' ... UCLA, which has won a school-record 12
games in a row, rewarded coach Bob Toledo with a two-year contract
extension ... Marshall fans are learning that not all of last
year's success for the Mid-American Conference champion was
attributable to wide receiver Randy Moss. Quarterback Chad
Pennington is proving that he's pretty good as well. Marshall is
unbeaten after three games, including a 24-21 win over South
Carolina last week, and Pennington has thrown eight touchdown
passes. Coach Bob Pruett is 28-3 in two-plus seasons at Marshall,
including a Division 1-AA national championship two years ago and
the MAC title last year in Marshall's first Division 1-A season ...
Count on Alabama being focused for this week's game against
Arkansas. The Hogs have beaten the Tide two of the last three
years, including a 17-16 stunner last season ... Florida is all but
out of the Southeastern Conference race. For the Gators to win,
Tennessee will have to lose at least two conference games ... One
of the surprise teams of the year is Colorado. ``We are an exposed
3-0,'' says coach Rick Neuheisel. ``We have found our faults and
know what we have to work on and know what needs to be corrected.''
... Virginia is 4-0 for the third straight season. Contrast that
with Wisconsin, which, if it beats Northwestern Saturday, will be
4-0 for only the second time in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Drawing Irish ayes
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you are a Notre Dame fan and want a good Christmas read, try
``Talking Irish: The Oral History of Notre Dame Football'' by Steve
Delsohn. It's not the normal rehash of Irish football history but
an account in the words of the participants. Delsohn says he grew
up a college football fan and was fascinated by Notre Dame's
mystique. The only people who refused to be interviewed for the
book were Paul Hornung and Joe Montana ... Dick Farley, who begins
his 12th season as coach at Williams Saturday, is No. 7 on the
all-time winning percentage list with a 73-12-5 (.847) record ...
How's this for justice? In the first football game in Bryant
College history two weeks ago, freshman tailback Clarence Bryant
was the star of the 20-19 win over Dean College, picking up 117
yards on 17 carries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
