<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURNS WORRIES THAT HOLDOUTS ARE WASTING TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Last year Pat Burns had no idea what kind of lineup he
would have for opening night.
</P>
<P>
   Early in training camp, the first-year Bruins coach had a group
of virtual no-names surrounded by a small core of veterans. Burns
figured he'd be in much better shape this time, but with four
unsigned Group 2 free agents sitting at home, including top scorer
Jason Allison, he is scratching his head much the way he did 12
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those guys, I would die to have them in here in camp right
now,'' said Burns, referring to Allison, Anson Carter, and Kyle
McLaren. ``They're missing great opportunities. With the team we
could have, we could develop something here and they could be part
of it. We're talking about two 23-year-olds, a 21-year-old. That's
three of the four guys. (Ted Donato remains out while waiting to be
traded.) These kids have an opportunity to go out and really make a
statement about themselves: `Yeah, I'll go out and work for it.'
You've got to work. I coached a Stanley Cup final my first year and
I was making $80,000. That was 10 years ago and it was Canadian
(money). I was happier than hell. I took the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns dipped his toe into the water a couple of days ago,
expressing frustration at trying to replace Allison in the lineup.
Before that, the coach had been reluctant to comment much on the
free agent situation. Thursday, though, he was expansive in urging
all three youngsters to look at the big picture _ if they continue
to produce, they will get the big money.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to put your time in,'' he said. ``I laugh when I
hear (some) say the Bruins don't want to pay. I know what goes on.
It's not that they don't want to pay. Put your time in, earn your
bananas, and we'll give you the money, but we're not just going to
hand it out to anybody that comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a pretty nice situation for years to come if we get
everybody there. I have to understand Harry (Sinden) and Mike
(O'Connell), too. They're not going to hand it out; you've got to
earn it. We had one good year last year. We didn't have a great
year, we had a good year. Players had good seasons, they didn't
have great seasons. Jason had an above-average season. At this time
of year last year, we didn't know what we were going to do with
him. &UR;  &LR; Finally, it broke through and he's improved a lot of things,
but that's what you have to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he thought Allison was ill advised in taking an
entrenched position, Burns said he thought it was more a matter of
Allison being led astray by comparing himself to other players and
believing he should be making the same salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you start comparing yourself ... I'm happy to have a job
and I'm happy to work,'' said Burns. ``How much did they offer
Jackie Parker, $500,000 for five years? I'm getting $550,000 for
six years. Put it that way. Jackie Parker never coached a game in
the NHL and I've been here 10 years. I don't worry about that
stuff. If you start worrying about the guy over there, if you start
saying, `How come he can have it and I can't have it?' ... I think
Jason, if he gives himself one more year, he's over the hump.
Sometimes you've got to put your ass on the block.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Burns's frustration stems from the fact that both player
and coach worked so hard to improve Allison's game, resulting in a
career year. He doesn't want that progress to stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe he's a one-year wonder,'' said Burns.``If he
comes in in the same frame of mind as he left here last year, he's
going to get all the opportunities he got last year. He's going to
play on every power play. He's our best power-play centerman. Those
things will fall into place for him.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he thought Allison would be the same hungry player
if the Bruins gave in on a big-money, long-term deal, Burns said,
``It's all a question mark. I personally think he probably would.
He says he would.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_____ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither Rob DiMaio nor Tim Taylor skated Thursday. DiMaio took a
nasty hit Wednesday night in Pittsburgh, resulting in back spasms.
His back tightened up Thursday, so he was given the day off.
Taylor's situation is potentially more serious. Burns said it's
possible Taylor is suffering from appendicitis. Doctors are
attempting to treat it with antibiotics rather than surgery ...
Beginning tonight, the Bruins play three exhibition games in as
many nights. They start by taking on Montreal in Providence in a
game in which the teams will experiment by not using the red line.
Then they play back-to-back games against the Florida Panthers,
tomorrow in Greenville, S.C., and Sunday in Sunrise, Fla. Burns has
always been adamantly opposed to removing the red line. ``I don't
have a clue how that game is played,'' said the coach, who
indicated he would go with a strong-skating lineup tonight. ``A lot
of guys don't have a clue how that game is played. I hope they
don't go with it (permanently). I don't think they will.'' ...
Burns had a message for right wing Landon Wilson _ wake up. Wilson
made his presence known Wednesday only when he rifled the puck off
the glass 51 seconds into the first period, shattering a pane,
which resulted in a 17-minute delay. &UR;  &LR; ``He can't play that way,''
said Burns. ``He's a big, strong guy. He has all the tools to be
one of those big power forwards. He has to find a way to get there,
be there, bump the guy, win the battles to the puck. He thinks it's
going to come to him. That's not how it works.'' Burns said it's
players like Wilson who can drive coaches to distraction. ``You
know they could do it. You stress to them when you talk to them
about it. You're hard on them, like Allison last year. The first 20
games, he drove me nuts and I drove him nuts _ until he understood
what he could possibly do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
