<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE, SOSA HOMERUN DERBY ON HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The late, great Ray Fitzgerald, covering the
interminable wait for Carl Yastrzemski's 3,000th hit, once wrote,
``It's lonely out here on the Yaz Watch.''
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty much the same out here on the McGwire-Sosa Watch, or
as Ted Kennedy would say, the ``Mike McGwire-Sammy Soo-ser'' Watch.
</P>
<P>
   No homers for the big guys Thursday. The Cubs, those blood
brothers of the Red Sox, did not play. As for McGwire, he went
homerless (1 for 3 with a walk) in four plate appearances during a
6-3 Cardinal victory over the Montreal Expos at Busch Stadium.
Three games remain and Home Run Derby '98 is deadlocked at a record
65.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine selling out all four games of a final weekend series
when you are 19 1/2 games out of first place, facing the Building
19 Expos. The Cardinals did it, thanks to You Know Who.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Tyler of Aerosmith (better known now as Liv's dad) threw
out the first pitch and it was a strike. Tyler looked like he'd be
OK to start for the Expos and serve up home run No. 66.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals wouldn't mind a little help for their big man.
There's a little sensitivity in these parts about the possibility _
after everything that's happened _ that McGwire might not even get
his name in the major league record book. St. Louis folks are
taking the Sosa challenge personally, and Oliver Stone might be
called in to document a Sosa-Bud Selig conspiracy theory.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it, sports fans. Start with last Sunday's game in
Milwaukee when fan interference and umpiring incompetence denied
McGwire a home run. Second base ump Bob Davidson made the wrong
call and Cardinal fans will never forget. During batting practice
Thurday night, a fan held a sign which read, ``Denkinger and
Davidson _ Separated At Birth.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Denkinger is the umpire who cost the Cardinals the 1985
World Series when he blew a call at first base in Game 6 against
the Royals. Until the Red Sox' choke in '86, it was the closest any
team came to winning a World Series without doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, getting back to the conspiracy theory. Sosa this year
hit 12 homers in 12 games against the Milwaukee Brewers. It's never
been done before and would not have happened if Brewer owner Bud
Selig, now the baseball commissioner, hadn't allowed his team to
move from the American League.
</P>
<P>
   There. The commissioner's town took a home run away from McGwire
and surrendered 12 of Sosa's 65.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis manager Tony La Russa correctly points out that
McGwire has been walked a whopping 160 times, more than twice as
many as Sosa (73 walks).
</P>
<P>
   ``Give Mark another 80 at-bats and see who has more homers,''
said the manager.
</P>
<P>
   La Russa had McGwire batting in his customary No. 3 spot in the
order. The world waits to see if Tony bats Big Mac leadoff Sunday
to give him an extra AB.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire himself seems lonely, as he did before the two-week
home-and-home lovefest with Sammy. Big Mac's not talking before or
after games unless he hits a homer.
</P>
<P>
   Informally, I spoke with McGwire after Thursday night's win. He
talked about not talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the big deal?'' he said when asked about his new
silence. ``This is what I've done all year. There's no sense in
talking unless I do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the night, McGwire signed autographs for five minutes
before making his way to the batting cage for batting practice.
Seven of his 15 BP swings produced home runs, all resulting in mad
scrambles and wild applause.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie righthander Javier Vazquez started for the Expos, and it
was quickly noted that the 22-year-old Puerto Rican had allowed 30
homers, a Montreal record.
</P>
<P>
   Vazquez (5-14, 6.02 ERA) certainly looked nervous. In the bottom
of the first, he hit No. 2 batter Brian Jordan, then faced McGwire
as flashes popped and everyone (including the two benches) stood.
The kid threw four straight balls, none of 'em close. McGwire no
doubt had the La Russa green light on 3-0, but the pitch was way
high. Cardinal Nation booed as McGwire trotted to first, then
cheered when Ray Lankford followed with a three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire came to bat in the third, he saw no pitch faster
than 79 miles per hour. He swung and missed on a pair of changeups,
then looked at a 2-2 curveball strike.
</P>
<P>
   On his third appearance in the fifth, Big Mac cracked a hard
single to left on a 2-2 pitch. In the seventh, he tapped back to
the mound on a check swing against righty Shayne Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Such a disappointment. Like Ray Fitz said, it's lonely out here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
