</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    DILLER GOES TO BAT TO LAND BOSTON'S CHANNEL 68 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and f coding) (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Barry Diller, the Hollywood mogul and owner of USA Networks
Inc., has apparently offered $35 million-$40 million to Boston
University to purchase its television stations, including Channel
68 (WABU), flagship of the Red Sox network.
</P>
<P>
   USA Networks Inc. officials signed a letter of intent in July to
purchase WABU and its sister holdings, WZBU in Vineyard Haven and
WNBU in Concord, N.H., plus Low-Power Station w67BA in Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase would give Diller and his evolving empire a
foothold in the nation's sixth-largest media market.
</P>
<P>
   Despite never-ending rumors that Diller remains interested in
purchasing an existing network such as CBS, he appears focused on
building an eighth network from the ground up, based on a
programming strategy called ``city vision,'' or, as he told
Newsweek, ``localism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a deep hunger for a big TV network,'' he recently
told Time. ``Our agenda is quite clear. I'm happy with our
agenda.'' But, he coyly conceded, ``if a network came to us
opportunistically _ which I doubt strongly is going to happen _
that would be nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Diller's agenda calls for loads of local programming combined
with sports. So far, the results have been less than expected. WAMI
in Miami debuted June 8, and among its shows is one called ``10s,''
which features buffed men and women strolling South Beach. The
station also has television rights to Miami Heat games.
</P>
<P>
   Renowned for founding the Fox network and the Home Shopping
Network, Diller owns 16 UHF station across the country, including
Channel 66 in Boston. USA Network Inc. is worth an estimated $8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sources familiar with the negotiations suggest that Diller wants
Channel 68 with or without the rights to the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The station has held those rights for the last two years but
refused to exercise a $14 million option for next season, largely
because it is losing an estimated $6 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   The station has offered to pay in the $7 million-a-year range,
but, citing proprietary information, has refused to detail its
offer to the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining the rights to Celtics road games makes Channel 68 more
attractive for potential buyers. The recently signed deal calls for
the station and team to split the advertising revenue and share the
production costs, while Channel 68 pays the rights fee over time.
The station would make money after a certain threshold is reached.
</P>
<P>
   The letter of intent was extended to Sept. 18, but it remains
unclear whether Diller has retracted the offer or asked for more
time.
</P>
<P>
   Neither officials at USA Networks nor Channel 68 would confirm
or deny the pending sale.
</P>
<P>
   BU purchased the station in 1993 from the Christian Science
Monitor for a reported $4 million. Rumors of the station's sale
have persisted for years, but the Diller offer seems to be still on
the table.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Yellow means go
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ESPN has launched a technological innovation developed by
SporTVision Systems for its NFL games. Called ``1st and Ten,'' the
technology enables viewers to see a yellow line that appears
painted on the field at the first-down marker.
</P>
<P>
   The marker allows viewers to see the first-down position
regardless of the location of the cameras. It's not as simple as it
sounds. The location of the first-down yard line is entered into
the systems computer, which also gathers data on the camera's pan,
tilt, zoom, and focus functions. Based on that information, the
system knows where in each frame of video the line should appear.
</P>
<P>
   The innovation debuts Sunday night during ESPN's coverage of the
Cincinnati Bengals-Baltimore Ravens game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
