<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FAST-TRACK (Washington) _ Legislation that would renew the
president's fast-track trade negotiating authority is expected to
be defeated Friday in the House. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CIA-SPY-(Washington) _ Former CIA officer Douglas Groat became
obsessed with grievances and threatened his former employer but
didn't commit espionage against his country, a judge says in
sentencing Groat to five years in prison. BY EDWARD FITZPATRICK.
</P>
<P>
   PROSTATE-CANCER (Washington) _ Prostate-cancer research
advocates led by former junk bond king Michael Milken deliver
500,000 petitions to Congress demanding increased federal funds to
counter a disease that is the No. 2 cancer killer of American men.
By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN ELECTIONS (Paris) _ already filed _ Helmut Kohl's 16
years as Germany's head of government may be ended Sunday by a
major error he committed nearly a decade ago at the time of his
country's re-unification following the collapse of communism. By
BERNARD D. KAPLAN.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ELECTIONS (Washington) _ Although heartened by polls
showing most Americans don't want President Clinton to leave
office, Democrats are bracing for a negative reaction in the
November election to the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal. Republicans,
however, are on a tightrope of their own. Not pursuing impeachment
would incur the wrath of the GOP faithful. Pursuing it too
vigorously might alienate swing voters. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
