<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4568 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-SEX-HNS &LR;      09-25 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS MEDIA TAKE HEAT FOR COVERAGE OF CLINTON SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When America's first newspaper, Benjamin Harris'
``Publick Occurrences Both Forreign and Domestick,'' printed a
salacious story in 1690 about the king of France sleeping with his
son's wife, the Massachusetts colonial authorities closed the
newspaper after exactly one issue.
</P>
<P>
   Politics and sex have been a part of American journalism ever
since, long before Bill Clinton and Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the America of three centuries ago, news of
hanky-panky in high places today is virtually inescapable. Credit _
or blame _ for this goes to the proliferation of media outlets and
the 24-hour news cycle that has come along with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics as sex scandal has been with us from the very
beginning,'' said Erna Smith, head of the Journalism Department at
San Francisco State University. ``The desire for this kind of
titillation is part of human nature. The country is fascinated and
repelled at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   While treatment of the Clinton scandal is reminiscent of blanket
coverage of other big stories _ most pointedly, the O.J. Simpson
trial and the death of Princess Diana _ the possibility of
presidential impeachment has allowed many media outlets to cloak
themselves in the mantle of the public's right to know and to toss
long-held standards out the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many (scandal) stories have been based on leaks. The
motivations of the leakers were questionable,'' Smith said. Yet she
allows, ``The most interesting thing is that every single leak has
proven to be true. When we first heard about the dress (Monica
Lewinsky's stained garment), it sounded so outrageous. Then it
proved to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   While daytime talk shows and cable news operations obsessed on
the story from the beginning, network TV's most respected
newsmagazine, ``60 Minutes,'' did its part by interviewing Kathleen
Willey about her allegations that Clinton groped her.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton's four hours of videotaped grand jury testimony was
released, all the major networks and cable news outlets aired it in
its entirety.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, meanwhile, jumped closer to the ranks of the
``legitimate'' media by carrying Matt Drudge's initial Lewinsky
report, the release of the report by Whitewater independent counsel
Kenneth Starr, and the on-line magazine Salon's piece about Rep.
Henry Hyde's past extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-hour news cycle also is feeding ``a rush to judgment,''
said David Caploe, director of media studies at New College of
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than 100 newspapers have called on Clinton to resign.
There's been no consistent examination of the potentially
deleterious effect on the country if that happens,'' Caploe said.
``In The New York Times, their front-page stories are much less
analytical than I can remember in the past. Their inside stories
are still solid and analytical, but they aren't running on Page
One.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, competition in print and especially
electronic media blurs differences in reporting: ``The intention is
to be different from everyone else. Yet they end up duplicating
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Clinton affair may already have surpassed coverage
of O.J. Simpson and the death of Diana, the Princess of Wales. It
might eventually even surpass the mother of all modern U.S.
political scandals _ Watergate _ although it's playing out in a
very different way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot more media now than when you had just three
broadcast networks,'' said Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the
Annenberg School of Communications at the University of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   With more and more media outlets chasing smaller and smaller
audiences, Jamieson said, media organizations jump with both feet
on any big story that could bring them more than a niche audience.
</P>
<P>
   Smith criticized the daily newspapers and much of television for
low-quality coverage. While she praised C-Span for consistently
showcasing the world press' reaction to the Clinton story, she said
that's a rare high point.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, MSNBC is the National Enquirer of the airwaves,'' she
said, blasting the cable network owned by NBC and Microsoft. She
likened MSNBC's scandal coverage to ``wall-to-wall talk TV. They
argue with each other, they're wildly opinionated and speculative.
I think they're a disgrace.''
</P>
<P>
   That depends on when, and whom, you're watching, said MSNBC
spokesman Cory Shields. ``There are so many different formats we
have in a 24-hour period: talk shows, call-ins, formal newscasts.
If I saw a single episode of `Friends' I didn't like, I wouldn't
say I don't like NBC.''
</P>
<P>
   The changing technology that turned cable TV and on-line
services into omnipresent electronic wallpaper also has had a
profound effect on how the news is framed and reported, said Rich
Noyes, the political studies director of the Center for Media and
Public Affairs, in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``More news outlets create more news that can't be ignored,''
Noyes said. ``If you put a senator on, and he says something, that
becomes the news for everyone else, who have to cover it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, he said, ``If you find a topic the public is
really interested in, you can play it out, rather than rounding out
your news diet. The media learned this in a big way with O.J.
They've been trying to replicate it ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   This development is not universally applauded, even among
journalists. For example, Pacifica Radio national affairs
correspondent Larry Bensky criticizes the commercial news media for
lack of proportionality and taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``Careers are made and broken on who gets the ratings, and who
can be the most provocative,'' Bensky said. ``All of them are
clamoring for attention like an unruly kindergarten of badly
behaved children. But they never go outside the box. They never go
out in the street to see what's really going on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
