<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CUPID' TAKES A SHOT AT GENDER WARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Meet Trevor Hale. He's either the Roman god of love or a
certified head case. Portrayed effectively and affectionately by
Jeremy Piven, still smug but less obnoxious than his ``Ellen''
character, he zips through ``Cupid'' like a freight train in a
hurry.
</P>
<P>
   His rush? The guy's thoroughly convinced that love isn't
something that stops to check off items on an ideal-mate list, that
it will be chemistry _ not compatibility _ that makes a married
twosome go at it on the dinner table 10 years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   This runs comedically and poignantly counter to the 15 years of
study, training and practice of psychiatric/relationship expert
Claire Allen (Paula Marshall), who happens to be stuck with Trevor
since his release from a psychiatric ward.
</P>
<P>
   Claire thinks women ought to wake up from their fairy tales and
not settle for the guy on the white horse _ unless he relaxes with
Mozart, drives a Volvo and wants to raise 3.6 children in the
'burbs, just like you. Compatibility, not chemistry, means
longevity, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six months, if you're lucky,'' is Claire's take on biochemical
unions. Then it's back to her theory, ``... negotiation,
compromise, friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   Trevor prefers the kind of in-your-face, fearless technique that
gives this comedy drama its spin. ``Make a move,'' he says to
singles in the hunt. ``Get in the game. Get hurt. Have a beautiful
train wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   I enjoyed this episode of ``Cupid'' (9 p.m. CDT, ABC). It's
witty, romantic, funny, mythical. It positions itself as a voice in
the gender wars that says we ought not to be so tentative,
contrived and psychoanalyzed when it comes to love. Too much mind
kills the heart.
</P>
<P>
   That's Trevor's thing when he busts up Claire's group session in
the opening episode (He calls it a ``pop psychology sensitivity
awareness festival for people shackled by fear''), but maybe we're
getting ahead of ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Trevor is that he may or may not be Cupid. His
story is that he was banished from Mount Olympus for losing his
touch. To work his way back, he must take on the guise of a mortal
and match 100 couples without the benefit of magic.
</P>
<P>
   This lands him in the nuthouse, where he eventually convinces
Claire that, yeah, he was psychotic but is now cured. The moment he
walks out the door, he's eyeing souls to match.
</P>
<P>
   Claire finds him more of a professional nuisance than anything
else. ``Fifteen years of training has prepared me to help these
people,'' she says of her group-session participants.
</P>
<P>
   Never caught without a snappy comeback, Trevor unloads: ``And
being the Roman god of love for 3,000 years has prepared me for
what, a desk job at Hallmark?''
</P>
<P>
   Snappy writing is part of ``Cupid's'' charm. Another part will
be watching subplots weave in and out of each episode, dealing with
love lost and found. In the engaging pilot, Trevor uses a plot
device from ``The Way We Were'' to bring a couple together.
</P>
<P>
   Through all this, something appears to be smoldering between
Trevor and Claire. Hmmm. In TV, we call that chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Also premiering Saturday night:
</P>
<P>
   DE PLANE TRUTH: You'd think the challenge facing ``Fantasy
Island'' (8 p.m. CDT, ABC) is how it can satisfy original fans
while capturing newcomers with its darker, more mystical tone.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. My take is that executive producer and visionary Barry
Sonnenfeld (''Men in Black'') isn't all that interested in dusting
off former ``Fantasy Islanders'' and plopping them down in front of
the tube.
</P>
<P>
   The show's more engaging devices _ taking two to three stories
per show and playing them out over an hour _ remain, and Sonnenfeld
has added the kind of touches that certainly give it a different
sheen from what you might remember.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike UPN's campy ``Love Boat: The Next Wave,'' ABC is
fashioning the new ``Fantasy Island'' as adult fare with creepy,
wild-eyed Malcolm McDowell as Mr. Roarke. Gone are the white suits;
this Mr. Roarke is all-Armani. In black.
</P>
<P>
   His sidekicks or facilitators helping out with fantasies include
Cal (Louis Lombardi), Harry (Edward Hibbert), and Ariel (Madchen
Amick), who has the chameleonlike talent for becoming anyone she
chooses. It appears that none of them is there of his own free
will.
</P>
<P>
   On the mainland, Fisher (Fyvush Finkel of ``Picket Fences)''
presides as a tour guide who books these often nightmarish jaunts.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night's episode involves three stories, all dealing
with heavier-than-usual life-affirming circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantasy Island'' wants to be the new ``Twilight Zone.'' Not a
bad goal to reach for.
</P>
<P>
   KUNG-FU FIGHTING: ``Martial Law'' (8 p.m. CDT, CBS) is the
wacky, hilarious drama introducing Hong Kong martial-arts star
Sammo Hung. Here he's Sammy Law, a Shanghai cop who joins the LAPD.
He's fat, fast and funny. The action is completely cartoonish,
often moving in fast-forward. Good for a laugh. But if dialogue is
your thing, read a book.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1442EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
