<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4624 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCOOBY-DOO-TEX     09-25 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOOBY-DOO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZOINKS! YOU CAN'T IMAGINE WHAT REALLY WENT ON IN THE MYSTERY
MACHINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC CELESTE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Kenneth Starr were interrogating Scooby-Doo, he might ask the
following question:
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Doo, why is it that now, some 29 years after your network
debut, you and Shaggy and the whole gang are still so incredibly
HOT?'' Is it because you are, and always have been, shall we say,
BAKED?''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, since its 1969 introduction, people have been
trying to figure out why Scooby-Doo is so popular _ Mike Myers is
penning a live-action Scooby movie _ as well as trying to decipher
the show's socio/sexual/political leanings. (Witness the online
``Scooby-Doo for president'' party, the Scoobapublicans.)
</P>
<P>
   Kids may think it's just a show about a goofy Great Dane who
can't pronounce his W's. But adults who grew up watching Scooby now
know better. It has long been argued that Scooby-Doo contains
subtext encompassing hippiedom, drug use and various other
influences from the late '60s, early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   With the release this week of a new made-for-video movie,
``Scooby-Doo on Zombie Island'' ($19.96, Warner Home Video), we'll
take the opportunity to debunk some common misconceptions and air
our theories as to what Scooby, Shaggy, Fred, Daphne and Velma were
REALLY up to while tooling around in the Mystery Machine.
</P>
<P>
   Misconception: Scooby-Doo is popular because he's so lovable. As
Don Messick, the original voice of Scooby, once said, ``I think
it's because he embraces a lot of human foibles. He's not the
perfect dog. In fact, you might say he's a coward. Yet with
everything he does, he seems to land on his four feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Our theory: We are lemmings. We love familiarity, and every
Scooby-Doo episode is the same. Ghost/monster scares locals,
Mystery Machine happens upon town, crew is told of local
ghost/monster, Shaggy and Scooby freak, the gang investigates,
shenanigans ensue, ghost/monster is unmasked and turned over to
local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Shaggy says, ``Zoinks,'' Scooby laughs his
hee-hee-hee laugh, Velma loses her glasses and says, ``Jinkies,''
Daphne says, ``Jeepers,'' Fred asks Shaggy and Scooby if they'll
undertake some ridiculous scheme ``for a Scooby Snack.'' Every once
in a while, Dick Van Dyke or Tim Conway or some other '70s star
shows up.
</P>
<P>
   Misconception: Scooby and Shaggy are all about drug use. The
Scooby Snack recipe from the Scooby Web `O' Rama
(web.paticafe.by.net/TelevisionCity/1145) lends support to this: 2
cups flour, 1 cup dry oatmeal, 1/2 cup cocoa, 1/2 cup sugar, 1
stick butter, 2 eggs, 1 tablespoon vanilla, 1 teaspoon walnut
extract. Optional: 1 ounce of finely ground herbal medicine.
Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Combine all ingredients in large
mixing bowl. Stir five minutes, add milk to aid mixing if needed.
Place on lightly greased cookie sheet and bake for 10 to 12
minutes, depending on how large you made your cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Our theory: The whole gang suffers reefer madness. They hang out
in the Mystery Machine; they say ``groovy''; they see ghosts and
talk to dogs, fer cryin' out loud.
</P>
<P>
   Misconception: Velma _ the frumpish nerd with the unisex haircut
_ is a lesbian. Consider what she said after her comely sidekick
Daphne delayed the mystery-solving process by having her picture
taken: ``Women! Wait a minute. What am I saying? I'm a woman!''
</P>
<P>
   Our theory: When you're right, you're right.
</P>
<P>
   Misconception: Fred and Daphne are secret lovers. According to
Stephanie, a 13-year-old who runs Steph's Groovy Scooby Site
(members.tripod.com/(TILDE)scoobz/pages/main.html) from her home in
Vancouver, British Columbia: ``Daphne and Fred were in love. You
could see it in their eyes. They were always flirting around.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, note the work of well-known Internet Scoobicians Mark
Dorr, Tim Solley and Chad Holder, whose seminal Scooby-Doo essay
argues that, taken separately, the Scooby-Doo gang ``each portrays
a certain degree of disillusionment found in all of us
(Gen-Xers).'' The esteemed troika argue that ``Fred's orange
`neckerchief' made him appear as though he was the consummate gay
male. In actuality, it was his secret weapon for hooking up with
Daphne.''
</P>
<P>
   Our theory: Fred was gay, while Daphne and Shaggy were secretly
in love.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1450EDT &QL; 
