<HEADLINE>
CLOSE PROGRAM BOX GIVES PC USER CONTROL WHEN MACHINE MESSES UP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: In Windows 95, when one enters Control-Alt-Delete on the
keyboard, a window called ``Close Program'' comes up. Can you
kindly tell me what exactly is contained in this window? I have not
been able to find any detailed explanation in any of the Windows 95
books that I have. Are these programs that have been loaded into
memory? Are they running (there's no evidence of this in some
cases)? Are they in RAM but dormant?
</P>
<P>
   A: That window does indeed show the programs that currently are
running in your system's memory. But, don't be surprised if you
aren't familiar with all of them.
</P>
<P>
   In the pre-Windows 95/NT days, doing a Control-Alt-Delete (also
known among the grizzled, old compu-guard as the ``three-fingered
salute'') was used to reboot your system. Now, it gives you access
to the programs running on your system, and in Windows NT it's also
used to log on to a computer.
</P>
<P>
   From the Close Program dialog box you can, of course, close any
of the programs you see there. Just click on the one you want to go
away and click the End Task button. You also can shut the entire
computer down from here.
</P>
<P>
   The real purpose of it arises when a program misbehaves.
Sometimes, a Windows 95/98 program will just stop working, while
the rest of your PC hums merrily along. If you bring up the Close
Program box, you'll likely see the words ``Not responding'' next to
the name of the program. Your best bet is to close that program
using the End Task button.
</P>
<P>
   You may get a secondary window that pops up asking whether you
want to wait a bit longer, or just kill the program.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the things you see listed in the Close Program dialog
box may not be familiar to you. They are programs running in the
background, or components of Windows itself. For example, one of
them is SYSTRAY. This stands for System Tray _ the area on the far
right of the Windows taskbar that contains the clock, the speaker
icon and possibly other icons.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a Logitech mouse, one of the items will be
``emexec'' _ this is the program that controls some of the mouse's
special features, such as a wheel or a third mouse button.
</P>
<P>
   One of the items also will be Explorer. Some people will
occasionally use End Task on the Explorer if the Windows desktop
starts behaving oddly.
</P>
<P>
   When you do this, however, any program icons that normally
appear in the tray will disappear. That means you'll have to
restart them in order to regain access to their capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I just upgraded to Windows 98 from Windows 95, and I like it
pretty much. However, for some reason Windows 98 dropped a Network
Neighborhood icon on my desktop. I don't have a network connection
_ just a dialup connection to the Internet. I can't delete the icon
by dragging it to the Recycle Bin; Windows won't let me. I've
discovered TweakUI from your column and tried to use it, but I get
a warning that there may be problems if I delete it. What should I
do?
</P>
<P>
   A: Go ahead and let TweakUI remove the Network Neighborhood icon
from your desktop. I've never had a problem using TweakUI in this
way.
</P>
<P>
   One precaution, though: Check and record your dialup networking
settings before you do this. Look in the Network module in the
Control Panel, as well as the Connection/Settings area in the
Dialup Networking folder.
</P>
<P>
   After you've removed Network Neighborhood, sign on to your
Internet service provider and make sure everything works. If not,
go back and reset your original settings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
