<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4649 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FANTASY-TV-LADN     09-25 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANTASY-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV GETS SERIOUS ON SATURDAY NIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Saturdays have become no laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   Four networks, 12 hours of programming and not a sitcom in the
bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ABC adds ``Fantasy Island'' and ``Cupid'' to an hour of
``America's Funniest Home Videos.'' CBS slides ``Martial Law''
between ``Early Edition'' and ``Walker, Texas Ranger.'' NBC leads
off its night with ``Wind on Water,'' which premieres in October,
followed by ``The Pretender'' and ``Profiler.'' As for Fox, it will
stand pat with ``Cops,'' more ``Cops'' and ``America's Most Wanted:
America Fights Back.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FANTASY ISLAND &QC;
</P>
<P>
   This is the darker, more sinister Malcolm McDowell-as-Mr.-Roarke
remake of the '70s hit ``Fantasy Island.'' And the show wastes no
time establishing the differences between the two versions.
</P>
<P>
   Roarke rummages through his closet, which has an endless supply
of identical white suits. He eventually settles on the one black
ensemble in the lot.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when Aaron Spelling, master of light
entertainment, is replaced as executive producer by Barry
Sonnenfeld, director of ``Men in Black.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the suits, the Tattoo character is also replaced. The
new resort staff includes bell-ringing ox Cal (Louis Lombardi),
Cal's partner Harry (Edward Hibbert) and Roarke's beautiful
assistant Ariel (Madchen Amick).
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot episode, the trip to the island was sandwiched
between two wonderful scenes in a dreary travel agency. People
happen upon Fisher (played by the wonderful Fyvush Finkel of
``Picket Fences''). He knows what their fantasy is, and soon enough
they are booked on a trip to Fantasy Island. The final scene of the
show was ``Bill Clinton'' entering the agency. The show ends before
we find out what his fantasy is, but I'd imagine you have a pretty
good idea.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of each story is still the same: ``Be careful what you
wish for'' and ``appreciate what you have.'' And the rule stands _
no one is ever allowed to know about your experiences on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   The show mixes action, morality and humor rather nicely. Filmed
in Hawaii, this is a visually appealing program, and there are
above-average special effects. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CUPID &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Cupid (Jeremy Piven) is in Chicago, and boy does he have a lot
of work to do. He's shooting for 100 lasting romances (sans bow and
arrow) or he'll never be let back onto Mount Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   That is, if he is Cupid at all.
</P>
<P>
   He may just be Trevor Hale, a delusional mental patient who
thinks he is Cupid. His psychiatrist _ relationship expert Dr.
Claire Allen (Paula Marshall) _ doesn't want to hear any of this
Cupid garbage.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting battle between science (years of medical training)
and romance (3,000 years as the Roman god of love) is an
interesting, different and certainly entertaining series.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, a hard-edged and probably too-practical woman, is ready
to scrap plans to write a book on love and romance but may be
inspired to forge ahead with the project after meeting the title
character, who is too idealistic for his own good.
</P>
<P>
   He is set free in society and, against her advice, starts to
make matches. As the first ends in disaster, and the second hits a
major snag, Cupid realizes his assignment is not a simple one.
</P>
<P>
   His roommate Champ (Jeffrey D. Sams) is a struggling
African-American actor who refuses to take roles written for black
characters (for example, ``the sacrificial `Star Trek' crew
member'').
</P>
<P>
   There are some holes in the story and very predictable parts,
but in all, this is a fine romantic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Piven (``Ellen'') stands out, adding plenty of humor to his role
as the self-assured mythological character or nut case. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MARTIAL LAW &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Martial Law'' opens with a great action sequence in a Shanghai
warehouse as a portly martial artist kicks butt and legs and
chests.
</P>
<P>
   Who says there's nothing different on television?
</P>
<P>
   Sammo Law (Hong Kong martial-arts superstar Sammo Hung) comes to
help the Los Angeles Police Department crack an international
car-theft ring.
</P>
<P>
   He is especially interested in the case because one of his
fellow officers and students, Chen Pei Pei (Kelly Hu) has gotten
wrapped up in the mess.
</P>
<P>
   His style is unconventional, but his ways seem to work. He knows
when to make a move and when to stay still.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving at LAX, Law is scammed by a fake cabdriver who
steals all of his possessions. Instead of fighting his way out of
the situation, he studies the perps, gets detailed information
about their cars and makes positive identifications, leading to
their arrest and the return of his suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   In other scenes, he beats a suspect with his own shoe and uses a
chalkboard eraser to beat back a racist cop. Later he revives a
woman who faints by massaging her feet.
</P>
<P>
   This is no ordinary action hero.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first episode, he and the bad cop are part of
an overseas officer exchange, allowing Law to hang around for the
TV season.
</P>
<P>
   He is teamed with detectives Dana Doyle (Tammy Lauren) and Louis
McGray (Louis Mandylor), a good-looking duo to counterbalance
Sammo's skunk-striped hair and big belly.
</P>
<P>
   Law is a unique and charming character, surrounded by a fine
supporting cast. He will either become a cult hit, adopted by the
``Walker, Texas Ranger'' crowd, or be ignored by an American
audience that likes its heroes to have washboard stomachs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1509EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
