<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4659 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEAFOOD-AZR &LR;      09-25 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAFOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER DEMAND ENDANGERING SEAFOOD'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL CLANCY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PH0ENIX - The fish counter at 99 Ranch Market in Phoenix gives
no indication of a problem, with its wide range of selections.
</P>
<P>
   The processing rooms of East Coast Seafood in Phoenix are full
with all kinds of fish, moving maybe 30 tons a day to Valley
restaurants and grocery stores, showing no hint of a shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Seafood is big in Phoenix, swept away on the promise that it is
good for you.
</P>
<P>
   But a new tide has been rising, first in environmental and
scientific circles, then moving into the regional mainstream press
and now washing over the public at large. If we continue eating
anything and everything from lake or sea, pretty soon there won't
be any left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got serious overfishing problems,'' says Mia Tegner, a
scientist with the Scripps Institute of Oceanography in La Jolla,
Calif., ``without even talking about by-catch, ghost fishing and
habitat changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's catching too many fish, methods of fishing that
bring up too much unwanted catch _ known as by-catch, fish farming
without regard for pollution, or just a growing appetite that will
not subside, mankind has continued to fish without regard for our
ability to catch anything tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Seafood makes up the last wild creatures that are hunted and
consumed in large quantities, says Merry Camhi of the National
Audubon Society's Living Oceans Program, which does business from
offices on Long Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The world's oceans will not be able to sustain the current
demand for long, she says. In fact, she says, the worldwide catch
has declined since 1989, even though more and more fishing boats
are sailing the high seas.
</P>
<P>
   Some species are especially in trouble:
</P>
<P>
   - The Atlantic swordfish, which many chefs have taken off menus
in a protest against overfishing. According to the U.S. National
Marine Fisheries Service, the number of breeding-age creatures is
only 30 percent of what it was in the '60s, when a fishing
technique called long lining became popular. Replacing traditional
harpoons, long lines of 25 to 40 miles long _ baited with hundreds
of hooks _ are sunk to the depths of an ocean and bring up
thousands of fish.
</P>
<P>
   The catch began to decline in 1989, and now is less than half of
what it was then _ although almost twice as many long lines are in
place.
</P>
<P>
   - Red snapper and drum in the Gulf of Mexico have been targeted
since the time chef Paul Prudhomme first blackened redfish (and
later, other regional fish) and made it popular about 20 years ago.
The fishery was developed, fished, crashed and closed within 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   - The catch of ground fish _ haddock, flounder and cod _
declined 65 percent in waters off New England from 1976 to 1986.
The New England yellowtail flounder lost 94 percent of its breeding
population in that same period.
</P>
<P>
   - The sardine fishery that enabled John Steinbeck to write
``Cannery Row'' is now history, as any visitor to California's
Monterey Bay Aquarium can see. In 1936, it pulled in 800,000 tons
of fish. The catch had dropped to 10,000 tons by 1953, and it had
collapsed altogether by 1967. Only now have sardines recovered
enough to reopen a small fishery there.
</P>
<P>
   - Tuna has been fished to its limits in many parts of the ocean,
in part because of the popularity of sushi. A bluefin tuna _ a
single fish _ can bring in an average of $20,000. The International
Commission for the Conservation of Atlantic Tuna estimates the
number of adult tuna has dropped 90 percent since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   - Orange roughy, which became popular with Americans in the
'80s, were thought to be plentiful around New Zealand. Before the
fish even could be studied, fishing vessels removed an estimated 80
percent of the fish. Only later did scientists learn that the fish
grow so slowly that it takes them 25 to 30 years to reach breeding
age. As a result, it may take a century or more for the stocks to
recover.
</P>
<P>
   - Shrimp are plentiful in some parts of the ocean but not in
that part of the ocean closest to Arizona, the Gulf of California.
For every pound of shrimp caught, there are seven pounds of
unwanted by-catch. What's more, shrimp farming _ which provides
half the world supply _ has pollution problems _ ranging from
destruction of oceanside habitat to water pollution.
</P>
<P>
   This list comes not from environmental organizations, which
consumers and industry representatives might feel have ulterior
motives. Instead, it comes from the government's National Marine
Fisheries Service, which under federal law must publish lists of
sea creatures that are overfished and devise plans to deal with the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Camhi of the National Audubon Society says the basic problem is
that the world's population has grown, as has its appetite for
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Most adults can remember a time when a fish meal consisted of
breaded fish sticks out of the oven. Now, most groceries complement
their frozen supplies with fresh-fish counters. What's more, almost
every restaurant has seafood choices.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Boyce, a former fisherman who now works for East Coast
Seafood in Phoenix, says news reports about the health benefits of
seafood fueled the demand that resulted in such bounty.
</P>
<P>
   His company has gone, in a period of about 20 years, from
providing fresh shrimp, crab legs and lobster tails _ supplemented
by a few frozen varieties _ to a full-service company that imports
fish from all around the world. On any given day, Boyce said, East
Coast may handle 80 species.
</P>
<P>
   Times have changed, however. Prices for fish such as North
Pacific rockfish, North Atlantic cod and orange roughy have doubled
over the past few years as supplies have diminished, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Audubon Society's Camhi, who specializes in sharks, says
many species have become overfished in less than 10 years _ since
sharks started being promoted as an alternative to swordfish and
tuna, which were under stress even then.
</P>
<P>
   Tegner at Scripps says that California's abalone fishery has
been closed and that less and less high-quality seafood is being
caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are eating lower and lower on the food chain,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   As the fishing industry has tried to keep up, it not only has
identified alternatives but has developed more sophisticated
methods of fishing.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 20 years, Camhi says, technology has improved
substantially, enabling the industry to catch fish more easily and
thus more easily deplete supplies. More ships have taken to the
ocean to catch fish. Practices such as long lines and bottom
trawling _ likened to clear-cutting the ocean floor _ bring up not
just a desired catch but tons of by-catch, most of which goes to
waste.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long way from a pole, a baited line and a bobber.
</P>
<P>
   Fish farming has filled some of the gap _ much of our salmon,
trout, catfish and shrimp come from fish farms. However, even that
is not problem-free, with prices to be paid in habitat destruction,
pollution and fish affected by disease, antibiotics or pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   Camhi hopes continued government oversight, more efficient
fishing that cuts down on by-catch, and perhaps a reduction in
demand will result in a healthy, productive fishery over time.
</P>
<P>
   For now, where does it leave a consumer who hopes to act
responsibly?
</P>
<P>
   Boyce and Camhi, coming from different directions, say education
is a key.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer awareness is a real issue,'' Boyce says. ``We should
all be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Camhi says consumers should make themselves aware of what kinds
of fish are in trouble, and then avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   Besides those listed above, they include shark and grouper,
Pacific rockfish, some types of salmon, and scallops.
</P>
<P>
   Camhi also recommends choosing the right fish to feed the
seafood craving. Those include Pacific cod, striped bass, mackerel,
herring, farm-raised trout and catfish, most salmon, crab and
squid.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a choice,'' she says, ``and it is a meaningful
choice.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1517EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
