<HEADLINE>
DESERT SHRIMP FARMING A REALITY  
 (PHOTOS HAVE BEEN SENT TO NYTNS PHOTO CLIENTS)
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The ponds are edged with tumbleweeds, surrounded by
cotton fields in the center of nowhere, not far from Gila Bend,
Ariz. Standing in the desert heat and staring at them, it is hard
to imagine that at the bottom of the ponds wiggle thousands of
pounds of white freshwater shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp farming looks like these 25 acres of big ditches that are
5 feet deep, with floating aerators that kick up spray. There is no
fishy odor _ only a hint of the future hangs in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shrimp may sound unusual now, but in five years, it may sound
like the only thing that's going to be practical to raise here,''
said Gary Wood, who has taken on marketing duties for his family
company, Wood Brothers Farms Inc., whose principals include his dad
and uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Their cotton farm never made a profit, Wood said, and several
years ago the company had to decide whether to abandon the farm or
go into something else. They decided to focus on specialty
products.
</P>
<P>
   So, Gary Wood is growing shrimp, and he wants to sell them to
the shrimp lovers of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Wood's favorite way to eat shrimp is just lightly cooked with a
hint of garlic. He wants to get some local chefs down to the farm
to see and taste the quality of his product, because he would love
to see Arizona-grown shrimp _ harvested the same day _ on state
menus.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 5 million people in Arizona eating the national average
of 15 pounds of seafood per year, we consume 75 million pounds,''
said Kevin Fitzsimmons, coordinator for aquaculture research at the
Environmental Research Laboratory at the University of Arizona in
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We produce less than 2 million pounds in the state, so we are
probably importing 73 million pounds into Arizona per year. That's
quite a market niche to fill.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's other shrimp farm, near Yuma, is run by longtime
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shrimp'' to Arizonans most likely means the giant blues sold
in the nearest seaport, at the Rocky Point fish market in Sonora,
Mexico, on the Gulf of California. However, in the off-season or
when the boats don't bring back enough, Fitzsimmons said, even the
shrimp in the Rocky Point market are farm-raised.
</P>
<P>
   Globally, domestically farmed shrimp and seafood could ease the
U.S. trade deficit and help the global environment, Fitzsimmons and
promoters of fish farming agree. The huge amount of shrimp imported
into this country mostly come from Third World countries, where
``rapacious and primitive'' farms have destroyed huge tracts of
mangrove forests, according to a recent ``Nutrition Action
Healthletter,'' published by the Center for Science in the Public
Interest. Farms in the desert, however, don't threaten fragile
marsh and bay areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go inland, and there's no environmental concerns, no diseases,
and no exotic species getting mixed in,'' Addison Lawrence said in
a ``Christian Science Monitor'' story on shrimp farming earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence is a professor at Texas A&AMP;M University's Aquaculture
Experimental Station in Port Aransas, Texas, and reportedly is
working on a grant to develop a huge private shrimp farm in this
area.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M is a leader in shrimp farming in arid lands and is
participating in research at Wood Brothers Farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, when we started this three years ago, we didn't tell
anybody,'' Wood said. ``They all thought we were crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has invested $2 million to $3 million in the shrimp
farm, Wood said, and this is the first year the firm has had enough
harvest, about 100,000 pounds, to warrant publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Because brood shrimp and their offspring are shipped worldwide,
the farm is biosecure to ensure a sanitary environment. It is not
open to the public. Pesticides are not allowed anywhere near the
shrimp ponds, and no chemicals, antibiotics, preservatives or
weight enhancers are used in the production of these critters, Wood
emphasizes.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Sweet Shrimp starts growing in these ponds in March, Wood
said. The one-cell eggs that start dividing to become embryonic
shrimp are laid by Hawaiian disease-resistant brood shrimp _ the
real moneymakers here. Brood shrimp, worth $40 to $50 each, are
bigger and more pampered than their for-the-table offspring. Brood
shrimp spend the winter in a greenhouse on the farm.
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp eat a diet of algae, supplemented by a commercial feed
that contains a small percentage of squid, a favorite shrimp food.
The fact that algae grow well here might be one reason
desert-raised shrimp seem to grow faster than anyplace else, Wood
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   A system of pipes and canals circulates water through the ponds.
After the water is used for the shrimp, it waters other crops.
</P>
<P>
   The water goes on maize (not corn) and 40 acres of an olive
grove. Many more tree cuttings are waiting in a greenhouse nearby
to be planted. The olive trees are expected to yield fruit in 2002,
when they will be shipped to California for table olives.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the company quit raising cotton was
environmental concerns, such as the use of chemicals, Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   Wood Brothers managed the large Paloma Ranch near Gila Bend for
decades, Wood said, and at one time managed a big shrimp farm for
the owners in Ecuador in the 1980s. Ecuador, Thailand, Indonesia,
the Philippines and India are the main global producers of
farm-raised shrimp. The Ecuadorean shrimp were shipped to France as
a gourmet product, Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   The flat desert ponds seem a world away from France or Ecuador,
as great blue herons swoop among the ponds, picking up the
occasional shrimp that manages to flip out of the water. In Texas
shrimp ponds, coyotes reportedly have learned to scoop up shrimp
dinners, but here, dragonflies are the main predator when shrimp
are in the larval stage. Power failures are the biggest fear. All
electrical systems have backups, and workers live on the site in
case of outages. Oxygen must be pumped into the water with aerators
at all times; oxygen levels are monitored four times during the
night.
</P>
<P>
   The shrimp are harvested when ponds are drained, immediately put
on ice, and are shipped to a downtown Phoenix processor, where they
are bagged fresh and taken to stores or deheaded and individually
quick frozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a science and an art,'' Wood said of shrimp farming.
``We're learning something here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
