<SLUG> BC-SHRIMPSIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA FARMERS LOOK TO FISH AS WAVE OF FUTURE  
 (WITH SHRIMP) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Farm-grown Arizona fish are swimming around in more
places than you ever dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   Experimental live eels, along with more standard fish crops of
tilapia, channel catfish and largemouth bass, are being grown at
Sweetwater Farms, near Firebird Raceway on the Gila River Indian
Community. Almost all the Sweetwater fish goes to Oriental markets
and restaurants in the Phoenix area, says Mark Lauch, a Sweetwater
fisheries biologist.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to edible species, Arizona fish farmers raise
minnows for bait, aquarium fish, decorative koi and carp, which are
used instead of chemicals to clean ponds and canals.
</P>
<P>
   State fish farmers raised about 1.5 million pounds of tilapia,
trout, catfish and shrimp last year in about 500 acres of ponds,
and sold it for $2.6 million, said Kevin Fitzsimmons, who is
coordinator for aquaculture research at the Environmental Research
Laboratory at the University of Arizona. Almost all of it is going,
live, to ethnic markets, where customers prefer to select their
dinner while it's swimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aquaculture is the fastest growing sector of agriculture
worldwide and nationwide,'' Fitzsimmons said. ``I'm not sure if
it's the fastest growing in Arizona, but it's one of the fastest.
We just think that with all the financial and social and
environmental pressure that farmers are under here, this is going
to be one thing that really helps them.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ostrich farmers, who must educate consumers about their
product, there is a ready market for fish.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of all seafood in the world is farm-raised.
Americans consume so much imported seafood that it's one of the
biggest contributors to the trade deficit, ranked fourth after
petroleum, electronics and automobiles, Fitzsimmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp and fish ponds, some experts predict, may become
relatively common in tomorrow's deserts. Fourteen high schools in
Arizona have aquaculture projects for future farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Because the state pumps so much water for agriculture,
Fitzsimmons said, the water, the land and a nice long growing
season already exist. His research deals with integrating fish
farming into regular irrigated agriculture and getting twice the
use out of the water by growing a fish crop and then using the
water on plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waste from fish is great fertilizer for plants,'' Fitzsimmons
said. ``The farmer gets two crops and can use less chemical
fertilizer, it's more organic, and there are fewer problems with
fertilizers contaminating the groundwater.''
</P>
<P>
   As the government drops subsidies, farmers must be more
efficient with land and water, he said. They already have some of
the basics needed for fish farming: tractors to pull nets to catch
the fish, silos to store fish food, and contacts with feed
suppliers and market outlets.
</P>
<P>
   However, James T. Hicks, president of the Arizona Aquaculture
Association, said, ``There's no do-it-yourself kit for fish
farming.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than 15 years, agricultural farmers who have tried to
get rich quickly with fish farming have failed, he said. Fish
biology in an arid environment is totally different from anywhere
else, and the big learning curve disenchants people whose main goal
is to make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was natural for farmers to get involved,'' he said. ``But
there's a big difference between growing plants vs. growing an
animal.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1523EDT &QL; 
