<HEADER>
A4708 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FALL-REVIEWS-SPI &LR;      09-25 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALL-REVIEWS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CUPID,' `FANTASY ISLAND' MAKE SATURDAY NIGHT WORTH WATCHING
AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC has a history of airing decent shows on Saturday night, such
as ``Relativity,'' ``Cracker,'' ``C-16,'' ``Nothing Sacred,'' ``The
Practice.'' Its record of keeping the shows alive is less
spectacular. Only ``The Practice'' remains on the schedule, having
since moved to Monday, then to Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make even a confident bettor leery of plunking
down the kids' tuition on the chances of ``Fantasy Island'' and
``Cupid'' making it to next season. Like ``The Practice,'' which
won this year's Emmy for best drama, both new shows have the
potential to be among the best in prime time, but being on ABC
means they also have the potential to vanish before Thanksgiving.
So, if you like them, tune in and tune in often.
</P>
<P>
   First to appear, at 9 o'clock, is ``Fantasy Island,'' a remake
of the series that America embraced in the late '70s and early
'80s. The premise is identical: Subscribers to the
other-man's-grass-is-always-greener theory are granted a
``fantasy'' vacation on a tropical isle, complete with whatever
experiences they've always coveted, only to learn that their own
fescue is probably better, crabgrass and all.
</P>
<P>
   A pleasant addition to this edition is an odd travel agency run
by Fyvush Finkel, who has dibs on Fantasy Island referrals. Once
ticketed, the travelers still arrive by float plane and they're
still greeted by Mr. Roarke.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm McDowell plays the new Mr. Roarke, white-haired but
dark-suited _ he had the white ones burned _ perhaps to remind us
that ``Fantasy Island'' has undergone some renovations. McDowell's
Roarke is a few shades darker than Ricardo Montalban's, but he
retains the mystical powers that Montalban's character exhibited in
the latter stages of the original series. Tonight, for instance,
Roarke is a tourism director's dream, changing cloudy skies to
sunny with the snap of a finger.
</P>
<P>
   Metaphorically, he does the same for visitors to the island,
including a man who thinks he married the wrong woman, a woman who
wants to know everything, and an adventurer who is seeking the
ultimate challenge. In the end, the fantasy is never as fantastic
as imagined, and everyone goes home satisfied with their humdrum
lives.
</P>
<P>
   This steady predictability puts considerable pressure on the
writers to keep things from sliding into the sewage lagoon in the
weeks ahead. ABC is banking on the abilities of executive producer
Barry Sonnenfeld, the film director responsible for such
black-humor hits as ``Get Shorty'' and ``Men in Black.'' His
production company, the same outfit that gave us this summer's
marvelous diversion, ``Maximum Bob,'' is doing ``Fantasy Island.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Mr. Roarke and his mysterious assistants _ they all seem
to be ``doing time'' on the island _ are essential, guest stars are
key to the show's success. As long as the producers stay away from
the tendency to invite faded movie and TV stars onto the set, it
looks as if ``Fantasy Island'' is worth a return visit.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for ``Cupid,'' a thoroughly captivating romantic
comedy/drama about a guy who claims to be Cupid and the skeptical
psychiatrist who treats him.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Piven (``Ellen'') chucks the diaper and archery set in
favor of normal street clothes, lending Cupid, a k a Trevor Hale, a
tough, real exterior that keeps the show from being too cute for
its own good.
</P>
<P>
   Cupid/Hale claims he has been sent to Earth to relearn his
craft; the high divorce rate has given him a bad rep among the
deities. His mission: make 100 successful matches.
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatrist and relationship expert Claire Allen (Paula
Marshall) encounters Cupid when he's sent to a mental institution.
She wins his release on the condition that she keep him under
observation. He starts in on his matchmaking with the singles group
that Dr. Allen counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The sparks between Cupid and Claire arc regularly, but the
current clearly alternates between aversion and attraction.
Together, Piven and Marshall concoct an enticing blend of sexual
tension, mutual attraction and subtle humor.
</P>
<P>
   Against the violence of CBS's ``Walker, Texas Ranger'' and the
darkness of NBC's ``Profiler,'' ABC has a bright, entertaining
alternative for Saturday stay-at-homes. Let's hope they give
``Cupid'' a chance.
</P>
<P>
   There is also some tongue-in-cheek humor in ``Martial Law,'' a
new companion to CBS's rock-'em-sock-'em standby, ``Walker, Texas
Ranger.'' But don't expect much else.
</P>
<P>
   Sammo Hung, a colleague of Hong Kong icons Bruce Lee and Jackie
Chan, still struggles with English, so his conversation is kept to
a minimum. As Chinese supercop Sammo Law, he speaks instead with
quick kicks and smart jabs, the only sort of dialogue thugs seem to
understand.
</P>
<P>
   Law has come to Los Angeles in pursuit of a former
prot &UR; gfacute &LR; eg &UR; gfacute &LR; e, Chen Pei Pei (Kelly Hu), who has fallen
in with the bad guys. His partners in crime-fighting are L.A.
detectives Dana Doyle and Louis McGray, played with little
distinction by Tammy Lauren and Louis Mandylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martial Law'' is from the same producer responsible for ``Nash
Bridges,'' and it delivers the same lightweight entertainment in a
much more violent package. Though not bloody _ Sammo Law doesn't
carry a gun _ it is extremely violent, as dialogue is frequently
interrupted by bodies flying through the air with the greatest of
tease.
</P>
<P>
   Folks attracted by these kick-to-the-head come-ons will be
enchanted, but ``Martial Law'' is utterly pointless, unless
full-figured men are able to find a new role model in the
well-padded Sammo Hung.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fantasy Island. Hourlong drama about a resort where a person's
wildest dreams can come true. Starring Malcolm McDowell, Madchen
Amick, Louis Lombardi, Edward Hibbert, Fyvush Finkel and Sylvia
Sidney. Premieres Saturday, ABC. Check local listings. Parental
guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Cupid. Hourlong drama about a man who claims to be the god of
love. Starring Jeremy Piven and Paula Marshall. Premieres Saturday,
ABC. Check local listings. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _ Martial Law. Hourlong drama about a Chinese policeman on loan
to the Los Angeles Police Department. Starring Sammo Hung, Tammy
Lauren, Louis Mandylor, Tom Wright and Kelly Hu. Premieres
Saturday, CBS. Check local listings. Parental guideline rating:
TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   John Levesque is the P-I's TV critic. Call him at 206-448-8330
or send e-mail to: tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
