<TEXT>
<P>
   The following photos accomany the Hearst News Service's series
on prostate cancer. The stories are for release starting Sept. 27.
The main story is called PROSTATE-RDP. All other stories are
slugged with the prefix PCA-XXX, the medical shorthand for prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Photo clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BETHESDA, Md.-- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR TUES., SEPT.
29 -- PCA-MILITARY-2-HNS, 9-25 -- Dr. Shiv Srivastava, a molecular
biologist and the lead researcher at Department of Defense's Center
for Prostate Disease Research studies prostate cells. Srivastava
and other researchers working at a laboratory believe they have
located a new gene linked to prostate cancer. `` This is a very
prostate-specific gene,'' says Srivastava. ``This is something that
is very new.'' (Jerry Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BETHESDA, Md.-- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR TUES., SEPT.
29 -- PCA-MILITARY-1-HNS, 9-25 -- Sitting in his office, Dr. Judd
Moul, a urologist and director of the Department of Defense's
Center for Prostate Disease Research, holds a model of the
prostate. ``So far, nobody in the private sector has really been
able to put together a nationwide, multi-center database with a
standardized system to collect tissues,'' says Moul. (Jerry
Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR TUES., SEPT. 29
-- PCA-POLITICS-2-HNS, 9-25 -- In an effort to boost federal
research and raise the profile of prostate cancer, a new lobbying
group, the National Prostate Cancer Coalition, opened its doors
about two miles from the Capitol last year. Jay Hedlund, sitting,
meets with U.S. Rep. Henry Bonilla (R-Texas) in a bid to boost
federal funding. (Jerry Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR TUES., SEPT. 29 --
PCA-POLITICS-1-HNS, 9-25 -- Jerry Donohue, 62, a prostate cancer
patient, leads an effort on Long Island aimed at building
grass-roots pressure on Congress to spend more money for prostate
cancer research. ``I don't make long-term plans,'' says Donohue
who's cancer has invaded his bones. ``I take it as it comes.''
(Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SAN ANTONIO -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., SEPT. 28
-- PCA-BRACHYTHERAPY-3-HNS, 9-24 -- At Methodist Hospital, Mary
King affectionately touches the lips of her husband, Jim, after
doctors implanted radioactive seeds into his prostate gland. The
procedure is designed to eradicate cancer in a diseased prostate
and halt the spread of the cancer in a patient's body. (Jerry
Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SAN ANTONIO . -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., SEPT.
28 -- PCA-BRACHYTHERAPY-2-HNS, 9-24 -- At Methodist Hospital, Dr.
Michael Sarosdy, in the green gown, prepares to inject radioactive
pellets, usually called ``seeds'' into Jim King. With Sarosdy is
Dr. Russell Hern, anesthesiologist, left, and Jerome Gonzales,
R.N., right. (Jerry Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SAN ANTONIO -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., SEPT. 28
-- PCA-BRACHYTHERAPY-1-HNS, 9-24 -- In his office at Methodist
Hospital, Dr. Michael Sarosdy explains an x-ray to Jim King. The
x-ray is from a patient who has had radioactive seeds procedures,
also known as brachytherapy. Sarosdy, a urologic cancer specialist,
will perform the same surgery in on King in a few days later.
(Jerry Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LA SELVA BEACH, Calif. -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR
MON., SEPT. 28 -- PCA-IMPOTENCY-B&AMP;W-HNS, 9-25 -- Howard Waage, an
insurance inspector, was diagnosed with prostate cancer two years
ago at age 49. He recalled being overwhelmed at learning how many
men had lost sexual function after they sought treatment.
``Everything vital to a man is down in that area,'' says Waage who
had to choose between sexual function and arresting the cancer.
(Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., SEPT. 28
-- PCA-SURGERY-1-HNS, 9-25 -- Dr. David McLeod, 63, an Army
colonel, and chief of urology at Walter Reed Army Medical Center,
removed the cancerous prostates of former Sen. Bob Dole and retired
Gen. Norman Schwarzkopf, among other Washington notables. ``I knew
Dr. McLeod and that he'd done a lot of operations, from privates,
to sergeants, to colonels, generals and foreign dignitaries,'' says
Dole about his surgery in 1991. ``I decided that he had the skills
and he was interested in me as a person, not just as a patient.''
(Jerry Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., SEPT. 28
-- PCA-SURGERY-1-HNS, 9-25 -- A just removed, cancerous prostate
gland. The surgical removal of the prostate - a radical
prostatectomy - is the most common treatment for early-stage
prostate cancer, but not all men with cancerous prostates choose
this remedy. If a patient didn't want surgery, he might have chosen
radiation, either external beam radiation or radioactive ``seeds''
implanted directly in the gland. (Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) GETTYSBURG, Pa. -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., SEPT.
28 -- PCA-TREATMENT-OPTIONS-2-HNS, 9-25 -- Jan Marfyaic, from
Gettysburg, Pa., a former government worker, was 59 when he was
diagnosed with prostate cancer six years ago. He opted to have
brachytherapy or seed implant treatment. This is when tiny
radioactive implants, no bigger than a rye seed and injected
directly into the prostate through the perineum. ``I selected seeds
because it was much less invasive and was a relatively new
treatment,'' Marfyaic explains. (Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MONTICELLO, N.Y. -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON.,
SEPT. 28 -- PCA-TREATMENT-OPTIONS-B&AMP;W-HNS, 9-25 -- Prostate cancer
patient Carl Silverstein, of Monticello, N.Y., opted for radiation
over surgery when he was diagnosed in 1995. A semi-retired lawyer
for the Sullivan County legal aid society, Silverstein, 69, felt
his chances of avoiding incontinence and impotence were better with
radiation. (Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SILVER SPRINGS, Md. -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 27 -- PCA-BLACKS-2-HNS, 9-21 -- Harry Harris, a retired
federal government worker, looks over the files of the men in his
support group. ``I'm still alive today, but I know a lot of people
who had the cancer and are dead,'' he says. Harris, who was
diagnosed eight years ago with prostate cancer at age 69, is using
his experience to help other men confront their illness at a local
prostate cancer support group. (Jerry Lara/Hearst News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HOUSTON -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 27 --
PCA-BLACKS-1-HNS, 9-21 -- Raleigh Woodard, at left, sitting next to
his uncle, Horace Woodard, participated in a genetic study of
prostate cancer in African-American men led by African-American
physicians. The physicians included, standing from left, Herbert
Watkins, Curtis Pettaway, William Boykin Jr. and Ronald Morton.
Inherited prostate cancer accounts for about 1 in 10 cases,
according to the National Cancer Institute. (Steve Ueckert/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. Times News Service
</P>
