</P>
<P>
   For Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) _ The House Judiciary Committee
meets in closed session to begin deciding what to do about boxes of
the remaining evidence from Kenneth Starr's investigation into
President Clinton's extramarital affair. The House has released
Starr's report on the probe and the videotape of Clinton's
testimony before a federal grand jury. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   FAST-TRACK (Washington) _ Legislation that would renew the
president's fast-track trade negotiating authority is expected to
be defeated in the House. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   CIA-SPY-(Washington) _ Former CIA officer Douglas Groat became
obsessed with grievances and threatened his former employer but
didn't commit espionage against his country, a judge says in
sentencing Groat to five years in prison. By EDWARD FITZPATRICK.
</P>
<P>
   PROSTATE-CANCER (Washington) _ Prostate-cancer research
advocates led by former junk bond king Michael Milken deliver
500,000 petitions to Congress demanding increased federal funds to
counter a disease that is the No. 2 cancer killer of American men.
By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FUNDRAISER (Chicago) _ President Clinton shows up at
fund-raiser for Rep. Glenn Poshard, who is running for governor of
Illinois, only to find out that Poshard wasn't going to attend. The
Democratic representative suddenly decided to race back to
Washington to vote on trade negotiating power that Clinton has
sought. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   STORM-GEORGES (Fort Myers, Fla.) _ Hurricane Georges, packing
winds in excess of 100 mph, moves across the Florida Keys.
Forecasters say the killer storm should skirt most of South Florida
as it moves into the Gulf of Mexico. By KIM COBB.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN ELECTIONS (Paris) _ Helmut Kohl's 16 years as Germany's
head of government may be ended Sunday by a major error he
committed nearly a decade ago at the time of his country's
re-unification following the collapse of communism. By BERNARD D.
KAPLAN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CITRUS-TEXAS (Houston) _ Rains arrived in the nick of time for
citrus crops in the Lower Rio Grande Valley. The industry estimate
is that the upcoming harvest of oranges and grapefruit will be as
large or larger than last year. By NELSON ANTOSH.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ Good employees are tough to find. And
expensive. For an executive-level post, it's typical for a company
to pay a head-hunting firm 25 percent to 33 percent of an
employee's first-year salary and bonus to find just the right
person. But some companies are finding ways to circumvent those
expensive fees by doing more of the work themselves. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ELECTIONS (Washington) _ Although heartened by polls
showing most Americans don't want President Clinton to leave
office, Democrats are bracing for a negative reaction in the
November election to the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal. Republicans,
however, are on a tightrope of their own. Not pursuing impeachment
would incur the wrath of the GOP faithful. Pursuing it too
vigorously might alienate swing voters. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ACALUPCO-HURRICANE (Venustiano Carranza, Mexico) _ A year ago,
Joaquin Flores Juarez used to drive his car up the steep slope of
this hillside suburb of Acapulco and park in front of his house.
Then came Hurricane Pauline last October that washed away
hillsides. Despite the promises of political leaders last October _
including President Ernesto Zedillo _ that storm damage would
rapidly be cleaned up and repaired, residents say nothing has been
done. By PHILIP TRUE.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-ERADICATION (Chapare Jungle, Bolivia) _ Under pressure
from Washington, Bolovian President Hugo Banzer has ordered
soldiers to destroy every illegal coca plantation in the nation
within five years. But the scorched-earth tactics have provoked
violent protests in normally peaceful Bolivia. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-COCA (Cochabamba, Bolivia) _ At a time when U.S.-backed
eradication teams are bent on wiping out coca crops in South
America, activists are trying to promote the healthful properties
of coca and convince the world that coca is not cocaine. By JOHN
OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-COKE (Chipiriri, Bolivia) _ Coca-Cola buys about 200
metric tons of coca leaves annually, according to the head of the
U.S. State Department's Narcotics Affairs Section in Bolivia. A
pharmaceutical company then removes the cocaine alklaloid, and
Coca-Cola uses the mulch for flavoring. A spokesman at Coca-Cola
headquarters declined to comment on the soft drink's secret
formula. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
