</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINSTREAM RESEARCHERS TAKE A SERIOUS LOOK AT ALTERNATIVE
TREATMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: saw palmetto is CQ)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Diagnosed 10 months ago with non-Hodgkin's
lymphoma, Terry Reinhard had already had 12 weeks of chemotherapy
and another month of radiation treatment when he learned in July
that his one tumor had turned into three.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhard, 56, of San Francisco, hasn't given up on conventional
treatment _ he's scheduled to start a new round of chemotherapy
Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to go off the deep end with all the oddball
drugs and things that are out there, but I think there are a lot of
alternative things like meditation, centering, acupuncture, herbal
remedies'' that could help, Reinhard said. ``I want somebody to
look at me as a whole person, that I'm a spiritual person, and I
want someone who has the conviction that there are other things
that can heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what might work, however, remains a mystery to Reinhard
_ and to scientists. Which is a big reason why the University of
California at San Francisco has opened the new Osher Center for
Integrative Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Funded largely by a $10 million grant from the Bernard Osher
Foundation, the center aims to use scientific methods to separate
the wheat from the chaff in the fast-growing, sometimes
mind-boggling world of alternative healing.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, don't look for university researchers to give
coffee enemas or pass magnets over their subjects' injuries,
therapies still considered on the outskirts, even of alternative
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Like Reinhard, the Osher Center is initially focusing on some of
the more near-mainstream therapies. Projects planned so far involve
yoga, guided imagery and support groups for women with breast
cancer; Tibetan and Chinese herbs for other breast cancer patients
as well as for menopausal women, and a study of acupressure
wristbands (often used to prevent motion sickness) to see if they
reduce nausea from chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Ornish, the nutrition guru, is also leading a study on
whether a low-fat, plant-based diet and other lifestyle changes can
reverse prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't ruling out more far-out therapies, but so far
research is focused on questions scientists have said they wanted
to pursue, said Andrew Avins, the center's director of research.
Figuring out how to dole out limited funds will be hard, and Avins
already fields many calls from people wanting the center to prove
that this or that therapy really works.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fairly wide-open field with a very poor evidence base,
which makes choosing questions very difficult. It becomes, on some
level, a matter of guesswork, but that's the nature of where things
are now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge will be figuring out how to measure benefits
of the therapies, which often improve quality of life and patient
satisfaction, rather than simply extend life spans, Avins said.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-present placebo effect, which is believed to play a
large role in benefits many patients derive from alternative
medicine, is also tricky, he said. Even though placebos are
harmless, medically inactive pills or other treatments, people
taking them often show some improvement in their condition. Using
placebos in conventional medicine is considered a form of deception
and therefore unethical, but Avins sees the situation differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``The placebo effect may be enormously powerful and beneficial
to patients, and we are learning how it works,'' Avins said. ``How
to harness the placebo effect in an ethical manner? Those are some
very tough questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of California at San Francisco, other leading
medical centers and the government are getting into alternative
medicine research because huge numbers of people are flocking to
it. Surveys have shown that at least one in three people in the
United States has used non-traditional therapy in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford University and the University of California at Davis
also are involved in scientific evaluation of alternative
therapies. Both schools have grants from the National Institutes of
Health's Office of Alternative Medicine to open centers.
</P>
<P>
   At Davis, scientists are looking at various treatments for
asthma and the immune system. Stanford's center focuses on
developing scientific standards for evaluating alternative
therapies. The center recently opened a clinic offering
acupuncture, meditation, support groups and biofeedback to
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Avins, who considers himself squarely in the mainstream, said he
decided to study the benefits of the plant extract saw palmetto for
enlarged prostates because so many of his patients said they were
using it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, it made me nervous,'' he said. ``I don't know whether
my patients who are taking this are really onto something or
whether they are poisoning themselves, and they don't know
either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
