<SLUG> BC-SWAIN-LOLITA-PROFILE-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH DOMINIQUE SWAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Sept. 27)  
(JT) 
 By DAVID COLMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On her first visit to a New York nightclub, Dominique
Swain said she had more in common with the title character in
``Pecker'' than the one for which she is known. That is ``Lolita,''
of course.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Swain had just seen the premiere of ``Pecker'' _ John
Waters' film about a naive young Baltimore artist whose life runs
amok when he is discovered by a hot-shot Manhattan dealer _ and she
had made her way to the post-premiere party on Thursday night at
Veruka in SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   The general fabulousness of the downtown movie and art crowd
seemed to intimidate Ms. Swain, who grew up in a rural canyon in
Malibu, Calif., where there are still more rattlesnakes than Range
Rovers. Despite signing more autographs and posing for more
pictures at Veruka than any of the ``Pecker'' principals, including
Waters and the film's star, Edward Furlong, Ms. Swain acted unsure
of herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like I belong here,'' she said, hiding out in a
booth, after introductions to the artists Cindy Sherman (who has a
cameo in ``Pecker'') and Nan Goldin. ``It's all so larger than
life. I feel like a bee in Queen Mary's bonnet, in the midst of all
this elite.''
</P>
<P>
   At such moments, Ms. Swain seems younger than she is, three
years after making ``Lolita'' at age 15. The much-debated film,
which had trouble finding an American distributor because of its
subject matter, was first seen on Showtime and finally opened in
theaters on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Swain girlishly reported how Furlong had said he liked
``Lolita.'' She spoke of the fairies she's been making out of
Sculpy, a modeling clay, and sipped cranberry juice through a
straw.
</P>
<P>
   But along with such innocent enthusiasms, she also vamped her
way past the flashbulbs on her way into the club with the amused,
youthful indifference with which Lolita put on lipstick. She wore
an azure fun-fur zip-up jacket and a butterfly pin in her blond
hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love posing for photos,'' she said with a shrug. ``I've
always been kind of attention-hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   With her boyfriend, Charlie Bambrook, who held her hand
throughout the night, Ms. Swain headed straight for the back of the
room _ to the food. As a tray of sushi went by her, she took a
piece, and then another. And another. The party was looking up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frederick's of Hollywood,'' she said with a conspiratorial
smile about the source of the glitter speckling her eyelids. ``I
went in and bought it at the store. But I was 18, so it was OK They
didn't even ask for ID.''
</P>
<P>
   If she shares one thing with the character Lolita, it's a
seeming carelessness toward things that others might kill for _
like stardom at a tender age. The insouciance might have made her
perfect for Adrian Lyne's remake of ``Lolita,'' but it could well
stymie any attempts to continue a career in movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent says I don't try very hard,'' Ms. Swain sighed, while
trying to catch the sushi bearer's eye. ``If it's a part like
Lolita, I would really go after it, but all these other auditions,
I just think, I have to spend all day memorizing lines, and I might
not even get it? It's such a waste of time.'' She rolled her eyes,
and decided it was about time to leave.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
