<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR SPEAKS PASSIONATELY ON MANIC DEPRESSION _ BECAUSE HE'S BEEN
THERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Mood disorders can make life terribly
difficult, Dr. Sam Barklis says philosophically.
</P>
<P>
   He was an assistant professor at the University of Illinois
Medical School in 1957 when he suffered his first significant
high-low episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was up for about three months, and just as suddenly, I
crashed down,'' Barklis recalls. ``At times I could be so buoyant,
talking faster and faster. The flow of ideas was amazing, but I was
easily distracted. I never went anywhere in a straight line.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are manic, you can be so very convincing and
charming. Some say they could sell the Brooklyn Bridge; some become
grandiose _ free-spending, as if they have the money when they
don't. You have a very heightened sex drive and get into
relationships you have no business being in,'' he says. ``It's
exciting, but very destructive of everything around you.''
</P>
<P>
   Barklis was 32 when his manic depression was diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   His doctor immediately put him on lithium, which was being used
throughout Europe. It would be 14 more years before lithium, now
the gold-standard drug for manic depression, would be approved by
the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky to be with the University of Illinois
Neuropsychiatric Institute, a medical doctor with manic depression
and lithium at his fingertips,'' says Barklis, a doctor with a
specialty in psychopharmacology.
</P>
<P>
   Barklis is passionate and personal when he talks about mood
disorders (depression and manic depression) and anxiety disorders
(phobias).
</P>
<P>
   And he talks about them often.
</P>
<P>
   He presents free educational programs for the Depressive and
Manic Depressive Association of Fort Worth and Tarrant County the
second and fourth Friday of each month.
</P>
<P>
   The National Depressive and Manic Depressive Association
recently honored Barklis as medical adviser of the year for his
work with its Fort Worth-Tarrant County chapter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NDMDA has been remarkably successful, especially in the
last 10 years, in educating the public about mood disorders and in
promoting support groups for those affected and their families,''
Barklis says. The local group ``has reached thousands of people
over the past decade with effective programs. I am grateful to have
participated.''
</P>
<P>
   Barklis came to Fort Worth in 1968 as vice president for science
and technology for Alcon Laboratories. He was directing his own
pharmaceutical research and development company 10 years ago when
he decided to go back into private practice.
</P>
<P>
   He currently practices at the Anxiety, Mood and Phobia Center in
Fort Worth along with three psychotherapists, including his wife,
Dr. Carolyn Self.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
