A4792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-25 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES FIND NEW WAYS TO REACH FUTURE STARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good employees are tough to find. And expensive.
</P>
<P>
   For an executive-level post, it's typical for a company to pay a
headhunting firm 25 to 33 percent of an employee's first-year
salary and bonus to find just the right person.
</P>
<P>
   But some companies are finding ways to circumvent those fees by
doing more of the work themselves.
</P>
<P>
   They're finding their own candidates. They're going back to
previous employees to see if they'd consider coming back. And
they're using recruiting firms that are willing to work by the
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Such an approach was used by Loran Kaminsky, senior executive
recruiter for Ernst &AMP; Young in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Kaminsky thought about ways he could hire the best at the
cheapest price and came up with an arrangement that let him to
identify potential job candidates instead of using a full-service
recruiter.
</P>
<P>
   He asked partners to identify people who would make good
partners at Ernst &AMP; Young. The partners came up with the names of
about 20 competitors, former colleagues and folks that they know in
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Kaminsky then hired the Alexander Group for an hourly fee to
find the targeted candidates and talk them into considering a job
with Ernst &AMP; Young. The Alexander Group is a recruiting firm based
in Houston. It has offices in Boston, San Diego and San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   About seven of the candidates indicated they were interested in
the partner job and met with Kaminsky. Ernst &AMP; Young ended up
hiring one of them and probably will hire a second one from that
group.
</P>
<P>
   Kaminsky said he paid a fee of about $9,000 and figures he saved
about $250,000 in full-service commissions for the new partners.
</P>
<P>
   The search procedure yielded such great candidates and saved so
much money, Kaminsky said, that he is trying to implement it
nationwide. The same system should work just as well to find
managers and other types of employees.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are increasingly interested in ways to cut down on
their recruiting costs, said Jane Howze, managing director of the
Alexander Group. But the traditional recruiting fee structure is an
impediment to coming up with innovative ideas, said Howze, whose
firm charges between $90 and $250 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Howze recently conducted a search for one employer that wanted
to track down 100 former employees that the company had identified
as stars to see if they could be talked into returning.
</P>
<P>
   They were scattered all over the world _ England, Switzerland,
Germany _ and Howze asked them why they decided to leave and if the
problem could be straightened out.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the employees reported they didn't get along with
their supervisors or had too long a commute or they wanted a
project with more challenges. When those issues were addressed, the
company, which didn't want to be identified, was able to rehire
five of the employees.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot cheaper to hire good people who already have worked
for you or who you've already identified as solid performers than
new ones, said John Lamar, managing director of the Alexander
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar conducted a search for an accounting firm in which he
contacted people the firm had offered jobs during the previous two
years but had turned them down. Five or six people decided to go
with the firm after they were reapproached.
</P>
<P>
   That's an interesting way of recruiting, but many times
companies want someone they don't know or who may come from an
entirely different industry, said Lou Rieger, vice chairman of
SpencerStuart in Houston, a blue chip recruiting firm that charges
the traditional 33 percent fee of the first year's cash
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Rieger said he recently did a search for a big oil company
looking for a general manager of its worldwide engineering
operations. Company officials said they have 20 people they could
have promoted to the $300,000-a-year job, but they didn't want
someone who would do the same job as the person before. Rieger said
he found an engineer at a consulting firm who was used to looking
at projects from the other side of the table.
</P>
<P>
   SpencerStuart has 575,000 rising stars in its database, which
includes resumes and interview notes, so if a recruiter in Chicago
is interested in an engineer who works for a Houston company, the
recruiter can check to see who has interviewed him and what his
impressions were.
</P>
<P>
   It saves money and time because recruiters aren't flying to
another city to interview someone who wouldn't be an appropriate
candidate, Rieger said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
