<HEADER>
A4809 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN26-COX     09-25 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Joe and Bubba in Miami Beach
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ At first glance I thought I'd received a piece
of fan mail. And so it was.
</P>
<P>
   Only problem, instead of me, it was for my Cousin Bubba.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it's been most of our lives. Everybody always
liked Bubba best, especially the women.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Young of Longview, Texas, is no exception. Here's what her
letter says:
</P>
<P>
   ``You have been writing about Russia and France and England, and
even down in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those places are interesting and far away, but I'm an old
woman who is more interested in family and friends, and I tend to
worry about them if I don't hear from them often.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know how long it's been since I've heard from Bubba?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been nigh on to a year since you have written
anything about Bubba. He seems to be the kind of fellow who needs
worrying about, and I'm plum worried about Bubba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish you would devote a column to Bubba so I would know how
he's getting along.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Bubba's doing just fine, thank you for asking.
</P>
<P>
   As regular readers may recall, we are first cousins, born just
19 days apart.
</P>
<P>
   We grew up on the same block, ran with the same crowd in high
school and dated the same girls.
</P>
<P>
   When we were starting out families of our own, we bought houses
across the street from one another.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays we may go weeks without getting together in person, but
we talk on the phone most every day. Mostly we talk about taking
off on a trip, just the two of us, like we did when we were young
and single.
</P>
<P>
   For a fact, we finally did this year. I was in Florida looking
for stories, and Bubba flew down and met up with me for a
sentimental journey of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   More than 35 years ago, we made much the same trip, driving
Bubba's brand-new Ford Fairlane 1,000 miles or more nonstop from
our little hometown of Lufkin, Texas, to Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   We were poor-boying it back then. I don't remember the actual
name of the place we stayed, but we dubbed it the River Rat Arms.
Heck of a floor show, though. Refugee circus acts from Cuba were
practicing in the courtyard several floors below our window.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly we hung out around the lobby of the elegant Fontainebleau
Hotel, dressed up like we belonged, and on the lookout for movie
stars and hotel security.
</P>
<P>
   This last trip we had intended to stay at the Fontainebleau. But
it was full up, and we ended up next door at the Eden Roc. Neither
place is what it used to be, but neither are we.
</P>
<P>
   Highlight of the trip was a meal at Joe's Stone Crabs, where
nobody can get reservations, except that I happen to know a guy and
Bubba and I were able to walk right past the crowd and be escorted
directly to a table that was being held for us.
</P>
<P>
   That may be the only time in my life that I've ever managed to
impress Bubba.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. He was a hit with the staff, especially the women.
Next time he'll probably be the one who gets us a table.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how many trips together we have left in us. I keep
trying to talk him into going to Europe. I think that would make a
good story, Bubba in Russia and France and England.
</P>
<P>
   But if not there, maybe Louisiana. I'll keep you posted.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
