<HEADER>
A4812 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REMNICK-NEWYORKER-$AD     09-25 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REMNICK-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COVERING THE INK WITH PANCAKE 
</HEADLINE>
 YORKER-$ADV27-NYT  (For release Sun., Sept. 27) 
(JT) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Remnick, once a rumpled writer for The New
Yorker, appeared on ``The Charlie Rose Show'' on Sept. 13 to
discuss his appointment as editor of the magazine. Gone were the
oversize horn-rimmed glasses readers saw on the jacket of his
Pulitzer Prize-winning book, ``Lenin's Tomb,'' and Remnick appeared
to have treated himself to an $80 haircut, a stylish,
windowpane-check suit and a plump silk tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gone downtown,'' said the Time magazine columnist
Margaret Carlson, who watched the broadcast. The key to the new
Remnick sophistication? ``High-care fibers,'' she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere on the way from Watergate to Zippergate, members of
the press _ once the embodiment of tattered, inky credibility,
their integrity magnified by their degree of frumpishness _ have
become polished, sparkling, talking television heads, deft with a
stick of pancake makeup and savvy about sitting on the tails of
their suits.
</P>
<P>
   Never has the trend been more apparent than during the last two
weeks, when the all-consuming presidential crisis has delivered a
flood tide of punditry-spouting press reporters before the hot
television-studio lights. Last week, David Talbot, the editor of
Salon, the online magazine that broke the Henry Hyde story,
appeared on both the network and cable talk shows, while Newsweek's
Howard Fineman and Michael Isikoff, Time's Karen Tumulty and the
presidential biographer David Maraniss cruised the cable networks.
All _ including Isikoff, who is not usually known for paying avid
attention to his grooming habits _ were uncommonly dapper-looking.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Jonathan Alter of Newsweek, who appears regularly on
NBC News, the ``Today Show'' and MS-NBC, gets his makeup advice
from Bobbi Brown, the makeup superstar who does Vogue cover models.
(She is Alter's neighbor in New Jersey.) If a Newsweek staff member
calls Alter, his wife has been known to respond: ``Can he get back
to you? Jonathan's on the treadmill.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tucker Carlson, a newcomer to the television game and a
writer for The Weekly Standard, made one of his first appearances
on CNN a couple of years ago, a makeup artist pulled him aside
after the interview, looked at his bright-orange tie and announced:
``Tucker. Your tie. It scares me.'' Carlson now pays close
attention to his neckware.
</P>
<P>
   Messrs. Alter, Carlson and Remnick are all part of a growing
writer beautification program, sponsored by the networks that
invite them to speak. In the last two years, as all-news networks
have proliferated _ MS-NBC, Fox News Network and CNN require guests
24 hours a day _ press journalists have been more and more in
demand. (Unless they are paid consultants to a network, they are
also, it should be noted, free.)
</P>
<P>
   But the problem for the networks has been that press journalists
spend their days hunched over computer screens, they have poor
posture and their accountants don't deduct hair-styling costs from
their taxes. The men's jackets ride up; the women wear glasses.
Unpopular in high schools where looks were highly ranked in the
popularity competition, future newspaper journalists tended to
follow their hearts into print, where the power of words would
convey the beauty deep inside them.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a network to do when it gets a member of the press to
a broadcast and he shows up in a suit from Today's Man, with a soup
stain on his tie? ``We say something to people,'' said Gail Evans,
the head of booking for CNN. ``You say, `Hey, wear that blazer,'
because you once saw them in a blazer that fit. And now they seem
to be listening.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, members of the press who used to look disdainfully at
their blow-dried cousins have embraced broadcast with open arms. A
magazine writer in New York who is a frequent on-air guest said
coming back to work with a layer of pancake is a badge of pride in
his newsroom (although he was too squeamish on the subject to be
identified).
</P>
<P>
   Time magazine has installed a television studio in its offices
on the Avenue of the Americas, so magazine reporters can go live on
CNN with breaking news. Formerly disheveled journalists are
catching on to their expanded roles. ``Reporters now know things
like not to wear stuff that will assault television viewers,''
Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek staff members marvel at how Alter has apparently
slimmed down. One former Newsweek staff member said, ``You can see
real effort there.'' Another Newsweek journalist suggested that
Alter had been bleaching his teeth on the sly, to which Alter
responded ``No!'' and squeaked out a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Carlson of Time, who appears with some regularity on CNN,
uses under-eye concealer and makeup, but stops at hair spray. ``If
God had wanted your hair not to move, he would have made you like
Pamela Harriman,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Kurtz, a Washington Post reporter who covers the news
media and is himself a regular on television, said: ``There is this
voracious appetite, and a small army of bookers trying to grab
less-than-telegenic reporters because they know something about the
Lewinsky story. And they can be identified as representing
impressive news organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Remnick's spokeswoman at The New Yorker conceded he had
purchased new clothes, especially evening wear, for his more
visible role. But she denied what some New Yorker staff members
have lately been speculating about _ that his new title comes with
a clothing allowance, like top editorships at some other Conde Nast
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Smith, the senior makeup artist at CNN in Washington, said
that press reporters are exhibiting new signs of television savvy
these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to come and say, `I don't need that stuff,''' Smith
said. ``Now, they come in and say, `Hey, where's the makeup guy?'
The worst kind are the ones that halfway know what they're doing,
and they bring their own stuff, and we're like, `No, we really
don't want you to do that,' and we have to gently take it out of
their hands. But they get very excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Marina Ein, a publicity agent for The National Journal, who
often places journalists on talk shows, noted a difference between
Washington and New York reporters. ``The glamorous print reporter
is more of a New York thing,'' she maintained. ``In Washington,
they look frumped, frazzled and frantic. In the days following the
Monica Lewinsky story, Mike Isikoff barely looked dressed and he
occasionally looked positively uncombed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got a haircut!'' Isikoff, the Newsweek reporter, who
had the Lewinsky story first, protested. He revealed that he cashed
in a gift certificate to a tony Georgetown salon that a pitying
friend gave him.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ein said: ``Because of the press of political events and the
number of programs that these people appear on, there is no time
for styling in Washington. In New York, you spend time with a
makeup guy. There's time for styling.''
</P>
<P>
   Talbot, the Salon editor, who appeared on ``Good Morning
America,'' CNN, MS-NBC and several Fox Network shows last week,
said that the most important thing to remember was not makeup or
clothes. ``It's all-nude mud-wrestling shows right now,'' he said.
``Except for Charlie Rose. So the only thing you can do now is try
and keep your dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
