<HEADER>
A4835 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAUVOIR-PHILOSOPHY-2     09-25 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAUVOIR-PHILOSOPHY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMONE DE BEAUVOIR'S POSTHUMOUS RISING STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICIA COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I don't consider myself a philosopher,'' Simone de Beauvoir
wrote in the second volume of her autobiography. For decades, most
philosophers have agreed with her.
</P>
<P>
   For them, the French novelist and intellectual who wrote ``The
Second Sex,'' creating modern feminism in a single, electrifying
stroke, was Jean-Paul Sartre's philosophical sidekick, a Dr. Watson
to his Sherlock Holmes. She may have promoted and applied his
French brand of existentialism, but she was not, they argued, a
philosopher in her own right.
</P>
<P>
   But now, fueled by the discovery of previously unpublished
diaries and correspondence, a growing group of philosophers and
Beauvoir scholars declare that she deserves the rarefied title of
philosopher herself. Some even argue that she was the prime
influence on Sartre. In the process, they are helping to reverse
the slide Beauvoir's reputation took a decade ago after some of the
less-than-noble details of her relationship with Sartre were
published.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought that Beauvoir was original in her thinking,''
said Margaret Simons, a philosophy professor and the director of
women's studies at Southern Illinois University at Edwardsville,
who will publish some of these new findings in ``Beauvoir and `The
Second Sex': Feminism, Race and the Origins of Existentialism''
next year. Beauvoir's contemporaries thought the same thing. An
eminent philosopher who sat on both Sartre's and Beauvoir's
university examination committees recalled that ``everybody agreed
that, of the two, she was the real philosopher,'' according to
Deirdre Bair's 1990 biography.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, no one would more vehemently disagree with the
claim that Beauvoir was a full-blown philosopher than Beauvoir
herself. Slamming her fist on a table for emphasis and flashing her
cornflower-blue eyes, she repeatedly swore that she was Sartre's
pupil. Until the end of her life, in 1986, Beauvoir insisted that
``Philosophically I only had the role of a disciple.''
</P>
<P>
   That unflinching subordination turned their more than 50-year
partnership into one of the most fascinating and frustrating
pairings of the 20th century. As Ms. Bair describes it, the
godmother of modern feminism would drop whatever she was doing to
chauffeur, make love to, find lovers for, nurse, edit, sit with,
read to and travel with Sartre. In 1940, Beauvoir put aside her own
novel ``without the slightest pang,'' because, she wrote, ``his
theory was worth so much more than any novel I could have written
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Her letters to Nelson Algren, whom Beauvoir called ``the only
truly passionate love in my life,'' recently published in ``A
Transatlantic Affair'' (New Press, 1998) poignantly underscore the
point: She would have given up everything to be with Algren _
everything, that is, except Sartre.
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars, however, refuse to take Beauvoir at her word.
They believe that she was so caught up in protecting the image of
their ideal communion that she quashed her own contributions.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Simons, the proof of Beauvoir's originality lies in some
pages from her unpublished diary. In a passage written on July 10,
1927, when she was a 19-year-old philosophy student at the
Sorbonne, two years before she met Sartre, Beauvoir wrote: ``I must
rework my philosophical ideas . . . go deeper into the problems
that have appealed to me . . . The theme is almost always this
opposition of self and other that I felt at beginning to live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' Ms. Simons said. ``This is
earthshaking to me. She is from the beginning very interested in
the problem of otherness.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Simons, this entry and others like it contain the guts
of the existentialist theory that has long been credited to Sartre:
the idea that an individual's identity or essence isn't preordained
by God, by biology or by human nature, but begins only with the
individual's existence. What you think and do defines who you are.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1943, when Sartre wrote his existentialist manifesto,
``Being and Nothingness,'' he believed that nothing _ not money,
not social convention, not physical limitations _ could check one's
freedom. Even though an individual would always be at odds with
others, each person is totally free to choose what he does or does
not do and thus is totally responsible for all his decisions. Of
the individual's complete freedom, Sartre wrote, ``Nothing can ever
happen to it from outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Beauvoir was much more sensitive to the ways in which society
could hobble one's independence and freedom, particularly if one
belonged to the ``other'' sex, the second sex. Eleanor Holveck,
chairman of the philosophy department at Duquesne University,
explains that ``If woman is the `other,' then she can be
restricted.'' Prejudice, lack of power or unquestioned assumptions
about who brings home the bacon and who cooks it could so confine a
person's activities and imagination, that she could become unable
to ``transcend'' her particular circumstances and reach her
potential. Her freedom would be restricted.
</P>
<P>
   As Beauvoir famously wrote in ``The Second Sex:'' ``One is not
born, but rather becomes, a woman ... it is civilization as a whole
that produces this creature.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea that men are the universal gold standard and women a
second-rate alloy runs through Beauvoir's life as well as her work.
``I went to schools where girls were given textbooks exhorting them
to think like a man,'' Beauvoir said, according to Ms. Bair's
biography. ``My father praised me for having the brain of a man . .
. . No wonder I had to spend so much time thinking and writing
about myself, who and what I was.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
