r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     09-25 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD SUPER DUTY TRUCKS ARE SUPER TOUGH, SUPER LUXURIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ford's F-series pickups have been the nation's best-selling new
vehicles for more than 15 years, and the best-sellers in Texas for
the past several years. Chevrolet comes in a close second in the
Lone Star State and across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The remake of the F-150 for 1996 and the F-250 for 1997 gave the
Fords an even stronger market position over the Chevy full-size
pickups, which are just now getting updates for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford introduced yet another series of new full-size pickups
for 1999, bigger and stronger than the F-150 and F-250 models that
arrived in '96 and '97.
</P>
<P>
   They are the completely redesigned F-series Super Duty models,
introduced at January's North American International Auto Show in
Detroit. They went on sale in March, way ahead of the new
regular-duty Chevrolet and GMC full-size pickups for '99, which are
just now arriving in showrooms.
</P>
<P>
   These new Fords are the serious work trucks of the F-series
pickup line, and they are quite different from the F-150 and F-250
models that were introduced earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Designed and built on an entirely different chassis, the Super
Duty trucks _ the F-250 and F-350 _ have completely different
exteriors from the regular-duty F-150 and F-250, and are the first
heavy-duty pickups to offer four doors as the standard
configuration in the extended-cab models.
</P>
<P>
   The front end of these trucks is stronger and more
muscular-looking than the regular-duty F-series, with a pronounced
domelike hood, bright chrome grille, massive all-steel bumper and
aerodynamically styled headlights flush with the sheet metal.
</P>
<P>
   The main technical differentiation between regular-duty and
heavy-duty Ford trucks is their maximum load; the regular F-series
is designed for a gross vehicle weight (empty weighty plus
passengers and cargo) of 8,500 pounds; the Super Duty trucks are
built on a tougher steel frame for gross weights of up to 11,200
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Duty trucks come in three trim levels _ XL, XLT and
Lariat _ and are available in regular, club and crew-cab versions
with either two- or four-wheel drive.
</P>
<P>
   Our test truck for the week was the F-250 Lariat crew-cab,
long-wheelbase model, the top of the line, which has a base price
of $25,030 plus $2,810 for the Lariat package (including leather
seats) and $640 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The crew cab has a full back seat with full-size rear doors like
a Ford Expedition or Chevy Suburban. This is the perfect vehicle
for people who routinely chauffeur adults around in the back seat
(as in a work crew, hence the ``crew cab'' designation), but also
need the pickup bed for hauling.
</P>
<P>
   The back seat is nice for the kids, too, and not quite as
crowded as that of the Super Cab models.
</P>
<P>
   Designed primarily for small-business and ranch use, these
trucks are also popular in some places _ such as Texas _ as
personal transportation, particularly by people who have active
lifestyles that involve pulling horse trailers or fifth-wheel
campers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you don't have to pull a trailer to justify buying
one of these. Two minutes behind the wheel of our test vehicle and
I was ready to buy one just to negotiate rush-hour traffic on the
local freeways.
</P>
<P>
   There are some drawbacks, of course. For one, it's too big to
fit in the average parking space. But out on the freeways, it's
just the thing to tame the aggressive jerks in their boy-racer cars
and pickups. Ain't nobody gonna mess with you when you're driving
one of these, I'll guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   Three engine choices are available, beginning with the 5.4-liter
Triton V-8, cranking out 235 horsepower and 335 foot-pounds of
torque. You can upgrade to the 6.8-liter Triton V-10, with 275
horsepower and 410 foot-pounds of torque. Both of these engines
operate on regular gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   If you're into serious hauling, such as a huge horse trailer
with living quarters, you might opt for the 7.3-liter turbocharged
V-8 diesel (a $4,445 option), with 235 horsepower (at just 2,700
rpm) and a whopping 500 foot-pounds of torque (at just 1,600 rpm).
This was the engine on our test truck, and the power the diesel
offered made the truck truly a joy to drive.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing not to like about these trucks. The interior is
remarkably comfortable and carlike, a clear indication that Ford
understands that people who drive these vehicles often virtually
live in them on long cross-country trips. The ride is remarkably
smooth; the suspension won't beat you to death, even on bumpy side
roads.
</P>
<P>
   Standard on the diesel models is a six-speed manual
transmission, but our test vehicle came with the optional
four-speed automatic ($970), which helped make the truck even more
carlike. Although I know there are manual-transmission purists who
would rather shift gears themselves, the automatic makes driving a
lot easier, especially when pulling a trailer on a long trip.
</P>
<P>
   There is ample room for three adults in the front seat, but if
you're alone or traveling with only a front passenger, you can fold
down the center of the seat between the driver and passenger to
form a combination armrest and mobile desk. This includes a bin
that is large enough to hold a laptop computer or portable fax
machine, and there is an extra power outlet besides the one used
for the cigarette lighter.
</P>
<P>
   A driver's side air bag is standard; a passenger air bag is
optional on XL and XLT models but was standard on our Lariat. It
comes with a deactivation switch on regular and Super Cab models so
you can put a rear-facing infant seat up front. On the crew cab
models like ours, the baby seat would have to go in the back seat.
</P>
<P>
   The cab is very carlike, with convenient and easy-to-operate
controls; big, readable instruments, and two large cupholders.
Cloth or vinyl seats are offered in base and midlevel models.
</P>
<P>
   Standard four-wheel disc brakes replace the previous front
disc/rear drum configuration, and rear-wheel antilock brakes are
standard. Four-wheel antilock brakes, included on our test vehicle,
are a $500 option _ a good safety feature to add to your list of
extra equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Other options on our vehicle included limited-slip rear axle
($260), trailer-towing package ($190), spare tire and wheel ($270),
premium in-dash AM/FM/cassette/compact disc stereo ($190), roof
clearance lights ($55), chrome rear step bumper ($150) and
trailer-hitch receiver ($150).
</P>
<P>
   Total price was $34,195, including transportation and a $1,405
options-package discount.
</P>
<P>
   F-350 Super Duty versions are available in the dual-rear-wheel
configuration commonly referred to as a ``dually,'' and even though
this is a cool truck with its wide rear end, it's a bit tough to
maneuver in city traffic. The dual rear wheels are meant for heavy
trailering.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel-economy ratings were not provided to us for any of these
trucks; the EPA does not require manufacturers to publish ratings
on vehicles over 8,500 pounds. The fuel tank on long-wheelbase
models holds 36 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Check out his Wheelin' new-car review column
weekly on the Internet at
ww.netarrant.net/today/news/opinions/necol.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
