<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 16:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAUVOIR-PHILOSOPHY-2     09-25 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAUVOIR-PHILOSOPHY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: I was.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A pinched sense of freedom can come not only from a hostile
world, but also from friends and lovers. As Ms. Simons says of
Beauvoir, she was also all too familiar with ``the problem of
losing your self in loving the other so much that you fuse your
identity with the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was Beauvoir's sensitivity to the web of relations
among people that led her to develop a full-fledged ethical theory,
says Kristana Arp, a philosophy professor and Beauvoir scholar at
Long Island University in Brooklyn. ``To will oneself free is also
to will others free,'' Beauvoir wrote in 1946 in the ``Ethics of
Ambiguity.'' Ethics were a footnote in ``Being and Nothingness,''
says Ms. Arp, but Beauvoir believed that ``in order to develop my
freedom, I have to work to develop the freedom of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward and Kate Fullbrook, British scholars, make the most
ambitious and controversial claim of all in their new book,
``Simone de Beauvoir: A Critical Introduction,'' (Polity Press,
1998): ``Beauvoir, and not Sartre, was the intellectual force
behind some of the key ideas which characterized French
existentialism in its most influential phase.''
</P>
<P>
   Using Sartre's wartime diaries and letters from Beauvoir, the
Fullbrooks discovered that Sarte had read an early manuscript of
Beauvoir's philosophical novel ``L'Invitee'' (``She Came to Stay'')
before he started writing ``Being and Nothingness,'' not after, as
had previously been believed. The Fullbrooks conclude that
Beauvoir's ideas in ``L'Invitee'' about relations between people,
the body, as well as the temptation to deceive oneself, or ``bad
faith,'' were not simply an application of Sartre's ideas, but the
reverse: the source of his own work.
</P>
<P>
   That's too much for even diehard Beauvoir fans. ``If she says
she got the notion of human freedom from Sartre,'' Ms. Holveck
says, ``I personally would hesitate to say that she didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   So who is the chicken and who is the egg? The truth may lie
somewhere in between. As Bob Stone, a philosophy professor at C.W.
Post College at Long Island University, says: ``It's altogether
possible that these ideas were in some sense originated by
Beauvoir, but in creative couples, there is such intense
interchange and development of ideas, it's very difficult to say
who originated the idea and who wrote it down.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, interest in Beauvoir is already ``exploding,'' says
Stone. Next year there will be a 50th anniversary celebration of
``The Second Sex,'' an international conference on the book and a
shelf full of new scholarly books published on Beauvoir.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the degree of interest isn't the only change; slowly and
subtly the sentiment surrounding Beauvoir's legacy seems to be
shifting too. Fewer than 10 years ago, when Beauvoir's and Sartre's
correspondence and diaries were published, with their disturbing
revelations of their tortured sexual lives and their manipulation
of other people, both reputations were tarnished. Shortly after
Deirdre Bair wrote her Beauvoir biography, she was stunned by how
many women she heard from, young and old, housewives and
professionals, who felt betrayed by their idol, Beauvoir. As one
said: Beauvoir ``told us she lived a perfect feminist life, so we
believed her and she inspired us, and now we don't have that
inspiration anymore. We believed her and she let us down.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the fallen idol is being picked up and dusted off. One
reason may be that feminist philosophers don't have many idols to
spare. ``Women philosophers are aware of how men discount the work
of women,'' Ms. Arp says. ``You look back and it's all Sartre,
Sartre, Sartre. What about Beauvoir? She wasn't his lap dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason Beauvoir is being rehabilitated may have
something to do with the drift of feminist theory. Sonia Kruks, a
professor of political theory and the director of the women's
studies program at Oberlin College suggested that the last wave of
gender theorists, ``went too far'' in declaring that it is culture,
not biology, that determines what are male and female traits.
``People are beginning to grope for some other way to answer that
question of what is a woman.'' And that has led scholars back to
Beauvoir. Like her friend Maurice Merleau-Ponty, a philosopher,
Beauvoir investigated ``the way our bodies shape how we can
experience the world and how we can act in the world,'' Ms. Kruks
says.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the recent sympathetic fascination with Beauvoir
represents a softening in today's culture. If the mania for
exposing secret, sordid details has blunted society's sense of
shame, maybe it has also humbled the rush to judgment. People may
be more accustomed to _ if not more understanding of _ how far
short people can fall of their own ideals.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, Beauvoir's philosophical rise happens to
coincide with Sartre's declining reputation and the demise of
French existentialism in general. Still, one can't help wonder
whether Beauvoir, who sacrificed so much for Sartre while they were
alive, would find much joy in finding herself elevated above him
after their deaths.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
