<SLUG> BC-AIRPORTS-GPS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATELLITES TO ALTER PLANES' LANDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By REBECCA ROLWING  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - A recent Continental Airlines flight that would put a
weary business traveler to sleep gave Honeywell's Michael Smith
cause to cheer.
</P>
<P>
   The flight, which started in Washington, stopped in Newark,
N.J., and landed in Minneapolis, marked the first commercial flight
using global positioning satellites to track and guide planes as
they land and take off.
</P>
<P>
   For travelers, the system promises safer landings, fewer
weather-related delays and less time thumbing through old magazines
while the plane sits on the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   For airlines, it stands to cut down on congestion and provide
more precise data on where planes are. It also will allow airports
to consider alternative landing paths _ a big bonus for angry
people who live under existing paths.
</P>
<P>
   And for Smith, Honeywell's vice president and general manager in
Phoenix, it's a step toward the airport of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This landing system that we demonstrated (Monday) is one step
toward . . . the way that airplanes are going to be managed as time
goes on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It requires the perspective of Roy Fuhrmann, aviation noise and
satellite program manager at the Metropolitan Airports Commission
in Minneapolis, to grasp the dynamics of aviation technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole new style of navigation capabilities that we
haven't seen for the last 30 to 40 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The GPS landing system, called SLS-2000, was developed by
Honeywell's Glendale-based Airport Systems division and Pelorus
Navigation Systems Inc. of Calgary, Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   In the works since 1994, it is the first GPS landing system to
get full approval from the Federal Aviation Administration. And
it's expected to quickly woo the world's airports and airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so good and it's so cheap . . . that there's a likelihood
that it will be adopted relatively fast,'' said Fred Abbott, vice
president of flight operations for Continental Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Honeywell is leading a government-involved consortium that will
install the system at 18 major airports and modify the aircraft of
10 airlines. The Federal Aviation Administration is expected to
kick off the consortium before the end of the year, and the planes
should be using the new equipment by this time next year.
</P>
<P>
   Most major U.S. airports use an instrument landing system. It
shoots a beam into the air about five miles out that the pilot
lines up with and follows in to land the plane. It requires pilots
to directly approach the runway, rather than coming in on a curve.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Honeywell/Pelorus system puts equipment on the
plane that allows global positioning satellites to track its
location. A ground station processes that information, finds the
best path for the plane to land and gives exact landing directions
to the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us the opportunity to know the precise location of an
aircraft at any given time, and it gives pilots the opportunity to
fly to a specific point'' rather than tracking a beam, Fuhrmann
said.
</P>
<P>
   While an instrument landing system costs up to $1.5 million and
must be placed at the end of each runway, a single GPS ground
station runs about $500,000 and can control all runway ends within
a 30-mile radius.
</P>
<P>
   Upgrading the planes costs between $40,000 and $100,000,
depending on the kind of plane and the equipment used. That price
is expected to drop over time.
</P>
<P>
   Since the system individually maps the best route down, the
pilots can come in at a curve rather than having to follow a beam
straight into the runway.
</P>
<P>
   That's an earful for those who live near noisy flight paths.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get too excited though, Fuhrmann warns. ``The GPS doesn't
take noise out of air. It gives the community the opportunity to
more precisely define where it is that they want that noise to
go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, limitations in existing technology force the airport to
require longer lag times between plane landings during bad weather,
Fuhrmann said.
</P>
<P>
   The accuracy offered by SLS-2000 should mean flights can stick
to their scheduled departure times during storms and snow flurries.
</P>
<P>
   It also will provide advantages as airports become more crowded
over the next several years. Some airports have runways so close
together that they might not allow flights to land at the same
time. The SLS-2000 should allow planes to zip in on both runways,
Abbott said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the system is just one element Honeywell is working
on to improve efficiency at airports.
</P>
<P>
   Other projects include using global positioning satellites to
track all vehicles at the airport. And Honeywell offers a lighting
system to control traffic on the tarmac. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
