<SLUG> BC-TV-FANTASY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAME OLD FANTASY ON `ISLAND' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
FANTASY ISLAND 
Starring: Malcolm McDowell, Madchen Amick, Louis Lombardi, Edward
Hibbert, Fyvush Finkel, Sylvia Sydney 
On: ABC 
Time: Saturday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new ``Fantasy Island'' looks absolutely fantastic. Shot on
location in Hawaii, it's a slick, inviting travel brochure of
gorgeous oceanscapes, pristine beaches, and lush green wilderness.
The mountains are majestic, and the island skies are full of drama,
with muscular clouds that speed up and slow down according to the
whims of our tasteful host, Mr. Roarke. A British gentleman with a
debonaire manner, Mr. Roarke dresses strictly in basic black,
requesting that all his predecessor's tacky white outfits be
torched.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it looks like a million bucks, but in its soul, the new
``Fantasy Island'' is still the old ``Fantasy Island,'' a
collection of superficial vignettes that are obvious, corny, and
moralistic. The darkly magical affectations are thanks to the
show's executive producer Barry Sonnenfeld, director of visually
splendid movies like ``The Addams Family'' and ``Men in Black,''
but the fluffy plot lines bear the stamp of the original show's
executive producer, a well-known cheese magnate by the name of
Aaron Spelling.
</P>
<P>
   And that's too bad, because the new ``Fantasy Island'' could
have been a latter-day ``Twilight Zone,'' with surreal adult
fantasies that delve into some unusual psychic corners. Instead,
the visitors to the island are subjected to adventures that are as
psychologically inventive as a game of Mystery Date and as familiar
as Charles Dickens's ``A Christmas Carol,'' or ``It's a Wonderful
Life.'' Tonight, a man who thinks he married the wrong woman gets
to date the right woman, who turns out to be the wrong woman;
competitive sisters go head on in a game of Jeopardy; and a man who
likes life-threatening sports activities learns to appreciate life.
By the end, all the characters have had the correct realizations.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm McDowell is the new, improved Mr. Roarke, the wizard
behind this tropical Oz. He's part Rod Serling, part Robin Leach,
as he welcomes his guests to the island with a mysterious but
cordial air. Instead of a midget assistant named Tattoo, who sights
visitors, yelling ``Da plane, da plane!,'' he has a trio of
indentured sidekicks who quietly help him cast his spells. One of
them, played by Madchen Amick, has the ability to morph into other
physical identities. All three are bound to Roarke in some way that
may become clearer as the series develops.
</P>
<P>
   A sweet new gimmick has each episode begin and end in a musty
old travel agency on a city street, where a kindly man played by
Fyvush Finkel greets visitors destined for the island. His prickly
assistant, played by Sylvia Sydney, adds a touch of class. But the
pair might as well be planning trips for UPN's remake of ``The Love
Boat.'' It's not as good-looking as the new ``Fantasy Island,'' but
it's just as much of a throwback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
