<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN `UH-OH' FROM THE FED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 27, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
(begin poetry style) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I am changing my name to Chrysler,
</P>
<P>
   I am going down to Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   I will tell some power broker,
</P>
<P>
   `What you did for Iacocca
</P>
<P>
   Would be perfectly acceptable to me.'
</P>
<P>
   I am changing my name to Chrysler,
</P>
<P>
   I am leaving for that great receiving line.
</P>
<P>
   When they hand a million grand out
</P>
<P>
   I'll be standing with my hand out,
</P>
<P>
   Yes sir, I'll get mine.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Changing my name to Chrysler,'' by Tom Paxton &QL; 
 &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve-sponsored bailout of a high-flying hedge
fund Thursday signals the rest of the financial world that it's
time to race for the exits.
</P>
<P>
   Like the dreaded shout of ``Fire!'' in the apocryphal crowded
theater, the quick shuffle organized by the New York Fed to save
Long-Term Capital Management L.P. may ignite a surge.
</P>
<P>
   If Wall Street insiders can have their bacon saved by a $3.5
billion emergency bailout by other Wall Street biggies, why should
all the other likely victims of what may become a planetwide
economic retrenchment swallow their losses and sulk in silence? If
this proves to be a one-time-only favor to accommodate some
extremely well heeled insiders, then the deal will begin to smell
like a five-day old haddock.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital went short-term, disastrously, after making
its rich investors even more rich. The Wall Street Journal says
that John Meriwether's for-rich-guys-only outfit had profits of 17
percent, 41 percent, and 43 percent the past three years. And while
it is true that the emergency bailout is money from other financial
houses, the New York Fed's role in midwifing the bailout will not
escape all the other folks who stand to get hurt in this worldwide
economic swoon.
</P>
<P>
   America's farmers, for instance, are getting slaughtered by the
drop in Asian demand, an across-the-board sag in prices, and keener
foreign competition. Result? Net farm income in the United States
will fall by 16 percent this year, says the government.
</P>
<P>
   When the sodbusters of Iowa and Nebraska, and the cowpunchers of
Texas and Oklahoma, realize that their income is dropping 16
percent, while the Big Boys on Wall Street are saving each other's
bacon, there will be hell to pay. And all those Sunbelt and
Midwestern congressmen who are messing around with
What-Monica-told-Linda-about-Bill's-drawers are going to be flogged
royally if they don't deliver some fast federal relief.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Paxton's nifty tune satirizing the Chrylser bailout could
serve as an anthem for those whose interests are sacrificed by
Congress in order that the already rich stay rich. ``We were hardly
up and walking,'' croons Paxton, ``before money started talking,''
and, ``If you're a corporate Titanic, and your failure is gigantic,
down in Congress there's a safety net for you.''
</P>
<P>
   A Congress that gorges on soft money stuffed down its greasy
throat by special interests is not a Congress that will win much
sympathy when the peasantry starts to revolt. And our super-hot
economy is in danger of derailing into Gluttony Gulch.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration still predicts 2.4 percent growth for
this year. But the rest of the world is dragging us down. No one in
authority anywhere is saying things will not get worse before they
get better. Evidence keeps emerging, like fossils tossed up by a
melting glacier, that financial institutions around the world are
shakier than anyone comprehended. The gold rush mentality of the
'90s created a worldwide credit bubble that is in the process of
breaking.
</P>
<P>
   Last week one of Britain's savviest politicians came through
Boston on a book tour. Chris Patten, the last British governor of
Hong Kong, handed over the go-go Asian financial capital to the
Chinese, and then wrote a very readable and timely assessment of
what's going on in Asia, titled: ``East and West; China, Power, and
the Future of Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Patten believes that the West obsesses about _ but fails to
understand _ China. While it has a quarter or a fifth of the
world's people, the United States exports as much to Australia (16
million people) as to China (1.2 billion). ``They're approaching a
real deflationary period in China,'' warned Patten. Then he dropped
this clue: ``I suspect their dollar-denominated debt is much
greater than they acknowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulp. The big banks of Japan are under water, sucked down by
vast debts that are now virtually uncollectible. The big banks of
Europe _ France and Germany and Switzerland _ got on the Asian
gravy train early, and got off too late. Think about what happened
to the train in the Bridge over the River Kwai.
</P>
<P>
   Patten mused wryly about ``the ball-and-chain job that will be
done on the (Japanese) economy when they start closing banks,''
which everyone outside Japan regards as an inevitability. It used
to be that Asian investments were funded by government money; now
it's private capital that's at stake, and much of it will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large short-term `hot' money flows into countries with
inadequate regulation of financial services is asking for
trouble,'' shrugged the former chairman of Britain's Conservative
Party. And the piper is at the door, demanding to be paid. Patten
says private investors ``should pay a price for being rescued.''
His philosophical bottom line: ``A lot of people behaved as
greedily and stupidly as ever. I don't know how you legislate
avarice out of the human condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The US Congress _ dumber than the Duma in the collective
tendency to fiddle while financial Rome burns _ is going to face
searing heat this fall to bail out this interest or that one. It
could be worse than the S&AMP;L bailout of the '80s. And the
Republicans who just voted down the hike in the minimum wage are
going to be squirming when their pals from Wall Street show up in
``that great receiving line.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
