<HEADER>
A4888 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHERS26-COX     09-25 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCHOOLS TAKING WRONG APPROACH TO OVERCROWDING, EDUCATORS
SAY(backslash)
 &HT;    380&AMP;add.
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Handing out emergency teaching credentials and
loading classroom duties on new teachers is the wrong way to deal
with America's overcrowded classrooms, the nation's two largest
teachers' groups said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members know that one incompetent teacher, one unprepared
teacher in a school is one too many,'' said Sandra Feldman,
president of the American Federation of Teachers (AFT). ``They know
the children suffer and when they get those children the following
year, they suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, more than 50,000 teachers lacked the training
required for their jobs and entered teaching on emergency or
substandard licenses, according to a 1996 report of the National
Commission on Teaching and America's Future.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the problem, new teachers are given excessive
workloads and too little mentoring, said Bob Chase, president of
the National Education Association (NEA).
</P>
<P>
   ``Many districts talk about putting a qualified teacher in every
classroom, but in reality too often there is a sink-or-swim policy
for new teachers,'' said Chase. ``The trouble with this approach is
when a teacher sinks so do his or her students.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase suggested that new teachers' work days be divided into two
parts, one devoted to teaching and one focused on training.
</P>
<P>
   The educators' comments came at a conference on teacher quality
sponsored by the NEA, which represents more than 2.4 million
educators, and the AFT, an affiliate of the AFL-CIO labor union
confederation. Participants included teachers, school board
members, superintendents, government officials and others from 80
communities across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The conference came at a time when the nation's schools are
facing severe teacher shortages.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Texas, for example, public school officials this year
raced to fill 116 teacher vacancies for its 98 campuses before the
start of school Aug. 12. Most openings were for high-demand math,
science and certified bilingual and special education teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Conference participants said the outlook for solving the
shortage issue is bleak. Nearly 50 percent of new teachers in urban
schools leave within their first five years of teaching, but an
estimated 2 million new teachers will be needed in the next 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Feldman also criticized school vouchers _ public stipends that
allow low-income children to attend schools of their choosing. She
said vouchers would not solve the declining quality of education
and that more emphasis should be placed on reducing class size and
increasing teacher training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think to experiment with America's poor children is wrong,''
Feldman said. ``We need to put in programs that we know work and
have a proven record of working.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldman and Chase said a joint council has been formed to
address such issues, and that solutions to these problems lies on
the local level. They encouraged city and state groups to continue
working on ways to prepare students for the challenges they will
face after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Education Secretary Richard Riley also addressed the conference
and said that increased parental involvement is needed in schools
and that the ``cumbersome'' teacher certification needs to be
revamped.
</P>
<P>
   Riley suggested the enactment of student loan forgiveness
programs for students who choose teaching as a profession and
grants to help states improve their teacher certification
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
