<HEADER>
A4907 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN26-COX     09-25 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Smile, cutie, and welcome to East Texas
</P>
<P>
   By Gary Borders
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   News item, from the Associated Press: ``Twelve Safeway employees
</P>
<P>
   have filed grievances over the supermarket chain(pi)s
</P>
<P>
   smile-and-make-eye-contact rule, complaining that they are being
</P>
<P>
   propositioned by shoppers who mistake company-required
friendliness for
</P>
<P>
   flirting.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the employees who filed the grievance said she is hit on
every day
</P>
<P>
   by men who think she is coming on to them.
</P>
<P>
   Let (begin ital) me (end ital) decide who I am going to say
hello to
</P>
<P>
   with a big smile,(pi)(pi) Richelle Roberts said in the AP story.
She added: aaA
</P>
<P>
   woman knows where and when not to open that door for certain
men.(pi)(pi)
</P>
<P>
   The company has a new policy, called ``Superior Service,'' which
requires
</P>
<P>
   employees to be friendly, and even uses undercover shoppers to
catch surly
</P>
<P>
   workers, according to the AP.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints come from Safeway workers in the San Francisco
area. The
</P>
<P>
   complaints will be heard by the National Labor Relations Board,
since the
</P>
<P>
   workers are unionized.
</P>
<P>
   I have a few observations to make:
</P>
<P>
   Any man who mistakes a cashier's smile and greeting as a
flirtation by a
</P>
<P>
   potential new love bunny has got a serious case of
swell-headedness,
</P>
<P>
   compounded by possible hallucinatory spells. He needs to take a
hard look in
</P>
<P>
   the mirror and realize that no, he is decidedly (begin ital)not
(end
</P>
<P>
   ital)God's gift to women.
</P>
<P>
   In East Texas particularly, any man delusional enough to think
every
</P>
<P>
   cashier that smiles and drawls, ``Y'all come back, now'' is
coming on to him
</P>
<P>
   likely will face at least two consequences:
</P>
<P>
   The cashier will threaten to sic her husband, boyfriend or
brother on
</P>
<P>
   the miscreant. This gentleman will be the size of a side-by-side
</P>
<P>
   refrigerator. His name will either be Bubba, or he'll have a
double name,
</P>
<P>
   such as Joe Don. The deluded Don Juan will know Bubba's name
because he will be wearing a western belt that has the name stiched
on the back. The masher might end up with the name stenciled on his
backside, if he doesn't
</P>
<P>
   immediately apologize and promise to never take liberties with
the cashier
</P>
<P>
   again.
</P>
<P>
   Or, the cashier will erupt into hysterical laughter, let her
co-workers
</P>
<P>
   in on the joke and make the masher feel about three feet tall:
``Didja heah
</P>
<P>
   what that peckerwood said to me? He thinks he's Gawd's gift to
women, and he looks lahk he got whupped by an ugly stick. Doesn't
that beat all-get-out?''
</P>
<P>
   Last, who would want to live somewhere where friendly service is
so rare
</P>
<P>
   that men think women workers who smile and say ``Hi!'' are
lusting after them?
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, folks in East Texas are friendly. We still
wave at
</P>
<P>
   pedestrians as we drive by, still allow cars to ease out of
parking lots in
</P>
<P>
   front of us on our busy streets, and still expect clerks and
cashiers to say
</P>
<P>
   thank you and hurry back.
</P>
<P>
   I said for the most part. There are some exceptions out there,
some old
</P>
<P>
   grumps and some young ones too. Sadly, even in our friendly
little town,
</P>
<P>
   there are people who don't deliver service with a smile.
Luckily, they are
</P>
<P>
   the exception.
</P>
<P>
   Rare as it may be, nothing gets on my last nerve more than a
surly
</P>
<P>
   waitress, fast-food worker or cashier. Fast-food places in my
unscientific
</P>
<P>
   view have more unfriendly and unhappy workers than other service
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The grumps are still in a minority, but there are too many folks
who will
</P>
<P>
   hand you a bag full of burgers and fries without so much as a
``thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   These workers are invariably young, and perhaps did not learn
manners as
</P>
<P>
   children. I usually try to teach them, by sarcastically saying
``you're
</P>
<P>
   welcome,'' to these future captains of industry, but I'm not
sure they get
</P>
<P>
   it.
</P>
<P>
   My policy is simple. If a hamburger or taco joint has rude or
indifferent
</P>
<P>
   workers, I go somewhere else. Lord knows there are plenty to
choose from.
</P>
<P>
   A smile and pleasant greeting go a long way. Most folks who deal
with the
</P>
<P>
   public know that. Just because a few dunderheads out there
mistake that
</P>
<P>
   friendliness for animal magnetism or some such nonsense is no
reason to quit
</P>
<P>
   doing it. Tell the Romeo wannabe to buzz off or you'll call his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   For those few in our neck of the woods who can't seem to muster
a smile or
</P>
<P>
   a thank you to their customers, I offer this bit of advice:
</P>
<P>
   Move to the big city as soon as possible. They're apparently
used to such
</P>
<P>
   behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
