<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4923 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS24-TAKE     09-25 1998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS24-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know that if President Clinton resigns, or is impeached,
convicted and removed from office, Al Gore becomes president and
Gore would appoint a new vice president to replace himself. If that
happens, and then Gore is impeached, would that vice president
become president? Or would Newt Gingrich become president?
</P>
<P>
   A: In your scenario, the vice president who had been nominated
by President Gore would become president if Gore were impeached and
convicted (or if he died, resigned or left office for any reason).
Then that president would nominate another vice president, who
would be subject to congressional confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   The only way succession would come into play would be if both
the office of president and the office of vice president became
vacant at the same time; for example, if both were assassinated or
resigned. In presidential succession, the following government
officials would be next in line to the presidency, if they are
American-born: speaker of the House; president pro tempore of the
Senate; secretary of state; secretary of the treasury; secretary of
defense; attorney general; and so on down a specified line.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are legal aliens eligible for Social Security benefits?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, but several conditions must be met, said Social Security
Administration spokeswoman Patti Patterson: The person must be
lawfully admitted into the United States; must be authorized to
work; must work under a job that is covered by Social Security; and
must meet all eligibility requirements to receive Social Security
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've heard that Army is now a member of a football league.
What is it, and what other teams are members?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's Conference USA. These are all the teams: Army Cadets,
Cincinnati Bearcats, East Carolina Pirates, Houston Cougars,
Louisville Cardinals, Memphis Tigers, Southern Mississippi Golden
Eagles, Tulane Greenwave. Before this season, Army was an
independent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will comprise the Monet exhibit in Boston, and how can
we get tickets?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Monet in the 20th Century,'' at Boston's Museum of Fine
Arts, is made up of more than 80 paintings. The works include
Monet's early views of his gardens at Giverny, France, with a
concentration on the Japanese bridge paintings of 1900; views of
London (1900-1904) and Venice (1908); a partial re-creation of
Monet's water lily exhibition of 1909, featuring more than 20
canvases painted between 1903 and1908; views of the water lily pond
done in Monet's new bold style between 1914 and 1918; later, more
abstract views of the famed weeping willow and Japanese bridge; and
a gathering of the enormous water lily murals painted between 1919
and 1926, some measuring more than 18 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, which opened Sunday, closes Dec. 27. Ticket
information: 617-542-4632; general museum information:
617-267-9300. Information also can be viewed at www.mfa.org online.
After leaving Boston, the exhibition will travel to the Royal
Academy of Arts in London, where it will be on view Jan. 21-April
18.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where does the name Caesar salad originate?
</P>
<P>
   A: Imperial Julius doesn't figure into it. Nor does ``Prince''
Mike Romanoff, who popularized the salad at his Hollywood
restaurant decades ago. The salad _ made with romaine lettuce,
garlic-flavored olive oil, lemon juice, grated parmesan cheese,
Worcestershire sauce and garlic-flavored croutons (anchovies
optional) _ is generally credited to Caesar Gardini, who ran
Caesar's Place, a restaurant in Tijuana, Mexico. According to the
story, one day in the early 1920s many more hungry tourists than
expected stopped at his restaurant on their way north from the
bullfights, races, beaches and other Baja California attractions.
So he improvised a salad from the ingredients he had on hand. The
result: Caesar salad. At one time a raw or coddled egg was another
ingredient, added tableside during preparation _ but for safety
reasons, that isn't done anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We frequently see that old photo of the young Bill Clinton
shaking hands with President John F. Kennedy. Has Clinton ever said
if that meeting with Kennedy was what sparked his interest in
politics?
</P>
<P>
   A: Clinton has said that his meeting Kennedy in the White House
Rose Garden, in the summer of 1963, made him want to run for
president. The teen-ager was an Arkansas delegate to Boys Nation, a
Washington conclave sponsored by the American Legion. In
interviews, Clinton still lists that meeting as the most memorable
day of his childhood. ``I never made a secret of the fact that when
I was 16 years old, I decided, if I can do that, that's something
I'd like to do,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But his interest in politics is said to have begun earlier, at
age 9, when he watched the Democratic and Republican nominating
conventions on television. Clinton's first political campaign was
for Congress in 1974, when he was 27. By the time he launched his
first campaign for president, Clinton had been in 17 primary and
general election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to send a letter of support to the president and
his family. What is the address?
</P>
<P>
   A: President Bill Clinton, The White House, 1600 Pennsylvania
Ave., Washington, DC 20500.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have an address for Kenneth Starr? We want to send him
our thanks and appreciation for what he is doing.
</P>
<P>
   A: Kenneth Starr, Office of Independent Counsel, 1001
Pennsylvania Ave. N.W., Suite 490 North, Washington, DC 20001.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Television coverage of the funeral of former Alabama Gov.
George Wallace showed that his casket, as it was being carried into
the Alabama Capitol, was covered with a white cloth with a red X.
What was that about?
</P>
<P>
   A: The casket was draped with the Alabama state flag, which
bears a crimson cross on a white field. The X is enormous,
stretching across all four corners of the flag. World Book
Encyclopedia notes that the cross is suggestive of the Confederate
battle flag.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the B.C. stand for in the recent Professional
Golfers Association tour event, the B.C. Open in Endicott, N.Y.?
</P>
<P>
   A: Endicott is in Broome County in south-central New York state.
The Broome County Community Charities has sponsored the B.C. Open
since it began _ as the Broome County Open _ in 1971. The event's
name was abbreviated in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who was the first American pilot shot down and captured in
Southeast Asia in the '60s?
</P>
<P>
   A: Several names are sometimes mentioned, but the Dictionary of
the Vietnam War and the Encyclopedia of the Vietnam War agree that
he was Lt. (jg) Everett Alvarez Jr. of San Jose, Calif. He also was
listed as first in a People magazine interview in February 1990 in
connection with a book he co-wrote about the experience, ``Chained
Eagle.'' Piloting an A-4 Skyhawk from the USS Constellation, he was
shot down over North Vietnam on Aug. 5, 1964. Four aircraft taking
part in the air raid, code-named Pierce Arrow, were lost. Alvarez
was transferred to the prison nicknamed Hanoi Hilton and spent the
next eight-plus years as a prisoner of war.
</P>
<P>
   He was among the first group of American POWs granted freedom
after the Paris truce agreement was signed in January 1973. When he
returned home, he was awarded a Silver Star, two Legions of Merit,
two Purple Hearts and several other medals. He continued in a desk
job with the Navy until retirement in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez subsequently earned a law degree from George Washington
University and served as deputy director of the Peace Corps and
deputy administrator of the Veterans Administration (now the
Department of Veteran Affairs). At last report, he was a computer
consultant in Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are President Clinton's medical records available to the
public?
</P>
<P>
   A: Generally speaking, no. They aren't public documents, said
White House spokeswoman Megan Maloney. They're his own personal
business, just like anybody else's records, she added. However, in
October 1996, before the general election in November, the White
House released Clinton's most recent such records to the media. It
was done as part of a briefing by press secretary Mike McCurry.
Internet sleuths can find it on the White House Web site _
www.whitehouse.gov _ by searching by term or by date (October
1996), Maloney said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you refresh my memory about Victoria Woodhull, who once
ran for the presidency? Also, doesn't the Libertarian Party
frequently put women on its ticket?
</P>
<P>
   A: Victoria Claflin Woodhull (1838-1927) indeed did run for the
presidency, in 1872, as a candidate of the new Equal Rights Party.
Women's voting rights groups admired her stand in favor of allowing
women to vote, but they rejected her candidacy on other issues she
supported, such as the right of women to have love affairs, whether
married or not. She co-founded a newspaper, then used it to promote
communism, free love and legal prostitution. It also was her
platform to expose the sexual shenanigans of a powerful New York
minister, a move that led to her own jailing. In 1870, Woodhull and
her sister, Tennessee Claflin, established the first stock
brokerage firm owned by women, in New York. After divorcing her
second husband, Woodhull fled in 1877 to England, where she married
a British banker and lived until her death in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   No women have run for president on the Libertarian Party ticket,
but two _ Tonie Nathan in 1972 and Jo Jorgensen in 1996 _ have run
for vice president, said Bill Winter of the Libertarians'
Washington headquarters. Winter added that the party doesn't keep
records on women candidates who have run for all offices
nationwide. ``We don't break (candidates) down by age, race or
sex,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have there been any other female presidential candidates
besides Victoria Woodhull?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, quite a few. Here's a sample of those in recent years,
with their party affiliation. 1968: Charlene Mitchell, Communist.
1972: Linda Jenness, Socialist Labor; Shirley Chisholm, Democratic.
1976: Margaret Wright, People's. 1980: Ellen McCormack, Right to
Life; Maureen Smith, Peace and Freedom; Dierdre Griswold, Workers
World. 1984: Sonia Johnson, Citizens. 1988: Lenora Fulani, New
Alliance; Willa Kenoyer, Citizens. 1992: Fulani; Helen Halyard,
Workers League; Isabell Masters, Looking Back; Glorida La Riva,
Workers World. Q: President Andrew Johnson was impeached by the
House of Representatives for firing a Cabinet member. Johnson was
acquitted by one vote. Who was that Cabinet member? What were the
circumstances of his removal? And did he get his job back?
</P>
<P>
   A: Johnson fired Secretary of War Edwin McMasters Stanton on
Aug. 12, 1867, and nominated Gen. Ulysses S. Grant to replace him.
The Tenure of Office Act, passed the previous March, made consent
of the Senate necessary for such removals. Stanton vacated his
office, but under protest.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, at its next reassembling, refused to sanction
Stanton's removal, and Grant at once resigned in his favor. Then
Johnson again removed Stanton and appointed Gen. Lorenzo Thomas to
the office. The Senate declared that the president had exceeded his
authority, and the House passed a resolution, 126-47, that he be
impeached for high crimes and misdemeanors. Votes on conviction
fell just one short of the two-thirds required. Stanton then
resigned and returned to his law practice. He didn't get the
secretary of war position back, in other words.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Grant succeeded Johnson as president and nominated
Stanton for the Supreme Court. Stanton died on Dec. 24, 1869, four
days after the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
