</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4925 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS24-TAKE     09-25 1954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS24-TAKE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Q: President Andrew Johnson was impeached by the House
of Representatives for firing a Cabinet member. Johnson was
acquitted by one vote. Who was that Cabinet member? What were the
circumstances of his removal? And did he get his job back?
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is meant by the term ``the Beltway''? I heard it
referred to by a commentator in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A: The Capital Beltway is Washington's Perimeter, I-495, which
cuts through the Virginia and Maryland suburbs. In England, ``ring
road'' is the term for the same thing. Think of a belt around one's
waist, and you have the idea.
</P>
<P>
   But the meaning here is not so literal. In referring to
Washington matters, ``inside the Beltway'' refers to the pols and
others with a government-centered mentality, and the business they
do; ``outside the Beltway'' refers to all the rest of
nongovernment-centered America.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does President Clinton actually own a house anywhere? Does he
even own a car?
</P>
<P>
   A: Neither the president nor first lady owns a house, according
to a White House spokeswoman. Clinton does, however, own a car, a
'66 Mustang convertible which he purchased in 1991 from his
half-brother, Roger Clinton. When Clinton left Arkansas for the
White House, the car _ painted a 1960s metallic shade of blue _
stayed behind in Little Rock. It subsequently was put on display at
the Museum of Automobiles atop Petit Jean Mountain in Morrilton,
Ark. Clinton has said that he planned to retrieve the car from the
museum at the end of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm interested in the prayer that President Clinton read when
he was addressing ministers last Friday at a prayer breakfast in
Washington. It was beautiful. Can you print it?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was a passage from a Yom Kippur liturgy contained in the
liturgy book ''Gates of Repentance,'' which Clinton said was given
to him recently by a Jewish friend. This is what he read:
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is the time for turning. The leaves are beginning to turn
from green to red to orange. The birds are beginning to turn and
are heading once more toward the south. The animals are beginning
to turn to storing their food for the winter. For leaves, birds and
animals, turning comes instinctively.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for us, turning does not come so easily. It takes an act
of will for us to make a turn. It means breaking old habits. It
means admitting that we have been wrong, and this is never easy. It
means losing face. It means starting all over again. And this is
always painful. It means saying I am sorry. It means recognizing
that we have the ability to change. These things are terribly hard
to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But unless we turn, we will be trapped forever in yesterday's
ways. Lord help us to turn from callousness to sensitivity, from
hostility to love, from pettiness to purpose, from envy to
contentment, from carelessness to discipline, from fear to faith.
Turn us around, oh, Lord, and bring us back toward you. Revive our
lives as at the beginning. And turn us toward each other, Lord, for
in isolation, there is no life.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: More than 65 percent of the American public has indicated
through numerous polls that we do not want impeachment proceedings
against President Clinton. If Congress decides to act contrary to
the wish of the people, is there any procedure by which the people
(apart from their elected representatives) can take formal steps to
petition and direct the Congress to comply with the wish of the
people?
</P>
<P>
   A: Other than voting against your representative at the next
election if he or she doesn't act in accordance with your wishes,
there's no formal means for voters to ``order'' Congress to do
anything. But Emmett H. Buell, professor of political science at
Denison University in Granville, Ohio, says there's a ``mistakenly
static frame of mind'' inherent in the question. Polls may change,
and public support for Clinton may erode, as inquiries progress.
There was a time, for example, when most Americans didn't think
President Richard Nixon should be forced from office, Buell said,
but as evidence steadily mounted that he had lied and abused his
power, his support eventually eroded in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Buell also pointed out that a majority isn't always right,
especially if it has limited information on which to base its
judgment. Members of the House of Representatives have more
information than private citizens do, he said, adding: ``They're
making a good deal of it available to us, however, and more
information may indeed change the public's mind. But in any case,
the idea that a partially informed majority is always right, as
reflected in a simple poll question, is not what the Founding
Fathers intended for this system, and is not the best means of
making important decisions like the one facing the country today.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the date when Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) first called for
impeachment of President Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   A: Barr wrote a letter in March 1997 to Rep. Henry Hyde
(R-Ill.), chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, asking Hyde to
consider beginning an impeachment inquiry of Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore. An article in the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
on March 15, 1997, reporting Barr's request, quoted Rep. John
Conyers of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the committee, as
saying most members of Congress would reject Barr's call. ``His
activity is on the political margins and won't be taken
seriously.'' Barr responded to that by saying, ``I haven't taken a
cheap shot. It is a very measured request. I have not asked for
articles of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will you print the exact text of the U.S. president's oath of
office? Where is the wording stipulated?
</P>
<P>
   A: Article II, Section 1, clause 8 of the Constitution sets out
the words that every president has restated at inauguration
(capitalization as in the Constitution): ``I do solemnly swear (or
affirm) that I will faithfully executive the Office of President of
the United States, and will to the best of my Ability, preserve,
protect and defend the Constitution of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The oath is the only part of the inaugural ceremony required by
the Constitution. Only Franklin Pierce in 1853 affirmed, rather
than swore, to faithfully execute the office that he was about to
enter. The practice of adding the words ``so help me God'' at the
conclusion of the oath was begun by George Washington at the first
inaugural ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What would President Clinton's pension be if he resigns? What
if he is impeached? Would he still be eligible for other perks, and
in what amount?
</P>
<P>
   A: If he resigns, Clinton will be eligible for a pension of
$151,800 a year, said Pete Sepp of the National Taxpayers Union.
Under the Former President's Act of 1958, he is entitled to that
pension only if he is not impeached. He can resign, he can stick it
out to the end of his term, and he even can be convicted outside
the impeachment process _ such as in a criminal case or civil suit
after he leaves office _ but if he is impeached and convicted by
Congress, he forfeits the pension as well as his office allowances.
Those allowances can be as much as $650,000 a year, Sepp said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been impressed by the insights in the national media
from George Stephanopoulos. Will you refresh my memory about the
circumstances surrounding his departure from the White House? What
was the official explanation?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was in December 1996 that Stephanopoulos, after five years
on President Clinton's White House team _ first as communications
director and later as senior adviser _ accepted a visiting
professorship at Columbia University, teaching a subject he knows
well: political science. He also announced his intention to join
ABC News as a contributing correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews in 1996, Stephanopoulos said this about his career
change: ``It just felt perfect. . . . I love New York. Columbia's
not only a top-ranked university, it's my alma mater.'' (He
graduated in 1982 with a bachelor's degree in political science,
summa cum laude, before going on to earn a master's in theology as
a Rhodes Scholar at Oxford).
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that it would be ``very hard'' to leave the White
House, adding, ``I'm going to miss him (Clinton) and it's tough to
leave the excitement of the White House. But it's time.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was a list of the victims aboard Swissair Flight 111 ever
released?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can find the names (passengers and crew) on the Internet:
www.cnn.com/WORLD/americas/9809/04/victim.list.01/
</P>
<P>
   Q: Mark McGwire has been taking some type of muscle stimulant
medication. Is Sammy Sosa also taking this?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's been widely reported that McGwire has been using
Androstenedione _ legal in baseball, but banned in the NFL,
Olympics and NCAA _ for more than a year. The over-the-counter drug
raises levels of the male hormone testosterone, which builds lean
muscle mass and promotes recovery after injury. Sosa says he
doesn't use Androstenedione or any other testosterone booster, but
admits to using the muscle-builder Creatine, an amino-acid powder,
after games to keep up his weight and strength. For energy before
games, Sosa says he takes the Chinese herb ginseng. McGwire also
says he takes Creatine.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the violinist Midori have any other name? When did she
start playing?
</P>
<P>
   A: Midori hasn't used her last name, Goto, professionally since
1986. She was born Oct. 25, 1971, in Osaka, Japan. Her father was
an engineer and her mother, Setsu Goto, a professional violinist.
Her mother began teaching her to play when she was 3, and when she
was 6, Midori gave her first public recital. She made her U.S.
debut at the 1981 Aspen Music Festival in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A newspaper column listed presidents who were involved or
rumored to have been involved in affairs before or during marriage.
George Bush was mentioned in connection with a Jennifer Fitzgerald.
Where did that information come from? I've never heard or read
about that.
</P>
<P>
   A: The list in the column you saw was compiled by the Fort Worth
(Texas) Star-Telegram. But long-whispered rumors about the
relationship have circulated, mainly outside the mainstream press,
for some time. The rumors were never substantiated, despite
investigations by a number of news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that Fitzgerald worked closely with Bush when he
was ambassador to China in 1974, and, in 1975, she was his personal
assistant at the CIA. She did the same job for Bush when he became
vice president. As president, he made her deputy chief of protocol.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, that doesn't mean there was any untoward relationship.
But rumors nevertheless cropped up. For example, at the end of the
1988 presidential campaign, the Los Angeles Weekly, an alternative
newspaper, printed an old tale that she had been Bush's mistress.
In a recap two years later, the Independent of London wrote: ``Wall
Street prices briefly plunged for fear that mainstream newspapers
would pick up the story, destroy Mr. Bush's image as a family man
and dissolve his commanding lead. . . . The story was reprinted
abroad but ignored by the U.S. news media.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the tabloid New York Post printed an article based on
the book ``The Power House'' by Susan B. Trento, a former
congressional aide. Asked about the newspaper report, Bush said,
``I will not respond to it. I have not responded to it in the
past.'' He then continued, ``Except to say it's a lie.'' Mary
Matalin, the Bush campaign's political director, blamed Democrats
for peddling the story.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
