<P>
   HEASTER-COLUMN (Kansas City, Mo.) _ City auditor's report adds
welcome fuel to raging debate over dvelopment subsidies. Economics
column by JERRY HEASTER. Story will move in the ``f'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4941 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      09-25 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUDITOR'S REPORT ADDS WELCOME FUEL TO RAGING DEBATE OVER
SUBSIDIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Mark Funkhouser's name is probably mud in
local development circles, but his challenging analysis of Kansas
City's favorite business tax incentive is nevertheless a highly
important contribution to the public policy debate hereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Kansas City auditor focused exclusively on Kansas
City projects, the questions that his findings raised probably will
influence future tax-subsidy policy throughout the area.
</P>
<P>
   Funkhouser's report called into question the economic
assumptions used to sell tax incentives as a spur to commercial
development. The concept in question assumes that revenues
initially forgone by governments to encourage development will be
more than recouped later from economic activity generated by the
development.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City's case, the incentive of choice is known as tax
increment financing, or TIF. It allows diversion of some new taxes
from real estate developments to reimburse developers for eligible
costs. The auditor's review of two dozen projects showed revenue
falling far short of estimates initially used to help justify tax
breaks for those developments.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the city's Tax Increment Financing Commission, John
Crawford, called Funkhouser's work ``profoundly flawed'' because it
didn't account for all the revenue that should be attributed to the
developments.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford's criticism probably will be only the first such salvo
fired at the auditor's study, because there's a lot of room for
debate when it comes to this issue. A good argument can be made, in
fact, for the rationality of public subsidies for private projects
in some cases. Critics, however, say the tax-subsidy concept is
used to indefensible excess.
</P>
<P>
   TIF defenders argue that it's a much better tool than, say, tax
abatement because it requires its beneficiaries to be more
accountable. Opponents counter that some TIF deals still create too
much risk for taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Funkhouser's study is a valuable addition to the
debate about public-private cooperative ventures. It gives the
skeptics more leverage to force developers and their public-sector
advocates to justify subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Taxpayer considerations aside, such subsidies can encourage
misallocation of capital and result in failures that are costly to
the community in many other ways. In a grander sense, Asia's
horrendous problems serve as a dramatic reminder of how badly
things can go wrong if capital gets misallocated to economically
unsound investments.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't just TIF, and it's not just Kansas City. It's
the entire national panoply of tax breaks often conferred whether
merited or not.
</P>
<P>
   Funkhouser's willingness to challenge the economics of
questionable tax incentives as a development tool makes the city
auditor a rarity for a public official. Seldom does anyone inside
City Hall decide to fight City Hall. Such policy challenges usually
are mounted from outside the establishment by maverick anti-tax
watchdog groups.
</P>
<P>
   Funkhouser may get beat up in this battle, if indeed a battle is
what is made of it. What he will accomplish, though, is to remind
all those with a stake in the process that tax incentives for
business aren't always slam-dunk, win-win propositions for the
community.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes they are, sometimes they're not. If Funkhouser brings
more judiciousness to the process, he will have won his place in
the taxpayers' Hall of Champions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4947 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-SCANDAL-2NDT     09-25 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-SCANDAL-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: but not impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country isn't in crisis. The media and political systems
are the ones...'' said Iowa State University history professor
Hamilton Cravens. ``We're at the point of eviscerating the
presidency so that anyone can be driven out of office by a
sophisticated public relations campaign. There's your crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats hope that the time is ripe for a compromise,
especially after Clinton's videotaped testimony that actually
helped him in the polls. They are talking up different censure
proposals, including one that would have Clinton coming to the Hill
and trying to explain himself.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans don't seem to be buying, many taking the tack of
Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri, to whom censure is meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Partisanship is part of the problem, Cravens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to broker that deal _ Newt Gingrich and Dick
Gephardt?'' he asked, referring to the combative party leaders in
the House. ``The situation is too polarized. Everyone's speaking
through megaphones.''
</P>
<P>
   Erik Smith, a spokesman for Minority Leader Gephardt, on Tuesday
said that ``there is no such thing as censure at this point,''
because Congress has no constitutional blueprint for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The polls and talking heads are getting way out ahead of
themselves. They're negotiating options in the media that don't
exist.''
</P>
<P>
   And Speaker Gingrich on Wednesday indicated that Republicans
weren't interested in negotiating before a House investigation is
finished. Any compromise now ``simply puts the cart in front of the
horse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   - Impeach: to challenge the practices or honesty of; accuse;
esp., to bring a public official before the proper tribunal on
charges of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment proceedings would stretch several months, amounting
to what Democratic U.S. Sen. John Kerry described as ``water
torture'' for the president.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 41 percent of Americans polled this week by ABC News
favor this option _ and not necessarily because they all want
Clinton out of office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we truly believe our constitutional system is a good one,
I'm perfectly happy to let the institutions work,'' said Loomis.
``It might be ugly, but that may be the best option for the country
in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   A legion of academics say impeachment _ divisive as it it sounds
_ may be the only route to closure. It's how Congress is supposed
to address questions of alleged ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' by
the president. In the end, the scholars note, Clinton could survive
the process and history may grant him a measure of sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment process begins with a series of U.S. House
hearings and resolutions _ part legal and part political. But it's
in the Senate, which currently holds 45 Democrats, where Clinton
would be tried. Conviction and removal from office requires a
two-thirds vote of all 100 senators _ a tall order in any event.
</P>
<P>
   Even ferocious White House critics such as Larry Klayman,
director of Judicial Watch, say the country would best be served by
witnessing Clinton's impeachment. He believes removal could be then
followed by criminal prosecution for alleged obstruction of
justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presidents should be held accountable,'' said Klayman. ``A
resignation would merely return us to 1974, when (President Nixon)
got off scot-free, received his pension and, in some corners, was
ultimately vindicated as a leader. It sent a signal that a
president is above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   - Drop it: to stop, end or have done with.
</P>
<P>
   Now you're dreaming, say Washington watchers.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the beltway, dropping it remains a rather popular
option. Between 30 and 50 percent of Americans have told pollsters
from the start that the sex scandal is insignificant, certainly not
worth the full-bore attention of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people have already decided: they don't want to listen to
this,'' argues professor Cravens.
</P>
<P>
   To lobbyist Clemente, the motivation is: ``the Republicans get a
two-fer. It distracts the country away from any substantive issues
at election time. And it's likely to increase the turnout of people
who hate Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Luntz, a GOP pollster, agreed that the scandal is driving
other legislative issues ``not only off the front pages, but also
off the inside pages.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, backers of the movement to set national standards
for HMOs and managed-care plans _ a hot campaign issue a few months
ago _ now say their proposals are all but dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``HMO reforms are getting buried in Monica Lewinsky's
skirttails,'' said Jamie Court of the political action group
Consumers for Quality Care. ``The sex scandal has turned attention
away from the real tough issues. A lot of politicians running for
re-election are pretty glad about that.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Pew Center for the People and the Press, 36
percent of adults are following news of the president's problems
``very closely.'' That's double the attention they say they're
paying to news about instability in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But by Pew's measures, the sex scandal wasn't even the top story
of the summer (45 percent of people said they paid very close
attention to the shootings of police officers at the U.S. Capitol).
Indeed, more than 100 news events of the past decade drew equal or
greater attention in the Pew Center surveys than has the Clinton
sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Then why can't Washington let it go?
</P>
<P>
   ``People still want to hear about education, Social Security and
those issues,'' said Pew Center director Andrew Kohut. ``But we're
also seeing an uptick in (concern for) morality as an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Uptick or turnoff, the scandal will be with us for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way they'll drop it,'' said Clemente. ``It's herd
mentality. It's what everyone hates about politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1720EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4965 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINDBERGH-BOOK-REVIEW     09-25 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINDBERGH-BOOK-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: being misunderstood.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A shy, aloof boy, Lindbergh was the son of two sadly mismatched
parents who spent much of the time apart, and his experience of
their contentious marriage seems to have left him with a lasting
sense of displacement.
</P>
<P>
   Although his marriage to Anne Morrow, the daughter of an
American ambassador, was a love match, their relationship soon
became a one-sided affair, with Lindbergh setting the agenda and
Anne doing her best to accommodate and please. After the birth of
each of their six children, Berg observes, Lindbergh would take his
wife away on a long plane journey _ often weeks in length _ as a
way of ``weaning'' her from her children. He bristled at her
displays of emotion (even in the wake of the kidnapping) and
rebuked her when she complained of writer's block.
</P>
<P>
   Anne's growing independence, which sprang largely from
Lindbergh's encouraging her to find her own voice as a writer,
apparently provoked ``greater intolerance'' on his part. Lindbergh
was constantly on the road, on business or pleasure, and Anne, Berg
suggests, began to welcome his long absences from home.
</P>
<P>
   Although the highly private Lindbergh loathed his own celebrity,
he determined to use it to promote causes he believed in, including
commercial aviation, conservation and, during the early '40s, the
isolationist America First movement, which aimed to keep the United
States out of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh was not simply concerned about the adverse effects the
war might have on America; he saw the conflict as marginal to the
country's interests. In one speech, he asserted that it was not a
war ``in which our civilization is defending itself against some
Asiatic intruder,'' that it was ``not a question of banding
together to defend the white race against foreign invasion.''
</P>
<P>
   He complained that American Jews were pushing the country into
the war, and declared that ``their greatest danger to this country
lies in their large ownership and influence in our motion pictures,
our press, our radio and our government.''
</P>
<P>
   During a trip to Berlin in 1938, Lindbergh accepted a decoration
for his services to world aviation from Goering, and he would speak
frequently of his admiration for aspects of Nazi Germany. ``I
shared the repulsion that democratic peoples felt in viewing the
demagoguery of Hitler, the controlled elections, the secret
police,'' he explained. ``Yet I felt that I was seeing in Germany,
despite the crudeness of its form, the inevitable alternative to
decline _ a challenge based more on the drive to achieve success
despite established `right' and law.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Berg quotes such damning statements by Lindbergh, and
also quotes anti-Semitic passages that were expurgated from
Lindbergh's published diaries, he does little to explain why, in
his words, the pilot ``buried his head in the sand when confronted
with the crimes of inhumanity that repelled so many others.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Berg sounds as though he were trying to rationalize
Lindbergh's actions. He writes that ``the Lindberghs were hardly
alone in being swayed by Hitler's magnetism.'' He writes that
Lindbergh's interest in ``race betterment'' _ which came at the
same time that Nazi Germany was obsessed with eugenics _ was an
unfortunate ``coincidence that would not be lost on future
detractors.''
</P>
<P>
   And he argues that Lindbergh's critics often judged him by his
fanatical followers (like the Rev. Charles Edward Coughlin),
although Lindbergh himself ``never associated with any pro-Nazi or
anti-Semitic organization; he never attended any Bund meetings; and
since more than four months before the outbreak of war in Europe,
he had neither consorted nor consulted with anyone known to have
any connections with the Third Reich.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Berg's depiction of Lindbergh as ``naive in war as
he had been in peace'' is insufficient _ particularly when
Lindbergh never recanted his most explosive isolationist
statements, when he never even conceded, as his wife did, that ``we
were both very blind, especially in the beginning, to the worst
evils of the Nazi system.'' It is a serious flaw in a biography, a
flaw that casts a dark shadow over the dazzling writerly
achievement on display in the first half of this uneven volume.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LINDBERGH'
</P>
<P>
   By A. Scott Berg
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 628 pages. G.P. Putnam's Sons. $30.
</P>
</TEXT>
