<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4949 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-SCANDAL-2TAK     09-25 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-SCANDAL-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION WAITS FOR WHEEL OF WASHINGTON ROULETTE TO STOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: In this game of Washington roulette, a restless nation
waits for the spinning to stop and for President Clinton's fate to
be decided.
</P>
<P>
   One space on the wheel says ``resign,'' but few are betting on
it. The pointer appears to be clicking past a peculiar space
labeled ``censure'' and moving toward another marked ``impeachment
hearings.''
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls _ no small factor in this game _ reveal an
audience torn in all directions in month nine of the Monica
Lewinsky scandal. Everybody thinks they know what's best for the
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 newspapers have called for Clinton's resignation.
White House spokesman Mike McCurry has replied, ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats seem to favor an immediate ``censure'' of
Clinton. There's even a variety of ``censure-plus'' proposals,
including some carrying fines or involving a criminal trial of the
president on charges of perjury and obstruction of justice when he
completes his term.
</P>
<P>
   To that, constitutional scholars scratch their heads. The rules
of this contest don't even include ``censure,'' not to mention
censure-plus, they say.
</P>
<P>
   At least you can find impeachment not only on the wheel, but in
the Constitution, say Republicans, who like the odds.
</P>
<P>
   A insider's tip. Don't bet on the space marked ``drop the
matter,'' the one that would end the game.
</P>
<P>
   A glance at each possibility:
</P>
<P>
   - Resign: to give up an office, position of employment, etc.,
esp. by formal notice.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers that have joined Republicans calling for the
president to short-circuit the system range from USA Today to The
Topeka Capital-Journal. The Chicago Tribune piped in last week:
``If he truly cares about the nation, and not just himself, he will
step down and spare us the constitutional crisis toward which his
recklessness has propelled us.''
</P>
<P>
   This option runs into several obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   First is the widespread belief among Clinton observers _ friends
and foes _ that the president holds too high of an opinion of his
skills to quit over a partisan inquest into sex and lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' said Frank Clemente, executive director of the Public
Citizens Congress Watch, a consumers lobby in Washington. ``Just
isn't in his personality,''
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion presents a second barrier. For all the poll
numbers that refect a growing distrust of Clinton, Americans
dislike the media even more. Fifty-five percent of Iowans surveyed
by a Republican polling company said it was ``inappropriate'' for
the media to call for the president's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, a CBS News poll after the airing of Clinton's
testimony showed his job-approval rating at 68 percent. Six of 10
respondents said he should finish his term, compared to 38 percent
who said resignation would be ``better for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Others argue that a second presidential resignation in a
quarter-century would mark a trend, one that could erode the
stability of the office and undermine the federal system of checks
and balances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm somewhat appalled to hear eveyone today say `resign,' ''
former Nixon aide Alexander Haig told The Wall Street Journal.
``That's not what our founding fathers had in mind, and I don't
think it's due process for our president.''
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, which operates under a parliamentary system, four
prime ministers have resigned in five years. Parliamentary regimes
place heads of state at the mercy of the ruling power in the
legislature. A change in party rule or a collapse in support
trigger changes at the top.
</P>
<P>
   Framers of the Constitution sought something else: a president
separate from the legislative branch and just as powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Clinton decides to resign next week,'' said University of
Kansas political science professor Burdett Loomis, ``then
essentially the key players in this whole scandal become Ken Starr
and the media.''
</P>
<P>
   - Censure: a condemnation as wrong; strong disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   Although this option is not spelled out in the Constitution,
legislators regard censures as formal reprimands that carry no
legal penalty and require only a majority vote.
</P>
<P>
   The House has conducted censure proceedings against its own
members 36 times, the last three for allegations of sexual
misconduct. The Senate has censured nine members, including
anti-communist crusader Sen. Joe McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   The only U.S. president to be censured was Andrew Jackson in
1834. The Senate on a 26-20 vote took the action after Jackson _ a
critic of the Bank of the United States _ fired his Treasury
secretary for refusing to deposit federal revenues in state banks.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution charged that he ``assumed an exercise of power
not granted him by the Constitution (and) dangerous to the
liberties of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators who pushed it ``were making up the rules as they went
along,'' said Harold Moser, editor of Jackson's papers at the
University of Tennessee. ``It was all politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The popular Jackson _ ``Old Hickory'' to his contemporaries _
worked the showdown to his advantage. He argued that members of
Congress were obliged to protect the interests of states and
districts, and only he, the president, represented all Americans.
In the final weeks of Jackson's second term, the Senate expunged
the censure. It was literally blackened out of the legislative
record.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls portray the public as more supportive of a Clinton
censure over impeachment or resignation. One survey, however, found
that four out of 10 Americans ``don't know what censure means.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts see it as a compromise measure against behavior
that may be disturbing but not impeachable. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
