<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP URGES INCREASED SPENDING ON PROSTATE CANCER RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A group led by Michael Milken, the former junk bond
king, urged Congress Friday to significantly increase funding for
prostate cancer research, bolstering its call with 500,000
petitions from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad fact is that men have not spoken out,'' Milken told a
news conference in front of the U.S. Capitol. As a result, Milken
said ``prostate cancer funding is too low.''
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer is the No. 2 cancer killer of American men.
</P>
<P>
   Milken, who has battled the cancer since 1993, founded a private
organization _ called CapCure _ that funds promising prostate
cancer research programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely must do more to fight this dreadful disease,''
said John Kelly, vice chairman of the American Cancer Society's
board of directors. ``We need a nationwide commitment to expand
prostate cancer research efforts in order to better understand and
prevent this disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Hedlund, the president of the Washington, D.C.-based
National Prostate Cancer Coalition, said the government had ignored
the statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite nearly 20 percent of all cancers diagnosed each year
being prostate cancer, until now less than four percent of total
federal funds for cancer research have been devoted to prostate
cancer,'' said Hedlund, standing next to more than a dozen boxes
filled with petitions from prostate cancer survivors, their family
members and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prostate cancer research money has been left behind,'' Hedlund
said.
</P>
<P>
   The news conference coincided with a rally in Washington this
weekend that seeks more federal research into all types of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The petitions, gathered from all 50 states and the District of
Columbia, call on Congress and President Clinton ``to commit to
eradicating prostate cancer, the leading form of cancer in men, by
increasing funding for research and making prostate cancer a
national priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The petitions and steady lobbying by those advocating stepped up
spending on prostate-cancer research may be having an effect on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate wants to boost the National Institutes of Health's
annual prostate cancer budget to about $175 million, from this
year's $114 million. Those lobbying for more research spending also
are confident that the Pentagon will provide $60 million. The
Defense Department provides more than $100 million each year for
breast cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Some 184,500 men will be diagnosed with carcinoma of the
prostate this year, making it the most diagnosed cancer in the
United States next to highly curable forms of skin cancer. Nearly
40,000 American men will die from the cancer, while lung cancer
will kill 93,000 American men, according to the American Cancer
Society.
</P>
<P>
   But prostate cancer research receives comparatively little from
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Breast cancer and prostate cancer killed about the same number
of Americans in 1997 _ 43,900 women and 41,800 men, respectively _
while about 14,000 people died from AIDs-related illnesses over the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the NIH (which includes the National Cancer Institute) spent
about $107,214 in AIDS research for every AIDS-related death in
1997; $9,362 in breast cancer research for every death; and $2,512
in prostate cancer research for each person who died from the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for the lopsided funding, Milken said, is that
men are too embarrassed to speak out about the disease because
treatments can curtail sexual function and urinary continence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too late to be quiet,'' Milken said. ``It's time prostate
cancer comes out of the closet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
