<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4975 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERGIO-MAD-LADN     09-25 1689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERGIO-MAD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS WORK DOES THE TALKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID GREENBERG  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sergio Aragones arrived in New York City in the
summer of 1962 with $40 in cash, a portfolio of cartoon strips and
dreams of making it big.
</P>
<P>
   Although he knew only a few words of English, the Spanish-born
artist managed to sell a few cartoons to small adventure and adult
magazines. To earn spending money, he performed the works of slain
Spanish poet and playwright Federico Garcia Lorca on street
corners, then passed the hat. He lived on salami sandwiches and
tomato soup made by dumping ketchup into hot water.
</P>
<P>
   And, eventually, Aragones went mad.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more precisely, he went to MAD _ the offbeat monthly
magazine with an international following of fans loyal to its
irreverent parodies. Struck by Aragones' lampoons during their
first meeting, the magazine's editors bought 10 cartoon strips for
$200. And Aragones launched the career he had dreamed of since he
was a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing exactly what I was doing in the third grade _
telling stories to my buddies,'' said Aragones, 61. ``Only the
teacher doesn't yell at me anymore, and people pay for my
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   From a cluttered studio above a Radio Shack in Ojai, where he
has lived since 1983, Aragones creates the pointed jibes that have
won him a following among MAD readers and admiration from fellow
cartoonists around the world. He has the distinction of being part
of MAD's ``usual gang of idiots'' _ the way the magazine's masthead
lists its staffers and regular contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Aragones possesses a cynical outlook that is perfectly suited to
MAD, a 500,000-circulation magazine that mocks everything and
everybody: war, schools, work, marriage, vacations, holidays,
movies, television, politics and social issues.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``A MAD Look At ...'' _ contributions that carry
his ``Serge-in General Dept.'' tag line _ Aragones is known for his
tiny but thought-provoking visual japes in the margins of other
cartoonists' strips.
</P>
<P>
   In his MAD strips and his series of limited-edition comic books,
Aragones satirizes the lighter side of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cartoons are a therapy for everything in life,'' he said.
``There is a balance. I'm angry about something, but I'm also happy
about something.''
</P>
<P>
   His offbeat humor and immediately recognizable style have won
him several awards from the National Cartoonists Society, including
Best Cartoonist honors in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sergio's one of the most admired cartoonists in the
business,'' said Charles M. Schulz, the legendary creator of the
``Peanuts'' strip. ``It does not matter what cartoonist it is. They
all think he is wonderful. He simply draws everything funny.''
</P>
<P>
   When Aragones is not drawing, he is thinking about what to draw.
Everything he sees and hears has the potential to evolve into a
cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Cartoonists) are basically critical of everything,'' Aragones
said. ``They see the foibles of man. The weaknesses of man. The
abuses that man inflicts onto men.''
</P>
<P>
   It is from that point of view that Aragones created ``MAD's
Do-It-Yourself Complete Clinton Scandal Guide,'' ``The Mall-Rat
Olympics'' and ``A Typical Religious Fanatic Tract,'' which
advertises a make-believe book titled ``Inspirational Divine
Institute of Total Salvation'' _ a tome with the acronym IDIOTS.
</P>
<P>
   Aragones' oblique outlook is easily woven into the MAD fabric,
according to Al Jaffee, another legendary MAD cartoonist, whose
work first appeared in 1955, when the magazine was just 3 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a natural-born cartoonist,'' Jaffee said. ``He's a
cartoonist's cartoonist because he's admired by all. He makes it
look easy. He makes it look like anyone could do it. And of course,
anyone can't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Jaffee added that Aragones has a ``tremendous
personality,'' Aragones himself warns that he and his peers are
serious people _ even boring at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to be funny on paper,'' Aragones said. ``I go to a
party, and I'm the guy who sits there and listens to the jokes. I
don't know how to tell a joke. I forget the ending.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, outside the office, he is not above moments of impromptu
silliness.
</P>
<P>
   During a trip to Italy, for instance, Aragones and other MAD
staffers were among the tourists snapping photographs of the
Vatican when a group of local shoe factory workers marched by in
protest of their low wages.
</P>
<P>
   Aragones quickly borrowed one of the picket signs and stomped
back to his friends, screaming, ``Americans go home! Americans go
home!''
</P>
<P>
   The situation become amusingly chaotic, he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American (tourists) who didn't know us ran away,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Aragones is admittedly an emotional man, prone to hysterical
laughter and volcanic outbursts _ born from frustration rather than
raw anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos come down very fast,'' he said. ``We get very excited,
we shout, then _ boom _ it's off.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a personality that evolved from the years Aragones spent
with his politically outspoken father, who moved the family to
France when civil war swept through Spain. When France fell under
siege by Hitler, the family fled again _ this time to Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   A habitual doodler, Aragones fondly recalled drawing mocking
caricatures of his teachers while attending school in Mexico City.
After being chastised for not paying attention, he learned how to
simultaneously sketch and listen, and he joyfully irritated his
teachers by giving correct answers when called on in class.
</P>
<P>
   To please his parents, who wanted to place a security blanket
around their would-be starving artist son, Aragones enrolled in the
University of Mexico to study architecture. He dropped out after
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going to make it as a cartoonist,'' he said.
``There couldn't have been another life for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1962, Aragones headed for New York. In the
spirit of Beat icon Jack Kerouac, Aragones slept on the bus at
night and spent his days touring cities that looked like they had
something to offer. Then he hand-bathed in bus station bathrooms
and hopped the next bus headed to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   After finally arriving in Pennsylvania Station, Aragones spent
his first night in New York sleeping on a park bench by the East
River. The owner of El Flamenco, a coffeehouse on McDougal Street,
befriended him and gave him food, money and a cot in the basement.
But he forgot Aragones was downstairs when he locked up for the
night, so the struggling artist found himself a prisoner until the
owner returned the following day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My second day, I just saw New York from a window,'' Aragones
said.
</P>
<P>
   When money was tight, Aragones often survived on a loaf of bread
and package of salami. When money was tighter, he mixed ketchup and
crushed saltines into a cup of hot water, creating a facsimile of
tomato soup.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're young, you don't care,'' Aragones said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had regularly read MAD while in Mexico City _ he was
a big fan of the irrepressible gap-toothed mascot Alfred E. Neuman
_ he shied away from the magazine's offices, then located on Third
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never ever fathomed I would work for them,'' Aragones said.
``They were too good and in another country in a language I didn't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Aragones had problems with the language barrier, his
characters did not. Then, as today, they speak not in words but
through facial expressions, movement, body language and dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sergio actually talks with his drawings,'' Jaffee says. ``He
does things with pictures that are easier to read than some of the
cartoons with words in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, at the urging of his new Greenwich Village friends,
Aragones decided to give MAD a shot. At the magazine's
headquarters, he asked for Antonio Prohias, the Cuban-born
cartoonist known for his ``Spy vs. Spy'' serial.
</P>
<P>
   The two had a lot in common and bonded immediately. Like
Aragones, Prohias spoke only Spanish. And like Aragones'
characters, the enemy spies in Prohias' column _ one dressed in
black, the other in white _ also never spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Aragones asked Prohias to introduce him to the MAD editors, but
the veteran cartoonist declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You have to introduce yourself because I don't speak
any English either','' Aragones recalled.
</P>
<P>
   His work has appeared in every MAD since that fateful day in
1962, save one issue during the late 1960s when the cartoons he
mailed while traveling in Europe failed to arrive. He has published
more than 7,000 marginal drawings and thousands more ``A MAD Look
At ...'' strips.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to Los Angeles in 1970 and Ojai in 1983 after visiting
the area to hear the Indian philosopher J. Krishnamurti.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an atmosphere of a small town. Everybody was very
friendly,'' Aragones recalled. ``There is a feeling of security
around here. And, more than anything else, it's very beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   His studio, just a few miles from Aragones' home, is cluttered
with hundreds of Donald Duck and other cartoon figurines, books,
files, hand-carved masks, back issues of MAD and numerous awards.
There, Aragones works into the wee hours of the morning, producing
a page of cartoons a day.
</P>
<P>
   For Aragones, life is a constant stream of simple pleasures that
he never takes for granted: finding a rare toy in the flea market;
watching a good movie, particularly ones that embody a relevant
point of view or contain samurai warriors; spending time with wife
Charlene and their 21-year-old daughter, Christen; taking long
walks through Ojai; or appreciating quality art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could spend hours watching a glass blower or a ceramist
making a pot,'' Aragones said.
</P>
<P>
   And he is an avid traveler, having visited more than 100
countries over the years. He has met hundreds of cartoonists during
his journeys, and he doesn't hesitate to offer them advice if he
believes they are serious about their craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cartoonists are an international community,'' he said. ``I can
go to any country in the world, meet a cartoonist and have a
friend, a brother.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
