<HEADER>
A4977 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESCUERS-TV-LADN     09-25 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESCUERS-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODNESS GET GREEN LIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Rabbi Harold Schulweiss stands before his
congregation every week, imparting words of wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   But is anyone listening? You bet. Schulweiss' proof will be
broadcast on television tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The final two installments of Showtime's six-part series,
``Rescuers: Stories of Courage,'' are scheduled to air back-to-back
starting at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The two one-hour films share with TV audiences one of
Schulweiss' most passionate subjects _ the righteous Christians who
risked their own lives to save Jews during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped transform my whole theology,'' said Schulweiss,
senior rabbi at Encino's Valley Beth Shalom. ``I was so depressed
whenever I came to the Holocaust. I wondered: How could I talk to
each individual being created in the image of God and essential
goodness ... and at the same time, there not being any shred of
evidence of that goodness?''
</P>
<P>
   Stories about the rescuers were a revelation. And he made it his
mission to shed more light on the people who prove there is
goodness in the world.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the rabbi has been bringing the heroes to speak at
his temple. He created the Jewish Foundation, which raises about $1
million a year for the rescuers. And from his pulpit, Schulweiss
often reminds his congregation of the largely unsung efforts of
those men and women.
</P>
<P>
   His message inspired two of his congregants, Gay Block and Malka
Drucker, to write a powerful book, ``Rescuers: Portraits of Moral
Courage in the Holocaust'' (Koen Book Distributor; $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   And in a coincidence that is every bit Hollywood, their book
landed on the desk of Showtime's then-newly named president of
programming, who also happened to be a longtime member of Valley
Beth Shalom.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Offsay had come in to the office to meet his staff a
couple of days before starting at Showtime. His soon-to-be
secretary had a package for him and asked whether she should pass
it on to him or hold onto it until his first day.
</P>
<P>
   He took it home. The package contained Block and Drucker's
``Rescuers'' _ and Offsay stayed up reading until 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   His mind was made up by the time he got to the afterword,
written by none other than Schulweiss.
</P>
<P>
   After a brainstorming session with Showtime executives, the idea
for six separate one-hour films was solidified. All Showtime needed
to green-light the deal was a powerful name to back the project and
attract top-notch writers, directors and actors. Enter Barbra
Streisand and Cis Corman's production company. And the rest is
television history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the most commercial subject matter,'' Offsay said,
``but subject matter like this does not come along very often. It
was another important step in reshaping the network. For the people
who did see it, it may very well be the most satisfying experience
they have had while watching television in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The first two hours of the Showtime series were shown in
October, the second couplet in May. Sunday's segments are subtitled
``Two Families,'' and consist of ``Malka Csizmadia'' and ``We Are
Circus,'' both adapted from first-person accounts in Drucker and
Block's book.
</P>
<P>
   The first, a love story, stars Robin Tunney as the title
character and Michael Rapaport as Szarany, a Jew living in the
ghetto near Malka's home in Hungary. Malka, who helps Szarany and
his friends escape, falls in love with the Jewish soldier. However,
he falls for her sister Irena (Caterina Scorsone) and they marry.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Circus,'' Tim Matheson and Daryl Hannah play Adolph and
Maria Althoff, master and star of a traveling circus that performed
acrobatic stunts, rode an elephant and harbored Jewish escapees
during the war. Eventually, aerialist Hans (Joe Bostick), whose own
family was killed during a bombing raid, informs the authorities
about the Jews in hiding. Then, the Althoff Circus has to slip past
their enemies and convince the Allies that they have no political
affiliation with Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   These are only a few of the other Oskar Schindlers who saved so
many lives.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the authors' contracts, the rescuers depicted in the
series will receive money from the production company, Drucker
said. It's well-deserved, Schulweiss adds, since many rescuers _
now in their 80s _ have not led great lives because their homeland
never regarded them as heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ignorance about this is appalling,'' he said. ``I think it
is because we are afraid of goodness. We are much more comfortable
with evil. We dote on evil. We know more about (high-ranking Nazis
Heinrich) Himmler and (Adolf) Eichmann than the family who risked
their lives to hide Anne Frank because, compared to them, we're
great people.''
</P>
<P>
   But listening to the rescuers' stories can only make us all be
better people, Schulweiss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a battle for our own moral survival, otherwise we will
turn cynical and pessimistic, and it destroys faith,'' he said.
``If you destroy faith in man, you cripple man.''
</P>
<P>
   Drucker, an author of children's books, heard every word of the
rabbi's message. She was so inspired by his teachings that she is
now an ordained rabbi. And the book is dedicated to Schulweiss, a
man whose influence she says has been ``phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   The feelings are mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``She and Gay Block did this marvelous book where people were
inspired,'' Schulweiss said. ``To honor people who are honorable is
a great mandate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
