<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-COMPARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANS VOTE SUNDAY IN RACE TOO CLOSE TO CALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMBURG, Germany _ As a hard-fought German election campaign
comes to a vote on Sunday, one of the most striking features is
that the two leading parties are fighting about very little.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates for chancellor defend Germany's generous social
programs. Both support plans to abandon the German mark for the
euro, the new European currency. Both give top priority to tax
reform, though their plans differ in the details. And both would
continue Germany's existing foreign policy, including a role in
peace-keeping forces abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Billboards for Gerhard Schroeder and his left-of-center Social
Democrats boast, ``We don't want to change everything, just make it
much better.'' Chancellor Helmut Kohl and his right-of-center
Christian Democrats promise ``Security, not Risk.''
</P>
<P>
   This matches the country's mood. German voters may be eager for
a change of government, but there is little popular pressure for
sweeping changes in policy or in Germany's protective social-market
economy. This may help to explain why the race remains far too
tight to call, with opinion polls showing a large number of voters
still undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a basic feeling that we don't want to see Kohl's face
anymore, but I am not sure that people want a basic change in
policy,'' said Theo Sommer, co-publisher of the weekly newspaper
Die Zeit. ``There is no debate between Thatcherism on the one hand
and state socialism on the other hand. It is about nuances.''
</P>
<P>
   Sommer's co-publisher is a former chancellor, Helmut Schmidt,
who was ousted by Kohl in 1982. Die Zeit has never been pro-Kohl,
but a rival publication, the conservative daily Die Welt, drew
strikingly similar conclusions about the country's mood in an
editorial this week. ``What is better for this country, continuity
or change?'' it asked. ``The answer being given is clear: both.''
</P>
<P>
   German elections usually lack sharp differences on issues, and
most of Germany's post-1945 governments have been coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way it is in every election battle,'' said Mario
Ohoven, president of the Federation of Mid-Sized Industry, in
Duesseldorf. ``It is not driven primarily by the content of
policies, but rather by the question of power. The policy-making
doesn't begin until the day after the election.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, business leaders argue that there is a basic
difference in the tendency of the two parties _ and they are
solidly behind Kohl's coalition. Even if both sides embrace similar
principles, they pull in different directions: Social Democrats
place less importance on stimulating business or reducing taxes,
while the Christian Democrats generally push toward further
de-regulation and less government spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a basic issue in this election, which is that the
Social Democrats still stand for the old German idea of more
caretaking by the state,'' said Berthold Leibinger, president of
Trumpf GmbH, which makes advanced machine tools just outside
Stuttgart.
</P>
<P>
   Germany has some big problems. Unemployment is above 10 percent.
Taxes consume nearly half the average paycheck. Many elementary
schools are so pinched for money that students are simply sent home
when a teacher is out sick.
</P>
<P>
   But those issues played little part in a campaign intent on
small details: Is Kohl, at 68, too old and tired? Has his Christian
Democratic Union run out of steam? Would the 54-year-old Schroeder
bring more youth and skill to get things done? Would a new
political coalition somehow be able to break through the gridlock
that has paralyzed efforts like tax reform?
</P>
<P>
   With both candidates fighting to capture the political center,
neither wants to alarm constituents. Schroeder's once substantial
lead over Kohl has narrowed to just two or three percentage points,
and at least 20 percent of voters are undecided. It is possible
that neither will muster a majority of votes with their most
obvious coalition partners, and that their parties will have to
govern in tandem in a ``Grand Coalition.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, as the race narrowed almost to a dead heat, the
debate has sharpened somewhat. Kohl spent more time warning that
the Social Democrats and the more leftist Green Party may form an
alliance with the successor to East Germany's Communist party.
Schroeder has muted the vaguely pro-business parts of his stump
speech and re-emphasized traditional Social Democrat themes like
social justice.
</P>
<P>
   In specific policy disputes, the candidates have focused on
marginal differences. Both parties have singled out tax reform as
their biggest priority, and both would lower top tax rates and
eliminate loopholes. Kohl would reduce the overall tax burden by
about 3 percent; Schroeder would not lower the overall burden but
would shift more of it to wealthy people and companies.
</P>
<P>
   Business executives overwhelmingly prefer Kohl and his tax plan,
which Social Democrats blocked in Parliament last year. But even
Kohl's plan leaves executives complaining that he was too cautious
and too willing to cut deals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ronald Reagan pushed for tax reform, he explained it in
clear and understandable terms,'' said Wilfried Prewo, president of
Hanover's Chamber of Commerce and Industry and an advocate of
deeper tax cuts across the board. Kohl's party, he said, ``took an
originally good idea and watered it down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By getting so entangled in compromises, they endangered the
purity of the tax reform and everybody was confused,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But the Social Democrats have hardly been a beacon of clarity.
Their most prominent proposals have been to roll back a handful of
Kohl's modest attempts to reform pension and labor laws. They have
yet to propose a way to salvage Germany's generous pension system
from bankruptcy, which looms when today's baby boomers reach
retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   One issue that does divide the parties is the treatment of
immigrants, of which Germany now has about 7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has called for tougher border controls and immediate
expulsion of immigrants who commit crime, and the calls often
generate the loudest cheering and applause in his speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder has been much quieter about the issue, though he
echoes the demand for immediate expulsion of foreign criminals. The
Social Democrats are big beneficiaries of ``foreigners,'' because
changes in citizenship law have allowed more than 100,000
German-born Turks to become citizens, and those voters are
adamantly Social Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   On the one issue where Social Democrats could have easily picked
a major fight with Kohl, they did not. The chancellor considered
the euro, the new European currency, his final and most important
project, even though most Germans opposed abandoning their trusted
marks. The Social Democrats decided more than a year ago that they
would not attack the euro, and contented themselves with
criticizing Kohl's steps along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it is only natural that there is little heated economic
debate, despite high unemployment. After long years of slow growth,
German voters sense a turnaround, and are relishing their stability
in light of crises in Asia, Latin America and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't detect that despair or despondency that I keep reading
about,'' said Sommer, at Die Zeit. ``The economy is improving, and
there have been changes. People feel we aren't actually doing that
badly, that we are on the right track.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1756EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GODS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-25 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GODS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GODS AND MONSTERS': PORTRAIT OF THE ARTIST AS A GAY MAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes at end of review.)  
(lb) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Gods and Monsters'' is an unalloyed success at the
New York Film Festival, with a performance by Sir Ian McKellen that
richly deserves to be remembered at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Like John Hurt in ``Love and Death on Long Island'' (giving a
similarly splendid performance, though in a narrower role), he
works wonders with the character of a marvelously urbane English
homosexual who becomes obsessed with an Adonis from a wildly
different world. In this case it's Brendan Fraser, also impressive,
as the hunk who mows the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   It happens that the English gentlemen in both these films find
themselves incongruously embroiled in American popular culture.
This time, it's the still-grand Hollywood of 1957, the year the
director James Whale, whom McKellen plays, met his mysterious
death. It was Whale who directed the famous Frankenstein movies.
(``I just directed the first two,'' he points out tartly here.
``The others were done by hacks.'')
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of a long career, he also painted, worked as an
actor and made many other films (among them ``The Invisible Man''
and the original ``Waterloo Bridge'').
</P>
<P>
   Taking off from Whale's complex nature and the unknown
circumstances of his last days, the film adapts Christopher Bram's
hypothetical novel about the filmmaker into an immensely touching
character study that is heightened by well-chosen glimpses of
Hollywood's past.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Bill Condon, who had his own fling with
tongue-in-cheek horror when he made the oddball ``Strange
Behavior'' and ``Strange Invaders,'' ``Gods and Monsters'' creates
a deeply resonant portrait of Whale and the gay Hollywood of his
era.
</P>
<P>
   One day, while having a marvelous time playing cat-and-mouse
games with an overeager young interviewer visiting him at poolside
(the Whale pool is used by its owner strictly as an instrument of
seduction), Whale succumbs to a small but debilitating stroke. He
is physically unimpaired afterward, as coy and debonair as ever,
but his mind has begun playing tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden sensations and painful thoughts of the past begin to
overwhelm him, in a manner that Condon illustrates with haunting
grace. (Carter Burwell's beautifully mournful score enhances these
moments.) At the same point in his life, he sees a tempting
opportunity when the gardener appears outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppose we say phooey to the hedges!'' Whale suggests to
handsome Clayton Boone (Fraser). ``Can you spare an hour after
lunch to sit for me?'' Clayton, who proves a far more
multidimensional figure than might be expected, is suspicious at
first of Whale's desire to draw him, but the old slyboots does a
dauntless job of getting under the young man's skin.
</P>
<P>
   Condon is at his most impressive when weaving their peculiar
bond into the spirit of the Frankenstein movies, something he does
with tenderness and insight. An inspired section of the film finds
all of its principals watching ``The Bride of Frankenstein'' on
television and responding to it in revealing ways.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Condon segues deftly through memory into the
moviemaking process itself. Here and elsewhere, real Hollywood
figures (Elsa Lanchester, Boris Karloff) are ably impersonated.
Particular attention is paid to George Cukor, a target for Whale's
cattiness and an emblematic figure in the closeted gay subculture
of his time.
</P>
<P>
   With a cast that also includes Lolita Davidovitch as Clayton's
occasional girlfriend and Lynn Redgrave, warmly attentive and
unrecognizably plain, as Whale's devoted housekeeper, ``Gods and
Monsters'' has been capably made in all regards. What especially
elevates it is the razor-sharp cleverness of McKellen's
performance, which brings unusual fullness and feeling to a most
unusual man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gods and Monsters'' will be shown Saturday night at 6 and
Sunday at 1:30 p.m. as part of the New York Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GODS AND MONSTERS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bill Condon; written by Condon, based on the novel
``Father of Frankenstein'' by Christopher Bram; director of
photography, Stephen M. Katz; edited by Virginia Katz; production
designer, Richard Sherman; music by Carter Burwell; produced by
Paul Colichman, Gregg Fienberg and Mark R. Harris; released by
Lions Gate Films. Shown with a four-minute short, Steve Salinaro's
``My Ex.'' Saturday at 6 p.m. and Sunday at 1:30 p.m. at Alice
Tully Hall as part of the 36th New York Film Festival. Running
time: 105 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ian McKellen (James Whale), Brendan Fraser (Clayton
Boone), Lynn Redgrave (Hanna), Lolita Davidovich (Betty), Kevin J.
O'Connor (Harry), David Dukes (David Lewis), Brandon Kleyla (Young
Whale), Pamela Salem (Sarah Whale), Michael O'Hagan (William
Whale), Jack Plotnick (Edmund Kay) and Sarah Ann Morris (Daisy).
</P>
</TEXT>
