<HEADER>
A5024 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-HEDGEFUNDS-ART     09-25 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-HEDGEFUNDS-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREADING THE RISKS OF HEDGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 27)  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hedge funds lost their luster in a big way last week when
Long-Term Capital Management, once the brain-trust darling of Wall
Street, came within a hair's breadth of bankruptcy and investors
were said to be left with 20 percent or less of their stakes.
</P>
<P>
   But even as some giant hedge funds have been tanking, banks,
investment firms and private money managers have been aggressively
marketing a relatively new type of product that they call a
low-risk way to play the hedge fund game. Indeed, if you have
$100,000 or more to invest, your broker or private banker may have
already pitched the investment idea: a fund of hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
   The structure is a pretty simple. A fund of hedge funds takes
your money and divides it among anywhere from 6 to 80 hedge fund
managers _ like Long-Term Capital or, of course, some
better-performing fund.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, on the one hand, is to put your money in the care of
savvy managers who do not limit themselves to investments as
mundane as stocks and, on the other hand, to spread the risk. The
managers can sell equities short, making bets that the market will
decline. They can invest in currencies, play with derivatives, pile
into commodities and make outsized bets on the direction of
interest rates. And because hedge funds often use futures, they can
pack leveraged punch, giving investors exaggerated returns _ good
or bad. Their aim is to turn a profit no matter what happens in the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   In funds of funds, the idea is that, because your money is
spread among multiple hedge funds, you can avoid volatility.
</P>
<P>
   But how have funds of funds been performing in one of the
rockiest stock markets in recent years? It depends on your
expectations. In an awful August, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index slid 14.5 percent, the Morgan Stanley Capital International
World index was down 13.4 percent and the 3,600 general equity
mutual funds tracked by Lipper Analytical Services skidded an
average of 16.7 percent. But the 212 funds of hedge funds tracked
by Managed Account Reports, a monthly hedge fund newsletter, posted
a relatively modest median decline of 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the year through Aug. 31, the funds of funds had a median
return of 2.3 percent. By contrast, the mutual funds fell 10.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the last three years, however, both the S&AMP;P 500 and
the mutual funds clobbered funds of hedge funds. In 1997, the S&AMP;P
500 returned 33.4 percent and the mutual funds returned 25 percent.
Funds of hedge funds mustered only 17.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say funds of hedge funds did not offer enough
protection during the selloff. Lois Peltz, managing editor of
Managed Account Reports, said many were insufficiently diversified
and were too heavily weighted in emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert de Botton, chairman of the London-based Global Asset
Management Ltd., which runs hedge funds, funds of hedge funds and
mutual funds in the United States and overseas, disagreed.
``Overdiversification neutralizes everything you do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because funds of funds beat their peers during the selloff, they
will be attractive to some investors; after all, most people are
interested in hedging against downturns, not updrafts. And the fund
minimums _ now as low as $100,000 _ are likely to fall further.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will probably become more democratic, because there is a
desire for investors to participate in investments that are not
dependent on market direction to generate a return and provide
diversification,'' said Steven Eckenberger, senior vice president
at AIG International Asset Management, which runs a fund of hedge
funds in partnership with Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of money in funds of funds has risen to an estimated
$29.5 billion this year, from $4 billion five years ago, according
to Hennessee Hedge Fund Advisory Group, a New York firm that
advises hedge fund investors.
</P>
<P>
   How can you judge a fund of hedge funds as a prospective
investment? As in mutual funds, you can look at the manager's
tenure, the fund's performance against the S&AMP;P 500 and the fund's
turnover rate _ taxwise, many are highly inefficient.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to weigh the relative merits of different funds of
hedge funds because their managers are not required to disclose
their strategies and holdings, as mutual fund managers are. And
most hedge funds of funds let investors withdraw their money only
at the end of a month, quarter or year.
</P>
<P>
   It is also hard to stomach the fees. Hedge fund managers have
long charged a 1 percent management fee and taken 20 percent of
profits. But with funds of hedge funds, the extra layer of managers
gets a healthy slice of the cake, too.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Bankers Trust last year started a fund of hedge
funds, named Topiary, that oversees $1 billion and uses 80
managers. It takes a 1 percent annual management fee that is paid
quarterly, said Nicola Meaden, chief executive of Tass Management,
a London-based firm that tracks hedge funds. That's on top of what
the underlying hedge funds are charging. Bankers Trust also gets a
cut of the profits: 10 percent after the fund's performance exceeds
the Treasury Bill rate, a very unaggressive benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   Those fat fee structures have provoked some sharp words from
critics, including Byron Wien, chief U.S. investment strategist at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, which does not market a fund of funds.
He argues that payment should be based on performance alone. ``I
would give them 50 percent of the amount by which they beat the
S&AMP;P,'' Wien said.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, you should understand the risk involved in any
hedge fund. As Long-Term Capital proved, hedge funds can be risky
business, indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
