s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$A     09-25 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK STOCKS: BATTERED, YES, BUT NOT TO BE FORGOTTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 27)  
 (bl)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the world's financial system in turmoil, it makes a certain
amount of sense that financial stocks, especially those of banks
and brokerage firms, have been pounded.
</P>
<P>
   Since its peak in the middle of July, an index of 24
money-center and superregional bank stocks compiled by Keefe,
Bruyette &AMP; Woods, a firm that researches bank stocks, has declined
by 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many banks don't have a dime of exposure in Asia or Russia,
let alone Long-Term Capital Management LP. They are still doing
basic blocking and tackling close to home and are not losing money.
</P>
<P>
   Keefe research director David Berry took a few minutes late last
week to discuss whether the world has really changed all that much.
</P>
<P>
   Q. On Thursday, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said the
problems at Long-Term Capital posed no systemic risk to our
financial system. What shape is the banking system in?
</P>
<P>
   A. The banking system is not as good as it was a few months ago,
but it is still in pretty good shape. And it is in much better
shape than it was in the late 1980s and early 1990s, the last time
there was a serious crisis. The industry today is much more
profitable, much more efficient and has lower levels of problem
assets than it did then. Unfortunately, that does not mean you are
going to make money in the stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is that to say you don't like the group?
</P>
<P>
   A. No, these stocks are attractive, but it is going to take a
while to calm people down.
</P>
<P>
   The money-center banks, which have fallen the most, are the
high-risk, high-return plays and are the focal point of investor
fears. Both they and the big investment banks need some restoration
or normalcy in the capital markets before folks start to relax. And
it is very possible regional bank stocks, particularly the
superregionals, will begin to recover when they start to report
third-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Assuming that an investor doesn't want to roll the dice with
a money-center stock, which companies look good to you now?
</P>
<P>
   A. The prudent, safe and sane thing is to avoid money centers
and invest in strong, superregional banks that are stable and
probably don't lend much to hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
   We like organizations like Suntrust, National City Corp. in
Ohio, Mellon Bank and State Street of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What do you expect third-quarter earnings to look like?
</P>
<P>
   A. Most of the bad news is out there. The biggest damage is in
money-center land, and we think the hit there is about $2.4 billion
more than we did a few weeks ago. To put that in perspective, the
entire commercial banking system earned $16 billion in the second
quarter. So we will fall short of that by about 15 percent. That is
a big and noticeable amount, but not staggering.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Last week Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal
Reserve, seemed to signal that he is prepared to cut short-term
interest rates. That should help the banks, right?
</P>
<P>
   A. It would help if we get some upward slope to the yield curve,
where short rates are lower than longer-term rates. But even if we
get a rate cut, it is not guaranteed that the yield curve will turn
positive. With the federal funds rate at 5.5 percent, even a
half-point cut wouldn't give you that upward slope. I have been
concerned that in the face of all that is going on, the Fed might
choose not to act.
</P>
<P>
   And yet over the last couple of days, the Fed approved the
Travelers-Citicorp merger. We got a fairly clear indication from
Mr. Greenspan that rates are coming down, possibly this week. And
we have this effort coordinated by the New York Fed to support
Long-Term Capital. That is a lot of very concentrated activity.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the consolidation trend over for now?
</P>
<P>
   A. There is a good case to be made that we are in for a hiatus.
The level of certainty that bank chief executives have today is
probably less than it was three months ago. Put another way, having
your stock price get knocked down by one-third hurts your
confidence and makes you less bold. Also, sellers are interested in
getting a certain price on a deal. Right now, they are not likely
to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Longer term, secular forces for consolidation are still there.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is your take on 1999 for the banks?
</P>
<P>
   A. We are walking around with the view that the economy will be
slower next year and that interest rates will be lower.
</P>
<P>
   For the banks, that means slower revenue growth and a refocus
back on the expense side of the equation. That outlook is not as
robust as it was a couple of months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, compared with other stocks, banks will show good earnings
momentum next year. I feel comfortable with the basic statement
that banks will show a bit better earnings growth than the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
