s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV27-NY     09-25 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC VIEW: POLICY MEANS NOTHING IF SHELVES ARE BARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 27)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who thinks all this global market turmoil is mostly about
devalued currencies, deflation and doomsday scenarios should try to
check in with Anwar Ibrahim. He's a bit hard to reach these days.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few weeks ago, Anwar was the insightful, canny finance
minister of Malaysia, the man anointed to take over as prime
minister some day, and the symbol of his country's astounding
transition from a backwater of rubber plantations and tin mines to
a leading maker of computer chips and cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   Today he is sitting in jail, held under Malaysia's Internal
Security Act, a law first used 30 years ago to detain suspected
communist insurgents without trial. Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad
is now wielding it to put down an economic insurgency led by Anwar.
The new subversives have the temerity to suggest that for Malaysia
to make the next leap, it must embrace the discipline of global
markets and stop rewarding Mahathir's cronies.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar's descent from the finance minister's suite to solitary
confinement is the story of a seemingly successful authoritarian
regime cracking under economic pressure _ the same pressure that
toppled President Suharto in Indonesia and brought chaos to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a humbling warning to economists whipping up
strategies for putting the world back on track. Bad economics _
horrendous misjudgments made worse by misguidance from the
International Monetary Fund _ may have set off the Asian crisis.
But not even a perfect economic solution, if someone had one, could
stuff the genie back in the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly this is a crisis about power politics and national
cultures. No economic elixir will work if it is politically
unpalatable to Muscovites searching empty shelves or to Indonesians
again desperate, as they were a generation ago, at the prospect of
unaffordable rice. No wonder the IMF, stuffed with more than 1,000
Ph.D. economists with little background in national politics, keeps
getting wiped out in Kiev and Surabaya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair to say that we misjudged the kind of
political currents that the crisis would unleash,'' a senior
official of the IMF conceded a few weeks ago. ``It's not the way
people in this building have ever been trained to think. If they
did, they would work at the U.N.''
</P>
<P>
   So now, 14 months into the crisis, the countries of the world
can be divided into three broad categories: the Defiant, the
Drifters and the Dutiful.
</P>
<P>
   The Defiant are the most interesting: the countries that, after
a year of dueling with global markets, have chosen to wall
themselves off. Malaysia is the prime example.
</P>
<P>
   While Anwar was echoing the language of Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin and the IMF, talking about austerity, transparency and
market reforms, his prime minister was spinning dark conspiracy
theories about how George Soros and a cabal of secretive financiers
were plotting ``new forms of colonialism.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually that cognitive dissonance grew too great, and Anwar
was sacked and accused, apparently spuriously, of sodomy by
Mahathir. Now acting as his own finance minister, Mahathir imposed
exchange controls and declared the country's currency worthless
outside its borders, leaving terrified international investors _
and Malaysia has plenty, from Intel to Motorola to Coca-Cola _ to
wonder if they will be able to repatriate their profits.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, where tax collection never took hold, never mind market
economics, is speeding into the Defiant camp as well. Its new
economic team, appointed last week, has been dealing with the
country's creditors by decree, with threats to default if the
country is not given more IMF aid on Moscow's terms. Meanwhile, it
is flouting the fund's prescriptions by printing money to pay off
unhappy miners and, more important, the restive rocket corps
officers who command the nuclear silos.
</P>
<P>
   Concern that the ranks of the Defiant will grow explains why
Washington is so worried about the Drifters, countries like
Indonesia and Japan that seem unable to get any traction because
their banks have collapsed and their leadership is paralyzed.
``These are nations that could go either way,'' one White House
economic adviser noted the other day. ``They could stumble through,
or try to wall off the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the Dutiful, following the Western
prescriptions and enduring the pain of slashed budgets and high
interest rates, who wonder hourly whether they are obedient
optimists. Brazil and Mexico lead the Dutiful pack and have staved
off disaster so far. There are signs of hope elsewhere: Interest
rates have fallen in Thailand and South Korea, the only two nations
to fully implement IMF programs. But the cranes in Bangkok still
aren't moving, and Korea's giant conglomerates have failed to
downsize in the face of street protests.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the future for all three groups depends most on the
outcome of the longer political struggle between the Anwars of the
global economy and the Mahathirs of cronyism and isolation. No
econometric model can forecast a winner in that fight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
