<SLUG> BC-BOX-LEWIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LEWIS, THE PROOF IS IN THE PUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNCASVILLE, Conn. _ There are many ways to look at the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Fear is one way. Confusion and misunderstanding are another. And
then there is the way World Boxing Council heavyweight champion
Lennox Lewis looks at it.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, like most heavy-handed knockout artists, likes to get to
the point. So when the question under discussion is the challenge
posed to him by an unknown Croatian with a Mohawk haircut, the
heavyweight champion of at least one-third of the world is succinct
in his commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's punched him?'' Lewis asks, in a tone that indicates
somebody intends to Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   When you think about it, that is as good a way as any to judge a
heavyweight boxer. So just who has punched Zeljko Mavrovic?
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, until this fight, at least, 27 nobodies.
</P>
<P>
   That trend will surely come to a concussive end early this
evening for the 29-year-old European champion. Not long after he
enters the 5,000-seat temporary arena at the Mohegan Sun Casino,
Lewis will be standing there waiting for him with right arm poised
to be thrown like Thor's thunderbolts.
</P>
<P>
   When that thunder crashes down on him from out of the starry,
starry night, Mavrovic may well see stars himself. What flows from
that (assuming it's not a sea of blood) will let us all know more
about the unknown. Or at least more about the unknown Croatian
challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Mavrovic will be able to withstand Lewis's crushing
right hand, with which he has knocked out 27 victims while twice
winning the WBC title. Perhaps he will prove he can box as well as
his trainer, John ``Darkie'' Smith, says he can. Perhaps he will
expertly parry and counter all of Lewis's advances, slip to and
fro, escape the worst of it while delivering his own blows.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he will show that his 22 knockouts against fighters of
less than world-class ability stand for something even if his
opponents couldn't stand up for long. In that case, HBO's audience
and an expected packed house at Mohegan Sun would be in for a bit
of a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   But what's far likelier is that after the 220-pound Mavrovic
(27-0) gets hit by Lewis a time or two, he will suddenly realize
that who is hitting him is all that matters when men in excess of
200 pounds are throwing the bombs. Regardless of the outcome, that
experience will be far different from being biffed and banged by
guys like Dannell Nicholson, Kimmuel Odom, Marion Wilson, and James
Pritchard, and how he reacts cannot be known until it happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox Lewis is a big man,'' his Hall of Fame trainer, Emanuel
Steward, said this week of the 250-pound champion. ``In the last 25
years, there's only been about four born-from-the-cradle punchers.
Sonny Liston, Mike Tyson, George Foreman, and Lennox Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   Born-from-the-cradle punchers are boxing's version of
natural-born killers. They are lethal and often ill-tempered, and
Mavrovic has never been in with such an opponent. Then again,
ignorance is bliss, which perhaps explains why Mavrovic's trainer
has been so willing to point out the champion's weaknesses and his
fighter's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zeljko has the potential to be the best heavyweight in the
world,'' Smith said, ``but you can only do what you're asked to do.
If Lewis expects us to say he'll beat Zeljko, then Lennox Lewis is
an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for Lewis, but I believe Mavrovic will
beat him. That's not insulting. It's what I believe. After watching
the Lewis-(Shannon) Briggs fight, we were very confident. Nothing
has changed since then.''
</P>
<P>
   That night, Briggs rocked Lewis early before succumbing to
fist-to-the-face-induced exhaustion. He collapsed to the floor
after missing a wild roundhouse left hand in the fifth round after
having been knocked down four times, and the referee looked at that
and came to one conclusion _ say good night, Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   Many who watched believe Lewis was in big trouble in the opening
round when Briggs appeared to hurt him badly, but the champion
himself was not among them. When he thinks back on that March
evening, he has little recollection of being in trouble. What he
remembers is who was punching Shannon Briggs and what happened
after he did that a few times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't that hurt, but it made it real exciting for the
public,'' Lewis said. ``You can't walk in the ring without getting
hit. In a fight situation, there's always a chance you'll get hit.
Shannon Briggs pulled out all the stops, and that gave him a
glimmer of hope that he was almost there.''
</P>
<P>
   That glimmer was extinguished quickly by the thing Lewis
believes in most: his right hand. When Lewis landed it, Briggs did
not react well, ending up too often on his knees. Thus, from
Lewis's point of view, we're talking about the familiar _ another
knockout victory.
</P>
<P>
   But a few feet from the ring that night in Atlantic City sat
Mavrovic, and what he saw was Lewis tottering backward on rubbery
legs after Briggs nailed him in the opening round. That is the
image he has retained from that night as his own time approaches,
wiping from his memory any thought of who was hitting Briggs at the
end while focusing on who was hitting Lewis at the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I saw was a fighter who didn't have the motivation for
the training,'' Mavrovic said. ``I saw a fighter who has a problem
with his mind and his motivation. He didn't prepare well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prepared 11 months for this fight. I always train very
seriously, and I can fight. I know his good points and his bad
points. During all my preparations, I thought about Lennox Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   The same couldn't be said for Lewis. While Mavrovic talks only
of the WBC champion, the WBC champion talks only of the World
Boxing Association-International Boxing Federation champion,
Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   It is Holyfield whom Lewis most wanted to be getting in with. It
is Holyfield who has what Lewis craves _ the respect of the
American boxing public. Most of all, it is Holyfield who is on
Lewis's mind even for this fight, despite the presence of a
different challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I came into boxing, what I always wanted to be was
undisputed champion of the world,'' Lewis said. ``My mouth was
watering watching Holyfield against (Vaughn) Bean (whom Holyfield
beat in a nondescript 12-round decision last Saturday). But I know
if I lose this fight, there is no after-fight. If I lose this
fight, there is no Holyfield fight. So I got to keep it going.''
</P>
<P>
   To do that, Lewis must do more than defeat Mavrovic. Steward
believes Lewis must dispose of him quickly, not only destroying his
challenger but uplifting himself in contrast to Holyfield's
lackluster victory over Bean. Such desires can open a man up to
possible disaster if they're not pursued with some care. But Lewis
seems to believe that Mavrovic is ultimately not unlike the
opponent he saw in Briggs and so many others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect him to try and box, to go into survival mode,'' Lewis
said. ``He'll try to use the ring to his advantage. He believes he
can elude me for 12 rounds. That's a big mistake. I'll search and
destroy. I don't plan on this guy going the distance.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because, unlike Zeljko Mavrovic, Lennox Lewis knows full
well who will be punching the unknown Croatian Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The heavyweight champion of the world will be. And, to put it in
the vernacular of the gym, he ain't no Kimmuel Odom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
