<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENT-FILMS-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHER HOPES AND MORE COMPETITION FOR THE INDIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twenty years ago it was a simpler world for
Warrington Hudlin and other young filmmakers who gathered in New
York for the first Independent Feature Film Market. ``There were no
expectations then,'' he said Thursday at a lunch to celebrate the
market's 20th anniversary. ``Camaraderie was incredible because
you'd made a choice not to make a Hollywood movie. You had to
reassure yourself that you weren't crazy, and the mutual support
kept you going.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, though, other things were on the minds of hundreds of
aspiring directors and writers who crowded the market, called IFFM,
in lower Manhattan to screen their work at the Angelika Film Center
and mingle with distributors, agents, and scouts from film
festivals and movie studios. Kinship had its place, of course, but
the emphasis was on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations now run high among the independents. Films like
``Shine'' and ``Fargo'' and, more recently, ``The Opposite of Sex''
and ``The Spanish Prisoner,'' may never be mistaken for
blockbusters at the box office, but their relative success makes
them legitimate economic properties and elevates the breed into
what has become a sleek and increasingly pampered genre.
</P>
<P>
   Why shouldn't that raise expectations? ``People feel if you come
to the market and don't get that `Roger and Me' deal, it's not
worthwhile,'' Hudlin said.
</P>
<P>
   These days even the Hollywood studios, all of them equipped with
``independent'' divisions like Miramax and October Films, are on
the lookout for material. They and a throng of smaller distributors
were on hand at the market, which is staged every fall by the
Independent Feature Project, an alliance of filmmakers and
production and distribution companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make a great film, somebody will want to show it,''
John Waters, director of ``Pink Flamingoes,'' told a group of young
filmmakers at a panel discussion at the Anthology Film Archive.
</P>
<P>
   For a young moviemaker with a project to sell, that's heady
talk, especially from a man who began his career in the underground
with experimental and exploitational films. There were qualifiers,
of course. ``The film has to make money, let's not forget,'' Waters
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another panel participant, Mary Harron, director of ``I Shot
Andy Warhol,'' reminded the filmmakers that while production was
up, distribution was abbreviated, with films quickly being shunted
from theaters to make way for other films.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, whose latest film, ``Pecker,'' opened Friday solidly in
the mainstream, agreed. ``A picture has to work fast,'' he said.
``There's absolutely no time for word of mouth any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Later at lunch, he, Ms. Harron, Hudlin and several other
filmmakers sat amid the din at Monzu and talked about what young
filmmakers should take away from their experience at IFFM. First,
they shouldn't put so much stress on finalizing a deal, which
happens infrequently at the market and usually only after much
cultivation later.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this talk about it being a golden time is misleading,''
said Joe Berlinger, director of ``Brother's Keeper'' and other
acclaimed documentaries, who was a fledgling himself when he
brought his work to the market 10 years ago. ``It's very difficult
to get into major distribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Berlinger sensed more pressure than usual at this year's IFFM.
``Expectations have been ratcheted so much higher,'' he said.
``There's a lot of desperation now.''
</P>
<P>
   The veterans' advice was to relax, make connections with people
you will work with (and who might back your project later if they
don't agree to do so now), learn the craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the market you're beginning to get a sense of the size,
velocity and competitiveness of the business,'' said Matthew
Harrison, director of ``Kicked in the Head.'' For years before he
sold the film, he said, he went to the market, set up a table in
the Angelika and concentrated on learning from those he
encountered.
</P>
<P>
   He and the others offered the following tips. First, look for
future collaborators, and don't be offended if they have money.
Filmmaking is 25 percent making the film and 75 percent business.
``Form a limited partnership and get money,'' Waters said. ``From
anywhere,'' he added. ``Always be nice to relatives with money.''
And don't be afraid of losing it. ``You don't go bankrupt at
20-something; you just burn the parents' money,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At IFFM, unlike a festival where the emphasis is solely on
selling films, distributors look for talent more than a particular
project. People wear badges color-coded according to occupation _
director, distributor and the like. Buyers sometimes don't wear
their badges so they won't be besieged by directors, who
immediately jump on people not wearing badges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buying movies is a weird game,'' Harrison said. ``Buyers come
here and they don't wear the badge, but then they track people.
It's an efficient place to locate talent. Kids who understand that
and come here with that approach have a better time.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, IFFM is a perfect place to learn about audiences. It's
never comfortable, but sit with people during test screenings. Try
not to be upset at their reactions, especially if they walk out.
During the panel, Todd Solondz, director of ``Welcome to the
Dollhouse'' and the much-anticipated ``Happiness,'' to be shown
Oct. 9 and 10 at the New York Film Festival, said that he always
went to screenings of his films. ``I like to see when they're
yawning,'' he said. ``And then when the eye finally closes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
