<P>
   SUDAN-STARVATION _ More than 700,000 people in Sudan are being
threatened by death from starvation. While the United Nations is
coordinating the largest airlift in the history of Africa, the
suffering continues. Mothers continue to bury their babies and
people stagger for days looking for food. (Melvin, Cox News
Service) WITH PHOTOS, GRAPHIC. 120 inches. MOVED TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-STARVE22 _ A shorter version of the above. 60 inches.
MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-INTRO _ Writer Don Melvin offers his views on the
difficulty of reporting the human hardship being waged as a result
of the famine in Sudan. (Melvin, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   SUDAN-LIST _ A partial list of U.S. agencies accepting donations
to fight the famine in Sudan. (Melvin, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-SECEDE _ LONDON _ The Northern Ireland Assembly began
work this month while Scotland prepares to sit its own parliament
for the first time in decades. The Welsh also are developing
considerable independence and even Cornwall has developed an
independence movement. While the BRitish intendeded these acts of
power decentralizatrion to strengthen the United Kingdom by
instituting a kind of quasi-federalism, the result as been to
actually at heat to the fires of independence. In the course of the
century, the British Empire, once one of the world's most powerful
and expansive political forces could enter the next century as ony
England and a few odd possessions. What does this mean? (Roughton,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With SCOTLAND-PRIMER _ A primer on England, Northern Ireland,
Scotland and Wales. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BARTER _ ENGELS, Russia _ The good news for Trolza, a
mammoth assembly plant and major employer in this depressed town on
the Volga River, was a recent deal worth $25 million to produce
buses for several Russian cities. The bad news: No cash will be
exchanged and no profits will result. Barter made the deal
possible. In a country with a sick economy, a flimsy currency and a
sea of debt, barter accounts for more than two-thirds of all
transactions in Russia. In the West, ``cashless society'' conjures
21st century images of ``smart'' credit cards and high-tech cash
registers and instant electronic debits from a bank account.
Russia's cashless society is from a century in the other direction.
It emerged from a Soviet-era economy that never quite made the
transition to capitalism. The Russian marketplace is hamstrung by
failing banks, the falling ruble, government corruption and an
oppressive tax system. The result is survival-by-barter from the
corner fruit stand to the highest levels of industry. (Holmes, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   BARTER-BOX _ SARATOV, Russia _ ``It involves a lot of time and
nerves and risks,'' Fyodor Shimchuk says of barter. He is general
director of Sapkon/Neftemash, a company in southern Russia that
makes pumps and values for the oil and gas industry. Earlier this
year, it took a dozen negotiators from his company and others more
than two months to complete a barter deal involving $100,000 worth
of equipment. Here's how it unfolded. (Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED
</P>
