<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _This fall is the first time Birmingham bombing suspect
Eric Robert Rudolph has been in the Western North Carolina
mountains during hunting season, and federal officals hope that
fact, combined with the coming winter, will give them a better
chance to find him. Bearhunting season starts Oct. 12, but federal
officials will meet with hunters in Andrews, N.C. to ask for their
participation and remind them of safety tips because agents will
also be in the woods. Bearhunters use tracking dogs, and it's
possible one could stumble on the fugitive or unearth some
evidence. We'll also round up everybody else still in the woods:
feds are now up to 80 agents, and there are a few hangers-on and
quasi-bounty hunters around. 25 inches. (Scruggs, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PARKS _ Rosa Parks is in Cincy to be honored in the inaugural
event for the National Undergound Railroad Freedom Center; retired
federal appeals judge a. leon higginbotham, who served as an
election observer in 1994 in south africa, speaks this afternoon,
as well. (Keilman, Dayton Daily News). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   GLENN _ John Glenn's shuttle flight will include a 30-minute
educational link with students back on earth, including a class at
John Glenn High School in New Concord and a hook up w/ COSI in
Columbus. (Montgomery, Dayton Daily News). 10.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON _ Rev. Jesse Jackson urges Congress to pass a Marshall
Plan for Appalachia, providing grants and low-income loans to help
struggling residents. Jackson spoke with reporters by conference
call before Sunday's march in Nelsonville that will also feature
Rev. Jerry Falwell, Martin Sheen and Willie Nelson. On Monday,
Hocking College and Jackson's Rainbow Push Coalition will sponsor
an economic roundtable to discuss ways to expand economic
development in the region. (Hundley, Dayton Daily News). 12.
</P>
<P>
   OZONE _ In May, smoke and haze from hundreds of forest fires in
Mexico darkened the skies above Texas. At the time, state officials
were concerned mainly about the potential health effects. Now their
concern has shifted to a new question: Did the smoke and haze cause
elevated ozone readings in Austin, San Antonio, Houston and other
cities? Officials believe it did and have asked the federal
Environmental Protection Agency to ignore those readings. An EPA
official told the state's top environmental officer last week that
the request would be granted. But now the federal agency says it
isn't so sure. The question is not academic. Cities deemed in
violation of the ozone standard are likely to be required to adopt
costly and inconvenient pollution-control measures, including
vehicle-emission inspections, reformulated gasoline and
restrictions on industrial expansion. (Haurwitz, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   UT-ASIAN-STUDIES-PROGRAM _ University of Texas administrators
begin their search this week with a series of ads for a professor
to head up an Asian American Studies program to start in the fall
1999 semester. The search culminates a three-year-effort by UT
students and faculty members to rectify what they consider a gaping
hole in the university's ethnic studies programs. While UT has
offered courses African American and Mexican American studies to
students, issues related to the experience of Asian Americans _ who
are the second largest minority group on campus _ has been limited
to the odd class or two. We also explore the place of ethnic
studies in universities nationwide who are still digesting the
Hopwood doctrine. (Shah, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ASIANBOX _ Box with 1998 enrollment figures and ethnicity
breakdown. (Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ASIANFACTS _ Box containing little-known facts about the
contributions of Asian Americans to American society. (Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   ILLEGAL-EMBALMING _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A $445,000 dispute between
the world's largest funeral home company and the State of Texas is
headed for mediation. The dispute has rocked the funeral home
industry in Texas as 1,200 funeral homes watch to see which side
will prevail: the tiny state regulatory agency or the $2.5 billion
industry powerhouse, Service Corporation International, known as
SCI. (Gamino, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC-FIGURE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ In an unusual case of a Waco
television reporter suing another television station for libel, the
Texas Supreme Court decided that the Waco reporter had no case. The
court's decision _ that the Waco reporter was a ``public figure'' _
was its first to define when someone involved in a high-profile
controversy falls into a category that makes winning a libel case
harder than someone considered a private person. (McCarthy, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
