<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO SYMPHONY: RUNNING HOT AND COLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now in his fourth season as music director of the San
Francisco Symphony, Michael Tilson Thomas has unquestionably made
his mark as an assembler of fresh and often surprising programs. By
revisiting neglected scores, finding new works that he can make a
case for without seeming doctrinaire, and giving these nearly equal
time with big works from the standard canon, he has persuaded his
listeners to trust him.
</P>
<P>
   His season programs, like those of Esa-Pekka Salonen, in Los
Angeles, have become models of how modern symphony orchestras can
inhabit the present without neglecting the past. Not
coincidentally, his programming has become a truncheon that critics
can use to beat up on Thomas' less adventurous colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, more to a music directorship than
programming, namely, getting an orchestra to play with brilliance
and precision, and perhaps a quality of sound that sets it apart
from its competitors. Here, Thomas' success has been less complete,
or at least, less consistent.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the all-Gershwin concert with which Thomas and
his San Franciscans opened Carnegie Hall on Wednesday evening was
stunning; yet on Thursday evening, when Thomas conducted works by
Henry Cowell, Berg and Mahler, the playing ran hot and cold, with
lukewarm as the frequent median.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' program, which moved backward in time, created an
interesting effect. Cowell's generically titled ``Music 1957''
hopped around wildly, with Asian-inspired percussion nestled
happily amid shards of 1950s American popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   Brief glimpses of bright, wind-heavy theatrical writing gave way
to passages that would been at home in the score for a western, and
others that were more overtly folksy. There was little of the
dissonant tone-cluster writing for which Cowell was known; instead,
the piece glanced at romanticism by giving its own time a romantic
gloss.
</P>
<P>
   Berg's early Three Pieces (Op. 6), did a similar trick, if less
flippantly. Their textures, dark mood, sweeping gestures and
portentous hammer strokes look back at Mahler, who died only two
years before these pieces were written, yet they brought their own
anxieties to the table. When Mahler turned up after the
intermission, in the form of his Symphony No. 1, he sounded almost
cheery by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra started in fine form, negotiating the changeable
textures and bright hues of the Cowell with an appealing vigor and
solidity. The Berg, with its murkier, busier textures, presented
challenges that the players were not always able to meet.
Entrances, particularly in the brass, sometimes went awry, and
although Thomas' elegant shaping of the work presented its
pessimism unmistakably, there was something missing in the way of
intensity and focus.
</P>
<P>
   That problem was magnified in the Mahler. In the big climactic
moments _ the end of the first movement, the beginning and end of
the last _ the players pulled out all the stops and let it wail.
But what of the rest of the work? Often, Thomas' tempos dragged and
the players' response was reserved and unanimated.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, fine details _ the pointed wind phrasing and some
bracing viola playing, in the third movement _ were offset by
awkward ensemble and occasional pitch problems. The result of these
deficiencies was a dissipation of structure that left the work
sounding episodic rather than unified. But perhaps that was Thomas'
goal: It linked the Mahler to the deliberately scattered Cowell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
