<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ELECTIONS-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS FACE SCANDAL FALLOUT AT POLLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For Release Sunday, Sept. 27)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although President Clinton continues to be buoyed
by polls showing most Americans don't want him to resign or be
impeached, Democrats nonetheless are bracing for a wave of voter
reaction against their congressional candidates on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats who last summer boasted they might take back the House
now say their main goal is preventing a GOP landslide or maybe even
gaining a seat or two.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republicans are confidently predicting a gain of 10
or more seats in the House _ if they correctly handle the tricky
politics of the White House sex scandal. The House now has 228
Republicans and 206 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are in a pickle: If they don't push the impeachment
process, Republicans won't fire up conservative voters to get out
and vote. On the other hand, if they are too aggressive, GOP
congressional candidates risk alienating key swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   Added to this volatile mix is the unknown impact of releasing
yet more evidence from the 445 boxes of grand jury material that
independent counsel Kenneth Starr turned over to the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment controversy is virtually certain to turn a
sleepy, low-turnout mid-term election into a pulse-quickening
series of races. All 435 House seats are up, as are 34 Senate
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Gans, director of the Center for the Study of the
American Electorate and an acknowledged expert on voter turnout,
predicted in June that turnout this November ``could possibly be
the lowest in American history.''
</P>
<P>
   This month he's changed his forecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we have a much more volatile situation than existed
three months ago,'' Gans said in an interview. ``I'm in the
business now of hedging my bets in ways I wasn't in June..MDNM/''
</P>
<P>
   Polls are sending mixed signals about how heavily the scandal
weighs on voters' minds. A New York Times-CBS poll last week showed
respondents by wide margins don't think impeachment hearings should
be held and don't think Clinton should resign. But the same poll
showed 53 percent of the most likely voters preferring a Republican
House candidate, compared to 41 percent for a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Much could depend on how much of each party's faithful shows up
to vote on election day.
</P>
<P>
   After the release on Sept. 11 of Starr's report, pollsters on
both sides were predicting Republican voters would be energized and
that Democrats would stay home.
</P>
<P>
   But now polls suggest that contrary to expectations, release of
Clinton's videotaped testimony last Monday actually helped the
president. Further, polls also show that many Americans just want
the whole thing to go away.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Democrats feel the momentum may be swinging back
towards them.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who go full tilt for impeachment are ``playing with
fire, and I think they're going to get burned,'' said Democratic
political consultant and pollster Mark Mellman.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic charges that House Republicans have overstepped their
bounds by releasing salacious material and pushing impeachment
``may excite (the Democrats') hardcore partisans, but it's not
going to play to the bulk of Americans out there,'' predicted Ed
Goeas, a Republican pollster and consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Goeas said polling done by his organization, The Tarrance Group,
shows the Republican vote hardening while the Democratic vote
softens. Polls notwithstanding, Americans have made up their minds
about Clinton's liability in the scandal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are in the process of coming to a decision about what
the punishment should be,'' Goeas said. ``To take public opinion at
a point in process and say `This is what people say' is not only
misleading, I think it's dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the White House sex scandal, Democrats also face
another gloomy reality: Even in normal times, off-year elections
generally bring bad news for the party in power in the White House.
The last time the president's party did not loose seats was 1934,
just as President Franklin D. Roosevelt, a Democrat, was launching
the New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   To get past the sex scandal, some Democrats in tight House races
are putting as much distance as possible between themselves and
Clinton. Most are trying to focus attention on issues such as
health care, Social Security and education.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also question whether the scandal will have much
impact on the elections at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our chances of regaining the House today would be basically
the same if Monica Lewinsky had never left Beverly Hills 90210,''
said Mellman.
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
