<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIG-SANCTIONS-NYT &LR;      09-25 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIG-SANCTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO FIGHT RELIGIOUS PERSECUTION ABROAD GAINS IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Pa., Okla., Minn., Neb.)  (bl)  
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After months of negotiations, a bill that would
require the U.S. government to punish any foreign country that
persecutes its citizens for their religious beliefs is likely to
become law this year.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week, senators brokered a compromise that would allow
Majority Leader Trent Lott to fulfill a promise he made to
conservative religious groups to bring a bill up for a vote before
Congress adjourns for the year. The Senate could vote on the
measure as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the House overwhelmingly approved a more
restrictive version of the bill, but the main author of that
measure signaled his support for the Senate bill Friday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good bill,'' said Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., who predicted
the full House would approve the measure. ``The failure to pass a
bill would result in open season on people's faith.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Countries found to be violating religious freedoms would be
subject to a wide range of penalties, from mild diplomatic protest
to strict economic sanctions. But the Senate compromise gives the
president much more flexibility in deciding those punishments than
earlier versions of the bill.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, who had said President Clinton would veto
the earlier House and Senate legislation, expressed cautious
optimism Friday that a handful of sticking points could be
resolved, allowing Clinton to sign the compromise bill and avoid a
risky political showdown with Congress.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With this year's congressional session rapidly winding down,
House and Senate Republican leaders are eager to tout the measure
to their conservative base as a major legislative accomplishment,
and put in the hands of candidates an achievement they can use on
the campaign trail.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, however, have been deeply divided over the bill
with social conservatives like the Christian Coalition saying the
measure is needed to protect religious freedoms, while moderates,
encouraged by the Chamber of Commerce, saying it would alienate
important diplomatic and trade partners.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough came Wednesday night when Sen. Don Nickles,
R-Okla., the majority whip, agreed to water down the Senate bill to
win the support of two pro-trade Republicans, Sens. Chuck Hagel of
Nebraska and Rod Grams of Minnesota, whose opposition had bottled
up the bill in committee.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who wrote the House bill with Wolf,
said in an interview, ``It's not as tough as our bill, but it's the
best compromise we can work out.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senators and their aides were still ironing out details on the
measure today, and it was still possible some last-minute problem
could unhinge the deal. A few important senators, like Joseph Biden
of Delaware, the ranking Democrat on the Foreign Relations
Committee, were holding out for changes the White House wants, like
fewer required reports on countries that are restricting religious
liberties.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of the bill expressed confidence that the
modified bill could go to the Senate floor for a vote as early as
next week. ``It should have broad bipartisan support,'' said John
Czwartacki, a spokesman for Lott.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one in Congress objects to the proposition that the United
States should do more to promote religious freedoms around the
world. The big question has been how.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the legislation cite a shocking stream of
incidents, from the killing of Christians in Pakistan and the
Sudan, to the torture of Tibetan Buddhist monks with serrated
knives and thumb screws, as evidence that tougher measures are
needed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In May, the House voted, 375-41, to impose automatic sanctions
against countries that permit or endorse a pattern of violent
attacks or other persecution against religious believers. Violators
would face a cutoff in U.S. aid, except for medical supplies and
food, and U.S. opposition to loans from international financial
institutions.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the House bill never stood a chance in the Senate because of
solid Republican opposition to automatic economic sanctions.
Moreover, senators complained that the House approach would
indiscriminately impose sanctions on such allies as Saudi Arabia,
Germany, Greece and Israel.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If we start picking on our allies and friends, then in the end
we may be doing more harm to ourselves and to the stability of the
world,'' Hagel said Friday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several months, Nickles has met quietly with about
half a dozen senators on both sides of the issue to hammer out a
compromise.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under this week's deal, the State Department would publish an
annual report on religious liberties country by country. As a check
on the administration, an independent commission would also issue a
separate non-binding report. Another State Department report would
identify the countries where the administration was taking steps to
improve religious freedoms.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the president and his aides decide that a specific
country had risen to the level of a ``particularly severe
violator'' of religious freedoms, the president would have to
impose one of more than a dozen penalties or waive the penalty for
national security reasons or because it would hurt religious
freedoms.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This change significantly weakens both the House and original
Senate versions, which required the government to issue an annual
list of countries declared guilty of religious persecution. The
president will now decide that on a case-by-case basis, sparing
offending countries the stigma of appearing on an annual ``bad
guys'' list, Senate aides said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as strong as we'd hoped for,'' said Jeffrey Taylor,
the Christian Coalition's chief lobbyist in Washington, ``but they
are changes we can live with.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
