<HEADER>
A5088 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACAPULCO-HURRICANE-$A     09-25 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACAPULCO-HURRICANE-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY FACES SURGE OF DISCONTENT OVER HANDLING OF STORM CLEANUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Sept. 27)   (EDs: Photos available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP TRUE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENUSTIANO CARRANZA, Mexico _ A year ago, Joaquin Flores Juarez
used to drive his car up the steep slope of this hillside suburb of
Acapulco and park in front of his house.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Hurricane Pauline last October, dumping more than half
of the rainfall this normally wet coastline receives in a year on
Acapulco in less than four hours and sending torrents of water, mud
and rocks cascading down the hillsides.
</P>
<P>
   Now Flores' wife and neighbors do their laundry in the stream
coursing through the house-sized boulders occupying what used to be
a paved road in this slum-like settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the promises of President Ernesto Zedillo and other
political leaders last October that storm damage would rapidly be
cleaned up and repaired, nothing has been done in Venustiano
Carranza, residents complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan Salgado Tenorio came through here four days after the
hurricane and promised us that they would rebuild the road and fix
everything,'' Flores said of Acapulco's former mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when?'' Flores asked.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the unrepaired damage is mute testimony to
Pauline's power, which struck an unprepared Acapulco, killing
nearly 200 residents and washing homes, businesses and vehicles
into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The city's opulent tourist hotel strip was restored in a matter
of days, even while bodies were still being dug out of the mud
farther up the hillsides, while poorer neighborhoods still
languish. Many here see that as a lesson to everyday residents from
Guerrero state's government, long run by the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   It is a lesson that is not lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that their (PRI's) history of lies is causing people
every day to go to other political parties,'' Flores said.
``They've been promising us things for years, but we can't do
anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Acapulco, including the hillside community of Venustiano
Carranza, is the largest city and revenue base for the state of
Guerrero; nearly one third of Guerrero's residents live and work
here.
</P>
<P>
   While most tourists in Mexico's flagship beach resort see
air-conditioned, high-rise hotels, classy restaurants and all-night
discotheques, they frequently miss the steamy urban poverty in
which 90 percent of Acapulquenses live.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Acapulco voters have loyally returned a
70-year-succession of PRI mayors to power, watching them go on to
become state party presidents, governors and important national
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Guerrero remains Mexico's third poorest state.
</P>
<P>
   But the center-left Democratic Revolutionary Party, or PRD, is
making inroads among frustrated voters in Acapulco and the
countryside, and it expects to contend for the statehouse in
elections here next February.
</P>
<P>
   Out in the countryside, another political force is growing.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrillas from the Popular Revolutionary Army (EPR) have been
ambushing state police and Mexican army patrols for more than two
years. Dozens of police officers, troops and guerrillas have been
killed.
</P>
<P>
   Although police and army investigators have uncovered a few EPR
safe houses in Acapulco, the guerrilla group has yet to launch an
urban commando raid within the resort city.
</P>
<P>
   But many say that as the political frustration mounts, the
conditions are ripening, and Acapulco could soon see the kind of
violence now experienced in Guerrero's countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that people are angry enough to join them,'' Flores
said of the EPR.
</P>
<P>
   Maximo Gomez Munoz, a Roman Catholic parish priest who lives
about 60 miles up the coast from Acapulco and who is considered a
kind of patron saint of Guerrero's peasant guerrilla movement,
agreed with Flores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult to bring that kind of rural warfare into
an urban environment like Acapulco,'' Gomez conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents a great challenge to the EPR,'' he said. ``But
they have a lot of people there. You will see that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Venustiano Carranza is an eight-year-old mountainside community
of 241 houses variously built of brick, split palm trunks, or just
palm fronds nailed to 2-by-4 uprights. You can see right through
many of them; others gain privacy by hanging cotton bedsheets
behind the palm fronds.
</P>
<P>
   Marcelino Cedeno Gomez has been community president here for six
years, representing residents' interests to the PRI-dominated
Acapulco city council and the Guerrero state government.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Cedeno how good those governments have been to Venustiano
Carranza and he unleashes a torrent of words only slightly less
powerful than the waters that tore through here last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here need streets, lights, water, electricity,
everything,'' Cedeno said. ``We pay our taxes just like everyone
else does, but we get nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are not in agreement with that; there have been
demonstrations and massacres (in other parts of the state). The
government has exploited the most marginalized people to drain our
wealth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While awaiting help from the city to repair the ruined roads,
Cedeno and others here built their own system of running water,
tapping a mountainside spring and bringing the water to
distribution points in garden hoses. To augment the few utility
poles, electric wires hang from braided steel cables draped in
convenient trees.
</P>
<P>
   In November, community members scraped together 5,000 pesos
(about $600) and gave the money to Acapulco city officials to hire
an earthmover to start roadwork, Cedeno said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then the mayor quit and the money disappeared, and we were
left with some paint marks on the boulders where they were going to
work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Cedeno says he is a loyal PRI man and will continue
to support his party.
</P>
<P>
   Right now that party is deeply divided in Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   At least seven early candidates are vying for the party's
gubernatorial nominations in elections next February. Several
consider themselves reformers, opposed to the near-feudal grip the
traditional wing of the party has had on Guerrero for nearly 70
years.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the seven have threatened to boycott the statewide party
primary because they say outgoing Gov. Angel Aguirre is using state
funds to promote his favorite against them.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the betrayals and the grumblings of many fellow
residents, who say they are going to vote for the PRD, Cedeno said
he would support one of the reform candidates.
</P>
<P>
   His reasoning reveals the hopeful stoicism _ now crumbling in
Guerrero _ that has helped keep Mexico's ruling party in power for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been a PRIista,'' he said. ``The party
principles are good. It is the local representatives who are bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
