<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE GEORGES BATTERS FLORIDA KEYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ala., Miss., La.)  (Eds: Will be updated later as story develops.) 
(ART ADV: Photo and map for use with this story are being sent to
NYT photo and graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After leaving nearly 300 people dead in a five-day
rampage across the Caribbean, Hurricane Georges slammed into the
Florida Keys with winds of more than 100 miles an hour Friday,
causing widespread flooding and extensive damage to buildings,
homes, roads, harbors and power lines.
</P>
<P>
   No deaths had been reported in the storm's passage across the
extreme southwestern tip of Florida. But fears that heavily
populated areas of Florida's Gulf Coast could be inundated by the
heavy rainfall accompanying the hurricane led authorities to extend
evacuation directives to a total of 1.4 million people. In Tampa
and Miami, shelters were said to be filled to capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hurricane Center here forecast that Georges would
strengthen by late Saturday to a category-three storm, with
sustained winds of at least 115 miles an hour. A hurricane watch
was issued from the Florida panhandle to Morgan City, La.
Meteorologists warned that the storm could make landfall again as
early as Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Packing 105 mile-an-hour winds and storm surges of up to seven
feet, the core of the storm hit Key West just before midday,
creating whiteout conditions much like those of a snowstorm and
knocking out the last remaining electrical power. The storm's
passage coincided with high tide, leading to extensive flooding
throughout the islands of the lower Keys.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dominican Republic, where rescue workers were still
fighting to get to villages isolated by floods and mudslides, the
official death toll rose to 134. But officials said at least
another 800 people are still missing and feared dead. ``In a word,
the picture is one of desolation,'' said President Leonel Fernandez
after visiting devastated areas.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Haiti, at least 87 bodies had been recovered, but
authorities feared the death toll would grow as they moved into
rural areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
