<SLUG> BC-GARDENFEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charleston festival digs into southern gardening
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C._Few events do more to re-energize Southern
gardeners after a long, hot summer than the Charleston Garden
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The Southeast's largest fall gardening extravaganza, set for
Thursday through Oct. 4, will include exhibits, workshops, garden
tours, a marketplace and symposium sure to inspire. The speakers,
several from the Atlanta area, will include:
</P>
<P>
   -- Allan Armitage, a University of Georgia horticulture
professor and author, who will take a look at the joys and woes of
gardening in the South.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mike Shoup, founder of the Antique Rose Emporium in Dahlonega
and Brenham, Texas, who will discuss cultivating old Southern
roses.
</P>
<P>
   -- Philip Watson, internationally known garden designer, who
will discuss ways to add romance and mystery to the garden.
</P>
<P>
   -- Felder Rushing, co-author of ``Passalong Plants'' (University
of North Carolina Press, $16.95), the best-selling gardening book
of 1993, who's guaranteed to make gardeners laugh at their
obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   -- Scott Ogden, a garden designer, author and bulb expert, who
will offer new ideas for Southern plant selections.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth annual festival celebrates ``A Sense of the South''
with special exhibits and lectures honoring two of Charleston's
most beloved gardeners: landscape architect Loutrell Briggs and
author Emily Whaley. ``This exhibit is going to be massive, some
4,000 square feet,'' said Rebecca Gosnell, festival manager.
</P>
<P>
   Another exhibit, by Atlanta garden designer Ryan Gainey, will
highlight ``A Southern Perspective,'' a garden featuring old roses,
boxwood hedges and traditional arbors.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds will benefit the event's sponsor, the Florence
Crittenton Programs of South Carolina, which provides services for
pregnant and single women.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Charleston Garden Festival
</P>
<P>
   When: Thursday through Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Gaillard Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $8 exhibit hall admission; tour and lecture prices
vary.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 843-722-0661; e-mail FloCritSC(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
