<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Sept. 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Friday, an intensified Hurricane Georges crossed through the
Straits of Florida, bringing destructive winds and torrential rains
to the Florida Keys. At midday Friday, Sombrero Key recorded a gust
of 113 miles per hour while several feet of sea water washed over
numerous sections of U.S. Highway One.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Georges will churn steadily toward the northwest,
posing a series threat to the central Gulf Coast. Some of the outer
bands of heavy rain should reach coastal Louisiana and the Big Bend
of Florida on Saturday afternoon. As is often the case with
tropical systems, thunderstorms embedded within the rain bands may
spawn isolated tornadoes, especially across western Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, a surge of unusually warm air will reach the
Northeastern states on gusty breezes from the southwest. Beneath
intervals of clouds and sunshine, afternoon readings will surpass
80 degrees in many locations. As a series of jet stream
disturbances intercept the fast flow of warm air, isolated but
severe thunderstorms will erupt across the Middle West and Great
Lakes. A few of the stronger storms will produce small swaths of
destructive winds and hail. Scattered thunderstorms will also form
along a cold front advancing southeast through the central Plains
and upper Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, moist winds circulating around low pressure will
bring clouds and showers to portions of the interior Northwest,
especially in the higher elevations. Meanwhile, the Southwestern
states will be mainly sunny and dry though patchy clouds will hug
the California coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Tornadoes and Hurricanes
</P>
<P>
   Twisters and Hurricanes Tornadoes were spotted in Florida on
Friday as Hurricane Georges moved into the Gulf of Mexico. While
hurricanes and tornadoes are very different, the strong winds of a
hurricane promote the conditions necessary for tornado formation.
Typically, the strongest winds of a hurricane are located a few
thousand feet above the ground. Objects on the ground impede air
flow. This effect, called friction, reduces air speed along the
earth's surface. The change in wind speed with height, called wind
shear, creates the twisting motions that can lead to tornado
formation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5111 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-CLINTON-COX     09-25 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-CLINTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some religious leaders call for judgment on Clinton, others
express willingness to put scandal behind them
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the president darts around the definition of a ``sexual
relationship'' and the question of whether he had one with former
intern Monica Lewinsky, some religious leaders express concern
about another relationship _ that between the president and his own
conscience. The question they ask is, ``Did he or didn't he truly
repent?''
</P>
<P>
   In Judaism, repenting is described as teshuvah, which means
turning. The concept is especially prominent in the Jewish
consciousness this time of year as Jews prepare to mark Yom Kippur,
the annual Day of Atonement, which begins at sundown Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself made a connection between his situation and the
concept on the day Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's report was
made public. On that day, Clinton read a modern Yom Kippur prayer
to a group of clergy at a White House prayer breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   It said in part, ``For leaves, birds and animals, turning comes
instinctively. But for us, turning does not come so easily. It
takes an act of will for us to make a turn. It means breaking old
habits. It means admitting that we have been wrong, and this is
never easy. It means losing face. It means starting all over again.
And this is always painful. It means saying I am sorry. It means
recognizing that we have the ability to change. These things are
terribly hard to do. But unless we turn, we will be trapped forever
in yesterday's ways.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What Jewish philosophy says is that God can only forgive you
for what you've done in relation to God,says Rabbi Steven Lebow,
Reform rabbi of Cobb County's Temple Kol Emeth. ``In order to
achieve atonement with fellow human beings, you have to go to them
and say what you've done wrong and ask them to forgive you.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's own faith, Christianity, emphasizes God's
willingness to forgive sinners. Whereas Judaism teaches that people
must atone for their wrongdoing by confessing and apologizing to
those they have wronged and attempting to make restitution,
Christianity accepts the concept of ``substitutionary atonement'' _
that Jesus' death on the cross paid for the sins of all his
followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes Christianity different in my perspective is Jesus
gives us a way to have our sins taken away,'' says Max Lucado, a
San Antonio minister and author whose latest book is the recently
published ``Just Like Jesus'' (Word, $19.99). ``First of all that
gives us the assurance _ you, me and President Clinton _ that I
confess my sins to Christ and they're taken away. My recourse is to
never deny sin, but to always confess sin.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is an expectation that change will be coupled with
confession in true repentance, says George Stroup, professor of
theology at Columbia Theological Seminary in Decatur. ``Repentance
does mean, in the context of Scripture, changing your path and
going in a different way,'' he says. ``To talk about repenting
means to intentionally try to turn one's life in such a way that
one does not continue down the same destructive path that one has
been going down, to do that from a Christian point of view with
God's grace.''
</P>
<P>
   The catch, says Stroup, is that cynics and skeptics may never be
able to know whether the president has truly repented. ``It does
seem to me that a person who has confessed sin and is genuinely
involved in trying to mend his life does not have to have that
observed by the public,'' he said. ``I guess for many of us the
very deep dilemma is in not wanting to be legalistic and
judgmental, to argue that God's grace is about forgiveness. On the
other hand, how do you keep it from becoming cheap grace where
anything goes?''
</P>
<P>
   The president has asked three ministers to be his spiritual
advisers. They are J. Philip Wogaman of Foundry United Methodist
Church in Washington, where the Clintons frequently attend;
evangelical pastor and writer Tony Campolo, a sociology professor
at Eastern College in Pennsylvania; and Gordon MacDonald, senior
minister of the interdenominational Grace Chapel in Lexington,
Mass., who acknowledged an adulterous affair 11 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some religious leaders have been quick to call for judgment on
the president. Christian Coalition founder and former presidential
candidate Pat Robertson told 3,000 coalition members last week that
they are obligated to forgive ``Clinton the man'' but should demand
impeachment for Clinton the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard a lot of discussion about repentance and
forgiveness lately,'' he said, ``but at the same time we recognize
that the God of Abraham, Isaac and Jacob is a God of law and
justice. ... We know that the Lamb of God is also the lion of
Judah.''
</P>
<P>
   Others already have expressed their willingness to put the
scandal behind them. Some prominent clergy, including several top
black church leaders, signed ``An Appeal for Healing: A Pastoral
Letter to the Nation'' calling for forgiveness of Clinton and a
``return to the real needs of people.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither quick judgment nor unconditional forgiveness may
bring about immediate healing of the country, say other
theologians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgiveness is not something arrived at easily and involves a
long process of efforts at confession, true contrition, prayer for
healing and prayer for reconciliation,'' said Kathleen M. O'Connor,
a Catholic teaching Old Testament at Columbia, a Presbyterian
seminary. O'Connor said she likes to break the term ``atonement''
into ``at one ment.'' That means, she says, that ``individuals,
community, God and peoples of the earth are celebrated as one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Forgiveness doesn't follow just because we decide to
forgive,'' she says. ``One has to work through feelings of anger
and betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   Forgiveness, she says, is a process.
</P>
<P>
   One person who can speak firsthand about the difficulty of
forgiveness is Debbie Morris, a schoolteacher, mother and author of
``Forgiving the Dead Man Walking,'' a recent autobiographical book
about her eventual forgiveness of Robert Willie, the convict whose
story was told by death row chaplain Sister Helen Prejean in her
book ``Dead Man Walking.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris was raped and kidnapped and her boyfriend was killed by
Willie 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Willie never asked for her forgiveness, but she gave it ``for
myself,'' she says. ``I needed to be able to let go of the anger
and the pain and the hatred that was harming me. I was being
destroyed by that _ not Robert Willie.''
</P>
<P>
   In cases where there is a relationship to be rebuilt,
restoration requires work beyond forgiveness, Morris says. That is
true of a marriage where there has been betrayal. And that goes for
a country and its president.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at the whole Bill Clinton thing, what he expects
after a history of dishonesty and unfaithfulness is to say, 'I'm
sorry. Forgive me. Let's move on.' People can say, 'We forgive you,
but the trust is not there any more.'''
</P>
<P>
   To rebuild that trust and to make something good come of an
awkward time in the nation's history, Americans have to focus on
themselves as well as the president, says O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view, the current conversation centers on
sexual sin and cover-up of that sin,'' she said. ``That is a
deflection from other moral issues _ sins of racism, sins that are
involved in our class blindness to the homeless on the street, to
the unemployed. We seem so obsessed with this event that the real
important political and moral issues are being sidestepped and
there's not energy left for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people seem to devote the same kind of attention to the use
of military power as they do to questions of the president's
behavior, she said. ``This may be our fault because as a people
we're so inner-focused and so content with our own power.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Franklin, president of Atlanta's Interdenominational
Theological Center, says he also believes that either quick
forgiveness or a race to judgment will deprive the president and
the country of an important period that can be used for
self-examination.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the annual meeting of the Religion Newswriters
Association in Atlanta last week, Franklin suggested that the
president take some time off _ perhaps to go to a monastery and
write a ``spiritual autobiography.'' The country should
symbolically do the same, says Franklin, who attended the
president's prayer breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to lead us forward, Mr. Clinton may first have to
lead us inward,'' Franklin says. ``For it is only within the
sanctity of this most private and spiritual space where we may
discover, individually and collectively, a moral consciousness that
inextricably ties who we are to what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
