</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5112 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHALEY-COX     09-25 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charleston's first lady of gardening pens a final message of fun
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C._Pushing 90, Emily Whaley could still tend her
garden, paint landscapes, give grandchildren dance lessons and bang
out at the piano one rambunctious rendition of ``The Dark Town
Strutter's Ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Charlestonian drove to a weekly bridge game and, until she
developed back problems several years ago, played golf and tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, at her family's urging, she wrote her first book.
``Mrs. Whaley and Her Charleston Garden,'' which made several
best-seller lists, landed her on the front page of national
newspapers and made her a hot ticket on the lecture circuit,
offered plenty of tips for creating a backyard paradise (``Early to
bed, early to rise, work like hell and fertilize'').
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was her simple recipe for getting the best out of life
that struck the loudest chord with those wrestling with day-to-day
stresses and consumed with materialism. ``You don't live but once _
at least that's all I think I'll get _ but we put a lot of emphasis
on things that don't matter,'' she said. ``We don't take the time
to appreciate what's around us.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes not only the beauty she found in her tiny garden
but in the friends she made while serving up her favorite
Charleston recipes _ a pastime she explores in a new book, ``Mrs.
Whaley Entertains'' (Algonquin Books, $17.95), which goes on sale
today.
</P>
<P>
   For Whaley, a lifelong goal was to be organized so entertaining
``will be no trouble at all ... so that I can sit serenely on the
front porch dressed up like a fiddler's bitch in my beads and
earrings and drink several cocktails and then invite everyone in to
supper and have it be perfectly delicious, just the right
temperature, sitting there in my latest kitchen gadget, the one
with the good-looking white domed lid.''
</P>
<P>
   A perfect hostess, yes.
</P>
<P>
   But above all, like most girls, Emily Whaley just wanted to have
fun. Did she ever _ right up until suffering a stroke June 13 at
her summer home in Flat Rock, N.C., where she died the next day, at
age 87.
</P>
<P>
   Whaley had looked forward to a busy fall schedule on the
speaking circuit with her new volume, said her daughter, Angie
LeClercq, of Charleston. ``She told me, `I'm on top of the world. I
want you to buy us a new camera so we can photograph the garden at
different times of day to explain the effects of light.'''
</P>
<P>
   One of those talks was to have been at next weekend's Charleston
Garden Festival, which will pay tribute to Whaley's work. Her
daughter will deliver the talk her mother had planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emily is the perfect person to be honored because she
single-handedly did more to heighten awareness for Charleston
gardens than anyone else by opening her garden to the public for so
many years,'' said Mary Palmer Dargan of Hugh Dargan &AMP; Associates,
an Atlanta landscape architecture firm that began in Charleston.
</P>
<P>
   An instant celebrity
</P>
<P>
   During the 60 years Whaley tended her Church Street retreat, it
became a favorite stop on the city's garden tours. And last year,
after South Carolina novelist William Baldwin collaborated with her
on ``Mrs. Whaley and Her Charleston Garden'' (Algonquin, $16.95),
the 30-foot-wide oasis drew up to 300 visitors a week.
</P>
<P>
   Though Whaley loved the attention, the crowds at her gate often
proved an intrusion for someone who enjoyed nothing better than
sipping an afternoon scotch in the solitude of her back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not my thing,'' she muttered last year while graciously
signing books for tourists ignorant of Charleston custom _ that an
open gate is an invitation, a closed one, a hint.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much the roses and hydrangeas that lured folks
inside, but the chance to meet a Southern belle unafraid to speak
her mind. In a town where societal standards reach as high as the
palmettos, Whaley cared little about what others thought. If she
chose to decorate her garden with sentimental seashells instead of
saintly statues, so be it. ``A garden is like your bedroom,'' she
said. ``You make memories there. You make mistakes there. But it's
nobody's business what else goes on there.''
</P>
<P>
   Always seizing the moment, Whaley realized tulips
</P>
<P>
   were a short-lived luxury but planted them anyway. ``A big
chocolate cake doesn't last either . . . You wear a wedding dress
once. You plant tulips once,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Always open to change, Whaley never entered her garden without
pruning shears in hand. ``Gardening is like interior decorating,''
she said. ``You move things around. Then one morning you get up and
ask yourself, 'Why the hell did I plant that there?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her broadmindedness, especially at her age, is what impressed
Shannon Ravenel, editorial director for Algonquin Books and a
childhood friend of Whaley's three daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``She also was a great role model for Charleston women because
she believed we could get out there and do whatever we wanted,
think independently and stand up for ourselves,'' Ravenel said.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes for friendships. Whaley relished cooking for her
husband, Ben, a prominent Charleston lawyer and state legislator,
and their children almost as much as she did planting her
perennials. As her mother had done, she compiled a cookbook of
family recipes 10 years ago for her own children. They are the
backbone of her new book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just remember, you can cultivate friendships just as you
cultivate flowers,'' she wrote. ``I have found over my eighty-seven
years that there are about the same percentages of amusing, gifted,
humorous, boring, stingy, and malicious people in every social
drawer. Life is short. Plant and tend a friendship garden that will
grow and flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   She stresses the need to develop confidence while entertaining.
``If the hostess is all aflutter like a butterfly caught in a
net,'' she wrote, then guests will feel, ``as the Irish say, 'I
wish I was to home and the party was to hell!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Whaley knew people were intrgued by the topic of aging but she
approached it head on. ``This categorizing of where old age starts
and what it looks like should be kicked overboard,'' she said. ``It
seems to me that as long we are physically independent and open to
absorbing new and different ways of doing things and incorporating
these news ways into our everyday life, then we qualify as viable,
productive humans.''
</P>
<P>
   She recalled an elderly visitor to her garden, who, after losing
his train of thought, apologized, explaining, ``I'm having a senior
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Whaley says she often borrowed that expression. But, though her
eyesight was failing, her mind was as sharp as her tongue, said
Baldwin, the McClellanville writer who recorded Whaley's memories.
``When the proofs came in, I'd read the entire text to her,'' he
said. ``She would listen and at certain parts say, 'Boring, boring,
boring.' She had a good ear.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially for music. And Whaley knew how to wake up a party.
</P>
<P>
   A cousin, Bobby Shealy of Columbia, S.C., will never forget a
realtive's wedding reception. ``Nobody was dancing,'' he recalled.
``So Emily comes up, grabs me and asks the band, 'Do you know 'Mack
the Knife?' They did, and she said, 'Hit it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The stoop-shouldered Whaley pulled Shealy to the middle of the
dance floor, where all eyes turned as she led a partner, 50 years
her junior, in a lively shag. ``After that, everyone poured onto
the dance floor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just so inspirational, at gardening and everything
else.'' Now, her garden and books will remain an inspiration.
Whaley left her home to her youngest daughter, Charleston artist
Marty Whaley Adams, who plans to continue opening the garden,
LeClercq said, for tours, such as next weekend's garden festival.
The event draws locals as well as tourists, who clog the
cobbletstone streets, visit historic sites such as St. Philip's
Church, where Whaley's ashes were placed near her husband's grave,
and dine in quaint seafood restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   In both books, Whaley couldn't resist giving her favorite
restaurant, California Dreaming, a plug. There, usually with her
good friend, 92-year-old Creighton Frampton, she enjoyed breaking
the rules of the low fat/low salt diets that rule the lives of so
many elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place is always full of young people, a tremendous variety
of people. And very noisy,'' she wrote. ``I pull my chair up to
Creighton. I get my right ear up to him, my good ear. I order a
glass of wine. We always have a grand time. We always order the
fried flounder. And fried potatoes. When we go in there we're not
going to eat a damn thing but fried food and a couple of glasses of
wine.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a ``senior moment,'' Emily Whaley style.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
