<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5113 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHALEY-REVIEW-COX     09-25 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHALEY-REVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mrs. Whaley delights us with companion cookbook
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We may never get around to making Laura's Coffee Jelly or
decorating a wedding cake with ivy leaves made of sugar, but Emily
Whaley did, and she wants to tell us about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Whaley Entertains'' is a dotingly annotated collection of
recipes and stories that serves as a bookend to last year's popular
``Mrs. Whaley and Her Charleston Garden.'' As good as the recipes
for shrimp pie, hominy bread and fried chicken might sound, the
best ingredient, naturally, is the delicious discourse of this
octogenarian bon vivant.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I finally married, my knowledge of cooking did not fill a
thimble,'' she writes in the opening pages of the posthumously
published volume, assembled for her grandchildren. Imagine a
country girl in a big Northern city, sipping her first martini and
eating her first raw oyster. Or a newlywed bride trying to roast a
chicken in the first electric stove she's ever seen. At her best,
Whaley can be as funny as Lucille Ball, as cheeky as Thackeray's
Becky Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Aunt Cad was a wonderful, rich personality,'' she writes
in the ``Charleston Seafood'' chapter, most of which happens in
Philadelphia. ``She looked like she had imbibed lots of clotted
cream and lots of everything else. She'd never held herself back.
She must have weighed 185, wore her dresses to her ankle and had
the richest, most wonderful laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like Aunt Cad would have loved Whaley's Chedda Cheese
Souffle and lasagna, her brownies, lemon bars, cakes and fudge.
While many of these recipes could be found in your average church
bazaar cookbook, ``Mrs. Whaley Entertains'' is a fascinating slice
of life from this century of change.
</P>
<P>
   Born into an era of wood stoves and white gloves, Whaley learned
to love her microwave and tennis shoes. Though some of the stories
feel a little half-baked, some of the language a tad stale, the
book is a testament to a way of life that's disappearing. It is a
paean to good manners, the corner grocery and Charleston's
long-vanished door-to-door shrimp salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Whaley was a self-described ``gadgeteer'' who never met an
asparagus server or a ``bacon triangle'' she didn't like. It was
her way of saving time for all that joie de vivre.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Whaley Entertains.'' By Emily Whaley with William
Baldwin. Algonquin. $18. 247 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Recipes for the good life.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
