<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5137 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAMB-CLINIC-LADN     09-25 0294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAMB-CLINIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MEDICAL CLINIC TO SERVE GAY, LESBIAN COMMUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENIFER HANRAHAN 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _In another sign that the AIDS crisis has abated in
Los Angeles, the L.A. Gay &AMP; Lesbian Center will open a doctor's
office to cater to the health-care needs of gays and lesbians
beyond just HIV and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The new Lambda Medical Group location, which will be staffed by
five family-practice physicians and one ob-gyn affiliated with the
University of Southern California School of Medicine, opens today
at the Museum Square Building, 5757 Wilshire Blvd., Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to offer a safe haven for gay men and lesbians in a
setting that combines sensitivity with quality care,'' said Lorri
Jean, executive director of the L.A. Gay &AMP; Lesbian Center, the
city's largest provider of social and medical services for the gay
community.
</P>
<P>
   Research has shown that lesbian and gay people avoid seeking
medical care because of fear of discrimination from doctors and
other medical workers, Jean said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some gays and lesbians avoid doctor visits or don't
reveal their sexual orientation, raising the risk of a
misdiagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   The Lambda Medical Group will be the umbrella name for the
center's full range of medical services, which includes a clinic
for people with HIV and AIDS and a women's health clinic. These
services, offered free or on a sliding scale for 15 years, will
continue to be available at the center's headquarters at 1625 N.
Schrader Blvd., Los Angeles. Most insurance, including health
management organization plans and Medi-Cal, are accepted at all
three locations.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call (877) 452-6232.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
