<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5148 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEDGEFUND-IMPACT-860(     09-25 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-IMPACT-860(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: HEDGE FUND'S FAILURE RAISES DISTURBING QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If there has been a single refrain as economic
shock waves rolled around the world for the last year, it is the
importance of spotting and addressing financial risks before they
get out of control.
</P>
<P>
   But after a year of demands by the United States that Asia
strengthen banking supervision and provide better information to
investors, and after unheeded warnings to Russia about the
demanding discipline of the markets, the precipitous fall of a
sophisticated Wall Street firm suggests that the Treasury
Department, the Federal Reserve Board and other regulators nearly
missed a potentially big problem at home.
</P>
<P>
   Right under the noses of the same people who were dispensing
advice to the rest of the world, smack in the middle of the
best-supervised, best-capitalized, most open financial markets in
the world, a single firm, Long-Term Capital Management LP, was
making bets so big that when they went wrong they threatened to
destabilize the whole system.
</P>
<P>
   And no one really knows what other problems might surface on
Wall Street and ripple through the economy as the global crisis
hits the United States with greater force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are less vulnerable than any other nation in the world by a
huge margin,'' said Roger Altman, a former deputy Treasury
secretary. ``But we are nonetheless vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us knows for sure whether there is another problem in
this volatile environment which could rear its ugly head soon, and
it might not be a hedge fund but something else,'' Altman said.
``Long-Term Capital Management happened to be a hedge fund. But the
real point was that its failure was judged to be unacceptable, and
that there's so much complexity and leverage in the global
financial system that events like this can occur.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the House Banking Committee, Rep. James Leach,
R-Iowa, said Friday that he would hold hearings in the next week or
two to explore the economic and regulatory issues raised by
Long-Term Capital Management's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Questions exist as to whether appropriate national and
international supervision exists and whether funds designed to
hedge risk for individual participants create risk to the system as
a whole,'' Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the regulatory system worked just as it should.
The Federal Reserve Bank of New York, in its role as monitor of the
financial markets, caught signals several weeks ago that Long-Term
Capital was in trouble. This week it brought together a group of
Wall Street powerhouses to assemble a rescue package that averted a
marketwide problem without calling on taxpayer money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is how the situation should have played out, given our
current regime,'' said Bert Ely, a consultant to the
financial-services industry. ``However, and this is where the
average citizen should be concerned, it raises public policy
questions about how this got out of control the way it did.''
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, the answer lies in the nature of the financial
instruments being traded by Long-Term Capital Management and other
investment firms and banks. Not only are derivatives so complex
that they are truly understood by only a relative handful of
people, but the trading strategies employed by Long-Term Capital
and other firms are closely guarded secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The hedge-fund industry operates largely outside the scope of
traditional bank and securities regulators, and relies on money
borrowed from a variety of sources, including commercial banks,
which to some degree are gambling with federally insured deposits.
</P>
<P>
   George Soros, perhaps the best-known hedge-fund operator,
described the industry in congressional testimony this month as ``a
daisy chain with many intermediaries, and each intermediary has an
obligation to his counterparts without knowing who else is
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Soros' appearance before the House Banking Committee on Sept. 15
came more than a week before Long-Term Capital Management's
problems became public. But his firm was almost certainly aware of
the developing difficulties at Long-Term Capital _ it was
approached earlier this month about providing financial help _ and
his description on Capitol Hill of the problems brewing in the
market proved prescient.
</P>
<P>
   After Russia's debt default rocked stock and bond markets around
the world last month, ``many hedge funds and other speculative
accounts sustained large enough losses that they had to be
liquidated,'' Soros said. ``Normal spreads were disrupted, and
professionals who arbitrage between various derivatives, that is to
say, trade one derivative against another, also sustained large
losses.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Soros said, banks were ``frantically trying to
limit their exposure, de-leverage and reduce risk,'' setting off a
global credit crunch that was hurting developing nations and
beginning to squeeze the United States.
</P>
<P>
   With hindsight, the brewing problems at Long-Term Capital were
no doubt a factor in the increasingly explicit hints from Alan
Greenspan, the Federal Reserve Board chairman, and William
McDonough, the president of the New York Federal Reserve Bank, that
the central bank might soon reduce interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan specifically mentioned during congressional testimony
on Wednesday that increasing disruptions to the financial system
were one reason that an easier monetary policy might soon be
justified.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, having focused for the last year on the lessons of
Asia's problems, policy-makers in the United States are well aware
of how the bursting of Japan's financial bubble in the early 1990s
and the subsequent credit squeeze have left the world's
second-largest economy moribund.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years, Greenspan has been making the case that
the Fed has to be concerned with big swings in asset prices as well
as product prices as it sets interest-rate policy, an approach that
seems increasingly justified with each new tremor that hits Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Greenspan has always been reluctant to impose more
heavy-handed regulation on derivatives, arguing that banks and
other financial institutions are better positioned than auditors or
regulators to determine the worth and risk of the securities they
hold and finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hedge funds are very strongly regulated by those who lend the
money,'' Greenspan told Congress earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin have been
warning for months about the perils of lenders becoming too
sanguine about risk. And in the case of Long-Term Capital, it
quickly became clear that some of the world's biggest and most
sophisticated banks and investment houses had little if any idea
what bets were being made with the money they lent.
</P>
<P>
   And it raised anew the question of whether the regulatory
approach to hedge funds is adequate today.
</P>
<P>
   Many hedge funds operate under an exemption in the Investment
Company Act of 1940. The exemption was intended to allow family
businesses that invest in securities to avoid federal regulation.
The exemption covered pools of money having fewer than 100
investors, which did not offer shares to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Funds can also be incorporated offshore and not allow Americans
to invest, thus escaping the jurisdiction of the federal
government. Or hedge funds can operate under the terms of a 1996
amendment to the federal securities laws that exempts from
regulation those funds that limit themselves to fewer than 500
``sophisticated'' institutions or individuals, defined as those
that invest more than $25 million or $5 million, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1857EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
