<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMBATIVE CLINTON STRIKES BACK AT REPUBLICANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Congress may hold his fate in its hands, but President
Clinton struck back Friday, accusing Republicans of putting
politics over people in this election year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's combative stance may reflect new polls that show a
public increasingly upset with Republicans for prolonging the
debate over punishment for the president. Clinton maintains he
committed no impeachable offenses despite misleading Americans
about an affair with a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton went on the offensive in Washington where he signed a
stop-gap spending bill that will keep government operating when the
new fiscal year begins Thursday. The measure will keep government
operating through Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislation is a regrettable sign that the Republican
majority in Congress has failed to address the urgent priorities of
the American people,'' Clinton said. He noted that the
Republican-led Congress has passed only one of the 13
appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   ``By failing to meet its most basic governing responsibility the
Republican majority in Congress has its priorities wrong;
partisanship over progress, politics over people,'' Clinton said.
``Moreover, on key national goals: improving education, providing
affordable child care, expanding health coverage, protecting our
environment, stabilizing the international economy, the House of
Representatives, in fact, is moving in the wrong direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton continued the theme here as he began a three-day trek to
Illinois, California and Texas where he will raise nearly $4
million for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., called Clinton's
criticism a ``gratuitous slap'' at Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing our work. Maybe he just hasn't noticed. He's
distracted. What he's trying to do is distract attention from his
problems,'' Lott said, referring to the pending impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times poll found Clinton's approval rating rebounding
to 67 percent in the wake of the Republican decision to release the
videotape of his testimony before independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's grand jury. The poll found 78 percent surveyed said the
videotape should not have been released and 65 percent responded
that Republicans were unfairly trying to weaken Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The poll suggested a possible backlash against Republicans for
being overly partisan.
</P>
<P>
   The president visited Jenner Elementary School in Chicago's
toughest neighborhood to highlight his education agenda. The
school, located in the heart of the Cabrini-Green housing projects,
has turned around its test scores with help from volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   The school's tutoring program is part of a volunteer effort
called Working In The Schools (WITS), which encourages corporations
to allow employees time to help children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of you have it pretty tough,'' Clinton told the
children who walk to school through gang-controlled streets with
the help of volunteers. ``I know that life's not so easy for you
when you're out of school. I know that you've seen a lot of things
in your life already that children should never see. But I want you
to know something else. You can do what you want to do with your
lives. You can be happy. You can be fulfilled. You can succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, standing in a stifling hot gymnasium, told the handful
of students and adults allowed into the room that his education
plan would give them the tools they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should not be a partisan issue. But the fact is that the
majority of the Congress is in the hands of the other party. And
earlier this year, I gave them an education plan that for both
partisan and ideological reasons they refused to act on, and we
know it could dramatically improve our schools,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also attended a $250,000 fund-raising luncheon for Rep.
Glenn Poshard who is the Democratic candidate for governor.
Poshard, however, remained in Washington where Congress was to vote
on free-trade authority and begin work on the Republican tax cut
measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, after almost nine months now, eight months, of
virtual complete inaction, some votes are being cast in Congress,''
Clinton said. He said Republicans are counting on few people
turning out for the elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enemy of the forces of progress in this election is not
adversity. Adversity is our friend. Our enemy is complacency,''
Clinton told Poshard's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The president also flew to San Jose, Calif., where he was
expected to raise $600,000 for the Democratic National Committee.
While there, the president was to reunite with first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton and spend a few hours with daughter Chelsea who is
attending Stanford University in nearby Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
