<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-OUTLOOK-NYT &LR;      09-25 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCA COLA CO. HIT HARD BY GLOBAL UPHEAVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Painting a bleaker picture than many analysts had
foreseen, Coca-Cola Co. revealed Friday that its short-term
business results had been severely battered by global economic
upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement following an early-morning meeting with Wall
Street analysts in New York, the company warned that earnings would
be flat in the third quarter, compared with the same period last
year, and would fall in the fourth quarter compared with last year.
About two-thirds of Coke's earnings come from markets outside the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Coke said its worldwide case-sales volume would grow only 3 to 4
percent in the third quarter, which ends next Wednesday, compared
with annual forecasts of 7 to 8 percent. Many analysts had thought
volume would come in around 5 to 6 percent. Last year, sales grew
11 percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``While management is moving to adjust their business plans in
some of the more chaotic markets, the impact will be severe in the
third quarter and even more so in the fourth quarter,'' said
Michael Branca, a beverage analyst for Lehman Brothers, who called
Coke's presentation Friday ``somber but realistic.'' Following the
meeting, Branca said he lowered his earnings forecast for this year
from $1.53 per share to $1.46, and ratcheted 1999 lower as well.
</P>
<P>
   Coke stock fell more than $3 a share as the stock market opened,
but partly recovered to close at $56.25, down 43.75 cents. The
stock has fallen 36 percent since July 15, when it closed at
$88.9375.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsico, Coke's main rival, issued its own third-quarter volume
results Friday as well. The company normally does not release those
numbers ahead of its earnings results, which are not due for
several weeks. In Pepsi's case, global beverage volume rose 5 to 6
percent for the third quarter, though most of that reflects sales
in the United States, since Pepsi's presence abroad is much smaller
than Coke's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the data, so we thought it would be useful to put it
out,'' said Richard Detwiler Jr., a Pepsico spokesman. At the same
time, Pepsico also announced appointments for its bottling
business, which many in the soft-drink business expect to be spun
off as a publicly traded company before long.
</P>
<P>
   Coke's news seemed to surprise many analysts, not in its general
outlook but in the depth of the damage done in a relatively short
time. But most analysts said the company's long-range fundamentals,
which were emphasized in the meeting by M. Douglas Ivester, Coke's
chairman and chief executive, and James Chestnut, the company's
chief financial officer, remain impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that the near term is worse than we
thought,'' said Jennifer Solomon, a beverage analyst with Salomon
Smith Barney. ``And there's no doubt that it took them a little bit
by surprise.'' She said Ivester seemed ``taken aback by the degree
of weakness in the global economy,'' but added: ``I would hardly
call him alarmed or worried.''
</P>
<P>
   No guidance was given as to 1999 earnings, Ms. Solomon said.
``They said they expect to get their volumes within 7 to 8
percent,'' she said. ``But earnings are going to be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Branca said the company indicated it would take unspecified
steps to manage the economic difficulties. ``Coke's information
systems enable them to assess their business every two to four
weeks,'' Branca said, ``which enables them to make adjustments but
does not give them immunity from severe economic problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Such steps could include cutting prices in some markets and
increasing marketing expenses in others.
</P>
<P>
   Another analyst, Bill Pecoriello of Sanford Bernstein, said he
left the meeting feeling ``still very confident in the long-term
fundamentals, and knowing Coke will emerge stronger when these
global economies turn around.'' Still, he said, ``I remain cautious
for the short run due to continued uncertainties.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the trouble spots for Coke is Japan, which is suffering
one of its worst economic declines and accounts for 17 percent of
Coke's profits. ``Management is hopeful that government actions,
such as a reduced consumption tax and more upbeat political p.r.,
could meaningfully improve that business,'' Branca said. Another
worry is Germany, which accounts for 8 to 9 percent of profits.
Sales in Coke's Greater Europe group are expected to increase just
1 percent to 2 percent in the third quarter, the company said,
while the forecast for the Middle and Far East Group is 2 to 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The near-term numbers are weaker than I thought, both in
volume and earnings,'' said Marc Cohen, a beverage analyst for
Goldman Sachs. ``That being said, I was somewhat encouraged by the
enthusiasm they showed for being able to grow 7 to 8 percent from
their 1998 levels.'' The company's discussion of the possibility
that it would accelerate its stock repurchasing program was also
encouraging, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The changes announced at Pepsi make Craig Weatherup, now global
chairman and chief executive of Pepsi-Cola, the leader of the
bottling company, to be called Pepsi Bottling Group. It will be
made up of all of the bottling operations Pepsi owns, which handle
58 percent of the company's domestic volume.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherup, 53, will be chairman and chief executive of Pepsi
Bottling. Craig Jung, 45, president of Pepsi's bottling operations
since last year, will become chief operating officer of Pepsi
Bottling. In addition, John Cahill, 41, was named executive vice
president and chief financial officer of the new bottling company.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi shares, which have been trading in the $29-31 range for
most of the month, fell 56.25 cents to $30.4375.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
