<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PINK-FASHION-$ADV27-N     09-25 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINK-FASHION-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY PINK? WHY NOW? IT'S SIMPLE. SORT OF. 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 27) 
(JT) 
 By FRANK DeCARO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The best clothes on the runway that Friday morning
were pale yellow _ a muted marigold _ and shadowy gray. But the
line of fashionistas waiting at the Chelsea Piers taxi stand after
Mark Eisen's show told another color story entirely.
</P>
<P>
   A woman more Camryn Manheim than Cameron Diaz fidgeted near the
curb in a hot-pink sweater set and a long black skirt. Farther down
the line, a pixieish scribe in a black pants suit and a hot-pink
ribbed shirt interviewed a pregnant woman in front of her. Behind
them, a cell-phone abuser in a black sleeveless shell and gray
pants had tied the sleeves of a hot-pink sweater around her neck,
although not tightly enough to stop her from shouting.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was that Mirabella senior market editor who, in
search of her driver, whooshed by wearing a hot-pink cashmere
sweater and matching hot-pink suede Chanel ballet flats. ``Pink is
it, definitely,'' she said, a bubble-gum-colored blur traversing
the blacktop.
</P>
<P>
   Who could argue with someone in those shoes?
</P>
<P>
   In a season when fashion is married to charcoal, some women are
quietly having a hot-pink love affair. Julia Louis-Dreyfus was the
darling of the paparazzi outside the Emmy Awards in a
cleavage-baring pink Bob Mackie dress. But away from the cameras,
smaller doses of pink are being happily consumed. Last week,
shoppers lovingly eyed the pink-sweater-clad mannequins in the
windows of the Express store on lower Fifth Avenue, for instance.
If gray is the new black, as the magazines say, pink is the new
orange. It is the accent color du jour.
</P>
<P>
   The imprimatur of Helmut Lang, who seems these days to be the
font from which all fashion currents come, hasn't hurt the trend.
The supremely influential designer _ whose defection from the
Seventh on Sixth show calendar spurred Donna Karan, Calvin Klein
and several others to present their collections for spring 1999 two
months early _ featured hot-pink silk organza over white
printed-cotton underpinnings in his show on Sept. 17. The next day,
the fashion followers had popped for pink.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it strong pink,'' a spokeswoman for Lang said.
</P>
<P>
   Lang does a strong _ and strongly influential _ color every
season. His color choices are often regarded as gospel by the
fashion faithful, even if they don't always buy from him. ``I left
Helmut Lang's show and went right to Club Monaco,'' a Dallas
fashion editor said at Eisen's show. ``A $19 hot-pink tank top
under a black pants suit. That's all you need.''
</P>
<P>
   To be in the vanguard of fashion, that's often true. But it has
to be the right pink piece worn in the right way. These days that
means a sporty accent to more minimalist attire. A hot-pink suit
with shoulder pads and an above-the-knee skirt is still a big
glamour don't.
</P>
<P>
   But why a push for pink? It's simple. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed a pink moment,'' said Margaret Walch, the director
of the Color Association of the United States, a trend-forecasting
group in New York. Sounding a bit like the late Kay Thompson's
character in ``Funny Face,'' Ms. Walch said women want to think
pink because ``things are a little grim and uncertain at the
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pink came on strong just when we needed it,'' she added. ``We
may need pink for several years, it would appear.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodging any political implications, Ms. Walch explained that
``color trends are truly about a time and a place and feeling
comfortable in a particular color.'' Gray seems ``terribly
relevant'' at the moment, she said. ``I'm even wearing it in
underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   The charm of charcoal may in fact have spurred the interest in
pink, she said. Women today like wearing pink as an accent because
they perceive it as a ``feminized'' color, but not a weak one.
``This is not '50s wimpy pink we're seeing,'' she said. ``These are
vital pinks. These are complicated pinks,'' unlike '80s pinks,
which were obvious. In those days, pink offset New Wave black and
white. Today, it makes the sea of gray in this fall's fashion
magazines seem more appealing, and slightly more upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Walch predicts that various shades of pink will be with us
for a while at least. The color is forecast through spring 2000 in
men's, women's and children's wear and for home interiors, she
said. Hot pink, she expects, will give way to fuchsia and then
violet in the next year and a half. The Bonnard show, currently at
the Museum of Modern Art, makes ``a great case for purples and
yellows,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   But yellow, which was the featured color at CK Calvin Klein for
spring 1999, ``won't do for women what fuchsia can do,'' Ms. Walch
cautioned. That's because pink is an easier color to wear. Like
those women outside Mark Eisen's show two weeks ago, Ms. Walch
herself recently bowed to the latest color trend. ``I just bought a
hot-pink J. Crew T-shirt to wear with my favorite black pinstripe
suit,'' she said, adding a bit sheepishly, ``Even those of us who
should know better are not outside its influence.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
