<SLUG> BC-INVEST-COLUMN-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CRUCIAL WEEK FOR A FRAYED GLOBAL SAFETY NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27)  
 (af)  
 By JONATHN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the world's central bankers and finance ministers, this is
the week to put up or shut up.
</P>
<P>
   If they do what many analysts now expect, they could provide a
much-needed breather for investors in a global economic crisis that
began with the devaluation of the Thai currency 15 months ago, has
engulfed Russia, is battering Latin America and threatening the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   But if they disappoint, watch out.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve policy makers meet on Tuesday, and Alan
Greenspan, the Fed chairman, has indicated _ but not guaranteed _
that a rate cut is in the offing. ``We have to bring the existing
instabilities to a level of stability reasonably shortly, to
prevent the contagion from really spilling over and creating some
very significant further difficulties for all of us,'' he told
Congress last week.
</P>
<P>
   While not a silver bullet, a quarter- or half-point cut in the
Fed's short-term interest rate target could ease fears in emerging
markets, lessening capital flight. It would also minimize the
chances that the American economy would aggravate the crisis by
slipping into its own recession.
</P>
<P>
   Taking no action would be a jolt, sending stocks here and around
the world lower.
</P>
<P>
   The election for German chancellor is set for Sunday; Brazilians
will select a president a week later. With the elections over, a
new German leader (Gerhard Schroder) or the current one (Helmut
Kohl) can pay more attention to global problems, a necessity if
there is any chance for a global rate cut.
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando Henrique Cardoso of Brazil, if he wins a new
term, as expected, will have to make good on promises of deficit
cuts and Social Security changes. Otherwise, it will be hard to
lure back investors.
</P>
<P>
   Then the world's financial leaders will be gathering in
Washington at the end of the week, for the semiannual meeting of
the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank. The Group of
Seven leading industrialized countries and the IMF will be expected
to do more to calm the waters. On top of the list is some kind of
standby bailout package for key Latin American countries like
Brazil. If no such deal is done soon, investors should worry about
a steeper Latin American downside.
</P>
<P>
   Even though many stock markets have settled into a volatile but
contained trading range over the last two weeks, the Fed and the
world's leaders still have plenty to worry about, especially in
Latin America. Mexico, Brazil and Argentina are where global policy
makers will have to make their last stand against a virulent
financial crisis that, if left unchecked, could send the whole
world into a recession.
</P>
<P>
   Jose M. Barrionuevo, director of global market strategy at
Lehman Brothers, has a risk barometer based on a country's level of
dollar currency reserves. This level is compared with what would be
needed, hypothetically, as a full defense against capital flight,
without resorting to unsustainably high interest rates to defend
the currency.
</P>
<P>
   On this basis, Brazil and Mexico are still extremely vulnerable
to a currency collapse and the economic crisis that would follow.
In Brazil, the level of actual reserves is $47.5 billion and the
defense level is $200.8 billion. In Mexico, reserves are $30.3
billion and the defense level is $100.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the absence of additional external and domestic measures,
these countries are likely to experience serious foreign exchange
devaluation pressures,'' Barrionuevo said.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina, which pegged its currency, the peso, to the dollar,
is less vulnerable by this measure, with a reserve level of $25
billion and a defense level of $33.6 billion. But Barrionuevo is
still concerned because Argentina's economic health is so
dependent, through trade, on Brazil. The Czech Republic is also
under threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The support from the Group of Seven and the IMF has to be
materializing soon,'' Barrionuevo said. The Fed must ease, he
added, because Latin America needs to see that the United States is
not slowing too much, closing a key export market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world,'' he warned, ``is walking a very fine line.''
</P>
<P>
   Look how quickly the Greenspan-inspired, rate-cut euphoria
evaporated on Wednesday. Just hours after the Dow finished the day
257 points higher, a more than $3.5 billion rescue was announced
for one of the biggest casualties yet of the financial crisis:
Long-Term Capital Management, the hedge fund founded by John W.
Meriwether.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow fell 152 points on Thursday, and for a day Meriwether's
mistakes outweighed Greenspan's promises. That could make the
chairman's search for stability tougher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
