<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-LEWINSKY-ART-80     09-25 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-LEWINSKY-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES POLL: YOUNG WOMEN MORE TOLERANT TOWARD LEWINSKY THAN THEIR
MOTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Some young women say: Let she who is free of all
Monica-style sin cast the first stone. Others say: Blame the
powerful man who cheats, not the weak woman who helps him. Still
others say: She was wrong. But Lord, the punishment of having every
desperate, pathetic, lovelorn detail bared to the entire country!
</P>
<P>
   For a variety of reasons that seem to reflect a variety of Ally
McBeal-generation attitudes and realities, young American women
hold somewhat more tolerant opinions of Monica Lewinsky than their
mothers and grandmothers, according to a national New York Times
poll, follow-up calls to respondents and several separate
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The Times survey, carried out from Sept. 12 to 14, found that
among women under 30, only slightly more than half said they viewed
Ms. Lewinsky unfavorably, compared with nearly three-quarters of
women over 65. Among the women in between those age groups, it
found the level of disapproval rising steadily with increasing age.
</P>
<P>
   Still, only 11 percent of the young women said they viewed Ms.
Lewinsky favorably, while 28 percent said they were undecided. And
many said they simply could not relate to or identify with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal,'' the much-talked-about Fox Television show, may
depict young American women in the workplace as confused huntresses
who wear mini-skirts to the courtroom, but ``real life is nothing
like Ally McBeal,'' said Christine Parker, a 25-year-old sales
support administrator in a Boston computer company. ``I don't know
anybody whose life is like Monica Lewinsky's,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while they did not accept Ms. Lewinsky as any kind of
kindred spirit or generational symbol, some young women did evince
a sense of sympathy for her and an unwillingness to denounce her
unequivocally, even though they heartily disapproved of her
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like she got herself into a situation she must have
known she was getting herself into,'' said Jill Freydberg, 23, of
Chicago. ``I wouldn't say she deserved it, but she should have
known better.''
</P>
<P>
   And Karen, a 29-year-old publishing employee in Manhattan who
asked that her last name not be used, said that for young women who
grew up after the early years of the feminist movement, there seems
little ideological need to denounce Ms. Lewinsky's workplace affair
with President Clinton as bad for the image of working women.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's sort of like a throwback to how the working woman was
perceived in an earlier era,'' Karen said. ``She just doesn't exist
as part of how the modern working woman sees herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, who was a 21-year-old intern in the White House
when her affair with the president began, may be a throwback in
that her relationship recalls the old maxim, ``Women have sex and
men have power and each wants the other.'' But her situation, the
uneasy coexistence of sex and work, is only too contemporary, young
women said.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Lehrman, author of ``The Lipstick Proviso: Women, Sex and
Power in the Real World'' (Doubleday, 1997), said that Ms. Lewinsky
was taught a lesson for trying to use sexual power in the
workplace, which ``is now met with much condemnation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Lehrman said, the youngest generation of women in the
workplace is also aware that despite the great movement against
sexual harassment, ``we don't lose our sexuality once we walk in
the door at 9 in the morning, and things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Several young women interviewed agreed that though they blamed
Ms. Lewinsky for pursuing Clinton, sexuality and flirting in the
workplace remain delicate issues, with no clear lines drawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that one of women's powers is sexuality,'' said Erika
Manuel, 26, who works for the Massachusetts Department of Mental
Retardation. ``I'm not saying that's what gets us ahead. It's part
of you as a person. You can't shut it off and become an automaton
at work.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Sagi, 24, who works at a Boston investment company,
said: ``There are very few roles women can take in the workplace.
They can take the role of the maternal figure, they can become a
man, or they can become this flirty thing in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Her lunch companion, Livia Foo, 22, also an investment company
employee, disagreed. ``I think the workplace is more balanced
out,'' Ms. Foo said. ``I don't think about those things. There's
definitely a boys' club at work. There's also, like, the women's
club. I think things are starting to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Lewinsky's putting pressure on the President to help
her get a job, that, too, could be understandable, said Persis, a
23-year-old receptionist in Schauburg, Ill., who also asked that
her last name not be used. Persis said Ms. Lewinsky seemed to be
saying: `` `You want me to disappear? Give me something. I'm not
going to disappear without something.' It seems like a legitimate
angle.''
</P>
<P>
   Persis also said, ``When somebody is married, it's not the fault
of the person they're cheating with, its the person who's
married.'' Referring to Ms. Lewinsky, Persis said: ``It is her
fault in that she knew he was married, but she's not the one who
vowed. You hold her accountable, but she's young and she's getting
a raw deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Young women's more tolerant attitudes fit in to a general
slowness among their generation to judge personal-life behavior,
said Ellen Fitzpatrick, a historian focusing on modern American and
women's history at the University of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been people who have experienced the highest divorce
rate _ or one of them _ in American history and a lot of
instability in family life,'' she said. ``A lot of them have come
to understand very well their parents' clay feet at a fairly young
age. So I think they probably find it less shocking than maybe some
older folks do.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Fitzpatrick also noted that older women would have been
taught to condemn ``the kind of sexual aggression that seems to be
part of what we have heard about the story,'' referring to the
Clinton-Lewinsky relationship. But several young women interviewed
did not sound at all surprised that Ms. Lewinsky had flirted so
avidly with the president, and one even commended her
``get-up-and-go.''
</P>
<P>
   If young women's attitudes sound a bit confusing and
contradictory, that is because they are, even to themselves, Ms.
Lehrman said. ``I can think of highly embarrassing moments when I
put my sexuality on the line and was kicked in the face one way or
another,'' she said. ``So I would think this reflects a complicated
view that they don't want to pity her but they definitely feel
empathy toward her.''
</P>
<P>
   Among all the young women interviewed, Erin Riley, a 28-year-old
law student at the University of Michigan, offered the most
Realpolitik- based explanation of why her generation is less
willing to condemn Ms. Lewinsky than older women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they understand more,'' Ms. Riley said. ``Or maybe
they're attracted to older men, whereas for older women it would be
their husbands who are having the affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
