<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 Attn: Style and Leisure Editors:  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following articles
from the Style section for use Sunday, Sept. 27, and thereafter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PINK-FASHION (New York) _ In a season when fashion is married to
charcoal, some women are quietly having a hot-pink love affair.
Julia Louis-Dreyfus was the darling of the paparazzi outside the
Emmy Awards in a cleavage-baring pink Bob Mackie dress. If gray is
the new black, as the magazines say, pink is the new orange. It is
the accent color du jour. By Frank DeCaro. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARM-CANDY (New York) _ Not long ago, a well-known publisher in
his 50s called a single woman he knew slightly and asked her to a
benefit dinner for several hundred at the Plaza. It was not a date;
the man had a serious girlfriend. He needed something else. ``Would
you be my arm candy tomorrow night?'' he asked. (italics)Arm
candy.(end italics) The phrase is bracing in its candor, implying a
beautiful object to attach to your arm, for others to feast their
eyes upon. In the image-obsessed 1990s, when a dominant mood is the
desire to inspire fits of envy in one's friends, a woman (and
sometimes a man) in the role of arm candy expresses the
quintessential modern relationship. By Alex Kuczynski.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REMNICK-NEW-YORKER (New York) _ David Remnick, once a rumpled
writer for The New Yorker, appeared on ``The Charlie Rose Show'' on
Sept. 13 to discuss his appointment as editor of the magazine. Gone
were the oversize horn-rimmed glasses readers saw on the jacket of
his Pulitzer Prize-winning book, ``Lenin's Tomb,'' and Remnick
appeared to have treated himself to an $80 haircut, a stylish,
windowpane-check suit and a plump silk tie. ``He's gone downtown,''
said the Time magazine columnist Margaret Carlson, who watched the
broadcast. The key to the new Remnick sophistication? ``High-care
fibers,'' she noted. By Alex Kuczynski. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOTH-TALES (New York) _ On many Monday nights, literary types
with book-party burnout seek refuge by listening to oral
tale-spinners at a gathering called Stories at the Moth. It's an
idea as old as the campfire: The lights dim, the crowd gathers and
people stand and tell stories. After its first successful year, the
Moth went on hiatus for the summer, but the series returns Monday
night at 9 p.m. to Lansky in Manhattan. By M.P. Dunleavey. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SWAIN-LOLITA-PROFILE (Undated) _ On her first visit to a New
York nightclub, Dominique Swain said she had more in common with
the title character in ``Pecker'' than the one for which she is
known. That is ``Lolita,'' of course. Ms. Swain seems younger than
she is, three years after making ``Lolita'' at age 15. The
much-debated film, which had trouble finding an American
distributor because of its subject matter, was first seen on
Showtime and finally opened in theaters on Friday. By David
Colman. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMS-SLAM-PROFILE (New York) _ Saul Williams walked into the
Antique Boutique in Greenwich Village as though it were his old
neighborhood. He had the same comfortable, long-limbed stride his
poet-rapper character in ``Slam,'' this year's Sundance grand prize
winner, used while walking around the projects in Washington.
Williams doesn't look as though he spends much time figuring out
his wardrobe. But he does. He is, after all, an actor, well aware
that he has an image to project. And lately, that has been
especially important, sitting for one interview after another _
usually at his favorite hangout, the celebrity-studded Time Cafe on
Lafayette Street _ to promote ``Slam,'' which opens in New York on
Oct. 9. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   With Photo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A garden's birds are a fine complement
to its flowers and vegetables. Not even cornflowers can match the
blue of an indigo bunting; no rose is as vividly red as a scarlet
tanager. Even drab-colored birds improve the landscape, like plants
grown as a quiet background. By Cass Peterson. &QL; 
