<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-UNREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUHARTO COOPERATES WITH INDONESIA'S PROBE OF HIS BANK ACCOUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Indonesia's former President, Suharto, has
authorized banks to turn over to the government any accounts in his
name in the first step of an investigation into the fortune he
amassed during 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
   With Suharto's authorization, the Indonesian government can
seize the contents of those accounts and return the assets to
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's attorney general, Major Gen. Mohammad Ghalib, said
Suharto came to his office ``of his own free will'' to deliver two
drafts of letters authorizing the government to open the accounts.
Suharto also notified the government that he had no plans to leave
the country, said General Ghalib, who added that no travel ban
would be placed on Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Formal action to seize the accounts cannot begin until the
letters are in their final form.
</P>
<P>
   The government's investigations into allegations that Suharto
and his family accumulated up to $40 billion through cronyism and
corrupt business practices has become a national obsession in a
country grappling with its worst recession in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Millions have been thrown out of work since the government first
went to the International Monetary Fund in October to help rescue
the ailing economy, which is expected to shrink 20 percent this
year in the wake of the rupiah's nearly 80 percent depreciation
over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   But critics doubt the ability of a government stacked with
officials put in power by Suharto to conduct a serious
investigation that is likely to implicate high-ranking Cabinet
members and influential businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts also warned that Suharto's penchant for issuing
government decrees favoring the businesses of his children and
associates would make it difficult to track down the wealth and
find a legal basis for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the government's decision to include outside lawyers and
independent experts in the investigation, protesters have continued
to take to the streets to demand that charges be brought against
the former president, who resigned under pressure in May.
</P>
<P>
   With public pressure building as Indonesia nears a special
parliamentary session in November, President B.J. Habibie this week
ordered the military to crack down on the protesters who, he said,
``are openly working to keep the situation in the country
uncontrollable, unsafe and unstable.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics labeled the order a ``Suharto-style'' tactic that could
easily backfire on Habibie as he tries to establish his authority
over a restless population of 200 million people, many of whom
continue to question his legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Habibie should not be using his power for personal gain as
this will undermine the authority of the government,'' said
Marsilam Simanjuntak, a lawyer and former student activist.
</P>
<P>
   Simanjuntak predicted the demonstrations would continue and
could eventually ``paralyze the government'' if it failed to insure
an adequate supply of basic commodities and rein in an inflation
rate quickly approaching 100 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5178 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTH-TALES-$ADV27-ART     09-25 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTH-TALES-$ADV27-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFECTING THE ART OF THE SPIEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(For release Sun., Sept. 27) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By M.P. DUNLEAVEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Candace Bushnell got up to contribute a tale to
an evening of storytelling on the theme of ``Scary Wedding
Stories,'' she found out it was harder than it seemed to enthrall
an audience without a written text. Ms. Bushnell, the author of
``Sex and the City,'' loped through a sprawling saga of sex, drugs
and matrimony, weaving in mentions of Hugh Grant, a pair of ruined
shoes, several continents and various men.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, both the audience and Ms. Bushnell were worn out.
``It would be great to get up there and discover that you're Eddie
Murphy, but you don't,'' she recalled ruefully of the evening last
spring, which was part of a storytelling series held at Lansky
Lounge downtown. ``I thought it would be like telling a story at a
cocktail party. If I had to do it again, I'd practice more.''
</P>
<P>
   On many Monday nights, literary types with book-party burnout
seek refuge by listening to oral tale-spinners at a gathering
called Stories at the Moth.
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea as old as the campfire: The lights dim, the crowd
gathers and people stand and tell stories. It's Lake Woebegone on
the Lower East Side. Well-known raconteurs like Malachy McCourt and
George Plimpton mingle with those less practiced in the art of the
spiel (Jonathan Ames, Shelagh Ratner, Dael Orlandersmith).
</P>
<P>
   After its first successful year, the Moth went on hiatus for the
summer, but the series returns Sept. 28 at 9 p.m. to Lansky, at 104
Norfolk Street. Hazelle Goodman, an actress, and Ames, author of
``The Extra Man,'' will riff on the theme, ``What Did You Expect?
An Evening of Stories About What You Wanted and What You Got.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Moth isn't about perfection,'' said George Dawes Green,
creator of the series and author of ``The Juror,'' a thriller that
became a Demi Moore movie. ``It's a casual enough event that we
don't care if someone falls on their face a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Green grew up in the single-minded story-swapping culture of
Saint Simon's Island, Ga., and drew much of his inspiration for the
Moth from that background. ``The art of storytelling has
atrophied,'' he said. ``When you watch someone like Malachy
McCourt, who is just masterful, you realize that this is a separate
and distinct art form that just hasn't been encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   A renowned storyteller long before his older brother, Frank,
wrote ``Angela's Ashes,'' making the name McCourt famous, the
portly, white-haired Malachy McCourt _ who recently published his
own memoir, ``A Monk Swimming'' _ told the tale at one Moth evening
about the time he got naked in a restaurant. It seems a bartender
had refused to serve him until he checked his coat. McCourt
returned to his car, stripped off his clothes and put his overcoat
on. He returned to the bar to ask a second time for a drink. When
the bartender again told him to check the coat, McCourt obligingly
surrendered the garment, whereupon, he related, ``a hush fell over
the room like the moment after Christ left the Apostles at the Last
Supper.''
</P>
<P>
   The punch line, as McCourt told it: he left the restaurant
without his coat, but had forgotten his car keys in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Even when there isn't a marquee name at the Moth, what draws the
elbow-to-elbow crowds _ 300 have phoned in reservations for
tomorrow night _ seems to be that old-fashioned ideal of the dream
of a literary community.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no hidden agendas,'' said Katherine Rich, senior
editor at Allure magazine, who organized the ``Scary Wedding
Stories'' evening. ``People tell stories with a sense of vision, as
opposed to a sense of getting their picture on the Time Out
literary page. It's not a lot of writers with trust funds and cell
phones; consequently you get people with something to say.''
</P>
<P>
   But true raconteurs are in short supply. There are moments at
the Moth that make one long to be at a cocktail party, in order to
excuse oneself and hunt for canapes. At an evening called ``True
Crime Stories'' last fall, a man took so long narrating himself to
the border of Mexico (the scene of the alleged crime) that the
audience heckled him away from the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens to a lot of people is that they fall into the
trap of monologue,'' said Joey Xanders, the Moth's director. ``You
have to transform the anecdote from `this happened one day' to get
to the point of revelation.'' The Moth is not meant to be a place
for anecdotal anarchy, spontaneous rants or happenings. The
organizers view storytelling as a kind of performance art, and
expect raconteurs to practice and shape their material.
</P>
<P>
   For each evening, Ms. Xanders chooses a curator to recruit
promising storytellers. Then each candidate auditions for Ms.
Xanders, who selects four or five per evening. Ms. Xanders
sometimes puts in hours helping a storyteller _ who could be a
writer, a monk, a monologuist or, in one case, a tourist _ hone the
tale until it's ready to be performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey is a masterful editor,'' said Ida Hakkila, a former
deejay and freelance comedy writer for ``Late Night with David
Letterman,'' who told an affecting story about finding and losing
her father. ``When you're working on a true story, it's really hard
to craft it, but Joey helps you find the pivot points in your story
that you couldn't even see.''
</P>
<P>
   In creating the series, Ms. Xanders, who formerly worked in the
theater, recalled asking Green, ``How do we distinguish a story
from readings, from performance art?''
</P>
<P>
   She and Green struggled with the question with a board of
directors. But it was only after they had their first event, in
Green's living room in the summer of 1997, that they got a sense of
what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the oral tradition of folk storytelling, the Moth wants
to encourage less rambling and stronger narratives. ``Even more
than the structure of beginning, middle and end, there must be a
character who wants something,'' Ms. Xanders said. ``Every
character is on a journey to find that thing, and on that journey
they have conflicts and struggles _ and how they resolve those
reveals something of who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Moth is just one of many storytelling outlets around the
country. There is, of course, the long-standing folk tradition of
storytelling, which has inspired a Website (www.storynet.org) and
an annual convention next weekend in Jonesburg, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   A storytelling salon called Nights With VCR takes place on
Mondays at Here, a bar in SoHo, which was started five years ago by
Victoria Rowan and named for her initials, VCR. It is geared to
young, untried performers.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, Beth Lapides started what she calls the
Un-Cabaret to bring stand-up comedy back to its story-based roots.
``Our performers don't do routines,'' said Greg Miller, a
co-producer of the Un-Cabaret. ``They tell a different story every
time they get up _ and that's what keeps the audience coming
back.'' Julia Sweeney developed the material that evolved into her
one-woman show about dealing with cancer, ``And God Said Ha,'' at
the Un-Cabaret. Janeane Garofalo is another alum, who Miller said
was scheduled to return to work on stories about the evolution of
her movie career.
</P>
<P>
   But not all storytellers seek to turn the craft into a
profession. As Ms. Rowan put it, ``I think it's part of your
definition as a human being to be able to entertain a group for 10
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
