<HEADER>
A5181 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILLIAMS-SLAM-PROFILE     09-25 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILLIAMS-SLAM-PROFILE-$ADV27-ART-925&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNTOWN TO STARDOM IN ONE LEAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 27)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saul Williams walked into the Antique Boutique in
Greenwich Village as though it were his old neighborhood. He had
the same comfortable, long-limbed stride his poet-rapper character
in ``Slam,'' this year's Sundance grand prize winner, used while
walking around the projects in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Brushing past rows of sweaters and pants in all the New York
colors _ black, charcoal, gray _ he stopped in the middle of the
floor, at a rack he seemed to know well.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it,'' he said, pulling a house-brand sweatpants-gray,
wool-blend sweater with a zippered neck from out of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Just then, a young saleswoman in a Morticia Addams-ish clingy
black dress approached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi,'' she said, giving him a hug and a peck on the cheek.
``How's that sweater you bought?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' Williams said, still holding the twin of the
sweater he had in his shoulder bag, ``I'm thinking of exchanging
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He had spent a good long time at the store the week before,
mulling over the virtue of this sweater. Still, he did exchange it,
for a pair of gray wool baggy pants with a drawstring waist.
``These are so dope,'' he said, holding the pants against him.
``They look really comfortable, and I like that too.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams doesn't look as though he spends much time figuring out
his wardrobe. But he does. He is, after all, an actor, well aware
that he has an image to project. And lately, that has been
especially important, sitting for one interview after another _
usually at his favorite hangout, the celebrity-studded Time Cafe on
Lafayette Street _ to promote ``Slam,'' which opens in New York on
Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Already a star in New York's spoken-word scene as the 1996
winner of the Nuyorican Poets Cafe grand slam championship,
Williams is on the verge, as the Hollywood types say. His
performance in ``Slam'' has made him a darling of the film festival
circuit, and winner (with his co-star Sonja Sohn) of the
Independent Feature Film Project's first Perry Ellis Breakthrough
award.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Slam'' opens nationally, on Oct. 16, and Williams
inevitably crosses the great divide between anonymity and
celebrity, he plans to do it looking like what he is, both
street-smart and artsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do like clothes,'' he said the other day, after yet another
interview at the Time Cafe. Runner-skinny, with a lean, dark brown
face and longish hair that he was wearing pulled back, he looked
very downtown in his black overdyed cargo pants from Canal Jeans, a
vintage white cotton-blend button-down shirt that accented his
narrow waist and a pair of clunky sneakerlike shoes (``They're
called Campers''), which he bought in London.
</P>
<P>
   At 26, a year after getting his master's degree in acting from
New York University, Williams is poised for all kinds of success.
While his first feature role has received hosannas, his writing and
spoken-word performances are also getting their shot in the
limelight.
</P>
<P>
   He was credited as a screenwriter for helping to create his
character in ``Slam,'' a sensitive type facing prison time on a
petty drug charge, and for writing the poetry that he performs in
the film.
</P>
<P>
   His first volume of poetry, ``Seventh Octave,'' (Moore Black
Press) has hit the stores, and he has recordings of his spoken-word
performances on Mouth Almighty/Mercury Records and Ninja Tunes
Rawkus Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never really into slams,'' he said, of the competitive
poetry readings that have hovered on the edge between faddishness
and obscurity for a decade. ``A lot of the poetry in these
performances is all about performing, and not about poetry. To me,
poetry has to work on the page. I did slams because of what I
thought they could do for me. Once I won the grand slam, I stopped.
I had nothing else to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   It was at a poetry performance at the Nuyorican Poets Cafe that
Williams met Marc Levin, the director of ``Gang War: Bangin' in
Little Rock,'' a 1993 HBO documentary. Levin, who would go on to
direct ``Slam,'' had run into a friend on the street, Bonz Malone
(who ended up playing a Washington jail gang leader in ``Slam''),
who told him he simply had to see the young Williams perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slam'' was born out of weekly workshops the director had over
a period of months with several collaborators, including Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind that `Slam' is going to be huge,''
Williams said, between bites of a veggie burger at the cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a film about the power of language,'' he said earnestly.
``People are going to see this and get blown away.''
</P>
<P>
   In this urban fable, Williams' character, Raymond Joshua, is
thrown into the District of Columbia jail after being caught by
police with enough marijuana to land him a mandatory prison
sentence, even though it's a first offense.
</P>
<P>
   He uses his talent for writing and performing poetry to stop a
budding rumble in the jail yard in its tracks, and he is so
transformed by the experience that he persuades an old friend who
was blinded by an enemy not to retaliate. He also falls for a poet,
a prison writing teacher played by Ms. Sohn, and the growing
spoken-word movement in little clubs, while out on bail. Williams'
eyes grew large and moist. ``There's a reason I named my character
Raymond Joshua,'' he said. ``Joshua in the Bible marched around
Jericho, and the walls came tumbling down after he marched around
seven times with his trumpet. If `Slam' plays in 700 theaters at
the same time, the walls of Babylon will come tumbling down.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After hearing this, it comes as no surprise to learn that
Williams is the son of the Rev. Saul Williams, a Baptist minister
in Newburgh, and that he grew up doing raps for his father's youth
rallies. ``I used to go through the dictionary looking for big
words that I could use in my rapping,'' he said. After getting
acting lessons for his 13th birthday, Williams was hooked. He
majored in both acting and philosophy at Morehouse College. He also
helped start a literary magazine. ``Poets are the soothsayers of
the new age,'' he said solemnly.
</P>
<P>
   He still performs his poetry. Sometimes he collaborates with his
girlfriend, Marcia Jones, a painter, with whom he lives in Harlem
with their daughter, Saturn, 2. During their performances, as
Williams recites poetry, Ms. Jones paints. ``She's a performance
painter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two have made themselves part of the downtown arts scene. On
a second shopping trip through the Village to hunt for something
Williams would wear for the premiere of ``Slam,'' the couple
stopped at least half a dozen times to say hello to friends and
acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   They also joked with the salesman at Omari, the SoHo shoe
boutique where Williams bought a pair of blue suede, crepe-sole
shoes to match a blue vintage shirt he had bought at the Antique
Boutique possibly to wear to the premiere. (``I just hope this
works with black leather pants,'' he said.)
</P>
<P>
   Between all the interviews and greetings, Williams and Ms. Jones
plan to perform at CBGB's next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is also making the usual rounds of auditions. ``Just
today, he said, ``I went on an audition for what turned out to be
another drug-dealer role.'' He shook his head. ``I knew, when I
walked in, that I wasn't going to take the part.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
