<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-SCIENTIFIC-MISCONDUCT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAD OF UNIVERSITY LAB ACCUSED OF MISCONDUCT IN AIDS-RELATED
RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.)  
(js) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cornell University officials are investigating
allegations of scientific misconduct against the head of one of the
university's largest immunology and AIDS-related research labs in
New York City and a recipient of more than $2 million in federal
money, Cornell officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher, Dr. John L. Ho, has been accused by members of
his lab of ordering subordinates to falsify data in one research
grant application; of knowingly using false claims to obtain
another federal grant for $1.5 million; of publishing a paper based
on falsified experiments; and of threatening or punishing members
of the lab who discovered damaging evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the allegations were pieced together from interviews
with seven current and former lab employees, three of whom would
speak only on the condition of anonymity and provided most of the
information, including supporting documents.
</P>
<P>
   Ho, 48, an associate professor of medicine and microbiology at
the Joan and Sanford Weill Medical College and Graduate School of
Medical Sciences of Cornell University, declined to respond to any
charges, saying, ``My guilt or innocence has to be evaluated in the
context of the whole current investigation.'' Asked if he was
guilty of scientific misconduct, he replied: ``I don't believe I
have intentionally conducted scientific misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho is not related to the better-known AIDS researcher Dr. David
Ho, who directs the Aaron Diamond AIDS Research Center, also
located in New York. Though Ho has not achieved renown as an AIDS
researcher, he is viewed by peers as an up-and-coming immunologist.
He sits on research peer review committees of the American Heart
Association and the National Institutes of Health, and his
collaboration in a 10-year, $5-million federal grant to study AIDS
in Haiti gives him a role in the search for an HIV vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The research projects tied to the misconduct inquiry involve
test-tube experiments to determine how the immune system is
affected by various microbes, including those of HIV, tuberculosis
and parasitic diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Hajjar, the dean of the graduate school, said the
university's inquiry began in mid-August, when allegations made by
one member of Ho's lab reached top officials. Dr. Dominic Falcone,
an associate professor of pathology appointed by the dean to
conduct a 60-day inquiry, said in an interview that so far, some,
but not all, of the allegations have been supported by other
people.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the integrity of Ho's research surfaced during
the last 19 months, lab members said. Also at issue in the inquiry,
officials said, is the disappearance of about 60 vials of human DNA
fragments known as plasmids, most of them encoded with HIV proteins
for experimentation. The plasmids vanished from a freezer in late
December, heightening what several researchers described as an
atmosphere of fear and distrust in Ho's lab, which occupies five
rooms on the fourth floor of the New York Hospital medical complex
in Manhattan. University officials said the plasmids had not been
found, but stressed that they were not dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cornell is not interested in anything but getting to the
bottom of it,'' Hajjar said.
</P>
<P>
   After Falcone reports on his inquiry, Hajjar, following
university policy, will decide if the allegations are
``sufficiently substantive'' to open a formal investigation by a
three-member committee, which would require notifying the National
Institutes of Health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
