<HEADER>
A5190 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-RELIEF-0926     09-25 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-RELIEF-0926-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HARD-HIT DOMINICAN REPUBLIC WELCOMES RELIEF AS DEATH, DAMAGE
TOLL RISES
 &HT;    EDs: With optional trim beginning at 480 words.
 &HT;    With HURRICANE-0926.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ As the death toll on this
hurricane-ravaged island continued to climb Friday, the first
international relief efforts arrived here with promises of more
support on the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Dominican government, which was caught largely unprepared
Tuesday for the force of Hurricane Georges, listed 125 dead and at
least 90 missing, but news reports from hard-hit rural communities
put the number of possible missing in the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The front page of one daily newspaper bore the stark headline:
``Mesopotamia No Longer Exists,'' referring to a city in the
western part of this country of 8 million people that was
overwhelmed by torrential floodwaters. About 9,000 people were
evacuated from the area, but U.S. Embassy spokesman Franklin
Polanco said ``nobody knows how many are in the mud.''
</P>
<P>
   In the town of Cambita, about 30 miles west of the capital,
about 40 people were reported missing when floods swept away the
shelter in which they were seeking refuge.
</P>
<P>
   For the third day, the country went without electricity or
running water except in buildings served by their own generators.
An 8 p.m. curfew remained in effect, enforced by the military.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile two plane loads of supplies from the United States and
one from France landed Friday providing rolls of plastic sheeting
used for shelters, as well as tents and generators. Another plane
was scheduled to arrive Saturday carrying chainsaws, water jugs and
eight 3,000-gallon water containers.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, 10 disaster relief officials from the U.S. Agency
for International Development, the Pan American Health Organization
and the Miami-Dade Fire and Rescue Service arrived on a BAC-111 jet
-- normally used to ferry rock bands and sports teams -- that left
from Baltimore-Washington International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just in the right place to do this,'' said chief pilot
Tony Gee(CQ) of Boca Raton, Fla. ``They just routed us to Baltimore
to pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Q. Parmer, U.S. AID assistant administrator for
humanitarian response who headed the relief assessment team, said
he would recommend that 100,000 pre-cooked relief meals be
stockpiled just outside Baltimore, Md. to be flown here, if
necessary. Late Friday, officials also were discussing the
possibility of shipping in rice, beans and other foodstuffs if
shortages developed.
</P>
<P>
   After a helicopter flight over the capital to assess some of the
damage and a meeting with U.S. Embassy Charge d'affaires Linda E.
Watt, Parmer said he also would recommend that U.S. military
helicopters be deployed to the island to help in reconnaissance
efforts. The Dominican Republic has only four government
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Medical assessment teams continued evaluating the damage and
preparing plans to provide medical aid, such as vaccines, and
sanitation assistance such as portable latrines.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add begins here.)
</P>
<P>
   Reporters who accompanied Parmer on the helicopter flight saw
houses and buildings ripped apart by the storm. Many roofs had been
torn off buildings and their interiors destroyed by the soaking
rains. Elsewhere, flood waters engulfed dozens of homes along the
Rio Ozama, the river that runs through the capital.
</P>
<P>
   In some places, homeowners dived into the muddy waters filling
their homes in search of lost possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Georges also dealt a severe blow to the Dominican
Republic's economy which, despite a poverty rate around 60 percent,
seemed to be heading for a growth rate of about 6 to 7 percent,
Watt said.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports indicated that the country's agricultural crops
-- including rice, plantains, yucca, coffee and sugar -- were
severely damaged.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 percent of the sugarcane crop was destroyed and the
country's five major sugar processing mills all suffered
substantial damage, Polanco said. Two major sugar warehouses
containing thousands of tons of processed sugar collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the rice in the country is under water,'' said Polanco,
the U.S. Embassy spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's tourism industry also was hard-hit. Although many
downtown hotels were open and operating on emergency power, resort
areas such as La Romana, along the southeastern coast, reported
that 60 to 75 percent of the roofs had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Watt said the psychological damage to the tourism industry could
linger long after repairs are made.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of European tourists come down to the Dominican
Republic,'' she said. ``They're going to go back to their country
and say 'This hurricane hit us.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane is likely to squelch the economy's robust
performance and drive more people into unemployment, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a double whammy. It's going to take a long time to
recover.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dominican Red Cross reportedly tried to enlist the aid of
home run-slugging native son Sammy Sosa to organize a pledge drive
among the 29 Dominicans in Major League Baseball. U.S. officials
said they were unaware late Friday whether the Red Cross had
succeeded in reaching Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
