<HEADER>
A5204 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAST-TRACK-HNS &LR;      09-25 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAST-TRACK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE KILLS FAST-TRACK TRADE AUTHORITY FOR PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Democrats and moderate Republicans, wary of
angering organized labor in an election year, united Friday to kill
legislation that would have given President Clinton special power
to negotiate trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 243-180 against renewing the so-called
fast-track authority enjoyed by George Bush and other recent
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Republican leaders in Congress support the
authority, which would streamline trade negotiations, but the
measure was staunchly opposed by labor organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a free-trade supporter who helped steer the North
American Free Trade Agreement through Congress in 1993, has focused
on avoiding a possible impeachment inquiry over his extramarital
affair and did not lobby for fast track as he did in an
unsuccessful effort last year.
</P>
<P>
   Three senior Democrats _ Reps. Robert Matsui and Vic Fazio of
California, and Steny H. Hoyer of Maryland _ are leading advocates
of fast-track authority but helped steer the measure to defeat by
announcing they were opposing it to protest the Republican
leadership's timing of the vote five weeks before the November
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Matsui, the ranking Democrat on the House Ways and Means trade
subcommittee, said he would not ``participate in an effort to
embarrass or defeat my colleagues by using trade policy as a
tool,'' adding the Republican tactic will send a dangerous message
that ``the U.S. isn't serious about international leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It soils the national debate on trade with the mud of partisan
politics,'' Matsui said. ``This debate is not about fast track,
this debate is about partisan politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Matsui said it was obvious that the fast-track measure would
fail because it is virtually identical to the bill that Republicans
pulled off the House floor last fall because they were short of
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Fazio said Republican leaders knew they lacked support to pass
fast track but chose to bring the measure up to force Democrats to
choose between alienating labor groups that oppose it, and business
and agricultural interests that support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could well put a lot of (Democrats) in a very tough
position,'' Fazio said. ``Democrats can't win because this has
become so divisive. It's a fight Republican leaders wanted to pick
... It's a meaningless, politically driven vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoyer said the Republican leadership scheduled the vote for
``political advantage,'' and would make it tougher for fast-track
authority to pass next year.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-track authority requires that when the president submits a
trade agreement for ratification, Congress must either accept it or
reject it without making amendments. Proponents say this gives the
president power to negotiate deals he wouldn't otherwise have if a
deal is subject to revisions by the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has granted fast-track authority to every president
since Gerald R. Ford, but the current authority lapsed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the fast-track authority say past trade deals have
failed to include provisions to adequately protect the environment
and ensure that trading partners have labor standards similar to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It places Clinton on the wrong side of the future,'' Rep.
Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., said in an interview. Pelosi said that
while ``San Francisco was built on trade, we also know about
environmental damage that can come with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said Friday's vote was not a sign of isolationism or
opposition to free trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about a much more enlightened look at trade,'' Pelosi
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., an ardent supporter of free trade
and fast-track authority, said in an interview the vote would send
a global message that the United States ``is lacking any leadership
from the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe said the Clinton administration ``is afraid of the demons
_ the labor unions _ in their own party.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe said if the administration had pushed for fast-track
authority as it did last year, it would have passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the weakest performance (by the White House) I've seen
in the 14 years I've been here,'' Kolbe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
