<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN WINS 505 CHAMPIONSHIPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYANNIS, Mass. _ Nick Trotman, the 27-year-old Massachusetts
native who sailed for Tufts University, Friday became the first
American skipper to win the 505 World Championships in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Winding up a seven-day regatta hosted by Hyannis Yacht Club that
included every condition from light-shift breezes to fresh 25-knot
northerlies, Trotman and crew Mike Mills placed just 14th Friday.
But after a consistent week of high scoring, it was more than
enough for the team that has been racing 505s together for more
than five years.
</P>
<P>
   Trotman, a member of the Team Racing World Championship sqaud,
narrowly missed the North American title last year and won this
year's Canadian championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This title has been the focus of my life for a long time,''
said Trotman, who sailed Lasers and then 505s at Tufts. ``I chose
this class when I was in college. It's the greatest one-design
dinghy in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Trotman plans to put his sailing activities on hold and hopes to
start business school at Columbia this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Another US team, Howard Hamlin and Mike Martin, finished second,
beating out Britons Ian Barker and David Cripps, who had been
second for most of the week.
</P>
<P>
   In fourth place was another US tandem, three-time North American
champion Mike Zani and Peter Alarie.
</P>
<P>
   The last US world champion had been Cam Lewis in 1982 and '83.
American Steve Taylor had won it in 1979.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
