<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-LACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBER OF AMERICANS LACKING HEALTH COVERAGE SOARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite a booming economy and rock-bottom unemployment rates,
the number of people in America without health insurance continued
to soar last year to 43.7 million, up 1.5 million from 1996,
researchers at Harvard Medical School and Columbia University
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers, based on data from the US Census Bureau, show a
nation that is ``treading water'' despite recent attempts by
federal and state governments to combat a seemingly intractable
problem of uninsurance, researchers say. Attempts include
legislation by several states to expand Medicaid eligibilty; a
federal infusion of $24 billion to fund state programs to insure
children; and a 1996 federal ``portability'' law that allows
workers who lose or switch their jobs to keep their health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``These programs are not making a dent in the problem of the
uninsured,'' said Dr. Steffie Woolhandler, associate professor at
Harvard Medical School and co-author of the national report,
published by the Physicians for a National Health Program, an
organization of 8,000 doctors who support universal access to
health care. &UR;  &LR; ``We had the equivalent of 125,000 people lose health
insurance every month this past year.''
</P>
<P>
   Three factors have undermined efforts to boost coverage.
</P>
<P>
   One is a loophole in the portability law that allows insurers to
shun sick people by jacking up their premiums, according to a
recent investigation by the US General Accounting Office.
</P>
<P>
   The second factor is an erosion in the number of people with
private, employer-sponsored health insurance. Cost is the culprit,
according to researchers. High premiums prevent many small
employers from offering insurance benefits. And among firms that do
offer coverage, many of their workers decide not to buy the
insurance because of unaffordable premiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coverage has become expensive,'' said Marilyn Ellwood, a
senior fellow with Mathematica Policy Research &UR;  &LR; in Cambridge.
``People at the lower end of the economy are having a harder time
affording'' health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The last factor involves a recent federal revamp of the nation's
welfare programs, which sought to limit the amount of time people
stay on welfare. As the number of people on welfare dropped, so did
the number of people on Medicaid, the government health insurance
program for low-income people. While Medicaid eligibility was not
affected by the reform and eligibility for welfare assistance is no
longer necessary for Medicaid coverage, many families either
weren't aware of the change or didn't have the time to sign up
their families, leading to a national drop of 1.8 million people on
Medicaid in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts saw a minor decline in the number of uninsured,
down 11,000 to 755,000 residents last year, according to a separate
report by researchers of Boston University's School of Public
Health. The drop gave the Bay State a chance to catch its breath
from a decade of relentless growth in the number of uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, however, Medicaid helped compensate for a big
drop in the number of people with private health insurance, said
Alan Sager, co-author of the Boston University study on
Massachusetts uninsurance rates. Medicaid enrollment increased by
81,000 people in 1997, while those with private coverage dropped
70,000. The result is a net 11,000 decline in the number of people
without health insurance. And while the number of uninsured fell,
the percentage of uninsured in the state actually rose to 12.6
percent in 1997 from 12.4 percent in 1996, presumably because of a
declining population.
</P>
<P>
   Sager was sanguine about the state figures. Massachusetts'
booming economy should have had a greater impact on the uninsured,
he said. ``The state created 324,000 jobs since 1992, and yet the
number of people lacking health insurance rose 133,000 during the
same period,'' Sager said. ``Clearly, many of these new jobs are
not providing health insurance benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   While these numbers have not hit crisis proportions, scholars
fear that a weakened economy could trigger a widespread loss of
health insurance. ``We're just treading water now, but if we see a
downturn in the economy, we're going to start sinking,''
Woolhandler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
