<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VANISHED BOY'S BIRTHDAY PASSES LIKE A PUFF OF AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - His birthday passed yesterday. The brown-haired boy
from Chandler would have turned seven. Imagine with me gifts,
games, a cake, seven candles plus one for good luck _ the
celebration that should have been.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the day vanished like the birthday boy, unnoticed,
traceless. Like a puff of air expelled from pursed lips.
</P>
<P>
   The leads in his case, the case of Omar Vargas, evaporate in
that same way.
</P>
<P>
   It happened again this week, 41 months after 3-year-old Omar
went missing, snatched from outside a revival tent in Agua Prieta,
Sonora, Mexico. This time, hope took the shape of a jailed Mexican
cop, a disgrace named Librado Castro Bravo.
</P>
<P>
   And again, hope proved a tease.
</P>
<P>
   Castro Bravo once helped lead the Vargas investigation. Three
years ago, it's said, he got three men to confess to kidnapping and
murder. Trouble is, those suspects recanted, saying Castro Bravo
tortured them. For seven months, the cop has sat in jail awaiting
trial. He tried an appeal to get out, then a hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
   When those tries failed, Castro Bravo played the Omar card.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came forward and claimed he knew where the body was,'' says
Norma Martens, an Arizona assistant attorney general on the case
since its start.
</P>
<P>
   The A.G.'s office sent an investigator. The Douglas police sent
two. For nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Martens explains: ``Basically, what he said was, `If you let me
out and give me some of my people back, I can find Omar's body
within a few days.' That was all he told us.''
</P>
<P>
   In a word, nothing. Which is not to say the cop's ploy passed
without effect. There's a house in Chandler where the name Omar
still rhymes with loss, ache, yearn. Erwin and Christine Diaz's
house.
</P>
<P>
   Erwin is Omar's half-brother, one sibling of 10. Christine is
his wife, a schoolteacher who entered his life as Omar slipped out.
This week, the TV reporters called to tell them about Castro Bravo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew all along it was just another scam,'' says Christine.
``That's always what it is. We knew he was just some cop that
wanted out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like salt in a wound whenever these false hopes
come up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Come up they do, like the silent birthdays and ever-shifting
rumors. Once, someone left a boy at an orphanage in Sonora _ but
not Omar. There have been stories that he was kidnapped to be sold
to childless Americans, stories that it was a case of mistaken
identity, stories that Omar was killed immediately and stories that
he died many months later, of a stomach infection.
</P>
<P>
   Christine and Erwin have their own favored scenario _ one that
involves Omar's father and his kin, a vendetta and an Agua Prieta
drug family driven to revenge. Martens, the assistant attorney
general, has heard that story, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been so many theories throughout this whole
thing,'' says the lawyer. ``I just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   No one does, which, impossibly, is worse than it sounds. For two
years, not knowing drove Omar's mother, Miriam, down to Agua
Prieta, to the city hall there. She rattled the uncooperative
Mexican cops, followed the cadaver dogs as they loped through the
streets, even got in to see Mexico's president.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in May of '97, Miriam and her twin, Lucy, died in a crash
six miles outside the town where Omar vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Two more bodies for a family still searching for a third.
</P>
<P>
   One more little boy Miriam lost the chance to touch. This time,
a grandson.
</P>
<P>
   Jonah Diaz was born two months ago, in the house where the name
Omar is still sore to the tongue. Christine and Erwin see the older
boy in the infant, and for that they hold their son that much
closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we look at Jonah, we're like `No way this child is ever
leaving our side,' '' says Christine. ``We value every minute we
have with him, because with Omar we thought we had all the time in
the world, but we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   No time. No gifts, cake or candles. Just a soft outward puff of
air, and then absolutely nothing. Gone like a birthday. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Leibowitz can be reached at david.leibowitz(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
