<SLUG> BC-COSMO-ELIGIBLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSMO `MOST ELIGIBLE' DENIES DRUG-RAPE CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A man who was selected this summer by Cosmopolitan
magazine from hundreds of Massachusetts entries as the state's most
eligible bachelor has been charged with secretly slipping a
homemade concoction to a woman and raping her while she was
unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan C. Martin, 22, was released Thursday on $20,000 bail after
pleading innocent to the charges, which allegedly took place at his
home.
</P>
<P>
   The woman told police that, when she awoke on the morning of
Aug. 8, she believed she had been unknowingly poisoned the night
before, and possibly sexually assaulted, according to
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The results of tests conducted by Massachusetts State Police
show that the liquid drug GHB, a ``date-rape'' drug that has become
a national concern on campuses and in nightclubs, was present in
the victim's blood, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who lives with his mother in his hometown of Greendale,
said Friday: ``I am innocent, and I want it to end up that way.''
He added that the woman making the allegations against him is
someone he knows ``very well.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said it was his mother who first entered him in the
magazine contest.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a 22-year-old community college student and aspiring
model who last year managed a city barroom in Worcester, apparently
impressed the magazine staffers with his telephone interview, and
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Friday the phones at the women's magazine were ringing with
questions about how and why Martin was chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Luthringer, director of public relations for Hearst
Magazines, said candidates for the second annual ``bachelor'' issue
were ``interviewed extensively by a team of editors.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to comment further on Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's alleged crime occurred one day after tougher
Massachusetts penalties for using date-rape drugs, including the
one suspected in Martin's case, were signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   The drug Martin's victim says he gave her is sometimes called
``Grievous Bodily Harm,'' or Liquid X, on the street. It was sold
during the 80's in health stores as a muscle enhancer, but the US
Food and Drug Administration issued several warnings about the
drug, say health and law enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said that just before the alleged attack the woman
making the allegations and another woman were drinking with Martin
after closing time in Sir Morgan's Cove, the bar where he once
worked.
</P>
<P>
   The Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette reported that the women told
police they each drank a green liquid Martin gave them, and became
sleepy afterward. Unable to drive, the women told police they
agreed to go home with Martin until they felt better.
</P>
<P>
   GHB is no longer available in retail stores but a recipe for the
drug exists on the Internet, and it is hailed as a homemade high,
though chemists know it as gamma-hydroxybutyrate, a synthetic
central nervous system depressive.
</P>
<P>
   The effects, say law enforcement professionals, can be
dizziness, confusion, loss of consciounsess and memory.
</P>
<P>
   Those symptoms are much like the ones that are caused by the
better known drug ``Rohypnol,'' which is illegal in the United
States, but has in recent years become an underground phenomenon
and a ``date-rape'' drug.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach Martin's attorney Friday were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from the Associated Press was used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
