u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-ELECT-700&AMP;ADD-     09-25 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-ELECT-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH 1 BIG EXCEPTION, BOSNIANS VOTE FOR MODERATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE O'CONNNOR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Election results released by
international officials Friday confirmed the victory of the extreme
nationalist candidate, Nikola Poplasen, as president of the Bosnian
Serb half of this country.
</P>
<P>
   While Poplasen and those who support him are seen by American
and European diplomats as hardline opponents of Western efforts
here, the results in most other races show a trend in favor of
moderate politicians, international officials said.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the major ethnically-based political parties that
once held monolithic power over Bosnia's three ethnic groups saw
their power eroded by voters, the international officials who
conducted the elections said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in seven years, since before the war, the
people of Bosnia are not represented almost exclusively by three
dominant political parties, each one of them coming from a single
ethnic group,'' said Zlatko Lagumdzia, president of a moderate
multiethnic party that gained considerably in the election.
</P>
<P>
   But, with the country still divided, and its main political
forces still largely nationalistic, and with ethnic Croatian and
Serbian politicians still heavily influenced by the strongmen of
Croatia and Serbia, much of the political environment here remains
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Further, in the complicated and often corrupt world of Bosnian
politics where many leaders preach an ideology of fear that helps
keep people divided, how the political forces align themselves and
what deals they reach may have more influence over Bosnia's
immediate future than the choices of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   The results released Friday have not yet been certified as
official, so the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe, which ran the election, did not announce how many
legislative seats individual parties won. Elections officials said,
however, that it was clear that nationalist parties had gotten far
fewer votes than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Poplasen's defeat of Biljana Plavsic was seen as a serious
setback for the Western strategy of supporting cooperative and less
nationalistic politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The reelection of Ms. Plavsic had been described by diplomats as
essential. With her defeat, the same diplomats are downplaying her
importance and emphasizing the general trend away from nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   One winner who has been singled out is Zivko Radisic, the
Bosnian Serb member of the three-person national executive, called
the presidency. He is described by some diplomats as a man who
sincerely favors strengthening the Bosnian state, which currently
has the trappings of a government, like offices, a flag and a
currency, but little power. However, his political party is the
Bosnian branch of the one controlled by the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic, and it is not clear how much control Milosevic
will exert.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign officials say that nearly all their attempts to give
life to the Bosnian national government were blocked by Radisic's
predecessor, Momcilo Krajisnik. His defeat seems a defeat for the
clique of Bosnian Serb leaders who began the war, since he was the
last of that group to hold an important office.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the presidency, Radisic could break the deadlock
that has led foreign officials to impose by fiat important measures
that the presidency could not agree on.
</P>
<P>
   Ante Jelavic, leader of Bosnia's branch of Croatia's ruling
nationalist party, was elected as the Croatian member of the
presidency. Some Western diplomats say that though he comes from
the hardline wing of his party, he may have recently changed his
views, though they seem more hopeful than certain.
</P>
<P>
   Other diplomats are less upbeat. A European diplomat said ``the
people who run his party are not interested in a Bosnian government
that works or has power because that is a threat to their financial
interests. Their goal is to keep Croats in ethnically pure enclaves
that they control.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Jelavic won easily, his party, the Croat Democratic
Union, was split shortly before the election, and a moderate
opponent fared well.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim member of the presidency remains Alija Izetbegovic, a
man thought to generally favor a strong national government. His
Party of Democratic Action suffered losses to more moderate
parties, election officials said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though the exact distribution of seats in the legislature of the
Bosnian Serb Republic is still not known, officials said it
appeared that the legislature will be controlled by a coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Since the assembly must also approve the person nominated by the
new president for prime minister _ the person who then appoints all
the ministers _whatever coalition emerges will have decisive power
over legislative and executive branches of the government.
</P>
<P>
   The new president, Poplasen, is an avowed opponent of unifying
Bosnia and strengthening the central government, which was the
promise of the Dayton Peace Accords that ended the war in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But, Poplasen can be blocked if, as some diplomats predict, the
coalition that opposed him and his allies during the election holds
together and joins with legislators elected by Muslims and Croats.
</P>
<P>
   There have already been warnings from the chief foreign official
in charge of implementing the peace accords, Carlos Westendorp,
that he could remove Poplasen, or others, if they follow policies
considered to be at odds with the peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man, in our view, is on probation and has to prove
himself as a democratic leader,'' said Ambassador Robert Gelbard,
the American special envoy to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting that foreign powers are willing to go so far as to
abridge Poplasen's freedom of speech, Gelbard said if Poplasen
repeated his calls for the secession of the Bosnian Serb half of
the country, ``The view of the United States would be that it is
grounds for his dismissal.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, however, Western governments have removed only a
few of the many officials blocking implementation of the peace
agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
