<SLUG> BC-FED-HEDGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OMINOUS SIGNS SEEN IN FED BAILOUT OF HEDGE FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A dark alley off Wall Street was illuminated by the bailout this
week of a hedge fund, Long-Term Capital Management. But though
hedge funds are mysterious _ even, sometimes, to their investors _
they have become the growth industry of the financial world.
</P>
<P>
   The funds have ballooned to an estimated $175 billion in assets
as sophisticated investors encouraged by success in traditional
markets began hunting down higher-risk ways to invest their ``mad
money.'' Whether buying Russian government bonds or short selling
on stocks, hedge funds often borrowed heavily to make big bets _
they often won.
</P>
<P>
   And the glamorous funds were run by the world's most famous
investors. International financier George Soros of Soros Fund
Management and Julian Robertson Jr. of Tiger Management Corp.
persuaded investors to tote up more than $10 billion for each of
their funds.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Vinik jumped ship at Fidelity Investments, where he managed
the world's biggest mutual fund, Magellan, to start a hedge fund,
amassing more than $1 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   But the rescue this week of Long-Term Capital, negotiated under
the eye of the Federal Reserve, raised questions about just how
entwined these mavericks are in the more visible financial world
inhabited by commercial and investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in the financial system is its own little island,''
said Richard Syron, former president of the Federal Reserve Bank of
Boston who is chairman of the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have something that's as sophisticated an operation as
this is that gets into this trouble _ it does show you can have
50-year hurricanes,'' he said. ``That does raise some concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Because these funds are not required to report to federal
regulatory agencies there are no definitive numbers on their size.
</P>
<P>
   What is known is that their growth has exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Assets of the 1,200 hedge funds that report their activities to
Managed Account Reports, a New York newsletter, exceeded $120
billion this year _ double their size two years ago. The total
industry has about $175 billion, according to Lois Peltz, managing
editor _ about the size of one of the money-center banks that lend
to the industry.
</P>
<P>
   And as they have grown, they made spun webs inside the
traditional financial industry.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the Who's Who of firms involved in Long-Term Capital
that agreed to provide additional credit in return for majority
ownership: In New York, there was Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., Bankers
Trust, Chase, J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. and Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. In Europe,
there was Barclays of London and Deutsche Bank of Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   The world's second-biggest bank, UBS, parent company of Union
Bank of Switzerland, which also participated in the bailout
disclosed on the same day that it had taken a $683 million charge
due to losses from investing equity in Long-Term Capital.
</P>
<P>
   UBS' losses follows similar reports in recent months by
international banks that have invested or made loans, often to
hedge funds, in Russia and other emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the involvement of these big players, hedge funds are
virtually unregulated.
</P>
<P>
   That was the intention when the funds were set up, in the 1960s.
Investors, seeking to avoid the Securities and Exchange Commission,
which oversees mutual funds, used them as a vehicle for more
free-wheeling investments.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge fund investors were not bound by restrictions on mutual
funds. One restriction they were eager to escape was a ban on
investing with borrowed money. They invested at first in futures or
options as a way to protect, or ``hedge,'' their holdings in
stocks. Over the years, the term hedge fund lost its meaning as
managers began investing in virtually any security.
</P>
<P>
   Hedge funds report their investment activities to the SEC if
they make sizable investments in the stock of corporations, which
are overseen by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed watches hedge funds through its regulation of banks,
which must submit detailed reports on their lending activities.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Although the Fed did not fund the bailout of Long-Term
Capital, its involvement in negotiations was striking.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Volcker, the former chairman of the Fed under President
Carter, took issue with it, noting that Long-Term Capital ``is not
a bank.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed was ``worried about the systemic failure of one hedge
fund,'' Volcker said. In other words, the Fed was being cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, at a time declining markets in Thailand, Indonesia and
Russia have triggered unpredictable declines in Latin America,
anything seems possible.
</P>
<P>
   Fed officials insist that Long-Capital was unsual, due to its
large size.
</P>
<P>
   Although that is probably true, Thomas Theurkauf, bank analyst
for Keefe Bruyette &AMP; Woods, is unsatisified with the lack of
information on hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
   Banks were ``caught flat footed'' by Long-Term Capital's
near-collapse, he said. ``They can't tell you with real precision
what their exposure is to the hedge fund industry. And believe me,
we've asked them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
