<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX READY TO DEAL WITH VAUGHN'S FREE AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once he rejected their contract offer at the All-Star break, the
Red Sox figured that slugger Mo Vaughn was headed to free agency no
matter what. So they weren't surprised when Vaughn said recently
that this indeed is his intention.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what trying to sign him in July was all about,'' says
the Sox' top man, John Harrington. ``We hoped it wouldn't get to
where it is now. But we still want Mo on our club in the future. We
have a plan. When the season is over, we will meet with his people
as soon as we can and make an offer. We expect that no matter what
we offer at that time, they will still go to free agency to see
what other clubs are willing to pay him. Once that happens, we want
an answer soon. As I've said before, we waited for (Roger) Clemens
to make up his mind a couple of years ago, and because we did, we
got shut out on some free agents we were interested in. That won't
happen again. We're sure that when the time comes, agents of other
free agents in the league will be calling us looking for offers,
and we will respond.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is it a true resurgence of baseball, excitment over
McGwire-Sosa, or too much football? Whatever the reason, should the
trend _ if you can call three weeks of viewing a trend _ for the
NFL on television holds, the networks are in big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week, the NFL was looking good. CBS, back in the
game after winning the AFC rights from NBC, had a 19.9 rating and
Fox an 11.6 for a total of 31.5. The year before, NBC and Fox
combined for a 30.3 in the opening week, so viewership was up 1.2
rating points.
</P>
<P>
   However, the last two weeks have been disastrous. The second
week saw CBS and Fox total 35.2. The year before, the total was
39.6, so the loss was 4.4. Last week the loss from 1997 was 4.8.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ``Monday Night Football'' has had the worst ratings
start in its history, establishing lows for first-, second-, and
third-week audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Each rating point is worth 980,000 households, and 2.3 people
are figured into a household. That means the NFL viewing audience
was down at least 10 million from a year ago in the second and
third weeks.
</P>
<P>
   There are contractual guarantees between the networks and
sponsors. If the audience doesn't reach a certain level, the
networks will have to provide some free advertising spots before
the year is out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Message to Mo: Beware of the rope-a-dope. In 1970, Carl
Yastrzemski of the Sox and Alex Johnson of the California Angels
went down the the final day of the season battling for the batting
title, as Vaughn and the Yankees' Bernie Williams are doing. In the
final game of the 1970 season, Yaz faced Yankees lefthander Fritz
Peterson at Fenway Park. Johnson would play his final game the next
day. Johnson said in advance that no matter what Yaz did, he would
play the entire game. Yaz singled his first time up, then went
hitless the next three trips to finish at .3296. The next night,
Johnson went 2 for 3. His second hit was an infield single in the
fifth, and when he reached first base, he walked off the field. He
had been told before the game that if he went 2 for 3, he would
have a .3298 average, good enough to beat Yaz. So he didn't play
the whole game as promised. Yaz later admitted that the reason he
played the whole game was that he believed Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There has been a lot written and said about the great finishing
burst by 26-year-old Yankee rookie Shane Spencer the last two
weeks, but this reporter will take what Ted Williams did in 1957
any day. The 40-year-old Williams had missed 17 days with the flu.
In his first game back, he hit a pinch home run to tie a game
against Kansas City. His next game, against Washington, he walked.
In his third game, still just pinch hitting because he was so weak,
he hit a home run into the upper deck at Yankee Stadium. By the
time he finished, he had reached base in 17 consecutive plate
appearances, still the major league record. During that streak, he
hit four home runs, including a grand slam. In his final 31 trips
to the plate that season, he reached base 25 times, going 12 for
16, a .750 average. He wound up the season hitting .388 even though
he did not have an infield hit the entire year because he couldn't
run anymore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Rick Pitino left Long Island as a teenager to enroll at the
University of Massachusetts, he never dreamed that one day he would
be sitting at a dinner in Boston raising $1 million in a single
night for scholarships at the university in the name of his late
son, Daniel. ``One of the big reasons I chose the University of
Massachusetts was to play with Dr. J (Julius Erving),'' said
Pitino. ``I practiced against him (as a freshman) but never got the
chance to play with him because he left (for the ABA) after his
junior year.'' Still, judging by these remarks he made during an
interview at UMass recently, Pitino had indelible memories of
Erving: ``Everybody would wait in line for miles just to see him
dunk. In those days, you could not dunk during a game. But he would
do it in warmups. He would dunk two basketballs and take off from
the foul line. It was a treat because no one else could do it.''
This was how basketball was transformed into a game played above
the rim. Erving brought the style to the ABA, then to the NBA,
where it is still copied by players today.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That injury he suffered here with the Patriots last year has
really slowed down Curtis Martin. He is only second in the NFL in
total yardage after three weeks. Barry Sanders is first with 324
rushing and 73 receiving yards, a total of 397. In his first year
with the Jets, Martin lags 6 yards behind (260-131_391), and
Marshall Faulk of the Colts (274-116_390) is next. Imagine what
Martin could do if he were really healthy and not damaged goods, as
Patriot apologists maintained after he left here as a free agent
... You know by the way Boston College dealt with Quinton Lee that
this is a new era under athletic director Gene DeFilippo and coach
Tom O'Brien. Lee, who was arrested in an off-campus incident last
weekend, has been suspended even though he is the second-best
running back on the team. Unless he makes a dramatic turnaround, he
won't be back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
