<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5239 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIATICAL-INSURANCE-AR     09-25 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIATICAL-INSURANCE-ART-$ADV27-1000(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH BENEFITS, NOW FOR THE LIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Texas)  (For release Sunday, Sept. 27) 
(see sidebar VIATICAL-POLICY-SALES) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching the premiums soar on his $100,000 life insurance policy
as he advanced through his 70s, Leonard Oxenberg wondered why he
was still making the payments.
</P>
<P>
   He no longer needed the coverage _ his son was grown, and his
wife had a good job. And there were many other ways that Oxenberg,
a retired advertising executive in Brookline, Mass., would have
liked to be spending the $5,000, soon to be $6,000, that he was
paying in annual premiums.
</P>
<P>
   But he felt stuck: If he just walked away from his term life
policy, he would get nothing _ as happens to many of the 6 million
Americans who drop insurance each year. And after paying premiums
for 15 years, that would be hard to take.
</P>
<P>
   Then Oxenberg found a solution: He could sell his unwanted life
insurance to one of the investment companies that, for years, had
been buying policies from people with AIDS and other terminal
diseases. Searching for fresh markets as new treatments continued
to extend the lives of AIDS patients, the companies have started
offering to buy life insurance of all kinds _ not only term, but
also whole-life and other types with cash value _ from relatively
healthy older people like Oxenberg.
</P>
<P>
   And so in an era when nothing is so alien as delayed
gratification, life insurance _ the ultimate form of delayed
gratification _ is being given a new twist: Now, it pays before
death. And it is not just helping with expenses in a policyholder's
waning days. Life insurance coverage can be turned into a vacation
in Europe, a new round of investments, gifts for the children now
rather than later, or just some extra spending money. The tradeoff
is giving up the big payoff at the end for one's beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   And though some policyholders may be wary of creating an
investment for strangers that pays off only when they die _ and the
sooner the death, the greater the return _ the business has grown
and there have been no scandals involving untimely deaths.
</P>
<P>
   As they have gone mainstream, the half-dozen companies doing the
buying say business is booming. One company, Viaticus Inc., a unit
of CNA Financial Corp., one of the biggest commercial insurers,
says it expects to buy up to $300 million of policies this year, up
from $75 million last year. Eighty percent of the deals, officials
say, will be with relatively healthy people. Another company,
Viaticare Financial Services, founded five years ago in Minneapolis
by four entrepreneurs, says it expects to buy $100 million in
policies, up from $18 million last year. And, it says, 70 percent
of the deals will be with the relatively healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an industry in the hundreds of millions of dollars,''
said Stephen Keller, president of yet another of the investment
companies, Kelco Inc., of Lexington, Ky. ``Now it's heading into
the billions.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives of these companies see the new deals as a shot in the
arm for the struggling life insurance business. If people know they
can change their minds and still get a good chunk of money back
when they no longer want their coverage, the reasoning goes, they
may be less reluctant to buy a policy in the first place. And some
of those who have cashed in their policies have already begun to
buy other things from life insurance companies, like long-term
health care policies, annuities and mutual funds. But the life
insurance industry, famously cautious, is not so sure. The big
companies, and little ones, too, distrust anything that alters the
hoary process of delivering death benefits to heirs. For one thing,
they worry that something could go terribly wrong with the largely
unregulated Johnny-come-lately investment companies, giving
insurers yet another black eye even as some companies are still
paying hundreds of millions of dollars to settle claims that agents
repeatedly misled customers with promises of unattainable returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether this idea is so great remains to be seen,'' said Mel
Feinberg, a vice president at New York Life Insurance Co.. ``This
whole new industry may not be around in 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some actuaries say the new approach could wind up
costing the insurance companies money. The insurers set premiums on
the expectation that a certain number of policies will be abandoned
and that no death benefits will have to be paid. If the investment
companies begin intervening widely, buying up and maintaining the
premiums on many policies, the insurance companies will end up
paying out more, said Tom Foley, an actuary who heads the life and
health division of the North Dakota Department of Insurance. Their
likely response, he said, would be to raise premiums _ and that, in
turn, could accelerate the long, downward slide in sales.
</P>
<P>
   For the investment companies, profits depend on the ability to
handicap death. They buy policies for something less than the face
value of the insurance and take over paying the premiums. Their
profit is the difference between what they pay out and the death
benefit, which goes to them when the insured person dies. They
shoot for profits of 12 percent to 14 percent, basing the purchase
price on life expectancy and the premiums due. The sooner a person
is likely to die and the lower the premiums, the more the seller is
likely to be paid for the policy. Anyone who lives beyond his
estimated time of death begins to cut into the profits of the
buyer.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase prices can vary greatly. For a $100,000 policy, for
example, a terminally ill person with a life expectancy of six
months could receive $80,000. But people in their 60s and 70s with,
say, 10 to 12 years to live, by actuarial estimates, could receive
much less _ perhaps $5,000 to $20,000. For a $100,000 policy, that
might not seem like much; Oxenberg got $16,500. But the investors
are especially looking for policies worth millions, and 20 percent
of the bigger policies begins to look like serious money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of these policies that we've bought have had face values
of more than a million dollars _ some have been over $5 million _
and we've paid many people hundreds of thousands of dollars,'' said
Gary Chodes, the president of Viaticus, which is based in Chicago.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Striving to prevent middlemen from coming between them and their
customers, dozens of insurers have begun making their own deals
with the terminally ill in the last few years, offering a so-called
accelerated death benefit. The insurer pays 90 percent or more of a
policy's value _ 10 percent to 20 percent more than investors
usually offer _ if a physician certifies that the policyholder has
only a short time to live.
</P>
<P>
   Viaticus is the only player owned by a major insurer; CNA itself
is a subsidiary of Loews Corp. The other companies are mainly
entrepreneurial ventures that operate by borrowing capital, buying
policies and reselling some of them to individual investors. The
companies act as brokers, taking a fee and passing on all or most
of the risk _ the bet on when the person will die _ to the
investors, along with the responsibility for paying premiums.
</P>
<P>
   An investor may buy a whole policy or a share in a policy or in
a pool of policies. One company, Affirmative Lifestyles Inc. of San
Antonio, says it is negotiating with a dozen institutional
investors, including university endowment funds and corporate
pension plans, to take shares of at least $10 million in a $200
million pool. Until now, though, institutional investors have
remained on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 40 or so investment organizations that have been
buying policies from the terminally ill have yet to begin dealing
with healthy older people. One reason, said Paul J. Moe, the chief
executive of Viaticare Financial Services in Minneapolis, is that
they do not want to tie up their money for long periods, as they
would need to do in dealing with healthier policyholders. Another,
he said, is that they lack the capital to take on the larger
policies that are being offered by older people, often in the
hundreds of thousands of dollars, if not millions. The original
deals with the terminally ill, which were known as viatical
settlements (from the Latin word ``viaticum,'' for the money and
supplies furnished to Roman officials embarking on official
journeys) were criticized as ghoulishly preying on desperate people
who were willing to trade away the full value of their life
insurance to get money for their final days. Now some critics talk
of graver concerns. With the stakes rising as investors await the
death of relatively healthy people insured for millions, insurers
and other critics say, homicide becomes more than a remote
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very easy to do,'' said David D'Alessandro, the
president and chief operations officer of John Hancock Insurance
Co.of America. ``If you bought 12 policies issued by different
insurance companies, there could be a series of car accidents that
would be very hard to trace back, one guy killed in Seattle,
another in Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the investment companies say they use codes to keep the
identities of insured people secret from investors _ trying, as one
broker put it, to guard against a visit ``from some guy in North
Jersey with a violin case.'' But complete anonymity is impossible.
In calculating payouts, the investment companies analyze medical
and family histories, and part of the sales contract requires the
insured person, his doctor, his lawyer or a relative to check in
periodically with the investment company. Someone, usually the
seller's doctor or a relative, also must agree to notify the
investment company of the insured person's death.
</P>
<P>
   While none of the generally healthy people have yet complained,
a few terminally ill patients say they have been harassed by
investors asking, as one person with AIDS put it, ``Are you still
alive?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
