u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV27-B     09-25 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTING DOWN THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, September 27, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a little luck, the near-collapse of an important hedge fund
will not matter very much _ another Black Monday, another nasty
surprise. The monetary and currency instruments available to
Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan and Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin are such that the slow-motion panic of the last six
weeks may turn out to be like the 1987 crash _ a spectacular
financial event with no recession.
</P>
<P>
   The bailout of Long-Term Capital Management L.P. is simply the
latest variation on an old story: unexpected problems arise from a
new and imperfectly understood financial technology. In this case,
a pioneering hedge fund pursued arbitrage strategies whose
aggregate risk was not well-monitored, not even understood, as was
the case in 1987 (remember portfolio insurance?). That it was an
investment pool organized for the super-rich added charm.
</P>
<P>
   The witty Lex Column of the Financial Times described the
problem this way on Friday: ``In essence, LTCM was was functioning
as a huge reinsurance company for Wall Street, taking on the risk
the big banks wanted to lay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``That these same banks were simultaneously lending it the money
to do so defied logic. And now that the emerging markets hurricane
has blown LTCM over, they were left with little choice but to bail
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the cracks in markets that appeared last week signaled
that the effects of the crisis that began last year in Asia at last
had reached New York. But they also clearly marked the edge of the
precipice to which the campaign to unseat the US president has
contributed.
</P>
<P>
   The same gang that three years ago shut down the US government _
the Republican majority in Congress _ is now threatening to shut
down the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the basic connection between the on-going financial
crisis and the continuing attempt to overthrow the government by
means of the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The history of the crisis was laid out in a fine four-part
series last week in The Wall Street Journal. Among the many salient
details, however, there was one startling omission.
</P>
<P>
   The series started started with an account of the events of the
last five weeks leading up to last week's bailout _ the flight to
quality that ensued in the wake of Russia's default on part of its
debt on Aug. 17. ``Russia was the match but the markets were ripe
for dislocation,'' noted one participant.
</P>
<P>
   The series then turned to the seven-year history of Russia's
attempts to decentralize its planned economy in a search for what
went wrong. Whatever its missteps, the Russian economy was poised
for recovery at recently as December 1997. Then a series of
political blunders, miscalculations, and accidents began,
culminating in the decision on the weekend of Aug. 15 to let the
ruble fall and default on some debt _ in effect, to give up on its
attempt to join the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   The third part of the series described attempts by the Clinton
administration to contain the Asian crisis, beginning with the
devaluation of the Thai baht in July last year. A parallel attempt
by the International Monetary Fund was traced: $17 billion for
Thailand, $42 billion for Indonesia, $58 billion for South Korea,
$23 billion for Russia _ until the cash ran out.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth article described various plans to deal with the
situation now, with Brazil last week having entered into talks with
the IMF about a possible rescue.
</P>
<P>
   The startling omission in all this, of course, is the lack of
any mention of the political situation as it has developed in
parallel in Washington. It was in January 1998 _ just after Boris
Yeltsin's government was faced down by a pair of the tycoons known
as ``oligarchs'' in an incident that began its tailspin _ that the
matter of Monica Lewinsky surfaced for the first time. And Aug. 17,
the day the match was lit, was also the date that Bill Clinton
testified to the grand jury convened by Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   News of the disastrous Russian default was completely
overshadowed. A six-column, two-line headline proclaimed Clinton's
confession across the top of The New York Times. ``Russia Acts to
Fix Sinking Finances'' noted a one-column headline barely above the
fold.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that House Republicans were refusing to vote the
emergency $18 billion assessment to the IMF that the Senate already
had appropriated didn't make the paper for the next two weeks. Such
is the power of obsession.
</P>
<P>
   The current confrontation with Congress has its roots in Mexican
peso crisis. When the freshly &UR;  &LR; elected Republican majority declined
to meet the administration's request for emergency aid, the
Treasury Department spent some of its own reserves, with the result
that the crisis was averted.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican loans have long since been paid back, but
conservative Republicans, led by House majority leader Dick Armey
(R-Texas), have been angry ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Even without additional US funding to prevent the spread of the
crisis to Latin America, the US and European economies probably
will escape recession _ for now. But the monetary easing that is
expected this week will, in all likelihood, be reversed next year _
just the pattern that followed the 1987 crash.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Clinton administration be free to pursue its policies
with relatively undivided attention then? Or will the congressional
leadership of the Republican Party still be doing its best to hound
Bill Clinton from office, and never mind the risk of throwing the
global economy into a stall?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5242 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIATICAL-INSURANCE-AR     09-25 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIATICAL-INSURANCE-ART-$ADV27-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: still alive?''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still, the business is growing rapidly. Scores of insurance
agents and financial planners have begun looking for people who
want to sell their policies, and many have also been recruiting
people with as little as $10,000 to invest, sometimes using
newspaper ads that promise returns of up to 60 percent. Last year,
the investment companies bought $600 million worth of insurance
policies from terminally ill patients, about half of them with
AIDS, according to the Viatical Association of America, a trade
group in Washington. Judging from the reports of the companies
leading the new trend, the volume this year is likely to exceed $1
billion, with the growth coming among deals to buy policies from
the healthy elderly.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent deal in the expanded market, Bill Senno, owner of
First Financial Resources, an estate planning company in
Moorestown, N.J., arranged for the sale of the $500,000 policy of a
72-year-old chemical company executive who had suffered a heart
attack 15 years earlier but had no apparent disabilities. The
investment company's actuaries gave him eight years to live and,
partly because his premiums were relatively low ($9,000 a year), he
was paid $210,000. The executive is buying a long-term health care
policy with some of the money and investing in mutual funds and a
fixed annuity.
</P>
<P>
   Senno got $1.2 million for the sale of a wealthy farmer's $3
million policy that had a cash value of $72,000 and annual premiums
of $100,000. The farmer, 67, had been diagnosed with leukemia and
was given six years to live.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Fiedler, who owns a financial company in Sausalito,
Calif., that specializes in helping people sell their policies,
arranged for the sale of Oxenberg's $100,000 policy. She also
brokered the sale of a $4 million policy for a lawyer who was in
his mid-70s and in excellent health. He received $235,000, or just
under 6 percent, for a term policy with no cash value; as part of
the deal, the investors took over his premium payments of $80,000.
Another of her clients, William G. Blackman, a retired insurance
administrator who is an 80-year-old widower in Palo Alto, Calif.,
got $20,000 for a $100,000 policy that cost him $6,000 in premiums
last year.
</P>
<P>
   While the trading in life insurance policies has attracted the
attention of federal and state regulators, only about 20 states
have laws specifically dealing with it, and those rules are limited
to transactions with the terminally ill. The laws provide minimum
payment standards intended to prevent terminally ill people from
being pressured to accept unfairly low prices for policies when
they are desperate for cash. But there are no licensing
requirements or regulations for the deals with generally healthy
people. Nor are there any formal protections for investors. Federal
and state regulators argue that many of the transactions,
particularly those in which shares in a policy are sold, are
covered by securities laws. But in a case that was argued over
several years, a federal appeals court ruled last year against the
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Many investment company executives say the less regulation, the
better. But Moe, of Viaticare, says comprehensive regulation would
enhance the industry's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   With no regulations to worry about, investment companies can
disclose what they like and offer any price they like to the
relatively healthy. Ms. Fiedler tells of a 74-year-old Texas
businessman who was eager to get out from under the $77,000 annual
premiums on his $3.8 million term-life policy. One company offered
him $10,000. He went to Ms. Fiedler for a second bid and ended up
selling the policy for $257,000.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, dozens of investors have complained of being
misled. The recurring theme, said Denise Voigt Crawford, the Texas
securities commissioner and president of the North American
Securities Administrators Association, is that investors were told
that the people covered by the policies they bought would die in a
year or two. But often, she said, because of new drug treatments
for AIDS, the insured people were still living three or four years
later. Even though the jurisdiction is not clear, Ms. Crawford and
securities commissioners in several states are investigating these
complaints. Since August, a task force of the securities
administrators association has been looking into the investments.
</P>
<P>
   For Oxenberg, who considers himself ``halfway healthy'' even
though he is a smoker who suffers from high blood pressure and has
to watch his cholesterol, shedding his annual premiums was almost
as important as the $16,500 he received from the investors. If he
had kept paying, he said, it would not have been long before he had
put in close to what his wife eventually would have received from
the policy at his death. She is 20 years younger than him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought my wife would be destitute, we would find a way
to keep paying,'' he said. ``But she's not concerned. And let's
face it, I was doing this for her.''
</P>
<P>
   They agreed, Oxenberg said, that they would rather have more
spending money. ``Why have the outflow?'' he asked. ``We're at that
stage where we travel a lot. We like to enjoy ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
