<HEADER>
A5244 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABOUT-CARS-OLDSMOBILE     09-25 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-OLDSMOBILE-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1999 OLDSMOBILE ALERO: A KEY PIECE IN A SURVIVAL BLUEPRINT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oldsmobile is the nation's longest-running auto maker and
General Motors' oldest division, but for a decade it has been
struggling to remake itself and remain relevant to consumers who
don't put much stock in history.
</P>
<P>
   For four consecutive years _ 1983 through 1986 _ it tallied
sales of more than a million cars a year. But sales slid in the
late 80s and 90s, totaling a mere 304,759 cars and trucks in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The drop has prompted many industry observers to speculate about
_ and even advocate _ the elimination of the division. Instead,
Olds is trying to reinvent itself as the GM division that competes
with imports.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, Oldsmobile has fully revamped its product line.
Gone, or on the way out, are some venerable names. The Cutlass
Supreme, the backbone of Olds in the 1970s and 80s, is no more; the
latest Cutlass goes out of production next summer. The Ninety
Eight, Oldsmobile's longtime flagship, was dropped, too. And the
last Eighty Eight will be built on Dec. 23.
</P>
<P>
   New nameplates have replaced the old, starting with the Aurora
in 1995. A luxury mini-van, the Silhouette, and a cushy sport
utility, the Bravada, have also joined the line.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Oldsmobile introduced the midsize Intrigue, which
critics have praised and customers have embraced, to battle the
Honda Accord and the Toyota Camry.
</P>
<P>
   Now Oldsmobile is adding the final _ and in volume, the most
important _ piece to its new lineup. The entry-level Alero, a
compact sedan and coupe just hitting the market, is expected to
generate up to 150,000 sales a year, about half of Oldsmobile's
current volume.
</P>
<P>
   To perform that well, it has to offer consumers compelling
reasons to turn their backs on the Accord, Camry and Nissan Altima,
as well as competitors from Ford and Chrysler, in a segment where
sales dropped nearly 14 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tall order for this small car. After test-driving two
versions of the Alero, I found many pluses, but I wondered if the
new, unknown nameplate had enough to take on the world's
heavyweights.
</P>
<P>
   The Alero went on sale last spring, but its production was
interrupted by the 54-day strike by the United Automobile Workers
at two parts plants that shut down almost all of GM's North
American assembly. Those plants now are up to full speed.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its significance, the Alero is being introduced with
fanfare. Its ad campaign, a first effort by Oldsmobile's new
creative team, is estimated at $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, the Alero replaces the Achieva, a sales
underachiever, in the compact segment. More directly, it will fill
in for the short-lived Cutlass.
</P>
<P>
   The Alero is sold as a coupe or a sedan, each with three trim
levels: the entry-level GX, the midrange GL and the top-of-the-line
GLS. A four-cylinder base engine and an optional V6 are available.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors for the coupe include the Chrysler Sebring, the
Dodge Avenger, the Mitsubishi Eclipse and the Accord. The sedan
aims at shoppers who might otherwise consider the Chrysler Cirrus,
the Ford Contour, the Altima or the Accord.
</P>
<P>
   The Alero's basic body structure is shared with the Pontiac
Grand Am and is substantially more rigid than the one it replaces.
The styling, however, is intended to be much more understated than
the Grand Am's in-your-face, boy-racer look.
</P>
<P>
   My first test Alero was a bright-red V6 coupe, more in the
Pontiac vein. The second car, a four-cylinder GL sedan of the ilk
expected to eventually account for most Alero sales, was jade
green, appropriately understated and elegant. The low-slung nose,
narrow cat's-eye headlamps and the hood emblem _ a circle slashed
with the diagonal, stylized Oldsmobile rocket _ mimic the larger,
more expensive Aurora. Only the oversize tail lights detract from
the sleekness.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the five-passenger Alero's tasteful and attractive cabin
reminded me of the larger Intrigue. The beige-and-taupe materials,
including the plastic, appeared to be high quality. The round dials
with simple markings were easy on the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The front-drive Alero is available with the base 2.4-liter
four-cylinder engine at 150 horsepower or the very quiet 3.4-liter
V6 at 170 horsepower. Unlike many of its competitors, the Alero
comes only with a four-speed automatic transmission; a five-speed
manual is planned for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The GL was equipped with a smaller engine, but it was peppy
enough. I had no problem in passing maneuvers, nor was I left in
the dust at stoplights. The engine, typical of GM's small
dual-overhead-cam type, was extremely loud under hard acceleration.
It quieted down at cruising speeds.
</P>
<P>
   The extra money that Oldsmobile pumped into the Alero's
relatively sophisticated suspension system, which has a number of
aluminum components for light weight and agile handling, was well
spent. Indeed, the suspension and the significantly more rigid body
structure provided fun-to-drive handling as well as a smooth,
comfortable ride. The body had a noticeably solid and tight feel,
without eliminating the feel of the road.
</P>
<P>
   Braking was extremely firm. The Alero comes with standard
four-wheel disk brakes with an anti-lock system and all-speed
traction control. Other standard features include air-conditioning,
tinted glass that cuts solar heating, a door-mounted trunk-release
button and two power outlets for items like cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   Safety features include daytime running lights and dual front
air bags. The car does not offer side air bags nor is there a
three-point seat belt for the center passenger in the rear seat.
</P>
<P>
   Quality control was difficult to gauge. Both cars were
preproduction models. The fit of some body panels and interior
components was slightly off, but that is likely to be fixed in
production. An on-again, off-again rattle came from the instrument
panel or steering column _ I couldn't detect which _ a problem
that's common in recent GM products.
</P>
<P>
   The Alero represents a fairly good deal in the compact segment.
Base prices, with destination fees, start below $17,000. The tested
GL sedan, with power, leather-covered seats, remote keyless entry
and a cassette/CD player, came in just shy of $21,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Alero's attractive price, elegant styling and fun-to-drive
nature should go a long way toward helping Oldsmobile achieve its
lofty sales objective, and, with the Intrigue, set Oldsmobile on a
more promising course for its second hundred years. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: A worthy vehicle for Oldsmobile's hopes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
