<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SENTENCES EX-CIA SPY TO FIVE YEARS IN PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD FITZPATRICK  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Douglas F. Groat, a zealous former police officer
who went on to join a supersecret unit within the CIA, was
sentenced to five years in prison Friday by a judge who described
him as a disgruntled ex-employee who tried to blackmail the
intelligence agency.
</P>
<P>
   But Groat was not trying to sell out his country. ``I don't
think you really had any intention of harming our national
security,'' Judge Thomas F. Hogan told Groat in U.S. District
Court. ``You were trying to resolve what you felt was unfair
personnel treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   But in doing so, Groat ``went off the deep end,'' Hogan said.
``You just couldn't get it out of your mind,'' he said. ``You made
threats and tried to carry them out, to some extent. You took steps
that went too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Groat, 51, pleaded guilty in July to attempted extortion,
admitting he demanded $1 million from the CIA in exchange for not
hindering U.S. spying efforts by selling his services to foreign
governments.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Groat was arrested on four charges of espionage, which
could have resulted in the death penalty. Groat was accused of
telling two unidentified nations they were under U.S. electronic
surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities dropped the espionage charges as part of a
plea bargain, saying they wanted to avoid a trial that might have
disclosed national security secrets and wanted to quickly find out
exactly what Groat had done.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan accepted the plea agreement Friday, recommending Groat be
sent to a minimum-security prison for the five-year sentence, to be
followed by three years' supervised release.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased justice has been served in this case,'' CIA
spokesman Mark Mansfield said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   After the sentencing, the judge said he knew of no harm that
Groat had done to national security. ``I don't think this was a
case where he was a spy,'' Hogan said. ``He did not get into
espionage for money or to be a traitor to his country.''
</P>
<P>
   According to prosecutors, Groat demanded eight lump-sum
payments, totaling $1 million, in exchange for not becoming a
communications-security consultant for other nations. In March and
April 1997, Groat made initial contact with several unnamed foreign
governments, and on July 18, 1997, Groat wrote to the CIA, offering
to ``suspend any and all actions that may interfere with agency
intelligence activities'' if he received the $1 million,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Groat, a native of Glenville, N.Y., joined his hometown police
force in 1973 after a stint in the Army Green Berets. His police
career, however, didn't last long and he was fired in 1977 on
allegations of misconduct and insubordination. Colleagues and
supervisors considered him an overzealous officer who didn't fit in
the small force.
</P>
<P>
   His firing was overturned by a court, but Groat went on to the
U.S. Marshals Service and then the CIA, where he would join a
special unit that broke into foreign embassies to steal code books.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's sentencing, Groat submitted a defiant three-page,
hand-written statement to the court. In it, Groat, who broke into
foreign embassies to steal codes as part of a CIA ``black-bag''
team, traced his troubles with the agency back to a botched mission
and described himself as a whistleblower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stand before you today because 8 1/2 years ago I cared too
much about my CIA mission and teammates,'' he wrote in an opening
paragraph, which was partly blacked out by the government before
the letter became public. ``I reported serious flaws ... that could
have gotten my teammates and me captured. ... Rather than learn
from the errors, the responsible manager lashed out at me and
threatened to end my career.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter described his attempts to salvage retirement payments
after the CIA fired him in 1996 for not taking a polygraph test and
allegedly taking home classified material.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my efforts to save first my career, then later my CIA
retirement, I have made many mistakes, many errors in judgment,''
Groat wrote. ``My methods have at times been unconventional. I
admit I put pressure on the government to resolve our dispute and
have used some of their own tactics against them.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Groat wrote, he has ``paid dearly'' for fighting for what
he considered unfair treatment. ``I have been punished with eight
years of persecution, the loss of my career, my job, back pay and a
CIA retirement, plus six months of solitary confinement under
harsher conditions than someone serving a life sentence under
lock-down.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Groat will be eligible for a pension, totalling about
$30,000 a year, when he turns 62, under the plea agreement. The
government is still not saying where Groat is being held and it is
expected to take about a month for the U.S. Bureau of Prisons to
decide where he will go next.
</P>
<P>
   Groat's attorney, federal public defender Robert Tucker, urged a
minimum-security prison, citing Groat's service in the Army, CIA
and Marshals Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, he lost a little judgment,'' but Groat poses no
security problem, he said. ``He wants to get on with his life. He
wants to put this behind him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
