<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-MEETING-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS SEE POLITICAL AND FINANCIAL REWARDS IN REPUBLICAN
ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)  (js) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After months of enduring withering attacks for
President Clinton's relationship with a White House intern,
Democrats are turning the Republican zeal to punish him into a
rallying cry.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders contend that a growing backlash against
Republicans eager to embarrass Clinton and punish him with
impeachment is helping energize supporters, displace apathy and
raise money. And on Friday, a co-chairman of the Democratic
National Committee said the scandal has become so good for the
party that it could help hold to a minimum any Democratic losses in
House and Senate elections this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're much stronger than we would have been,'' said a
committee co-chairman, Steven Grossman. ``Good times create
complacency and apathy, which are the enemies of our party. When
things are good, people tend to stay home. Sometimes you need a
crisis, an existential crisis, to motivate you.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party officials, meanwhile, have said that the
scandal has also pumped up their efforts, especially in fund
raising. They say disgust with Clinton's behavior has helped
increase fund raising to levels well beyond what the party would
normally see at this point in a year with midterm elections.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman and other Democratic Party officials appeared at a
briefing for reporters Friday to discuss what they viewed as
positive developments arising out of Clinton's admission that he
had an adulterous relationship and the Republican efforts to
impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, they noted, polling data suggest that
Democrats are fuming over efforts by Republicans. Day after day,
Democrats have worked to capitalize on this by criticizing
Republicans for ignoring issues Democrats claim are far more
important to most Americans, like the administration-led
initiatives on education, health care and social security.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Romer of Colorado, the other Democratic co-chairman,
said party leaders have been especially heartened by recent polls
that show Clinton's popularity has been rising since Monday, when
the videotape of his Aug. 17 grand jury testimony was shown to the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton's improving stature has resulted from a backlash
against Republican tactics, which he described as ``the gross
overreaching on the part of a conservative Republican-led party,''
and the ability of the public to ``cut through the fog and smoke''
of their strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats,'' he said, ``have the high ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman said the polls reflect the country's ``revulsion
against the politics of polarization to the extent Democrats
recognize that the stakes could not be higher'' in the fall
elections.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, he conceded that the scandal, with all its
smarmy details and the Republicans' campaign for impeachment, is
playing a major role in the re-awakening of Democratic voters,
shaking many of them out of an apathy that usually beclouds them in
midterm elections. If that works to improve turnout, which for
midterm elections is generally one-third of registered voters, then
Democrats could fare better than expected, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Gersh of the National Committee for an Effective Congress,
a Democratic organization, said a close analysis of congressional
races has convinced him that neither party would lose more than
five seats.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have predicted that because of the scandal,
Republicans could improve their majority in the House by as many as
two dozen seats and their majority in the Senate by as many as
seven seats.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to tell you Democrats will win the House or even
pick up seats,'' Gersh said. ``But there's no evidence of major
erosion of Democratic support in marginal districts.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman said that one of the marketing tools producing evidence
of a renewed energy among Democratic voters is a three-page mailing
signed by Hillary Rodham Clinton that reached Democratic donors
four days ago.
</P>
<P>
   He said the letter, in which Mrs. Clinton seeks support on
behalf of children as ``our nation's most vulnerable citizens'' and
invites written responses, exceeded a fund-raising goal that
generally takes months to meet.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman declined to say how many letters were distributed, how
much money was raised or the target amount. But he acknowledged
that the mailing drew ``thousands of letters'' of response.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people are responding to,'' he said, ``is venality and
mean-spiritedness and a total absence of fairness. It has energized
our base.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
