<HEADLINE>
THE AMERICANIZATION OF A GERMAN POLITICIAN  
 (EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOGNE, Germany - It was a scene that could have been scripted
in Hollywood: A handsome candidate radiating self-confidence moves
regally through an adoring crowd. The packed arena swells with
triumphant music as he ascends the stage and waves his arms in a
victorious semaphore.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate is Gerhard Schroeder, whose campaign for
chancellor has introduced a distinctly American flavor to a country
where voters long have based their votes more on a party platform
than an individual candidate. And many Germans have found the new
style of campaigning disagreeable in the run-up to today's federal
election, as the telegenic but ambiguous Schroeder tries to unseat
the uncharismatic but steady Helmut Kohl, who has led Germany for
16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers call the new style Schroeder's
``Americanization'' of the campaign. It is an uncomplimentary term
that denotes slickness and superficiality, an emphasis on
personality instead of political substance, on warm and fuzzy
feeling instead of sober-minded discussion. It has helped to
establish the English word ``show'' _ in a language that has
already adopted ``spin doctor'' and ``TV spot'' and ``PR'' _ in the
German vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, dynamic and telegenic at 54, is being marketed as a
movie star who is ready to breathe new life into an office now
occupied by a tired old man of 68. Schroeder dismisses Kohl as
``used up,'' and ``unfit for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohl counters that Schroeder, with his Italian suits and Cuban
cigars, is a show horse for the Social Democratic Party. On
campaign posters in hundreds of towns across this Montana-size
country, he warns his 80 million countrymen that they should allow
``no experiments.'' He says the party's left-leaning leadership
will discard Schroeder's pragmatic rhetoric about a new center as
soon as he is safely in office and it has control of the Bundestag,
as the parliament is known.
</P>
<P>
   But while Kohl dismisses Schroeder as superficial and
opportunistic, Schroeder has emerged as the narrow favorite. His
Clintonesque efforts to forge ``a new center'' may succeed, despite
the Kohl camp's criticism that he stands for nothing and promises
something to everybody. One of Kohl's lieutenants offered an
ironically ``Americanized'' critique, calling Schroeder ``the
Richard Kimball of German politics, always a fugitive from his own
comments.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kohl has refused to be drawn into an American-style
televised debate with Schroeder, who is far more comfortable with
television. That prompted Schroeder, in their one televised joint
appearance in the Bundestag, to taunt, ``You say you can't pin me
down. Well, pin me down, then.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's style isn't the only feature of this campaign that
Americans would find familiar. Once the debate moves beyond the
alleged superficiality of Americanization, it enters the deadly
earnest territory of globalization.
</P>
<P>
   Germany has lost tens of thousands of jobs to countries such as
Poland and the Czech Republic, where labor costs are less than
one-fifth of the $30 per hour that is common here. The collapse of
the Soviet Bloc that opened the East to German industry produced a
punishing side effect that had to do with the military
de-Americanization of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   As U.S. forces here have been reduced from the 340,000 troop
level of the 1980s, thousands of jobs on bases have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closing of the bases was a big shock for us,'' said Erhard
Goltze, a reporter in the central German town of Giessen. Goltze
said the closing of American bases and supply depots cost the area
a quarter of the 4,000 jobs that Germans had there.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Wirtschaftswunder,'' the economic miracle that was
virtually destroyed in World War II, is history. Unemployment has
reached levels not seen since the turbulent 1930s that saw Hitler
take over. Meanwhile, Germans have no interest in low-paying
service and construction jobs that have been filled by foreigners
whose presence here has made immigration one of the touchiest of
campaign issues. It is one of the few areas of clear difference
between Kohl, who has pledged to clamp down on foreign lawbreakers,
and Schroeder, who wants Germany to be more ``foreigner-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigration is bound to be a difficult issue for a country that
40 years ago belonged to a homogeneous ``Volk,'' that had few
foreigners in its midst. Now, Germany's population of 80 million
includes 7 million foreigners, including not only workers but
political and economic refugees from around the world. A country
that met the post-war challenges of de-Nazification,
demilitarization and democratization is now gripped by even more
intractable problems that won't be solved by its characteristic
discipline and straight-ahead diligence.
</P>
<P>
   This society built its post-war order with a market economy
whose German name carries a prefix that sets it apart from its
American counterpart. Germans are proud of their ``social
market-economy,'' which implicitly rejects vasts disparities of
wealth as it provides womb-to-tomb security, from free medical care
to free university education to one of the most generous systems of
unemployment insurance, pensions and vacations in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Germans, for whom six-week vacations are a legal right, look at
vacation-poor America with sympathetic disbelief. Their acceptance
of a system for which they pay far higher taxes than do Americans
is the underlying expression of a sense of social organization that
also manifests itself with a remarkable system of public
transportation and inner-city pedestrian zones that stretch for
blocks and bring everyone together in a communal exercise of
shopping and sharing common space. Individualism is not the driving
force of life in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl, the leader of a coalition of Germany's conservatives, is
far to the left of Republicans in the United States. While the
social-security network was in place before he took office in 1982,
he helped extend it, raising taxes 14 times.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State University history professor Gerald Kleinfeld said
Germans have a fundamentally different view of the role of
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have the view that the federal government is a
foreign entity,'' he said. ``They have the continental European
view that the government is an important part of their world.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Schroeder, the role of the state likely would continue to
grow. He has promised job-training for 100,000 workers and to
cancel Kohl's modest cuts in unemployment insurance. Schroeder says
he admires the dynamism of the American economy but hastens to add,
``We could never tolerate its social and economic inequalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Something else Schroeder couldn't tolerate, were he an American
politician, is American interest in its politicians' personal
lives. He has been divorced twice, most recently from a woman who
wrote bitterly about his defection to a woman 20 years his junior,
whom he married last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue has been no issue in the campaign. Kohl addresses
it indirectly in his stump speech, saying, ``Loyalty is important
in private as well as public life.'' Schroeder has gotten away with
simply declaring that his willingness to try marriage three times
shows his ``earnestness'' about the institution.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl's public appearances provide a stark, distinctly
un-American contrast to Schroeder's shows. A rally at Munich's
Marienplatz on Thursday evening began with the precise German
punctuality that still allows train passengers to set their watches
by a train's departure: ``This is not about show, but about
substance,'' the chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, German voters will decide whether Kohl was correct. &QL; 
Arizona Republic reporter Jerry Kammer traveled to Germany last
week to observe the final phase of the German election campaign.
The trip was organized by the Hans Seidel Foundation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
