<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5264 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPUS-SPIRITUALITY-B     09-25 1315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPUS-SPIRITUALITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPUSES EXPERIENCING A SPIRITUAL REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After decades of being confined to the margins of college life,
spirituality is making a dramatic comeback on America's campuses.
</P>
<P>
   The spiritual revival is not only apparent in rising enrollments
in religion classes and larger membership in student religious
groups, but in a growing awareness by many universities that they
have too long neglected their students' souls.
</P>
<P>
   One tangible measure of this is the enormous response generated
by an upcoming national conference exploring the spiritual
dimension of higher education sponsored by Wellesley College.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers had at first expected a largely regional audience
with representatives from perhaps a couple of dozen universities.
But at last count more than 800 people, including some 30 college
presidents, were expected to attend from more than 350 higher
education institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly is much bigger than we ever expected and seems to
suggest that we've tapped into a movement that's happening on many
campuses across this country,'' said Victor Kazanjian, dean of
religious life at Wellesley College and a main organizer of the
conference Sunday and Monday. ``There is a great desire to have the
kinds of conversations about spirituality that haven't occurred for
a very long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Many working in higher education believe training minds is no
longer enough in an era of widespread concern about society's moral
erosion and when institutions usually charged with instilling
ethics _ family and church _ no longer have the same influence on a
younger generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to produce smart people but what do they do
with their knowledge?'' said Robert Randolph, senior associate dean
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where worshipers at
Friday night Islamic services cause traffic jams outside the
school's religious center on Massachusetts Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been shown that success in life is determined by
intellect and emotional health, which includes the spiritual,''
said Felipe Jain, 20, a junior at Brown University who practices
Siddha yoga, a type of Indian meditation, every day. ``If the
university isn't good in the last area then how successful is it
going to be training students for life?''
</P>
<P>
   The conference will explore two main themes: the impact of
religious diversity on college campuses and how spirituality can be
introduced into education in a nonthreatening way that promotes
values, morals and ethics and produces responsible, as well as,
learned students.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the mission statement of so many colleges,
including this one, you realize that they were founded to inculcate
moral as well as intellectual values and I think we need to find
ways to use that to produce a better citizenry,'' said Rabbi Susan
Laemmle, dean of religious life at the University of Southern
California. ``I know it's a minefield and makes some people nervous
but it's a risk worth taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the country's most prestigious colleges, beginning with
Harvard in 1636, were founded by religious men and women who
expected that spiritual and intellectual formation would go
hand-in-hand.
</P>
<P>
   But over the decades as universities broke their historic ties
to religious denominations and became more secular, most
institutions jettisoned any talk of spirituality or relegated it to
the four walls of the campus chapel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pendulum swung so far toward a secular orientation that
universities seemed to emphasize the fact that we have no ethics,
no values, no beliefs and I think we're realizing that that kind of
attitude does a serious disservice to our students and to
society,'' said Margaret McKenna, president of Lesley College in
Cambridge, Mass., where courses looking at the connection between
spirituality and health are among the school's most popular.
</P>
<P>
   Many secular colleges, particularly those whose roots are within
Protestant denominations, have long been squeamish about
confronting issues touching on spirituality for fear of promoting
or forcing religion on students. An aversion to anything spiritual
is even more pronounced at public colleges and universities leery
of doing anything to weaken the wall between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our educational process has really led to the separation of
the life of the mind and the life of the whole person, including
the spirit,'' said David Scott, chancellor of the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst, where students have petitioned the
administration to turn the campus chapel into a center for
spirituality. ``But I don't think the framers of the Constitution
intended that in the interest of not promulgating one particular
religion we should eliminate all religious or spiritual views.''
</P>
<P>
   The newfound receptivity to sprituality on many campuses is
driven by a number of factors, including booming religious
diversity among college students and worries that young people are
growing up in a moral vacuum. And many college students, reflecting
American society at large, are on spiritual quests, yearning to
find deeper meaning to their lives beyond making the honor roll,
paying tuition or landing a summer internship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spirituality in the classroom is one of those taboo subjects
no one wants to talk about because education is supposed to be so
secular and rational,'' stated Yasmeen Golzar, 20, a junior at
Wellesley and a Muslim representative on the school's multi-faith
council. ``We've made American higher education feed the mind and
not the soul. But for me spirituality is very important. I want to
find meaning in whatever I do. I want to know how I can use what
I'm studying to make the world maybe a better place.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, anecdotal evidence from many colleges around
the country shows a proliferation in religious student
organizations from evangelical Christians to Hindus, more campus
talks devoted to religious and spiritual issues, and greater demand
for religion classes. At Tufts University, a student outcry helped
save the religion department, said the Rev. Scotty McLennan, the
university chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   Now, broad spiritual issues are seeping into non-religion
classes on secular campuses.
</P>
<P>
   At Tufts University, for example, originally founded in 1852 by
what is now the Unitarian Universalist Association, McLennan
teaches a course called ``Ethics through Literature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at characters in novels, plays and short stories and
ask about their morals, vices and virtues,'' said McLennan, ``and
use that to help students reflect on their own decisionmaking and
the development of moral courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a subject like mathematics, which seems as far removed from
the spiritual as possible, can still be an opportunity to discuss
spiritual issues, said Patrick Morton, a Wellesley math professor
who is leading a workshop at this weekend's conference called
``spiritual dimensions of creativity in mathematics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As I do mathematics there is a feeling of being led and guided
through the process by something larger than myself,'' Morton says.
``I think there is a way of introducing spirituality into the
classroom if it is done with care and respects the individual, the
classroom and the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   At UMass-Amherst last September, more than 200 students turned
out for a series of five workshops on interreligious dialogue at
the university.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of students want to move beyond a strictly secular world
view,'' said William Johnston, director of religious studies and
history professor at UMass. ``They are interested in discussions
that don't assume that economics and politics explain all human
behavior. They are not embarrassed to talk about their souls and
how to tap into their spiritual side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
