<HEADER>
A5269 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE-STOCK-COX     09-25 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-STOCK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola profit projections cut
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Analysts are cutting their projections for Coca-Cola
Co.'s profits through 1999 after Chief Executive M. Douglas Ivester
warned economic turmoil in key global markets will drag down the
company's performance for the rest of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, who met with analysts Friday morning in New York, said
third quarter earnings should be 35 cents per share, on sales
volume growth of just 3 percent to 4 percent. That compares with
growth of 11 percent in the year-earlier period, when Coca-Cola
earned 34 cents per share excluding a gain from the sale of stakes
in bottlers.
</P>
<P>
   The third-quarter consensus estimate of analysts reporting to
First Call had been 42 cents per share at the beginning of the
quarter, though it was revised to 39 cents just hours before the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon Friday, First Call's consensus estimate had
dropped to 35 cents for the third quarter, 30 cents for the fourth
quarter and $1.46 for the year.
</P>
<P>
   For 1999, the early consensus is $1.60 a share _ down more than
10 percent from the previous 1999 estimate of $1.79.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going through a short-term period of uncertainty, which
Coke should come out of (in the) second or third quarter of 1999,''
said Morgan Stanley Dean Witter analyst Andrew Conway, who attended
the meeting. ``Fundamentally, nothing has changed in terms of the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Ivester put forth a positive front to reassure
investors that Coca-Cola will weather the harsh economic climate,
and come out stronger, as it has in previous downturns. Despite
economic uncertainty in Asia, Latin America and Eastern Europe, the
company should reach its stated goal of annual volume increases in
the 7 percent to 8 percent range both this year and in 1999,
Ivester said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can deny that the simultaneous economic slump in most
markets is having a short-term impact on all global businesses,
including ours,'' Ivester said. ``Yet we remain intensely focused
on building this business system for the long-term by making the
right decisions and continuing to invest for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no intent to sacrifice the long-term health of this
business merely to reap short-term rewards, which would only be
temporary in nature,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which does business in 197 countries, gets 70 percent
of its sales and 75 percent of its profit from international
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Through careful hedging, the company usually limits the impact
from currency fluctuations on earnings to no more than 3 percent.
But the global economic flux, coupled with the strong dollar, has
thrown that trend off track this year. This quarter, currency's
impact is expected to shave 10 percent off earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was the second time in 13 months that Coca-Cola has
warned earnings would fall short of expectations because of
economic conditions in some parts of the world. This time, the
warning came with news that sales are slowing in Brazil, Japan and
Russia, where weak economies are curtailing consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   Investor concern has sent Coca-Cola's stock down sharply in
recent months. By Friday, when it closed down 50 cents at $56.18
3/4, the stock had fallen 36 percent from its 52-week high in July.
More than 11.2 million shares changed hands, nearly three times the
six-month daily average.
</P>
<P>
   Buying back shares
</P>
<P>
   Ivester said the company will likely step up its share
repurchase program, which, since 1984, has bought back more than 1
billion shares at the average price of $11.93.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has spent from $1.2 billion to $1.8 billion buying
back shares each of the last several years, and Ivester said the
company should spend near the high end of that range on stock
repurchases in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Companies typically buy back shares to help support their stock
price. Coca-Cola had 2.47 billion shares outstanding as of July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Through the end of second quarter, the company had bought 198
million of 200 million shares the board of directors had approved
repurchasing between 1992 and 2000. That buyback plan is likely to
be completed by now, so the company can move on to another program,
approved in 1996, to repurchase 206 million additional shares
through 2006.
</P>
<P>
   The company has enough cash to aggressively repurchase shares
and pour money into infrastructure improvements in emerging
markets, where weak economies give Coca-Cola more bang for its
buck, said Jennifer Solomon, a beverage analyst with Salomon/Smith
Barney.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're kind of hunkering down,'' she said. ``They're gearing
up for battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ivester told analysts he'd rather be managing a business
that has a system in place in 200 countries than trying to build a
similar system in the midst of an economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   What's the true value?
</P>
<P>
   While Coca-Cola's market value has fallen about $80 billion in
the last two months, some analysts and money managers say the drop
has put the company's price-to-earnings multiple in a more
realistic range.
</P>
<P>
   ``The multiple has come down from about 55 to about 35,''
explained Bill Hackney, managing partner with Atlanta Capital
Management, an investment firm that manages $3.9 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   That price-to-earnings multiple generally is compared with the
S&AMP;P 500, which historically carries a multiple of about 15 but has
been pushed into the 20 percent to 25 percent range by this year's
market roller coaster. For years, Coca-Cola's multiple has
outdistanced the S&AMP;P 500, which some critics say creates a risk for
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coca-Cola is a bit like Microsoft and GE. It's is so well
managed and it dominates its markets so well, it always looks too
high priced for its growth rate,'' Hackney said. ``It's much more
reasonably priced today. We're getting a historical opportunity to
buy the stock cheaply.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, who has had a more conservative outlook on Coca-Cola
than many of Wall Street, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be buyers in the low $50s,'' said Solomon, who has a
``neutral'' rating on the stock. ``It's getting to the point...
where we would upgrade our rating.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
