<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANTS-MORTGAGES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Immigrants create opportunities for mortgage lenders
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In 1994, when Benjamin Rincon began working for
Norwest Mortgage as community development branch manager, the
company made 35 mortgage loans to Hispanic families. This year, it
will make between 550 and 600.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, says Rincon, on Nov. 1, Norwest Mortgage will open
a Buford Highway office, one mile from the Latin American
Association in the heart of one of Atlanta's Hispanic communities.
It will be part of an ongoing effort to encourage Hispanic people
and other immigrants to buy houses.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Rincon, other mortgage lenders and real estate agents
say the burgeoning number of immigrants to the United States _
projected by the Immigration and Naturalization Service at 10
million this decade _ is creating challenges as well as
opportunities to create another population of home buyers.
</P>
<P>
   To meet the new demands, real estate professionals and mortgage
lenders are hiring bilingual employees, developing ethnically
sensitive advertising campaigns and adjusting selling techniques to
ethnic attitudes and cultural practices.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae reported a 47 percent growth in immigrant homeowners
between 1980 and 1995 but anticipates another 45 percent jump by
2010. That means during the next decade, 6.8 million people not
born in the United States could own homes here, especially in the
suburbs, where they seek the same quality schools, churches and
transportation as their native-born counterparts do.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the groups, Hispanics have had and continue to have the
greatest impact on the real estate industry, according to Century
21 Real Estate Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Lynnette Rodriguez, director of family services at the Latin
American Association, said the organization's third annual housing
fair, scheduled for April 24, is being orchestrated by a committee
of lenders and Realtors. Although seminars will be given in
Spanish, other housing-related services are manned by bilingual
people.
</P>
<P>
   Even at Summit Bank, a Chinese-owned commercial bank in
Chamblee, directors are considering a move into the mortgage
lending business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are testing the waters,'' said manager David Yu of Summit's
Asian Banking Center, ``but there are issues such as timing and the
economic cycle that we have to consider.''
</P>
<P>
   Real estate agent Michele Fiechter said her sales to immigrant
families have grown 500 percent during the past 12 months in west
Cobb, Smyrna, Tucker, Alpharetta and Paulding County. She works
with Century 21 in east Cobb County and assists the Latin American
Association in running seminars.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRIES OF ORIGIN
</P>
<P>
   Country of origin for foreign-born residents of the United
States as of March, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico27.1
</P>
<P>
   Philippines4.6
</P>
<P>
   China, Hong Kong3.9
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam3.8
</P>
<P>
   Cuba3.5
</P>
<P>
   El Salvador2.8
</P>
<P>
   India2.7
</P>
<P>
   Dominican Republic2.4
</P>
<P>
   Great Britain2.4
</P>
<P>
   Korea2.2
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere 44.7
</P>
<P>
   Less than 2.2 percent for any one country.
</P>
<P>
   Source: U.S. Census Bureau
</P>
