<HEADLINE>
NOTES AND QUOTES ON BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for Love In the Fed Funds Rate &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like a love-struck intern parsing the boss's neckwear for a
secret sign that the feeling is mutual, world markets hunted
obsessively last week for reasons to believe that the Federal Open
Market Committee would cut interest rates at its meeting on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hearts skipped beats at midweek when Alan Greenspan suggested to
Congress that action was needed ``shortly'' to keep the contagion
of economic instability now afflicting emerging markets from
``really spilling over and creating some very significant further
difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   The remark apparently sounded enough like ``Will you marry me?''
to send stocks soaring for a day. By week's end, the main question
seemed to be how big a diamond, er, rate cut would be forthcoming,
with some Fed watchers liking the way a half-point sounded. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even a Hedge Fund Can Be `Too Big to Fail' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital Management was every inch a hedge fund. For a
big-money client list, the fund's big-name managers took big
chances with even bigger leverage in pursuit of really big returns.
</P>
<P>
   Lately the fund had bought risky emerging-markets bonds and
hedged by selling Treasuries short, a strategy that got it in big
trouble when Russia devalued, setting off a market stampede to
safety that made both those moves big losers and nearly wiped out
the fund's capital.
</P>
<P>
   When the fund's founder, John W. Meriwether, failed last week to
raise enough new money to stave off insolvency, the Federal Reserve
stepped in.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing an asset fire sale that would clobber credit markets
worldwide, the Fed organized an unprecedented $3.5 billion bailout
by big institutions like Morgan Stanley and Chase Manhattan. News
of the fund's near failure shocked stock markets and made lenders
leery of other hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss bank UBS said it would report a big third-quarter
loss, in part because of Long-Term Capital's troubles. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's Faltering Profits May Delay an Offering &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After debating fitfully about it for years, the 189 partners of
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. finally voted in June to go public, and look
what's happened since: Currencies have collapsed, emerging markets
melted, stock markets swooned, bond yields sunk, merger deals
unraveled, and new equity offerings all but vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow Goldman still made a profit of $754 million in its
fiscal third quarter, the company said on Tuesday, but the falloff
from earlier in the year was sharp enough to cast doubt on
Goldman's plan for a November debut for its stock.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts called the Goldman offering a canary in the mine:
Postponement would be read as a warning that top investment bankers
see the stock market getting worse before it gets better. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed a bankruptcy bill that will make it
substantially harder for consumers to walk away from debts. ...
Philippine Airlines shut down after last-ditch efforts to resolve a
bitter labor dispute collapsed. The carrier handled 80 percent of
domestic air passenger and cargo traffic in the island nation; the
government and smaller carriers scrambled to fill the void. ...
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter reported a drop in profits of only 5
percent for the third quarter, much less than expected, but the
cheery report got lost in the hedge-fund bailout flap and Morgan's
stock slipped on the day.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Lehman Brothers Holdings said profits fell
23 percent in the quarter; it, too, was reckoned to have escaped
much damage, and its shares bounced on the news. ... Orders for
durable goods jumped 1.6 percent in August, pointing to continued
economic strength; GDP growth in the second quarter was revised
upward, to an annual rate of 1.8 percent. ... The huge
Citicorp-Travelers merger cleared its last regulatory hurdle,
winning Federal Reserve approval contingent on selling some
businesses. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SO TO SPEAK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Eerie Echo &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two famously cagey witnesses on the topic of ``legally
accurate'' testimony: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``It was not my responsibility to volunteer a lot of
information. ... I was doing my best to be truthful. I was not
trying to be particularly helpful to them, and I didn't think I had
an obligation to be particularly helpful to them.''(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   _ President Clinton, in his Aug. 17, 1998, grand jury testimony,
referring to statements that he and his lawyer made about his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky when he was deposed in the Paula
Jones sexual harassment suit in January. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics)``I never undertake to instruct the man who asks me
questions. ... It was no part of my duty as a witness to volunteer
testimony. While they thought they were leading me into a trap, I
let them go into a trap themselves.''(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ John D. Rockefeller Sr. to his authorized biographer, William
O. Inglis, referring to testimony in 1888 before a New York State
Senate committee. When the committee's counsel mistakenly referred
to a notorious price-fixing and kickback scheme as the Southern
Improvement Co. instead of the South Improvement Company,
Rockefeller was able to deny taking part in it without committing
perjury. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV     09-25 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOFTER THEY FALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Calif., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What is the lesson from the rescue of Long-Term
Capital Management, the hedge fund based in Greenwich, Conn.,
that's run by John W. Meriwether and a band of Wall Street's
savviest traders? That it helps to be big, to be bold and to know
the right people.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Streeters not involved in the fund's $3.5 billion bailout
by a consortium of large banks and brokerage firms are agog not
only at the size of the losses but also at the idea that so
speculative a firm would be saved from a demise of its own making.
Cries of crony capitalism, Wall Street style, are growing louder.
And with some justification.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the deal _ in which companies like J.P. Morgan,
Chase Manhattan, Travelers Group and Goldman, Sachs agreed to put
up roughly $300 million apiece to stabilize Long-Term Capital _
goes against the advice that American policy makers have been
dispensing to tattered economies around the world.
</P>
<P>
   If a financial institution is bankrupt, Washington has scolded,
it should be allowed to fail. The United States has been especially
vocal on this score to officials in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the small matter of exactly why these
institutions, under the Federal Reserve's sponsorship, came to
Long-Term Capital's rescue. According to Sanford I. Weill, chairman
of Travelers, the financial industry concluded that a bailout was
``the best way to maintain orderly markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Weill is surely right. Forcing Long-Term Capital to liquidate
its holdings under pressure would have unleashed a firestorm on
already damaged worldwide bond markets. Because Meriwether had big
holdings in junk bonds, for instance, a liquidation of those
securities would have clipped their prices badly, hurting
individual investors who own high-yield-bond mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   But the retail investor is only part of the story and hardly the
heart of it. The bailout was in the bankers' self-interest, too.
Most of the firms that executed Meriwether's trades piggybacked on
them, putting on the same positions.
</P>
<P>
   So a mass liquidation of Meriwether's portfolio would have
slashed the value of their holdings. Furthermore, some of the
rescuers _ Merrill Lynch and UBS AG, for example _ had stakes in
the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Is the bailout throwing good money after bad? An investment in
Long-Term Capital may turn out to be a home run for Merrill Lynch
and the other firms, which now have 90 percent ownership of the
hedge fund. But the idea that many of these institutions extended
so much credit to Long-Term Capital with little understanding of
the risks doesn't say much about their management controls.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers find it interesting to compare Meriwether's
treatment with that of another failed investment manager _ Robert
Citron, the disgraced former treasurer of Orange County, Calif. As
with Meriwether, Citron's undoing was a series of wrongheaded
interest-rate bets; his caused the county's 1994 bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   There are big differences, of course. Citron was investing with
public money, not the funds of high-rolling private investors. And
he diverted money from one public account to another. He also was
no denizen of Wall Street's corridors, given to wearing turquoise
jewelry, not chalk-striped suits.
</P>
<P>
   How many more hedge funds are about to need bailing out? Alan
Greenspan, the Federal Reserve chairman, knows that the biggest
hazard of one bailout is that it makes people expect another and
another. He testified to Congress on the subject 10 days ago. And
yet the New York Fed brokered the Long-Term Capital deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That the Fed decided to send a helicopter to sprinkle money
over Greenwich means Mr. Greenspan knows that the problem must be
so big on the other side,'' said Stan Jonas, managing director at
FIMAT/USA, a broker dealer in New York, referring to the banks.
``It must be big, if he's willing to sacrifice principle just to
get rid of it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
