<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5278 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-MANAGEMENT-$ADV27     09-25 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MANAGEMENT-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN MANAGEMENT SHOOTS FOR THE MOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 27)  
 (bl)  
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Management theorists, who have created clunky terms like
``co-opetition,'' are generally not known for their elegance with
language. That's not likely to change anytime soon, considering the
buzzword now sweeping through corner offices around the country:
BHAGs, for ``big, hairy, audacious goals.''
</P>
<P>
   A BHAG (pronounced BEE-hag) is supposed to inspire an
organization to reach for a goal it might otherwise think
impossible, as when NASA set out to land a man on the moon in the
1960s. In management circles, the notion was refined by Gary Hamel
and C.K. Prahalad, who observed in a 1989 article in The Harvard
Business Review that companies that emerged as global leaders had
invariably begun with outsized ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   But the bigness and hair were added by James C. Collins and
Jerry I. Porras, who apparently coined the term BHAG in their 1994
book, ``Built to Last: Successful Habits of Visionary Companies''
(HarperBusiness). And the idea seems to be gaining momentum. Warren
Bennis, a professor at the University of Southern California and
the author of several books on leadership, said he kept hearing the
term at a recent management conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to really hit everybody,'' he said. ``People keep
raising the bar, and in order to be competitive, you have to set
these goals. It's all part of the hyper, turbulent, spastic
business environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there are a lot of attention-getting goals being
trumpeted by corporate executives. Samir Gibara, chief executive of
Goodyear Tire and Rubber, a $13 billion company, has told Wall
Street that he will add $10 billion in sales within five years, a
tall order for a slow-growth industry. Procter &AMP; Gamble is still
working on its goal of doubling the company's size in 10 years. And
Times Mirror wants to increase the circulation of The Los Angeles
Times by 500,000, a 50 percent jump.
</P>
<P>
   But are these goals big, hairy and audacious enough to be
bona-fide BHAGs?
</P>
<P>
   Collins says incremental financial targets don't qualify.
``People are setting short-term targets and confusing them with
BHAGs,'' he said in an interview. ``They just pick a big goal
because they feel they need to have a big goal.''
</P>
<P>
   So how can you spot a genuine BHAG? By Collins' thinking, it has
to be something with at least a 30-year horizon, a mountain of a
goal, with 10-year financial targets serving as base camps along
the way. BHAGs should help stimulate progress while preserving a
company's central mission.
</P>
<P>
   Sony, for example, set out to change the world's perception that
Japanese products were cheap. General Electric pledged to become
No. 1 or No. 2 in every market it served, while moving with the
speed and agility of a much smaller company.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, Boeing invested two-thirds of the company's net
profit from the postwar years to develop the 707, the early
commercial jetliner; it has since emerged as the world's largest
aerospace company, absorbing the remnants of most of its 1950s
rivals. (Boeing's recent stumbles in speeding up its production
lines suggest that it might be better at BHAGs, than what, with
apologies to Collins, might be called small, nettlesome ancillary
goals, or SNAGs.)
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the companies that seem better at meeting
short-term objectives than sculpting a BHAG. Bristol-Myers Squibb
Co. set out in 1994 to double sales, earnings and earnings per
share by the end of 2000 _ a difficult hurdle that it has a good
shot at clearing. But that sharp focus gets lost in setting out its
loftier mission. ``The pillars of our success,'' the company states
in its annual report, ``will remain Growth, Productivity and the
continued development of a Dynamic Operating Culture that fosters
innovation and rewards success.'' On the cover of its annual
report, Bristol uses the anything but audacious tag line ``Building
Tomorrows.'' Bristol says the slogan is meant to capture the
company's core mission of ``enhancing and extending lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, mere audacity does not a BHAG make. ``The critical
variable is that a BHAG has to be connected to the purpose of the
company _ not just any random big goal, but one that really
connects back to the enduring values and purpose of the
institution,'' Collins said. ``Companies that change best over time
know first and foremost what should not change.''
</P>
<P>
   But when companies go after a BHAG, they can easily create a big
hairy foot to trip over.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Campbell Soup chairman David Johnson released a
gaggle of goals for the company in 1996. He wanted to take Campbell
to ``a new level,'' he said, ``vaulting our company into the ranks
of the world's renowned consumer-goods companies.'' He wanted to
make Campbell ``best of show,'' instead of just tops in its class.
Last but not least, he said he wanted Campbell Soup to be
considered a global leader, like Coca-Cola or Gillette. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To get there, Campbell Soup has steadily predicted annual jumps
in sales of soup, even though the category has remained flat for
years. Such predictions, when not met, can undermine investor
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many packaged food companies can be accused of selling their
stock as hard as their products,'' said John M. McMillin, an
analyst for Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   But what's wrong with a little BHAG-ian bravado? Bennis, the USC
professor, said there might be a long-term price to pay for feeling
compelled to pursue a BHAG.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost may be in impulsive decisions,'' he said, like
chasing dubious mergers for the sake of doing something big _ and
doing it quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``And somehow the phrase,'' he added, ``lacks a certain
aesthetic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
