r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-COLDWAR-AZR &LR;      09-25 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COLDWAR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN EXPLORES LIFE ON THE BRINK IN `COLD WAR'  
 (EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Watch just a little of the massive new CNN documentary
``The Cold War,'' and one conclusion is inescapable: What peewees
we've all become.
</P>
<P>
   The state of affairs that currently possesses the affairs of
state are laughably light when weighed against the overwhelming
issues that occupied world leaders until just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   More than public decency or faith in elected leadership stood on
the brink of annihilation during most of the nearly five decades of
the Cold War. Humanity's future waited there, watching for the big
flash on the horizon. Our elders sweated Stalin and Castro so we
can spend our time combing through the Starr report?
</P>
<P>
   You'll wonder that, too, as you work your way though the 24-hour
documentary, which will unfold on the Cable News Network one hour
at a time each Sunday night until spring, starting tonight. It's
simply amazing, looking back, that we survived. And where have all
those larger-than-life leaders gone?
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 witnesses, both ordinary citizens and world
honchos, were interviewed for ``The Cold War.'' Actor Kenneth
Branagh narrates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the cold facts of our history in this world
over the last 50 years, you end up with a very great deal of
respect for the leaders on both sides,'' said Sir Jeremy Isaacs,
executive producer of the series, in a recent meeting with TV
critics.
</P>
<P>
   Respect for leaders. How quaint.
</P>
<P>
   CNN founder Ted Turner, in the same meeting with critics, said
the idea of a comprehensive Cold War series came to him during the
1994 Goodwill Games in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   The Berlin Wall had fallen, the long war was over. Files on all
sides of the conflict, for the first time, were opening. Video and
newsreel footage from dozens of countries was becoming available.
And many of the key policymakers and eyewitnesses, though aging,
were still alive and available for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always been a student of history,'' said Turner. ``I was
particularly touched by ``The Civil War,'' Ken Burns' series on
public television, and perhaps even more _ because it was more
poignant, more relevant to me _ by the series ``The World at War,''
which took a multinational viewpoint of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who are old enough to remember the Cold War . . .
only saw our side of it. We never saw what appeared on Russian
television or Vietnam television or Chinese television.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, a lot of people say television is a vast wasteland.
There's a lot of garbage on television. Sometimes it makes me
ashamed to be in the business, because it's such a waste of
people's time. But this is not a waste of people's time.''
</P>
<P>
   Isaacs, who also oversaw the making of 1974's ``The World at
War,'' will get most of the credit for ``The Cold War,'' though an
army of researchers, historians and telejournalists worked for
nearly four years on the final product. It will be available in
various multimedia forms, including an accompanying book and
CD-ROM, and, of course, a big package of videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   Though there are few big revelations in the series, its value as
an educational tool is high. Viewing it hour-by-hour as
entertainment will be a difficult assignment, but there are
important lessons throughout its frequently gray, sometimes dense
narrative.
</P>
<P>
   If the danger of the Cold War years now seems like such a
distant part of history, the people who led the world through those
treacherous times cast ever-more-impressive shadows on our era.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic that humanity learns from its mistakes and
near-mistakes, and I think that the danger of a world war is far
less than it has been at any time in the last 100 years,'' Turner
said. ``I don't think the great danger to humanity now is in
another world war or nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the great danger is in overpopulation and
environmental destruction, and we need to deal with that. (But)
that's a much more difficult thing for us to deal with because it
occurs more slowly, and it's easy to go into denial about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody understood that a nuclear bomb would ruin your
weekend.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
