<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-NY-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. HAITIANS FOCUS ON HURRICANE RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also HURRICANE-GEORGES) 
(mk) 
 By GARRY PIERRE-PIERRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Haitian immigrants in New York City are scrambling to
put together a relief effort to send emergency supplies to Haiti in
the aftermath of Hurricane Georges, and some have expressed dismay
at what they see as the slow response of the administration of
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to the situation there.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen Haitian organizations have created the Haiti
Disaster Relief Committee, and have set up drop-off sites where
people can donate goods and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Haitians acknowledged Friday that they did not act
quickly enough in assessing the damages in Haiti and failed to
reach out to city officials until late this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This challenges us once again to look at the way we operate in
the Haitian community and to do better next time,'' said Jocelyn
McCalla, executive director of the National Coalition of Haitian
Rights and chairman of the ad hoc relief committee. ``We generally
do not engage elected or appointed officials in a consistent
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office said that the city was ready to send
emergency supplies as soon as it finds an organization in Haiti
capable of distributing the aid once it arrives, said Colleen
Roche, the mayor's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to guard against the relief aid ending up in the
black market,'' Ms. Roche said, adding that the city was prepared
to send whatever was needed in Haiti, including blankets, water and
food.
</P>
<P>
   On its destructive path through the northeastern Caribbean,
Hurricane Georges hit the Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico the
hardest.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Hispanic community in New York City said they did
not wait for the city to begin planning a relief effort. When it
appeared that the full force of the storm would hit Puerto Rico and
the Dominican Republic, they reached out to the mayor's office and
created an emergency plan. New York City dispatched a team of
police officers and firefighters to the Dominican Republic. Similar
efforts have been coordinated for Puerto Rico and other Caribbean
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Ninfa Segarra said that these relief efforts would
be extended to wherever they were needed. ``Certainly, this is not
just for Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic,'' Ms. Segarra
said. ``We've been working with groups from across the Caribbean.''
</P>
<P>
   Haitians said that the hurricane's impact on Haiti was also
devastating, given that mountainous country's problems with erosion
and its poor infrastructure. In Haiti, the poorest country in the
hemisphere, even the most routine rainfall can bring flooding in
the capital of Port-au-Prince.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, because of poor roads and communication, scant
information is known about the storm damage and death toll in the
northeast and central plateau regions, which bore the brunt of the
hurricane in Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports, Port-au-Prince, where roughly 2 million
people live, is completely flooded. Thousands of people living in
Cite Soleil, a teeming seaside slum, were left homeless when the
storm washed away their cardboard homes. Health officials fear an
outbreak of cholera and malaria in a country with poor sewage
systems and a lack of potable water.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The relationship between the Giuliani administration and Haitian
immigrants was severely strained following an assault case in
August 1997 involving a Haitian immigrant, Abner Louima. Four
police officers from the 70th Precinct in Brooklyn were indicted on
federal civil rights charges in the case, in which prosecutors say
Louima was beaten and brutalized in the station house. Haitians
organized a march across the Brooklyn Bridge to protest what they
saw as a climate in the Police Department that allowed brutality,
an event that Giuliani denounced as anti-police.
</P>
<P>
   ``In almost every instance, we're not considered,'' said Henri
Frank, executive director of the Haitian Centers Council, a
Brooklyn-based group. ``It seems that there is favoritism. The
other groups make noise and they get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   Tatiana Wah, chairwoman of the Haitian American Alliance, a
community group, agreed, saying of Giuliani: ``I do think Haitians
have been slighted by his administration overall. He could have
rallied the Haitian community. He just felt that this time he
didn't have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Georges Bousiquot, a Haitian immigrant and Giuliani supporter
who is director of operations at the city's Department of Housing
Preservation and Development, said Haitians have taken a victim's
posture that undermines their potential political strength and
exposes their lack of cohesion in a community that is perceived by
outsiders as being tight-knit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always bashing Giuliani and now we want him to come to
our aid,'' Bousiquot said. ``It doesn't make any sense. Why should
he reach out to us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the Haitians were late in planning for this
disaster,'' McCalla said. ``Now we have to develop very quick and
fruitful relationships.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
