<HEADLINE>
BUSH PREPARES TV PITCH TO HISPANIC VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In an expensive bid to attract Hispanic voters
who have traditionally supported Democrats, Republican Gov. George
W. Bush's campaign Friday unveiled a series of television
commercial in Spanish and English.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's opponent, Democratic Land Commissioner Garry Mauro, has
won the Hispanic vote in his previous elections. But the Bush camp
believes the governor could grab a larger-than-usual proportion of
the Hispanic vote in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Although no specific dollar figures were given, the Bush
campaign said it is making an ``unprecedented'' push in the
Hispanic community. At least a quarter of the campaign's TV budget
will be spent on the Hispanic TV ads that begin airing Monday in
most Texas markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you this campaign is going to devote more time,
more money and more resources and more personnel to reaching out to
(Hispanic voters) than any campaign in Texas history, Democrat or
Republican,'' said Mark McKinnon, Bush's media specialist and a
one-time Democratic consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro dismissed the importance of the ad campaign, saying Bush
doesn't understand what it takes to win votes in the Hispanic
community.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro is far behind Bush in fund-raising efforts, and he has yet
to introduce TV ads in the final stretch of the campaign because he
needs about $2 million to do so.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to get about $1 million of that when President Clinton
goes to San Antonio to Houston on Sunday to attend private
fund-raisers for Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   ``You carry the Hispanic vote because you understand the
community and you support the ideals and values the community
supports,'' Mauro said, inferring he is that candidate _ not Bush.
</P>
<P>
   There are three separate commercials done in Spanish and
English, and Bush speaks some Spanish in two. The Spanish ads will
run on Spanish-language stations and English-language stations,
while the English ads will only go on English-language stations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5289 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GOP-SPENDING-     09-25 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GOP-SPENDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KEY TEST FOR CLINTON, ANOTHER SPENDING BATTLE LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With nine working days until the deadline for
approving money to keep the government running, President Clinton
is facing his first real test of power with the
Republican-controlled Congress since the effort to impeach him
engulfed the Capitol weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton still has the veto pen, and he has threatened to use it
on seven of the 13 must-pass spending bills. The question is
whether he has the strength to use it and whether his fellow
Democrats in Congress will back him if he does.
</P>
<P>
   Looming are battles over major issues that could bring a partial
shutdown of the government. These include differences over tax
cuts, spending for education, environmental controls, fixing the
Year 2000 computer bug in government computers, aid to farmers to
compensate for the drought, whether to grant school vouchers in the
District of Columbia and to what extent to finance the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   They include perennially contentious issues like family planning
and, new this year, whether the Food and Drug Administration should
be allowed to use taxpayer money to approve abortion-inducing drugs
like RU-486. Another novel dispute is over how to conduct the
census in 2000, which, because it helps determine the number of
seats each party can win in Congress, is deeply important to both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   But the chief hang-ups at the moment, and the reason the process
may seem stalled, stem from disagreements among Republicans in the
House and between Republicans in the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reischauer, who was the director of the Congressional
Budget Office earlier in the Clinton presidency and is now a
scholar at the Brookings Institution, said of the impasse that he
sees building: ``A lot of this reflects the internal divisions
within the Republican Party and the fact that the Republican
majority in the House is a very small one. The leadership can't
offend the moderate wing or the conservative wing and still have a
majority.''
</P>
<P>
   The House has passed 12 of the 13 spending bills. The Senate has
passed 10. The House and Senate have agreed upon and sent to
Clinton only two _ one to pay for scores of military projects in
local congressional districts and one to cover congressional
operating costs. Typically by this stage, Congress has passed five
or six of the bills.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties have been slowly laying the groundwork to blame the
other for a possible government shutdown that could result if they
fail to resolve their differences. But Clinton, who is rebounding
in public opinion polls, lashed out at Congress on Friday as part
of his strategy to focus attention away from his troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging like a bear from a cave with sudden ferocity, Clinton
accused Congress of ``failing to meet its most basic governing
responsibility,'' a reference to Congress missing its deadline five
months ago for passing a budget resolution outlining its broad
goals for federal spending.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that Congress' need to buy more time to finish its
spending bills _ postponing its deadline for the spending bills
from Oct. 1 to Oct. 9 _ was a ``regrettable sign'' that Republicans
were not addressing urgent problems. But such postponements have
become accepted practice. In eight of the last 10 years, Congress
has provided temporary financing to keep the government running
past the start of the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The president's comments riled Republicans on Capitol Hill.
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott accused the president of taking a
gratuitous slap at Congress as he ``jumps on a plane and runs off
for three days of fund raising.''
</P>
<P>
   And Republicans insisted that they did not want a shutdown.
``With everything else going on, it would be wrong to have a battle
over the minutiae of the financing of the government,'' said Sen.
Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, chairman of the Senate Appropriations
Committee. ``We won't close down the government; we'll just past a
CR to bring us back after the election,'' a reference to a
``continuing resolution'' that would keep the government running.
</P>
<P>
   But he suggested the president was spoiling for a fight as a way
to deflect talk of impeachment. ``This is the first year that I can
remember that they haven't sent people around to talk to me about
how they feel about the bills,'' Senator Stevens said. ``I'm afraid
it means they want to veto bills and close down the government.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee, had the same reaction. ``The big question is, how much
disruption does the president want to refocus the attention of the
American people away from his own problems?''
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and Senate have scheduled conferences next week
to reconcile their differing versions of four or five other
noncontroversial spending bills and send them to the president. And
they still have time to complete final action on all the bills
sooner than they have done in previous years. Last year, for
example, they took until Nov. 13 to resolve the spending bills. In
1987, they went until Dec. 22.
</P>
<P>
   An added incentive this year is that many Republicans are eager
to get home and campaign for re-election, and their advisers hope
they will be able to do that and avoid a shutdown or a major
confrontation with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the bully pulpit, and he can determine over which
issues the government is shut down,'' said Ralph Reed, the former
executive director of the Christian Coalition and an adviser to
numerous Republican congressional candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even during the darkest days of Watergate, Nixon sustained a
series of vetoes on Capitol Hill,'' he said. ``To underestimate the
institutional power of the presidency because of the unique
personal weakness of the person occupying it is a serious
mistake.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5291 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-ELECT-645&AMP;ADD     09-25 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-ELECT-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAGUE, YES, BUT SCHROEDER COULD UNSEAT CHANCELLOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ With a promise to restore ``social justice to
Germany,'' and a flash of his winning smile, Gerhard Schroeder on
Friday wound up his campaign to replace Helmut Kohl as German
chancellor in national elections on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite seeing his lead erode in recent weeks, and despite a
refusal to clarify his plans, Schroeder appears to have a better
chance of succeeding than any of his four predecessors as Social
Democratic candidates, who tried and failed to dislodge Kohl over
the last 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   During those Kohl years, the Berlin wall came down, Germany was
unified, the European Union was consolidated, a new European
currency called the euro was agreed to, and 16 million former East
Germans were granted pensions, social security and German marks at
a staggering cost to the nation but without social upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   The achievement speaks for itself, but Schroeder has cleverly
avoided speaking about it, concentrating instead on the high
unemployment, the fragmenting of Germany's social model, the
widening gap between rich and poor and the uncertainty that has
accompanied the country's push for global competitiveness and
acceptance of unification.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Kohl came to power, 25 percent of university students
were from working-class families,'' Schroeder told a crowd in the
former eastern part of Berlin on Friday. ``Today, that figure is
less than 14 percent. I intend to change this. Only a society with
social justice can be a true democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The setting for Schroeder's last speech was clearly carefully
chosen, for it is in the former east that his best chance of
success appears to lie. With 20 percent of the work force
unemployed in the area that constituted the former East German
state, support for Kohl's Christian Democrats has crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   This decline, and a weariness with Kohl that is palpable
throughout much of Germany, and especially among young people, may
be enough to push the Social Democratic share of the vote to as
much as 42 percent, compared with estimates of about 37 percent for
the Christian Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Other opinion polls, however, suggest a much closer finish, with
the parties separated by just 2 percent. With more than 20 percent
of the electorate saying it is undecided, and many of these
believed to be former Christian Democratic voters, the outcome is
too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that Schroeder has taken a calculated risk in
avoiding clear commitments right to the last, a tactic that has
exasperated many Germans who take the practical view that they
should know what their vote is for.
</P>
<P>
   But this approach may have enabled the Social Democratic
candidate to win votes in the center while not alienating the
bedrock support of workers, for it has enabled the Social Democrats
to lambaste the unacceptable costs of the welfare state and at the
same time pledge its preservation or even its extension.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Schroeder promised to reduce taxes for working
families, combine ``economy and ecology,'' provide jobs for the
young, preserve or increase pensions, and refashion a society
``where the rich get richer and the poor get poorer.'' But he went
into no detail about how he would do all this.
</P>
<P>
   Battling to compete, and to increase productivity, German
companies cut about 2.7 million jobs between 1991 and 1997. This
drive created a wide sense of alienation in a society long known
for its cohesiveness. But recently the economy has revived _ 2.7
percent growth is expected this year _ and the unemployment rate
has begun to decline.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder believes this improvement has come too late for Kohl.
His campaign organizers are convinced that Schroeder's modern air,
his Clintonian push for a ``new center'' and his new face itself
will be enough to overcome the visceral conservatism of many German
voters, for whom change is tantamount to possible instability.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Oskar Lafontaine, the chairman of the Social Democratic Party,
who tried and failed to defeat Kohl in 1990, spoke before
Schroeder, describing with great eloquence his dream that the young
would find new hope in a Social Democratic government.
</P>
<P>
   It was, by any estimate, a much better speech than Schroeder's.
But that was not the point. Having failed so often, the Social
Democrats have decided to be pragmatic _ and Schroeder, polls
repeatedly show, is the man with greatest capacity to broaden the
center-left party's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``World-Class for Germany,'' says Kohl's campaign poster. But
Schroeder, like Clinton in his campaign against George Bush in
1992, is betting that the world matters less to Germans than their
domestic problems, and that Kohl's historic achievements now belong
in the history books. It is a big wager, and one whose outcome, it
now seems, will be uncertain to the last.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
