<P>
   ACALUPCO-HURRICANE (Venustiano Carranza, Mexico) _ A year ago,
Joaquin Flores Juarez used to drive his car up the steep slope of
this hillside suburb of Acapulco and park in front of his house.
Then came Hurricane Pauline last October that washed away
hillsides. Despite the promises of political leaders last October _
including President Ernesto Zedillo _ that storm damage would
rapidly be cleaned up and repaired, residents say nothing has been
done. By PHILIP TRUE. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-ERADICATION (Chapare Jungle, Bolivia) _ Under pressure
from Washington, Bolovian President Hugo Banzer has ordered
soldiers to destroy every illegal coca plantation in the nation
within five years. But the scorched-earth tactics have provoked
violent protests in normally peaceful Bolivia. By JOHN OTIS.
(Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-COCA (Cochabamba, Bolivia) _ At a time when U.S.-backed
eradication teams are bent on wiping out coca crops in South
America, activists are trying to promote the healthful properties
of coca and convince the world that coca is not cocaine. By JOHN
OTIS. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-COKE (Chipiriri, Bolivia) _ Coca-Cola buys about 200
metric tons of coca leaves annually, according to the head of the
U.S. State Department's Narcotics Affairs Section in Bolivia. A
pharmaceutical company then removes the cocaine alklaloid, and
Coca-Cola uses the mulch for flavoring. A spokesman at Coca-Cola
headquarters declined to comment on the soft drink's secret
formula. By JOHN OTIS. (Already filed)
</P>
