<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUGHTS OF REPENTANCE AND COMMUNITY FOR YOM KIPPUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the nation's political leaders and the news
media preoccupied by the scandal involving President Clinton, words
like sin, repentance and forgiveness have flowed freely in
newscasts and political debate for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But one might ask if such words are being used superficially, or
is any thought given to them as profound religious concepts?
</P>
<P>
   The question seems appropriate given the imminence of a major
religious holiday, Yom Kippur, the Day of Atonement, which Jews
worldwide will begin observing on Tuesday at sundown.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief overview of the holy day, included in an edition of
the Yom Kippur prayer book published by Mesorah Publications Ltd.
of Brooklyn, Rabbi Nosson Scherman writes that sin, without
repentance, progressively diminishes a human being.
</P>
<P>
   ``It engenders within him an indifference to evil, a tolerance
for evil, an appetite for evil _ and, eventually, a distaste for
good,'' writes the rabbi, who is general editor of the company's
Artscroll series of religious books.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Friday, Scherman said the idea of the
personal decline that comes from repeated sinful acts was a major
theme in Jewish ethical thought. ``The Talmud,'' he said, referring
to Jewish oral law and tradition, ``says if somebody sins once, and
then repeats it, to him it becomes a permitted act. If you do it a
third time, it becomes a commandment.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, human beings have a way of rationalizing the
wrong they do. Rabbinic sages, he added, called that process ``the
insulation of the heart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So repentance is a process of stripping away that built-in
insulation,'' Scherman said. ``It doesn't come easy. It's a long,
hard process.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate interview, Rabbi Marc Schneier, president of the
New York Board of Rabbis, offered some other thoughts for the holy
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that during this penitential season, the Jewish
community comes before God,'' he said. This is not just an
individual process, he added. ``We are coming before God in a
communal judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneier's emphasis on the word `communal' is not surprising,
given that he and five other rabbis, representing the Reform,
Conservative and Orthodox movements within Judaism, had just
emerged Friday afternoon from a brief meeting with Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel, who was visiting New York.
</P>
<P>
   Since he became the organization's president in January, Rabbi
Schneier, who is Orthodox, has tried to point to the board of
rabbis (whose membership list, he said, includes more than 800
Orthodox, Conservative, Reform and Reconstructionist rabbis) as an
example of how Orthodox and non-Orthodox can cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   That idea has undergone enormous strain in the last two years, a
period when Orthodox and non-Orthodox leaders have fought verbally
over whether rabbis in Judaism's Reform and Conservative movements
should be allowed official recognition in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The two movements comprise the majority of religious Jews in the
United States, but are a small minority in Israel, where the
Orthodox have held official control of religious life (conducting
conversion ceremonies, performing weddings, granting divorces)
since the founding of the state 50 years ago. The non-Orthodox have
challenged this in the Israeli courts; the Orthodox, who have three
political parties, have responded with attempts to codify their
status in Israeli law.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the rhetoric of the debate, in both the United States
and Israel, has been deeply divisive.
</P>
<P>
   Schneier recalled that officers of the New York rabbinical board
met with Netanyahu in January, when the prime minister had said
that the board could try to be a model of cooperative relations
among rabbis across the spectrum of Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to minimize the conflict,'' Schneier said.
``I'm not trying to minimize the differences that do exist.'' He
said that examples of cooperation among Orthodox and non-Orthodox
rabbis in New York and other North American cities might be no more
than a drop in the bucket, but he wanted people at least to know
``that the drop exists.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken the position that before you can address sensitive
issues like conversions and divorce'' in Israel, he said, ``you
have to focus on Step One, and that's having lines of communication
and trust.''
</P>
</TEXT>
