<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS BRIEFS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe Pepsi Has a Job For a Dogged Coke Critic &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Albert J. Meyer, a mild-mannered accountant, gained fame in 1995
for leading investigators to what proved to be fraud of tens of
millions of dollars at New Era Philanthropy in Philadelphia. His
doggedness in uncovering that scam helped win Meyer a job at Martin
Capital Management, a small investment firm in Elkhart, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after Meyer, 47, used that same tenacity to go after
the accounting methods of Coca-Cola, he and the investment firm
have agreed to part ways.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's founder, Frank K. Martin, said that a factor in his
decision to distance the firm from Meyer's research was that
Coca-Cola was ``a pretty intimidating company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody was able to tell me that Coke wouldn't seek retribution
against our firm,'' Martin said. ``Nowhere in our mission statement
does it say that we should go after elephants with peashooters.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer and other critics say Coke and its giant bottling company
are in reality a single business and should consolidate their
financial statements. Coca-Cola, which disputes Meyer's research
and says it properly follows all accounting rules, says no one from
the company has called the investment firm to complain.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said he found it odd that Martin was even worried.
And Martin confirmed that he had not heard a peep from Coke.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, who sold his house in Elkhart this month and is
interviewing for various jobs, said he was not sorry that he wrote
papers criticizing the soft-drink giant's accounting. He said
investors needed a more complete picture of the company's
relationship with its largest bottler, Coca-Cola Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it for the public,'' he said. ``Some people appreciate
someone who is independent in his thinking and others don't.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Melody Petersen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doing a Number on the Boss &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During Robert Crandall's 18 years as maximum leader of American
Airlines, he was the most brilliant and feared executive in the
airline industry, known for his predawn staff meetings and
profanity-laden rebukes.
</P>
<P>
   But even the chain-smoking Crandall, who once likened airline
competition to war, had to put his pants on one leg at a time. And
when he opened his closet in the morning, he faced a rack of more
than a dozen nearly identical gray suits.
</P>
<P>
   How could he be sure that his trousers matched his jacket?
</P>
<P>
   Now that he has safely retired, Crandall's secret can be told.
His wife, Jan, carefully sewed a number into each of her husband's
jackets and trousers. With a quick peek, he could always be sure
that he was not heading to the battlefield wearing the pants from
Suit 2 with the jacket from Suit 5.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Crandall proudly pulled back his coat to
reveal the number 10 _ then stood up and turned down the top of his
trousers to show that, indeed, he had it right that day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Role Model for Us All &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the July 1 celebration of PricewaterhouseCooper's first day
as a merged firm, Rocco Maggiotto, the global leader of the firm's
financial services practice, received thunderous applause from the
roughly 4,500 people assembled.
</P>
<P>
   But they were not cheering Maggiotto for his role as host of the
event, a breakfast at Tavern on the Green in Manhattan, but because
he had chosen to skip it. As he explained in a telephone call
broadcast to the crowd that morning, he had to drive his
12-year-old son to summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The firm wants employees to make these kinds of judgment
calls,'' said Maggiotto, who shares the responsibility for his two
children with his wife, Kathleen Fisher, who works at a major
investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   And that wasn't some short-lived revolt against the corporate
grind. Just this month, Maggiotto bowed out of a dinner with the
firm's global management team to take his 8-year-old daughter on a
cruise around Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Reed Abelson &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sir, Your Room Is Not Quite Ready &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Top executives of Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide, based
in White Plains, appear to have rather fickle taste in housing.
When the chairman, Barry S. Sternlicht, moved to Greenwich, Conn.,
several years ago, he and his wife built a new house, abandoned the
project and then bought an existing house that ``unfortunately had
to be practically rebuilt,'' he wrote in the Harvard Business
School's 10-year reunion book from the class of 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his newly appointed chief executive and close friend from
business school, Richard D. Nanula, has bought a house in Greenwich
for $6 million, but is renting elsewhere until it is renovated.
Juergen Bartels, another Starwood executive, also bought a big
house in the same neighborhood recently, and he, too, is renting
until the contractors are finished with a makeover. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adam Bryant
</P>
</TEXT>
