<SLUG> BC-MA-NAACP-RENEWAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBLEMS PERSIST DESPITE REVAMP AT BOSTON NAACP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISA VALDES-RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In 1995, a state senate clerk named Leonard Alkins,
then 51, took charge of a sinking ship called the Boston branch of
the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   As the first regional outpost for the nation's oldest civil
rights organization, Boston's branch once served as the model for
hundreds to follow. But by 1995, it had been crippled with
mismanagement, infighting, and scandal. Leaders didn't pay national
dues. They broke national bylaws, and were removed from office. The
branch fell into receivership, and the Massachusetts Avenue
building was abandoned, the paint left to peel in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Now, three years after taking the helm, many say Alkins has done
the impossible: patched most of the leaks, and set the tarnished
tanker to sailing once again. National NAACP president and CEO
Kweisi Mfume will attend Boston's annual fundraising dinner at the
Marriott Hotel Saturday night _ a much-needed nod of approval.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there are others who say that continued low
membership numbers, poor resources, and lack of appeal to people
under 35 mark the growing irrelevance of Boston's NAACP, whose
founding missions _ desegregation and civil rights _ may hold less
significance for a new generation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Alkins has apparently resuscitated the branch,
attracting to it dozens of new members who had avoided it in the
past, the branch still has a long way to go to regain its former
glory.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston chapter has no office, no central phone answered by a
person, no web site, only 600 members _ a number that has remained
constant since the time of scandal _ and a youth chapter that seems
to shrink every year.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this comes as a suprise to those who have noticed the
NAACP local branch, and Alkins, appearing more in local news media
as sources.
</P>
<P>
   But in spite of Alkins's efforts to organize the group, and to
make public statements on everything from racial discrimination at
the MBTA to affirmative action, the branch still lacks basic
resources. Chapter files are kept in boxes at Alkins's Brockton
home, and phone calls are picked up by a voice mail system he
monitors from his day job at the state house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really unfair,'' said Thomas F. Welch, a real estate
developer and new member. ``One of the things we ought to do as
members is sit down with Lenny and staff the organization. Right
now he is the staff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the organization in his heart,'' said Darryl Settles,
restaurant owner and new member. ``But it hasn't been easy.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties stem in part from a lack of members and a lack
of funding, Alkins explained.
</P>
<P>
   Money remains short because donations to the local branch, a
501c4 nonprofit, are not tax-deductible. Donations to the national
branch, a 501c3 nonprofit, are tax-deductible. Because of this,
about 70 percent of money made from fundraising in Boston goes to
the national headquarters in Baltimore, Alkins said.
</P>
<P>
   But membership is an even more important issue. Even with new
recruits, the numbers are not growing. And among young people,
vital for survival of the branch, membership is shrinking, a fact
that Alkins says ``pains me more than any other.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Warren, a professor of economics and politics at
Northeastern University, and one of the dozens of members to join
since Alkins took over the Boston branch, says he thinks the
organization simply may not be relevant to young people anymore,
and must change its focus to include them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NAACP has a history of civil rights, we've defined it
narrowly in the past,'' Warren said. ``We wanted equal rights. We
wanted not to be segregated. It seems to me that's been
accomplished. We're no longer segregated in an absolute sense.
We've accomplished our mission as far as young people are
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   But interviews with several teens in the Boston area showed that
issues of segregation and racism are alive and well for them.
However, many of them simply did not know what the NAACP stands
for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that the thing about the movie?'' asked Kelly Excellus, 14,
an 8th grader. Excellus also said she believed she had been denied
an after-school job this year because she was black, but felt
powerless to do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   Tareesha Burton, 16 and a sophmore, said she knew about the
NAACP but said she had no interest in joining. ``Most people are
racist, and you can't change 85 percent of them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Burton had learned about the NAACP from television when she saw
the NAACP Image Awards, which air on Black Entertainment Television
Saturday night. The national branch is trying to attract youth. The
show is co-hosted by actress Vanessa Williams and features the
trendy, turbaned singer Erykah Badu.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to figure out how to appeal to younger people,''
said Warren. ``We need to define civil rights in a broader sense,
because young people aren't going to join anything as amorphous as
we are right now. What Lenny has been doing with us these last
couple of years is try to redefine the mission statement. It's
happening, but slowly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
