<SLUG> BC-RIDERS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ENVIRONMENTAL 'RIDERS' CLING TO APPROPRIATIONS BILLS
 &HT;    700&AMP;optional trim. With RIDERS-DATA.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - As Congress moves closer to its planned fall recess
without having passed funding bills for most of the government, a
showdown struggle is shaping up over environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   That's because many of the must-pass appropriations bills still
pending in the House and Senate contain amendments - known as
``riders'' - that environmental groups contend would harm
wilderness areas, delay pollution cleanup and turn over valuable
resources to industries at bargain prices.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is scheduled to recess for the fall elections on Oct.
9. That day also marks the expiration of temporary legislation
funding nearly the entire government.
</P>
<P>
   Although environmental groups have obtained White House
commitments that President Clinton will veto bills that contain
particularly controversial riders, some fear that Clinton's
political problems in the Monica Lewinsky scandal could lead to an
unpredictable game of ``rider roulette'' between him and
congressional Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potentially, we see the environment emerge as the focal point
of a major dispute over whether they're going to keep the
government open or not,'' said Greg Whetstone, a lobbyist for the
Natural Resources Defense Council, an environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   The standoff Whetstone and others fear could develop if
congressional Republicans decide to lump appropriations for several
different agencies into a single omnibus bill that included the
environmental riders, then recess and leave town.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave Clinton the choice of signing the bill or
vetoing it and shutting down a large part of the government until
members of Congress returned and either overrode the veto or passed
a different bill.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13 separate appropriations bills that must be enacted to
keep the government running, only one - providing funds for
military construction - had been signed into law by President
Clinton by Friday. The rest were still awaiting approval by
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative affairs specialists with environmental organizations
have counted 57 separate environmental riders, affecting everything
from logging practices to global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Provisions attached to appropriations bills by Alaska's two
senators and lone House member would protect illegal commercial
fishing in Glacier Bay National Park, require construction of
controversial roads through wilderness areas, impede parkland
acquisition in Alaska, speed up logging in the Tongass National
Forest and give up to 500,000 acres of federal land to the
University of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Another rider would delay efforts by the Interior Department to
require companies that mine for gold and other metals and minerals
on federal lands to meet new environmental standards, including
paying to restore damage to natural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Still another would delay an increase in royalties paid by oil
companies for oil taken from federal land.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, author of the royalty rider,
said the Interior Department was trying to a rewrite federal law
that spells out how oil company royalties are to be calculated at a
time when crude oil prices are at a 20-year low.
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim for papers using the accompanying data
box.)
</P>
<P>
   A House amendment to the bill that provides funds for the
Departments of Veterans Affairs and Housing and Urban Development
would prohibit the use of federal funds to reduce the ``greenhouse
gases'' believed responsible for global warming until the Senate
has ratified the Kyoto Protocol on climate change.
</P>
<P>
   Another rider would prohibit use of federal funds to encourage
developing countries to meet the provisions of the Kyoto Protocol,
even though provisions of the protocol giving those countries more
time to comply have been a chief reason for opposition to it in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   A House rider would delay Environmental Protection Agency
regulations aimed at curbing mercury in air pollution from power
plants, opposed by the electric power industry. Another would block
plans to reintroduce grizzly bears to wilderness areas in Idaho and
Montana. Another would make it easier for developers to build on
fragile barrier islands in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A rider would prevent the U.S. Forest Service from raising the
rent it charges celebrities such as actor Bruce Willis for vacation
cottages in Sawtooth National Forest, Idaho. After the General
Accounting Office revealed that some wealthy leaseholders were
paying the government as little as $156 a year, the Forest Service
set out to increase the rent to as much as $28,125 a year.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The National Environmental Trust charged Friday that the
Interior Department appropriations bill alone was loaded with
``lobbyist-written taxpayer rip-offs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The smart thing for Congress to do would be to pass a
continuing resolution to keep the government in operation and head
for the hills,'' said Whetstone of the National Resources Defense
Council. ``But there are powerful voices over there, especially in
the Senate leadership, that want to take advantage of the
president's problems because they think he won't shut down the
government .''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Francis of the Wilderness Society said he was afraid
White House lobbyists will negotiate away many of the riders and
Clinton will then sign an omnibus bill containing others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be some issues the White House will compromise on
and some the Republicans will drop for now,'' Francis said. ``If
that happens, the chances of us getting a veto are somewhere
between slim and none.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
