<SLUG> BC-ORE-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON WELCOMED BY OREGON DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ The Oregon Democrats running for governor and
Congress haven't disguised their views of President Clinton: They
support his policies, condemn his adultery, and prefer that he stay
in Washington rather than campaign for them.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, however, they made it equally clear that their opinion
of Hillary Rodham Clinton is quite different.
</P>
<P>
   At the first lady's appearances for three Democratic candidates
here, the scandal afflicting the president not only had not
undermined his wife's political effectiveness, it had turned her
into an even bigger draw as the November elections approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because his public presence has been tainted greatly, she's
going to have to step up to the plate and do more,'' Janna Loper,
an official with a state agency called Children First for Oregon,
said after hearing Mrs. Clinton speak Friday morning. ``I have to
admit I didn't expect much before she began ... but now I know she
can rise above it all and be very effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has always been a skilled public speaker and campaigner,
able to rouse an audience _ especially the women in it _ about as
well as her husband can.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the president all but housebound by Democrats
nationwide afraid he'll do them more harm than good (except perhaps
as a fund-raiser), the campaign spotlight is effectively turning
onto Vice President Al Gore and Hillary Clinton. And to many
Democratic candidates, the first lady is the first choice, because
she can point to the administration's accomplishments without being
blamed for the affair that has tarnished her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the rank-and-file Democrats interviewed before and after
Clinton's appearances here Friday said that, if anything, she has
become a more sympathetic and appealing figure as a result of the
Monica S. Lewinsky controversy. ``She the one who was cheated on,
but she's still so dignified, so articulate, and so strong. It's
very impressive,'' said Libby Upham, a writer for a local
television station's web page.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for Clinton's apparent ascent to campaigner-in-chief
have been on display this week on a bicoastal tour for candidates
from New York to Oregon. She has drawn big crowds and standing
ovations at each stop, and has raised hudreds of thousands of
dollars for Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In Oregon Friday, she started with a rousing speech on behalf of
congressional hopeful David Wu at a child-care forum at Portland
State University. Then she rode down the street for a $250-a-plate
luncheon for Wu and, at the same hotel, private meet-and-greet
sessions at which supporters of Governor John Kitzhaber and US
Representative Darlene Hooley contributed to their re-election
efforts by paying $500 to $1,000 each to get their pictures taken
with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Clinton flew to San Francisco to meet up with the
president and make the final campaign appearance of her current
tour. Aides said she would maintain a full schedule of speeches and
fund-raisers until November.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tailors her message at every stop to address the central
issues of the campaign she's trying to promote, and takes aim at
her favored candidates' Republican opponents. She invariably
stresses, however, widespread Democratic concerns that the Lewinsky
scandal will help the GOP by keeping Democrats away from the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do everything you can to make sure that everyone you know
turns out on election day,'' she said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the Democratic candidates here have expressed their
preference that the president not campaign for them, asserting that
the public and the press would be so focused on the Lewinsky
scandal that their own concerns wouldn't get through. Hillary
Clinton, on the other hand, wasn't asked once about her husband's
travails Friday.
</P>
<P>
   She did make one fleeting reference to Republicans' continuing
discussions about whether to start impeachment hearings against the
president. And she did so to take a partisan shot, her voice laced
with sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get them to focus on education,'' Clinton told
about 200 listeners at the Wu luncheon, who had greeted her with a
sustained standing ovation and whoops of support. ``They were busy
doing other things of grave concern to our country.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hillary Clinton's obvious popularity among the Democratic
faithful hasn't kept detractors away in each city she has visited.
But there weren't many on the streets of this Democratic stronghold
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a dozen protesters, carrying signs calling for the
president's impeachment and telling voters ``Don't let Hillary Wu
you,'' marched outside the hotel where Clinton was speaking.
</P>
<P>
   One demonstrator, Pat Sharp, said she drove 90 miles from the
town of Albany to make sure people understand ``that there are
mothers and grandmothers, like me, who disapprove of Hillary's
behavior, too.'' Sharp, a hairstylist, said Clinton should have
publicly chastised the president when she learned he had engaged in
an affair with an intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``She could have come out and said, `He's my husband and I love
him, but his behavior's deplorable,'' said Sharp. ``Now, not having
done that, how can she look her daughter in the face ... when she
knows what her dad has done?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
