<HEADER>
A5324 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JONES-NYT &LR;      09-25 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND JONES NEGOTIATIONS CONTINUE; AGREEMENT COULD BE NEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for Paula Jones and for President Clinton
on Friday appeared close to an agreement to settle the sexual
misconduct lawsuit, which has led to the impeachment crisis
confronting Clinton, advisers to both parties said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Mrs. Jones' lawyers rejected a $500,000 offer Clinton
made this week to have her withdraw her lawsuit, and they gave the
White House until Tuesday morning to sweeten the pot, the advisers
said. Earlier this month, the White House rejected a request from
the Jones camp to pay $1 million to settle the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House adviser said that the suddenly vigorous
effort to put an end to the lawsuit was being propelled by a
political calculation that to do so would help Clinton present the
best possible case to Congress to battle any impeachment
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, one of the staunchest opponents to any kind of
concession to Mrs. Jones _ Hillary Rodham Clinton _ has now acceded
to the idea of a settlement, Clinton associates say.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement, which appeared elusive for years, is a strong
possibility now, because of the profoundly changed political _ and
some would moral _ standing of Clinton since he publicly
acknowledged a sexual liaison with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   That is a major reason Mrs. Jones lawyers say she has dropped
her demand that any settlement include some sort of apology from
the president or some explicit acknowledgment that her claim about
Clinton's behavior was true. Her previous insistence on an apology
had always proved an insurmountable obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones' advisers say she no longer feels a need to prove
that Clinton behaves in a sexually irresponsible manner, given the
avalanche of detailed material about his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The events of the last several weeks and months have
vindicated Paula Jones' case,'' said John W. Whitehead, the
president of the Rutherford Institute, which is funding Mrs. Jones'
legal efforts. He said that any settlement from the president would
constitute an admission of Mrs. Jones' allegations, if not an
apology. Mrs. Jones contended that in 1991, when Clinton was
governor of Arkansas, he invited her to his hotel suite in Little
Rock, and when alone with her, made a crude sexual advance. Clinton
has always denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead said that he was hopeful a settlement would be
reached, but he cautioned that the talks could still fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   Senior White House officials expressed a similar mix of hope and
caution. The advisers said that Mrs. Clinton had only recently been
persuaded to allow negotiations aimed at settling the lawsuit after
firmly resisting such a course since the beginning because that
could be taken as evidence of wrongdoing. One aide said that Mrs.
Clinton, who has been deeply anxious over mounting legal bills, had
to be assured that the money for a settlement could come out of the
legal defense fund that has been created for the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, one adviser to the Clintons said, there is a
feeling that a settlement would not affect the president's standing
with the public, which has already taken that part of his character
into account in digesting the Starr report about his liaison with
Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we go before Congress on the impeachment matter, the Paula
Jones suit is now still on the table,'' said a Clinton adviser, who
spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Anything we take off the table
may be enormously helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Mrs. Jones said she is eager to reach a settlement
and be done with the matter. Another incentive for her is that if
the appeals court does not reinstate the case, she would get
nothing after four years of high-profile litigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
