<HEADER>
A5325 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLO-SAILING-MEDICINE     09-25 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLO-SAILING-MEDICINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRM PROVIDES EMERGENCY AID DURING SOLO YACHT RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the last around-the-world solo sailboat race, Mark
Schrader packed a finger-amputating device in his first-aid kit so
he could discard a crushed digit then get on with the racing.
</P>
<P>
   Not until he was far at sea did it occur to Schrader that the
stainless steel device, given to him by a doctor, required two
hands in good working order to manipulate the amputation levers.
Bad medical planning, concluded Schrader.
</P>
<P>
   He has since become director of the 27,000-mile Around Alone
race departing Saturday from Charleston, S.C., and this is partly
why Schrader has hired physicians from WorldClinic Inc., based in
Boston, to coordinate medical care for the 16 competitors about to
embark on one of the most gruelling, fatiguing, solo sailing
competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advances in technology have made it easier not only to send
distress calls around the world, but also deliver medical help by
remote control,'' said Schrader, director of a race that, because
of the storms it encounters, has been likened to riding the spin
cycle of a clothes washer. Consider, for example, that the boats
will sail in the shadow of Hurricane Georges and are on a collision
course with three other hurricanes and two tropical depressions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it. Health happens when you're 60 days from land,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1982, this race _ formerly known as the BOC Challenge _
has been run every four years, claiming more than a dozen boats and
the lives of two sailors. The tally does not include contestants
such as the late Mike Plant of Jamestown, R.I., who died alone
trying to get to the start of the 1992 race when his boat
apparently flipped.
</P>
<P>
   Around Alone is a race where small lacerations, bruises, and
infections can quickly become big problems. For example, during the
1986-1987 contest, Pentti Salmi, a Finnish sailor, mildly scraped
his arm on a barnacle. Within days, an allergic reaction swelled
his arm to the thickness of his thigh. Fever-ridden and far at sea
with a useless, pain-throbbing arm, Salmi could not trim sails or
take down his spinnaker.
</P>
<P>
   It so happened that another sailor, Jean Luc Van den Heede of
France, was several hours ahead, the needed medicine and syringe in
his first aid kit. But the men, struggling to communicate by radio,
had difficulty developing a transfer and useage plan because
neither spoke the other's language.
</P>
<P>
   They eventually worked out a strategy: The Frenchman stalled
long enough for the ailing Finn to catch up. When the Finn careened
past, spinnaker flying, the Frenchman threw the medicine and
syringe across to his boat.
</P>
<P>
   The package was wrapped in a Playboy Magazine centerfold. A red
``X'' on her anatomy marked the proper spot for the shot.
</P>
<P>
   Race organizers have concluded there is a better way to deal
with medical emergencies for solo sailors at sea. Enter
WorldClinic.
</P>
<P>
   Incorporated last spring, WorldClinic has cornered a niche
market on the Seven Seas, combining pre-race medical evaluations
with state of the art FAX, E-mail and satellite telephone
communication technology. Now, for instance, a racer will be able
to wash and suture his or her wounds using digitized photographs
and instructions dispensed from Dr. Daniel Carlin's office at New
England Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin concedes there may be better ways to deliver health care;
then again, there are probably better ways than riding 50-foot
waves through a southern gale to see the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not your normal hospital walk-ins,'' Carlin pointed
out. These clients clean and stitch first, then tend to sails,
then, if time permits, deal with the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``With computers, we can move very specific, high quality
medical information and graphics back and forth to patients very
far away,'' Carlin said. ``They no longer need to set sail with a
copy of Grey's Anatomy.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlin's partner is Dr. Ronald Ruffing, who, similar to Carlin,
is affiliated with the New England Medical Center's Division of
Geographic Medicine and Infectious Disease; Dr. Davidson Hamer,
director of the division's Traveler's Health Service, consults for
WorldClinic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; They work in an office where pins and tiny flags in a
wall-sized world map indicate the location of about 25 clients
(mostly sailors, with a few landlocked contractors sprinkled in)
and the nearest hospitals should an emergency arise.
</P>
<P>
   WorldClinic charges anywhere from $500 to $1,500 annually for
its 24-hour-a-day consulting service. Generally, the higher the
health risk, the steeper the fee. Indeed, knowing a client's
medical history, gleaned from medical screenings the likes of which
Around Alone sailors experienced earlier this week in Charleston,
is key to early diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   For example, not long ago a client and her husband were sailing
across the Caribbean Sea when she began to suffer an earache. She
had been swimming, and Carlin surmised from an earlier examination
that because she had a small ear canal, salt water had created an
infection that probably would lead to deafness or worse if the
problem was not addressed immediately. There was already temporary
hearing loss. The client was hundreds of miles from the nearest
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Via the internet, Carlin located, then transmitted, an image of
the inner ear that, coupled with his instructions on a satellite
telephone, allowed the sailor's husband to perform the minor
surgery required to relieve the pressure, save her hearing _ and
perhaps her sanity from the pain.
</P>
<P>
   The Around Alone competitors are scheduled to sail with medical
kits prepared by WorldClinic. Equipment includes skin staplers
(taking the place of sutures), staple removers, allergy and
antibiotics medications, and nitroglycerine tablets for symtoms of
angina, to name a few. Some racers are taking a variety of straps
and harnesses to suspend themselves from parts of their boats
should they need to reset a dislocated joint. It's not a race for
the queasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least there are no more finger saws,'' said Schrader. ``Now
the sailor just dials direct, rigs up the speakerphone, and follows
the doctor's orders.'' Hopefully with all fingers functional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
