<HEADER>
A5331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENYA-BOMBING-ART-NYT     09-25 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENYA-BOMBING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI FOCUSING BOMB SEARCH ON HOUSE NEAR NAIROBI 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUNDA, Kenya _ As FBI agents continue their investigation into
the bombing last month of the U.S. Embassy in Kenya, they have
returned to a fashionable, two-story white house with a red tile
roof in this Nairobi suburb, which they combed over after the first
suspects were captured.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday agents walked around the back yard and examined the
two-car garage, talking among themselves about whether it was large
enough for a pickup truck, people who were present said Friday.
Small trucks were used in the embassy bombing in Nairobi and the
one in Tanzania on the same day, according to the indictments
handed down in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is intensely interested in the house because in the
weeks before the bombing, the tenant was one Haroun Fazil,
according to neighbors and the landlady. Fazil, a citizen of the
Comoros, has been charged with having orchestrated the Aug. 7
bombing here, which killed 258 people, including 12 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment of Fazil says that he operated out of a ``villa
in the vicinity of Nairobi,'' and that it was in the villa that the
bomb was built. The indictment does not further identify the villa,
but it is in New Runda Estates, a 5-year-old development on the
edge of Karura Forest about eight miles north of the U.S. Embassy
in downtown Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who live in the 243 houses are expatriates,
working for various agencies of the United Nations, which has its
compound on the other side of the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by his accounts of his activities at the house in the
week of the bombing, Fazil is a man with proverbial nerves of
steel. Two days after driving away with his wife and family, he
apparently used the same vehicle to lead the bomb-laden vehicle to
the embassy. Then after the attack he returned to supervise the
cleaning of the house, which had little in it, except for a
television set.
</P>
<P>
   But the house, with hardwood floors and a family room that opens
through sliding glass doors to a well-kept garden, may not have
been cleaned well enough. The FBI found ``large amounts of gray
powder,'' which is similar to aluminum powder used in bombs, the
indictment says.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said that young Arab-looking men came and went from
No. 43, and that two stayed in the servants' quarters _ two small,
concrete-floored rooms with tiny windows, behind the garage.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men was Mohamed Rashed Daoud Al-'Owhali, according to
neighbors who identified him from photographs that have appeared in
the newspapers and on television here. 'Owhali has been indicted in
connection with the bombing, and has admitted that he drove in the
vehicle carrying the bomb to the embassy, and then threw a grenade
at the guard before fleeing on foot.
</P>
<P>
   Fazil moved into the house in May, with his wife and their
4-year-old daughter and 2-year-old son, neighbors recalled. They
kept to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tended to hide,'' said Omega Wycliffe, the night watchman
at a property across the street, who said he had been interviewed
by the FBI. ``He refused to even let people stand there,'' he said,
pointing to the black gate, suspended between white pillars, which
opens on to the property. He said the mosque did not want people to
see his wife. She was fully covered in black, except for her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Fazil said his work was ``of the mosque,'' said John Simide, who
earned $4 a day as a gardener for Fazil. ``He didn't seem to want
anyone in the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Fazil drove a white Datsun pickup, neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   One day Fazil said to his gardener: ``I'm going. My work is
finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he loaded his wife, two children and ailing father-in-law
into the Datsun, drove down the short hill, turned right, right
again, up a hill and out of the suburb. That was Wednesday, Aug. 5,
Simide said.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later Fazil drove a white pickup truck toward the U.S.
Embassy, showing the way for the bomb-laden vehicle that followed,
according to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The blast at 10:30 that Friday morning was heard in New Runda,
though the residents had no idea what it was.
</P>
<P>
   By noon Fazil was back at the house and asked Simide to find a
woman to help clean the house.
</P>
<P>
   While the woman, Pauline Wambui, was sweeping and dusting, Fazil
turned on the television. The news had pictures of the carnage and
destruction downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ```It seems there was a bomb in town which destroyed buildings
and killed people,''' Simide recalled Fazil saying.
</P>
<P>
   Fazil said he did not have money to pay Simide. He gave him the
television.
</P>
<P>
   Then he got back in the white pickup and drove off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
