<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBE LOOKS GOOD TO RED SOX FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD TO CLEVELAND OR TEXAS _ Go, Tribe.
</P>
<P>
   This should be the mantra of Red Sox fans this weekend. Take a
good look at those standings, you citizens of Sox Nation. The
Rangers have been gaining like mad on the Indians and could wind up
being Boston's first-round playoff opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Trust me when I tell you that the Sons of Jimy Williams do not
want any part of the Texas Rangers right now.
On-the-road-to-Cleveland-or-Texas, I spent three days in California
watching the Rangers beat up the Angels and take their lunch money.
It was nasty stuff, an aggregate score of 25-3 _ on Anaheim's home
field. It was mildly reminiscent of when the Yankees savaged the
Red Sox four straight times (by a count of 42-9) at Fenway in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers went into Friday night's game at Seattle with a
four-game winning streak and eight victories in their last 10.
Texas leads the American League in hitting (.289) and ranks second
(to the Yankees) in runs. The pitching staff is coming around with
the addition of Todd Stottlemyre and a 20-game winner you've
probably never heard of (Rick Helling). They've got a proven World
Series closer in John Wetteland and their lineup features certain
American League MVP Juan Gonzalez, who has knocked in 157 runs,
plus Ivan Rodriguez, Will Clark, and Rusty Greer.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, the AL wild-card winner was a lock to play
Cleveland, but the Tribe got swept in New York and shut out by the
Twins Thursday night and carried a mere one-game lead over the
Indians into Friday night's action. If Cleveland and Texas finish
with the same record, Boston plays Texas because the Rangers won
their season series with the Tribe.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a good development. If you are a Red Sox fan, you
want Cleveland. Boston was 8-3 against the Indians this year but
only 6-5 against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox don't need any additional pressure in this postseason.
It's bad enough that they'll be lugging a major league-record
13-game postseason losing streak into Cleveland or Texas. The Sox
have not won a playoff or World Series game since Bruce Hurst beat
the Mets in Game 5 at Fenway in '86. Boston has not won since Bill
Buckner's error (speaking of Buckner, Chicago Cubs outfielder Brant
Brown _ the man who dropped the infamous fly ball Wednesday _ said,
``You can tag me all you want, but someone dropped a `Buckner' tag
on me, and I wasn't appreciative of that'').
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland is the way to go. The Indians will pitch Jaret Wright
and Dwight Gooden in the first two games of the playoffs. After
that, it's a jump ball for Tribe manager Mike Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
   While the Rangers are playing their best ball of the season and
the Indians sputter, the Red Sox have wobbled in the final month
(10-14 before Friday night). The ever-reliable Nomar Garciaparra
knocked in only three runs over a 20-game stretch and started
throwing the ball away (25 errors). Pedro Martinez yielded the Cy
Young trophy to Roger Clemens, losing three straight in September,
then giving up three homers in his final start. Mo Vaughn is still
a candidate to win the batting title, but he goes into the playoffs
with that 1995 Cleveland Doughnut (0 for 14, seven strikeouts)
hanging around his neck. The Sox are without a dependable No. 4
starter and there's concern that the Darren Lewis and Mike Benjamin
types have played over their heads too long already.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, it was premature to speculate on the playoff
opponent. Sox fans were concerned with clinching a playoff spot and
not paying much attention to whom Boston would play.
</P>
<P>
   But now it matters. A lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been paying attention,'' said Montreal coach Tommy
Harper, a Red Sox loyalist still. ``And it looks to me like Texas
is the team that nobody wants to play right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Go, Tribe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
