<SLUG> BC-FLU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flu vaccine: Get one soon to beat the bug
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- It's barely cool enough to think about wearing a
jacket, but once flu season arrives, it'll be too late to cover
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Influenza, a contagious and potentially deadly lung disease, can
be prevented by a yearly vaccination _ but you must be vaccinated
before mid-November, when the flu season starts.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, as part of a statewide immunization effort with the
American Lung Association, more than 1,000 health care providers
will offer flu vaccines. Some Kroger and CVS stores also will offer
shots.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. vaccine contains inactivated, noninfectious flu viruses
from three strains: the Harbin type B and two type A strains,
Beijing and Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Those allergic to eggs cannot receive the vaccine, since it is
made with eggs. Acutely ill people with fever should wait until
they recover to be vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
   To help counter historically low immunization rates among
African-American people 65 years and older, the Clark Atlanta
University Horizons Project is offering flu and pneumonia vaccines
from 10:30 a.m. to 1 p.m. today at Quality Living Services, 4001
Danforth Road in Atlanta. Those eligible should bring their
Medicare cards or numbers.
</P>
<P>
   For information about the Horizons immunization drive, call
404-880-6203.
</P>
<P>
   To find out about flu shot locations throughout the state, call
the American Lung Association at 1-800-586-4872 (LUNG-USA), or
check out the immunization site list on the Internet at
http://www.gmcf.org
</P>
<P>
   /stopflu.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
