<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZENGA LOOKS TO NEXT SEASON WITH FINAL GAME AGAINST METROSTARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Walter Zenga's five-game coaching career
began last month. Velibor ``Bora'' Milutinovic's 21-year coaching
career started in Mexico City and has taken him to teams in Africa,
Central and South America, Europe, and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Both Zenga and Milutinovic have made their reputations on the
world stage, in high-stakes competition, far from Foxboro Stadium,
where they will be matched on the final weekend of Major League
Soccer's third regular season.
</P>
<P>
   For Zenga's Revolution, Saturday night's meeting with the
MetroStars in their 1998 finale is a platform to launch them into
next season. For Milutinovic's MetroStars, this is a chance to
become acquainted with their new coach and to prepare them for
their playoff opener at Columbus Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, there is a sense of anticlimax about the match,
though a crowd of more than 20,000 is expected. The Revolution were
eliminated from playoff contention last week and are in last place,
2 points behind Tampa Bay, in the Eastern Conference. The
MetroStars clinched a playoff berth last month but lost six
successive games before firing coach Alfonso Mondelo.
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic's hiring was announced Monday, and his first
practice with the MetroStars was Tuesday. Though he has made his
reputation on the national team level _ he is the only coach to
have led four teams (Mexico, Costa Rica, the US, and Nigeria) past
the first round of the World Cup finals _ he has been less
successful with club teams in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   After a playing career in Yugoslavia, France, Switzerland, and
Mexico, Milutinovic used his coaching experience at UNAM Pumas in
Mexico City to vault him into the Mexican national team job for the
1986 World Cup. Mexico, playing at home, had its best tournament
under Milutinovic, advancing to the quarterfinals before losing on
penalty kicks to West Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic then had brief stops at Udinese in Italy and Velez
Sarsfeld in Argentina before returning to the international game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bora is one of the greats,'' Zenga said Friday. ``He really
deserves all the recognition he gets. In Italy, he is regarded as a
sort of mythical figure.''
</P>
<P>
   But Milutinovic's notoriety borders on novelty status at times.
He has had great accomplishments with small teams, exemplified by
his leading Costa Rica to two victories before second-round
elimination against Czechoslovakia in the 1990 World Cup in Italy.
Milutinovic was rightly admired for that, while Italy and Zenga
were vilified after a semifinal elimination by Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Milutinovic and Zenga last met in April 1997, when Milutinovic
coached Mexico in a 2-2 tie against the US in a World Cup qualifier
and Zenga was playing for the Revolution at Foxboro Stadium. Then
Milutinovic seemed split in his allegiances, since he had coached
many of the US players from 1991-95, and he was being treated as a
lame duck by many in the Mexican federation. Several of his former
players will be involved in Saturday night's match, including the
Revolution's Mike Burns, Damian, and Joe-Max Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bora is a great motivator,'' Damian said. ``When I was playing
for Mexico, I had not seen my family for about a year. He showed us
a film before the game of my mother saying she missed me and good
luck in the game. That's the kind of thing that makes you want to
jump right out onto the field and give everything you've got and
more.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have 29 points, 4 fewer than in their first
season ... Midfielder Ivan McKinley is doubtful with a right knee
strain ... Eduardo Hurtado, the MetroStars' Ecuadoran
international, is out with a broken nose.
</P>
</TEXT>
