<HEADER>
A5339 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAYINN-COX     09-25 0334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAYINN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holiday Inn owners told of need to improve
 &HT;    By Shelia Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Thousands of hotel owners and operators got a pat
on the back and a stern lecture Friday on the need to continue to
improve.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas R. Oliver, chairman and chief executive officer of Bass
Hotels &AMP; Resorts, the parent company of Dunwoody-based Holiday Inn,
said its aggressive eight-year push to improve quality and customer
service was on target but franchisees can not afford to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition is intensifying,'' Oliver said at the Bass Hotels
&AMP; Resorts worldwide conference. ``We're all running harder for
fewer dollars, pounds and yen.''
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 hotel owners and operators attended the conference.
Bass acquired Holiday Inn in 1990. Its brands include Holiday Inn,
Holiday Inn Express, Crowne Plaza and Inter-Continental.
</P>
<P>
   In order to become more competitive, Holiday Inn, which ranked
as one of the lowest rated mid-priced hotels in a Consumer Reports
survey recently, is in the midst of an aggressive improvement
program. Franchisees have been told they must meet higher standards
_ or else.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, about 100 hotels closed because they failed to
meet the new standards, and 600 Holiday Inns have been renovated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Oliver is right on track,'' Emerson Hoffman of the Natala
Corp. in Tifton, Ga., which owns two Holiday Inns in Georgia. ``I
think we have given this business to our competitors with our own
deficiencies. I think Bass is committed to regaining the market
share that we've lost over the last 15 to 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Patel, who owns a Holiday Inn Express in Lexington, S.C.,
agreed. ``They're giving the older, tired-looking properties a
fresh look. Every dollar they invest, they get back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass is launching its new extended stay brand, Staybridge
Suites. The first will open in Alpharetta in November.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
