<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5342 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-BOZZOTTO-BOS &LR;      09-25 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BOZZOTTO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-UNION LEADER FACES CHARGE IN UNUSUAL CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RIC KAHN   AND STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Captured by a surveillance camera this month, the image
was bizarre and unsettling: A middle-aged balding man in a business
suit casting furtive glances, darting between pay phones, his hand
tapping the receiver but his lips never moving _ at least when the
camera catches his face.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the person who believes he received almost 700 crank calls
from that man claims he has unmasked the caller seen driving away
from those phone banks in a blue Massachusetts Turnpike Authority
Taurus with the number 98 license plate. It is, he contends, none
other than Domenic Bozzotto, the legendary former bearded boss of
the Boston hotel workers union who is now a clean-shaven Mass Pike
manager with a company car.
</P>
<P>
   Bozzotto, 58, denies making the harassing phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   For almost two decades Bozzotto had nurtured a mystique of a
working-class streetfighter battling corporate kings; a militant
merry prankster ready to brandish baseball bats against scabs or,
according to one memorable allegation, unleash rodents in hotels to
bring home higher wages to the maids who toiled in the ``back of
the house'' of Boston's hotels.
</P>
<P>
   But now the would-be leaders of Local 26, once hailed for aiming
daggers at hotel management's jugular, are at each other's throats.
</P>
<P>
   The man pointing fingers at Bozzotto, it turns out, is not a
hotel owner but a fellow hotel worker _ a fresh-faced 35-year-old
waiter named Andrew McLeod, who is running his second insurgent
race for president of Local 26 against Bozzotto's protege. McLeod's
charges recast Bozzotto from a lion of the labor movement to a
snake turning on one of his own; an immigrant workers' demigod
reduced to making prank calls to a longshot candidate who
questioned Bozzotto's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   In filing a harassment complaint that will be heard next month
in Boston Municipal Court, which may decide whether McLeod's tape
is part of an elaborate hoax or a ``gotcha'' video, McLeod has
positioned himself as a Bozzotto of the '90s, a young reformer with
multicultural connections railing against an entrenched union
leadership he accuses of mismanagement and using dirty tricks to
stifle dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pathetic,'' says McLeod.
</P>
<P>
   During the '80s, Bozzotto created an image as the radical bad
boy of Boston's labor movement. Using high-profile, high-pressure
tactics, he took up the cause of immigrant hotel workers in the
back of the house with the same fervor of civil-rights activists
fighting for those forced to ride the back of the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Taking to the manicured front lawns of hotel owners with raucus
picketers, Bozzotto won for underclass workers a host of benefits,
from higher wages to an education fund, and a landmark
affordable-housing trust.
</P>
<P>
   By the early '90s, however, Bozzotto found himself further
isolated on the fringes of labor's frontier, shunned by labor
progressives who accused him of selling out by supporting the hotly
contested 1990 tax rollback petition and embracing Republican
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bozzotto made good on his long-stated intention to
leave Local 26, but not before guiding his hand-picked successor,
Janice Loux, to a resounding victory over McLeod 749-146.
</P>
<P>
   Now, McLeod is again challenging Loux in a spring election, and
seems intent on taking down the presumed power behind the throne,
accusing the man who walked the streets of solidarity with Cesar
Chavezcq of launching phoney phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Ludicrous, say Bozzotto backers, who portray McLeod as a tool of
old-guard ``front of the house'' waitresses and doormen, a
candidate trying to build a name by tearing down Bozzotto's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's irrelevant,'' said Bruce Marks, a former Bozzotto aide,
of McLeod. ``He's not a threat to anybody but himself.''
</P>
<P>
   From his downtown office as the turnpike authority's
$75,000-a-year director of employee relations, Bozzotto denies
McLeod's allegations, saying he doesn't even know his home phone
number.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of it is true,'' he said. ``There will be a hearing and
we'll show that.''
</P>
<P>
   And he derides McLeod as unworthy of his wrath, saying: ``I have
not harassed this kid, there's no need to harass this kid. He lost
8-to-1.''
</P>
<P>
   But, others say, perhaps McLeod's allegations of union
mismanagement _ from questions about pensions and retirement plans
to whether membership numbers have been inflated _ just got under
Bozzotto's skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's true, it's the same old Bozzotto,'' said Joseph
Faherty, former president of the Massachusetts AFL-CIO. ``It's the
same tactics. This time he's just turning it around against his own
cause _ what used to be his cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Festa, a onetime Bozzotto ally in Local 26 turned foe, said
once a union gets accustomed to using strong-arm tactics, it's hard
to let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you disagree with Domenic, &UR;  &LR; that's the end of you,'' said
Festa, 62, who claimed that after her falling out with Bozzotto her
phone would ring all night, and her car was vandalized with
Superglue.
</P>
<P>
   Bozzotto acknowledges he could well be the man on McLeod's
video, the one seen making calls outside the Walk Hill Market near
his home in Boston's Hyde Park section and then hopping into a car
with his Pike license plate. After all, Bozzotto said, he routinely
buys lottery tickets and uses public phones there to conduct family
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a car phone and don't have a cellular phone,'' he
said. ``I make pay phone calls.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bozzotto flatly rejects McLeod's charges of mismanagement,
saying the union's many enemies would have produced an indictment
already if there was any hint of financial wrongdoing. Loux did not
return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's just trying to neutralize my ability to campaign
for her,'' Bozzotto said.
</P>
<P>
   And he denounces the dirty-trickster label. ``We reveled in
being tough, taking no quarter,'' he said. ``We never reveled in
being underhanded or shadowy....In your face between the eyes is
not dirty tricks. Organizing the workers to use their strengths for
winning benefits is not dirty tricks.''
</P>
<P>
   But, McLeod says, this may be: Inundating his home with
unsolicited CDs and magazine subscriptions, and making 683 phone
calls to his home since June. The caller never spoke, said McLeod,
but made unintelligible noises that sounded like scraping and
sawing. ``Trying to wear me down,'' said McLeod.
</P>
<P>
   But the faster the calls came, McLeod said, the harder he
campaigned. ``It's a Tao philosophy,'' he said. ``You take the
energy being given to you, and instead of fighting it, you go with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   McLeod said he traced the calls, taped and timed the messages,
and dispatched a private investigator with a video camera to a
cluster of phones in the city's Jamaica Plain section.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 8, McLeod said, he got a suspicious call at home and
alerted the private eye. Hidden behind tinted glass, the video
camera captured the image of a man making a call from one phone,
walking 20 feet and making two more calls from a second phone, and
then driving two blocks to a third phone.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod said his caller ID traced the incoming calls to those
same phones.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as he watches the video roll from his tiny TV, McLeod's
anger grows, his polite speech turning profane.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the man,'' he shouts, mouthing allegations of
skullduggery that linger over Local 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going forward, we're going to change the union,'' he
adds, his voice rising. ``I'm going to be a fighter. This should be
a lesson to anybody not to fool with us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
