<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKHEED-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More jet orders may give lift to Lockheed
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The chief executive of Lockheed Martin Corp. picked a
good day to visit the company's Marietta plant and ride on the new
and improved C-130J cargo plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a wonderful experience,'' Vance D. Coffman, chairman
and CEO of Bethesda, Md.-based Lockheed Martin, said Friday after a
40-minute flight in which he got a pilot's-eye view.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet for the Marietta plant was news that Congress may add
six C-130Js worth $482 million to the defense spending bill for the
upcoming fiscal year. The Clinton administration had asked for one
C-130J.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate negotiators agreed on the boost to speed
replacement of aging models, Bloomberg News reported. The bill
isn't yet final, but totals rarely change after joint negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The seven additional planes would lift C-130J orders from 83 to
90, with 34 by the U.S. military. Lockheed Martin developed the
updated plane, which features new engines and cockpit technology,
at its own expense.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration certified the model just
this month after several delays. The Marietta plant is producing
about two C-130Js a month but could boost that rate as orders
warrant.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional negotiators also voted to spend $771 million to
continue Lockheed Martin's F-22 fighter program, only $14 million
less than requested. Final assembly of the F-22 is done in
Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Coffman, promoted to CEO in April, said he's confident those two
programs will remain on track and sustain the plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The C-130J is in demand around the world,'' he said. The
company took the plane on a world marketing tour earlier this year.
It has been asked by 28 countries to submit sales proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Coffman briefly flew the plane, with some enthusiastic coaching
from pilot Bob Price, director of flight operations at the Marietta
plant. Price demonstrated the rugged plane's short-takeoff
capability, lifting it off the Dobbins Air Force Base runway in
less than 1,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Price also showed how a new ``stick pusher'' system prevents
stalls, or loss of lift at low speeds. Computers sense imminent
stalls and automatically push the yoke forward to drop the nose and
regain speed and lift.
</P>
<P>
   After the flight, Coffman said Lockheed Martin may explore new
international aircraft alliances in the wake of its failed merger
attempt with Northrop Grumman.
</P>
<P>
   Under one rumored scenario, it might team with European jet
maker Airbus and make airliner parts in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some excess capacity here that could be productive,''
Coffman said. ``But it's speculation at this point, and we better
leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coffman also said he's confident Lockheed Martin will gain
regulatory approval for its $2.6 billion buyout of Comsat Corp., a
move to be a bigger player in satellite services. He said initial
negative investor reaction was due to ``misunderstanding'' of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The stock rebounded this week, closing Friday at $102.06 1/4, up
$3.56 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
