<SLUG> BC-TV-MARTIAL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MARTIAL LAW': MORE KUNG FU NONSENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM McDONALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If, as soldiers say, war consists of endless boredom punctuated
by moments of stark terror, ``Martial Law'' boils down to an hour
of tedium punctuated by frenzied bouts of kung fu fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The people at CBS who slapped this martial-arts show together
over the summer aren't asking that it be taken seriously, of
course; its silliness is by design. Indeed, the show hardly
pretends to know precisely what it is. ``A new comedy action
drama'' is how its producers bill it. ``Or whatever,'' they might
have added.
</P>
<P>
   But even taking ``Martial Law'' on its own mix-and-match terms,
one would hope for a good laugh under the ``comedy'' part of the
equation, or a bit of drama that seemed, well, dramatic. Alas, the
only inventiveness in this show is in its cartoon kung fu
choreography, exploding onto the screen every 12 minutes or so.
</P>
<P>
   Trading on the popularity of Hong Kong action films, ``Martial
Law'' has imported one of the genre's stars, the squat, 220-pound
Sammo Hung, for the lead role of Sammo Law. Sammo is a renowned
Shanghai detective who joins forces with the LAPD to troll the
Chinese-American underworld for his abducted and beautiful protege
(Kelly Hu). He's also a renowned, and rather cuddly, master of
martial arts given to dispensing aphorisms (``You don't break rocks
with eggs'') between body slams.
</P>
<P>
   The built-in joke, of course, is that Sammo's black belt is
about a size 44, affording cheap opportunities for giggling. And
predictably he gets the last laugh, proving time and again that
he's lighter on his feet than the stone-faced foes he likes to
thrash in sometimes hilarious and always acrobatic ways.
</P>
<P>
   Bodies do turn up, presumably to make good on the promise of
drama. But so does game show host Bob Barker, in a painfully lame
scene in the premiere episode in which Sammo winds up as a
contestant on ``The Price Is Right'' (on CBS, naturally; check your
local listings).
</P>
<P>
   Yet if ``Martial Law'' is clumsy when it isn't kick boxing, it's
clearly surefooted in going after the audience it wants. The tipoff
comes about six minutes into the premiere. After a spectacular kung
fu exhibition in a Shanghai den of thieves, the action shifts to
Los Angeles. Enter a gorgeous blonde (Tammy Lauren playing a police
detective). Kung fu and a major babe: what more could a teen-age
boy want?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MARTIAL LAW'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Saturdays on CBS
</P>
<P>
   Created and written by Carlton Cuse. Stanley Tong, director;
James Chressanthis, director of photography. Music by Mike Post.
Jack Clements, Pam Veasey, producers; Jeremy Littman, supervising
producer; Rick Husky, co-executive producer; Cuse, Stanley Tong and
Andre Morgan, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   With: Sammo Hung (Sammo Law), Tammy Lauren (Dana Dickson), Louis
Mandylor (Louis Malone), Tom Wright (Capt. Benjamin Winship), Kelly
Hu (Chen Pei Pei), Tzi Ma (Lee Hei), F.J. Rio (Det. Antonio
Valdez), Michele T. Carter (Officer Yates), Shawn Michael Howard
(Rickey Dukes), Mike Starr (Alex Portman), Dennis Bowen (Andy),
Sonya Eddy (Anne), Christine Ma (Mei Ling), Bob Barker (himself),
Rod Roddy (Announcer) and Ilia Volok (Sarkov).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
