A5358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-SAMPLING-NYT &LR;      09-25 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-SAMPLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND SETBACK FOR ADVOCATES OF CENSUS SAMPLING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Ga., Pa., N.J.)  (lb) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal judges in Virginia have dealt another
setback to the Clinton administration's plans to use statistical
sampling in the 2000 census, agreeing with judges in Washington
that use of the technique would be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   A special three-judge panel for the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, which heard arguments in Roanoke, Va., last month, ruled
unanimously on Thursday that sampling would violate a 1976 census
law. Judge Claude Hilton headed the panel, which included the
district judges Emory Widener Jr. and Raymond Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling was similar to one issued on Aug. 24 by a special
panel for the District of Columbia U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
The Supreme Court has agreed to take up the issue in its next term,
so the latest ruling means it will have two decisions to review.
</P>
<P>
   The wording in the 1976 law differed from that in earlier census
legislation, in a way that the plaintiffs argued was meant to
prohibit sampling. Agreeing, the Virginia court referred to Supreme
Court precedent that a statute must be construed ``in such fashion
that every word has some operative effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in the cases are similar and the issues almost
identical. The Virginia suit was brought by Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga.,
by a conservative Atlanta law firm, and by suburban counties in
Pennsylvania and New Jersey. The District of Columbia suit was
brought by Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   The administration wants to use sampling _ simply put, gauging
the characteristics of households that do not respond to census
queries based on the traits of those that do _ to avoid a
repetition of what happened in the 1990 census, which undercounted
the population by several million people.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those missed in the last census were city dwellers and
members of minorities. People who favor sampling contend that
because of the undercount, big cities were short-changed on federal
aid based on population. Some people have said sampling would work
in the Democrats' favor in the reapportioning of legislative
districts.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents of sampling have contended that it is not only
illegal but unconstitutional _ an issue the High Court has not
ruled upon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
