<HEADLINE>
SATURDAY'S KEY GAMES  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   No. 9 Washington (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 2 Nebraska (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska has been doing fine, and now quarterback Bobby Newcombe
and tailback DeAngelo Evans return from injuries. The Huskers have
won 17 straight games overall, 44 straight at home. Their last home
loss was in 1991 _ to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   No. 18 Southern California (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 10 Florida State (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   Chris Weinke, Florida State's 26-year-old quarterback, righted
himself and passed for 241 yards in trouncing Duke. Southern
California has fattened up against mediocre teams and struggled
against Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 8 Florida (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   Florida can't settle on a quarterback and its turnover ratio
(minus 10) is 112th and last in Division I-A, but it should still
win. Kentucky, on Tim Couch's passing, leads the nation in total
offense (572.7 yards a game).
</P>
<P>
   EAST
</P>
<P>
   Tulsa (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 19 West Virginia (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia has found potent passing to complement Amos
Zereoue's running.
</P>
<P>
   Army (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   at Rutgers (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers has lost 16 straight to I-A opponents. Army may run all
day.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   at Bucknell (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   Bucknell can run. So can Columbia, which beat Harvard on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   at Yale (1-0)
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's big-play defense should handle Yale's promising
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Grambling (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   vs. Hampton (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   at East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, with 13 straight regular-season victories, should win
this New York Urban League Classic game. Grambling, now coached by
Doug Williams, an old quarterback, needs a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH
</P>
<P>
   Houston (0-3)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 4 Tennessee (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee stopped Florida's offense with five sacks and minus 13
yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   No. 11 Virginia (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   at Duke (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   Virginia is struggling but winning. Duke has lost 18 straight
Atlantic Coast Conference games.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 21 Virginia Tech (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   Tech, the better team, is banged up. Pitt played Penn State
tough in a seven-point loss.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   at Louisville (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cloud of Boston College is averaging 184 yards rushing a
game, second best in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   MIDWEST
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 14 Wisconsin (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern beat Rice with a fake punt, an onside kick, a quick
kick, unusual formations and a hurry-up offense. This could be a
tight game.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 23 Notre Dame (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame has given up 923 yards to Michigan and Michigan
State. This should be easier.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   at Michigan (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   Two disappointing teams that won the last time out, State over
Notre Dame and Michigan over Eastern Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHWEST
</P>
<P>
   No. 22 Alabama (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   at Arkansas (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   Alabama has an imaginative offense and the nation's No. 2
rushing defense (allowing 36 yards a game).
</P>
<P>
   No. 23 Air Force (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   at Texas Christian (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   Blane Morgan is 13-2 as the starting quarterback in Air Force's
multiple-option offense.
</P>
<P>
   FAR WEST
</P>
<P>
   Baylor (1-1)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 15 Colorado (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's defense is sound, its rushing and pass protection
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford (1-2)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 20 Oregon (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   Oregon's two best running backs are hurt, but its passing should
win.
</P>
<P>
   MISMATCHES
</P>
<P>
   Northeast Louisiana (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 5 Kansas State (3-0)
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State is first in the nation in scoring (62.3 points a
game), second in total defense (183 yards a game).
</P>
<P>
   Idaho (2-1)
</P>
<P>
   at No. 6 Louisiana State (2-0)
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana State, although sometimes unsteady, can stop the run.
Idaho can't stop much.
</P>
