<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-PARTNERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFITS STILL LOOK GOOD FOR HEDGE FUND'S PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT, HEDGEFUND-IMPACT) 
(mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite the huge losses and shattered reputations
that have resulted from the near-collapse of Long-Term Capital
Management, the firm's 16 partners still appear to be sitting on
gains in their original investments in the hedge fund they managed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, for their work as portfolio managers of Long-Term
Capital Portfolio, as the hedge fund is formally known, the
partners of Long-Term Capital Management are likely to have
collectively earned hundreds of millions of dollars over the four
and a half years the fund has been operating.
</P>
<P>
   As representatives from a newly formed oversight committee of
outside investors begin picking through the wreckage, it remains
unclear which partners have taken money out of the firm and which,
having left their investments in both the hedge fund and the
management company intact, face further personal financial
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the huge paper profits, and breathtaking losses,
that flowed to John Meriwether and the firm's general partners is
almost too large to comprehend. In early 1994, a group of 10
general partners of Long-Term Capital Management collectively
contributed $100 million to the fund. The fund then raised another
$1.1 billion from outside investors, otherwise known as limited
partners. Later in 1994, the fund raised another $2 billion in
capital.
</P>
<P>
   That money was invested according to Long-Term Capital's arcane
computer-driven mathematical models, which produced a net profit of
nearly 20 percent in the partial first year, followed by full-year
profits of 43 percent, 41 percent and 17 percent in 1995 through
1997.
</P>
<P>
   By the beginning of this year, the value of the shares of the
fund owned by the general partners, who now number 16, had grown
from the original $100 million to $1.5 billion. Nearly all the
partners kept their entire stake invested in the fund, financial
executives say, forgoing the payout of profits that outside
investors were forced to take last year.
</P>
<P>
   But as the fund's investments went sour, the value of the
partners' stake has fallen to roughly $200 million _ a devastating
loss, but still representing an average individual gain of about 25
percent, to $12.5 million for each of the 16 partners from an
assumed original investment of $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, each partner is not likely to have kept exactly the
same amount in the fund. If some partners borrowed against the
value of their fund holdings at a time when their profits were
high, their debts might now far outstrip their remaining investment
profits.
</P>
<P>
   But investments in the fund were not the only source of
potential profits for partners at Long-Term Capital. Over the last
four and a half years, the company that managed the fund reaped an
estimated $2 billion in revenue from its annual management fee,
which equaled 2 percent of the fund's assets, and its 25 percent
share of the fund's gross investment profits.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that $2 billion went to pay salaries of the
approximately 170 nonpartner employees of Long-Term Capital, as
well as to buy computer systems, rent office space and pay
utilities and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also likely that a considerable chunk of that revenue
became net profits for the partners. Some of the most profitable
mutual fund companies, for example, earn net income equal to 25
percent of revenue _ a benchmark, which if matched by Long-Term
Capital would mean net profits to the 16 partners of $500 million,
or an average of more than $30 million apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the partners apparently took at least some of that money
out of the firm, but others left substantially all of it in or
borrowed against that which remained. The extent of that activity
is not known, but word spread on Wall Street Friday that more than
one upper-level executive at Long-Term Capital was facing possible
personal bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Rosenthal, a spokesman for the firm, declined to comment
on the rumors. ``But the one thing they all have,'' he said, ``is a
little bit of hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
