<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN ONCE IMPEACHED AS JUDGE IS CRITICAL OF STARR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (bl)  
 By CARL HULSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a lawyer and former federal judge, Rep. Alcee
Hastings has more than a passing familiarity with the Constitution.
And his reading tells him that Congress is badly mishandling the
impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   His real expertise in the subject comes not from arcane legal
theory and dusty law books but from unique personal experience _
the Florida Democrat is the only member of the House to have been
impeached himself. He was removed from the federal bench by the
Senate in 1989 on grounds of bribery and perjury and three years
later was elected to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as he joins his House colleagues in weighing the
impeachment of President Clinton, Hastings, 62, is trying to use
his familiarity with the process to protect Clinton from what he
sees as the same unfair system that led to his own judicial exile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great deal of experience in the process of
impeachment,'' said Hastings, who became Florida's first black
federal judge when he was appointed by President Jimmy Carter in
1979. ``I also have a great deal of experience in judging whether
or not prosecutors have committed prosecutorial misconduct. In this
instance, firmly I come down on the side affirmatively that he
has,'' he said, in reference to Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman said he has made no judgment on whether Clinton
should be impeached, only that Congress should be more measured in
its approach.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings' chief complaint is that Congress abdicated its
responsibility in the matter to Starr, relying too heavily on the
special counsel's findings, which he put forth in a 445-page report
delivered to Congress last week. Hastings likens the situation to
his own case, saying the House was swayed by an impeachment report
from a panel of 26 federal judges, an imprimatur of authority that
he said lawmakers were unable to resist.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings' first attack on Starr came in the form of a House
resolution to impeach the prosecutor for egregious misconduct,
including leaking grand jury material and ``wasting'' $40 million
on the investigation. It was quickly and overwhelmingly dismissed
by the House on Wednesday on a 340-71 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans were offended by the resolution and branded it
an outrage. But the failed attempt will not be Hastings' last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure he is going to proceed to deal with the
circumstances we are confronted with based on his experience,''
said Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., who chairs the Congressional
Black Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings was a rising judicial star when he was charged in 1981
with conspiracy to accept a $150,000 bribe in a criminal case he
was overseeing in Miami. He was acquitted by a jury two years later
although another lawyer, charged in the case as a co-conspirator,
was sent to jail. The alleged accomplice, accused of being the
go-between in the conspiracy, refused to testify against Hastings.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not the end for Hastings. In 1987, a panel of
federal judges delivered a 381-page report to Congress accusing him
of having committed the original crime as well as having lied about
his conduct during his defense.
</P>
<P>
   The House, including many members he now serves with, voted
413-3 to impeach him in 1988. The Senate, in a decision some
lawmakers said was agonizing due to Hastings' double jeopardy
argument, voted 69-26 for conviction, as Hastings, there to make an
appeal, watched.
</P>
<P>
   The ousted judge, who passionately maintained his innocence
throughout, found the experience surreal. ``There were times when I
was sitting there and it was as if I was talking about someone
else,'' Hastings said.
</P>
<P>
   A hero in the black community for his persistence in fighting
the charges against him, Hastings was elected to the House in 1992
from a newly drawn, heavily minority district centered in Fort
Lauderdale. Last year, questions were raised about laboratory work
done by the FBI on evidence given to the judicial panel in
Hastings' case. House leaders, however, refused to reopen the
impeachment issue.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings says he made peace with many of those in the House who
supported his impeachment, taking official overseas trips with Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who is chairman of the Judiciary Committee, and
working on legislation with Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, senior
Democrat on that panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``One would argue one ought to dislike them,'' Hastings said of
those who backed his removal. ``But what happened is they became
part of a process that was driven by constitutional abdication of
responsibility that allowed the judges to drive the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastings, who generally keeps a low profile in Congress, can
elicit strong emotions. A Florida Republican who asked not to be
named said one of his most disturbing moments upon arriving in
Congress was seeing Hastings, an impeached federal judge, presiding
over the House when the Democrats still held the majority. And
after Hastings introduced his Starr impeachment resolution, he said
a House staffer sent him an e-mail saying, ``Impeach yourself, you
idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   And to those who see his criticism of Starr and the ongoing
congressional process as an effort to lash out at the system that
stripped him of his judicial authority, he says it isn't so.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no striking back at all,'' he said. ``I have the
responsibility as a citizen but even more so now as a
congressperson.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone does not stop the madness, the madness continues,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
