<SLUG> BC-BBN-DISPUTED-BALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT FILED OVER HOME RUN-THAT-WASN'T BALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Queens high school student was sued Friday over the
ball that Mark McGwire hit for what some fans thought was his 66th
home run of the season in County Stadium in Milwaukee last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The student, Johnny Luna, 18, was accused in the suit of taking
the ball from the fan who caught it, Michael Chapes, 31, a high
school gym teacher in Waterford, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The hit by McGwire, the St. Louis first baseman, was ruled a
double after Chapes extended his glove over the fence to grab the
ball. The ball, which could fetch big money on the baseball
memorabilia market, somehow ended up in the hands of Luna, a senior
at Long Island City High School in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Chapes' lawyer, Thomas C. Boyd, said in the lawsuit, filed in
Milwaukee County Circuit Court, that as his client caught the ball,
he was pushed against the inside fence by the crush of fans behind
him. While Chapes was doubled over and in danger of falling, Luna
jumped down into the 4-foot-wide trough between the two fences and
spirited the ball away, the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Luna had traveled to Milwaukee with Gerald DiGilio, 40, a bridge
painter from Astoria, Queens; his two teen-age sons, and another
young man. Luna and DiGilio are named as defendants in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, DiGilio told reporters that they planned to sell the
ball to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd said DiGilio ``organized this group for the purpose of
securing the ball.'' The lawyer said he did not know how to reach
either defendant. DiGilio was not listed in the Queens telephone
directory.
</P>
<P>
   A similar lawsuit involving Sammy Sosa's 62nd home run ball was
settled in Chicago Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
