A5366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-VODKA-NYT &LR;      09-25 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-VODKA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA MOVES TO ASSERT MORE CONTROL OVER VODKA INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Reining in Russia's boundless thirst for illicit,
untaxed and therefore cheap vodka is easy. President Boris
Yeltsin's government already has done it dozens of times.
</P>
<P>
   There was last year's decree banning walk-up liquor sales at
sidewalk kiosks, which promptly mutated into sidewalk stores with
phone-booth size sales rooms. There was the previous year's decree
of an 18.4-ruble-per-liter minimum price at stores, which aimed to
wipe out the price advantage of untaxed vodka, but instead expanded
the black market.
</P>
<P>
   There were another 40 or so similar decrees, plus a near-war
with Georgia last fall to block invading fleets of ethyl alcohol
tank trucks _ all to some, but not very much avail.
</P>
<P>
   Now Russia's new prime minister, Yevgeny Primakov, is preparing
a new vodka decree _ a get-tough plan with the statist stamp of
Yeltsin's new Communist-led ministries, as well as the endorsement
of moderates. Which is not to say it will work, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alcohol industry is now under mafia control,'' said
Nikolai Petrakov, an economist and director of the Institute of
Market Problems in Moscow. ``It was simple to privatize production
and trade of vodka. It will be very difficult to return to the old
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov intends to try anyway. Details are scarce, but his
aides said the government would effectively retake control of key
parts of the vodka industry that were set free when Yeltsin
liquidated the state vodka monopoly in May 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Private vodka manufacturers _ they are not distillers, just
mixers of alcohol, water and flavors _ would keep their licenses,
as long as they let the government sign off on major production
decisions. The government also would decide who gets to sell the
billions of one-liter bottles of vodka that fly from Russian
shelves each year.
</P>
<P>
   The government already controls the 162 distilleries that make
virtually all the pure alcohol used in legal Russian vodka. Control
of production and distribution supposedly will re-establish
something approaching the vodka industry of Soviet days, but with
some room for private profit.
</P>
<P>
   ''All those who will get a quota to produce alcohol will
function. Those who will not get this quota for various reasons
will either have to change their product line or work according to
the government,'' the deputy prime minister for agriculture,
Gennady Kulik, said at a news conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Among Russians, at least, the motive for such sweeping changes
goes without saying. In czarist days, half of all state revenues
came from state-controlled vodka sales. The Soviets received as
much as 35 per cent of their income from vodka, before oil and gas
became big moneymakers in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin opened the pasture gate, and the cash cow walked out. By
the latest estimate, no more than four per cent of Russia's
revenues come from vodka taxes or sales, though that is a half to a
third of what it should be.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's goal is to pay off at least half of the immense total
of back wages owed state workers with the proceeds from stricter
enforcement of alcohol laws.
</P>
<P>
   For bootleggers, evading taxes is the game. Vodka is such a
heavily taxed commodity that the riches gained from cheating
outweigh the risks.
</P>
<P>
   Bootleggers cut costs by making vodka from cheap ethyl alcohol
smuggled into the country or illegally produced after-hours at
government distilleries, a rampant practice. By some estimates,
government distillers produce twice as much alcohol as they list on
official sales reports.
</P>
<P>
   The bootleggers skirt excise taxes by marketing their vodka at
discount prices, often under reputable names _ counterfeits, in
essence.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Smirnov, a Russian vodka maker whose family name is also
on a competing line of foreign-made ``Smirnoff'' vodkas, said in an
interview that at least one new counterfeiter is reported to his
factory each week. Licensed vodka makers also produce extra bottles
in the dark of night, then juggle their books to hide the income
from sales.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the hidden vodka production is staggering, so to
speak: in 1997, licensed makers reported producing 868 million
liters of vodka. Meanwhile, Russians reported drinking 2.15 billion
liters. No one knows, or at least is saying, where the difference
came from. Still, it is easy to surmise.
</P>
<P>
   When Russia's border service blocked tank trucks from running
foreign alcohol into the country from Georgia last fall, provoking
a diplomatic incident, legal alcohol production by state distillers
more than doubled in three months.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, Yeltsin's government fired the head of the border
guards who ran the anti-smuggling operation. Smuggling has since
resumed; so has the unsteady course of state production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
