<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-425&AMP;A     09-25 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN SELECTS FINANCE MINISTER  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL WINES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Ending an agonizing deliberation that held world
financial markets and national politics in its thrall, President
Boris Yeltsin finally chose a finance minister for Russia's new
government Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But his choice provoked a second key minister to walk out,
triggering a search for a replacement. And later, the head of the
nation's securities commission resigned, also apparently in protest
of the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin apparently stirred their anger by naming Mikhail
Zadornov, a 35-year-old free-market advocate, as finance minister.
He held the same job under the last prime minister, Sergei
Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment was welcomed by western analysts and investors
who have been searching for some sign that Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov's new government would remain open to western-style
financial practices and reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Zadornov is the most prominent reformer left in a cabinet more
or less dominated by left-centrists and members of the Communist
party. In response to the appointment, the leading centrist in the
new cabinet, Deputy Prime Minister Alexander Shokhin, resigned
after a mere nine days on the job. Shokhin, who is in charge of
economic policy in the new government, was, in effect, Zadornov's
boss. The second resignation was that of Dmitri Yasilyev, head of
the Russian securities regulation commission. Yasilyev, like
Zadornov, is considered a reformer. The nature of his difficulties
with Zadornov were not clear.
</P>
<P>
   Shokhin said he was quitting because the selection of Zadornov
was ``a political mistake'' that would make it impossible for him
to form a united front on fiscal policy and debt negotiations with
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not want to be a fig leaf talking to the West without
being sure that the ministries I was overseeing would be guiding
the policies I could be responsible for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview Friday evening, Shokhin noted that he
had urged Zadornov to quit the government earlier because no ruling
coalition could function effectively if it included key officials
who were responsible for the fiscal collapse that occurred last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Shokhin said he had told Primakov and Yeltsin of his decision
early Friday, but had withheld the formal announcement until they
were convinced that he was serious.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov reacted coolly to the decision. ``I think this is
irresponsible, especially at such a difficult time,'' he said,
adding that Yeltsin had done Shokhin ``a great favor'' by elevating
him to the post.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Primakov added that his government was unaffected by the
departure. But it was not clear who might now accept the job.
Shokhin's departure swings the Russian government even further
toward the Communist left, something he acknowledged in a
television interview Friday night. Shokhin was a national
legislator and the leader of Our Home Is Russia, a political
faction closely allied with the centrist policies of the former
prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Shokhin made headlines by suggesting that Russia
could default on its debt to other nations and the International
Monetary Fund unless lenders gave the country more leeway to
restructure its finances.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party leader in the legislature, Gennady Zyuganov,
seemed to welcome Shokhin's departure. In a television interview
Friday night, he said Shokhin left because negotiation over debts
to western creditors were stalled and his old post as legislative
leader of Our Home Is Russia was soon to be filled by someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Shokhin has quit the government before. In 1994, he left the
post of finance minister to protest Yeltsin's appointment of
conservatives to his cabinet. Then as now, he has been playing an
important role in negotiations with the International Monetary Fund
and western creditors for money to fuel what was then Russia's
economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech made Friday before his resignation became public,
Shokhin said he believes there remains a small chance that the IMF
will deliver the second segment of a multibillion-dollar loan
commitment to the Russian government.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, an IMF mission evaluating Russia's financial
situation left Moscow Friday, saying the country's difficulties
remain serious, but offering to work with the government to resolve
them.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF experts gave no hint of whether the organization would
continue to extend credit to Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
