<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A GREAT SEASON ENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill., Mo.)  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sammy Sosa is the symbol of a great baseball season
coming to a close.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees closed in on baseball immortality Friday night,
becoming the first team since 1954 to win more than 111 games in a
season. The Mets, Cubs and Giants are virtually even in a furious
wild card race. Sosa and Mark McGwire are neck and neck in a home
run chase.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has pursued McGwire through spring and summer. Now in the
fall, the Dominican Republic's 29-year-old hero finally has pulled
even. With three games left the question of who is king of the hill
comes down to a final test of skills: strength, timing,
coordination, concentration.
</P>
<P>
   There is national pride, too. Up and down Broadway, beyond 155th
Street all the way up to the 200s, groups of men and women from the
Dominican Republic will crowd around television sets for the next
three days, watching and waiting for news of the chase.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is reminiscent of the Harlem of 50 or 60 years ago
when men and women crowded around their radios and listened to Joe
Louis fight. Every blow seemed like some symbolic punch for The
Race. Each new round was a symbol of stamina, of a capacity to
endure. So it is with Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday night, Jose Correa, manager of the popular Margot
restaurant in Washington Heights, sat in his restaurant and tried
to put Sosa in perspective. ``The Dominican people are coming up,
especially here in New York,'' Correa said. ``Before, we were
labeled as bad, corrupt, now they see it's not like that. Sosa has
given light to a whole lot of other things. Not only in sports,
we're coming up in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians predict that this baseball season will have
resonance. David Voigt, a professor emeritus at Albright College
and the author of seven books on baseball, including an extensive
three-volume history of American baseball, said: ``This will be one
of the more memorable seasons. It will be remembered for the
overall accord in the game. The strike that set the game back is
being forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The season will also be remembered because this was the Monica
Lewinsky year,'' Voigt added. ``People could turn to the
McGwire-Sosa thing if they were fed up with that stuff. That gives
the season a benchmark. Sometimes external stuff gives baseball a
benchmark.''
</P>
<P>
   Voigt was 13 years old during the 1941 season, attending the
Hershey Industrial School in Hershey, Pa. It was the season of Joe
DiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak; Ted Williams hit .406; the
Yankees won Game 7 of the World Series when Tommy Henrich reached
first base when the Dodgers catcher, Mickey Owen, dropped the third
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then World War II breaks out and that gave that year a
timelessness,'' Voigt said. ``You had nothing but wartime baseball
for the next four seasons. That's what you remember. That's how
externals have a way of sharpening one's perception of standout
baseball years.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Sosa slammed his 64th and 65th home runs of the
season, just as Hurricane Georges slammed into the Dominican
Republic. The front page headline on Thursday in Listin Diario, a
newspaper from Santa Domingo, Dominican Republic, was ``65.'' Sosa
dedicated his homers to the Dominican people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am at the side of all Dominicans, of my people, of my nation
in these difficult moments,'' Sosa said as the Cubs left Milwaukee
Wednesday night. ``Hopefully these home runs will bring a little
happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Correa said he already has. ``When he's playing, if he hits a
couple of home runs, it'll be a couple hours that no one will be
thinking about the hurricane,'' Correa said. ``Our minds will be
relaxed. He'll bring a little joy.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been complaints that throughout his race with
McGwire, Sosa was given the short shrift. He has been left for dead
two or three times this season, treated as though his performances
were merely a warmup act for McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Was race a factor? Probably: People of color always have to
scream a little louder. Was U.S. jingoism at play? Probably: We
tend to wrap our flag rather tightly around this game of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wanted McGwire to break the record,'' Correa said as
the last customers left. ``Everybody was pulling for McGwire,
`cause he was white. Now, this guy, Slammin' Sammy Sosa, comes from
nowhere to break up everything. He really did it to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're making up for it,'' Correa said, referring to the
media. ``They're making up for it because they know they did
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has left the debates to those of us on the ground. He's
taken the high road. He has been gracious and deferential; his
mantra has been ``Mark's the Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Now we will see: The last day of the season is Sunday and many
things are still up in the air: Mets-Cubs-Giants; McGwire-Sosa.
Things even out _ life evens out _ and adulation, like home runs,
comes in bunches.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire broke the record; Sosa will probably take the record and
the Giants will grab the last playoff spot. How's that for justice?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
