<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT HOPES TO PUSH ISRAELIS AND PALESTINIANS TOWARD PEACE
AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is preparing
to open a round of shuttle diplomacy on U.S. soil, traveling
between Washington and the United Nations in New York in the hope
of making progress in talks between Israel and the Palestinians,
administration officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, the officials said, is for Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu of Israel and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, to
hammer out at least some of the final details of an agreement
before they meet separately with President Clinton next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can break off parts of this very complex piece and try to
get agreement on it,'' said James Rubin, the State Department
spokesman. ``The question is whether the political will is there to
make the hard decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said there is little hope of an overall
settlement next week, especially because Netanyahu must be back in
Israel before Tuesday evening for the start of the Yom Kippur holy
day. He is to meet Clinton in the White House on Monday morning and
then leave immediately for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Still, administration officials said the White House hopes for
some concrete agreements next week, if only to prove that the
president remains actively involved in foreign policy and has not
been distracted by the political turmoil resulting from his sexual
misadventures.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two years with little visible progress in peace
talks, Israel and the Palestinians are reported to be near an
agreement under which Israel would cede another 13 percent of the
West Bank to the Palestinians. About one-quarter of the newly ceded
area would be designated as nature reserves to prevent Palestinian
settlements.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli army radio quoted Netanyahu as officially confirming
that Israel was ready to withdraw from another 13 percent of the
West Bank. The report also quoted a senior Israeli official as
saying an agreement with the Palestinians could be signed within
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. officials say there are various issues to be resolved,
including Israel's demand for concrete guarantees from the
Palestinians that they will not allow their territory to be used as
a haven for terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who met with Netanyahu earlier this week when both
were in New York for the opening of the U.N. General Assembly, is
expected to return to New York on Saturday for late-night meetings
with both the Israeli leader and with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said she is expected to remain in New York on Sunday ``in
order to continue to work on this effort in advance of meetings the
president will hold.'' State Department officials did not rule out
the possibility that she might try to arrange a joint meeting this
weekend with Netanyahu and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   She is scheduled to be back in Washington on Monday for the
White House meeting with Netanyahu, and then to return to the
United Nations, possibly to talk to Arafat again in preparation for
his White House meeting with the president later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is to address the General Assembly on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
