<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES RELEASE OF MORE DOCUMENTS FROM STARR INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Mich.)  (See also CLINTON-JONES, CLINTON-DAY) 
(js) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee on Friday approved
the release of thousands more pages of documents that had been
delivered by the independent counsel, finding near unanimity this
time on particularly sensitive information that would be kept from
public view.
</P>
<P>
   After days of wrangling, Republicans and Democrats on the panel
agreed to release the audiotapes of surreptitiously recorded
conversations between Linda Tripp and Monica Lewinsky, the White
House intern who had an affair with President Clinton. The
committee voted unanimously to make the same sort of deletions of
sensitive or immaterial information on the audiotapes as it did the
accompanying transcripts of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The documents are set to be released on Thursday at the
earliest, with the tapes probably made available a few days later
for technical reasons, promising the public a third round of
details about Clinton and his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Tripp tapes, the documents also include the
transcripts of grand jury testimony of several important witnesses
in the case, including Clinton's secretary, Betty Currie, and his
confidant, Vernon Jordan, as well as a number of depositions and
FBI interviews with a long list of people.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a sharp distinction from the committee's last go-around,
which was sharply partisan, Republicans cast Friday's proceedings
as a model of cooperation and comity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we're trying to be sensitive to the American people,
of whether they need more or less,'' Rep. W. Asa Hutchinson,
R-Ark., said regarding the release of information.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats immediately tried to dispel that notion of
togetherness. There was ``a modest change'' signaling ``a
Republican retreat in the face of public opinion polls showing
increasing disappointment of what they are doing,'' said Rep. John
Conyers of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the panel. ``At
another level, the partisanship continues.''
</P>
<P>
   In a stark departure from last week's partisan roll call,
Republicans and Democrats took 15 unanimous votes on what
information to redact or withhold, some of it for national security
reasons. On one occasion Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth
Starr requested that three transcripts _ two of people interviewed
by the independent counsel and one grand jury witness _ be kept
secret, and the committee acquiesced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
