<SLUG> BC-INVEST-DIARY-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ITEMS ON INVESTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of Bloomberg IPO index is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27)  
 (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Initial Offerings, 1998 Is a Year to Forget &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investors who bought into one or more initial public offerings
this year might prefer not to be reminded of them. The average
initial offering was down 13.9 percent through last Thursday,
according to Commscan, a New York company that tracked 333 such
deals.
</P>
<P>
   And the Bloomberg IPO index, which tracks stocks for 12 months
after their debuts, was down 30.2 percent from its April 22 high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a market this poor,'' said Tom Zita, a
Commscan analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Also unusual are the huge differences in the report cards of the
brokerage firms that brought these offerings to market. For
example, the 23 offerings for which Goldman, Sachs was lead
underwriter returned an average of 21.7 percent, the best of any
firm. By contrast, the four companies taken public by SG Cowen were
down 56.1 percent, on average.
</P>
<P>
   Among Goldman's hits: Inktomi, a network software company, up
322.2 percent through Thursday; Visual Networks, a provider of
network management systems, up 111 percent; Exodus Communications,
an Internet services firm, up 82.5 percent, and last week's star,
Ebay, the Internet retailer, up 163.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Cowen's four losers were Command Systems, a technology services
company, down 72.9 percent; Schein Pharmaceutical, down 25.4
percent; Symphonix Devices, a hearing aid maker, down 68.2 percent,
and V.I. Technologies, a blood products maker, off 57.8 percent. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's Endowment Has A Flow of Crimson Ink &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University's endowment, the world's largest university
nest egg, has been decimated over the past 10 weeks, as $1.3
billion was shaved off its $13 billion portfolio, the school's
investment arm said in its fiscal year-end letter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jack R. Meyer, president of the Harvard Management Co., which
runs the portfolio, tied the 10 percent decline to two factors.
About three percentage points resulted from arbitrage trades, which
though currently unprofitable, should rebound, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder was due to the endowment's 13 percent exposure to
emerging-markets stocks at the start of the quarter. The decline
was first reported in The Boston Globe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meyer acknowledged disappointment over the quarter's results.
``We typically do better in down markets than up markets,'' he
explained. But he did note the bright side. ``Unlike hedge funds,''
he said, ``we do not have shareholders who redeem.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Long Run, Sector Funds Outperform Their Rivals &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Psst! Ready for yet another tip on how to beat your average,
run-of-the-mill general stock fund? Try this: Dump your diversified
offerings and buy a collection of industry-specific funds.
</P>
<P>
   The average annual return of sector funds was 16.2 percent over
the 10 years ended Thursday, as calculated by Lipper Analytical
Services, the research firm in Summit, N.J., compared with 14.5
percent for general equity funds. Lipper tracks 573 sector funds
and 3,670 general equity portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is interesting in that the sector funds included
such laggards as real estate funds, which returned just 6.6
percent, annualized, over the 10 years; utilities, 10.9 percent,
and natural resources, a miserly 7.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in other sectors, of course, fared far better. The
best-performing sector fund categories were health and
biotechnology, with an annualized 10-year return of 21.3 percent;
science and technology, 20.4 percent, and financial services, 20.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   (The sector category did not include gold funds, which lost an
average of 2.7 percent, annualized. Those funds are relegated to
Lipper's world equity category.)
</P>
<P>
   The only type of general equity fund that the sector portfolios
did not beat was the group that tracks the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index. Those funds returned 17 percent a year, on
average.
</P>
<P>
   General equity funds outperformed the sector funds over shorter
time periods, but sector funds were again the winners during the
recent market downturn, losing an average of 9.7 percent from June
30 through Sept. 24, compared with a loss of 13 percent for general
equity funds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum
</P>
</TEXT>
