<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PRODIGAL TEAM PLAYER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT in parentheses has been used in
the final graf instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable to
some newspaper systems.) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am part of a small team that creates product marketing
materials for our manufacturing company. One member of our team
chews up much more than her share of our group budget, overpaying
for necessities and wasting money on frills. Should the rest of us
keep pinching pennies, even though the quality of the work suffers,
or should we spend what we think we need, knowing that it will call
down the wrath of the bean counters on the whole team? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Without a doubt, your best option is C: Neither of the above.
(Isn't that always the case?) Both courses you mention aren't
really plans at all; rather, they are ways to avoid dealing with
your team's problem. And you do have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   It is essential for everyone in a group to recognize that each
member is responsible for the performance of the whole, says Jon R.
Katzenbach, a director with McKinsey &AMP; Co., the consultants, and an
author of ``The Wisdom of Teams'' (HarperBusiness). ``All members
should be mutually accountable to one another for their
expenditures or the budget or whatever,'' he said. ``Otherwise, you
don't have a real team.''
</P>
<P>
   For a work group to function effectively _ and profitably _ the
members must address internal crises like a spendthrift's breaking
of the budget. They shouldn't wait for an outsider to instill
order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team should confront the person,'' Katzenbach advised.
``Say: `Look, we're all accountable for this. We have to
collectively be comfortable that this spending is going to help us
achieve our purpose.' ''
</P>
<P>
   David Schafer, a vice president at Enron Corp. who has worked
closely with self-directed teams, said, ``One characteristic of
teams that really should have appeal is the self-policing nature of
the group.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it can take time for a team to learn how to handle
conflicts itself, rather than relying on a supervisor. ``It's
certainly not automatic,'' Schafer said. ``One of the things I
would tell my teams is that there's safety in numbers. You've got
to be careful not to look like you're ganging up on someone, but
whoever confronts the person can say: `This isn't just my take on
the issue. This is the way the group sees it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Burnaska, a consultant at the General Electric Co. on
personnel and team issues, offered a four-step approach:
</P>
<P>
   _ Designate a team member to confront the offender about the
group's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask the offender the reasons for his behavior. (There may be a
good explanation.)
</P>
<P>
   _ If the explanation isn't convincing, work with the person on a
corrective plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Arrange a follow-up meeting with the person to review the
situation and determine if progress is being made.
</P>
<P>
   No one likes confrontations with co-workers. But if the problem
festers, Schafer warned, ``frustration levels on the team rise and
suck the energy out of the group.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, your team's only alternative is to wait for a higher-up
to step in and handle your management responsibilities for you. And
that wouldn't look good on your year-end performance evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she will
respond to readers' questions about career and workplace issues.
Send them by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to
Working, Money &AMP; Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
