<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fund's Bailout Points a Finger Back to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   During a year of worldwide financial crises, the United States
has often assumed the role of schoolmarm, lecturing other nations
on the need for banking regulation, market discipline and better
information. But the near-collapse of a large Wall Street hedge
fund has showed that even the top student in advanced capitalism
has something to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in some ways, the U.S. system worked as it should, as
regulators swiftly acted on signals that the fund, Long-Term
Capital Management, was in trouble. And the fact that the fund came
near the brink may simply reflect the secrecy and complexity of the
fund's trading.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 partners of Long-Term Capital still appear to be sitting
on gains in their original investments in the hedge fund they
managed despite the fund's near-collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes of a Rate Cut Lifts Stocks
</P>
<P>
   Stocks reversed early losses to rally on optimism about the
Federal Reserve Board's likelihood of cutting interest rates next
week, which offset concern that banks would report more losses on
hedge-fund investments. The Dow Jones industrial average rose
26.78, or 0.3 percent, to 8,028.77, to end a roller-coaster week
that left the average 1.7 percent higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
gained 2.05, or 0.2 percent, to 1,044.77. The Nasdaq composite
index rose 23.33, or 1.4 percent, to 1,743.67.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices ended higher, pushing the yield on the benchmark
30-year issue to 5.12 percent from 5.16.
</P>
<P>
   FDA Clears Breast-Cancer Drug
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration approved Herceptin, a
genetically engineered drug developed by Genentech, for the
treatment of advanced breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Reports Show Economic Strength
</P>
<P>
   Home resales declined last month but remained near a record
level, while consumer spending rebounded. Economists said the
latest data indicated that the impact of Asia's financial crisis on
the United States has remained muted so far.
</P>
<P>
   House Rejects `Fast-Track' Bill
</P>
<P>
   A bill that would give President Clinton enhanced authority to
negotiate trade agreements, or ``fast-track'' powers, was defeated
by the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Cautious Optimism in Latin America
</P>
<P>
   Outflows of capital appear to be slowing from stock markets in
Latin America, and Wall Street analysts attribute the change to
signs that world lenders are preparing to rescue Brazil from a
potential financial collapse. But the cautious optimism could
evaporate if Brazil's president, Fernando Henrique Cardoso, loses
the election on Oct. 4 or reneges on promises of fiscal austerity
in Latin America's most important economy.
</P>
<P>
   NASA Contract for Lockheed
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin said it had won a $3.44 billion 10-year contract
to run the space operations of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, beating out Boeing. Lockheed's initial contract is
valued at $1.9 billion over five years, with options for another
five years totaling $1.54 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Number of Uninsured Grows
</P>
<P>
   Despite a strong economy, the number of Americans without health
insurance rose 1.7 percent last year, to 43.4 million, the largest
increase since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin's Thirst for Vodka
</P>
<P>
   Russia's new prime minister, Yevgeny Primakov, is preparing to
reassert state control over key parts of the vodka industry,
terminated when President Boris Yeltsin ended the government's
vodka monopoly in May 1992 and now rampant with corruption. The
change, if successful, would result in something akin to the vodka
industry of the old Soviet days and provide the state with a badly
needed source of income.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
