A5401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT-550     09-25 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-BAILOUT-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 MORE EUROPEAN BANKS CITE LOSSES LINKED TO LONG-TERM CAPITAL
FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN and PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two more big European banks on Friday reported losses from their
dealings with Long-Term Capital Management LP, the large
speculative investment fund salvaged from insolvency with a $3.5
billion infusion from an elite roster of Wall Street saviors
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   One day after UBS AG of Switzerland, Europe's largest bank,
reported a loss of as much as $721.6 million partly because of its
risky investments with Long-Term Capital, Germany's Dresdner Bank
AG said it lost $144 million and Switzerland's Credit Suisse Group
said it lost $55 million because of bad investment bets by the
Greenwich, Conn.-based hedge fund.
</P>
<P>
   Some European financial markets fell sharply Friday in reaction
to fear that further huge losses would come to light. U.S. stock
markets, which tumbled Thursday in reaction to the Long-Term
Capital rescue, fell in early trading Friday but recovered by the
end of the day to post a gain.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were nervously watching developments to determine
whether other big players in the universe of 3,000 hedge funds,
many of which had bond market positions not unlike those of
Long-Term Capital, would face pressure from banks to sell
securities to pay off margin loans, potentially weakening the
already fragile world bond market.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Bakstansky, a spokesman for the New York Federal Reserve,
which arranged the private-sector rescue of Long-Term Capital, was
cautious when asked if there might be other hedge funds that are at
risk or if the bailout of Long-Term Capital had succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that initial signs are good. ``The firm has not
collapsed, and the market reaction at this point seems to be
reasonable,'' Bakstansky said. ``If there are losses taken, they
are among the creditor firms. They are well capitalized and they
have strong market positions.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Fed pulled together a consortium of private banks
and brokerage houses early this week to rescue Long-Term Capital,
which the Fed feared could send shock waves through a world
financial system already destabilized by Asia, Russia and other
emerging market woes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fed's quick action to save the hedge fund from collapse
has raised other questions. Some Wall Street bankers say privately
that they felt strong-armed by the government regulator into
putting up the $3.5 billion needed to shore up the hedge fund.
There were also concerns raised in Washington about whether the
largely unregulated hedge fund sector should continue to operate
without direct oversight, given the fears that the failure of just
one big hedge fund raises about the stability of financial markets
generally.
</P>
<P>
   Another question raised by regulators in the United States and
Switzerland was whether there should be closer scrutiny of the
links between banks and hedge funds. Banks provide much of the
capital the hedge funds need to take highly risky positions in
stock, bond and currency markets. Long-Term Capital, for example,
had just over $2 billion in investment capital, but was able to
borrow enough money to make bets valued at $80 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, chairman of the House Banking Committee,
announced that he will hold hearings soon on the Long-Term Capital
bailout. At the top of the agenda are questions about how and
whether to regulate hedge funds.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Regulators elsewhere are also concerned. Britain's Financial
Services Authority has ordered 55 banks and other financial
institutions to provide information on their exposure to Long-Term
Capital and to other hedge funds. Swiss bank regulators asked UBS
for details about its involvement in Long-Term Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Zuberbuehler, director of the Swiss Federal Banking
Commission, said the matter required closer investigation. ``What
leads serious banks to involve themselves to such a degree in such
a vehicle?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium of financial institutions participating in the
rescue of Long-Term Capital announced Friday that the duration of
their equity recapitalization is three years, suggesting that
participants expect the slow resolution of the firm's trading
positions.
</P>
<P>
   The group said it would provide ``adequate liquidity to sustain
Long-Term Capital Management while it work to realize the inherent
value of its portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   An oversight committee is being formed at the direction of the
consortium, and will include representatives of Goldman Sachs,
Merrill Lynch, JP Morgan, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Travelers
Group, and UBS.
</P>
<P>
   The oversight committee, which now controls 90 percent of the
equity in Long-Term Capital, has assumed authority over all aspects
of the fund's operations, including investment strategy, capital
structure, risk management, compensation, hires and terminations,
and ``other significant decisions,'' the statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
