<HEADLINE>
DR. DONALD A. PIOUS, IMMUNOLOGIST, 68 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (js) 
 By FORD BURKHART   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Donald A. Pious, a University of Washington immunologist who
advanced understanding of the immune system's responses to
transplants and infection, died on Sept. 6 at his home in Seattle.
He was 68.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was pancreatic cancer, family members said.
</P>
<P>
   Pious made important contributions to immunology by producing
cell mutations that revealed how the body's killer T-cells
distinguish between foreign substances, or antigens, and the the
body's own cells, said Dr. Hugh McDevitt, an immunologist at
Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Pious' work led to the discovery of how particular molecules
appear on protein markers, like flagpoles, that protrude through
the cell's membrane and can identify a cell containing a virus as
foreign tissue to be rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Arno Motulsky, a medical geneticist at the University of
Washington, said Pious was a leader in the use of genetics to
create mutant cells for immunology studies.
</P>
<P>
   Pious' advances were central to later research on autoimmune
diseases, like rheumatoid arthritis and multiple sclerosis, as well
as on the entire system of histocompatibility, which involves the
body's response to transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Pious, who was born in Bridgeport, Conn., graduated from the
University of Pennsylvania in 1952 and earned his M.D. there in
1956.
</P>
<P>
   After a residency in pediatrics at Yale University Medical
School, he was a postdoctoral fellow in biology at the University
of California at San Diego from 1961 to 1964. Pious then joined the
University of Washington, working in its departments of pediatrics
and genetics and helping to create the department of immunology
there in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Constance; a son, Tony, of Oakland,
Calif.; a daughter, Lisa, of Berkeley, Calif., and a sister,
Barbara Bresler, of Fairfield, Conn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2121EDT &QL; 
