<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-KILLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPLICATIONS MULTIPLY IN CASE OF SLAIN GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Chicago remains rattled over the case of an
11-year-old girl who was sexually molested and killed this summer
in a patch of weeds in a poor South Side neighborhood. Two months
after her death, the case has taken extraordinary twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
   At first, police said two boys, ages 7 and 8, had confessed to
killing Ryan Harris, a girl from the south suburbs who was staying
with her godmother in the boys' Englewood neighborhood so she could
attend a summer camp. Authorities charged the boys in the July 27
killing, saying they had hit Ryan with a rock, knocked her
unconscious, and then suffocated her by stuffing her panties in her
mouth and putting leaves and grass in her nostrils _ all to take
her bicycle. The boys were believed to be the youngest children
ever charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   Then, earlier this month, prosecutors dropped the charges after
semen was found on the girl's panties. Authorities said it was
virtually impossible for boys that young to produce semen. Police
still believe that the boys may have been involved because they
knew specific details about the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Now, investigators have matched the DNA in the semen to a
29-year-old neighborhood man who was already in jail after being
charged in August with sexually assaulting a 10-year-old girl.
Friday, he was charged with sexually assaulting a 14-year-old girl
in January and an 11-year-old girl in May in the same area.
</P>
<P>
   But police have not charged him in the Harris case and will not
even officially confirm that he is a suspect. Unofficially, they
said they had not yet determined exactly what the man had done. A
police official, who would speak only if he was not named, said the
man told investigators that he had not killed Ryan but that he had
performed a sexual act on her after she had been killed. The man
has also said he saw two boys near her body.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors complicate the case. Investigators have been
unable to interview the boys about the 29-year-old man because the
boys' lawyers will not let them talk to police as long as they are
considered possible suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Ferguson, a public defender who represents the
7-year-old, is worried that police would try again to get her
client to admit involvement and that they might bring the boys in
under the pretext of identifying the 29-year-old, when their real
intention would be to have the man identify the boys. She said that
even if her client saw something happen to Ryan he was so
traumatized and confused by police that he may never be able to
articulate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're giving this new suspect an easy way out,'' said Andre
Grant, a private lawyer for the 8-year-old, who said his client
knew nothing about Ryan's death. ``The cops know they have the
right person. They just don't have the moral fortitude to admit
they made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   People in the Englewood neighborhood, historically distrustful
of police, have become even more angry and embittered by the
apparent mishandling of the case and are, in some cases, reluctant
to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to solve the case has become so intense that police
two weeks ago took the unusual step of calling a news conference to
exonerate another man, whom they had interviewed after lawyers for
the 7-year-old said they considered him suspicious because he had
begun giving toys to the boy after Ryan's death.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department has been beset by accusations that a
detective who obtained the confessions from the boys coerced a
confession from an 11-year-old boy in a murder case four years ago.
The accusations, made in a civil lawsuit filed this month by
lawyers for the 11-year-old, mirrored some complaints made by
lawyers for the boys in the Harris case. Pat Camden, a spokesman
for police, said the detective, James Cassidy, had done nothing
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fallout from the Harris case has prompted
prosecutors, police and members of the City Council to consider
making substantial changes in juvenile investigations, including
videotaping interviews with children, insuring that a parent is
present and requiring prosecutors to approve the filing of criminal
charges against juveniles, as they do with adults.
</P>
<P>
   The Fraternal Order of Police, sensitive to the criticism,
teamed up this week with a group off Englewood business and
community leaders to offer a $10,000 reward for information leading
to Ryan's killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still very angry,'' said Shirley Blanton, who runs
a laundromat in the neighborhood where the boys live. ``They're
getting sick of this. They just want it to be over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
