<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: MORE JOY OF SEX  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK RICH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't listen to the Clinton lackeys' bitter gripes about Henry
Hyde's impending impeachment show. It's hard to imagine what
Judiciary Committee investigating this president could be more
qualified _ and bipartisan _ than this one. Both Hyde, its
chairman, and Barney Frank, its ranking Democrat, have had their
own embarrassing sexual adventures exposed for all the world to
see. Who better than these guys to render justice on Clinton's
seemingly perjurious efforts to parse the sex out of oral sex?
</P>
<P>
   Hyde _ whose name by Washington journalistic decree cannot
appear in a sentence unadorned by the adjectives ``revered'' or
``beloved'' (and who has an impressive silver mane to match) _ has
expertise in the fine points of lying about sex, too. When the
chairman was revealed by the on-line magazine Salon this month to
have carried on an illicit affair with the married mother of three
more than 30 years ago, he declared, ``The statute of limitations
has long since passed on my youthful indiscretions.'' Youthful?
Hyde began the affair when 41. Indiscretion? The affair went on for
five years. Apparently any word with the prefix ``in-'' _ witness
Bill Clinton's ``inappropriate'' relationship _ is the
one-size-fits-all fig leaf to cover carnal sins in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   There are many more members of the Judiciary Committee, and by
the time they get through all the Linda Tripp tapes, we may know
all there is to know about their sex lives as well. Hyde is just
one of three outed congressmen so far this month. Republicans _
such as Tom DeLay, who wants to sic the FBI on Salon _ will keep
blaming such revelations on a White House ``scorched-earth''
strategy allegedly masterminded by Sidney (Sid Vicious) Blumenthal.
Democrats will counter by arguing that Kenneth Starr unleashed the
dogs of sexual McCarthyism with a report that Larry Flynt has now
praised for outdoing Hustler magazine in prurience.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of bipartisanship, I'd say both these theories are
simplistic. Starr, by spending $40 million to make the world safe
for Peeping Toms, and Clinton, by so loutishly giving him so much
to peep at, have merely poured gasoline on bonfires smoldering over
the decade since the travails of Gary Hart, Anita Hill and Clarence
Thomas ushered us into this brave new world. Throw in the
concurrent expansion of our tabloid press, especially in the
ballooning electronic media _ and the competitive rush to the
bottom it has kindled _ and we've reached the nadir where a
commentator on MSNBC this week took pains to share with us the
checkered marital histories of the Clinton allies Vaclav Havel and
Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   Were Clinton to leave office today, these forces would not
abate. As William Bennett, our self-appointed morals czar, warned
in February: ``Notice to Republican candidates: If you committed
adultery, I don't think you are going to get the nomination.'' (And
he did not bestow absolution on those with distant messy divorce
histories: ``If Gingrich did what Gingrich is alleged to have done,
that's relevant too.'') Already the likes of Dan Quayle and John
Ashcroft are running in part on the purity of their marriages; a
congressional candidate in Illinois has challenged his opponent to
join him in releasing a signed affidavit denying any hetero- or
homosexual extramarital high jinks. Even as the All Monica show
starts to wane, All Scandal All the Time is in the wings. We're all
sex addicts now.
</P>
<P>
   In a country where the video porn business is bigger than Major
League Baseball and Broadway combined, according to a study by the
trade publication Adult Video News, this shouldn't be a shock. The
question is whether anyone's sex life is relevant to public office.
In the journalistic profession, there has been some sensible
reflection of late on self-policing guidelines that might stop the
non-tabloid press from chasing the latest Drudge sludge. But in the
cutthroat race of the nonstop news cycle, these rules are no sooner
enumerated than they are broken the instant the next salacious
scoop comes along.
</P>
<P>
   The only practical antidote to the madness now may be to let the
sexual fever run its course until the media and their audience
overdose on erotic expose, and the right to privacy, for
politicians no less than the rest of us, comes back into fashion
again. Should Hyde's impeachment proceedings hasten that day, the
circus may yet be a blessing in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
