<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tough task for Jackets
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Georgia Tech try to end a 53-year-old drought and
gain a measure of respect tonight when the Yellow Jackets travel to
North Carolina for a nationally televised game (7:30 p.m., ESPN).
</P>
<P>
   It will be the ACC opener for the Yellow Jackets (1-1), who had
a week off after beating New Mexico State on Sept. 12. Winning at
Chapel Hill for the first time since 1945 would be a meaningful
accomplishment for this program.
</P>
<P>
   But Georgia Tech stands to gain a lot more if it can beat the
Tar Heels (0-2). A victory, coach George O'Leary said, would be a
significant confidence-builder for a team that thinks it can
compete for the ACC title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad our players are thinking that way, because three
years ago they weren't,'' O'Leary said. ``They know this is the
kind of game that can set the tone for an entire season.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech may find it tough to win at Kenan Stadium. North Carolina,
11-1 last year, has lost both of its games _ to Miami of Ohio
(13-10) and Stanford (37-34) _ on last-second field goals. The Tar
Heels and first-year coach Carl Torbush have their backs to the
wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are obviously better than their record,'' O'Leary said.
``They have recruited well and have a lot of great athletes. Still,
I think the game is very winnable, if we play well.''
</P>
<P>
   Also today, the Atlanta Football Classic matches Florida A&AMP;M and
Tennessee State in the Georgia Dome at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a couple of key games in Florida are expected to be
affected by Hurricane Georges, which already has postponed UCLA's
scheduled trip to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   No. 8 Florida will try to bounce back from last week's 20-17
overtime loss to Tennessee as it hosts undefeated Kentucky (3:30
p.m., CBS). At the same time, No. 10 Florida State (2-1) will be
out to prove it still belongs in the national championship race,
against No. 18 Southern California (3:30 p.m., ABC) in Tallahassee.
Rain is supposed to be a factor in both games. In Saturday's
biggest national game, No. 9 Washington (2-0) travels to No. 2
Nebraska (3-0). Nebraska, the defending national champion in the
coaches poll, has won 46 games in a row at home.
</P>
<P>
   In other SEC games, No. 22 Alabama (2-0) should find out if it
will be a legitimate contender in the West when it travels to
Arkansas (2-0) (6 p.m., ESPN2). South Carolina will be out to avoid
a 1-3 start when it hosts Mississippi State (12:30 p.m., WATL).
</P>
<P>
   In the ACC, Clemson (1-2) is at home against Wake Forest (1-1)
(noon, ABC), while No. 11 Virginia (3-0) visits Duke (2-1) (noon,
Fox SS).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
