<HEADER>
A5414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COLLEGE-PREDICTIO     09-25 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COLLEGE-PREDICTIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurricane won't slow Seminoles or Gators
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The state of Florida, once the focal point of the
college football world, can't get a break.
</P>
<P>
   First Florida State loses to N.C. State and drops out of the top
five for the first time in forever. Ditto for Florida after it
falls to Tennessee last week in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Now, improved Miami, which was licking its chops to get No. 3
UCLA in the Orange Bowl, has been cut off at the pass by a
hurricane named Georges.
</P>
<P>
   But do not weep for the Sunshine State. Florida and Florida
State will play through the rain today against legitimate opponents
and both should win. And given the wackiness of college football,
at least one of them will be in the national championship race.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to weep anyway, please do it for your humble
prognosticator, who got beat up last week by some goofy games,
Marshall over South Carolina, to name just one.
</P>
<P>
   While we're preparing to dodge Georges' rain drops, let's take
another stab at it:
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech (1-1) at North Carolina (0-2), 7:30 p.m., ESPN: The
Tar Heels are in trouble after losses to Miami of Ohio and
Stanford. Georgia Tech has a chance in this one if it can exploit a
defense that gave up 37 points to a bad Stanford team. Problem is,
Georgia Tech's defense hasn't exactly been a steel curtain. The
home team wins because, frankly, they've got to. North Carolina 31,
Georgia Tech 24.
</P>
<P>
   Houston (0-3) at No. 4 Tennessee (2-0), 7 p.m.: It's a cliche,
but in this case, it's true: Houston might be the best 0-3 team in
America. Tennessee is still enjoying the high of last week's huge
win over Florida, and so the Vols need to be careful. Talent,
however, should prevail, and the Vols have plenty of that.
Tennessee 31, Houston 17.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky (3-0) at No. 8 Florida (2-1), 3:30 p.m., CBS: Kentucky
is undefeated, but the Wildcats and Tim Couch will learn there is
nothing more dangerous than a wounded Gator. Florida is still
hurting from the loss to Tennessee but will prevail at home, where
it has won 23 in a row. Florida 35, Kentucky 21.
</P>
<P>
   No. 18 Southern California (3-0) at No. 10 Florida State (2-1),
3:30 p.m. (ABC): If the Seminoles are going to be contenders,
instead of pretenders, for the national championship, they need to
take care of business against the Trojans. FSU quarterback Chris
Weinke is starting to get more comfortable with the offense and
should play well. The Seminoles have won 35 straight games at home.
This will be 36. Florida State 31, Southern California 20.
</P>
<P>
   No. 22 Alabama at Arkansas (2-0), 6 p.m. (ESPN2): Two teams
hoping to find out if they have the right stuff to contend in the
SEC West. Alabama has lost three out of its last four games to
Arkansas, but the Crimson Tide feels good about its new offense and
Shaun Alexander, who has 321 yards and eight touchdowns in his
first two games. This game is the first real test for Houston Nutt,
the first-year coach at Arkansas. Because of Alexander the Great,
we like the Tide. Alabama 24, Arkansas 17.
</P>
<P>
   No. 9 Washington (2-0) at No. 2 Nebraska (3-0), 3:30 p.m.: The
Cornhuskers have been without running back DeAngelo Evans and
quarterback Bobby Newcombe for two weeks, and now both are back.
The Huskies do not have a running game, which means quarterback
Brock Huard is going to take a beating. There is a reason Nebraska
has won 46 in a row at home. Nebraska 35, Washington 14.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State (2-1) at South Carolina (1-2), 12:30 p.m.
(Jefferson-Pilot): South Carolina is in a must-win situation after
last weak's inexplicable loss to Marshall. Mississippi State is
coming off a tough road loss to Oklahoma State. The Bulldogs think
they are good enough to win the SEC West. They'll prove it in
Columbia. Miss. State 24, South Carolina 14.
</P>
<P>
   Wake Forest (1-1) at Clemson (1-2), Noon: The Tigers were on the
verge of a major upset at Virginia last week and let it slip away.
Now their backs are to the wall against the Deacons, who have lost
four in a row to Clemson. Clemson gets the edge at home, but it
won't be easy. Clemson 24, Wake Forest 17.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue (2-1) at Notre Dame (1-1), 2:30 p.m., NBC: Notre Dame has
had a week off since getting trounced by Michigan State on Sept.
12, while Purdue is coming off an impressive 35-7 win over Central
Florida. Purdue upset the Irish a year ago, but this year Bob
Davie's club has a better idea of what they are doing. Notre Dame
28, Purdue 24.
</P>
<P>
   The others:
</P>
<P>
   ACC _ Virginia 31, Duke 20; Maryland 21, Temple 14.
</P>
<P>
   SEC _ LSU 42, Idaho 14; Mississippi 21, SMU 17.
</P>
<P>
   Top 25 _ No. 5 Kansas State 70, NE Louisiana 14; No. 14
Wisconsin 24, Northwestern 20; No. 15 Colorado 31, Baylor 14; No.
17 Texas A&AMP;M 42, North Texas 21; No. 19 West Virginia 30, Tulsa 17;
No. 20 Oregon 42, Stanford 17; No. 21 Virginia Tech 21, Pittsburgh
20.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's record: 13-7.
</P>
<P>
   Season's record: 36-21.
</P>
