<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-UNC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech, UNC both at critical juncture
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- For the past couple of years, playing North Carolina
has been about trying to move into the upper echelon of the ACC for
Georgia Tech. But tonight's ACC opener at Kenan Stadium at 7:30 on
ESPN is more about survival for the Tar Heels.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina (0-2) is reeling after a pair of losses to Miami
of Ohio and Stanford, two teams the 1996 and 1997 Tar Heels
wouldn't have imagined losing to. They are trying to regain some
face among their fans who have gotten used to winning and were
shocked by legal problems surrounding the program, most recently
with the suspension of offensive guard Jon Hall after he was
arrested for allegedly assaulting and threatening a woman.
</P>
<P>
   First-year coach Carl Torbush is scrambling for his first win
since adding the title of head coach to defensive coordinator with
the departure of Mack Brown for Texas. He's likely to be going with
a true freshman quarterback, Ronald Curry, gifted but untested in
his first ACC game. Torbush already is talking about must-wins and
trying to prevent Carolina from going 0-3 for the first time since
1988, Brown's first season in Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to be in the bowl picture, this is a game we
need to win,'' Torbush said. ``There comes a point when you need to
have success if you're planning to have a very solid football
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets (1-1), meanwhile, are not much more proven
than North Carolina, with their only win against a low-caliber
opponent in New Mexico State. A loss in Chapel Hill would make the
season-opening Boston College loss a lot more vivid. A win would go
some way in building confidence for the rest of the ACC schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big game for us because it's the first ACC game,'' Tech
quarterback Joe Hamilton said. ``And they've been a tough opponent.
It's equally important to them because they're 0-2. They'll be a
little hungry. They're playing in front of a home crowd. It will be
a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech has not won at Kenan Stadium since 1945, the year before
coach George O'Leary was born. To win this one, the defense will
have to continue the progress it showed against New Mexico State.
North Carolina does not have a dominating running back, but Curry
is dangerous running the ball himself.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels have some key injuries, including receiver L.C.
Stevens, who is questionable with a sprained knee, and running back
Ronnie Robinson, who has been slow to recover from a concussion he
suffered against Stanford. Their two best athletes _ Curry and
All-American cornerback Dre Bly _ both have missed practice time
this week because of the deaths of their grandfathers.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, Hamilton needs to have his best game yet against
North Carolina. He will feel the heat from a defense trying to
rebound from giving up 451 yards to Stanford, the most since a 1994
game against Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a pivotal game for the program, not just the
season,'' Tech slot back Charlie Rogers said. ``We're trying to
move forward. This would give us momentum in the coming weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
