<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jesse Jackson attempts to brings public awareness to the plight
of the Appalachia's poor
 &HT;    By Wendy Hundley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Just as the Selma, Ala. march focused the
nation's attention on voting rights for blacks, Rev. Jesse Jackson
is trying to turn the public spotlight on the plight of the poor in
Appalachia.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Jackson will be joined by Rev. Jerry Falwell, singer
Willie Nelson and actor Martin Sheen for a rally at Hocking College
in Nelsonville, according to Jackson's Rainbow/PUSH Coalition. The
march will be followed on Monday with an economic summit at Hocking
in that southeastern Ohio community.
</P>
<P>
   In a teleconference Friday, Jackson told about 25 reporters that
``the real needs of the American people are going unaddressed''
while the media chase the President Clinton-Monica Lewinsky sex
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to keep pressing this case until the press becomes
obsessed with impeaching poverty, illiteracy and disease,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the the six-state region in the heart of Appalachia
represents the ``richest soil but the poorest people in our
nation.'' The area, he said, is plagued by a lack of economic
development, inadequate housing and health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Titanic, 1,500 people were killed and people are still
traumatized,'' Jackson said. ``But 1,500 people die each year from
black lung disease every year and it's hardly noticed.'' United
Mine Workers President Cecil Roberts also participated in the
teleconference.
</P>
<P>
   .Jackson is calling for a kind of domestic Marshall Plan that
would encourage economic development in the region with tax-free
zones, long-term, low-interest loans and other incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should do for Americans what we do for our allies abroad,''
said Jackson, who went on a 13-stop bus tour last week through
Ohio, West Virginia and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights leader said he wants people in the impoverished
area to recognize their power to improve their situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as Selma sent a message about the right to vote,''
Jackson said, ``our focus is on the underserved Americans who have
played by the rules and yet growth and prosperity has passed them
by.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
