<HEADER>
A5419 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARKS-COX     09-25 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio honors Rosa Park
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ On Dec. 2, 1955, the night after Rosa Parks refused
to give her seat on a public bus to a white man, the Ku Klux Klan
burned a cross on the tallest hill in Villa Rica, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   John Hindsman was there, watching the smoke curl over the
graveyard where his mother was buried. The Klan set the fire to
show the town's black people that Parks' immediately famous act of
defiance had changed nothing, recalled Hindsman, now an 81-year-old
Daytonian.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Klan) didn't think nobody would have the courage to stand
up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   History's verdict on that notion was evident Friday afternoon,
when Hindsman and about 250 others, black and white, crowded the
atrium of the Cincinnati Westin Hotel to greet the woman whose act
of courage changed history.
</P>
<P>
   Parks, now 85, was in town to receive the first International
Freedom Conductor Award from the National Underground Railroad
Freedom Center.
</P>
<P>
   The former seamstress emerged from a black stretch limousine in
front of the hotel at 12:46 p.m. and made her way through a
cheering gauntlet of admirers. Once inside, dozens of
schoolchildren serenaded her with America the Beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   Parks didn't speak long, only about 5 minutes. She recalled the
fateful afternoon when, tired from a day of work and fed up with
decades of mistreatment, she told a Montgomery, Ala., bus driver
that she had no intention of surrendering her seat.
</P>
<P>
   Two police officers took her to jail. But Parks' bravery sparked
a year-long boycott that put the company out of business and put
the modern civil rights movement on the map.
</P>
<P>
   Parks told the audience her experience still had relevance
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you find that you're being mistreated, you don't need no
fussing or fighting _ in a quiet way, let them know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   One man who doesn't mind fussing or fighting was also on hand
Friday. Retired federal Judge A. Leon Higginbotham, a
blunt-speaking civil rights champion, gave the Freedom Center's
first Theodore M. Barry lecture.
</P>
<P>
   In a stentorian voice, Higginbotham recalled his days as one of
Antioch College's first black students, and he remembered Jessie
Treichler, the white college secretary who raised money to bring
him there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treichler was one of the first persons I ever met who seemed
totally devoid of racial bias and prejudice, and who saw inherent
humanity in all individuals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also said the spirit of the Underground Railroad is
still needed today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its goal of enabling all Americans to be truly free has not
been realized,'' he said. ``In the history of this nation, there
have been, and still are, many persons who . . . are in a real
sense still shackled.
</P>
<P>
   `` . . . They carry what at first glance are the almost
invisible shackles of illiteracy, a grossly inadequate education,
and a lack of any essential skills to get a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Parks will receive her honor tonight at a black tie dinner.
The International Freedom Conductor award is meant to recognize
those whose words and deeds reflect the spirit of the Underground
Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   As Parks left the atrium escorted by white-shirted policemen,
Hindsman walked over to a display of a bus seat refurbished to look
much like the one Parks refused to relinquish. He snapped a few
photos of it, but those probably won't be the pictures he'll
remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me 50 years to get a photo of Rosa Parks,'' he said.
``But I got it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-09-25-98 2009E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
