<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLASSIC25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FAMU has 7-game win streak in matchup of mutual respect
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Coaches Billy Joe of Florida A&AMP;M and L.C. Cole of
Tennessee State are singing the praises of each other's team before
today's 10th annual Atlanta Football Classic at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennessee State has a very explosive offense. They've got some
great skill position players,'' Joe said. ``They can score from
anywhere on the field. If we don't play our best football, we could
have some serious problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole said, ``The edge in this game has to go Florida A&AMP;M because
of all the points they've scored. They've got a lot of skillful
players. And what's really great about their situation is that
coaching staff has been together so long. That's hard to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers (2-1), with a coaching staff that includes four
assistants who have been with Joe all five of the years he's been
in Tallahassee, decimated their last two opponents. They routed
Norfolk State 84-14 and then blasted Jackson State 45-7 last week.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee State (1-1), off a week after a 33-21 win over Jackson
State before a crowd of 55,000 in Memphis, is averaging 487 yards a
game in total offense.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams will start quarterbacks who began their college
careers in Division I programs. Tennessee State sophomore Leon
Murray, who transferred from Pittsburgh, has averaged 347 yards
passing per game this season.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's primary targets have been senior All-America candidate
Tyrone Butterfield (17 catches, 258 yards) and Corey Sullivan, a
sophomore who has caught 13 passes for 178 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murray has done an excellent job,'' Cole said. ``He's gotten
better each game.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe, making good on his promise to start each of his team's top
three quarterbacks, puts the offense in the hand of senior Pat
Bonner against Tennessee State. Bonner, a Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,
native who transferred from Temple, passed for 343 yards and three
touchdowns against Jackson State, while sophomore receiver Jacquay
Nunnally leads Division I-AA averaging 131 yards receiving per
game.
</P>
<P>
   Florida A&AMP;M has beaten TSU seven times in row. Three of those
victories came in this classic sponsored by 100 Black of Men of
Atlanta. And if Joe's assessment of his team is true, the Rattlers
just might be able to register their eighth victory in row over a
Tiger team that was beaten by South Carolina State in this classic
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've played as well as we need to play,'' Joe
said. ``Our best football is still ahead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE STATE VS. FLORIDA A&AMP;M
</P>
<P>
   -- When, where: Today, 4 p.m.; Georgia Dome, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   -- Series: Tennessee State leads 23-14.
</P>
<P>
   -- Records: Tennessee State 1-1; Florida A&AMP;M 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   -- Game notes: This is the fifth meeting of these two teams in
Atlanta, and their first in the Georgia Dome. In the previous four
games _ two played at Georgia Tech (1989 and '90) and two at
Atlanta- Fulton County Stadium, they averaged 46,767 in
attendance.... FAMU, which has won its last seven games against
TSU, will be seeking its third straight victory on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
