<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-EARLY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leagues differ from NBA on eligibility issue
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Kenny Anderson skipped out of Georgia Tech for the
NBA after only two years. Stephon Marbury stayed just one season.
</P>
<P>
   The latest incoming Yellow Jackets point guard out of New York
must wait four years before having the option to play for pay.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Niesha Butler, and the professional leagues she has
her eye on prohibit women from suiting up until they've completed
their college eligibility. Defeated in the courts 24 years ago in
its efforts to keep out college underclassmen, the NBA has
reluctantly opened its doors to them _ plus graduating high-school
seniors. Not so with the ABL and WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   The women's leagues might not be on firm legal ground, but the
money to be made _ $150,000 for top stars, not counting
endorsements _ has not offered enough incentive for a player to
bring a test case. Some day, it will happen. Either salaries will
escalate, or the leagues will relax their rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, it's antitrust,'' California-Berkeley coach Marianne
Stanley said. ``It's going to take the first woman to say, `Hey, if
guys can leave early, I should be able to leave early, too.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee star Chamique Holdsclaw is believed to have considered
a challenge but decided to remain in college.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion is split among lawyers and sports agents whether the
leagues' refusal to draft underclassmen might be a violation of
antitrust law. Some suggest that the courts would agree, because
the WNBA and ABL have no collective-bargaining agreement with their
players and yet unilaterally impose provisions for a draft. At the
same time, however, Supreme Court decisions since 1985 have
weakened antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``You now need to show it hurts a whole market of players,''
said attorney Mark Levinstein, a specialist in antitrust law. ``One
person being kept out isn't going to be enough. But, really, no one
can say for sure how a challenge would shake out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leagues aren't doing it to raise prices or hurt
competition. They're doing it because they want to look good
public-relations-wise and they want to have good relations with the
universities.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler, the all-time leading scorer in New York high schools,
maintains that the rule is unfair to women. She wrote a
first-person story on the topic for a sports Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see why men should have the opportunity to turn pro
early but not women,'' she said. ``That's why you go to college _
to create options for yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech coach Agnes Berenato agrees to an extent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a stupid rule,'' Berenato said. ``It's an unfair
rule. I don't think anybody is ready (to turn pro) at 17 or 18. But
the point is, men can do it and women can't. Somebody will
challenge that.''
</P>
<P>
   The inconsistency between the women's leagues and the NBA is
irksome to leaders of the women's sports movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure the cat's meow for a very talented performer is
to go through college from 18 to 22 if your performing lifetime is
limited,'' said Donna Lopiano, executive director of the Women's
Sports Foundation. ``You can go to college anytime you want. I'm
sorry, (but) this is not sacred ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the policies point to the increasing antisocial
behavior of NBA players and trace some of the blame to the early
entry of teenage athletes. WNBA commissioner Val Ackerman, a former
NBA employee, says her league has been assured its stand is solid
and that the men's league wishes it didn't have to accept the
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're set up as a single enterprise, which is different than
the NBA,'' Ackerman said. ``Because of that legal and corporate
structure, our lawyers have indicated this sort of a rule would be
unassailable. So we have great comfort in that.''
</P>
<P>
   WNBA star Sheryl Swoopes hopes the rule stands up, to help her
league maintain some of its innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA made that mistake when it let guys come out (early),''
Swoopes said. ``I hope it never gets to that point with the women.
Now, it seems the men are all about money. They're not doing it for
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
