<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5423 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-ESSAY-COX     09-25 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-ESSAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kersee: It's acceptable to be a tomboy now
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jackie Joyner-Kersee, a six-time Olympic track-and-field
medalist and a former star basketball player at UCLA, is widely
recognized as the greatest female athlete of her generation.
Kersee, 36, retired after this past track season to devote full
attention to her St. Louis-based sports marketing firm. This
summer, she was the lone woman on ESPN's town-hall meeting on race
in sports, which featured President Clinton. Joyner-Kersee wrote
the following essay for the Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   When I was growing up in East St. Louis, Ill., my introduction
to competitive sports came early in my sophomore year at Lincoln
High School. I was bigger than most girls my age. On the
playground, I had discovered I could out-run a lot of the boys. So
here I was, trying out for the girls basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   I can still remember the coach coming into the gym that first
afternoon, telling us, ``Well, we're going to have to move practice
to 6:30 (p.m.)'' I'm thinking, ``Mom is not going to let me come up
here at no 6:30!'' It's dark by this time. A lot of our parents
didn't have transportation, and we lived all over.
</P>
<P>
   The reason we were being pushed back is the boys were supposed
to get the gym first. It wasn't about sharing half of the court. It
was simply that we were females, and we would have to practice
after the boys.
</P>
<P>
   By the next year, after a lot of debate, we got the gym at 3:30.
One reason was safety. But we'd also opened some eyes with a great
showing on the court. My sophomore year, we went to the state
championships. A lot of the same girls were on the undefeated team
my senior year.
</P>
<P>
   I can tell you, people were jealous because we were so dominant
not only in basketball, but softball, volleyball and track. It
might sound silly, but we thought there was a conspiracy where some
guys on the boys teams were encouraged to get some of the girls
pregnant so we couldn't win as much. Our coaches talked about it,
warning us to be careful about who we were dating and what some
boys' agendas might be.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, it's still hard to understand why people were so
upset that we were getting more publicity and attention than the
boys.
</P>
<P>
   What I find really positive today is the far greater
appreciation for women's sports. When I was growing up, it wasn't
really looked upon as the right thing to do. You weren't considered
feminine. You had my idol, Wilma Rudolph, in track. You had Billie
Jean King in tennis, and what she brought to the sport was great.
But she was almost ostracized because of the very private choice of
her sexual preference.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to say that hurt, but it gave people a reason not
to want to support women's athletics. That shouldn't have been the
case, because people should have the freedom to be who they want.
Probably all of us heard the negative, unflattering comments.
``Tomboy'' was a big one.
</P>
<P>
   When I started making a living on the international track
circuit, I caught on immediately that men and women weren't treated
the same. In 1984, only a few top female athletes were earning
between $5,000 and $10,000 per meet. Promoters had this mentality
that people didn't want to see women compete. Now, it's not unheard
of for a woman to command a $25,000 to $40,000 appearance fee,
although you might have only four or five female athletes earning
top dollar. Still, it's better than it was 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It was unheard of for a female to have a shoe named after her. I
never had that opportunity. Now, there are several women with shoes
named after them.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the Los Angeles Olympics 14 years ago, you didn't
see women on the business side of sports. I only saw myself as an
athlete. But now I'm able to parlay my athletics into a
sports-marketing company. I can do things to help other female
athletes. I can go out and register as an agent with the NBA and
NFL. My firm can represent an NFL No. 1 draft pick like Terry Fair,
and no one calls me a tomboy.
</P>
<P>
   When people ask me to project the hot names over the next 10
years, I often say Mia Hamm in soccer, Marion Jones in track and
Chamique Holdsclaw, the Tennessee basketball star, just to name a
few.
</P>
<P>
   I really think women's basketball will grow. The WNBA has done a
great job selling the game and bringing in fans that wouldn't
ordinarily watch women's basketball. The ABL has established a
foundation, too, but I find it hard to see two leagues surviving.
It's difficult when the WNBA is on TV consistently and the ABL is
not. Rather than a merger of leagues, you might see a day when the
WNBA simply absorbs a few teams or players from the ABL.
</P>
<P>
   Whether other women's pro leagues reach the same level, I'm not
so sure. Women's soccer is here to stay, and you can say the same
about softball and maybe even hockey _ at least at the Olympic or
international level. Basketball was truly a natural. The other
sports have to grow that talent base and interest at the college
level.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, we'll also see more women in decision-making
positions. It makes sense that females with roots in sports should
head up the NCAA, run college athletic departments or be
influential in the advertising and marketing business.
</P>
<P>
   My husband Bobby and I eventually would like to start a family.
And if we were to have a daughter, we'd like for her to benefit
from the big changes in women's sports. I'm glad she'll have
opportunities that didn't used to exist for other young girls and
myself when I was coming up.
</P>
<P>
   I know it sounds corny to say women have come a long way, but
it's true. Now, it's okay for us to sweat, be tough, get dirty. And
people don't mind coming to see that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
