<HEADER>
A5425 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOMEN-SALES-COX     09-25 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-SALES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Are women bound to same competitive standards as men?
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The familiar fodder of sports-radio call-in programs
temporarily vanished from America's jock-talk menu in late
February. It was replaced by a subject that rarely shows up on that
combative format's radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   The injured Nykesha Sales had scored a ``gift'' basket that
enabled her to become the University of Connecticut's career
scoring leader. Her coach defended the move by asserting that women
are different emotionally and bring a unique perspective to sports
that should be understood and appreciated. The league commissioner
said he would have had a different opinion for a male athlete,
because women are more sensitive and should be treated accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   The simple layup and complex aftermath generated the kind of
discussion that is virtually non-existent on the sports airwaves.
And it forced an examination of how far women's sports have come.
</P>
<P>
   Should female athletes be given a pass from the difficult
lessons of sports? Or should they be bound to the same competitive
standards and values under which males have operated for years?
</P>
<P>
   How those questions are answered will help determine the status
of top-level women's sports as it enters the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Sales, who ruptured an Achilles' tendon the week before, walked
onto the floor in uniform at Villanova, took the opening tip as the
other players stood idly by and scored to rousing applause.
</P>
<P>
   She had been two points short of the record when her college
career came to a crashing end. UConn coach Geno Auriemma and
Villanova's Harry Perretta agreed to stage the uncontested hoop.
Big East commissioner Mike Tranghese learned of the plan in advance
and approved it.
</P>
<P>
   For the better part of a week, the media devoted considerable
time and space to the Sales controversy. UConn's status as a
high-ranked, high-profile team in the back yard of the New York
market made it a national story.
</P>
<P>
   Many talk-show hosts complained that Auriemma was promoting a
double standard at the same time that women are demanding equality
in athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Beau Bock, a veteran Atlanta sports radio host at ``SportsTalk
790 The Zone,'' had a different spin. As the father of two
basketball-playing daughters, he had no trouble seeing what
Auriemma was trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the greatest things I've ever seen in sports,
men's or women's,'' he said. ``What's wrong with showing a great
athlete some compassion?''
</P>
<P>
   How that compassion should be defined when it comes to women
athletes has been part of the fallout. A number of Auriemma's
coaching colleagues defended his gesture, although others thought
it bordered on fixing a game. UConn beat Villanova that night in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma unleashed a furious assault on his critics. He called
ESPN ``SportsCenter'' host Kenny Mayne an idiot for questioning his
sincerity and went on popular New York City sports-radio station
WFAN to defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought, 'What is he (Auriemma) doing?' `` said
Marilyn Childress, former president of the advocacy group Georgia
Women's Intersport Network. ``But later on, I realized that we
don't have to necessarily fit the men's mold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came across like a daddy taking care of his daughter.
Nobody talks about it when a football coach does the same thing
with his players. It's a father-son thing then, and it's widely
admired.''
</P>
<P>
   Some men who coach women's sports have immersed themselves in
female psychology to understand the differences. Anson Dorrance,
whose University of North Carolina soccer teams have won 15 NCAA
titles, notes that female athletes generally have less
self-confidence than males. His approach is to build up each
player, one by one, then fold them into an emotionally cohesive
unit in which teamwork and mutual support are paramount. In men's
sports, coaches often have to break down individual egos to get the
same result.
</P>
<P>
   (In August, Dorrance was sued on sexual harassment grounds by
two former players seeking $12 million in damages. Included in
their complaints is that Dorrance was too intrusive, often asking
about their private lives, and that he made unwanted advances,
including what they considered inappropriate touching. Dorrance
denied the charges, and other former players have signed a
statement in support of him.)
</P>
<P>
   Hartford Courant columnist Jeff Jacobs condemned Auriemma's
action, suggesting that it was Soupy Sales, rather than Nykesha
Sales, who set the scoring record and to ``forget all that
namby-pamby innocent stuff so many try to peddle about women's
sports. The women must understand rigging events is inherently
dishonest.''
</P>
<P>
   For his opinions, Jacobs received threatening phone calls. On
the eve of the NCAA Tournament, his newspaper published a special
four-page section containing only letters to the editor about the
Sales controversy. Most of them blasted Jacobs for being harsh.
</P>
<P>
   Auriemma stood by his actions: ``Are we supposed to be just like
men's sports?''
</P>
<P>
   Women's Sports Foundation executive director Donna Lopiano
ripped Tranghese for allowing the ``fix'' to go on and said the
gender of the athlete should have nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most sexist and irresponsible comment by an athletics
commissioner I have ever heard,'' she said. ``People's motivations
were good, but all that stuff is ethically unjustifiable.''
</P>
<P>
   Other women's sports advocates say that while they were glad
their issues were getting some attention, they're uneasy with the
reasons why.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was blown out of proportion,'' said Nancy Levin, publisher
of W Sports, a national magazine for women's sports that will start
up next year. ``(Sales' basket) was probably a bad decision, but
there are still a lot of people out there who are looking for a way
to bash women's sports. People who didn't know who Nykesha Sales
was were chiming in. It even made Dan Rather (and the CBS Evening
News).''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Sales controversy soon died out, it might have
signaled the beginning of what figures to be occasional forays into
women's sports topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put opinions out there and it drives people crazy,'' Bock
said. ``I mean, some of these knuckleheads who called up about this
didn't know what we were talking about. But there are a lot of guys
out there who do watch women's sports, and I think they're going to
continue to take off.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
