</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENTV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV exposure on upswing, but ratings slow to follow
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The pursuit of women's sports programming on
television has picked up to the extent that even Lifetime, a cable
channel associated more with the touchy-feeliness of such shows as
``Sisters,'' has spun itself into a poor woman's ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   What started as a diversion four years ago _ sponsorship of the
first women's sailing crew to compete in the America's Cup _ has
swelled to a five-year agreement with the WNBA, coverage of an LPGA
event, the creation of a Lifetime Sports division and an Internet
site that includes a tutorial, ``Sports 101.''
</P>
<P>
   The results? Doug McCormack, the Lifetime CEO, conceded, ``When
our viewers turn on their sets and get a basketball game, we don't
do as well in the ratings as we do with movies. But anytime you
expand a franchise, you take one step back before you take two
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   There is disagreement as to whether those steps throughout the
industry are forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Women's sports have had unprecedented growth on television. In
addition to Lifetime's commitment, ESPN has expanded its coverage
of college basketball and added such new properties as the WNBA,
the women's World Cup in 1999 and professional fast-pitch softball.
NBC carries some WNBA games. ABC plans World Cup coverage. CBS,
while dropping the women's NCAA basketball tournament, still
carries regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   A universal decrease in coverage is unlikely, given the
proliferation of cable channels. But TV has yet to find a gusher to
join the likes of Olympic women's figure skating and gymnastics,
which appear only once every four years.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the amount of programming has gone up, many of the
ratings have dropped. ESPN drew a 4.0 rating for the NCAA women's
basketball title game in 1997 but fell back to 3.7 this year. One
rating point is equivalent to approximately 980,000 households, so
the drop constituted about 327,000 homes.
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA, despite an extensive marketing campaign created and
funded by the NBA, also has gone backwards in the ratings. In its
first year, the women's league drew average ratings of 2.0 on NBC,
0.9 on ESPN and 0.5 on Lifetime. But in the just-completed season,
including playoffs, it averaged only a 1.6 on NBC, 0.7 on ESPN and
0.5 on Lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   NBC Sports publicist Jennifer Arnold, asked whether the network
is concerned about the decline, said, ``We're in this for the long
haul. In looking at all the factors, this is a sport that is
building a solid foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lifetime spokesman Brett Henne echoed those remarks, saying,
``Our demographics show that we drew in a younger audience, and
that's what we wanted.'' Nonetheless, Lifetime's 0.5 rating (less
than 500,000 homes) pales in comparison with the cable network's
average rating for a movie of 1.8 (1.764 million).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about individual numbers,'' McCormack said.
``Lifetime has an obligation to be a leader in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   Former CBS Sports president Neal Pilson, now a consultant,
speculated that ratings growth isn't imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to grow a sport in the current
environment, when ratings in most sports are on the decline,'' he
said. ``Women's sports has a solid platform _ an advertising base
and a viewer base. I have confidence they'll do OK. But I'd hate to
predict growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will women's sports ever get the ratings of men's sports? I
don't think so. But it could chip away.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Gutkowski, former head of programming at ESPN, said women's
events are ``becoming more attractive for advertisers.'' But he
said it's difficult to project a ratings climb, which ultimately
decides air time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it'll have some pocket hits,'' said Gutkowski,
president of a sports-marketing firm, ``but whether women's sports
will, across the board, see tremendous growth, I'm not sure. NBC
has done a good job (marketing) the WNBA. But (the league) hasn't
represented that it can rate well.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether women's sports programming fits into the category
of hot, uncertain or fad, Gutkowski said, ``It's a hot, uncertain
fad.''
</P>
<P>
   Figure skating and gymnastics long have been the dominant
women's sports, in terms of viewership, and skating has been
particularly strong since the Tonya Harding-Nancy Kerrigan saga in
1994. It's been suggested that the ratings are connected to both
because they are so-called ``leotard sports,'' where women athletes
appear more feminine than in basketball or golf.
</P>
<P>
   But Pilson said, ``I don't see ice skating as a leotard sport.
Ice skating is more story-telling and theater.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN vice president John Wildhack believes viewership of all
women's sports will rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very bullish on the women's sports,'' he said. ``I think
it's here to stay. I don't see any leveling off (in interest).''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN has grown into three networks and needs to fill air time.
Wildhack denied that the growth is the sole reason the company
carries more events. ``As much as we (need) programming, seldom do
we have a situation where we say we have holes to fill,'' he said.
``We try to target marquee properties.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS had carried the NCAA women's finals but let the entire
tournament package go to ESPN. ``I think advertisers are
interested,'' CBS vice president/programming Mike Aresco said.
``Ratings just don't justify a bigger commitment yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
