<P>
   his weekly visits to his old college mentor,
</P>
<P>
   who was near death's door.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE DEATH OF OUTRAGE, by William J. Bennett. (Free Press,
</P>
<P>
   $20.) A former secretary of education takes a critical view
</P>
<P>
   of the Clinton presidency. (b).
</P>
<P>
   4. A PIRATE LOOKS AT FIFTY, by Jimmy Buffett. (Random
</P>
<P>
   House, $24.95.) While traveling from the Florida Keys
</P>
<P>
   to the Amazon, the singer-songwriter reflects on his
</P>
<P>
   half-century of life.
</P>
<P>
   5. THE TEN COMMANDMENTS, by Laura Schlesinger and Stewart
</P>
<P>
   Vogel. (Cliff Street/HarperCollins, $24.) The radio
</P>
<P>
   psychologist and a rabbi discuss the significance of the
</P>
<P>
   Ten Commandments in contemporary life.
</P>
<P>
   6. A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $25.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   7. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt.
</P>
<P>
   (Scribner, $24.) An Irish-American writer
</P>
<P>
   recalls his childhood amid the miseries
</P>
<P>
   of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   8. HIGH CRIMES AND MISDEMEANORS, by Ann H. Coulter.
</P>
<P>
   (Regnery, $24.95.) A lawyer states the case for the
</P>
<P>
   impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   9. CONVERSATIONS WITH GOD: Book 1, by Neale Donald Walsch.
</P>
<P>
   (Putnam, $19.95.) The author addresses questions
</P>
<P>
   of life and love, good and evil, guilt and sin. (b).
</P>
<P>
   10. HIS BRIGHT LIGHT, by Danielle Steel. (Delacorte,
</P>
<P>
   $25.) The novelist recalls the life of her son Nick
</P>
<P>
   Traina, who suffered from manic depression and died at
</P>
<P>
   19.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Longstreet, $22.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans discloses that they
</P>
<P>
   have seven characteristics in common. (b).
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) WE ARE OUR MOTHERS' DAUGHTERS, by Cokie Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   (Morrow, $19.95.) The television news anchor's personal
</P>
<P>
   reflections on women in politics and business, and as mothers,
</P>
<P>
   wives, sisters, and friends.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE GIFTS OF THE JEWS, by Thomas Cahill.
</P>
<P>
   (Talese/Doubleday, $23.50.) What Western civilization
</P>
<P>
   owes an ancient nomadic tribe.
</P>
<P>
   14. A MONK SWIMMING, by Malachy McCourt. (Hyperion,
</P>
<P>
   $23.95.) The writer and actor (and brother of Frank
</P>
<P>
   McCourt) recalls his life in America and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE ROARING 2000s, by Harry S. Dent Jr. (Simon &AMP;
</P>
<P>
   Schuster, $25.) An economist discusses the prospects
</P>
<P>
   for the upcoming millennium. (b).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO, AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. THE 9 STEPS TO FINANCIAL FREEDOM, by Suze
</P>
<P>
   Orman. (Crown, $23.) How to manage your money.
</P>
<P>
   2. SUGAR BUSTERS, by H. Leighton Steward, et al.
</P>
<P>
   (Ballantine, $22.) A diet designed for losing
</P>
<P>
   weight, increasing energy, and combating disease. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. IN THE MEANTIME, by Iyanla Vanzant. (Simon &AMP;
</P>
<P>
   Schuster, $23.) Ways to find what you truly need. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. ONE DAY MY SOUL JUST OPENED UP, by Iyanla Vanzant.
</P>
<P>
   (Fireside/S&AMP;S, $13.) How to raise one's morale and
</P>
<P>
   realize one's ambition.
</P>
<P>
   5.(x) EAT RIGHT 4 YOUR TYPE, by Peter J. D'Adamo with Catherine
</P>
<P>
   Whitney. (Putnam, $22.95.) Diets to suit each of the four
</P>
<P>
   blood types. (b)
</P>
