<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAKER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: RUBE GOES TO TOWN  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By RUSSELL BAKER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I spent four days in New York. It was swell.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the restaurant prices. I'd planned to stay five days
in New York, but after the fourth day, restaurant eating had
already cost me $3,792.87.
</P>
<P>
   That was without wine. By leaving wine alone, you can save $800
to $900 per meal in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ask for water, but don't let them bring you that bottled
imported water all the restaurants push.
</P>
<P>
   That costs $200 to $300 per bottle, depending on where the water
is imported from, whether it was bottled in a vintage year and
whether the bottler has an advanced degree in hydrology.
</P>
<P>
   Stay with tap water. New York tap water is tops, and most
restaurants charge only $10 a glass with one free refill.
</P>
<P>
   My first day in town the president showed up. You know what it's
like when a president leaves Washington. Or maybe you don't.
</P>
<P>
   I once went to a college commencement where a U.S. president
showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Spoiled it for everybody. Cops everywhere, traffic detoured all
the way out to Chaos Township. Armed men standing by metal
detectors to seize absent-minded professors who'd forgotten to
leave their Kalashnikovs at home.
</P>
<P>
   In short: mass-teria!
</P>
<P>
   And that was a small New England town. Imagine what a president
can do to New York. Catastrophe is too mild a word. With Clinton
this week it was King Kong without Fay Wray, the San Francisco
earthquake without Jeanette MacDonald, Iwo Jima without John Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   All right, that's hyperbole, and I don't want to sound cross
with the president. He's got enough people cross at him already.
</P>
<P>
   Not many in New York, though. New Yorkers must have a deep
working knowledge of sin, because those I talked to spoke kindly of
the president and agreed with the New Testament about the moral
qualification required for throwers of the first stone.
</P>
<P>
   This probably shows I was meeting only the most despicable class
of New Yorkers; to wit, liberals. Worse, New York liberals.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be surprising. I was a New York liberal myself until
all the big lecture fees started going to Washington conservatives.
Where was I _ ?
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations, that's where. Some big fuss was on over
there, which brought several dozen alien statesmen to town, and
they had to have V.I.P. treatment, just like Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gigantic cars, sirens, flashing lights, sinister-looking
escorts.
</P>
<P>
   What a mess! Streets that carry a million cars per hour were
closed to traffic. Those millions were detoured into streets that
already had millions of cars parked in congealed masses.
</P>
<P>
   It being the Age of Terrorism, cops in battalion strength were
bivouacked in midtown. Have you noticed that the more security we
Americans have, the less secure we are?
</P>
<P>
   It was exhilarating to walk rapidly through midtown admiring the
security. The reason I walked was that nothing motorized was able
to move for days.
</P>
<P>
   The reason I walked rapidly was that New Yorkers who don't walk
rapidly can be run down and badly dented by other walkers, all of
whom walk at a speed of 22 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   This pace shows they are very busy, or on vital missions
carrying secret papers, or in training for the Olympic
urban-walking competition, or something.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they walk so fast because it makes them feel they're going
someplace important to do something important, whereas slowing down
might give them time to wonder about the pointlessness of things,
especially being treated like sheep so big shots can party under
heavy security.
</P>
<P>
   It's generally supposed that periods of intolerable commotion
like this week's leave New Yorkers exhilarated. You sometimes hear
them say they wouldn't live anyplace else, be it Xanadu or the
Seven Cities of Cibola.
</P>
<P>
   I used to feel that way myself sometimes during my dozen years
of residence. It's seductive. I used to walk 22 miles per hour and
never think about the pointlessness of things and, if confronted by
hicks, boasted about the exhilaration of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Then I found I could no longer walk faster than 21 miles an
hour, and real estate prices went cosmic, and I couldn't cut the
New York mustard anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Still, give me four days now and then, and it's swell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
