<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: THE FINAL WEEKEND TAKES FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bobby Cox has it all figured out. He knows how to
handle the last weekend of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play the game, you get in the plane, you land somewhere,''
Cox said Friday night before his Braves played the New York Mets on
the final Friday of the regular season, with the Mets tied with the
Cubs for the National League wild card.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy for Cox to talk about going wherever the team charter
goes. He has, after all, managed 79 postseason games during his
career with Toronto and Atlanta. Some managers are dispatched
before they get to 79 games in one year.
</P>
<P>
   The logistics and the mind-set of the last weekend can be
complicated. The Braves have got this drill down pat, because they
have the best record in baseball since the start of 1991, winning
one World Series and losing three.
</P>
<P>
   They needed to win one more game this weekend to ensure
themselves the best record in the National League and consequently
the extra home game in the league championship series, if they get
there.
</P>
<P>
   Also, they would not mind eliminating the Mets because that
would mean they would very likely open against the Cubs rather than
face Kevin Brown and the Padres. Cox also had the consolation of
knowing that the Braves are opening at home in the first round _ no
charters till midweek.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have no such assurances. They came here with their
families, not knowing if they would fly happily to Houston on
Sunday night or fly home to New York for a one-game playoff with
the Cubs or perhaps the Giants, or to clean out their lockers for
the winter.
</P>
<P>
   There is a fourth possibility: The rain from Hurricane Georges
could spread northward, threatening the games scheduled for
Saturday and Sunday. Fortunately, the Mets were told to pack for a
trip continuing to Houston, so theoretically they have enough
clothes in their suitcases. But there is that eerie sense of not
knowing what they will be feeling or doing 48 hours from Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a feeling of anticipation, not anxiety,'' said Bobby
Valentine, the Mets' manager.
</P>
<P>
   In that occasional sport of football, players are goaded to
``get up for the big game,'' because it comes around only once a
week. Baseball players cannot afford to seek an emotional high in
every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, your stomach churns,'' Cox said. ``But it's no different
from early in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox did happen to remember the churning in 1985, when he was
managing the Blue Jays, and Butch Wynegar of the Yankees hit a
homer to delay the clinching until Saturday. But Cox, now 57, was
younger then. Is there a temptation to overmanage in the final
weekend of the season, to make that one brilliant move that will
catapult a team into the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had all the answers now, why didn't you do it all
season?'' Cox said. ``It's the other way around, almost. You might
tend to be more conservative, not try to do anything unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox certainly has more experience than Valentine in postseason
games _ 79-0, if you're counting _ but John Schuerholz, the general
manager with the best record in baseball since coming to Atlanta
from Kansas City for the 1991 season, has consistently retooled the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were not total neophytes in big games. John Olerud and
Carlos Baerga, both starting for the Mets on Friday night, have
played in the World Series. So has Al Leiter, Saturday's scheduled
starter, who last year started the seventh game for the world
championship Florida Marlins. (Sounds kind of weird, doesn't it?
Almost as if that never happened.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there's bound to be some question,'' Leiter said about
the confidence level of a team that collectively has not played in
a momentous series. ``But from what I see, the guys are relaxed.
There's always a first time. This three-game series will mean the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Mets have said they did not particularly mind being
on the road for the final weekend of the season. They have heard
the impatient New York fans when the team did not perform well.
``It's kind of sad,'' Valentine said. ``That's not how I would
script it.''
</P>
<P>
   He would script a tie with three games left in the season. He
would even take his chances in a one-game playoff on Monday at
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the finality of the season,'' Valentine said.
``You can touch it. This is why we hold winter meetings. This is
why we took spring training, to get to know each other. We played
159 games. These are your players. We had a pretty loose plane ride
down. Now I can't wait to play the games.''
</P>
<P>
   There would be another plane ride soon. As of Friday night, the
destination, and the mood, were still to be determined.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
