<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-4-QUESTIONS-ART-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW DAY, A NEW URGE TO REFINANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of how refinancing affect the nestegg is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27)  
 (Eds: Please note subslug for BIZ-10-QUESTIONS)  
 (af)  
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this year, it seemed that stock prices would never stop
going up. Now, it seems that mortgage rates will never stop going
down.
</P>
<P>
   Many homeowners are scrambling to refinance their mortgages,
some for a second, third or even fourth time in a decade, as
interest rates have skidded to a 31-year low of 6.64 percent for a
conventional 30-year loan. That is barely one-third the 1981 peak
of 18.63 percent. Indeed, more than half of all mortgage
applications these days are for refinancing.
</P>
<P>
   But should you join the crowd? If so, should you go for the loan
du jour, a 15-year mortgage, instead of the traditional 30?
</P>
<P>
   The experts' answers to these questions may surprise some
people. These are turbulent times, and some long-held assumptions
may no longer apply. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRUISM NO. 1 The higher costs of a 15-year loan ultimately lead
to savings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you want to lower your mortgage rate, you are probably
enticed by 15-year mortgages, with an average rate (6.32 percent)
about one-third of a percentage point below those of 30-year loans.
But many advisers say you should resist the temptation.
</P>
<P>
   The advantages are undeniable: You wind up paying fewer dollars
for your house, and you arrive far earlier at the the peace of mind
that full ownership brings.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the monthly payments are lower on 30-year
mortgages, freeing up money that can be invested elsewhere _
perhaps the stock market. Despite the market's summer swoon, there
is a strong case to be made _ as shown in the accompanying chart _
that money invested in stocks is going to grow faster than equity
sunk into a home on an accelerated payment schedule.
</P>
<P>
   According to Thomas P. Ochsenschlager of Grant Thornton, it
might be wiser to sign a 30-year mortgage and pump the money you
would otherwise spend on higher monthly payments into a mutual
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming average annual returns of 10 percent on the fund, you
would end up with almost $528,000 after 30 years, compared with
$406,000 if you had taken a 15-year-mortgage, waited until you paid
it off and then poured the equivalent of your larger monthly
payments into a similar mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   But Ochsenschlager said the gap would shrink to $38,000 if the
average return fell to 8 percent and would vanish if it dropped
much below that.
</P>
<P>
   And a 30-year loan may be best even if you're getting gray in
the temples. So what if the loan outlasts you? Lenders don't care
how old you are as long as you can make the payments; the house is
collateral. Besides, in the real world, most people move before
they are anywhere near mortgage freedom. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRUISM 2 Don't refinance unless you can slice two percentage
points off your rate. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For many years, that was the general advice; in addition, you
needed to plan on staying put for at least three years in order to
justify the costs. But now, with intensified competition and the
emergence of so-called no-point, no-cost loans, specialists say
refinancing makes sense even if the new rate is only a half-point
lower than the old.
</P>
<P>
   ``That old rule has just totally been thrown out,'' said David
Seiders, economist for the National Association of Home Builders.
Basically, you calculate the reduction in your monthly payment
under the new loan and decide whether you'll keep the house long
enough for the savings to offset the transaction costs.
</P>
<P>
   Those costs can mount, in less-than-obvious ways. If you don't
maintain at least 20 percent ownership when you refinance, for
example, you may end up having to pay for mortgage insurance for
the lender.
</P>
<P>
   And some fees _ for services like an appraisal, credit check,
settlement, deed recording, title insurance, copying and even for
considering the application _ might have to be paid out of pocket,
at costs typically between $1,500 and $3,000. Most can be added to
the loan, but you don't want to wind up with more debt than you can
afford.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest single expense is often ``points'' _ a percentage of
the loan that is due upon signing. (If a bank charges three points
on a $100,000 loan, for example, you have to write a check for
$3,000.)
</P>
<P>
   Points are deductible immediately when you buy a house, but must
be prorated over the life of the loan when you are refinancing. If
you refinance a second time, the unamortized points from the first
refinancing then become deductible right away. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRUISM 3 Always take money at the cheapest rate. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These days, mortgage specialists frown on adjustable-rate
mortgages, or ARMs, which bob up and down every year, or every few
years, in tandem with an underlying interest rate like one-year
Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
   ARMs today are priced at 5.43 percent, roughly a point below
fixed-rate loans. But with fixed-rate mortgages themselves so low
and inflation creeping up, logic suggests that future adjustments
will be up rather than down. Indeed, few homeowners are choosing
ARMs these days.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you don't expect to stay in your home for more than a
few years, you might want to consider a version called the 7-23,
which is especially popular in California. In this ARM you get a
special low rate for the first seven years. By the time it adjusts
upward, the odds are that you will be gone. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRUISM 4 Don't try to time the mortgage market. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this principle stands the test of time. If you want to
refinance, the experts say, you probably shouldn't dally in hopes
that rates might fall a tad more.
</P>
<P>
   Already, they contend, the flight of capital to the United
States as a result of financial turmoil overseas has driven
interest rates on Treasury securities, the chief benchmark in this
country, artificially low.
</P>
<P>
   And keep in mind that a lot of other people are holding out for
the bottom, just as you are, which means that the slightest uptick
will set off a stampede that could not only drive interest rates
even higher but might also overwhelm lenders' processing
capabilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
