<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JONES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON-JONES NEGOTIATIONS CONTINUE; SETTLEMENT COULD BE NEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs for additions and rewriting.)  (lh) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to give President Clinton a stronger
position as Congress considers impeaching him, his lawyers are
involved in intense negotiations with representatives of Paula
Jones and may reach an agreement in the next few days to settle her
sexual misconduct lawsuit against him, advisers to both parties
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the negotiations is the question of how much
Clinton must pay Mrs. Jones to achieve a settlement in the suit
that has led to the impeachment crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones' lawyers Friday rejected a $500,000 offer Clinton
made this week, and they gave the White House until Tuesday morning
to sweeten the pot, the advisers said. Earlier this month, the
White House rejected a request from the Jones camp to pay $1
million to have her withdraw the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House adviser said that the suddenly vigorous
effort to end the lawsuit was being propelled by a political
calculation that doing so would help Clinton present the best case
to Congress to battle any impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we go before Congress on the impeachment matter, the Paula
Jones suit is now still on the table,'' said one Clinton adviser,
who like the others would speak only on condition of not being
named. ``Anything we take off the table may be enormously
helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, associates of the president say that one of
the staunchest opponents of any kind of concession to Mrs. Jones,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, has now acceded to the idea of a
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement, which had appeared elusive for years, is now
possible because of the profoundly changed political _ and some
would say moral _ standing of Clinton since he publicly
acknowledged a sexual liaison with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones' lawyers say that is a major reason why she has
dropped her demand that any settlement include some sort of apology
from the president or some explicit acknowledgment that her claim
about Clinton's behavior was true. Her previous insistence on an
apology had always proved an insurmountable obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones' advisers say she no longer feels a need to prove
that Clinton behaved in a sexually irresponsible manner, given the
avalanche of detailed material about his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The events of the last several weeks and months have
vindicated Paula Jones' case,'' said John W. Whitehead, the
president of the Rutherford Institute, which is financing Mrs.
Jones' legal efforts. He said that any settlement with the
president would constitute an admission of Mrs. Jones' allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones contends that in 1991, when Clinton was governor of
Arkansas, he invited her to his hotel suite in Little Rock and,
when alone with her, made a crude sexual advance. Clinton has
always denied the allegation.
</P>
<P>
   Whitehead said that he was hopeful a settlement would be
reached, but he cautioned that the talks could still fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   Senior White House officials expressed a similar mix of hope and
caution. The advisers said that Mrs. Clinton had only recently been
persuaded to allow negotiations aimed at settling the lawsuit after
firmly resisting such a course since the beginning, because that
could be taken as evidence of his sexual misbehavior. One aide said
that Mrs. Clinton has been anxious over mounting legal bills and
had to be assured that the money for a settlement could come out of
the legal defense fund that has been created for the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, one adviser to the Clintons said, there is a
feeling that a settlement would not affect the president's standing
with the public, which has already taken that part of his character
into account in digesting the report by the Whitewater independent
counsel, Kenneth Starr, about Clinton's liaison with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty obvious why we would like to settle now,'' one
senior adviser to the White House said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the case against the president now being considered in
Congress stems from the lawsuit Mrs. Jones filed in 1994. During a
deposition taken under oath last January, Clinton told Mrs. Jones'
lawyers that he had not engaged in ``sexual relations'' with Ms.
Lewinsky or had an affair with her.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, in his referral to Congress about possible impeachable
offenses, said Clinton had knowingly lied when he gave those
answers, and therefore that he committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his lawyers have argued that while his answers may
have been misleading, they were ``legally accurate'' because of the
definition of sexual relations that was approved by the judge that
day.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement activity comes at a time when the White House is
seeking to fashion some sort of negotiated settlement with Congress
that would allow Clinton to keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a three-judge panel of a federal appeals court is
scheduled to hear arguments on Oct. 20 in St. Paul, Minn., on
whether to reinstate the lawsuit, which was dismissed last April by
a trial judge in Little Rock. If Mrs. Jones' lawyers succeed in
persuading the appeals court to reinstate the lawsuit, it could
mean a new round of discovery in which the president would be
subject to more embarrassing questions about his personal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones' lawyers have already said they intend to use the
contents of the Starr report as part of their case before the
appeals court. White House lawyers and advisers have said they
believe there is a strong likelihood the appeals court panel,
composed of Republican-appointed judges, would rule in favor of
Mrs. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers have said that one reason he has
resisted acknowledging that he misled Mrs. Jones' lawyers is that
such an acknowledgment could be used against him in a revived Jones
lawsuit. Removing the suit might also make it easier for Clinton to
acknowledge unreservedly that his answers in the Jones deposition
were untrue, as many members of Congress have been demanding as
part of some kind of plea bargain.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Such an admission would not eliminate in a legal sense his
culpability for his misleading and possibly perjurious answers in
the Jones deposition. But his advisers say it could allow the
president to argue that Congress would be proceeding on impeachment
on the basis of a civil lawsuit that was not settled.
</P>
<P>
   While that argument may not have any legal merit, White House
officials hope that it would help with members of Congress who are
wavering on whether to seek Clinton's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how that would actually affect deliberations.
Several members of Congress canvassed Friday said they were unsure
that a settlement of the Jones lawsuit would make any difference,
but they also said it was too early to tell.
</P>
<P>
   The judge in the case, Susan Webber Wright, has also raised the
possibility that she would hold Clinton in contempt for offering
misleading testimony in January. A settlement of the suit would not
eliminate that possibility, but White House advisers said they
hoped it would make it harder for Ms. Wright to take such a step.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones' lawyers have suggested that if they do not achieve a
settlement by Tuesday, they will file a petition with the judge to
bolster her resolve to hold a contempt hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Mrs. Jones said she is eager to reach a settlement
and be done with the matter. If the appeals court does not
reinstate the case, she would get nothing after four years of
high-profile litigation.
</P>
<P>
   But there are various claims on any money Mrs. Jones receives in
a settlement, and her friends said she is anxious that not all of
it go to lawyers and expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Her first team of lawyers, who resigned from the case after she
rebuffed a tentative offer that did not include what she deemed a
sufficient apology, have a court order entitling them to at least
$700,000 to cover their legal expenses. The Rutherford Institute
has paid about $400,000 in legal expenses, and Mrs. Jones' new team
of lawyers has also incurred significant costs. Mrs. Jones'
husband, Stephen, was reported to have lost his job with Northwest
Airlines a few months ago, and the family may be in difficult
financial circumstances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
