<SLUG> BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING OVER AND ALREADY IN THE KNOW  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Questions should be boldfaced)  
 (af)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Plucked from relative obscurity, James E. Goodwin became
president and chief operating officer last week of the UAL Corp.,
parent of United Airlines, the country's largest airline and
largest employee-owned company. He succeeded John A. Edwardson, who
resigned after United's two biggest unions made it clear they would
block his becoming chief executive when Gerald Greenwald retires
next year. United's board has hired a search firm to find a
successor for Greenwald.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin, 54, is the ultimate insider. He has spent 32 years at
United, managing virtually every phase of operations, from airplane
maintenance to in-flight food. In his first interview since
becoming president, he spoke from Buenos Aires, where the board met
last week. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You've attended your first board meeting as president. What
are your marching orders? Did the board make clear that you are a
candidate to succeed Gerald Greenwald? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We didn't have any conversations about the succession. But we
did spend some time talking about where we want to take the
company. I have a very tough job ahead of me to step into this job,
and that is where my focus is going to be. The board and Jerry have
the responsibility of looking at the CEO succession; I am going to
focus on running the day-to-day business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Given Edwardson's experience, do you need to mend fences with
the unions? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. John was relatively new to United Airlines. I, on the other
hand, have spent really my entire professional life here. I've
witnessed periods where we had internal conflict that came close to
tearing this company apart. I know our people, and I believe they
know me as someone they can talk to about issues that are pertinent
to their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   I am also not naive enough to believe that we have seen an end
to internal disagreement. But I believe that our employees would
like to see us move forward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Many investors are chary of employee ownership, especially in
the airline industry, because they think it means management can't
be tough with labor. Are they right? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Our investors to some degree don't totally understand the
ESOP structure. That has complicated their view of all the
successes that this company has had over the last four years. We've
improved our balance sheet. We've reduced our debt. We are getting
close to investment-grade rating, and we reallocated resources
during this period of economic crisis in Asia and moved those
capital resources to other parts of our system to generate profits.
All of that has created disruptions to our employee base, and I
think we have demonstrated that we can make the tough decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Our employees also recognize that there are times when we have
to make these tough decisions, just like they did in 1994 when they
agreed to insure the economic health of our company by doing the
ESOP. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The employee stock ownership plan expires in 2000. Should it
be renewed? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know that I can say for certain that it should be
renewed. It clearly has brought value, in terms of tying all our
employees economically to the health of our company. In order for
us to go through the first ESOP, our employees made some
significant financial sacrifices. As a result, they have gained
significant rewards, because our stock price has certainly
reflected the improvement in our earnings.
</P>
<P>
   When you look at the future, I'm not sure whether our employees
would want to step up to another economic investment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Much of the public resents airlines because of high ticket
prices and poor service. What can be done to change that image? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know that I agree that all of the consumers believe
this industry is bad. If you look back over the last 20 years since
deregulation, I think it is very safe to say that consumers have
more choices and are paying less over all. At the same time I
recognize that our airports and our planes are more crowded than
they have ever been, but that is true of our highways and a lot of
our other transportation systems.
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that we as an industry have not done a good
job of is communicating to the consumer what benefits they have
derived from this new era of air transportation. It is probably
something as an industry that we have to do more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
