<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5458 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-SCIENTIFIC-     09-25 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-SCIENTIFIC-MISCONDUCT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-550(2TAKES)NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGES OF RESEARCH FRAUD ARE RAISED AGAINST THE HEAD OF A CORNELL
AIDS LAB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Adds 2nd take of 1200 words chronicling the events leading to the
charges against Dr. Ho.)   (EXCLUSIVE; 10:45 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 12:01 a.m. ET
EMBARGO for electronic media.)  
(js) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cornell University officials are investigating
allegations of scientific misconduct against the head of one of the
university's largest immunology and AIDS-related research labs in
New York City and a recipient of more than $2 million in federal
money, Cornell officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher, Dr. John L. Ho, has been accused by members of
his lab of ordering subordinates to falsify data in one research
grant application; of knowingly using false claims to obtain
another federal grant for $1.5 million; of publishing a paper based
on falsified experiments; and of threatening or punishing members
of the lab who discovered damaging evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the allegations were pieced together from interviews
with seven current and former lab employees, three of whom would
speak only on the condition of anonymity and provided most of the
information, including supporting documents.
</P>
<P>
   Ho, 48, an associate professor of medicine and microbiology at
the Joan and Sanford Weill Medical College and Graduate School of
Medical Sciences of Cornell University, declined to respond to any
charges, saying, ``My guilt or innocence has to be evaluated in the
context of the whole current investigation.'' Asked if he was
guilty of scientific misconduct, he replied: ``I don't believe I
have intentionally conducted scientific misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho is not related to the better-known AIDS researcher Dr. David
Ho, who directs the Aaron Diamond AIDS Research Center, also
located in New York. Though Ho has not achieved renown as an AIDS
researcher, he is viewed by peers as an up-and-coming immunologist.
He sits on research peer review committees of the American Heart
Association and the National Institutes of Health, and his
collaboration in a 10-year, $5-million federal grant to study AIDS
in Haiti gives him a role in the search for an HIV vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The research projects tied to the misconduct inquiry involve
test-tube experiments to determine how the immune system is
affected by various microbes, including those of HIV, tuberculosis
and parasitic diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Hajjar, the dean of the graduate school, said the
university's inquiry began in mid-August, when allegations made by
one member of Ho's lab reached top officials. Dr. Dominic Falcone,
an associate professor of pathology appointed by the dean to
conduct a 60-day inquiry, said in an interview that so far, some,
but not all, of the allegations have been supported by other
people.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the integrity of Ho's research surfaced during
the last 19 months, lab members said. Also at issue in the inquiry,
officials said, is the disappearance of about 60 vials of human DNA
fragments known as plasmids, most of them encoded with HIV proteins
for experimentation. The plasmids vanished from a freezer in late
December, heightening what several researchers described as an
atmosphere of fear and distrust in Ho's lab, which occupies five
rooms on the fourth floor of the New York Hospital medical complex
in Manhattan. University officials said the plasmids had not been
found, but stressed that they were not dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cornell is not interested in anything but getting to the
bottom of it,'' Hajjar said.
</P>
<P>
   After Falcone reports on his inquiry, Hajjar, following
university policy, will decide if the allegations are
``sufficiently substantive'' to open a formal investigation by a
three-member committee, which would require notifying the National
Institutes of Health.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There is growing concern in the scientific community that the
incentives to commit fraud have intensified as competition has
increased among researchers to win grant money and publish
findings. But since research inevitably involves mistakes, proving
intent to mislead has become the key to a formal finding of
scientific misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations as serious as those in the Cornell case are rare,
said Chris Pascal, the acting director of the Federal Office of
Research Integrity, which has the power to prevent researchers from
receiving federal money if they are found to have committed fraud.
He said the office, which is part of the Department of Health and
Human Services, is notified each year of 35 to 40 investigations by
the 3,000 institutions that receive federal research grants, some
involving single instances of plagiarism. It makes about 15
findings of misconduct annually, Pascal said.
</P>
<P>
   Ho's success in winning money from the National Institutes of
Health began in the mid-1990s, about half a dozen years after he
joined the Cornell faculty from Tufts University-New England
Medical Center in Boston. Born in Canton, he is a graduate of the
State University of New York at Stony Brook and was trained as a
doctor at New York University Medical Center and
Columbia-Presbyterian Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble in Ho's lab surfaced in February 1997, after David
Kaufman, a young medical and PhD student, conducted a promising
experiment with blood samples from four people. According to a
detailed account provided by one lab researcher and confirmed by
another, Ho told Kaufman to create a graph in support of a grant
application that would present the results of the four samples as
averages from the blood of 40 people. In what more experienced
members of the lab described as an act of courage unusual in their
hierarchical world, Kaufman refused, telling Ho that such a graph
would be fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the researchers said, Ho ordered Miguel Camargo, a lab
technician, to create the same graph. When Kaufman saw the graph on
Camargo's computer he tried but failed to persuade the technician
to defy Ho, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a lab member familiar with the incident, Ho assured
Camargo that such things were done in grant applications all the
time, and threatened retaliation if he made trouble.
</P>
<P>
   When told about the incident, Pascal said, ``We're not aware
that it's happening all the time, it shouldn't be happening all the
time, and we don't get allegations like that and dismiss them.''
</P>
<P>
   Camargo declined to comment. Kaufman, who left Ho's lab late
last year, refused to answer specific questions, saying: ``I'm a
graduate student at Cornell. It wouldn't be good to discuss this
with you.'' But he added: ``I absolutely don't condone any sort of
scientific misconduct like that. I personally don't like to be
involved in the politics of these situations.''
</P>
<P>
   A second round of questions about Ho's work surfaced in the lab
in spring 1997, when Ricardo Caminha, a physician from Brazil
working on his PhD thesis, tried and failed to reproduce results
that Ho had described in a paper being prepared for publication.
The paper, which Ho and others submitted for publication anyway,
aimed to show the mechanism by which the human immune system
overcomes tuberculosis, pointing to novel treatment strategies.
</P>
<P>
   But when Caminha checked old lab data books, two of his former
colleagues said, he discovered that streptomycin, an antibiotic
used against TB, had been added to the culture medium in the
experiments. They said after Caminha confronted Ho, he was cut from
the project.
</P>
<P>
   When this account was related yesterday to Caminha, who was in
Rio de Janeiro, he said: ``I can't talk to you. I can't confirm or
deny anything about this investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadhana Chitale, a postdoctoral fellow who was a co-author of
the paper, said she had worked on a different aspect of the
research and could not comment on the streptomycin. She went on to
say, ``I was told there was an oversight, that it was added by
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   She said, ``I tried to keep myself distant'' from the conflicts
in the lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a job to keep,'' she said. ``I do whatever is assigned
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   By fall 1997, a third controversy had erupted in the lab, this
one over the $1.5 million federal research grant that Ho had won in
1996 to study an unusual molecule known as LPG, which other
scientists have shown is used by the parasitic disease
leishmaniasis to thwart the body's defenses.
</P>
<P>
   In his grant application, Ho said that in test-tube experiments
he had found an interesting property of LPG: it reduced the level
of HIV, while not inhibiting the proliferation of healthy cells. At
least two researchers in the lab, Magda Carvalho and Ana Teresa
Nogueira Dumans, built LPG experiments based on that crucial claim.
</P>
<P>
   But lab members said that when Ms. Dumans gathered the lab's
past studies on LPG, she discovered test results in February 1995
demonstrating that contrary to Ho's 1996 grant application, LPG did
inhibit cell proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   Ho's longtime lab technician, Howard Doo, confirmed in a
telephone interview that he had performed LPG tests in 1994 and
1995 that showed the molecule blocked cell growth, and had turned
over all his results to Ho. Two other researchers said that when
Ms. Dumans confronted Ho about this, he denied seeing his
technician's data before writing the grant.
</P>
<P>
   Doo, who worked in the lab for six years and left this spring,
said he could not remember the events well and was unaware of any
misconduct. He added, ``I'm a friend of Dr. Ho.'' Ms. Dumans did
not return calls, and Carvalho declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The disappearance of the plasmids in December 1997 distressed
the lab members again, researchers said. Sabotage and theft were
possible explanations discussed in the aftermath, Doo said. Ms.
Chitale called the disappearance scary.
</P>
<P>
   Ho took the unusual step of placing a lock on the lab freezer,
retained the key himself and doled out material for experiments bit
by bit.
</P>
<P>
   According to an account confirmed by three researchers, one day
in May Ms. Dumans and Caminha were left without access to the
supplies in the freezer they needed to keep lab experiments from
ruin. After trying to reach Ho at home, they opened the freezer by
unscrewing the hinges. Both were reprimanded by Ho over the
incident, two researchers said, and left soon afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Ho then tried to defuse criticism at a session for his lab's
researchers. Two people who attended said Ho tried to demonstrate
his motivation as a researcher by showing slides of dying children
in a Cambodian refugee camp in Thailand where he had worked as
medical coordinator early in his career.
</P>
<P>
   But the session did not quell complaints. In late June, as the
allegations filtered out, Dr. Warren Johnson, chief of the Division
of International Medicine and Infectious Diseases and Ho's
supervisor, was asked to look into the controversy, said Paul
Macielak, a Cornell spokesman. Johnson, who is principal
investigator in the same 10-year AIDS study on which Ho is working,
declined to comment. But others said that after a brief review,
Johnson told the lab members there was no problem.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks later, after a researcher pressed the issue with
university officials, the present inquiry began.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
