<SLUG> BC-BBA-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR JIMY WILLIAMS, THE JOURNEY CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Through it all _ through the early Yankee blitzkrieg
which turned the American League East race into a quest for a
wild-card slot before Father's Day, through the September swoon,
through the trials and tribulations of Pedro Martinez, through the
ongoing Mo Vaughn soap opera, through the snickers and the sniping
from his critics who joked about everything from the way he talked
to the way he managed _ the man in the office just off the Red Sox'
clubhouse at Fenway Park was consistent and unflappable.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy was, well, Jimy, and if that wasn't good enough for some
people, so be it. Jimy Williams really didn't care. He would run
the club the same way he had run the Blue Jays from 1986-89 and
almost the same way he had done things since 1974 when he was a
rookie minor league manager at Quad Cities.
</P>
<P>
   Through all those years and all those teams, Jimy Williams had
never managed a team that won a pennant. Now he has a shot to do it
here, because with Thursday night's 9-6 victory over the Baltimore
Orioles, the wild-card Red Sox are in the AL playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we're down to zero now,'' said Williams with a smile,
referring to the raging topic of the past several days as the Red
Sox gradually reduced their magic number in quest of their first
playoff appearance since 1995. ``It feels good. They earned it.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Williams, who was greeted in Boston with as much
skepticism as praise when he was hired as the 41st manager of the
Red Sox on Nov. 19, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In typical fashion, Williams deflected the praise, to the
players, to the coaches and trainers, to upper management. He
talked about the highlights of a season that was, despite the woes
of September when almost everyone seemed to be struggling, a joyous
surprise. It all started on Good Friday when Vaughn's ninth-inning
grand slam gave the Sox a come-from-behind victory over Seattle in
their home opener, seemingly setting the tone for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Sox can relax for three days and wonder whom they will
face in next week's best-of-five Division Series, either slumping
Cleveland or surging Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say we're a wild-card team. But I call it a four-legged
race,'' said Williams, referring to the two-tiered playoffs that
will determine the AL World Series representative. ``Can we get
there? We'll see. All I know is that we're going to be somewhere
next week. That's what the wild card does. It travels.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jimy Williams _ who came so close in 1987 with Toronto
before watching his team lose its last seven games and get nudged
out by Detroit, who was part of the Atlanta Braves' dynastic run
through the early '90s as a coach, and who is now the leader of
this improbable wild-card team _ the journey is just beginning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
