<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-watch-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  New York Times Votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, Sept. 25 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: WAGE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Tuesday voted to block a minimum wage increase. By a
55-44 vote, senators decided to table -- or set aside for the year
-- a proposal to raise the federal minimum wage by $1 over the next
two years. Supporters of the procedural vote cited an increase in
the minimum wage within the past several years. Opponents of the
motion to kill the increase said it would have helped working
families stay above the poverty line. A ``yes'' vote favors tabling
the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: BANKRUPT
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Wednesday voted, 97-1, to overhaul the nation's
bankruptcy laws, making it more difficult for consumers to file for
bankruptcy. Supporters said the law needs to be changed because
currently many people exploit the bankruptcy system to get out of
paying debts. The opponent said the overhaul would make it harder
for those who legitimately need to file for bankruptcy to do so. A
``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: FAA
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Friday voted, 92-1, to renew Federal Aviation
Administration programs and earmark $10.1 billion in fiscal 1999
for the agency. The measure would increase flights at busy airports
while restricting flights over national parks. Supporters said the
legislation would provide increased service to underserved areas.
The opponent said the legislation goes against previous agreements
to turn airports over to regional authorities. A ``yes'' vote
favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: SCHOOLS
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Sept. 18, the House approved a measure, 212-198, that
would reallocate money from 31 federal education programs to block
grants given directly to the states. The grants would total $2.7
billion in 1999 and $14.3 billion over five years. Supporters said
it would allow teachers and students to focus on learning.
Opponents said the measure would not address serious education
problems, such as classroom overcrowding and a lack of qualified
teachers. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: IMMIGRANTS
</P>
<P>
   The House Thursday approved, 288-133, a bill that would allow
more skilled immigrants to work in the United States. The measure
would increase the number of visas given to immigrants who would
work in such high-tech fields as computer programming and
engineering. Supporters said the bill would not necessarily result
in immigrants taking jobs away from U.S. workers. Opponents said
companies will lay off U.S. workers to hire immigrants who will
work for lower wages. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: SS
</P>
<P>
   The House Friday voted, 240-188, to set aside a portion of the
budget surplus for Social Security. The measure would place 90
percent of the estimated $1.6 trillion budget surplus over the next
10 years in a reserve account until the future of Social Security
is set. Supporters, mostly Republicans, said the measure could save
Social Security, and the remaining 10 percent could be used to cut
taxes. Opponents said the entire surplus should be put into the
reserve account and that using the money for tax cuts would be an
assault on Social Security. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   The attendance record tracks the cumulative attendance of
members to date when they are physically present for roll call
votes.
</P>
