<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5471 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS &LR;      09-25 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL OK'S RELEASE OF SECRET RECORDINGS OF LEWINSKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The secretly recorded voice of Monica S. Lewinsky
discussing her affair with President Clinton will soon reach the
airwaves, after the House Judiciary Committee voted Friday night to
release portions of Linda R. Tripp's audiotapes and nearly 40,000
additional documents related to the sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Amid intense jockeying for public support in advance of a
probable full impeachment investigation, the deeply divided
committee unanimously approved releasing edited transcripts and
copies of Tripp's 17 tapes of her talks with Lewinsky. The
transcripts are expected to be available by next Thursday, with the
other 40,000 documents and the audiotapes released several days
later.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy, closed-door fray Friday, the Republican majority
on the Judiciary Committee joined far more attempts by Democrats
than in a similar session last week to black out sexually explicit
material that could be damaging to Clinton and offensive to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats were stymied in numerous other efforts,
including attempts to define the scope of the inquiry and to gain
access to about 20 boxes of investigative material on the Lewinsky
case that Starr did not deliver to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 25 unanimous votes today, but on the biggies, we
didn't make it,'' said Representative John Conyers Jr. of Michigan,
the highest ranking Democrat on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Tripp tapes, including some whose authenticity is under
investigation, triggered the probe by the independent counsel,
Kenneth W. Starr, that resulted in the preliminary House
impeachment inquiry. Their release will provide Americans with
their first chance to hear Lewinsky's voice.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the first avalanche of Starr's investigative material
released Monday, the final batch, including the Tripp tapes, will
include relatively little sexually explicit material, several
lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   The mass of evidence to be released also includes FBI interviews
and transcripts of grand jury testimony involving dozens of
witnesses before Starr's grand jury, including such central figures
as Clinton's secretary, Betty Currie, and Vernon E. Jordan Jr., a
Clinton confidant who helped Lewinsky find a job around the time
she filed a false affidavit denying her sexual relationship with
the president.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican majority on the Judiciary Committee, facing
heightened concern about a potential backlash from another large
release of sexually explicit material, rebuffed far fewer
Democratic attempts to black out salacious references in this mound
of investigative material than they did last week.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, three Republicans joined the Democratic
minority in voting 17-16 to approve blacking out sexually explicit
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't going to be shocked anymore,'' said
Representative W. Asa Hutchinson, an Arkansas Republican who serves
on the committee. ``The blushing days are over.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat who
serves on the committee, attributed the bipartisanship over
withholding some material to GOP fears of the inquiry backfiring.
``I think Republicans recognize the fact that most Americans feel
the president is being railroaded, so they are making more of an
attempt to at least appear bipartisan,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   To Democrats, the most important issue other than withholding
inappropriate material was a motion by Conyers to permit the
committee to review the investigative documents that Starr
withheld. Several Democrats said the material could include
evidence that is exculpatory for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Starr informed the committee he would release the material upon
a joint request from the panel. But Conyers' move failed along
party lines, with all Republcans against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is not the independent counsel,'' said
Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat. ``It's the
Republicans, who don't want us to see the information.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican counterattack on the Conyers motion was led by
Representative Bob Barr, a Georgia Republican who was one of the
first House members to call for Clinton's impeachment. Other GOP
members joined him, calling the motion a veiled attack on Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also rejected a Democratic motion to investigate
Starr's request in January to Attorney General Janet Reno to expand
his Whitewater probe to the Lewinsky matter. All Republicans on the
37-member committee rejected the motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not appropriate for us to be diverted by an effort to
discredit the independent counsel,'' said Representative Charles
Canady, a Florida Republican and committee member.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton maintained his newly aggressive stance
toward Congress Friday, lashing out at Republicans for having
approved only one of 13 appropriation bills with a week left before
the end of the fiscal year. He renewed the attack after signing a
stopgap spending measure to keep the government running through
Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislation is a regrettable sign that the Republican
majority in Congress has failed to address the urgent priorities of
the American people,'' Clinton said before leaving Washington for a
weekend fund-raising blitz.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Republicans was one more salvo fired by the White
House as it seeks to persuade the public that Clinton is focused on
tending to the nation's business while the GOP is fixated on moving
forward with impeachment proceedings against him. If Congress does
not approve more appropriation bills by Oct. 9, Clinton will be
forced to sign another stopgap measure to avert a government
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flew Friday to Chicago, where he promoted his education
policies at an elementary school and attended a luncheon expected
to raise $250,000 for Representative Glenn Poshard, a gubernatorial
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   From Chicago, Clinton was heading west to San Jose and Los
Angeles for more fund-raising and to join the first lady for a
visit with their daughter, Chelsea. He also was set to attend DNC
fund-raisers in San Antonio and Houston, before returning to
Washington late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton's private lawyers and those for Paula Corbin
Jones were expected to continue talks over the weekend to end the
four years of legal wrangling over her sexual harassment suit
against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Jones's attorneys approached the Clinton team 2 1/2 weeks ago
with a proposal that they drop their plan to appeal a judge's
ruling in the case in exchange for a roughly $1 million cash
settlement, said a lawyer for Jones. Jones would also drop her
demand for an apology from Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, Clinton's private attorney, Robert S. Bennett,
countered with an offer of about $500,000, according to the Jones
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the probability'' for settlement, the lawyer
said. ``In this kind of case, with politicians, you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jones lawyer said an apology, which had been the biggest
obstacle in previous negotiations, was no longer an issue. Jones
now feels vindicated by Clinton's acknowledgment in his Aug. 17
grand jury testimony that he was not necessarily forthcoming or
entirely truthful in the deposition he gave in the Jones case last
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an admission,'' her lawyer said. ``Paula Jones, in the
events over the last couple of months, has been vindicated. It's no
longer he said-she said. You got your basic apology; it's the best
of both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge appeals court panel in St. Paul is scheduled to
hear Jones's appeal Oct. 20. Her case was thrown out by US District
Judge Susan Webber Wright in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Jones were planning to file a motion of contempt
next week asking Wright to sanction Clinton for lying in the
deposition. Under the terms of the settlement, they would also drop
those plans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
