<HEADLINE>
BC, FACING NOTRE DAME, HOPES TO WIN FOURTH STRAIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ One to go for 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College will attempt to cap a perfect September and get
off to its best start since 1992 (7-0-1) Saturday against
Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here for two years, but I'll tell you, it's a lot
different,'' said junior nose guard Chris Hovan, referring to the
positive atmosphere surrounding the team. ``It's a lot different
when you walk on campus and everything. Guys on this team really
believe in each other. I think it's really the main cog of this
team. It's team unity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles have sailed along in their first three games,
including last week's 31-7 triumph over Temple. Then BC hit its
first bump in the road when coach Tom O'Brien placed junior running
back Quinton Lee, backup to senior workhorse Mike Cloud, on
indefinite suspension following his arrest last Sunday morning on
charges of disorderly conduct and assault and battery on an
officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fine,'' said O'Brien when asked about his team's
response to its first encounter with adversity. ``They've practiced
hard and they've worked hard. There's no excuse for us not to play
a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloud, the nation's No. 2 rusher (88 carries, 552 yards, 7
touchdowns), will have to shoulder more of a burden but will have
some help from sophomore Cedric Washington and junior Carlton Rowe.
</P>
<P>
   BC will also be without sophomore tight end Robert Ellis, who
injured his left shoulder against Temple. Ellis will be replaced by
redshirt freshman Josh Cervi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally, I think it was (a loss),'' Cloud said of Lee's
suspension. ``Everyone was friends with Quinton, and Quinton was a
great guy. He was funny and everything. But I think we've just got
to put it in the back of our minds and focus on this next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a meeting right after it happened, and (senior
cocaptain) Brian Maye said, `We've just got to put it in the back
of our minds and think about the upcoming games.' Quinton was a
friend to all of us, but we've just got to stay focused and not let
all that we've done slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge facing BC's offense this week will be to maintain
its balanced attack in the face of Louisville's ``storm'' defense,
patterned after Arizona's Desert Swarm, which utilizes a flex
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, BC will have to stop the wide-open passing game
installed by first-year Louisville coach John L. Smith, whose team
snapped a 10-game losing streak last week with a 35-9 win at
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, who held Temple's fourth-ranked rushing attack to
151 yards _ barely half its average _ last week, will have to
switch gears, focusing on Cardinals quarterback Chris Redman, the
No. 5 passer in the nation (81 for 151, 993 yards, 6 TDs).
</P>
<P>
   Redman has been sacked just once this season. ``I think it's due
in large part to him because he never holds the ball,'' O'Brien
said. ``It's tough to get to him because the ball comes out fast.
Obviously, they have a good line, but he helps them because he
doesn't hang on to the ball that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Redman's favorite target, tight end Ibn Green, will be back
after sitting out last week's game with a viral infection. Green,
Redman's teammate at Louisville Male High, was hospitalized last
Monday and Tuesday, lost 15 pounds, and was unable to travel with
the team to Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Redman still completed 27 of 50 passes for 275 yards, including
a 26-yard TD to Arnold Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   He's one of the obstacles standing in the way of 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just play it week to week,'' said O'Brien, whose team will
be off next week before hosting Virginia Tech Oct. 8. ``But we just
want to beat Louisville. So if we beat 'em, then we're 4-0 and
that's great. But the key thing is just to win. We want to keep
winning. I said to the team earlier in the week that we'll worry
about the record at the end of the year. We just have to play it
week to week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
