<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS ALMOST OUT OF DAVIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Breaker, breaker, breaker, breaker _ broken. And
just about busted out is the United States, whose reserves weren't
much in the clutch _ four tie-breakers _ as lightly regarded Italy
pounced for a huge 2-0 lead in their best-of-five Davis Cup
semifinal Friday at an outpost that seemed a desert island in the
scheme of things.
</P>
<P>
   Though the American cupboard wasn't quite bare after Pete
Sampras, Andre Agassi, and Michael Chang mailed in their regrets,
there wasn't much shelf life in the leftovers _ a frazzled rookie,
Jan-Michael Gambill, and a used-up Todd Martin.
</P>
<P>
   If Gambill, ranked No. 50, and Martin, No. 28, are perhaps
household names here and there in this land, the guys who tied up
and broke them, No. 37 Andrea Gaudenzi and No. 47 Davide
Sanguinetti, are strangers everywhere but Italy, where their
headlines are very heady this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is favored in Davis Cup _ funny things happen. We can't
believe it, but we did it,'' beamed the All-American Italian,
Sanguinetti, who ran the slow-reacting, 6-foot-6-inch Martin out of
the Arena, 7-6 (7-0), 6-3, 7-6 (10-8), in the second match.
Sanguinetti, 26 today, won his A-A status five years ago at UCLA,
where he made the NCAA semis, although he was the team's No. 6
player.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Cup debut jitters seized 21-year-old Gambill immediately.
(Remember Sampras freezing in his 1991 coming-out, losing both
singles, to Henri Leconte and Guy Forget, in the defeat by France
in the final?) Though the unorthodox Gambill _ who uses both hands
both ways, a la Monica Seles _ recovered momentarily to bake a
second-set bagel and gamely banged his way out of eight match
points as Gaudenzi anguished, he was down, up, down, down like the
market. In a wacky, suspenseful but loosely played bout, he came
apart, 6-2, 0-6, 7-6 (7-0), 7-6 (7-4).
</P>
<P>
   The critical game: Gaudenzi held to 6-5 in the fourth through
two break points. ``If I don't,'' he said, ``I could be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The US needs a doubles win today from another rookie,
21-year-old Justin Gimelstob, plus Martin, over Diego Nargiso and
Gaudenzi to avoid impeachment and keep alive a shot at the Cup.
Sweden, leading Spain, 2-0, appears ready to win the 98-year-old
crock for a second successive year.
</P>
<P>
   The Gambill gamble didn't work for US captain Tom Gullikson, who
selected him over sore-armed Jim Courier. ``I was never so nervous;
it was my most disappointing loss. I was playing for more than
me,'' said Gambill, beaten by superior experience. Gaudenzi (11-7
in Cup singles) held down his errors to 37 while the American
sprayed 66. Sanguinetti, unburdened mentally with the 1-0 lead,
made 23 mistakes. Martin, in a must-win situation, had 50 and
couldn't punish with his big gun, the volley.
</P>
<P>
   Has the US ever revived from 0-2? Oh, yes. In 1934, against
Australia in a semi at Wimbledon. Andre Agassi's late
grandfather-in-law, Frank Shields, beat Viv McGrath in the deciding
match.
</P>
<P>
   That's the news. Now the damning questions about US Tennis
Association blunders which call for censure:
</P>
<P>
   Why was this important engagement played in uninterested
Milwaukee, where merely 3,500 attended _ albeit spirited, stomping,
flag-flapping folk _ in an 8,000-seat building?
</P>
<P>
   Why wasn't it played in Las Vegas, home of America's best
Cupper, Andre Agassi, where the 1995 semi against Sweden drew about
10,000 daily? Agassi, who opted out to host a benefit for his
charitable foundation, says he would have found time to play this
weekend in his neighborhood. In the lineup on a hard court, he
would have been worth two wins himself. When you've got Agassi's
phone number, you'd better call often and get his OK on every move.
Obviously. Davis Cup committee chairman Bo Driskill says the USTA
couldn't find a Vegas site. Agassi says he would have found it
personally.
</P>
<P>
   Why, with the home-court edge, did the US generously give that
advantage away by installing a turgid carpet? The Italians,
dirt-kickers who lust for slow courts, couldn't believe the gift.
``The court was so slow, like clay,'' said Sanguinetti with a grin.
So you're stuck with Gambill and Martin? You bring in the fastest
rug you can find, even if you have to soak and freeze it.
</P>
<P>
   Although the USTA has booked Delray Beach, Fla., for the
December final, presumably against Sweden, one hopes it didn't make
a nonrefundable deposit on the hotel rooms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
