<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL TO RELEASE EDITED AUDIOTAPES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans will soon be able to hear Monica Lewinsky
talk about her relationship with President Clinton whether they
want to or not.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee made that decision for them
Friday, voting to release edited versions of 27 audiotapes that
Linda Tripp surreptitiously made of her conversations with
Lewinsky. Tripp turned the tapes over to independent counsel
Kenneth Starr, who used them to seek expansion of his investigation
to include allegations that the president lied about and tried to
cover up his sexual encounters with the former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-member panel of 21 Republicans and 16 Democrats also
agreed to make public what one member described as 40,000
additional pages of testimony and other documents that Starr used
to bolster his report to Congress outlining 11 charges against the
president that could amount to impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's decision after a daylong, closed-door meeting
that was described as ``civil and contentious'' by one member,
fulfilled a House resolution passed two weeks ago calling on the
panel to release as much of the Starr materials as possible.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the country has been exposed to Lewinsky's sexually
explicit testimony about her trysts with the president, as well as
Clinton's own videotaped testimony in which he was questioned
repeatedly about those encounters. Now the public will be able to
hear Lewinsky's own voice as she recounts the affair to Tripp and
then read Tripp's testimony before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The information will also include the testimony of Washington
lawyer and Clinton friend, Vernon Jordan, as well as that of the
president's personal secretary Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
   But committee members insisted that the information, which will
be released late next week, has been severely edited so as not to
include as much graphic and salacious detail as some of the other
Starr materials that Congress has released. Committee member Asa
Hutchison, R-Ark., described the new materials as the G-rated
version, suggesting that instances of profanity, gossip and
references to people unrelated to the Clinton-Lewinsky matter will
be erased from the tapes before copies are released.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say you're not going to get shocked anymore. The blushing
days are behind us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats hailed the decision by Republicans to support more
severe editing of the materials as a victory of sorts. Most of the
16 Democrats on the committee had argued against releasing any
information at all until the committee had at least settled the
question of whether to proceed with impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion polls have supported that view as well, and
Democrats were quick to suggest that the GOP had finally gotten the
public's message that ``enough is enough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a victory in that Republicans recognize they may have
been too hasty in releasing as much information as we have,'' said
committee member Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Although Friday's committee session started off in a bipartisan
fashion with a series of unanimous votes on a dozen motions, the
partisanship reasserted itself when Democrats sought to obtain more
information from Starr, including any notes and briefing papers
that were presented to Attorney General Janet Reno by Starr last
January when he sought and received her permission to expand his
investigation based on the Tripp tapes.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats said they were concerned about reports that Starr
may not have presented an accurate picture to Reno of what the
Tripp tapes contained.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee described the motion to request more information
from Starr as ``a procedural issue of great importance'' that would
have given committee members better information about how the
decision was made to expand a four-year investigation of Whitewater
and other matters to include sex in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans rejected the motion on a party line vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some members on the Democratic side who simply want
to conduct an investigation of Mr. Starr's investigation,'' said
committee member Charles Canady, R-Fla. ``That is not the question
before us. It's not appropriate for us to be diverted by an effort
to discredit the independent counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also rejected a Democratic motion calling on the
committee to define what constitutes an impeachable offense before
proceeding with the release of more materials or hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee called it ``shocking'' that member of the committee
``could not even reach agreement on that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still not working together and collaborating together on
establishing any standards,'' she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to release more Starr materials was never in doubt,
given the resolution that passed the House with only 63 dissenters
two weeks ago. But the redactions that the committee agreed to make
in the materials went much further than expected
</P>
<P>
   For example, the testimony from more than a dozen witnesses
before the grand jury will not be included in the released
material. The omitted information includes testimony from FBI and
Secret Service agents, as well as Lewinsky's mother who appeared
twice before the Starr panel.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, most members of the committee had not yet gone
through all the materials supplied to Congress by Starr. But over
the next 10 days, the committee staff will prepare a report of its
own on the information, which will be presented to the committee
Oct. 5 or 6. After the committee hears from the staff, it's
expected to pass a resolution calling for the House to open an
official inquiry of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
