<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurricanes bring happiness to some
 &HT;    By Rachel Masory
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Hurricane Andrew brought Katia Lynch a
husband. Hurricane Georges brought her a daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lives are pretty much marked by hurricanes,'' Katia said.
</P>
<P>
   Katia, 29, and James, 35, were both working for Allstate
Insurance when Hurricane Andrew hit South Florida in 1992. James
worked in New York, Katia in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   James volunteered to come down to South Florida six days after
the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked out of the Miami office for one week,'' James said.
``My last day there, I asked her out and she said yes _ after
looking at me like I had three heads.''
</P>
<P>
   James worked out of the Homestead office for another eight
months. The couple got engaged on Aug. 19, 1993; they married on
Aug. 19, 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, in Lake Charleston in suburban Boynton Beach,
the Lynches were preparing for the birth of their first child when
Hurricane Georges threatened South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our lives are pretty much marked by hurricanes and it's always
been good things,'' Katia said. ``So I guess I shouldn't get
scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I got nervous about the hurricane and in my
subconscious, I just decided to go into labor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Katia gave birth to Erika Lynch, 8 pounds and 3 ounces, at 11:58
p.m. Thursday at Boca Raton Community Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's just perfect, my daughter and my beautiful wife,''
beamed James.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family have asked if they named their daughter
Georgette or Georgiana. ``I don't think so!'' James said.
</P>
<P>
   James, a homeowner adjuster for SCS &AMP; Associates, expects to be
very busy after Georges passes through. Katia, an accountant, plans
to return to her job in three months.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
