<HEADER>
A5492 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     09-25 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAF FIGHTS WAR OF WORDS WITH HALLOW POINTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Streams of unconsciousness while wondering if you can
retroactively change a Heisman ballot:
</P>
<P>
   Some videotape just never gets old, like the frames of the
Chargers' Ryan Leaf throwing a tantrum at a reporter this week. It
took Leaf only three games to become the most immature starting
quarterback in the NFL, breaking the previous record held by Jeff
George.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf, 22 going on 2, got upset because a reporter reported that
Leaf cursed a TV crew filming postgame interviews Sunday. One
presumes the crew was asking Leaf how it felt to go 1 for 15
passing against the Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Life isn't easy for quarterbacks in the NFL, especially for
rookie quarterbacks. But you'd think Leaf would know better than to
attempt career suicide so early.
</P>
<P>
   He did play on a Rose Bowl team last year, so he shouldn't be
intimidated by questions. He went through a rough sophomore year,
too, in which Washington State coach Mike Price had to sit on the
kid's habit of blaming everyone else for mistakes and losses.
</P>
<P>
   He also has one of the better agents around in Leigh Steinberg.
Perhaps Leaf should read a copy of the new book written by
Steinberg: ``Winning With Integrity.'' There must be a chapter in
there about losing with integrity in there.
</P>
<P>
   What all this does most is make one wonder about Leaf's
formative years. Sure enough, there's something creepy under his
rocks. The Seattle Post-Intelligencer did a story during the Rose
Bowl crush on Leaf's reputation around his hometown, Great Falls,
Mont.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Great Falls didn't think Leaf was so great. He
quit his high school basketball team as a junior after flipping off
the home crowd. Local police often found him driving his car 100
miles an hour along the interstate. He was considered cocky, brash
and rude, Great Falls' own version of Brian Bosworth. The Boz was
last seen getting mowed out of the NFL by Bo Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf reportedly ticked off a lot of his Charger teammates by
holding out and then arriving with an attitude. Junior Seau tried
to snap him out of it behind closed doors, but his attempts
reportedly only made Leaf cop more attitude.
</P>
<P>
   If Leaf isn't careful, he'll get fragged by his own troops. ...
</P>
<P>
   Considering his blood lines, it's not the least bit surprising
to see Peyton Manning struggle in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   His dad Archie never played on a NFL team that had a winning
record. Never. The closest he came was 1979, when the Saints went
8-8. In 1983, he was traded to Minnesota, which finished 8-8, but
he didn't play a down for the Vikings all season.
</P>
<P>
   Archie won his first game with the Saints, 24-20, against the
Rams (why is that not shocking?). But the Saints would win only 18
games in his first five seasons. He sat out 1976 with an injury. In
the next five seasons, from 1977 to 1981, Manning and the Saints
would win only 19 more games.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints under Manning went 2-11-1 in 1972, 2-12 in 1975, 3-11
in 1977, 1-15 in 1980, and 4-12 in 1981. With Houston in 1981, the
Oilers went 1-8, and the Vikings went 3-12 in 1984, Manning's last
season in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Manning didn't exactly play for many Hall of Fame coaches. The
list includes J.D. Roberts. John North, Ernie Hefferle, Hank Stram
(post-Chiefs era), Dick Nolan, Dick Stanfel, Bum Phillips
(post-Oilers era), Ed Biles, Chuck Studley and Les Steckle. ...
</P>
<P>
   The rash of quarterback injuries has led me to discover a great
new NFL pool.
</P>
<P>
   Before each season, 20 or so football fans get together and
select which NFL quarterback they think will be sidelined first by
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps each player picks three quarterbacks in this injury
pool, and he earns points for each game missed or severity of
injury. A re-entry draft could be included at various stages of the
season to keep the game fresh and lively.
</P>
<P>
   I'm calling the patent office. ...
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Kosar doesn't know it yet, but the front office executive
for the new Cleveland Browns may also have to be the team's backup
quarterback. If the NFL's lack of depth at quarterback is bad now
with 30 teams, imagine how diluted things will become when it
expands to 32 teams. If L.A. ever gets a team, Pat Haden may be
asked to play quarterback. ...
</P>
<P>
   Erstwhile Ram Deacon Jones remains in the spotlight here despite
the Rams' departure and L.A.'s NFL-less status. He's created his
own charity foundation dedicated to education, employment and
mentoring for inner-city children, and has the support of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Until otherwise noted, that's as close as L.A. will get to the
NFL, beyond the TV screen. ...
</P>
<P>
   The always active Los Angeles chapter of the NFL Alumni group,
which has put on benefits for youth groups, children's museums and
juvenile detention facilities, will hold its annual golf classic
Monday at Coto de Caza Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Children's Hospital of Orange County (CHOC) will be
the beneficiary. For information, call (310) 787-1573. ...
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Ryan Leaf needs a heart-to-heart talk from a rookie who is
dealing well with the expectations of being a first round pick
Randy Moss. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
