<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-GEORGES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE GEORGES BATTERS FLORIDA KEYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for comprehensive update)  (ART ADV: Photo and map for use with this story are being sent to
NYT photo and graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After leaving nearly 300 people dead in a five-day
rampage across the Caribbean, Hurricane Georges slammed into the
Florida Keys Friday with winds of more than 100 miles an hour,
causing widespread flooding and extensive damage to buildings,
roads and harbors but apparently no deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Friday evening, the powerful storm moved into the Gulf of Mexico
on a track aimed away from the Florida peninsula and almost
directly at Mobile, Ala. But fears that heavily populated areas of
Florida's Gulf Coast could be inundated by the heavy rainfall
accompanying the hurricane led authorities to extend evacuation
directives to include a total of 1.4 million people, or nearly a
10th of the state's population, including 346,000 residents of the
Tampa area.
</P>
<P>
   In both Tampa and Miami, hurricane shelters were said to be
filled to capacity. To ease that strain, emergency management
officials in Tampa suggested that those leaving their homes in
vulnerable coastal areas seek refuge with relatives or friends.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hurricane Center here forecast that the hurricane
would strengthen by late Saturday to a Category 3 storm, with
sustained winds of at least 111 miles an hour. A hurricane watch
was issued for the northern coast of the Gulf of Mexico, from
Morgan City, La., to the Florida panhandle, and meteorologists
warned that the storm could make landfall again as early as Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With 105-mile-an-hour winds and storm surges of as much as seven
feet, the core of the storm hit Key West just before midday,
creating whiteout conditions much like those of a snowstorm and
knocking out the last remnants of electrical power. The storm's
passage coincided with high tide, leading to extensive flooding
throughout the islands of the lower Keys, most of which are barely
above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   On Little Torch Key, about 22 miles northeast of Key West, the
water was reported to be four feet above canals, causing some boats
to float into the yards of residents. Callers to a local radio
station reported seeing a fish swimming along one submerged road
and a refrigerator floating down another, both in the area of
Cudjoe Key.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the storm was battering the Keys, leading to flooding in
towns such as Tavernier and Marathon and taking roofs off houses in
Key West, Gov. Lawton Chiles was already sending units of the
Florida National Guard to an armory in Homestead, ground zero for
Hurricane Andrew in 1992. With U.S. 1, the only highway in the
Keys, impassable, Guard members were waiting for flood waters to
recede before moving in to help.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to action taken in the 1992 hurricane, which
inflicted $25 billion in damages, making it the most costly natural
disaster in American history, Federal Emergency Management Agency
teams also were being deployed early.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are as ready as we can be, and we pray that the human and
material cost will be limited,'' President Clinton said in
Washington Friday. Later in the day, he declared a state of
emergency in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane watch remained in effect for the Gulf Coast of
Florida, from the Everglades through Naples and Fort Myers to
suburban communities north of Tampa. But after the hurricane
departs the Keys, its course was expected to take it far enough out
to sea that those areas would be spared the worst punishment of
winds and water.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We are on the very periphery,'' Nancy Schapira, a spokeswoman
for Tampa's Emergency Operations Center, said with relief in a
telephone interview Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, said Jerry Jarrell, director of the National
Hurricane Center, ``there should not be a storm surge problem, but
just a lot of rain'' along the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Heavily populated areas of south Florida experienced gusts of
high winds and heavy rains intermittently throughout the day, but
suffered relatively little damage. Alex Penelas, mayor of
Miami-Dade County, indicated Friday afternoon that the most serious
problem for the 2 million residents of his county was that the
storm left ``upwards of 100,000 people without electricity.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Miami nor the Fort Lauderdale airports was
officially closed, but airlines moved their planes out of south
Florida and suspended their flights as of 9 p.m. Thursday. Marc
Henderson, a spokesman for Miami International Airport, said that
``hopefully in the next day or so, we will get back to normal
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   On the hard-hit island of Hispaniola, rescue operations
continued in the Dominican Republic, where the official death toll
rose to 134, and in Haiti, where 87 were confirmed dead. But
government officials in both countries said the death toll could
increase as rescue workers made their way into isolated rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
   With a state of emergency already in place, President Leonel
Fernandez of the Dominican Republic appealed for international
assistance, and warned his country's 7.5 million citizens that it
could be six weeks before electrical power can be restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a word, the picture is one of desolation,'' Fernandez said
after visiting devastated areas. He calculated damage just to the
nation's electrical system at more than $100 million, and said that
up to 90 percent of some major crops peasant farmers depend on for
their livelihoods had been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Tourist resorts such as Casa de Campo were also badly hit,
according to government officials, as were the country's three
principal airports on the southern coast, including Las Americas
International Airport outside Santo Domingo. ``The problem there is
not the tarmac, but the terminal'' and control tower, both of which
were heavily damaged, Bernardo Vega, the Dominican ambassador to
the United States, said Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Haiti's hillsides have been deforested by peasants in
need of fuel, which increases the possibility of mudslides and
inundations. In the wake of the storm, there were also fears that
epidemics of cholera and typhoid could break out and that swollen
rivers could overflow their banks and deluge the fertile Artibonite
Valley, which grows much of Haiti's food.
</P>
<P>
   Under a disaster declaration by President Clinton, Puerto Rico
was getting $39 million to repair public housing and was authorized
to use $300 million in previously awarded housing aid for disaster
relief.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, three additional hurricanes, Ivan, Jeanne and
Karl, were meandering across the Atlantic. They pose no immediate
threat to the Caribbean or the United States, but are being closely
monitored at the National Hurricane Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has gone on way too long,'' Jarrell, the director of the
center, said Friday, undoubtedly speaking for millions of other
Florida residents. ``We need a break.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
