<P>
   (NYT37) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- CLINTON-CONGRESS, 9-25
-- At one level, ``the partisanship continues,'' says Rep. John
Conyers Jr. of Michigan, ranking Democrat on the House Judiciary
Committee. The committee approved Friday the release of thousands
more pages of documents that had been delivered by the independent
counsel, finding near unanimity this time on particularly sensitive
information that would be kept from public view. (Shana Raab/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- CLINTON-HASTINGS, 9-25
-- Rep. Alcee Hastings, D-Fla., was removed from the federal bench
by the Senate in 1989 on grounds of bribery and perjury. He was
elected to Congress three years later. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 27 --
INVEST-WITH-KERSCHNER, 9-25 -- Peeking into baby boomers' closets
gives insights about trends that affect buying - information Edward
Kerschner, Paine Webber's chief investment strategist, uses to pick
stocks. ``If you're right about the trends, the stock-picking is
easy,'' says Kerschner, 45, of this thematic investing approach.
``I mean, they become obvious.'' (Ruby Washington/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- DEMS-MEETING, 9-25 --
Gov. Roy Romer of Colorado, left, and Steven Grossman, co-chairmen
of the Democratic National Committee, cite polls Friday in
Washington that show the Clinton scandal is actually helping the
party. ``Sometimes you need a crisis, an existential crisis, to
motivate you,'' says Grossman. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) BOSTON -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- WOMEN-LEWINSKY-2, 9-25 --
For a variety of reasons that seem to reflect a variety of Ally
McBeal-generation attitudes and realities, young American women
hold somewhat more tolerant opinions of Monica Lewinsky than their
mothers and grandmothers. ``I think the workplace is more balanced
out,'' says Livia Foo, 22, who works at a Boston investment
company. ``I think things are starting to get better.'' (Michael
Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) BOSTON -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- WOMEN-LEWINSKY-1, 9-25 --
``I don't know anybody whose life is like Monica Lewinsky's,'' says
Christine Parker, a 25-year-old sales support administrator in a
Boston computer company. Young American women seem to hold somewhat
more tolerant opinions of Ms. Lewinsky than their mothers and
grandmothers, according to a national New York Times poll,
follow-up calls to respondents and several separate interviews.
(Michael Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) HAVANA -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- HURRICANE-GEORGES-4, 9-25 --
Local children tempt their fate as huge waves crash past the
sea-wall and onto the main street in Havana on Friday, where
flooding was extensive. Four people were killed when they were
electrocuted by fallen power lines and thousands of homes sustained
damage, the Cuban official news agency Prensa Latina said. (Lonnie
Schlein/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) MARCO ISLAND, Fla. -- Sept. 25, 1998 --
HURRICANE-GEORGES-3, 9-25 -- High winds whip palm trees next to
rows of empty condominiums Friday as Hurricane Georges bears down
on Marco Island. After leaving nearly 300 people dead in a five-day
rampage across the Caribbean, the hurricane slammed into the
Florida Keys with winds of more than 100 miles an hour, causing
widespread flooding and extensive damage to buildings, homes,
roads, harbors and power lines. (Ernst Peters/Lakeland Ledger
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) MOSCOW -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 27 --
RUSSIA-OLIGARCHS, 9-25 -- Few Russians harvested the spoils of
Russia's troubled encounter with capitalism as feverishly as
Vladimir Potanin, a young Soviet-era bureaucrat who in a few short
years had parlayed his Kremlin ties into a sprawling business
empire. ``Everything is going to change, and the role of the
oligarchs will be less,'' says Potanin, 37. (Jacqueline Mia
Foster/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) MILL VALLEY, Calif. -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 27 -- BIZ-CONFLICT-WORK-WEEK, 9-25 -- As co-owner of a
business, Paula Reynolds arranged part-time hours allowing more
time at home in Mill Valley. ``My kids are at an age where they
want to be with me more than anybody else,'' says Ms. Reynolds, 43,
whose firm supplies temporary executives to corporations. ``I'll
have plenty of time later to develop my career.'' (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) SAUSALITO, Calif. -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 27 -- VIATICAL-INSURANCE-3, 9-25 -- Carole Fiedler owns a
financial company in Sausalito that specializes in helping people
sell their insurance policies. As they have gone mainstream, the
half-dozen companies doing the brokering say business is booming.
(Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) CHICAGO -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 27 --
VIATICAL-INSURANCE-2, 9-25 -- Gary Chodes, president of Viaticus
Inc., an investment company in Chicago that buys insurance
policies. Investors take over the premiums on a policy and become
the beneficiaries. They make money unless the original holder's
death comes significantly later than they have estimated. (Steve
Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 27 -- VIATICAL-INSURANCE-1, 9-25 -- Selling a life insurance
policy to raise cash was once an opportunity offered only to the
terminally ill. Now some companies are buying the policies of
healthy older people. Leonard Oxenberg of Brookline no longer
needed his $100,000 term policy but didn't want to drop it,
forfeiting any return for the premiums he had paid. He sold the
policy for $16,500. (Evan Richman/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
