ABOUT-CARS-NAMEPLATES, 9-25 -- A 1963 Buick Riviera concept car,
left; the1999 model. General Motors is continuing to thin its herd,
recently announcing plans to discontinue the Riviera, for which
sales have been falling in recent years. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 27 --
ABOUT-CARS-OLDSMOBILE, 9-25 -- Oldsmobile is hoping that the newest
member in its lineup, the entry-level Alero, a compact sedan and
coupe just hitting the market, will generate up to 150,000 sales a
year. It's a tall order for this small car. The Alero has many
advantages, but probably not enough to take on the world's
heavyweights. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 27 --
MOTH-TALES, 9-25 -- Dael Orlandersmith, an actor and playwright,
spins a tale at a downtown salon. On many Monday nights, literary
types with book-party burnout seek refuge by attending a gathering
called Stories at the Moth. It's an idea as old as the campfire:
The lights dim, the crowd gathers and people stand and tell
stories. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 27 --
SWAIN-LOLITA-PROFILE, 9-25 -- Actress Dominique Swain at Veruka.
The general fabulousness of the downtown movie and art crowd seemed
to intimidate Ms. Swain, who grew up in a rural canyon in Malibu,
Calif., where there are still more rattlesnakes than Range Rovers.
``I don't feel like I belong here,'' says Ms. Swain, who seems
younger than she is, three years after making ``Lolita'' at age 15.
(Miles Ladin/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 27 --
WILLIAMS-SLAM-PROFILE, 9-25 -- Saul Williams, star of ``Slam,'' a
prize-winning movie about rap, poetry and jail, which opens on Oct.
9. Already a star in New York's spoken-word scene as the 1996
winner of the Nuyorican Poets Cafe grand slam championship,
Williams, 26, is on the verge, as the Hollywood types say. ``Once I
won the grand slam, I stopped,'' he says. ``I had nothing else to
prove.'' (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- NY-LITERARY-BAR-2, 9-24 --
Dani Shapiro, who teaches writing at Columbia University and the
New School, reads excerpts from her new book, ``Slow Motion,''
during the reading night at the KGB Bar in the East Village. The
bar has burnished its own mystique with the publication this month
of ``The KGB Bar Reader,'' an anthology of 28 stories edited by Ken
Foster, the curator of the reading series. (Norman Y. Lono/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- NY-LITERARY-BAR-1, 9-24 --
Listeners during the reading night at the KGB Bar in the East
Village. The evening features contemporary American literature, and
the audience has many young writers just starting their careers.
(Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- NY-COOK-PROFILE, 9-24 --
Barbara Cook, the cabaret performer and veteran of Broadway. ``I've
