<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    21st victory would place Glavine in select group
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Glavine makes his final start today before Cy Young ballots
are due. If he earns his 21st win, he would join John Smoltz as the
only NL pitchers in the last five years to win more than 20. Smoltz
won 24 in 1996, his Cy Young year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll treat it as a normal start from the standpoint that I
want to pitch well,'' Glavine said. ``If I have an opportunity to
win the game, I'd like to do it. At the same time, I don't think
I'm going to stretch myself any further than I have to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my emphasis is going to be working on everything and
getting comfortable and getting to the point where I'm happy with
the way I'm throwing the ball to get ready for the postseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine went into the weekend as the league's only 20-game
winner. He is 8-2 since July 17 with a 2.08 ERA and recorded his
third shutout of the season in Arizona last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cy Young choice has hardly been clarified in the last weeks.
Entering Friday night's game, San Diego closer Trevor Hoffman had
52 saves, the second most ever accumulated after Bobby Thigpen's
major-league record 57 (1990). Kevin Brown started for the Padres
with an 18-7 record and a 2.36 ERA that ranked second in the league
to Greg Maddux's 2.24. Brown also was second in innings pitched and
strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Walt, meet Keith
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, for the first time since Aug. 22, shortstop Walt
Weiss started a game next to second baseman Keith Lockhart. Weiss
reports his left quadriceps has felt better the last several days,
while Lockhart has felt better about his right hamstring every time
he has tested it.
</P>
<P>
   But manager Bobby Cox was uncertain just how long to go with the
two middle infielders this weekend. Weiss had been sidelined for
eight days and has just 10 at-bats this month. Lockhart has started
just three games in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll play it by ear,'' said Cox. ``We'll have to wait and see
how they do.''
</P>
<P>
   When both Weiss and Lockhart have started, the Braves' record
entering Friday was 40-16.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle mothballs
</P>
<P>
   Limited to just 12 innings this month with bursitis in his left
shoulder, Denny Neagle threw in the bullpen before Friday's game
and was hoping to work one or two innings today in preparation for
his reliever's role in next week's League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it might be best to go (Friday) night,'' he said.
``That gives me three, four days until next Tuesday. If I can't
come back on three days, then I shouldn't be pitching anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Dexter Santos, the Braves' director of community relations and
fan development, is leaving the club Oct. 5 to assume a similar
position with the Atlanta Hawks. ... Former Brave Brad Clontz has
been on the Mets' 60-day disabled list since Sept. 11, when he had
bone chips and bone spurs removed from his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
