<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5499 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-49ERS-COX     09-25 0461
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-49ERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Got to disrupt their timing'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the undefeated Falcons take on the undefeated 49ers Sunday
in San Francisco, cornerback Ray Buchanan and the Atlanta secondary
will be under the gun in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers pass first, then think about the run. Led by two
future Hall of Famers in quarterback Steve Young and receiver Jerry
Rice, the Niners put all kinds of pressure on defensive backs, with
both skills and scheme.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Rice is fairly big at 6 feet 2, 196 pounds, and
young receivers Terrell Owens (6-3, 217) and J.J. Stokes (6-4, 223)
are bigger. Owens and Stokes developed by leaps and bounds last
year, when Rice missed most of the season with knee injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Communciation will be more important than ever in the secondary.
Buchanan sat down with The Atlanta Journal-Constitution to talk
about slowing the 49ers' ``West Coast'' offense.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: What's the biggest difference in defending against this
passing offense compared with a more typical one?
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan: We have got to be aware of where (teammates) are,
where (the 49ers are), talking all the time, and we have to be in
the right position and make tackles. They're always crossing (in
patterns), motioning one way or another, trying to get DBs to make
the wrong decision as far as who to cover. It's up to us to be
there when the ball is caught, if it's caught.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: You're normally the left cornerback, although in the nickel
defense you go to the slot. For this game, will you move around
more, and perhaps shadow Rice?
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan: (Smiles) That's for me to know, my little secret.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Other than talking to each other, being in position to make
tackles, and then making them, what can the secondary do to improve
its chances?
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan: You've got to disrupt their timing. It's an offense
based entirely on timing. You've got to get physical with the
receivers, try and throw off their timing.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: How far can you go with that strategy, though?
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan: It's about how the officials let you play. (San
Francisco receivers) throw cornerbacks around, and push off and
things like that. Then somebody in the secondary finally does
something like that, and maybe (officials) throw a flag.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: So both sides do it, making it a matter of who gets caught.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan: You talk to officials before the game, and say, ``This
guy's going to be pushing off and this and that, and don't say
nothing if I'm doing the same thing.'' It may come down to how well
known you are (by officials). If you know them pretty well,
sometimes they'll hesitate to throw the flag on you.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
