<HEADER>
A5500 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES-COX     09-25 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcon DLs on lookout for Niner cut blocks
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- When the Atlanta Falcons play at San Francisco on
Sunday, the game will be different from most. First, both teams are
2-0 and tied with New Orleans atop the NFC West. Second, the
Falcons will try to end a six-game losing streak in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Atlanta defensive linemen will have to worry about a
game within the game. San Francisco linemen go for the legs _ a
lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cut (block) more than anybody,'' left end Lester
Archambeau said. ``I think some of the things they do across the
line (become illegal).''
</P>
<P>
   Cut-blocking is legal in many instances, so long as it's not by
a second blocker when a first blocker is engaged with a defender.
</P>
<P>
   That's not all the Falcons need to be prepared for, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leg-whipping is illegal, and they do it,'' said Archambeau,
who will square off with right tackle Derrick Deese. ``You get
heated; nobody likes to get kicked. It's going to be a battle. You
have to ... get your hands on the guy and keep him from getting all
the way into your legs.''
</P>
<P>
   A key matchup: 49ers Pro Bowl right guard Kevin Gogan (6 feet 7,
330 pounds) vs. Falcons left tackle Travis Hall (6-5, 300), one of
the top young interior linemen in the NFL. In a recent survey of
players, Gogan was voted one of the league's three dirtiest
players.
</P>
<P>
   Roster moves
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' four early inactives are DT Shawn Swayda, S Omar
Brown, injured LB Henri Crockett and CB Elijah Williams. Williams'
absence means somebody else will return kicks with rookie WR Tim
Dwight. ... A game-day decision could be made on LG Calvin Collins
(ankle). Rookie Bob Hallen is the backup.
</P>
<P>
   Family reunion
</P>
<P>
   Falcon TE Ed Smith's younger brother, Irv, is the 49ers'
starting TE, replacing retired Brent Jones. ``We talk two, three
times a week,'' said Ed, still looking for his first career
reception. ``My mom and dad are coming out from (Trenton) New
Jersey. We're going to make a full weekend out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will play only one more game on grass after San
Francisco, traveling to New England Nov. 8. They play three more
games outdoors: Oct. 11 at the Giants, Oct. 25 at the Jets and New
England. ... Atlanta is averaging 10 penalties a game, third-worst
in the NFL, trailing Oakland (12.7) and the Giants (10.7), teams
that are a combined 1-5. ... Atlanta and San Francisco are 2-0, but
the Falcons' opponents (Carolina and Phildadelphia) are a combined
0-5 so far, and the 49ers' opponents (Jets, Redskins) are 1-5. ...
San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci said he likes Atlanta's Dwight
as a KR/PR, but Atlanta is averaging just 5.6 yards yards per punt
return, 26th in the NFL. The Falcons are averaging 24.3 per kick
return, 10th in the league. ... LB Malcolm Hamilton (6-1, 235),
signed to the practice squad Wednesday to replace LB Brandon
Tolbert, has looked good. Hamilton was on the Redskins' practice
squad last year and was waived last month by Washington. ... The
Falcons have the NFL's No. 2 defense against the run (58.5 yards
per game), trailing Green Bay (53.5). Atlanta is No. 1 per carry,
allowing 2.6 yards to the Packers' 2.8. ... Falcons reserve QB
Steve DeBerg, a 49er in 1978-80, will show today that he knows the
way to San Jose. He'll travel to his alma mater to be one of the
first two San Jose State alumni inducted into the school's Ring of
Honor. DeBerg played there 1974-76, going back to school and
getting a degree last year. Rams coach Dick Vermeil, a former SJSU
quarterback, is the other inductee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
