</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MOORE-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unlike Falcons, Niners have a definite grasp on stability
 &HT;    By Terrence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. -- While visiting the locker room of the San
Francisco 49ers on Friday, something hit an Atlanta columnist like
a 5.2 on the Richter scale. You had defensive end Chris Doleman on
one side and cornerback Darnell Walker on the other. They start for
one of the world's best organizations, but they were considered
expendable by one of the worst.
</P>
<P>
   What's up with that?
</P>
<P>
   Doleman shook his head, then he spoke for Walker and others who
he said had ``escaped'' from Suwanee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not with the Falcons anymore, because we live our lives
to a higher standard,'' said Doleman, a Pro Bowl veteran in his
14th season in the league after stints with Minnesota, Atlanta and
San Francisco. ``Darnell and I didn't get into the petty,
backbiting ways that kills them every year in terms of the players,
the coaches and the management.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments before, the Atlanta columnist had triggered that
response by asking Doleman to compare the 49ers and the Falcons,
especially since he'd played for both within the past three years.
Doleman said, ``I guess the locker rooms are about the same size.''
</P>
<P>
   Rim shot. Even so, when the Falcons enter 3Comm Park on Sunday,
they'll join the 49ers with a 2-0 record. And unlike Doleman's
tenure with the Falcons during the 1994 and 1995 seasons, the
Falcons have watched their front office evolve from owner Rankin
Smith Sr., president Taylor Smith, general manager Ken Herock and
coach June Jones to just Dan Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Smith remains president, but he delegated everything from
personnel to coaching decisions to Reeves last year. ``I don't want
this to come out wrong,'' Doleman said, ``but you can't have one
man trying to do everything. Dictatorships don't work in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   No, they don't. You needn't look further than the 49ers'
philosophy, which stresses that it takes all five fingers to make a
fist to punch away your competition.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, we have the continuation of one of life's biggest
miracles. Whenever something hints of turning the 49ers into a
fallen king, they gain another crown or threaten to do so. Since
1981, when the 49ers began their run to a record five Super Bowl
victories and 13 NFC West titles in the past 17 years, they've had
three different head coaches, two different quarterbacks, many
Dolemans and many more Walkers.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 49ers have co-owner Eddie DeBartolo trying to avoid an
indictment by the feds investigating charges of gambling fraud in
DeBartolo's involvement with a former Louisiana governor. There
also is the question whether taxpayers will build the 49ers a new
stadium. Then there is the resignation of long-time 49ers official
Carmen Policy.
</P>
<P>
   The results? The 81 points are the most the 49ers have scored in
the first two games of any season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carmen never made a tackle, and that's another difference
between the Falcons and the 49ers,'' Doleman said. ``Everybody here
knows their role, and they concentrate on what they have to do
without worrying about somebody else. It's a matter of pride that
runs all the way down to the person who empties the trash every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   And when that person can block or tackle a little, the 49ers are
even better.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
