<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEYS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Residents brace for the aftermath of Georges
 &HT;    By Gary Kane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANTATION KEY, Fla. _ Patti Music couldn't bring herself to
look inside her mobile home at Sea Breeze, an oceanfront trailer
park. So, she didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just put a new floor in a month ago,'' she said, bracing
herself against a mighty gust as she surveyed the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours earlier, Hurricane Georges had muscled a sea surge
that turned the park into a mobile home swampland. Currents of
brown water flowed through front and back yards and submerged the
narrow streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a deck out back. It's gone!'' Music gasped.
</P>
<P>
   Music and her husband, Vince, fled their mobile home when
authorities issued the mandatory evacuation order. They found
refuge at Casa Thorn, a bed-and-breakfast across the highway from
the trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided not to evacuate too far this time,'' said Vince
Music. ``During Andrew, we evacuated to South Miami and they
(police) didn't let us back into the keys for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew took its toll on the Musics' 1972 Ritz Craft mobile home.
Their refrigerator defrosted when the storm knocked out power
lines. Water that leaked from the fridge gradually rotted the
floor. The refrigerator then cracked through the floor.
</P>
<P>
   As Georges seemed to subside by mid-afternoon Thursday, the
couple returned to inspect their property. They stood in pushy
wind, walked about their property, and left without going inside
their trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I went inside, I'd just start nailing things together,''
Vince Music said.
</P>
<P>
   The Musics moved into Sea Breezes about 17 years ago after Vince
retired as a computer operator for a Chicago steel mill. The couple
embraced the keys lifestyle and Vince even began drawing a comic
strip called Conch Crittters for the local weekly newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Musics say they plan to move to Costa Rica, where they
also own a condominium with a view of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting tired of the Keys,'' Vince Music said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Central American country is free of hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, but this year we've been through an earthquake and a
volcano erupted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
