   EDS, PLEASE NOTE:
</P>
<P>
   The following photos accomany the Hearst News Service's series
on prostate cancer. The stories are for release starting Sept. 27.
The main story is called PROSTATE-RDP. All other stories are
slugged with the prefix PCA-XXX, the medical shorthand for prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BETHESDA, Md.-- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR TUES., SEPT.
29 -- PCA-MILITARY-2-HNS, 9-25 -- Dr. Shiv Srivastava, a molecular
biologist and the lead researcher at Department of Defense's Center
for Prostate Disease Research studies prostate cells. Srivastava
and other researchers working at a laboratory believe they have
located a new gene linked to prostate cancer. `` This is a very
prostate-specific gene,'' says Srivastava. ``This is something that
is very new.'' (Jerry Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BETHESDA, Md.-- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR TUES., SEPT.
29 -- PCA-MILITARY-1-HNS, 9-25 -- Sitting in his office, Dr. Judd
Moul, a urologist and director of the Department of Defense's
Center for Prostate Disease Research, holds a model of the
prostate. ``So far, nobody in the private sector has really been
able to put together a nationwide, multi-center database with a
standardized system to collect tissues,'' says Moul. (Jerry
Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR TUES., SEPT. 29
-- PCA-POLITICS-2-HNS, 9-25 -- In an effort to boost federal
research and raise the profile of prostate cancer, a new lobbying
group, the National Prostate Cancer Coalition, opened its doors
about two miles from the Capitol last year. Jay Hedlund, sitting,
meets with U.S. Rep. Henry Bonilla (R-Texas) in a bid to boost
federal funding. (Jerry Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR TUES., SEPT. 29 --
PCA-POLITICS-1-HNS, 9-25 -- Jerry Donohue, 62, a prostate cancer
patient, leads an effort on Long Island aimed at building
grass-roots pressure on Congress to spend more money for prostate
cancer research. ``I don't make long-term plans,'' says Donohue
who's cancer has invaded his bones. ``I take it as it comes.''
(Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) SAN ANTONIO -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., SEPT. 28
-- PCA-BRACHYTHERAPY-3-HNS, 9-24 -- At Methodist Hospital, Mary
King affectionately touches the lips of her husband, Jim, after
doctors implanted radioactive seeds into his prostate gland. The
procedure is designed to eradicate cancer in a diseased prostate
and halt the spread of the cancer in a patient's body. (Jerry
Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) SAN ANTONIO . -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., SEPT.
28 -- PCA-BRACHYTHERAPY-2-HNS, 9-24 -- At Methodist Hospital, Dr.
Michael Sarosdy, in the green gown, prepares to inject radioactive
pellets, usually called ``seeds'' into Jim King. With Sarosdy is
Dr. Russell Hern, anesthesiologist, left, and Jerome Gonzales,
R.N., right. (Jerry Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SAN ANTONIO -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., SEPT. 28
-- PCA-BRACHYTHERAPY-1-HNS, 9-24 -- In his office at Methodist
Hospital, Dr. Michael Sarosdy explains an x-ray to Jim King. The
x-ray is from a patient who has had radioactive seeds procedures,
also known as brachytherapy. Sarosdy, a urologic cancer specialist,
will perform the same surgery in on King in a few days later.
(Jerry Lara/Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LA SELVA BEACH, Calif. -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR
MON., SEPT. 28 -- PCA-IMPOTENCY-B&AMP;W-HNS, 9-25 -- Howard Waage, an
insurance inspector, was diagnosed with prostate cancer two years
ago at age 49. He recalled being overwhelmed at learning how many
men had lost sexual function after they sought treatment.
