<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., SEPT. 28
-- PCA-SURGERY-1-HNS, 9-25 -- A just removed, cancerous prostate
gland. The surgical removal of the prostate - a radical
prostatectomy - is the most common treatment for early-stage
prostate cancer, but not all men with cancerous prostates choose
this remedy. If a patient didn't want surgery, he might have chosen
radiation, either external beam radiation or radioactive ``seeds''
implanted directly in the gland. (Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) GETTYSBURG, Pa. -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON., SEPT.
28 -- PCA-TREATMENT-OPTIONS-2-HNS, 9-25 -- Jan Marfyaic, from
Gettysburg, Pa., a former government worker, was 59 when he was
diagnosed with prostate cancer six years ago. He opted to have
brachytherapy or seed implant treatment. This is when tiny
radioactive implants, no bigger than a rye seed and injected
directly into the prostate through the perineum. ``I selected seeds
because it was much less invasive and was a relatively new
treatment,'' Marfyaic explains. (Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MONTICELLO, N.Y. -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR MON.,
SEPT. 28 -- PCA-TREATMENT-OPTIONS-B&AMP;W-HNS, 9-25 -- Prostate cancer
patient Carl Silverstein, of Monticello, N.Y., opted for radiation
over surgery when he was diagnosed in 1995. A semi-retired lawyer
for the Sullivan County legal aid society, Silverstein, 69, felt
his chances of avoiding incontinence and impotence were better with
radiation. (Hearst News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SILVER SPRINGS, Md. -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
SEPT. 27 -- PCA-BLACKS-2-HNS, 9-21 -- Harry Harris, a retired
federal government worker, looks over the files of the men in his
support group. ``I'm still alive today, but I know a lot of people
who had the cancer and are dead,'' he says. Harris, who was
diagnosed eight years ago with prostate cancer at age 69, is using
his experience to help other men confront their illness at a local
prostate cancer support group. (Jerry Lara/Hearst News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HOUSTON -- Sept. 25, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., SEPT. 27 --
PCA-BLACKS-1-HNS, 9-21 -- Raleigh Woodard, at left, sitting next to
his uncle, Horace Woodard, participated in a genetic study of
prostate cancer in African-American men led by African-American
physicians. The physicians included, standing from left, Herbert
Watkins, Curtis Pettaway, William Boykin Jr. and Ronald Morton.
Inherited prostate cancer accounts for about 1 in 10 cases,
according to the National Cancer Institute. (Steve Ueckert/Houston
Chronicle Photo)
</P>
