<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-POLE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Irvan puts Pontiac in pole position
 &HT;    By Tom McCollister
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox New Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ Ernie Irvan put the Ford and Chevrolet camps
on notice Friday that he and his Pontiac will be a handful Sunday,
easily winning the pole for the NAPA AutoCare 500 with a speed of
93.608 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The car has been doing everything it's suppose to do,'' said
Irvan of his second pole of the year and 22nd of his career.
``We'll be able to race them real hard Sunday. It's the same
Pontiac we had here last time. There's nothing more I'd like to do
than to win here at Martinsville, but we've yet to get a top
five.''
</P>
<P>
   If Irvan was a minisurprise where few Pontiacs have trod this
year, consider his front row partner, Ricky Rudd, who put a speed
of 93.576 mph on the board. It will be Rudd's best start of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made some pretty good gains late in practice and that put
us up there on the front row,'' Rudd said.``I think if we get our
act together, it's got to happen because we go out and run well.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, neither Jeff Gordon nor Mark Martin showed on the
front row. Following a sub-far first lap around the .566-mile oval,
Gordon turned it up, running 93.511 mph, third fastest, to share
the second row with Rich Bickle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew our first lap wasn't going to be good,'' Gordon said.
``After that first lap, we saw some other guys running good on
their first lap, so I knew I'd better make it up on the second one.
It was a great lap, the fastest we've had here in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin seemed never to get up to speed, settling for the seventh
row, running a poor 92.928 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an excellent run for what we had to work with,''
Martin said. ``We gave 'em all we had. If they gave us another shot
at it, I don't know if I could do that good again or not. So, we'll
take that and get ready for Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, this was one of the strangest qualifying sessions of
the year. Bickle failed to make the field at Richmond three weeks
ago; Mike Bliss, a Craftsman Truck circuit regular, starts 25th;
Derrike Cope failed to qualify, as did Jimmy Spencer and Kenny
Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt perhaps put it best after qualifying 32nd.
</P>
<P>
   ``That qualifying lap was just like we had been running in
practice _ sorry. We just ain't going nowhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
