u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STORM26-COX     09-25 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Residents unmoved by Georges presence
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY WEST _ As the worst of Hurricane Georges assaulted the tip
of this island with a storm surge that sent waves cresting over
streets, Kevin Martine clung to the marker designating the Southern
Most Point and screamed:
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I can!''
</P>
<P>
   The trademark resiliency of the Keys' Conchs showed itself
Friday as Georges pounded the island with driving winds, torrential
rain and pounding waves while residents hunkered down around the
island in houses and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   When the first wave of the storm passed at 11 a.m., islanders
emerged on Duval Street, curious to survey the storm's power.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just so exciting,'' said Donna Dalton, a carpenter
holed up in a Antonia's restaurant with friends. ``It breaks up the
humdrum.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalton, like others staying in restaurants along the street, had
prepared thoroughly for the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great feast: filet mignon, lamb chops, mussels and
all the wine you can drink,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff and friends at the restaurant kept in touch with a crew
barricaded at Mangoes, where tables became beds, with a two-way
radio. Mangoes' managers Robert Robinson and Rusty Barry said they
stocked up enough food to feed most of Duval Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're one of the few people with a generator so we kind of
have to,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-hour lull of the eye, police tried to herd
gawkers back to shelters, but many ignored their warning, as they
did earlier mandatory evacuation orders. All around the island,
they found trees uprooted and utility lines flung across fences and
roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're in the eye now. I've always wanted to be in the
eye,'' said Dustin Shaffer, who moved to the island from Oregon a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   As the second wave struck with more intense wind and rain, most
fled inside though a few, like Martine, tried to ride the storm
outside. As hurricane winds gusted, some even walked their dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Curry and his four children and former wife tried to stay in
their stilt house with friends, but abandoned it even before the
end of the first wave and fled to the 72-year-old La Concha Hotel,
the tallest building on the island, where dozens found safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got a little bit shaky when the window blew out,'' Curry
said.
</P>
<P>
   But even while Curry settled in his family, he insisted he
wanted to return to his house alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make it,'' he said. ``I don't think my life's
going to be taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
