</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-GEORGES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLY GEORGES DELIVERS GLANCING BLOW TO FLORIDA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, Fla. _ Hurricane Georges battered the Florida Keys on
Friday with 105-mile-per hour winds and high water, but spared the
rest of South Florida as it swept into the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The storm appeared to be aiming its next punch _ possibly Sunday
_ at the coast between Louisiana and the Florida panhandle.
Forecasters worry that the storm may draw strength from the warm
Gulf water, arriving on land as a more deadly Category 3 storm.
</P>
<P>
   Georges, which killed more than 280 people and flattened homes
and crops as it moved across Puerto Rico, Haiti, Cuba and the
Dominican Republic earlier in the week, was kinder to the Keys.
There were no reports of storm-related deaths in Florida. But
preliminary reports indicated that the storm delivered heavy
property damage to some of the Keys.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe County Sheriff's Department spokesman Cindy Peryam warned
late Friday that the extent of the damage had not been tallied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just poking our head out of the hole,'' said Peryam at
the Marathon sheriff's department substation. ``It's getting dark,
and we're still under a hurricane watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sustained some heavy damage, especially in the lower
Keys,'' Peryam said. Miami and the major cities along Florida's
southeast coast suffered little more than downed trees and spotty
power losses.
</P>
<P>
   With fresh memories of Hurricane Andrew's 1992 devastation, many
area residents fled low-lying areas for the safety of public
shelters and aggressively prepared for the storm that ultimately
delivered only a glancing blow.
</P>
<P>
   A hurricane warning remained in effect along Florida's southeast
Gulf Coast until 11 p.m. Friday, but the storm's slight turn back
to the west after leaving the Keys also meant that it was expected
to deliver the coastal communities of Marco Island, Naples and Fort
Myers Beach little more than a slight pummeling by gusting winds.
</P>
<P>
   In the Keys, where the string of tiny islands sits just a few
feet above sea level, connecting U.S. Highway 1 was underwater in
some places. Trees blocked roadways, roofs were blown off and
floodwaters coursed through homes.
</P>
<P>
   A Monroe County Sheriff's deputy reported that the Big Pine Key
area appeared to have taken the brunt of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a tale of woe, but I'm not going to let it get me
down,'' said Big Pine Key resident Tom Bryant. He lost everything
in Hurricane Hugo in 1989 when he was living in St. Croix, he said,
and now he'd taken a big hit from Georges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The storm has destroyed my house,'' Bryant said. ``The whole
ground floor has six feet of water because of the storm surge. The
saltwater killed all my coy in the pond. The property had huge
banyan and oak trees. They're all gone, and it's flooded.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he would not leave the house to check out the rest of
the neighborhood until the water subsided.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're asking for danger and death, downed power lines,''
Bryant said. ``I'm here with 17 exotic birds in the kitchen, my
dog, Duke and my two kitties, Daily and Midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said the wind sounded ``like some kind of monster train
coming through _ wah, wah, wah, wah, wah!''
</P>
<P>
   In Key West, Marc Hightower said the storm woke him rather
abruptly Friday morning, dropping a large tree on the roof over his
bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Hightower pulled on shorts and sandals and strolled Key West
during the storm, he said, curious to see what it was delivering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out all day, cruising and checking it out.''
</P>
<P>
   He captains a boat, he said, and was not frightened by the
storm. He sat down under the shelter of an open-air bar, he said,
and watched the wind blowing across the harbor. It tore off part of
the roof of the Galleon Resort as he watched, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly, we have a lot of really huge trees down,'' Hightower
said. ``It's been a long time since we've had a hurricane, so we
have lots of big old trees.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was not the only ``rubbernecker'' wandering about in the
storm, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get down to the boat and it took me about two
hours because I kept bumping into people,'' Hightower said,
including friends of his who were hoisting a few drinks at the bar
(closed for the storm) where they work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the old Key West spirit,'' Hightower said.
</P>
<P>
   On the southeast coast of Florida, near Fort Myers, hundreds of
people crowded into shelters Friday even though the storm was not
expected to deliver a heavy blow.
</P>
<P>
   Many were complying with earlier ordered evacuations from mobile
homes, others simply lived in flood-prone areas and didn't want to
risk the high water.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
