</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-STOWAWAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINE DOMINICAN STOWAWAYS ARE FOUND IN CHINESE SHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Dominican Republic)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELIZABETH, N.J. _ The police and customs inspectors on Friday
captured nine stowaways from the Dominican Republic who had spent
five days on rough seas in the hull of a Chinese container ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently they were surviving on candy bars, cookies and bags
of water,'' said John Leyden, a regional director of passengers and
enforcement for the U.S. Customs Service. ``They were living in the
crevices between empty containers.''
</P>
<P>
   While the ship was at Port Newark, six of the stowaways
scrambled from the ship's hold at 8 a.m. when crew members opened
the hatches to load the empty containers, and four of the six tried
to escape by jumping as much as 60 feet down from the ship's deck
into Newark Bay, said Lt. Erich Herkloz of the New Jersey State
Police Marine Unit.
</P>
<P>
   The three remaining stowaways were found hiding inside the
vessel, which is named the Li Bai, Herkloz said.
</P>
<P>
   Leyden said three of the men were treated for dehydration, while
the rest were immediately turned over to immigration officials. The
stowaways, who were in their late teens or early 20s, will probably
be deported, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The captain and 35-member crew of the Li Bai were apparently
unaware of the stowaways' presence, Leyden said.
</P>
<P>
   The Li Bai, owned by Chinese-Polish Stock Shipping Co., was
picking up empty cargo containers, and the crew planned to reload
at Port Newark, a spokeswoman for Cosco North America Inc., the
company leasing the ship, told The Associated Press. The vessel,
which could hold 300 cargo containers, stopped in Venezuela before
going to the Dominican Republic, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Often stowaways from South America and the Caribbean are found
to be transporting cocaine, Leyden said, but no drugs were found in
this case. ``Some of them have family members in the metropolitan
area, so it seems obvious they were trying to enter the country
illegally to start new lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leyden said the customs employees who helped apprehend the
stowaways were inspectors on hand for a routine check of the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Herkloz said that none of the men who jumped from the ship's
deck were injured. ``They were cold,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
