<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5517 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-LADN     09-25 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC HAS AN EYE ON THE WEATHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ USC appears to be dodging Hurricane Georges,
which means the Trojans only have to worry about Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Or so said the latest report in the topsy-turvy world of
hurricane forecasting, which had Georges skipping today's game but
probably tossing a substantial rainstorm toward Doak Campbell
Stadium this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The most reliable forecast offered a 70 percent chance of
thunderstorms, although no one could rule out the chance the
hurricane might make an unpredictable turn east back toward
Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Amid these conditions better suited for a meteorologist, USC has
arrived with one eye on the weather and the other on the Seminoles.
And fully aware that one local team already had its game canceled
because of hurricane fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what happened with UCLA, with Bob Toledo being
interviewed about feeling relieved, our guys feel that (UCLA's)
game was canceled because there was a problem,'' USC coach Paul
Hackett said. ``Ours is not called off because there is not a
problem. I feel like the state of Florida deals with these things.
If they call it off, it's for a good reason. If they don't, it's
going to be a rainy day.''
</P>
<P>
   The state had not made any announcements about canceling the
game Friday night, leaving Hackett more concerned about playing in
inclement conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unpredictable. The only thing I would hate is if the
weather is so out of whack, the teams can't show what they can
do,'' Hackett said. ``We should be fine. I think this is really
good for us to play in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to go up north (later in the year). It makes us a
better football team. You've got to find out about this. It will
help answer questions, like `Do we have a mudder runner?'''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: A tailback who can trudge through a muddy field.
Truth be told, it's a question the Trojans would prefer to answer
later in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett is also re-examining his playbook because of the adverse
conditions, expecting to make more decisions today than he has in
any of USC's three previous games, and that's before he even thinks
about Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really have got to be on the job in terms of orchestrating
the game,'' Hackett said. ``This one's got to be played by ear.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Friday afternoon, Hackett was re-visiting the NCAA
rulebook, checking to make sure that the Trojans had the right-size
cleats for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we could change cleats,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, teams can only wear {-inch cleats, which is
what the Trojans normally wear.
</P>
<P>
   `We've got the same size they've got,'' he said. ``They don't
have any magic, bionic shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that these issues have been addressed, maybe the Trojans can
concentrate on the Seminoles, who are unbeaten in their past 35
home contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made plays in our house last year. Let's hope we can make
plays in their house,'' Hackett said. ``The issue is who's going to
make the play? I think we need to find out where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's easier to go back to hurricane talk. But seriously,
this is the game USC (3-0) has been waiting for, even though
players were strongly encouraged not to refer to it during the
first three games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're faster than any team we've faced this season,'' wide
receiver Mike Bastianelli said. ``When you have that speed, it's
hard to match up.''
</P>
<P>
   USC hopes, rain permitting, that it can surprise the Seminoles,
since speedy Chad Morton has replaced the departed Delon Washington
at tailback since the teams played last September.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State (2-1) has its own problems. The Seminoles caused
more worries in Tallahassee than Hurricane Georges, since North
Carolina State's 24-7 upset two weeks ago. It was Florida State's
first loss to an unranked opponent since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   With fan criticism mounting, Seminoles coach Bobby Bowden
basically told upset supporters to buzz off this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are a lot of angry people, but to me they are
people who take football too seriously,'' Bowden said. ``There is
more to life than football. Gee whiz, you can't cut your wrists
over a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Also: Hackett said tight end Antoine Harris, who has practiced
sparingly this week because of a recurring sore ankle, will play.
Center Matt McShane, who has a strained knee ligament, can play in
an emergency. Defensive tackle Darren Collins, who strained a
ligament in his foot, is also available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
