<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5523 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-FOSTER-LICENSING-B     09-25 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-FOSTER-LICENSING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE TO BEGIN LICENSING FOSTER HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts will begin licensing foster homes for the
first time next month, becoming one of the few states to require
that foster parents be literate, have adequate income, and get
yearly training, among other requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Social Services is also cutting the maximum
number of children allowed in a foster home from eight to six.
</P>
<P>
   The heightened requirements of foster parents were driven by the
deaths and alleged abuse of several children in foster homes over
recent years, and are intended to boost the quality of foster care.
But they will also almost certainly diminish even further the
already-dwindling ranks of foster homes, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may weed out some foster homes,'' acknowledged DSS
spokeswoman Lorraine Carli. ``But I think everybody would rather
sacrifice quantity for quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Legislature ordered DSS to draw up foster
home licensing requirements after the deaths and sexual abuse of
several children in foster care in 1995. They included the
suffocation death of a 3-month-old baby accidentally left in car in
Medway, and the strangulation death a 3-year-old Dorchester boy,
ruled a homicide.
</P>
<P>
   New foster homes will have to comply with the new licensing
requirements &UR;  &LR; beginning Thursday. The state's existing 3,600 foster
homes will be licensed over the next year, as they come up for
their annual evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   While all states require some kind of certification process for
foster parents, Child Welfare League of America officials said the
new Massachusetts rules appear to be more far-reaching than most.
</P>
<P>
   Foster parents will have to demonstrate for the first time that:
</P>
<P>
   _They have sufficient income beyond the $13-$17 a day they are
paid by the state for each foster child. No income guidelines are
specified, and welfare payments will still count as income.
</P>
<P>
   _At least one parent in the home is literate.
</P>
<P>
   _They have a car or other access to transportation, and have a
telephone in the home.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, foster parents will have to provide references
every two years from their employer, their own children's schools,
and three people who can vouch for their character. Until now,
references have only been required from foster parents at the
outset.
</P>
<P>
   Foster parents will also have to pass a physical exam.
</P>
<P>
   Carli said existing foster homes that do not meet the licensing
requirements will not be immediately shut down. Instead, they will
allowed to keep foster children placed with them as long as the
children are deemed safe, but will not get any additional foster
children.
</P>
<P>
   Most foster parents interviewed this week said they believe the
new licensing requirements will professionalize foster care and
improve its image. A few said the new standards are so onerous they
could discourage qualified people from remaining or becoming foster
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it looks like we are running a tight ship from our end, the
negativity will decrease,'' said Cheryl Haddad of Winchendon, a
foster mother for nine years. ``But is is not going to help with
recruitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the new requirements, foster parents will also have to
undergo 10 hours of training each year, in addition to the 30 hours
of training they get now before they are approved.
</P>
<P>
   Some foster parents called it unfair that the licensing apply
only to foster homes willing to take any foster child, but not to
foster parents who care only for their relatives' or neighbor's
children.
</P>
<P>
   DSS will also begin next month limiting the number of young
children who can be in each foster home to no more than two
children under age 24 months and no more than one child under age
one month. Exceptions could be made to keep siblings together.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the agency will reduce the overall number of
children who can be in a foster home. Currently, the maximum is six
foster children and two biological children under age 18. The new
maximum will be four foster children and two biological children.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have been calling for several years on DSS to reduce the
number of children, but state officials had resisted, citing a
shortage of foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   To ease the shortage, DSS has been increasingly relying on
relatives and neighbors to take in children. The state has also
created a number of temporary group residences, called bridge
homes, and plans to contract with private agencies this year to
open and operate 16 foster homes, each with an adult paid to live
there full time to act as a foster parent.
</P>
<P>
   In a number of homes where foster children have died, there were
a large number of children. For example, a Dracut foster home where
a 2-year-old boy drowned in a pool when after being left unattended
briefly in the backyard, had a total of nine children, five of them
foster children.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the new standard, Massachusetts will still allow more
children in foster homes than the maximum of four recommended by
the Child Welfare League of America.
</P>
<P>
   Foster parents seemed divided over the new limits, with some
seeing it as an affront to their parenting skills and saying the
state should decide on a case-by-case basis how many children a
foster home can handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be personally insulted if they reduce it to four,''
said Haddad. ``I have six foster children and my house runs
great.''
</P>
<P>
   William LaPierre of Haverhill, a foster father for 13 years,
said he believes the new limit is needed, since foster children
scarred by sexual and physical abuse or born drug-addicted require
much more attention than a typical child.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids are more damaged than they were a few years
ago,'' said LaPierre.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
