<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITRUS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAINS SAVE SOUTH TEXAS CITRUS HARVEST DESPITE EARLIER DROUGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NELSON ANTOSH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After a spring and summer of scorching drought, rains
in the Lower Rio Grande Valley of Texas have given the citrus crop
a shot in the arm.
</P>
<P>
   While the heat is likely to mean slightly smaller grapefruit,
the harvest is expected to be at least as big as last year's, and
some in the industry predict a harvest 15 percent larger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of bailed us out in the nick of time,'' said Ray
Prewett, executive vice president of the Texas Citrus Mutual, a
trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fantastic; it's so beneficial,'' said Dwayne Bair,
president and general manager of the Edinburg Citrus Association, a
cooperative of growers that owns a large packing shed in Edinburg,
a city of 36,000 near the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service office in Brownsville measured 8.62
inches for the first 23 days of September, with rain falling during
12 of those 23 days.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Smith, a grower and owner of a grove care company in
Mission, said he has measured 9 inches of ``nice, sweet rain'' on
his property since Aug. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Up to that point, the entire Valley was turning brown from a
lack of rain that dried up crops ranging from corn to sugar cane.
While there was little growth, the tough citrus trees held onto
fruit set in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting pretty desperate, frankly,'' said Bill Weeks,
president of the Texas Produce Association.
</P>
<P>
   The rain flushed the salt produced by irrigation water from the
soil, penetrating deeply, and produced a spurt of growth on
grapefruit and orange trees.
</P>
<P>
   The fruit, which had been growing very slowly until the rains,
has also started to grow. Rain produces more rapid growth than
irrigation water.
</P>
<P>
   ``The size will be all right; you just have to leave them on the
tree a little longer,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Growers in the Valley will harvest about 9.5 million 40-pound
cartons of grapefruit and oranges compared with 8.4 million a year
ago, estimates Bob Thornton, executive vice president of TexaSweet
Citrus Marketing in Mission.
</P>
<P>
   Drought hurt row crops such as cotton and milo much more than
citrus, Thornton said. It will be a good year for grapefruit and
oranges, he said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The harvest is on the verge of starting, with a small quantity
of early ripening Marrs variety oranges picked last Saturday.
Packing sheds would be gearing up to start if the wet soil hadn't
kept harvest crews out of the orchards.
</P>
<P>
   Grapefruit picking won't start until October. Fieldmen who check
orchards for the Edinburg co-op say that some is already passing
the state's requirements on sugar-acid ratio, Bair said.
</P>
<P>
   This year's grapefruit are likely to be one size smaller than
normal, Thornton said, with the bulk of the harvest in the
48-per-carton range instead of the more typical 40 per carton.
Fruit really don't start gaining size until September, so the rains
were timely, he said. The heat of summer always keeps growth slow.
</P>
<P>
   If you let them hang on the tree during the cooler months,
grapefruit continue to increase in size until February, according
to Thornton. They can get as large as 18 per box. The gift fruit
trade typically uses the 40- to 36-per-box range.
</P>
<P>
   This year's fruit is clean-looking and will grade well, he said.
The dry weather held down populations of insects such as the rust
mite and citrus leaf miner. Plus, there was little wind last
spring, he said, during a time that fruit is sensitive to scarring
_ marks on the skin that reduce their value but have no effect on
eating quality.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks questions whether the 15 percent increase over last year
can be attained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be looking at a crop comparable with last year, but
that's still good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The season's first estimate by the federal-state crop reporting
service won't be issued until Oct. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The trees that were planted after the 1989 freeze are maturing
and there should be increased production almost every year, Weeks
said. There is a total of 35,000 acres planted with grapefruit and
oranges in the Valley, a figure that is not expected to increase
because of a glut caused by overplanting in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen packing sheds will be handling citrus, said Weeks, the
same number as last year.
</P>
<P>
   From 8,000 to 8,500 acres of citrus were served by irrigation
districts that ran out of water, Prewett said. They have supplies
now, he said, as the result of rains that boosted water in the
reservoirs from a low of 19 percent of capacity to nearly 34
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The water now in the reservoirs is almost exactly the same
percentage as at this time last year, a sobering thought. ``We are
out of the immediate crisis situation, but we didn't get any
cushion,'' Prewett said.
</P>
<P>
   The rains also have brightened the outlook for fall and winter
vegetables, said Weeks of the produce association. An informal
survey indicates that acres planted in crops such as onions,
cabbage and carrots will be ``pretty much the same as last year,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the worst of the drought, predictions were that the
number of acres planted would be cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   Now that there is moisture, some growers are planting less,
while others are planting more, Weeks said. Farmers like to stagger
plantings so that everything doesn't ripen at once, but the recent
rains have made that difficult. ``But they are so happy to get the
rain, they can deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
