<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHER-TESTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON UNIVERSITY TO GIVE ITS OWN TEST TO TEACHING STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Threatened by a state plan that could shut down its
school of education, Boston University is refusing to sponsor any
candidates for the state's teacher test unless they pass a
preliminary test administered by BU first.
</P>
<P>
   The university says it is simply trying to make sure its
students are prepared for the test. But other schools of education
are accusing BU of ``gimmickry'' designed to evade responsibility
and embarrassment as the state plans to close any school where more
than 20 percent of students fail the state test.
</P>
<P>
   Boston University's was among the 42 teacher education schools
with a failure rate of higher than 20 percent during the first two
administrations of the test in April and July.
</P>
<P>
   The results set off an embarrassing public excoriation of those
schools, and prompted state action to tighten standards at schools
of education.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Education, led by BU Chancellor John R.
Silber and including BU School of Education dean Edwin J. Delattre,
approved a proposal last week to shut down programs with more than
20 percent of candidates failing in two consecutive years. The
proposal will take effect in 2000. The Department of Education will
decide by Oct. 13 whether schools with high failure rates this year
and next will fall under the requirement, or whether it will apply
only to tests in the two years after 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent last week, Delattre told students and recent
graduates that they would have to pass a test Saturday in order to
be sponsored by BU on the third administration of the state teacher
test Oct.3.
</P>
<P>
   Delattre's letter asks those who don't pass the BU test to not
take the state test. If they do, BU will deny that they attended
the university, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Students indicate on the test where they did their teacher
training, and the state then verifies that information with the
schools before releasing the school-by-school scores publicly.
Those students disclaimed by BU will appear as ``unaffiliated'' in
the public results, and therefore would not be counted against the
university when the state calculates what percentage of BU students
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Other deans said the school is trying to create a loophole to
avoid the tough new state standards. The BU action creates the
impression, they said, that the goal of reform is to keep schools
open, not to train teachers better.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes the whole process of evaluating competence appear
to be gimmickry,'' said Mary Brabeck, dean of the education school
at Boston College, where 78 percent of the 151 students who took
the state tests in April and July passed. ``If the goal is for BU
to have 100 percent pass, they can manipulate things so that will
happen. If the goal is to prepare the most well-trained students
for teaching, then this conversation shouldn't even be taking
place.''
</P>
<P>
   State education officials, while they reserved public comment,
also questioned whether the BU action is true to the spirit of the
reform, which was intended to improve teacher education programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the point of the policy was to try to limit the
number of kids,'' one said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
``It was to make sure that everyone was well prepared to be a
teacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, 59 percent of students failed the test given in
April, and 47 percent the test given in July. In April, 34.3
percent of BU students failed the test, and 28 percent did in July.
Only the Harvard Graduate School of Education and Wellesley College
had more than 80 percent of their students pass each time.
</P>
<P>
   The BU test Saturday is based on sample state test questions
given on the state Department of Education's Web site. It includes
only reading and writing; the state test also includes exams in
specialty areas.
</P>
<P>
   Delattre, because as a board member he knows what questions will
be on the actual test, said he recused himself from preparing the
test BU will give Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Delattre said BU is giving the test to prepare students, but
also to see whether it could be a reliable way to screen transfer
students, who performed poorly on the two state tests and one
reading test given by BU this fall.
</P>
<P>
   He also shot down suggestions that BU is merely trying to ensure
an 80 percent passing rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want the state to have everybody denying their own
students to get 80 percent,'' he said. ``We don't want to do that
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Commonwealth Education Deans Council, a group of education
deans, said it does not know of any other school that plans to
disclaim students. Brabeck suggested that BU should be tightening
whom it admits in the first place, rather than allowing students to
pay tuition and attend school, only to be denied the right to take
the state test as a BU student.
</P>
</TEXT>
