<SLUG> BC-BBN-SOSA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOSA'S 66TH MATCHED BY MCGWIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For a guy who essentially conceded the race five days
ago, Sammy Sosa is still doing a pretty good impression of a home
run king.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs slugger temporarily seized the 1998 lead and all-time
record when he hit his 66th homer Friday night. But typical of this
historic duel that has evolved into a game of leapfrog, he soon had
company. Later in the evening, at St. Louis, Mark McGwire _ whom
Sosa had declared the likely champion Tuesday when he trailed the
Cardinals slugger by two and was in an 0-for-21 slump _ responded
with his 66th.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa did his damage in the fourth inning at the expense of the
playoff-bound Houston Astros. He slammed an 0-1 pitch thrown by
fellow Dominican Jose Lima, a close friend, into the
left-center-field seats. Sosa made it look easy, and it probably
was. He now has four home runs against Houston, three off Lima.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 23, Lima gave up two home runs to Sosa in one game at
Wrigley Field. The other was at the Astrodome Aug. 16 off Sean
Bergman, a solo shot.
</P>
<P>
   A sellout crowd was on hand despite the fact that Houston had
long since wrapped up the National League Central title. They
simply could not resist the lure of Sosa and a race that has been
give-and-take for months.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, it was suggested that Lima might groove a pitch
to his old friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are friends,'' said Sosa. ``But not on the ball field.''
</P>
<P>
   In his pregame session, Sosa had more than home runs on his
mind. After all, the Cubs were locked in a battle for the NL wild
card with the Mets, with whom they were tied entering the night,
and the Giants, who trailed by a game. Two days after tying McGwire
with Nos. 64 and No. 65 in Milwaukee, he entertained a new herd of
media who invaded Texas on a football Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa used the forum to plead for financial assistance for
victims of Hurricane Georges, which has ravaged Puerto Rico, Cuba,
and the Dominican. Sosa gave more than lip service to the cause. In
conjunction with the Cubs, he announced that donations would be
accepted for the Sammy Sosa Charity Foundation to help sponsor a
relief effort. Additionally, he announced that if he was able to
gain possession of home run ball No. 62, with which he became the
second man to break Roger Maris's 37-year-old season record, he
would put it up for auction, with all the proceeds going to the
hurricane victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the Dominican Republic called me and told me
how bad things were,'' said Sosa. ``Then he said, `I know you have
to go out and play the game. Don't worry about it. We're going to
take care of things here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He was right. This is my job. I'm here regardless of what
happens. The only way it can better is that I make something
happen. I almost feel bad that I had to come here and do it in the
other team's park. But all I do is try to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's home run came almost on cue. Most of the fans
were not in their seats when Sosa came to the plate in the first
inning, and he popped out. But by the fourth, everybody was settled
in quite nicely. They seemed to know what was coming.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Sosa was back in a groove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just relaxed,'' he said. ``I said to myself that I was in a
tight situation. My teammates, they need me. If it happens, it's
going to happen for Mark or myself. I'm not thinking about a win.
I'm thinking about making it to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa relaxed his way. He went to the Cubs' video room and
watched himself on tape for an hour. It paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been swinging at too many bad pitches,'' he said. ``I
wanted to know what I was doing wrong. I was trying to find my good
mechanics, my swing, what I've been doing with my feet. I found out
from watching the video what I was doing wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
