<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HOMERS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HAPPY HOMER CHASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The best moment came at 8:37 p.m. CST when both
Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire were standing in their respective
batter's boxes at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy had already homered in Houston, to take a 66-65 lead. But
now McGwire, trailing in the Great Home Run Chase for all of 45
minutes, launched his 66th into the left-field lower deck at Busch
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It is never going to get better than this, sports fans. The
greatest baseball season of them all is winding down in
near-perfect fashion. Two days remain _ maybe three for Sammy's
contending Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   There was some thought Friday night that McGwire might be done
hitting homers in 1998. He'd cranked No. 65 in Milwaukee Sunday,
then was robbed of No. 66 by a bad umpiring decision. When he spoke
with the media before Friday night's game against the Montreal
Expos, he sounded like a man who'd put his bat in the rack for the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sosa cracked No. 66 in the fourth inning in the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Big Mac didn't stay second for long.
</P>
<P>
   It was the sixth inning in Houston and the fifth in St. Louis
when McGwire came up for his third plate appearance of the night,
his first against Expo righthander Shayne Bennett. A split screen
was needed. Both men were at the plate at the same time. Standing
in the press box in St. Louis, you didn't know where to look. Sammy
on TV or Mark live and in color?
</P>
<P>
   Happily, Sosa grounded out before McGwire saw his first pitch.
And Big Mac didn't get cheated. He ripped at Bennett's first serve
and hit it high and far, into the third deck of Busch. Alas, it was
foul, correctly called by third base ump Joe West.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire ran the count to 1-2, then ripped another Bennett pitch,
this one fair, over the wall in left.
</P>
<P>
   There was a scramble in Section 282 and bedlam throughout Busch.
The Great Home Run Chase was tied. Again. But for how long?
</P>
<P>
   McGwire broke his silence before the game. Since homering
Sunday, he'd been communicating only through a pool reporter, but
he agreed to a short press conference at 3:45 p.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked how he would feel about finishing tied with Sosa
and said, ``I think it would be fantastic. But if I'm ahead or he's
ahead, just look at what we've done. People have been saying for 37
years that this (breaking Roger Maris's record of 61 homers)
couldn't be done, and yet two guys have done it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have fun. I'm not going to go away hanging my
head if Sammy is ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he was asked about Bob Davidson's blown call in Milwaukee _
a gaffe that could change history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm happy about it,'' said McGwire. ``It was a
home run, but I respect the ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal manager Tony La Russa, attemping to preserve the
integrity of the game, said he would not bat McGwire leadoff to get
him any extra plate appearances.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire walked on a 3-2 pitch on his first trip against righty
Miguel Batista. Cardinal fans put down their cameras (thank
goodness today is a day game and there'll be no flashbulbs) and
booed with gusto when McGwire trotted to first.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was standing on first in the top of the third, holding a
baserunner, when the big boaad in centerfield posted Sosa's No. 66.
Minutes later, Big Mac returned to the plate and lined deep to left
on an 0-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the dramatic fifth inning in St. Louis. How often does
a man hit a foul home run, then follow it up with a fair one?
Rarely. Almost never. Then again, no one's ever hit 66 home runs in
a season before this year.
</P>
<P>
   Now we have two men, chasing each other, chasing history,
assured of immortality. Perhaps today will be better than Friday
night. And perhaps tomorrow will be better than today. And maybe
Sosa will hit a Bobby Thomson playoff homer Monday to put the Cubs
in the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   It just keeps getting better. To the finish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
