<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Tut Aims for King's Ransom  
 By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Hoping to take advantage of a revived market for initial stock
offerings, Tut Systems plans to go public just as its home
networking technology appears to be taking off.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The small company, based in Pleasant Hill, will announce on
Monday a system to bring high-speed Internet access to apartment
complexes through regular phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Tut, which filed for its IPO on July 31, said yesterday the
stock could start trading within weeks. According to the prospectus
filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Tut wants to
sell 2.5 million shares _ about one-quarter of its total _ for
between $14 and $16 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which was founded in 1991, is not yet profitable,
having lost $8 million last year on sales of $4.5 million. Like
many young technology companies, it has been spending more money
than it makes in an effort to develop products that can gain it a
foothold in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the offering come as the window for IPOs appears to
have reopened. The online auction company eBay showed earlier this
week that investors are eager for hot new stocks. Its shares nearly
tripled on the first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   The timing couldn't be better for Tut. In the past two months,
its system for home networking has been embraced by two of the
biggest names in the computing industry, chip giant Intel and
Compaq Computer, the leading maker of PCs. With those companies
behind it, Tut's technology could soon be built into many new PCs.
</P>
<P>
   What may really fire up investor interest, however, is the
system the company has developed for bringing high-speed access to
existing apartment buildings _ a market for which Tut claims to
have the first practical solution.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Tut's new system leverages our technology to distribute
high-speed Internet access within a multitenant complex,'' said Tut
Systems chief executive Salvatore D'Auria.
</P>
<P>
   The system that Tut will announce Monday consists of a box about
the size of a toaster oven that connects to a high-speed access
line coming into an apartment complex. The box connects to the
central phone system for the complex and provides 1-megabyte data
access to every phone line in every apartment. That's about 20
times as fast as a 56K modem.
</P>
<P>
   Tut's system also makes it possible to use a single phone line
simultaneously for a computer connection and a telephone call,
eliminating the need for separate lines.
</P>
<P>
   To get the high-speed access, users in the apartments must
install a network card in their computers and attach an adapter
that lets the network card connect to a regular phone jack.
</P>
<P>
   Installation of the card and adapter is expected to cost users
around $100, with monthly Internet service running between $35 and
$50 a month. That's roughly on a par with cable modem systems such
as AtHome, which advertises higher speeds, and considerably less
than what phone companies are charging for DSL, which offers
comparable high-speed access. And neither cable modem service nor
DSL is generally available to apartment dwellers because they
involve special wiring.
</P>
<P>
   Tut charges about $5,000 as a base price for its box and related
equipment. It will sell the system directly to an apartment complex
owner, or to an Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tut's system is pretty cool stuff,'' said analyst Jim
Balderston of Zona Research. ``It's relatively simple. You don't
have to hire guys to tear up floors or pull wires through walls.''
</P>
<P>
   With an estimated 34 million apartment dwellers in the United
States, the market for systems such as Tut's could be enormous. Not
only does it promise revenues for Tut, it also is seen as a way for
apartment owners to attract tenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to set us apart from other apartment
communities,'' said Doug Kampillo, director of information for BRE
Properties. BRE has a pilot installation of the Tut system at its
Promontory Point apartment complex in San Ramon. Complexes in San
Rafael and Palo Alto are scheduled to go online within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who's tried it seems to love it because they get the
same speed at home that they have at work,'' said Kampillo.
</P>
<P>
   Optimism is running high at Tut, which employs about 100 people.
Said marketing vice president Craig Stouffer: ``If I gave an honest
answer about how I feel about this new system, I'd be in trouble
for hyping the stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the company understands that it's in a fiercely
competitive field in which prices drop faster than you can say
shrinking margins. In addition, other networking companies
including Cisco Systems and Ascend Communications can be expected
to jump into Tut's markets, especially if they prove lucrative.
Meanwhile, a range of other vendors are also offering home
networking systems similar to Tut's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
