<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Video Search Technology Lets Web Users Quickly Find Clips  
 By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
Voyeurs who want to watch President Clinton squirm at the mention
of the blue dress don't have to sit through four hours of video
testimony on the Internet.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A San Mateo startup says it has developed the first video search
engine that lets online users type in a phrase or keyword and then
view only the video segments associated with those words.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done for video what Internet directories have done for
online text searches,'' said Dave Bayliss, a spokesman for Virage.
``You no longer have to painfully watch X minutes of jerky motion
images to get to the good parts.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Virage's first public deployment of its Video Cataloger
technology went up on Tuesday at  &LR; video.altavista.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   It contains a search bar where users type in a keyword or
phrase. It then conducts a search over the four-plus hours of
Clinton's grand jury testimony and comes up with a list of video
clips on that topic. Users have a choice of playing one- to
two-minute video clips and/or reading a transcript of that clip.
</P>
<P>
   Without Virage, people had to sit through entire video from
start to finish or watch it on a site that had edited it into
smaller segments.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, many viewers decided to watch Clinton's testimony
last week on TV rather than the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit of Virage: Users can view snippets of the
document without downloading the entire video, which can clog up
the computer.
</P>
<P>
   The new video-engine technology _ which was developed last year
for corporations to catalog videos internally _ converts real-time
video into data code that can be searched on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The data code is collected from the Clinton videotape, captured
onto clips and translated into other formats, including HTML.
</P>
<P>
   For the Clinton video, Virage paired the video with a written
transcript obtained from closed-caption TV. Soon, it will add voice
recognition and speaker identification to distinguish between
different voices.
</P>
<P>
   Virage, a 4-year-old privately held company, is licensing its
technology to online news media and other sites that use video.
</P>
<P>
   So far, ABC News, the British Broadcasting Corp., CBS News, CNN
and federal agencies are early licensees of Video Cataloger and are
expected to make it a staple of their Web sites. Several plan on
indexing scores of existing video clips online so consumers can
perform searches, Bayliss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``While everyone was racing to put a bunch of dumb video on
their Web sites, we produced the first intelligent video,'' Bayliss
said. ``We expect use of this technology to become widespread.''
</P>
<P>
   The 60-person company is backed by Adobe Ventures, Sutter Hill
Ventures, Trinity Ventures and others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
