<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Oddball Coalition Was the Loser in High-Tech H-1B Struggle  
 By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
When the votes were finally tallied, the high-tech industry had won
a resounding, bipartisan victory in its bid to raise the quota of
foreign temporary workers it could hire under H-1B visas.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The loser in Thursday's lopsided 283-to-133 vote in the House of
Representatives was the odd coalition of liberal, pro-labor
Democrats and conservative, anti-immigration Republicans who had
given the tech lobby its toughest fight in years.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Bay Area's 17 House representatives only three voted
against the H-1B increase: East Bay Democrats Barbara Lee and Pete
Stark, and Windsor Republican Frank Riggs, known for his kiss-my-ax
stand on timber issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``High-tech has been among the selfish and least helpful
corporations in the country,'' Stark said. ``All they've ever done
is come to us and ask for tax breaks and free trade. They're all
take and no give, and (the visa bill) to me is another example of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The thread uniting these congressional naysayers is that they
represent minority or blue-collar constituents who feel edged out
for the best jobs by skilled foreigners. Visa opponents claim tech
firms would rather hire quickly from abroad than take the time to
train people at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one good thing that came out of this fight is that it
brought blacks together with over-40, white professionals,'' said
John Templeton, an entrepreneur who formed the Coalition for Fair
Employment in Silicon Valley, an ad hoc group that advocates
training and hiring of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   African American activists like Templeton formed one strain of
opposition to the H-1B hike. Indeed, H-1B opponents in the House
staged their last stand around amendments sponsored by
Representative Melvin Watt (D-N.C.) and Representative John Conyers
(D-Mich.), leaders of the Congressional Black Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Watt and Conyers wanted to force all employers to swear that
they hadn't laid off U.S. workers to hire H-1B employees. After
their amendments were rebuffed, House members piled on to support a
White House-backed version of the bill, which took milder steps to
prevent foreigners from displacing U.S. workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was close to a betrayal of the African American
community,'' said Templeton of the White House's bargain with the
high-tech lobby.
</P>
<P>
   One reason tech execs prevailed in the debate was that early on
they popularized the notion of a huge shortfall of engineers.
Although the study they used was later debunked, the shortage
notion stuck.
</P>
<P>
   The tech lobby also created the impression that H-1B workers
were essential to the booming tech economy _ writing cutting-edge
software or founding the next Intel _ when in fact one-quarter of
these foreign temps are physical therapists and another one-quarter
work in noncomputer fields.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Matloff, the University of California at Davis professor
who has taken up the cause of older high-tech workers, predicted,
``There's going to be a larger and larger pool of angry and bitter
computer professionals'' because of the H-1B vote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by phone
(650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail
(abateATSYMBOLsfgate.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
