<HEADER>
A5568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS26-COX     09-25 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panel to release more Starr papers, as Democrats lose
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans trotted out of the House Judiciary
Committee's chambers Friday night declaring a newfound comity with
Democrats in the bitter battle over whether to move forward in the
impeachment process aimed at President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting behind closed doors for most of the day, the panel voted
in a series of motions to make public some 60,000 pages of
documents, grand jury testimony and other related evidence turned
over to the committee by independent counsel Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The material is expected to back up Starr's allegations that
Clinton committed perjury, obstructed justice and abused his
presidential powers to conceal a sexual affair with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats quickly dismissed the notion that harmony had been
achieved, saying the committee was actually as divided as ever.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement about the level of partisanship shaped public
statements Friday about the decision to make public the remaining
documents turned over to the panel by Starr earlier this month.
Already, the panel has released the 445-page Starr report, the
president's grand jury testimony and more than 3,000 pages of
depositions, interviews and FBI reports.
</P>
<P>
   The latest batch of evidence is expected to include grand jury
testimony from Linda Tripp, the former White House employee who
revealed to Starr that Lewinsky had a sexual relationship with the
president. The committee vote to release edited versions of these
tapes was unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   Also expected to be released is grand jury testimony from Betty
Currie, the president's personal secretary, who was aware of
Lewinsky's visits. Testimony from Vernon Jordan, the president's
friend and confidant, also will be included in the latest release.
Jordan helped arrange a job for Lewinsky after the affair sputtered
to a close, but the job fell through when the firestorm over the
affair began.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to release additional documents was a foregone
conclusion, but Democrats on the panel tried unsuccessfully to
prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, Democrats said that they believed the public has had
too much of the lurid details of this investigation, and voted to
stop the release of all of this grand jury material,'' said
Michigan Democratic Rep. John Conyers, the ranking member of the
committee, after the daylong debate.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Republican Bob Barr had a different view.
</P>
<P>
   While the debate was contentious, Barr said, it was civil and
successful in that the material will be released and the public can
judge for itself whether the president committed impeachable
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a good day,'' agreed Rep. Steve Buyer (R-Ind.),
echoing his Republican peers on the committee and pointing to
bipartisan vote tallies as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   But before a gaggle of television cameras, Rep. Barney Frank
(D-Mass.) quickly disagreed with Buyer and Barr's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   Frank pointed out that the Republicans, led by Barr, voted down
a Democratic proposition to require Starr to release more
information outlining how Tripp taped telephone conversations with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Starr wired Tripp to tape her conversations
with Lewinsky before U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno approved
expanding his probe into the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   But Buyer argued that the committee's Democrats were the ones
who were trying to keep information out of the public domain.
</P>
<P>
   The material is expected to be made public next Thursday, when
the committee also plans to hear its own lawyers present Starr's
evidence of potentially impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is expected to vote by the end of next week on
whether to launch a formal impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   That will be followed by a House vote on the inquiry, probably
on Oct. 5 or 6.
</P>
<P>
   Even Democrats say there is nothing they can do to stop the
``impeachment train.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House continued to mount its campaign against
impeachment, emphasizing polls that showed Clinton's popularity
rising after his videotaped grand jury testimony on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton himself accused the GOP of placing ``partisanship over
progress, politics over people.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats such as Martin Meehan (D-Mass.) said that the
Republicans were clearly trying to drag out the impeachment process
to engage in a ``mud fight'' that would improve their chances of
taking over the White House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) scoffed at such
notions, saying Clinton's remarks amounted to ``a gratuitous
slap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing our work,'' said Lott. ``Maybe he just hasn't
noticed. ... What he's trying to do is distract attention from his
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
