<SLUG> BC-BOX-MAVROVIC-LEWIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NAME'S MAVROVIC, AND HE'S OUT TO STOP LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (lb) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNCASVILLE, Conn. _ It is not easy being Zeljko Mavrovic. He has
been virtually ignored as he prepares to take on Lennox Lewis, the
World Boxing Council heavyweight champion, in a title bout Saturday
night and his name is mangled so much that he simply wants to be
referred to as ``Zed.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis calls him ``Magnovich,'' which is not remotely close to
the correct pronunciation and is said with a hint of derision. When
Mavrovic held his first telephone news conference with reporters in
New York last month to announce his bout with Lewis on Saturday
night, he introduced himself and one of the reporters in the room
shouted, ``How do we know it's you?''
</P>
<P>
   But if Mavrovic (pronounced mahv-RO-vitch) can upset Lewis
inside the big white tent that has been set up outside the Mohegan
Sun Casino, a lot of people will have to become familiar with his
name. That includes Evander Holyfield, the International Boxing
Federation and World Boxing Association heavyweight champion, who
has referred to Mavrovic as ``Maverick.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavrovic, who is from Croatia, takes his low profile in America
in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say?'' he said. ``If you talk about me in Europe,
they know me. I have been three years European champion. Anybody
who knows and likes boxing knows about me. In the United States it
is a different story. Not many people know about me, because I
haven't had many fights in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavrovic has fought three times in the United States against
opponents with less name recognition than he has. His bout against
Lewis, which will be broadcast on HBO as part of its Championship
Boxing Series at 10 p.m., will give him more exposure than he has
ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Mavrovic, 27, looks like a punk rocker with his dirty-blond
mohawk haircut, which he says is a result of a barbering mistake by
his girlfriend, Jelena Balabanic. Balabanic also dabbles in
astrology and does not believe the stars are in the proper
alignment for Mavrovic, an Aquarius, to do his best on Saturday
night. But she is withholding any more bad news until the bout is
over.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who weighed in at 243 pounds Friday, believes Mavrovic
will be in survival mode when the bout gets under way. But Mavrovic
is more confident than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm too quick for him; so, so quick,'' Mavrovic said. ``I have
a big right hand, too. I can knock people out with my right hand.''
He added: ``Lennox Lewis is not someone who can take a lot of
punches. If you punch him in the right place at the right time, he
will go down. I saw that in Atlantic City.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavrovic was at ringside for Lewis' last fight, against Shannon
Briggs in March, a bout in which Lewis was rocked in the first
round by Briggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox Lewis is a great talent,'' Mavrovic said. ``But what I
saw in that fight was that he didn't have good preparation and
motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavrovic, who weighed in at 214 1/4 pounds (his lightest in
three years), has been preparing for this bout against Lewis for 11
months, because that is when he found out that he was the WBC's No.
1 contender. The bout kept being postponed, and Mavrovic kept
training in Croatia. He has also been on a macrobiotic diet, which
includes no meat. It has resulted in him being 10 pounds lighter
than he has been in his six previous fights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
