<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HAMPTON-NYT &LR;      09-25 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HAMPTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMPTON MAY UPSTAGE WILLIAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   All the hoopla will surround Doug Williams, the coach with the
National Football League background, Super Bowl ring and legacy to
follow. But at the conclusion of the 28th annual New York Urban
League Football Classic on Saturday, coach Joe Taylor and his
Hampton University Pirates are very likely to be the ones in the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, the defending black college national champion, is
favored to defeat Grambling State University in the 5 p.m. game at
Giants Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J. Even Williams, Grambling's
first-year coach, admits that his Tigers (1-1) are probably
overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was blessed with 6-foot-6, 320-pound offensive
linemen like coach Taylor is,'' said Williams, who has replaced the
legendary Eddie Robinson, the winningest coach in college football
history. ``We're going to get there, though. We're not coming to
the Meadowlands just to lay down, but it would be a pleasure just
to go into overtime with Hampton and lose if that's the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Grambling, which has played in all but three of the Classics, is
billing this season as the ``Dawn of a New Era.'' Williams, who
starred at Grambling from 1974-1977 and went on to lead the
Washington Redskins to victory in the 1989 Super Bowl, is the first
coach besides Robinson to lead the Tigers since 1940. He has
replaced Robinson's historic wing-T offense with a multiple pro set
and substituted the traditional black and gold for the Tigers' red
and multicolored uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will always give coach Robinson his props,'' Williams said.
``But at the same time, it's time to move on to the future. Let the
Doug Williams era begin.''
</P>
<P>
   While it may be Williams' time at Grambling, it is Taylor's time
in black college football. His Pirates (3-0) are dominant, having
won 78 percent of their games since he took over seven years ago.
In just their fourth year after moving up to Division I-AA in the
NCAA, they are ranked fifth in the nation and first in the Sheridan
Broadcasting Network's ranking of historically black colleges.
Taylor, last season's SBN coach of the year, has a record of
117-44-4.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who reveres Robinson, says he looks up to Taylor as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to have just half the amount of success that coach
Taylor has had,'' Williams said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
