<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5575 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LAWYERS-775(2     09-25 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LAWYERS-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER'S JOB AND SEX ACTS ARE MATTERS OF DEFINITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID MARGOLICK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a cascade of contrition, President Clinton has almost
greedily accepted responsibility for his present predicament. But
when blame for the Monica Lewinsky matter is apportioned, the
finger-pointing goes in another direction: toward Clinton's
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Privilege shrouds all discussions between the president and his
legal counsel, making it impossible to know who said what to whom
and whether Clinton has received bad advice or has refused to
follow good advice. But authorities on legal ethics and culture _
that is, lawyers who monitor other lawyers _ say the president's
problems stem in part from systemic weaknesses in the legal
profession, a profession ill-equipped to represent extraordinary
clients or to take the national interest into account.
</P>
<P>
   These weaknesses, some experts say, are both as timeless as the
inherent tension between lawyers and powerful clients and as new as
the deterioration in the training lawyers now receive.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows whether Clinton was initially any more candid with
his lawyers, notably Robert Bennett and David Kendall, than he was
with his closest associates, his Cabinet or his family. But what
legal experts do argue is that by training and temperament, lawyers
don't always press their clients for the truth or try to learn the
truth themselves.
</P>
<P>
   That has always been the case. But to some experts, the
president's highly legalistic defense, using a tortured definition
of sex that has earned him great ridicule, could be related to
something new: the training elite lawyers are now likely to get,
which can blind them to what matters most.
</P>
<P>
   While the best and brightest have always marched off to Wall
Street-style law firms, the firms themselves have changed, largely
as result of a vastly more competitive marketplace. Increasingly
profit-oriented, less likely to have long-term counseling relations
with loyal clients, less concerned with inculcating values into
young associates, these firms seem to be producing lawyers who are
more parochial, with dulled ethical and political instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawyering business really has kind of shrunk from a
profession of general counselors and advisers to the notion of a
very narrow technical specialty in which what the lawyer does is
simply advise on the available legal strategy,'' said Robert
Gordon, a legal historian at Yale Law School. As a result, Gordon
said, lawyers are more likely to focus on minutiae than on the
larger issues usually involved in highly charged political cases.
``You get very little sense from Bennett or Kendall that what is at
issue is a president, his capacity to govern, his place in
history,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   To William Simon of Stanford Law School, the very lack of
perspective for which Clinton's lawyers have often been faulted
applies in even stronger measure to the unrelenting Whitewater
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr. ``When you put lawyers in
charge of a moral crusade, you risk that they'll handle it without
any sense of proportionality, largely because it's not part of
their makeup,'' he said. ``We try to teach lawyers to make value
judgments, to weigh principles, but the professional culture of
technicality and literalism is even stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Legally speaking, it was Paula Jones who begat Monica Lewinsky;
perhaps the most fateful decision by Clinton and his lawyers was
not to settle Mrs. Jones' sexual harassment suit out of court.
Strictly as a legal proposition, her case was extremely weak, and
sure enough, Bennett's elaborate, powerful arguments persuaded a
federal judge (a Republican) to throw it out. (Even had it gone to
trial, they were confident that it could be disposed of in a week
or two.)
</P>
<P>
   But in the unique context of presidential politics, what
mattered most was less the merits of Mrs. Jones' case against
Clinton than what her lawyers learned about Clinton along the way.
Bennett's approach, like that of many lawyers, reflected great
faith in precedent, logic and the primacy of winning in court _
safe assumptions in many cases but not necessarily in so
politically charged a suit. That Clinton's lawyers have recently
resumed settlement talks with the Jones lawyers only underscores
this initial mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Legal education and legal culture make victory in court the
only victory,'' said Stephen Gillers of New York University Law
School. ``But the Jones case was only partly about what will happen
in court, and mostly about the survival and reputation of the
president. So it became dangerous to let lawyers control the
progress of the case. People unencumbered by legal training and
experience might have chosen differently.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his new, posthumously published memoir, ``Lawyer: A Life of
Counsel and Controversy'' (Public Affairs, 1998), Arthur Liman
makes a similar criticism of Starr, comparing him to other
prosecutors who have wrongly ``tried to make criminal cases out of
political offenses.'' Liman himself, however, was faulted as being
overly legalistic in the Iran-Contra hearings, letting Oliver North
outflank him in the court of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   That clients lie to their lawyers is nothing new. ``The first
reaction of every white-collar client is not to tell the whole
truth and nothing but the truth,'' said Kenneth Mann, a law
professor at Tel Aviv University and the author of a study on
American lawyers who represent white-collar criminal defendants.
And lawyers are not ethically bound to ferret those lies out. ``I
never ask a client whether he did it or not,'' Alan Dershowitz of
Harvard Law School once told Charlie Rose. ``I don't want the
client to feel that he has to start his relationship with me by
lying.''
</P>
<P>
   While the American Bar Association has condemned the practice of
avoiding knowledge, no lawyer has ever been sanctioned for doing
so. But what is ethically tolerable is not always tactically wise.
``About half of the practice of a decent lawyer is telling would-be
clients they are damned fools and should stop,'' Elihu Root, a
prominent New York lawyer who went on to become secretary of state,
once said.
</P>
<P>
   The Linda Tripp tapes, the questions from the Jones lawyers, the
White House phone logs and Secret Service documents as well as
Clinton's own past evasiveness and hair-splitting on topics like
sex, the draft and drug use _ the president is, after all, a
graduate of Yale Law School and a former law professor _ were all
tip-offs that the president's denials about Ms. Lewinsky were
implausible. The question is whether Bennett and Kendall pushed
Clinton aggressively enough to change his answers before the issue
of perjury arose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lawyers too often submit to demanding and powerful clients,''
said Gillers, who examines Clinton's counsel in the coming issue of
The American Lawyer. ``To call the president a fool or to tell him
he's acting like an ass is no easy thing. But it's precisely when
you represent a president that you have to be tough and blunt and
shake him up a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that Clinton's lawyers _ or today's crop of
lawyers _ are deficient. Leonard Garment, former counsel for
President Richard Nixon, says that Clinton's improved fortunes in
the polls in the last few days reflects that his lawyers have
pulled off the impossible: maintaining his political viability
while limiting his legal liability.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe Freedman of Hofstra Law School, a pioneer in the field of
legal ethics, said Clinton's high-caliber counsel probably pushed
him as far as they could. Nor, he said, were contemporary lawyers
necessarily any less public-spirited and worldly, or yesterday's
lawyers any more enlightened, as Gordon contends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can he think that the lawyers who represented the robber
barons were not pulling hypertechnical stuff?'' Freedman asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
