<HEADLINE>
CONVICTION IS DISMISSED IN A RECANTED CASE OF SEX ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW CITY, N.Y. _ Six months after a young woman recanted graphic
sex-abuse accusations against her father, a judge threw out the
father's conviction Friday and said it was unlikely that a retrial
would succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Although prosecutors held out the possibility of an appeal, they
too said that a retrial itself was ``highly unlikely.'' Thus
Friday's decision begins to draw the curtain on a four-year-long
ordeal for Joseph Hoehmann, a 38-year-old building contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Hoehmann was forced out of his home by the abuse charges, and
his troubles deepened when his infant daughter later died in a fire
_ a death Hoehmann believes might not have happened if he had still
been at home.
</P>
<P>
   Absorbing the news at the apartment of Stacey Hoehmann, the
20-year-old daughter who accused him at a 1996 trial and then
reversed herself last March, Hoehmann said Friday that he was still
worried that prosecutorial zeal might make it difficult for him to
resume his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``When do we put the brakes on and say, `Hey, this is a
malicious prosecution'? '' he said. ``Let everyone live their lives
and get on with their lives. If only these people would get their
minds out of the gutter and let the family be.''
</P>
<P>
   The case began in January 1995 when Ms. Hoehmann, who had been
bridling for years under her father's discipline, began telling
friends that he had molested her on three occasions, starting when
she was 14 years old. In October 1996, Hoehmann was convicted at a
non-jury trial by Clarkstown Town Justice Victor Alfieri Jr. of
third-degree sexual abuse and endangering the welfare of a child.
</P>
<P>
   While she was the only eyewitness to the supposed abuse, Alfieri
repeatedly said he found her accusations sincere and credible. That
feeling may have been strengthened when Ms. Hoehmann, at her
father's sentencing, made an angry speech, telling her father,
``You're burning in hell for what you did.'' Hoehmann was freed on
bail, but has been spending every day since under the cloud of a
one-year jail sentence and an even more painful stigma. He has been
unable to find steady work.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1998, Ms. Hoehmann wrote a startling letter to the
judge saying that she had lied. Prosecutors shot back at a July
hearing that she was repudiating her testimony to get back with her
family and had even told two friends the recantation was a lie.
</P>
<P>
   But Alfieri signaled his inclination to overturn the conviction
by lifting an order of protection, enabling father and daughter to
reunite for the first time in four years. On Friday, he threw out
his own finding of guilty because he said he found her recantation
as credible as her original accusations had been.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said that Stacey understood that by recanting, ``she is in
fact accepting the responsibility and blame for her sister's
death'' _ a 15-month-old sister killed in an electrical fire while
the father was barred from his own home _ and the breakup of her
family. He was also persuaded by her willingness to recant knowing
that, in theory, criminal charges of perjury could be filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may very well be the case that Stacey has purchased the
companionship of her family with perjured recantation testimony,''
the judge wrote in a 29-page decision. ``If this is so, the
defendant has made a fool's bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge explained that even if the recantation is a lie Stacey
``may always be an outcast'' in the family.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Ms. Hoehmann, who manages a coffee
shop at the Palisades Center mall and studies at St. Thomas Aquinas
College in Sparkill, said that her family had ``accepted me back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still things that need to be worked out, but we're
pretty much there,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
