<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-COLISEUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLISEUM DISPUTE FORCES GAME CANCELLATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINEOLA, N.Y. _ Legal skirmishing over the structural safety of
the Nassau Coliseum forced cancellation of Friday night's scheduled
exhibition game between the New York Islanders and the New Jersey
Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not going to get this matter resolved by game
time,'' said state Supreme Court Justice Burton Joseph at the end
of a frustrating day-long hearing on safety issues at the
26-year-old arena.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 7:30 p.m., the judge adjourned the hearing until
Monday morning, and ordered the lawyers involved in the dispute not
to discuss the matter over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're under a gag order not to say anything,'' said Gary
Bettman, commissioner of the National Hockey League. ``But I'm
hopeful we've taken a step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Bettman said the Islanders remained under a temporary
restraining order issued by Joseph a week ago, barring the team
from playing any scheduled home games anywhere but the Coliseum.
The next scheduled game is with the Washington Capitals on Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the Islanders claim that the cement and steel
reinforced trusses that hold up the Coliseum are cracked, that the
scoreboard that hangs over center ice was held in place by a
defective hoist and that the roof was leaking, creating safety
hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County, which owns the arena, contends the arena is safe
and that the owners of the Islanders, who bought the team in
February, are using the safety issue as a ruse to break their
long-term contract with the county and SMG, a group that manages
the Coliseum for the county.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph, in an effort to resolve the dispute, gained the help of
Bettman and his aides during a hearing on Wednesday in which they
appointed a team of engineers and assigned them the task of
inspecting the Coliseum. However, the engineers and lawyers
returned to court on Thursday and again early Friday morning,
complaining to the judge that they could not agree on what items to
inspect.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman told the judge he needed at least another day and a half
for his engineers to complete the job, but the county resisted the
move, claiming its engineers and appropriate county regulatory
officials had already approved the safety of the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The judge attempted to limit the inspections to four items _ the
scoreboard support system, the truss supports, the arena's cement
bleachers and the external walls of the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Ortego, a lawyer representing the county, argued that the
county did not believe the NHL was a neutral party in the dispute
and should not be given such powers by the court.
</P>
<P>
   Ortego argued that only county and state regulators had the
power to rule on safety issues at the Coliseum. ``Thc court should
not permit the NHL to usurp those powers and let the Islanders
continue their fishing expedition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman acknowledged during the hearing that the bitter
differences between the Islanders and Nassau County were
detrimental to both and that it harmed their future hopes of
building a new arena, hotel and convention center on the 80-acre
Coliseum site in Uniondale.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0484 </DOCNO>
