<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5690 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-HIGHWAY-PROPOSAL-3     09-25 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-HIGHWAY-PROPOSAL-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA DEALS TURNPIKE LINK A NEW SETBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 BY RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDISON, N.J. _ In the latest setback for New Jersey's longest
pending highway project, the federal Environmental Protection
Administration announced Friday that it was opposed to a $300
million, high-speed, limited access highway that would connect the
New Jersey Turnpike with the thriving business corridor along Route
1 in the central part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly 18 months of studying the proposed highway, the
agency concluded that the highway would not solve the area's many
transportation problems as its proponents had insisted it would and
that it would not justify the loss of 18 acres of wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the agency and its transportation consultants found
that a series of improvements and expansions of existing local
roads at a number of key points could do just as much to ease
congestion as the highway would.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the cost of losing irreplaceable wetlands and at $300
million, Route 92 is an overpriced solution,'' said EPA regional
administrator Jeanne Fox, at an agency compound here as she
announced that the agency would oppose the issuance of a permit by
the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers to build the road. ``It is an
expensive proposal which in reality solves little and would
diminish the natural resources we must endow to future
generations.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear whether the EPA ruling doomed the
project. Gov. Christine Todd Whitman and the State Department of
Environmental Protection are on record as supporting the highway,
and within the next 30 days they can challenge the agency's
position before the permit is taken up formally by the U.S. Army
Corps of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Jayne O'Connor, a spokesman for the governor, said she would
first take time to review the EPA position before deciding how the
state would proceed.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, a spokesman for the turnpike authority disputed
whether the local roads could under any circumstances handle the
existing and projected traffic volumes, especially the truck
traffic. Even so, the statement continued, the highway authority
would study the alternatives suggested by the EPA.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In one form or another, the proposed highway link has been in
state planning documents since 1938 and in that time it has
metamorphosed from a 25-mile long freeway linking the western part
of the state with the Atlantic shore to the current, 6.5-mile,
75-cent toll road running virtually uninterrupted and without exits
between Princeton and Jamesburg. It is the last major highway
project on the drawing boards in the metropolitan region.
</P>
<P>
   About 11.1 million square feet in commercial development and
12,000 units of housing are planned for the area around the Route 1
corridor. The proponents of Route 92 envisioned it as a way to keep
the office-park developments along Route 1 to the west and the
growing warehousing and trucking operations that cluster to the
east both accessible and expanding.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Dowgin, a South Brunswick resident and a leader in the
local campaign against Route 92, applauded the environmental
agency's ruling, saying it would save soybean fields and fruit
orchards that are visible from her house from being turned into a
ribbon of concrete.
</P>
<P>
   But Anthony Pizzitullo, chairman of 92 Now, the coalition of
labor, business and educational institutions that have supported
the proposed highway, called it ``a sad day for central New
Jersey.'' He said the ruling was ``an unbalanced and narrow
decision'' that, if left unchallenged, would have devastating
consequences for the area and its growth.
</P>
<P>
   The major EPA alternative would be a 1.2-mile access road on the
existing Route 32 as it runs between the turnpike and several
connecting, local roads. Such a project would cost $73 million by
the EPA's estimate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
