</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBIERE-OPERA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IL BARBIERE DI SIVIGLIA': NEW VOICES TAKE ON EVERGREEN ROSSINI 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the unwritten mandates of the New York City
Opera is presentable productions of the standard repertory offered
at affordable prices. Thursday night's return of ``Il Barbiere di
Siviglia'' checked out nicely. It also gave us a look at some
interesting young singers.
</P>
<P>
   Desmond Heeley's bright, traditional sets offer no surprises,
but they are honest representations and blessedly distant from the
moth-eaten productions with which the company struggled during the
1980s. The newcomer to Rossini will not be misled and the
connoisseur not terribly disappointed. Albert Sherman's direction
is jokey but rarely out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the singing was exceptionally promising. Among those
making their debuts was Kristine Jepson as Rosina. She is
self-assured and scrupulous onstage. The voice carries easily in
this big space and negotiates the music's intricacies without
incident. Ms. Jepson is the kind of finished young American singer
who keeps international opera houses, large and small, more or less
in business, and her presence should help the City Opera
considerably.
</P>
<P>
   As the old theatrical saying goes, careers are often launched
atop the misfortunes of others, and so it was here. Daniel Mobbs, a
company baritone, was ill on Thursday, but Mel Ulrich was ready to
take his place as Figaro.
</P>
<P>
   Ulrich, also new to the company, did very well. The voice, suave
and elegant, is generated by excellent diction. Ulrich looks good
and moves well onstage; he is a natural Figaro. For all its
seamlessness, however, the voice sounds young. Everything it did
succeeded, but one felt a technique operating just at the edge of
its capacity.
</P>
<P>
   I worry about such a promising talent pushing hard in a large
space like this, but if Ulrich and his handlers are very careful,
he might become a notable operatic personality.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the cast, Matthew Polenzani sang Almaviva in his
light and attractive tenor. Laura Knoop, another newcomer, made a
nice impression as Berta.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Glavin brought to Dr. Bartolo the requisite agility for
Rossini's rapid patter. At one point, Glavin sang flat for comic
effect; too often his waywardness of pitch was less a matter to
smile over. Recitative in particular careered so eccentrically that
Bartolo's interlocutors had to work hard remembering the key they
had begun in.
</P>
<P>
   Time, as ever, is the City Opera's constant enemy. There is
never enough to truly make things work. Robert DeCeunynck's clever
mimicking at the harpsichord still couldn't rescue the often
halting connections between players during recitatives. Guido
Ajmone-Marsan conducted a performance that in broad outlines was
alert and deft, but full of small smudges and missed connections.
</P>
<P>
   Shon Sims (Fiorello), Kevin Maynor (Don Basilio), John Lankston
(Ambrogio) and William Ledbetter (the Official) all did well. The
lighting is by Ken Tabachnik, and Frederic Hand played the guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Il Barbiere di Siviglia'' repeats at Sunday's matinee.
Listeners who don't know the opera will be honestly informed and
have a good time. No one will be cheated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
