<DOCNO> NYT19980925.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-25 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5702 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SOHO-RETAIL-2TAKES     09-25 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SOHO-RETAIL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RE-CREATING MADISON AVE. DOWNTOWN: IN SOHO, CONSUMERISM IS AN ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A uniformed security guard stands by the door of the
imposing new Louis Vuitton store on Greene Street. Inside,
fashionably dressed couples, many from Europe or Japan, eye the
rich leather bags arranged one to a shelf like exemplars of a rare
type of ancient pottery. Downstairs, clothes are displayed with a
studied casualness _ a long skirt here, a jacket there. A steamer
trunk with a price tag of $25,000 rests on the highly polished
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Vuitton? In Soho?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. And yes. And it is hardly alone. Before long, Vuitton will
be joined by the likes of Yves Saint Laurent, Prada, Helena
Rubenstein and the jewelers H. Stern and Bulgari.
</P>
<P>
   Madison Avenue is migrating downtown, hoping to draw a mix of
affluent customers, including inhabitants of increasingly costly
Tribeca and Soho loft buildings, foreign guests of two new Soho
hotels and weekend daytrippers from the suburbs. Some retailers say
they plan to use their new stores, many in former gallery spaces,
to try out new ideas, broaden their customer base or display a
wider range of goods than they could accommodate uptown.
</P>
<P>
   Around Soho these days, a good number of old-timers are more
than a little upset that all of this is happening to a place that
has long defined itself as an antidote to uptown taste in art and
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   It was that ``funky'' character that attracted Sean Sweeney to
this neighborhood of cast-iron facades and wide-open loft spaces 22
years ago. ``If there's one place in the world I didn't want to
live in, it was the Upper East Side,'' said Sweeney, who is the
executive director of the Soho Alliance, a community group. Now, he
said, ``It looks like it's turning into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as with pretty much any hip New York neighborhood,
Soho has been getting steadily less so ever since it became an
acronym (which is about as long as people have been bemoaning the
loss of the ``old'' Soho). The high-end retailers' southward
stampede is actually only the latest change to wash over a
neighborhood that became an artists' enclave nearly three decades
ago as loft buildings once occupied by light manufacturing were
converted into studios and living spaces. In recent years, as rents
rose, many of the art galleries that followed the artists have had
to give up their storefronts and were replaced by home furnishing
shops.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, this newest incarnation is really, in a sense, a
return to Soho's roots: In the mid-19th century, the area south of
Houston Street formed a luxury shopping district not unlike the one
that is crystallizing there today. Tiffany &AMP; Co., Lord &AMP; Taylor,
Brooks Brothers and Crouch &AMP; Fitzgerald were just a few of the
elegant stores of that era to find a home on lower Broadway, the
eastern end of Soho.
</P>
<P>
   One such establishment, E.V. Haughwout &AMP; Co., at Broadway and
Broome Street, supplied the White House with china during the
Lincoln presidency. The store dazzled the eye with every imaginable
type of serving vessel and even carried its own brand of champagne.
</P>
<P>
   But lower Broadway's role as a carriage-trade thoroughfare was
short-lived. By the end of the Civil War, most of the tony shops
had moved north to Union Square. Soho evolved into a center for
manufacturing, wholesaling and warehousing.Soho
</P>
<P>
   These days, real estate brokers say, luxury stores are competing
furiously for space in Soho, and spending heavily once the deal is
secured. Helena Rubenstein, for example, will invest more than $5
million in a spa and cosmetics store on Spring Street.
</P>
<P>
   It may eventually be joined by Ralph Lauren. Along with a
British partner, Polo Ralph Lauren bought a 55,000-square-foot
garage on West Broadway last year and then, in January, acquired an
additional 30,000 square feet of space in a building a few doors
away. But no workers can be spotted at those locations, and the
company ``has not made any determination on how the space will be
used,'' said Lynn Tesoro, a spokeswoman for Ralph Lauren.
</P>
<P>
   These high-end retailers are avoiding Broadway, which is a mere
four blocks from West Broadway but much farther away in spirit.
Broadway is now lined with nationally known medium-priced chain
stores like A/X Armani Exchange, Victoria's Secret and the Pottery
Barn. The much-admired iron-front building where Haughwout once
welcomed its customers now houses a Staples office supply store.
</P>
<P>
   But the pricey stores are turning up everywhere else in the
neighborhood _ from side streets like Wooster, Greene and Mercer to
the wider and more heavily traveled blocks of Prince and Spring
Streets and West Broadway. During Soho's brief moment as the
antebellum equivalent of Madison Avenue, ``major retailers did not
bother with the side streets,'' said Christopher Gray, an
architectural historian and a contributor to The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Boardinghouses _ and later, houses of prostitution _ abounded on
those streets, he said, and as the neighborhood deteriorated, the
major retailers fled uptown.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of a stigma, the side streets are beginning to have
cachet, said Stephen Tarter, a Soho real estate broker. ``But a
major difference in the past year,'' he said, ``is that the very
high-end luxury retailers are going onto side streets. It used to
be `either West Broadway or Spring or don't show me any space.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rents in Soho, as elsewhere in Manhattan, are soaring as
retailers compete for scarce space. Storefronts on Spring and
Prince Streets that cost $100 a square foot a year not long ago can
now command as much as $150 a square foot (or even $250 a square
foot, for a small space suitable for, say, an optician). On Wooster
and Greene Streets, rents have risen to about $100 a square foot
from $60. Prices like these are beyond the means of most gallery
owners and retailers, but Soho is still a bargain compared with
Madison Avenue, where space goes for $300 a square foot or more.
</P>
<P>
   Several retail executives said they hoped to draw customers who
shun uptown shopping. ``We know where our customers live and where
they shop,'' said Thomas J. O'Neill, the president of Louis Vuitton
Americas. ``We know that downtown people don't shop uptown.''
</P>
<P>
   H. Stern is building a 6,000-square-foot store on Prince Street.
``We're not going for kings and queens in Soho,'' said Roberto
Stern, the executive vice president. ``But we are going for the
people who have taste, are educated and who don't like to buy on
Fifth Avenue or Madison. They are intellectual and more interested
in the arts and design.'' In contrast to the company's Fifth Avenue
store, where a necklace can fetch $100,000, the Soho shop will
carry a contemporary collection of jewelry priced at $1,500 to
$4,000, Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Soho has also become the neighborhood of choice for less famous,
but equally expensive, European retailers. Among them are
Philosophy di Alberta Ferretti, a women's clothier based in Milan;
Fortuna Valentino, a shoe store, also from Milan; and Rene Lezard,
a German clothing store, all of which opened their only New York
stores downtown. ``We get a lot of people from uptown because the
product is a very uptown product,'' said Aitor Azua, the manager of
Fortuna Valentino, where boots made from reptile skins can cost as
much as $800.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate brokers tend to be very upbeat about the
neighborhood's prospects. Caroline Banker, a broker with New
Spectrum Realty, said that haughty Madison Avenue is losing some of
its luster, particularly in contrast with the less intimidating
Soho, where stores keep longer hours and stay open on Sundays.
``There's no buzz on Madison right now,'' she said. ``Madison
Avenue dies at 6 o'clock. On weekends, especially in summer, there
is no one walking on those streets.''
</P>
<P>
   But Isaac Lagnato, the president of Tactical Retail Solutions, a
marketing research company, sounded a warier note, predicting that
Soho would be unlikely to provide the highest-priced retailers with
a reliable customer base.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a profitable proposition, I'm very skeptical,'' he said.
``It's a little bit of an ego trip.'' He said that stores with a
wider range of prices, like Ralph Lauren, would have a better
chance of performing well. Soho Faith Hope Consolo, the senior
managing director of Garrick-Aug Associates, a midtown company
specializing in store leasing, agreed that Soho could prove a risky
proposition, especially for stores that depend on only one location
for all of their United States revenues. ``What scares me,'' she
said, ``is that a market can become so hot that it outprices itself
for the kind of sales it can do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Christophe Girard, the executive vice president of Yves
Saint Laurent in Paris, said that Soho is the ideal location for
its Rive Gauche Homme men's wear collection, which has a new young
designer who is very much in tune with the spirit of the
neighborhood. Next month, the men's department, which carries suits
that cost as much as $2,500, will move from Madison Avenue, to a
new store on Wooster Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to Soho is a natural move for us,'' he said, pointing
out that the company opened its first store in
St.-Germain-des-Pres, on the Left Bank in Paris, in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, St.-Germain-des-Pres is in a ``much more
bourgeois state,'' he said. And why?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only luxury stores,'' he said. ``There are no young
designers. It's too expensive. Things change. This is life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
