<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-HOMESICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: LONGING FOR GOTHAM ON LEFT COAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I recently moved to Silicon Valley, and I am
constantly homesick for all aspects of New York life,'' Rosemary
Shashoua wrote in a recent e-mail. ``Please write a column
regarding this feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of being a user-friendly, full-service column,
why not?
</P>
<P>
   After all, who among us has not felt utterly lost when family or
career beckoned with a new ZIP code? Sure, there's a certain
novelty to having strangers greet you on the street with a smile or
being able to shop in supermarkets that are big enough to hide a
jumbo jet.
</P>
<P>
   But those comforts do nothing to prevent the longing that grips
your soul in those moments when you bite into what passes for a
bagel or a slice of pizza anywhere outside the five boroughs of New
York City. Never mind the rush of nostalgia that washes over those
unfortunates who catch a glimpse of Gotham on some TV show.
</P>
<P>
   What then?
</P>
<P>
   Calls are made daily to friends and family, catching up on
gossip and news, while avoiding The Big Question: Why did you leave
in the first place? The truly desperate run to the video store,
getting their hands on anything set in the city _ but please, no
Canadian stand-ins with midblock alleys or mountains on the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Shashoua, 51, knows these rituals. She and her husband
moved to San Mateo, Calif., in 1996 after living in Jackson
Heights, Queens, and out on Long Island, in Islip. Maybe it was a
good idea then, but listen to her now as she describes life amid
abundant sunshine, good vibes and malls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing else people need out here,'' she said.
``Except to have their heads examined.''
</P>
<P>
   She traded coasts in 1996 to help her brother-in-law with his
Italian-food distribution business. And food is something that she
soon noticed was just not the same as what she was used to. She
felt like a trained mouse in a swapped maze when she started going
to the Safeway supermarkets after decades of shopping at
Waldbaum's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aisles are different,'' she said. ``Don't ever go from
Waldbaum's to Safeway. In Safeway, you can't find something, they
take you by the arm and show you where it is. At Waldbaum's, they
tell you it's on the bottom of aisle six on the right. But they
don't know left from right, which is a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like Safeway is a safe bet, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like Safeway,'' she insisted. ``The stuff they have is
junk.''
</P>
<P>
   And expensive, like everything else. She tried haggling when
shopping for a vacuum cleaner, but in one store she couldn't even
get a clerk to pay attention to her. She thinks he was interested
only in making a fat commission by selling her a computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Silicon Valley,'' she said. ``They want to suck you
dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Shashoua used to be involved in community issues and local
politics back on the East Coast. But the level of discourse where
she now lives leaves her longing for the rough-and-tumble attitude
embodied by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really homesick because the people out here are wimps,''
she said. ``They listen too much to all the flak that comes from
the Beltway. If Clinton sneezes, they run with a tissue. Then they
want to know what made him sneeze. They rub his back. They don't
care what they rub; they just want to placate him.''
</P>
<P>
   What would placate her? She longs to see a Broadway play, hear
the noise of a city street or take a ride on the subway _ which to
her has its own bit of theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss the solicitation on the subway when the homeless people
try to sell you something,'' she said. ``Boy, I miss that. Here
they wear a placard that says, `I need a beer.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes an episode of ``Spin City'' eases her homesickness.
She says the television show gives her a dose of New York, as well
as showing different ways of dealing with bad situations. Too bad
it also reminds her how the local politicos where she now lives are
``wishy-washy'' in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here talks a lot but doesn't do anything,'' she
said. ``The representatives out here don't do anything. They love
giving out medals for good deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   She would probably give a medal to whoever would help her find a
new source of herring. She used to buy it in bulk, but the store
stopped selling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose because the general public didn't purchase enough of
it,'' she lamented. ``I will hunt around the local supermarkets and
ask people if they can find out where else I can get it. If not, my
brother-in-law has contacts in Brooklyn. He has a lot of contacts
in Brooklyn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
