u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-HURRICANE-NYT &LR;      09-25 0317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HURRICANE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DIVINING THE IMPACT OF GEORGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Sept. 26:
</P>
<P>
   There are many ways to measure the force of a storm _ by
rainfall, tide height and wind speed, by the number of utility
customers inconvenienced or residents displaced, by the damage in
dollars or human lives. But none of these measures the profound
psychological force of a storm like Hurricane Georges, which has
devastated the Caribbean and southern Florida over the last few
days.
</P>
<P>
   A keen sense of what is normal protects most of us most of the
time. The occurrence of hurricanes, which arise predictably enough
to form a ``season,'' is certainly normal, even though the
conditions they embody _ torrential rain, massive disturbance of
tidal patterns, and 100-mph winds _ are extreme. The notion that
Georges is somehow a normal event brings solace to no one, for the
effect of a storm like this one is to undermine the very idea of
normality, to leave the human emotions exposed, unbuffered for a
moment, by the continuum of everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have argued that repeated exposure to rapid climatic
change is one of the underlying conditions that helped define the
human character as it evolved. This may be true of the species over
eons, but anyone who has experienced a truly violent storm knows
how quickly it can bring you to the edge of emotional self-control,
to a place that feels less like evolution than extinction.
</P>
<P>
   A storm like Georges does more than blow the roofs off houses,
flood the sewer systems and take human lives at will. It redefines
the extraordinary benignity of this earth _ the storm's eye in
which we nearly always live _ even as it makes the blue skies that
will surely follow seem tentative, a veil over a planet whose
extremes we barely know at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
