<HEADER>
A5719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-ART-     09-25 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-530(2TAKES)NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES RELEASE OF MORE DOCUMENTS FROM STARR INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 3rd &AMP; 4th grafs to add info. on impeachment inquiry process;
adds 2nd take.)  
 (ATTN: Ark., Fla., Mass., Mich.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(See also CLINTON-JONES, CLINTON-DAY) 
(js) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee on Friday approved
the release of thousands more pages of documents that had been
delivered by the independent counsel, finding near unanimity this
time on particularly sensitive information that would be kept from
public view.
</P>
<P>
   After days of wrangling, Republicans and Democrats on the panel
agreed to release the audiotapes of surreptitiously recorded
conversations between Linda Tripp and Monica Lewinsky, the White
House intern who had an affair with President Clinton. The
committee voted unanimously to make the same sort of deletions of
sensitive or immaterial information on the audiotapes as it did the
accompanying transcripts of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's meeting of the Judiciary Committee brings to an end the
first phase of the preliminary inquiry, a process marked mostly by
discord, as members and the committee staff took on the task of
sorting through the two sets of 18 boxes of documents shipped to
Congress by the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The panel is scheduled to meet again in early October and vote
whether to go forward with an impeachment inquiry, after which the
resolution would come before the full House. The measure is
expected to pass by a comfortable margin in the House, Democrats
and Republicans say. It would be the second time in 25 years that
the House of Representatives considered whether to impeach a
president.
</P>
<P>
   The documents are set to be released on Thursday at the
earliest, with the tapes probably made available a few days later
for technical reasons, promising the public a third round of
details about Clinton and his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Tripp tapes, the documents also include the
transcripts of grand jury testimony of several important witnesses
in the case, including Clinton's secretary, Betty Currie, and his
confidant, Vernon Jordan, as well as a number of depositions and
FBI interviews with a long list of people.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a sharp distinction from the committee's last go-around,
which was sharply partisan, Republicans cast Friday's proceedings
as a model of cooperation and comity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we're trying to be sensitive to the American people,
of whether they need more or less,'' Rep. W. Asa Hutchinson,
R-Ark., said regarding the release of information.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats immediately tried to dispel that notion of
togetherness. There was ``a modest change'' signaling ``a
Republican retreat in the face of public opinion polls showing
increasing disappointment of what they are doing,'' said Rep. John
Conyers of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the panel. ``At
another level, the partisanship continues.''
</P>
<P>
   In a stark departure from last week's partisan roll call,
Republicans and Democrats took 15 unanimous votes on what
information to redact or withhold, some of it for national security
reasons. On one occasion Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth
Starr requested that three transcripts _ two of people interviewed
by the independent counsel and one grand jury witness _ be kept
secret, and the committee agreed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many of the rest of the 23 votes on the matter were near
unanimous, with a few exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats who have listened to the tapes say they are
helpful to Clinton because they portray Mrs. Tripp as scheming and
manipulative and Ms. Lewinsky as lewd.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes contain hours of meandering conversations between the
two women as they discuss the ups and downs of Ms. Lewinsky's
relationship with the president and their legal troubles as
potential witnesses in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct case. The
tapes pose other problems because Starr noted in his report to
Congress that some of them show signs of duplication. Starr said
the matter was still under investigation because Mrs. Tripp had
testified to the grand jury that no copies were made.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans briefly considered withholding the tapes and simply
releasing the transcripts with deletions, and even Democrats were
uncertain about how to handle the tapes. But Democrats were furious
that Republicans had easily released Clinton's videotaped grand
jury testimony, and then sought to keep secret Mrs. Tripp's tapes,
accusing them of political motives. In the end, the argument for
full disclosure, which had carried so much weight with Republicans
last week, won out.
</P>
<P>
   Facing polls that show the public's distaste for the committee's
handling of the material, which many consider lurid, Republicans
said on Friday that they ``listened to each other'' and did their
best to meet Democrats halfway.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats won on several votes that split Republicans, including
one on the question of how to deal with the ``Jane Does''
interviewed by prosecutors. One vote concerned information about
Dolly Kyle Browning of Dallas, a classmate of Clinton's who has
said that she had a relationship with him for more than three
decades, which at one point included an affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed to give up on everything virtually they wanted us to
give up on,'' said Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., who is on the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   A round of verbal sparring broke out immediately following the
meeting as the two sides squabbled over the genuineness of the
bipartisanship and their eagerness to appear before the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., conceded that ``Republicans are not
automatically saying no.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats were infuriated by the party-line rejection of one
of their motions to put forward a joint request for the remainder
of Starr's information, material he deemed immaterial to the case
but that Democrats believe could benefit the president. Starr has
said the Republican-controlled committee could look over the
remaining documents if they put in a ``joint request.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to get more information,'' Frank said. ``To be told
we shouldn't have more information is disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they expect to make that joint request but did
not wish to entangle Friday's proceedings with that issue, and
other issues, including the scope of the anticipated impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Republicans tried to shift the focus back on the
committee's newfound communion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a very good day,'' said Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla.,
``vote after vote after vote. We need to look at the record of
those votes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
