</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS SET AMERICAN LEAGUE MARK WITH 112TH VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y., Ohio)  (js) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees sent a platoon of scouts to the series
between the Anaheim Angels and the Texas Rangers this week, when it
appeared that the winner would emerge as the team that would play
in Yankee Stadium in the American League playoffs next week.
</P>
<P>
   But now there is a very real chance the Yankees will play
Cleveland in the first round, rather than the Rangers. If Texas
surpasses or matches the Indians' won-lost record this weekend, the
Rangers will play host to Boston in a division series, while
Cleveland will have to play the Yankees _ a team the Indians
eliminated in a division series last year. Going into Friday
night's play, the Rangers (87-72) were one game behind the Indians
(88-71).
</P>
<P>
   The shifting tides, however, will not affect the preparation or
the planning of Yankee manager Joe Torre, whose club has regained
its stride as it nears the regular-season finish line. The Yankees
have won five consecutive games, and Friday night, in front of
32,447 at Yankee Stadium, they established the American League
single-season record for victories, beating Tampa Bay, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have 112 victories, one more than the 111 won by the
1954 Cleveland Indians (who played a 154-game season). With two
games remaining, the Yankees have won more games this season than
any other team except for the 1906 Chicago Cubs, who finished
116-36.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez (12-4), who is expected to start Game 4 in the
division series, pitched five innings Friday night and allowed one
run in five innings. Andy Pettitte, who will most likely start Game
2, pitched three shutout innings. David Wells is expected to start
Game 1 on Tuesday and David Cone Game 3 on Friday. Torre intends to
formally announce his rotation over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said the identity of the division series opponent would
not affect the make-up of the Yankee bullpen, which slowly has
rounded into form this month. ``The majority of our guys out there
are right where we hoped they would be,'' said Mel Stottlemyre, the
team's pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson, the most crucial piece of the Yankees' middle
relief, came back from lower back trouble Sept. 4 and Torre and
Stottlemyre were not sure if his back would hold up, despite
Nelson's stubborn insistence he would be fine. Nelson has been
excellent: in six and two-thirds innings over nine appearances, the
right-hander has allowed one hit, walked three and struck out nine.
Pitching the ninth inning in a save opportunity on Thursday against
Tampa Bay, Nelson mostly threw fastballs, whiffing Wade Boggs with
a slider that broke across the outside corner, before blowing a
high fastball past Randy Winn to end the game. ``He's answered all
the questions about whether his back would be sound enough for him
to pitch,'' Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre: ``Nelson was, last night, by far the best outing
he's had. He had the stuff, but his command was the best he's
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Stanton, the left-handed set-up man, has had some moments
of inconsistency, but since blowing a lead on Aug. 25, he has
pitched 181/3 innings and allowed five runs, his earned run average
dropping from 6.41 to 5.49. He has walked four and struck out 16 in
that span.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera, the closer, is finishing what has been a strong
season, with 36 saves in 41 opportunities; he has held opposing
batters to a .209 average, walking only 14 and allowing just 3
homers in 591/3 innings. Rivera has not pitched in recent days,
however, after being hit on the chest by a batted ball, the bruise
bothering him somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend Torre met with Graeme Lloyd in Baltimore and told
him that he had a week to reverse a September slump, the inherent
threat being that Lloyd might be dropped off the post-season
roster. Lloyd, confused and somewhat miffed over the latest
uncertainty, has pitched effectively in his last two outings,
lowering his ERA to .172. The velocity of his fastball increased to
89-90 miles an hour, from 86-87 mph, and his cut fastball moved
more sharply. Lloyd, a left-hander who specializes in facing
left-handed batters, has held opponents to a .189 average this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu (13-9, 4.00) and Ramiro Mendoza (10-2, 3.27) most
likely will be part of the team's long relief in the playoffs,
stepping in if a starting pitcher gets into trouble early. Torre
said he wanted to carry 10 pitchers on his post-season roster, and
Darren Holmes, an experienced reliever who has been terrific this
month _ he has allowed one run in 101/3 innings over his last seven
outings _ may be left off the post-season roster.
</P>
<P>
   -----------
</P>
<P>
   Inside Pitch
</P>
<P>
   If Texas and Cleveland finish with identical records, Texas will
win the tie breaker because the Rangers have a better record in
head-to-head play. . . . Bernie Williams was two for two Friday
night, raising his average to .337; Boston's Mo Vaughn was two for
four, improving to .336.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
