<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIATICAL-POLICY-SALES-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IDEA THAT WON'T WORK FOR EVERYONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Ill.)  (for release Sunday, Sept. 27) 
(sidebar with VIATICAL-INSURANCE) 
(js) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who should consider selling a life insurance policy?
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the list, financial planners say, are people who
are straining to pay large premiums on term policies but whose
loved ones won't need the benefits. Simply dropping the insurance
means that the premiums go to waste, because term policies have no
cash value. A sale can redeem at least part of the years of
payments while putting a halt to the policyholder's cash outlays.
</P>
<P>
   Others who might wisely decide to sell their policies, planners
say, are wealthy people who have life insurance intended to cover
the taxes on their estates but whose assets have lost value,
leaving them with more insurance than they need.
</P>
<P>
   A company that buys insurance on the lives of employees in
high-ranking positions may want to sell a policy after an executive
retires. Similarly, a partnership or small business may have
unneeded insurance after a partner leaves or a business shuts down.
</P>
<P>
   In the right circumstances, selling an insurance policy ``could
solve some other financial problems,'' said Rick Adkins, a planner
who owns the Arkansas Financial Group in Little Rock. ``It's like a
reverse mortgage, where instead of making house payments, people
start receiving income.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Chodes, the president of Viaticus Inc., a Chicago company
that buys unwanted insurance policies, said that about half the
people who explore deals with his company don't end up selling
their policies. Sometimes, he said, the most the company can offer
is, say, $40,000 when the cash value that has built up in a
whole-life policy comes to $50,000. In that case, he said, the
policyholder simply cashes in with the insurance company. Other
times, he said, the offer may be so small in proportion to the face
value of the policy that the owner decides to keep the coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance company executives say that to build the best value in
a life insurance policy, the holder should see it through to the
end rather than share a substantial portion with a middleman.
Holders of whole-life policies can borrow against the cash value if
they are short of cash. Policies can also be used as collateral for
loans. Or, with some policies, owners can use the cash value to pay
premiums, said Mel Feinberg, a vice president at New York Life
Insurance Co. Alternatively, Feinberg said, premiums can be
reduced, or in some cases eliminated, by scaling down the face
amount of the policy.
</P>
<P>
   When the owner of a multimillion-dollar policy finds huge
premiums to be more than he can handle, said David D'Alesandro,
president of John Hancock Insurance Co. of America, heirs may
consider taking over the payments. That way, he said, the family
keeps the sum that would go to a middleman if the policy were sold.
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested that a university endowment fund or other
charity might be willing to take over the premium payments in
exchange for the death benefit; there can be tax benefits for the
policyholder in such arrangements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-25-98 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
